<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, June 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ASSESS (Abuja, Nigeria) _ News Analysis: Abuja is in
many ways suggestive of Nigeria as whole, a country still seeking a
firm basis for democracy and unity 38 years after independence. It
is this solidly democratic state that the country's new military
ruler, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, has now solemnly promised
Nigeria's 105 million citizens. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Chihuahua, Mexico) _ A radical idea is gaining
momentum within Mexico's governing party: primary elections. For
six decades after its founding in 1929, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party so thoroughly monopolized Mexican politics that
elections were a mere ritual in which its candidates won election
to all but a handful of government posts. But in recent years,
one-party rule has come under assault in Mexico as elsewhere in the
world. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   MACAU-GANG-WAR (Macau) _ In an isolated jail cell on a tiny
island next to this Portuguese colony sits a 43-year-old Chinese
man who has held Macau in thrall. Law enforcement officials here
say he is one of the most notorious organized crime figures in
Southeast Asia. His lawyer says he is merely a colorful businessman
whose penchant for publicity has landed him in a world of trouble.
By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAY-CANDIDATE (Everett, Wash.) _ Although she has never run for
office before, Margarethe Cammermeyer would seem to have a resume
tailor-made for politics: She is a mother of four, a nurse with a
doctorate degree and a Vietnam veteran who won the bronze star. But
the one thing voters in this fast-growing district north of Seattle
are sure to hear in her run for Congress is that she is also a
homosexual. As one of four open lesbians running for national
office this year, Ms. Cammermeyer is trying to do something no one
has ever done: become the first, openly-gay, nonincumbent elected
to Congress. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS-VISAS (Undated) _ A prominent Indian scientist who
had planned to participate in a scientific conference in Virginia
this week has been denied a United States visa, prompting charges
by American physicists that Washington is imposing political
restraints on the free exchange of scientific information. By
Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   FREEMEN-RANCH (Jordan, Mont.) _ At the old Clark farmhouse,
where Freemen theorists once advocated the supremacy of white
males, a new kind of pecking order is incubating. Under bright
lights, 1,000 pheasant brooders are fattening, preparing for
release this summer into the rolling hills of the Missouri Breaks.
The 960-acre Clark ranch, which two years ago was embedded into the
nation's consciousness as a symbol of far-right anti-government
resistance, is being reinvented as a place for tourists to pay to
hunt birds. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-CONFIRM _ For the first time in recent memory, the
Senate this week may reject a president's choice to head a branch
of the armed forces. Critics are challenging the flight record and
truthfulness of Daryl Jones, Clinton's pick to be the first black
secretary of the Air Force. The nomination has split Republican
ranks. The Senate Armed Services Committee is to vote on Wednesday.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT18,19) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GM-SATURN (Spring Hill, Tenn.) _ A month after strikes at parts
factories in Flint, Mich., forced every other GM plant in the
United States to close, the enormous Saturn factory here is still
churning out cars, as workers have quietly set aside union
solidarity in favor of preserving the nation's best-known
experiment in cooperation between labor and management. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGECOUNTY-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ A look at how an aggressive
securities salesman, who knew how to manipulate clients' weaknesses
and made soothing reassurances if they balked at risky investments,
contributed to the Orange County's financial problems. What
happened when both he and his superiors ignored danger signals as
things began spinning out of control in the California county. By
Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: a graphic, a chronology, has been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UTILITY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paradise has been portrayed in
myriad ways in books, paintings, films and plays. But rarely has it
been suggested that paradise may be found in New Jersey. That
unlikely assertion is the premise of a campaign for Public Service
Enterprise Group Inc. in Newark, parent of the state's dominant
utility, Public Service Electric and Gas. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ As technology and
telecommunications companies continue their tarantella of mergers,
one of the rules that has emerged from the whirlwind is that
integration is essential to a successful deal. A look at Northern
Telecom Ltd. of Canada, and Dave House, chairman of Bay Networks
Inc., try to rally Wall Street behind Northern Telecom's pending
$9.1 billion acquisition of Bay, they seem to have a different
idea. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICAN-FILM (New York) _ A film festival marks the
coming of age of Asian American directors.
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTEIN-MUSIC (New York) _ A Critic's Notebook: Leonard
Bernstein was right: all music is tonal. By Anthony Tommasini.
