<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-VICTIM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCAFFOLD CRASH VICTIM DESCRIBED AS QUIET, GRACIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)  (also see NY-SCAFFOLD-CRASH, NY-SCAFFOLD-SCENE, NY-SCAFFOLD-HOTEL,
NY-SCAFFOLD-BUILDERS) 
(sw) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the top floor of the Woodstock Hotel on 43d
Street, Thereza Feliconio could look out onto Bryant Park, the news
zipper around 1 Times Square and the dense collection of high-rise
buildings east of Broadway. She was a big-city person who loved
living in the heart of the city, and although she lived in a
subsidized residence for the poor, she dressed as if it were the
fanciest hotel in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had her hair in place and nice makeup,'' said her
nephew, Ricardo Muniz, who frequently took her to dinner, movies
and the theater.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning at 8:30, one of the many chunks of steel that
broke free from a construction site across the street crashed into
her room, No. 1202, burying Ms. Feliconio, 85, and all of the
knickknacks and memories she had accumulated in her pink-accented
room over the years in a shower of plaster and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ground zero was the room Thereza Feliconio was in,'' said
Cynthia Dial, executive director of Project Find, which owns and
operates the 285-room, single-room occupancy hotel that caters to
the elderly poor. ``Her room was reduced to rubble.'' It took
rescue workers 20 minutes to dig through the wreckage to recover
her body, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feliconio, her nephew said, grew up in Sao Paulo, Brazil, in
a large and prosperous family. About 30 years ago, she moved to New
York City, where she made a living caring for elderly people. Her
only living brother, Carlos Feliconio, is flying to New York on
Wednesday morning from Hollywood, Fla., Muniz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She helped the disabled people, people who needed personal
care,'' Muniz said. ``She had the heart, the strength to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And she had a love of the lights and glitter that drew her to
live in Times Square, he said. ``She was active,'' Muniz said.
``She liked to go out, to dine out, to have nice lunches and long
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved Carmine's,'' he said, referring to a popular Italian
restaurant. ``We went to Phantom, Beauty and the Beast, musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, Muniz was at his office a few blocks away,
where he works as an airline ticket agent, when he heard about ``a
commotion.'' He went out to investigate. ``It was surreal,'' he
said. ``I bumped into a guy who worked at the hotel and he broke me
the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dial remembered Ms. Feliconio as a ``lovely, lovely quiet
woman.'' She had decorated her room herself, she said. ``She had
lots of nice furniture and knickknacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees described her as reserved and gracious, a woman of
medium height who gave everybody a quiet hello. She had lived at
the Woodstock for about 10 years, Muniz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never complained _ even when things were not going so
great,'' he said. ``She always pumped me up. She made me feel good
about life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
