<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS OF NBA AND PLAYERS DECIDE TO RESUME BARGAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Revealing progress for the first time since the
National Basketball Association's owner-imposed lockout began three
weeks ago, commissioner David Stern and players' union leader Billy
Hunter met on Tuesday morning and decided to resume bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Hunter talked for 90 minutes over breakfast to discuss
a potential date for the first negotiations since talks broke off
after an unproductive 30-minute meeting between representatives
from the league and the players association June 22. Stern and
Hunter are expected to call each other Friday and set up a
bargaining session for early August.
</P>
<P>
   ``David and I met, and it was a cordial meeting, but it didn't
focus on the specifics of our negotiations,'' said Hunter, who is
the executive director of the players association. ``Instead, we
talked more generally about our desire to resume bargaining. I let
David know that my ultimate goal remains reaching an agreement both
sides can live with as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither side has budged on the key issues preventing
labor peace. If the dispute is left unresolved heading into the
season, the battle could lead to lost games for the first time in
league history. Eight days after the last bargaining session ended
abruptly, the lockout began. Until a new labor agreement is signed,
teams are prohibited from negotiating with, signing or trading
players.
</P>
<P>
   This also means that players whose contracts call for them to be
paid during the summer months are without their salaries. Acting on
their behalf, the players association requested arbitration with
John Feerick, the grievance arbitrator under the labor agreement
that expired at midnight June 30.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the NBA sued its players union, contending that the
league should not have to pay players during the lockout and that
it should not have to go to arbitration. The league also asked that
Feerick, who reduced Golden State guard Latrell Sprewell's
suspension from Stern for choking his coach, P.J. Carlesimo, be
removed as arbitrator on the grounds that his term had expired.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Feerick handed the players association a small
victory when he decided that he has the authority to decide if he
has jurisdiction to be the arbitrator in the matter, said a union
spokesman, Dan Wasserman. He will hear arguments from both sides on
July 30.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the dispute over the collective bargaining
agreement, owners want to put a ceiling on how much players can
earn in a system they reluctantly approved three years ago. Under
the old agreement, the owners had the right to reopen the deal if
player payroll exceeded 51.8 percent of basketball-related
revenues. Stern has said player payroll accounted for more than 57
percent of the revenues taken in by the league last year. That
figure has been seriously questioned by the players association.
</P>
<P>
   There is also one more major issue that divides the two sides,
one that the players feel is sacred: the Larry Bird exception. This
clause enables teams to pay their own free agents whatever they
want regardless of the salary cap, allowing the Bulls' Michael
Jordan to be paid $33 million last year when the cap for an entire
team was $26.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The players say it is up to owners to show fiscal
responsibility, and intend to resist changes in the system that
would result in a hard salary cap. Although neither side has budged
on the issues, they are scheduled to talk again. And after three
weeks of silence during the lockout, this is a breakthrough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
