<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAK'S EARLY SUCCESS SURPRISES EVEN HER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a derailment last week at the JAL Big Apple Classic, in
New Rochelle, N.Y., where she finished four over par following her
record-tying 23-under performance a week earlier, Se Ri Pak will
try to get back on track in time for the du Maurier Classic, Aug.
6-9, in Windsor, Ontario, the last major on the Ladies Professional
Golf Association tour.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, 20, has taken women's golf by storm in the United States by
becoming the first rookie to win two majors in the same year since
Juli Inkster in 1984, and the first woman under 21 to capture two
majors in a year. She followed her triumph at the McDonald's LPGA
Championship with a playoff victory in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Pak admitted in a conference call Tuesday from Warren, Ohio,
where she is in the field for the Giant Eagle LPGA Classic, that
her goal had been to win her first major in the year 2006. ``I'm
surprised that things happened so fast,'' she said. ``I was looking
to learn the golf courses the first few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak also said she was surprised at how many young people in her
native South Korea have taken up golf because of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear too many children start golf because of me,'' she said.
``I just want to be like Nancy Lopez. She's the top player, and
she's nice to people. I want to be remembered like Nancy Lopez. She
plays every tournament like it's important, so I want to push
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   With Lopez and Annika Sorenstam, the JAL winner, joining her in
this week's field, Pak will have plenty of motivation. She said her
father, Joon Chul Pak, has helped her over last week's stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind is settled down because he's my first teacher,'' Pak
said. ``I feel comfortable now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hustling Around the Course
</P>
<P>
   Watched by some 50 spectators, four members of Gardiners Bay
Country Club in Shelter Island, N.Y., played 117 holes in 15{ hours
Monday _ walking the course in the heat and humidity _ to raise
money for Junior Golf on Long Island and the entire metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   Playing from 5 a.m. until 8:30 p.m., the foursome raised $12,500
in completing six and a half rounds over the par-72 course.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Adipietro, an anesthesiologist at Mount Sinai Medical
Center, initiated the affair. He was joined by Barry Walz, a
contractor; Jay Card, a police officer, and Gary Blados, who works
in the pro shop and plays golf for St. John's University. Blados
led the group in scoring by averaging 67.5 strokes a round.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had blisters on their feet at the end, but it was all for
a worthy cause,'' said Robert DeStefano, the head pro at the club.
</P>
<P>
   No Help Needed
</P>
<P>
   Carl Alexander of Pine Hollow in East Norwich, N.Y., showed up
for the Met Open qualifying at nearby North Hills Country Club on
Monday to discover he had no caddie as he competed with 167 other
players for 18 spots in the tournament, which will be staged next
month at the Creek Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guy I was playing with I'd better do something on
the front nine because I'd get tired on the back nine carrying my
bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander proceeded to birdie six holes on the front nine and
finish at six-under 66 as the medalist at the 6,475-yard North
Hills course to qualify for his third Met Open. He finished tied
for sixth in the New York State Open last week.
</P>
<P>
   Doell Wins State Amateur
</P>
<P>
   Sara Doell rallied from a four-hole deficit after 27 holes to
capture the New York State Women's Amateur with a 2-and-1 victory
over Chawwadee Pompothong last week at St. Andrew's Golf Club in
Hastings-on-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Doell, of Webster Golf Club near Rochester, plays at Penn State,
and Pompothong, of Dunwoodie Golf Club in Yonkers, plays at Yale.
Pompothong dominated the 36-hole match through 27 holes, but Doell
played the next eight holes in four under par to win her first
state title.
</P>
<P>
   In other women's amateur play, Sue Sempler's streak of
consecutive Bergen Country titles came to an end at five last week
at Arcola Country Club in Paramus, N.J. Sempler finished tied for
third behind the winner, Kattie Allison, and Joni Clause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
