<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT OK WITH BEING LIFTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pitchers usually have to be dragged out of a game
in chains when they have an opportunity to finish a shutout _ all
the more so when they're in position to register a one-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' Darren Dreifort, however, said Tuesday he had no
particular quarrel with being lifted for the ninth inning of his
impressive performance against Cincinnati on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a shot at one (a shutout), you want to go out
there and finish it yourself,'' said Dreifort, who worked eight
innings of one-hit ball in a 2-0 victory over the Reds. ``But we're
not in that position right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dodgers, with four teams to jump over in the
National League wild-card race, aren't exactly operating on a broad
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of the best way to win a ballgame,'' manager
Glenn Hoffman said of the decision to replace Dreifort with closer
Jeff Shaw for the ninth. ``No-hitter? Yeah, (Dreifort) stays out
there. But we had a healthy Shaw out there, loaded and ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dreifort) will get many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw underscored the wisdom of the call by striking out the side
on 12 pitches for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort nodded in assent. ``Especially where we are in the
season and the standings, you don't want to fool around and maybe
give away a big game,'' he said. ``They told me if we would have
scored two runs in the bottom of the eighth, I would have gone back
out there. But in a save situation, you've got to go to your
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to chance: Juan Castro got in some batting practice
Tuesday afternoon... twice.
</P>
<P>
   The infielder jumped into the cage in the broiling sun of
mid-afternoon, a time usually reserved for bench players. Then he
returned late in the afternoon for his regular session with the
other members of the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is known as a superlative defensive player _ he has done
some outstanding work at shortstop in the absence of the injured
Jose Vizcaino _ but he'd like to broaden that label some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a better hitter. I've been working a lot and I'm
going to keep working,'' said Castro. ``I'm not going to let it
go.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a lot of ground to make up. Castro is a career .190
hitter (.206 this year), despite having batted a cumulative .331
over his last two stays in Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Vizcaino, on the disabled list with a sprained right
ankle, hit from both sides of the plate, but the shortstop's work
in the field will determine his return to action. ``It's critical
for a middle infielder to have agility for both legs,'' said
Hoffman, who used to be one. Vizcaino is thought to be a week or so
away.... Second baseman Eric Young (strained right thigh) is
eligible to come off the disabled list Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
