<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     07-22 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS HIRE HARTSBURG AS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Unaffected by not being the Ducks' top coaching
choice, Craig Hartsburg accepted that post while hosting a poolside
barbecue on Monday afternoon at his Batchawany Bay summer home.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 miles north of the Michigan peninsula town of Sault
Ste. Marie, Hartsburg left his hideaway at 4:30 Tuesday morning for
a flight to Orange County through Toronto. He told wife Peggy to
tell all callers that he ``has gone fishing, at the Pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced as the Ducks' new coach late Tuesday afternoon at the
Pond, Hartsburg had hoped to take care of his first order of
business, talking with team captain Paul Kariya, by this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg was Chicago's coach last season when Gary Suter of the
Blackhawks belted Kariya with a cross check on Feb. 1. Hartsburg
vigorously defended Suter, and Kariya missed the final 28 games of
the season with postconcussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it wasn't intentional by Gary,'' Hartsburg said. ``I
know what type of player Gary is and what type of person he is....
It's a violent, tough game. It's unfortunate, the league and
Anaheim lost one of the best players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very bad for Paul, getting hurt. I was a player who had
to retire because of injuries, so I know what that's all about. To
me, it's over and done with now. I'll protect Paul as best as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks general manager Jack Ferreira said Tuesday that he had
talked to Kariya about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said that (the injury and its aftermath) wouldn't faze
him one bit,'' Ferreira said. ``Craig Hartsburg didn't send Gary
Suter out to hit (Kariya).''
</P>
<P>
   It is the second move the Ducks made within a week to stabilize
the franchise, as former assistant general manager Pierre Gauthier
took over as president for the re-assigned Tony Tavares last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, 39, flew in Saturday for a second interview with
Ferreira, who held that title at Minnesota in 1989-90 when
Hartsburg was an assistant coach for the North Stars. He played for
the Stars from 1979-80 to '88-89, serving as team captain for his
final six seasons. Known as an attacking defenseman in the mold of
Ray Bourque, Hartsburg scored 98 goals. Injuries limited him to
only 27 and 30 games, respectively, in his last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Goring, an International Hockey League coach in Utah for
the last four seasons who coached the Boston Bruins for two seasons
in the mid-'80s, turned down an offer to coach the Ducks last
Wednesday. Goring reportedly felt he had been low-balled with a
take-it-or-leave-it annual salary of $400,000. Hartsburg signed a
three-year deal that is worth about $500,000 a year, which was what
Pierre Page earned last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks finished 26-43-13 last season, their worst record in
their five-year history. Page was fired on June 15, 10 months after
signing a three-year deal and 2{ weeks after assistants Don Hay and
Walt Kyle were canned.
</P>
<P>
   In that brief span, Ferreira realized the philosophical
differences between him and Page were too great to let them fester.
Ferreira said having a former NHL player in such a critical
position, background that Page did not possess, should be
invaluable to the Ducks. Ferreira intimated that Hartsburg's
background as an NHL coach is what enhanced his contract above the
offer made to Goring.
</P>
<P>
   In '95-96, Hartsburg took over an aging Chicago team and led it
to a 40-28-14 record. The Blackhawks swept the Calgary Flames in
the first round of the playoffs, then lost to the eventual Stanley
Cup-champion Colorado Avalanche. Chicago lost to Colorado in the
opening round the following season, and it missed the playoffs last
spring for the first time in 29 years. Soon after, Blackhawks
management fired Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Described by NHL followers as droll, dull and dry, Hartsburg
will focus on only one D-word with the Ducks _ defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win more battles than the other guys,'' he said.
``When you win more battles, you win more games. You have to play
with grit in this league to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, who declined to mention his assistant candidates,
said work ethic, discipline and a team-first attitude will
characterize the 1998-99 Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we'll be the best-conditioned team in the NHL,'' he said.
``Without that, those first three things don't mean anything. And
we will have enthusiasm. Everything will be done for the good of
the team. We'll play together, have fun together and win
together.''
</P>
<P>
   He said not being the Ducks' top choice was a ``moot point,''
that he is simply ecstatic to be a head coach in the NHL making
more money than he ever dreamed of earning as a player.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said three years in Chicago taught him plenty about
himself, but he chose not to divulge his self-analysis. He said
he'll make some mistakes with the Ducks but that he'll learn from
them. Hopefully, he said, while winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different situation than Chicago,''
Hartsburg said. ``Chicago was an older team that had only one
chance. (The Ducks) are a team that's young and will just get
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
