A6380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     07-22 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GINGRICH'S KILLER AMENDMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 22:
</P>
<P>
   With each passing day it has become clearer that many moderate
Republicans are ready to defy Newt Gingrich and support the
Shays-Meehan campaign finance reform bill. That is why the speaker
is now accelerating his efforts to kill the legislation by trying
to lure Republicans into supporting amendments designed solely to
repel Democrats from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Today the House is scheduled to debate and vote on three such
``killer amendments'' designed by Gingrich and his agents to divide
the emerging bipartisan majority for cleaning up the system. We
urge lawmakers to stand firm, as they have in the past, and reject
those amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The target of two of the amendments is the National Voter
Registration Act, or motor voter law, which many Republicans have
hated ever since it was enacted in 1993. The law allowed for
mail-in registration and other steps that have expanded the number
of voters in poor and minority communities. One amendment would
repeal the mail-in registration requirement of the act and allow
states to drop voters from the rolls simply for not voting. Another
would allow states to require voters to produce photo
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans sincerely believe that the motor voter bill has
led to fraud. But they should realize that this concern has nothing
to do with the problem of curbing the influence of special-interest
money in elections. Should either of these amendments pass,
Democrats will defect from the Shays-Meehan bill, dooming its
chances. Another amendment that should be rejected would require
candidates to raise at least 50 percent of their funds within their
district. It is not intended to serve as reform, but to place a
particular burden on candidates in poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would end the practice of unrestricted
contributions of ``soft money'' by corporations, unions and
individuals to political parties. It would also limit fund-raising
for campaign ads by independent groups within two months of an
election. These are sensible steps that would prevent a repetition
of the worst abuses of the last election. A majority of House
members have successfully pushed aside other killer amendments
aimed at hurting labor unions. It may be difficult for some
moderate Republicans to vote against measures they believe in, but
to take Gingrich's bait will help him bury reform legislation that
the nation needs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
