<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SO MUCH FOR ELECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 22`
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wondering why New York City is cursed with an abysmally
weak congressional delegation could find the answer this week in
Queens. Rep. Thomas Manton, the longtime incumbent from the Seventh
District, announced in the dark of night that he would not be
running for re-election. Before most of the active Democrats in the
district had even heard the news, Manton had engineered the
installation of a hand-picked successor in a method that appears to
guarantee a virtually uncontested election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Manton, who doubles as the Queens Democratic chairman, has been
a mediocre congressman at best, devoting most of his time to
district politics. His chosen successor, Assembly member Joseph
Crowley, has had an equally undistinguished career notable mainly
for party loyalty. The district is crammed with elected officials a
generation younger than Manton who would like to have had a shot at
the post, most of them far abler and more energetic than Crowley.
But the congressman waited until it was too late for any of them to
file for a primary challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The real losers, of course, are the voters in Queens, whom
Manton and Crowley have conspired to deprive of any real say in
choosing their member of Congress. Crowley, who might have had a
hard time winning a fair primary, has been forced down the
district's throat, and there is little the electorate can do about
it. The local Republican Party, which had a nonaggression pact with
Manton, refrained from nominating a serious candidate even though
the district might easily be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Congress, Manton will quickly be forgotten. But
back home he should be remembered as an emblem of the sickness that
permeates New York politics _ an attitude that elections are
unnecessary evils that get in the way of the serious business of
dispensing patronage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
