<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER MOVE: GREENE SURGES TO VICTORY IN THE 100 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ In the biggest 100-meter race of the season,
the world champion Maurice Greene defeated his training partner,
Ato Boldon, to win the Goodwill Games event in 9.96 seconds Tuesday
night. Considering that the race was run into a 2-mile-an-hour
headwind, it was one of the greatest 100 meters ever run.
</P>
<P>
   Boldon, of Trinidad, finished second in 10.00, while Donovan
Bailey of Canada, the 1996 Olympic champion and world record-holder
at 9.84 seconds, was seventh Tuesday night in 10.30 seconds.
Greene, who won the 1997 world championship in 9.86 seconds, and
Boldon, the 1996 Olympic bronze medalist, train with coach John
Smith in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson continued his comeback from early season
hamstring injuries in the 400 meters with a time of 43.76 seconds,
the fastest time in the world this year before an appreciative
crowd of 9,756 at the Mitchel Athletic Complex. It is the first
time anyone has run under 44 seconds since April 1997, when Johnson
opened his season with a time of 43.75.
</P>
<P>
   Tyree Washington, who finished second Tuesday night in 44.43
seconds, made a move on Johnson in the backstretch and had pulled
slightly ahead entering the final turn. But Johnson has apparently
regained the endurance that he lacked earlier this season. He drew
ahead in the middle of the curve and hammered the final 150 meters
to win convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   This was the most dominant Johnson had been since he sustained a
leg injury in a 150-meter race against Bailey in June 1997. Over
the last month, he has finally overcome leg injuries caused by a
problem with the alignment of his hips and which led to repeated
interference with his training. Johnson became the only man ever to
win the 200 and 400 meters in the Summer Games in 1996 and has said
that only injuries have prevented him from regaining his Olympian
form. After Tuesday night, it would be perilous, even foolish, not
to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I needed was races after my injuries,'' Johnson said.
``I'm definitely on the road back to being as strong as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final heptathlon of a career that has produced two
Olympic gold medals in the event, Jackie Joyner-Kersee tied for
first place after three events but faded badly in the 200 meters to
fall into second place.
</P>
<P>
   Dedee Nathan of the United States won the 200 with a personal
best of 24.11 seconds and held the lead after the first day with
3,867 points, 34 ahead of Joyner-Kersee. Nathan ran the 100-meter
hurdles in 13.28, high-jumped 5-11\ and threw the shot put 47-5.
Joyner-Kersee ran 13.29 seconds in the 100-meter hurdles,
high-jumped 5-8} and threw the shot put 51-1} before fading in the
200 in 24.47 seconds. She will probably need a huge effort in her
specialty, the long jump, on Wednesday to have any chance of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Noureddine Morceli of Algeria, who is tenuously maintaining his
world record of 3:44.39 in the mile, won the event Tuesday night in
3:53.40, patiently waiting for three laps then drawing away with a
56.10-second final lap. However, the season's top performer, Hicham
el-Guerrouj of Morocco, did not compete.
</P>
<P>
   William Tanui of Kenya finished second in 3:54.05. Daniel Komen
of Kenya, the only person to run two miles under 8 minutes
(7:58.61), faded to third in 3:54.78. Steve Holman of the United
States went to the front early, but got tangled up and fell early
in the bell lap.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100 meters for disabled runners, Brian Frasure, who
trains in the same sprinting group with Marion Jones and coach
Trevor Graham in Raleigh, N.C., won in 11.44 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   With Greene, Boldon and Bailey, trash-talking in the open 100
meters has come to rival the bluster of professional wrestling.
Bailey has made thinly-veiled drug references to Greene and Boldon.
Greene has said that Bailey was using hamstring and tendon injuries
as an excuse to duck Greene and Bailey this season and to explain
away inevitable failure. The antagonism began in earnest at the
1997 world championships in Athens. Bailey entered as the 1995
world champion, the 1996 Olympic champion and the world
record-holder from the Atlanta Games. Greene had been a sprinter of
unfulfilled potential who moved last season from his home in Kansas
City, Kan., to train with Boldon and Coach Smith.
</P>
<P>
   By late summer of 1997, Smith had refined Greene's technique,
teaching him to use his speed more evenly and maintain it longer in
the 100 meters. In the past, Greene had often produced searing
starts only to run out of gas before the finish. Like a mechanic,
Smith took apart Greene's engine and put it back together again. He
won the 1997 national championship and arrived in Athens a month
later as a threat to Bailey's supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals at the world championships, Bailey looked
dismissively at Greene, asserting that he was over his nagging
injuries and said, ``I'm back.'' Greene replied, ``Yeah, but I
gotcha.'' And in the final he did, winning the world title with a
personal best of 9.86 seconds, tying the third-fastest time in
history. At 23, he had run as fast as Carl Lewis ever had. As he
crossed the finish line in Athens, Greene stuck his tongue out
scornfully at Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Greene set a world indoor record of 6.39 seconds
for 60 meters. In May, he ran the 100 meters in a 9.79 100 meters _
a half-second under Bailey's record and the same time that Ben
Johnson ran in his disgraced race at the 1988 Summer Olympics _ but
the wind was over the allowable limit for record purposes. A 9.84
race run last month at the national championships was also
wind-aided.
</P>
<P>
   Boldon began his sprinting career at Jamaica High in Queens, New
York City, when he was spotted on the soccer field by the track
coach, Joe Trupiano. He had moved from Trinidad to New York at age
14 with his mother. Boldon has credited his quick starts partly to
drills that Trupiano employed in the hallways at Jamaica High. One
of the drills required the sprinters to lay on the floor until they
heard Trupiano drop an eraser or a paper clip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-365&AMP;     07-22 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS KEEP PIRATES FROM CROSSING HOME PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rick Reed provided one of his amazingly precise
pitching performances Tuesday night. So precise that the only
unanswered question was why Mets manager Bobby Valentine did not
leave him in to pitch the ninth inning and possibly record a
shutout. So precise that Reed's greatest concern after the 4-0
victory over Pittsburgh was how quickly he could pack for the
departure to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of enjoyable night for the Jekyll-and-Hyde Mets
at Shea Stadium. The kind in which Todd Pratt replaced the injured
Mike Piazza at catcher and started the biggest inning the Mets have
fashioned in two weeks. The kind in which Todd Hundley looked a bit
more like himself at the plate and a bit more like a decent left
fielder on defense. The kind in which the Mets looked more like
wild-card contenders than pretenders, even if it was for one night.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Reed on the mound will do that. Spotting his fastball on
the inside corner and brushing the outside corner with breaking
balls and changeups, Reed confounded the Pirates for eight
determined innings. He throttled them on six hits while striking
out nine, including six who gazed at strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Reed is a real pro, and he has proven it to everyone who
has watched him,'' said Valentine, who used John Franco for the
ninth because Reed is pitching a day game in his next start and
because of the humid weather. ``We've had a couple of tough games
and he wanted to keep the rotation going.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Reed tamed the Pirates and because the Pirates put fancy
wrapping on New York's four-run third inning, the Mets finished a
disappointing homestand with a 5-7 record. Although the Mets tossed
three combined shutouts in the last five games _ contests started
by Reed, Hideo Nomo and Al Leiter _ it was not a rollicking 12-day
stay at Shea. But Reed (11-6) gave the Mets momentum as they hit
the road for seven games in five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got the four-run lead, it gave me some breathing
room,'' said Reed, who held the Pirates to 2 hits in 10 at-bats
with runners on. ``It makes a difference because you don't have to
be perfect. After we scored, I felt like a different pitcher.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Different from the pitcher who struggled in the first inning.
Tony Womack and Keith Osik singled to start the game, and Turner
Ward bunted them to third and second. Reed was in trouble, but he
rebounded to strike out Kevin Young and induce Jose Guillen to chop
a ball behind the mound.
</P>
<P>
   It was Pittsburgh's best chance, and even the modest Reed said:
``Getting out of that inning was huge. That was the ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was not surprised that Reed survived the threat and gave
the Mets their first triumph over the Pirates in the last six
games. ``He has good concentration and he knows what he wants to
do,'' Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, who started because Piazza has a stiff right elbow, had a
double off Jason Schmidt (8-7) to start the third, the same Schmidt
who has not won in his last nine starts. Rey Ordonez pushed a nifty
bunt to second for a single that advanced Pratt to third, from
where he scored when Reed's dribbler slithered past Womack's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Edgardo Alfonzo rapped a two-run double down
the third-base line for a 3-0 lead, and Hundley later launched a
double to the left-center warning track to make it 4-0. Hundley
also had an assist from left field when he threw behind Lou Collier
and caught him straying too far off third base after Womack's
double in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roberto Clemente,'' Hundley said, joking. ``That's me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets still had runners on second and third after Hundley's
double and were hoping to enrich the most productive inning of
their homestand when the baseball show turned into a sideshow.
After the plate umpire, Bob Davidson, called Huskey out on a 3-2
fastball, Huskey jumped in front of the plate in protest and walked
away.
</P>
<P>
   Once Huskey returned to the dugout, Davidson heard a voice shout
at him, and he instantly ejected the Mets right fielder. Both
Huskey and Valentine streaked toward Davidson, with Huskey pointing
his finger in the umpire's face and hollering at him. Why were they
so perturbed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say anything,'' Huskey said. ``Someone said something
from the bench. It wasn't me.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he told Davidson that Huskey was innocent and
conceded that he had been the one barking from the dugout. Asked
what he had screeched, Valentine said, ``Damn.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter. Tuesday night, Reed's snazzy pitching
enabled the Mets to laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
