<SLUG> BC-PLANE-FIRE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMICALS SUSPECTED IN DC-10 FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Transportation Safety Board said
Tuesday that it suspected the cause of an in-flight fire on a
Federal Express DC-10 in September 1996 was improperly shipped
hazardous material, volatile chemicals in a piece of biomedical
equipment. But Tuesday's final report on the incident stopped short
of identifying those chemicals as the definitive cause of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The five people on the Memphis-to-Boston flight escaped injury,
but the DC-10 and most of its cargo was destroyed in the fire,
which burned for four hours after the plane made an emergency
landing at Stewart Airport in Newburgh, N.Y. No one on the ground
was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The board also said that the accident showed that the Federal
Aviation Administration and the airline industry had not done
enough to minimize the risk posed by in-flight fires, even after a
crash that killed 110 people aboard a Valujet passenger plane in
the Everglades. That crash, caused by hazardous materials that were
packed improperly, occurred four months before the DC-10 caught
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the plane was mechanically sound, and that
the fire was started by cargo, but not cargo declared as hazardous
by the shipper. The plane was carrying cargo that was declared as
hazardous, but it was later found in containers that were intact.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect that the fire began in a DNA synthesizer,
used in the pharmaceutical industry. The synthesizer, built by
Chiron Corp., of Emeryville, Calif., had two highly volatile
chemicals in it.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that a review of the cockpit voice recorder
after the Federal Express fire showed that the crew had not put on
smoke goggles or oxygen masks, which experts say are crucial to
safety if a fire spreads quickly. Pilots say the gear is difficult
to put on, uncomfortable and severely restricts their vision.
</P>
<P>
   George Black, one of the five members of the safety board, said
that the incident showed the need for better training and equipment
that crews would be willing to wear. ``We're running the chance
that a crew that's already in trouble, with a fire and smoke on
board, not having adequate vision to properly land the airplane, if
they make it that far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA promised in November to immediately act on that issue,
but has not. In August 1997, 15 months after the Valujet crash near
Miami International Airport, the safety board recommended that the
FAA stress to pilots the importance of putting on goggles and
breathing equipment at the first indication of smoke or fire. Smoke
can fill a cockpit so suddenly, safety board experts say, that a
pilot who waits until smoke appears may be overpowered before
equipment can be put on.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokesman, Les Dorr, said that the agency was working on
a bulletin to make that point to pilots. The agency originally said
that it would issue the bulletin in November, but then decided to
check the condition and use of cockpit smoke goggles and masks
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact it does not appear that the industry is doing things
exactly the way they should,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, the chairman of the safety board, complained Tuesday
that the FAA had failed to inform the board when it decided not to
issue the bulletin in November, as it had promised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
