<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockies' Brownson tosses 4-hitter
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Two hours, 10 minutes, no runs.
</P>
<P>
   That is pretty much all you need to know about what happened at
the Astrodome on Tuesday night. The Astros sped out of town ahead
of schedule but behind on the scoreboard thanks to Colorado Rockies
pitcher Mark Brownson, who tossed a four-hit shutout in his
major-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-0 loss snapped the Astros' four-game winning streak and
was their shortest game of the season. The Astros departed for a
five-game road trip to Los Angeles and San Diego after Tuesday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to get beat, you don't want to get beat
slowly,'' Astros center fielder Carl Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownson took care of that, making short work of the Astros
before a crowd of 28,718. The young righthander took a no-hitter
into the sixth inning and needed only 100 pitches to tag the Astros
with their third shutout loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we face a guy we haven't seen before, we don't seem
to fare too well,'' Astros catcher Brad Ausmus said. ``We were a
little flat, which compounded his mastery. He did well, and we
weren't good; that combination leads to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Zero also is the number of wins Astros pitcher Mike Hampton has
in his past five starts. If afforded a mulligan for the first
inning, Hampton was every bit as good as Brownson. Unfortunately
for Hampton, one bad inning was all it took to kill any hope of his
first victory since June 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies banged Hampton around for four runs in the first
inning, which was more than enough support for Brownson, who came
within one out of matching the Rockies' record for hitless innings
at the start of a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play in the Kerry Wood game (the Astros struck out 20
times and managed just one hit), but I think this was the best game
pitched against us all year,'' Everett said. ``You have to give
(Brownson) his due.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood helped the Chicago Cubs blank Atlanta 3-0 on Tuesday night.
The second-place Cubs moved to within four games of the Astros in
the National League Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   His sterling debut notwithstanding, there was nothing in
Brownson's Class AAA statistics that suggested he was capable of
stifling a team with as many offensive weapons as the Astros.
Brownson was 6-8 with a 5.13 ERA in 20 starts for the Rockies'
top-level minor-league club at Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a guy come up from the minor leagues and pitch
like that in his first game,'' Rockies manager Don Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownson had almost flawless command of a fastball, curveball,
changeup and slider, but Everett believes his best weapon might
have been his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't have that deceiving motion, he'd be in trouble,''
Everett said. ``That really helps him. You could see his pitches,
but he had fastball arm speed on a changeup, and we were swinging
at his motion instead of swinging at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, who snapped a six-game losing streak, didn't have
any problem solving Hampton in the first inning. Shortstop Neifi
Perez's seventh homer of the season opened the scoring, and his
buddies just kept piling it on. Vinny Castilla's RBI single, Todd
Helton's sacrifice fly and Mike Lansing's RBI double gave the
Rockies an early 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brownson retired 14 of the first 17 batters he faced
and kept the Astros off-balance by precisely locating his fastball
and by changing speeds masterfully. The 23-year-old rookie often
managed a 30-mph differential between his fastball and his breaking
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched well, and we didn't swing the bats particularly
well,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``He just beat us.
It was as plain and simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton spoiled the no-hit bid with a leadoff double to left in
the sixth inning. The pitcher was wiped out on the bases attempting
to move from second to third on Biggio's bunt single down the
third-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Brownson sat down the Astros in order in the seventh and worked
around Ricky Gutierrez's leadoff double in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about (a no-hitter),'' Brownson said. ``I
noticed it in the fifth, but I was trying to be realistic. I never
thought I was going to no-hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton retired 19 of the 24 batters he faced after the first
inning and didn't allow another runner to advance beyond second
base with the exception of Castilla, who led off the sixth with a
home run. Rookie lefthander Trever Miller pitched a scoreless ninth
in relief of Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamp was aiming the ball early in the game,'' Ausmus said.
``He was trying to be too fine. He flip-flopped and got back to the
old Mike Hampton, though. The second half of the game was
definitely the Mike Hampton we know.''
</P>
<P>
   The spacious comfort of the Astrodome helped Brownson preserve
his shutout in the bottom of the ninth. Jeff Bagwell hit a towering
fly ball to the center-field wall, but Ellis Burks was there to
make the grab and secure the youngster's gem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're facing someone who is just up from
Triple-A, you can jump on him right away,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``That obviously wasn't the case tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't take long for it to become obvious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
