u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      07-22 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE AND JETER MAKE SHORT WORK OF TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the night after, David Cone restored some
semblance of sanity to Yankee Stadium. The New York Yankees and the
Detroit Tigers did not play 26 innings, or even 17. They did not
take 5 hours 50 minutes to play the game that the Yankees won
Tuesdy night, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, with a little help from his friends, tucked the Tigers
away in a relatively crisp 2 hours 46 minutes, providing the
perfect antidote to the exhaustion that overtook the players the
night before.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to mount a strong case for his first full-season Cy
Young award, Pedro Martinez notwithstanding, Cone stymied the
Tigers on eight hits, allowed no earned runs, walked only one and
struck out 10 in eight innings. The game marked the 10th time in
his last 11 starts that Cone, who won the Cy Young in the
strike-shortened 1994 season, has permitted fewer than three earned
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers scored against Cone in the first inning, but they did
it with the aid of an error by Scott Brosius, who let Tony Clark's
bouncer get through him with runners at first and third. The Tigers
scored no more.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, on the other hand, staged a varied offensive as the
first two hitters in their lineup produced three runs with bats and
legs. Derek Jeter and Chuck Knoblauch each hit a home run in the
same game for the second time this season, and Jeter used a walk
and two stolen bases to put himself in position to score on a
sacrifice fly by Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to go extra innings,'' a weary Jeter had said
before the game, and he took steps to make sure the game ended in
the regulation nine.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Yankees' 70th of this magical season, the
first time in the franchise's glorious history that the team has
won 70 of the first 95 games. With 67 games remaining, the Yankees
need to win 47 to register the most victories in a major league
season.
</P>
<P>
   A 47-20 record computes to a .701 percentage. The Yankees' 70-25
season record produces a .737 percentage.
</P>
<P>
   In gaining his 14th victory, most in the majors, against three
defeats, Cone has an .824 winning percentage. His 3.44 earned run
average is misleading because he gave up 16 earned runs in his
first two starts. Subtract those spring training-like performances,
and Cone has a nifty 2.51 ERA, a figure that more accurately
reflects the impressive pitching that the 35-year-old right-hander
has provided this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' master did his best pitching Tuesday night in the
first and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   After the first-inning error by Brosius left runners at first
and third with one out, Cone struck out Luis Gonzalez and retired
Geronimo Berroa, always a dangerous Yankee Stadium hitter, on an
infield popup.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bako, who at that point had caught 28 consecutive innings
over two nights and three games, led off the seventh with a single
to center field, the third of his four hits. Deivi Cruz, the ninth
batter in the Detroit lineup, then struck out. So did Brian Hunter,
who extended his series futility to no hits in 18 at-bats over two
nights and three games.
</P>
<P>
   But Damion Easley rapped a grounder past a diving Brosius for a
double that sent Bako to third. Bobby Higginson, whose two-run home
run made Monday night's second game closer than the Yankees liked,
was the next batter, but Cone did not let him repeat his effort. He
threw a third strike past him, and the threat, that quickly, was
ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
