<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES _ sports COWBOYS' NEWTON ENDS SILENT(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE IVEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Guard Nate Newton doesn't want to talk
about his weight, or lack thereof, but at least he's talking.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old veteran ended his vow of silence with reporters
Tuesday after morning workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk about weight, I am not going to talk to
you. If you want to talk about me advancing and being a part of
this team, or you want to talk about the offensive line, I'll talk
about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, listed on the training camp roster at 320 pounds,
accepted part of the blame for last season's offensive line woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was injured the whole year and never got in top shape, so I
put a lot of that on me,'' he said. ``I put like 60 percent on me.
... I am a Pro Bowl player and last year I came out and I was an
average player. I let everybody down, but most of all I let myself
down.''
</P>
<P>
   He said last season's disappointment motivated him to get back
to the form that earned him All Pro recognition from 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I had to do to get back here,'' he said. ``Whether
it was me losing weight, or keeping my mouth closed or not going
out and having a good time or whatever, I'm here.'' ELLIS SITS OUT
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft choice Greg Ellis didn't participate in
practice Tuesday after experiencing back spasms, Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey said. He is listed as day-to-day. Gailey said Ellis, a
6-foot-6 defensive end, has no history of back problems. FIRST
WORKOUT THRILLS TEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Safety George Teague participated in his first full practices of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenalin was flowing all last night, up until today,''
Teague said. ``It feels extremely good just to able to get back and
run around full time.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague's activities were limited to stretching and conditioning
last week while he recuperated from arthroscopic knee surgery last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any problems with my knee,'' he said. ``It
hasn't flared up. It didn't hurt or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Teague long to get in his first solid hit. He
gave Billy Davis a hard shot after Davis had caught a pass over the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   In his second stint with the Cowboys, Teague is among four
players trying to fill the free safety position vacated by Brock
Marion, who signed as a free agent with Miami. Teague's competition
includes second-year players Kenny Wheaton and Omar Stoutmire and
third-year player Charlie Williams. SHOTGUN LOADED
</P>
<P>
   Gailey expressed disappointment last week with how the offense
picked up from where it left off at the last minicamp in the first
week in June, saying he thought players looked rusty.
</P>
<P>
   He was much happier with how the players looked Tuesday when
they began practicing the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked back up on the shotgun better than we did the base
offense,'' Gailey said. ``I guess the overall timing, having thrown
the ball around for three or four practices, enhanced our picking
back up on the shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun, absent from the Cowboys' playbook most of this
decade, will be used in third-and-long and two-minute situations.
HE SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmitt is the starter and I'm just here to complement him on
offense in any way I can, whether it's 10 carries \Rper game\S or
30, or maybe catching a pass out of the backfield. I'm comfortable
with that.'' _ Chris Warren,
</P>
<P>
   The all-time leading rusher for Seattle before he signed with
the Cowboys in April
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
