<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S TORRID JULY CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Just in case the citizens of Florida's
Suncoast hadn't already heard it, Ken Griffey Jr. spent a good deal
of his pre-game clubhouse media session Tuesday night disavowing
any interest in home run races. Particularly those with his name in
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a game matching teams moving in opposite directions, he
went out and stirred some more home run conversation, splattering
his 40th to center field as the Mariners kept a good July going
with an 8-3 victory over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about (Mark) McGwire,'' Griffey said. ``I don't
worry about Sammy (Sosa). I worry about the guy that's 60 feet in
front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, he never thinks about it,'' Jay Buhner ribbed loudly, a
couple of locker stalls away, after the M's had registered their
seventh victory in eight games. ```What do I need, 21 more?'''
</P>
<P>
   Before this night, Griffey had exactly five hits in 30 career
at-bats against lefthander Wilson Alvarez. He had three more in his
only tries against Alvarez, whose forgettable season Griffey and
the M's made a little more unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez (4-8), who hasn't won since May 15 and who lost seven
weeks to shoulder tendinitis, was tagged for three doubles in a
four-run Mariner first, and later, homers by Griffey and Russ
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's 40th came 27 days earlier than his 40th of 1997, which
he struck on Aug. 17. In a season when he hit 56, he had 24 after
Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the M's perking with a 12-5 record this month,
and, even at 9{ games behind Texas, sustained the notion that their
season may not yet be kaput.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have very easily rolled over a month ago, two months
ago, and said the season's over,'' said Jamie Moyer, who went eight
innings and evened his record at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't accomplished anything yet, but it could be fun.
It's going to be fun trying to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight brings a confrontation notable on two counts: It is a
fetching matchup of Randy Johnson against the Rays' All-Star,
righthander Rolando Arrojo, whose 11 victories and 2.87 ERA lead
all American League rookies.
</P>
<P>
   In this same stadium late in May, when reports had him all but
dealt to the Dodgers, Johnson was widely believed to be making his
last start as a Mariner. Two months later, he could be doing that
again, although the club's resurgence weighs against it.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would accept the kind of run support Moyer got from the
M's Tuesday night. The first pitch Alvarez threw was kissed for a
double into the right-field corner by second baseman Rich Amaral,
and the last one Alvarez launched was hit for a double to almost
the same spot by catcher John Marzano.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the M's had all seven of their runs, and although Moyer
wasn't razor-sharp _ allowing homers by Bubba Trammell and Bobby
Smith _ he didn't have to be. The expansion Rays are hitters only
in a loose sense _ they have been shut out a shocking 13 times, and
upon entering the game with 345 runs, they trailed the next-worst
AL run-producing team, Kansas City, by 69.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mariners, there was very little to quibble about. For
one, Davis, playing his third game in left field, had a two-run
double to go with his homer, and he caught a fly ball in left. He
had had two other chances in left field in his earlier appearances,
and erred on both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russ has been swinging the bat real well,'' Mariner manager
Lou Piniella said. ``And he got himself a fielding average, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's, so often leaky in the field, were almost superlative in
this game. Alex Rodriguez first made a pretty play on a difficult
chopper and then ran down a blooper in short left. And David Segui
denied Fred McGriff with a lunging, backhand stab of a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are rallies that aren't getting started,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only sour note was the flareup of Buhner's left
knee, necessitating his removal from the game in the second inning.
Piniella said he probably will be rested tonight, to welcome the
grass in Baltimore after another off-day.
</P>
<P>
   A media contingent of 15-20 left Piniella to crowd around
Griffey, getting little but trying, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's lot of home runs,'' Piniella mused, pondering Griffey's
40, which still trails McGwire's 43. ``My God, we're only in July.
It's scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
