</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, GONZALEZ `DEEP SIX' ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Texas Rangers do not rely on the home
run.
</P>
<P>
   This lineup achieved success using the two elements manager
Johnny Oates deems most critical for offensive prosperity: on-base
percentage and hitting with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's 15-5 victory against the Kansas City Royals
served as an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman Stadium served as a launching pad on this warm, muggy
evening, and the Rangers discharged six home runs measuring 2,393
feet _ the length of more than 61/2 football fields.
</P>
<P>
   That made little impression upon Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go around hitting six home runs every night,'' Oates
said. ``Now, I like the runs. I'll take the runs. It was nice to
put the big number up there in the first inning, but you know I'm
not an advocate of the home run. I'm an advocate of the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve Rangers runs crossed the plate as a result of a home run.
Designated hitter Juan Gonzalez, who had three of the Rangers' 17
hits, drove in five runs with two 400-foot blasts and a run-scoring
single.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, perhaps right fielder Mike Simms _ a platoon player who
starts against left-handed pitchers _ supplied the evening's most
significant at-bat with his three-run home run in the first inning
off Royals left-hander Jose Rosado (4-8).
</P>
<P>
   Simms extended the inning with a 414-foot home run with two
outs, and a three-run home run later in the inning by center
fielder Roberto Kelly gave the Rangers an nine-run advantage before
the Royals' first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Simms continues to be extraordinarily productive in his role.
The home run gives Simms 26 RBI through 94 at-bats this season.
That represents an RBI per 3.6 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's me,'' said Simms, who matched his
single-season best with his ninth home run. ``I think that's a
credit to the guys hitting in front of me and getting on base. I
can't take any credit for that. A player can't get any RBI if no
one is on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies their secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers built the American League's most prolific offense
with their on-base percentage and ability to hit with runners in
scoring position. The Rangers entered Tuesday night's games leading
the league in hitting with runners in scoring position (.307) and
ranked second in on-base percentage (.355).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the two most prolific offensive teams in this league _
the Rangers and Yankees _ entered Tuesday night's games ranked
seventh and 10th, respectively, in home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the six home runs represented the second-most
during a single game by the Rangers, who launched seven against the
Twins on Sept. 13, 1986, at the Metrodome. Gonzalez's performance
gave him six home runs and 22 RBI during seven games this season
against the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps lost in this slugfest was Rick Helling's complete-game
victory. The right-hander's effort represented the Rangers' first
complete game since May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (13-5) surrendered five runs (four earned) on seven
hits, including two home runs, but he did not issue a walk. Helling
threw 102 fastballs in his 126-pitch appearance for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hot out there,'' Helling said of the 95-degree heat.
``All I wanted to do was get our team off the field and into the
dugout as quickly as possible. I basically said, `Here it is. Hit
it if you can.'''
</P>
<P>
   It resulted in some well-hit balls, but Helling produced the
desired result.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he was supposed to do,'' Oates said. ``He got a
big lead, and he threw strikes. They hit a bunch of balls on the
nose right at our outfielders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers sent six unplayable balls over the heads of Royals
outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   That mattered little to Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you how many hits we had,'' Oates said. ``I had to
guess at the number of home runs we hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      07-22 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLARD PERSEVERING DESPITE ACHING BODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ The biggest joke going around the Seahawks'
training camp involves one of the team's largest players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been kidding House that they're going to have to
announce the defense before every game this year because he can't
run out of the tunnel,'' Grant Williams, a third-year tackle, said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   So much for respecting your elders.
</P>
<P>
   Howard ``House'' Ballard will be 35 in November, midway through
his 11th and probably final NFL season. His arthritic right knee is
a constant reminder of just how much he loves this game and will
miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Why else would Ballard continue to play?
</P>
<P>
   One of the most lasting memories of the past few seasons is the
6-foot-6, 330-pound Ballard down on all fours and looking as if he
will need to be dragged from the field while his teammates jog back
to the huddle. Somehow, some way, Ballard struggles to his feet,
limps to the line of scrimmage and makes a key block on the key
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``House has a very high pain tolerance,'' said Gregg Smith, who
coaches the offensive line. ``He cannot look very good running
around, but when it's time to do it, he's going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   To help ensure Ballard will be around to get it done, he sees
limited action in the afternoon on days when the team practices
twice. Ballard also won't play a lot in preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's healthy and can play, he's one of the best tackles
there is,'' Williams said. ``No players have ever given him
problems. The only thing that's ever slowed him down is his own
body.''
</P>
<P>
   And only recently. Until late last year, Ballard had played 154
consecutive games, starting 138 _ third longest among active
players behind the Oilers' Bruce Matthews (160) and the Steelers'
Dermontti Dawson (143). And then it was a fractured right forearm
that forced Ballard to sit out the final six games.
</P>
<P>
   But Ballard's knee has been bothering him the past few years _ a
memento of playing on four straight Super Bowl teams with the
Buffalo Bills (1990-93) and his entire career with clubs that play
on artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Seahawks sent Ballard back to Seattle during
training camp to have a magnetic resonance imaging test on the
knee. Ballard was hoping it would detect torn cartilage or
something else that could be removed to relieve the pain. Instead,
he was told if he continued to play it would be in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we just have to deal with,'' Ballard said.
``God is looking out for me, and we have been put in a situation
where the right play has been called at the right time. Some times
when we're really hurting really bad, the right play needs to be
called so we can recover for a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard is well aware of the long-term consequences of what he
is doing. He knows at some point he'll probably need an artificial
knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes down to that, there's nothing we can do to change
it,'' he said. ``We'd rather have that than the feeling that we
left the game when we could have played one more year.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something else you should know about Ballard. Some
athletes speak in the third person. He speaks in the plural. When
he says ``we'' he means ``me.'' Hey, when you're that big and go by
the nickname ``House,'' you deserve to be a ``we.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Ballard's fifth season with the Seahawks, who signed him
as a free agent in 1994. But he's the anchor on a line that has
been in constant flux. Kevin Glover, who was signed in free agency
this year, is the team's fourth starting center in Ballard's
tenure. He has played alongside three different starters each at
left tackle, left guard and right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard also is the leader of this group. He presides over the
locker room court that doles out fines to the linemen for various
offenses, and Ballard's word is final.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Ballard is still a pretty good football player, gimpy
knee and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last night we were watching (practice) film and you hear,
`Good job, House.' Or, `Good footwork, House,''' Williams said.
``He's just amazing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
