<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIVE AND KICKING, SEAHAWKS STARS ACCEPT SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ You're sitting in your living room, watching TV,
when one of those new Seahawk ads comes on.
</P>
<P>
   You know the ads: A mass of Seahawks running down a rain-soaked
street in downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Then you get the snippets and cameos and one-liners of some of
the Seahawks' young marquee players.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Springs, Walter Jones, Ricky Watters, Joey Galloway,
Michael Sinclair and Jason McEndoo _ all fresh and funny and
looking to make a good impression.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, fifth-year defensive tackle Sam Adams steals the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Adams adds a slam-dunk ending to the spunky ad. He goes
one-on-one against the camera as the 285-pounder shouts an urgent
message to anyone out there inclined to be a Seahawk fan:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo. We're alive and kicking. Wassup? Are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Adams starts to get up out of his chair. His eyes bug open
wide. The frame freezes with Adams staring wild-eyed and energetic
_ a look you can't quite forget.
</P>
<P>
   You know the TV spot has attitude and is destined to be a hit,
like the Paul Allen Seahawks are aiming to be after all the money
he has spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had me in there screaming and hollering and jumping
around. I like to rap a little, sing. But I was in there yelling
for so long. I was trying to get that out to the (producers): `Man,
I've been in here forever,''' Adams said Tuesday, as Day 2 of
two-a-days did not seem to diminish the club's enthusiasm and
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   According to Adams, there is little doubt the Seahawks are
moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   When Adams first came to the Seahawks as a first-round pick in
1994, ``It was cold. It was cold and old and dragging around. It
was slow. Mentally slow. And the attitude. It was sluggish,'' Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, it's peppy and spry and you look around and everyone
knows and feels that we should win. Not that we can possibly win if
we play well. We're supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this ad campaign is to bring Seahawks into your
living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the Mariners and Sonics. The (fans) know those people.
Why do they know those people? Because they're out there busting
their butt to get the players acquainted with the community,''
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   What's most amazing about this marketing campaign is that the
Seahawks actually have a slew of talented, charismatic and slightly
camera-hungry players capable of pulling this thing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like the spotlight, you shouldn't be playing pro
football,'' Springs said. ``We're just trying to drum up some
interest in the team, let people know that just because we're
athletes, because we're football players, we aren't mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let them know a little bit about us personally. And the
commercials can only help. When you know people are out there,
watching you on TV, supporting us, we have a heavier weight on our
shoulders. ... We cannot let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   With this kind of sincere mission statement, it's clear that the
days of Seahawk public relations straight out of ``Cops'' and
``NYPD Blue'' are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days of ex-Seahawk Patrick Hunter, intoxicated,
rolling his truck into a car outside a Bellevue bar.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days of allegations against running back Chris
Warren slapping a woman's rear end in an Eastside nightclub; the
curbside arrest of ex-back-up cornerback Orlando Watters, whose car
registration was expired and who police found with marijuana; coach
Dennis Erickson's major mistake of driving after too many drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone, it seems, is the nightmare of receiver Brian Blades'
horrific decision to take a loaded gun into the middle of a family
dispute and wind up with his beloved cousin dead.
</P>
<P>
   You almost feel guilty just bringing up these things, especially
since some members of the front office have been with the
organization since Day 1. There was never a question the Seahawks'
organization had a heart and a soul in the community. But there was
so much negative stuff that brought this organization to its knees,
you wondered if it could ever shine again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think your team reflects your management,'' two-time Pro
Bowler Sinclair said yesterday. ``Like with the Behrings. No
offense to them, but we carried the attitude of what was going on
in our upstairs office. Your top-echelon teams, your Super Bowl
teams, they have great front offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the players are ready to deliver the goods, in a snappy,
spry and fresh fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As professional athletes, we have to carry ourselves in a
professional manner, on and off the field. The job goes 365 days a
year,'' Adams said. ``As soon as we step off the field, we have to
carry ourselves in a manner that's respectable and acceptable in
the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The public eye is so used to the bad stuff, it's blinking in
amazed relief.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
