r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-22 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT REDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Or the big tease?
</P>
<P>
   The next couple of weeks could determine the Dodgers' intention.
And their direction. But they are beginning to bear watching.
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Cincinnati Reds 4-2 on Tuesday night before
30,452 fans at Dodger Stadium, the Dodgers won for the sixth time
in their last nine games and crept _ with colossal exertion _ to
two games above .500 (51-49) for the first time since mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   The effort had a familiar look: a strong performance by a
starting pitcher, in this case Ismael Valdes, some gritty work by
the relief staff, and just enough output from the usual offensive
suspects, Gary Sheffield, Eric Karros, Adrian Beltre and Raul
Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   It has put the Dodgers in the thick of the National League
wild-card race, and undoubtedly has interim general manager Tommy
Lasorda squirming over whatever move he might want to make next.
</P>
<P>
   This probably can't qualify as a surge _ not for a team that has
locked on .500 a total of 24 times this year. But it's a glimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to get anything, we need some kind of consistency
to get a streak going,'' said manager Glenn Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next couple of weeks, the Dodgers could be put to the
test in that regard. In a 12-game stretch, nine of the meetings
will be divided among a division leader (Houston, beginning tonight
at Dodger Stadium) and two of the teams that lie ahead of L.A. in
the wild-card standings (Philadelphia and New York). The latter two
series will be played on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's game was the type that tends to boost a team's
confidence, because it didn't come without considerable effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, leading 4-1 to start the seventh inning, quickly
faced a bases-loaded, one-out situation after Valdes faltered and
Sheffield and Mondesi crossed signals under a fly ball in
right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Radinsky got one critical out when he retired the
dangerous Reggie Sanders, a pinch hitter, on a pop to second.
Radinsky, after starting out 3-and-0 to the next man, pinch hitter
Barry Larkin, yielded a walk to force in a run. But the Dodgers
survived disaster when Dmitri Young lined to Karros at first base
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was 4-2, and since the Dodgers now have Jeff Shaw in
their bullpen, that meant they had a realistic chance of holding
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jeff closing the door, he's a closer who can do the
job,'' said Valdes, who improved to 8-9. ``He throws strikes. He
knows what to do out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's giving the Dodgers a luxury they haven't enjoyed in
some time.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, acquired from the Reds for Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes
on July 4, turned away his former team for the second straight
night. Hoffman called on him early, in the eighth inning, with a
man on, two out and... Konerko at the plate?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Yet another bizarre sight in this Twilight Zone season for
the Dodgers. Shaw got a fielder's choice grounder in that
confrontation, ending the inning, then went 1-2-3 in the ninth for
his 27th save _ and his fourth in as many opportunities since
joining the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told (Hoffman) a lot of work is not unusual for me, the
eighth inning is not unusual for me,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The way he's pitched lately, he should make sure he keeps his
arm limber. Shaw has retired 22 of the 24 batters he's faced, seven
by strikeout, since arriving here.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, meanwhile, continued a solid stretch of work that began
six weeks ago and has included two complete-game shutouts. He
worked 61/3 innings on five hits and two runs, striking out six _
two of them on called third strikes to end innings with a runner in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does well when he locates his fastball because he has very
good offspeed stuff,'' said catcher Charles Johnson. ``When he can
throw his fastball in and out (corners of the plate) he's tough,
because he can get people out with his breaking ball. You can't
just sit on one pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, by contrast, sat on a few from Reds starter Brett
Tomko (9-7) in the early innings _ and squashed them.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Beltre hit the second home run of his
major-league career, a bomb to center to drive in Karros, who had
singled.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Sheffield, with a single, and Karros, with a
double the other way, each drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for the Dodgers attack. Valdes welcomed the four
runs, though _ it was more output than the Dodgers had provided in
12 of his previous 20 starts this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
