<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECURITIES
</P>
<P>
   Open positions of short sales on the New York Stock Exchange
increased 1.97 percent in the last month, to 4.13 billion shares on
July 15, surpassing last month's record of 4.05 billion shares, the
exchange reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figure equaled 1.6 percent of all shares listed on
the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   On the smaller American Stock Exchange, short interest fell 0.4
percent as of July 15, to 194.38 million shares from 195.07 million
shares, the exchange reported.
</P>
<P>
   A short position is created when an investor sells shares that
have been borrowed. If the share price falls, the investor can
profit by buying shares at a lower price to replace the borrowed
ones.
</P>
<P>
   While an increase in a short position may indicate a rise in
bearish attitudes toward stock prices, the volume of short
positions can also increase because of complex trading strategies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   Kinko's Inc. in Ventura, Calif., said on Tuesday that it had
named TBWA Chiat/Day in Venice, Calif., to handle its worldwide
account, with billings estimated at $40 million. The creative
portion had been handled by the Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney unit of
Publicis S.A. in Chicago, while the media portion had been handled
by CPM Media Management in Chicago; both agencies and Kinko's
parted ways in May.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a two-month review that had been
narrowed to TBWA Chiat/Day, part of Omnicom Group, and two other
finalists: Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York, part of the Lowe Group
unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies, and Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New
York, a unit of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The Kmart Corp.is joining the ranks of retailers promoting their
private-label jeans lines with a national television campaign for
its Route 66 brand. The commercials are unusual for Kmart in their
hip, contemporary attitude meant to reach younger consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The coming back-to-school shopping season is ``the perfect time
to appeal to the teens and younger customers,'' said Larry Davis,
vice president for advertising at Kmart in Troy, Mich. The Route 66
line, which has been around for two years, has been expanded to
offer clothes for boys, girls, men and women; it competes against
brands like Canyon River Blues, sold by Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., and
Arizona, sold by the J.C. Penney Company.
</P>
<P>
   The two commercials in the campaign, created by Kmart's lead
agency, Campbell Mithun Esty in Minneapolis, are infused with an
edgy attitude that contrasts markedly with Kmart's general market
advertising. That is underlined in the theme: ``Route 66. Clothes.
Jeans. It's not Mainstreet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the commercials appeal to the young, spirited
customer,'' said Joe Sapienza, product development director at
Kmart, ``and that is obviously whom we are targeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, for which spending was not disclosed and which
just began, will run for four weeks, Davis said, to be followed by
additional commercials in the fall. Campbell Mithun is majority
owned by the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. said on Tuesday that it
had expanded its relationship with the BBDO Worldwide unit of
Omnicom Group in New York by naming BBDO Asia-Pacific to handle
creative duties for the Pepsi-Cola and Mountain Dew brands in
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam, and media planning and account management duties for its
Mirinda and 7Up brands in those countries. The duties, with
billings estimated at $40 million, had been handled by offices of
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New York, part of WPP Group PLC. BBDO
Asia-Pacific was awarded the assignments after a review that also
included another unit of WPP, the J. Walter Thompson Company. BBDO
now handles Pepsi-Cola brand advertising in 59 countries.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   International Home Foods Inc., Parsippany, N.J., the maker of
Bumble Bee tuna and Pam cooking spray, said it had bought Libby's
canned meat business, which has revenues of $139 million, from
Nestle S.A., for undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Gencorp, Fairlawn, Ohio, a maker of polymer products, aerospace
systems and automotive sealing components, agreed to acquire the
Sequa Chemicals unit of Sequa Corp., for undisclosed terms.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Services Corp., Hamilton, Ontario, a scrap-metal and
industrial-waste recycler, agreed to sell two businesses valued at
$35 million as part of its plan to cut its $1.1 billion bank debt.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Mary Doan, a top executive at the advertising agency of Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi in San Francisco and New York, said on Tuesday that she
would leave the agency, citing ``personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The project that I have been working on is done,'' said Ms.
Doan, 44, who has worked for Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, part of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi PLC, for nine years. ``It's time to take a break and do
something else.'' For the last 18 months, she served as worldwide
director for client service applications; before that, she was
chief executive of the San Francisco office. Roy Elvove, a
spokesman for Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, said that no successor would be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Laschever was named publisher of GQ magazine, New York,
part of the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance Publications,
succeeding Richard Beckman, now publisher of Vogue magazine, New
York, also part of Conde Nast. Laschever had been president and
group publisher of Departures, Your Company and Sky Guide
magazines, New York, which are published by the American Express
Publishing Co. and the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., San Francisco, named William Chiasson chief
financial officer, effective next month, succeeding George James,
who retired on June 30. Chiasson is senior vice president-finance
and information systems of Kraft Foods Inc., a unit of Philip
Morris Cos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith Corona Corp., Cortland, N.Y., said its chairman, Peter
Parts, had been named president and chief executive, succeeding W.
Michael Driscoll, who retired from his management position but will
continue to work as a consultant.
</P>
</TEXT>
