<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOGAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Hogan memorabilia leaving Colonial 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The widow of golf legend Ben Hogan has
reached an agreement with U.S. Golf Association officials to move
the brunt of Hogan's memorabilia from Colonial Country Club to the
USGA Museum and Library in Far Hills, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Parties with knowledge of the negotiations confirmed the
agreement Tuesday, but said a binding contract has not been signed.
Andy Mutch, USGA curator, said a formal announcement of the
agreement is planned for later this week at the U.S. Senior Open in
Pacific Palisades, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Hogan, widow of the nine-time major champion who died
last July, was unavailable for comment Tuesday because she was at
the Senior Open attending a function to honor Hogan on the 50th
anniversary of his 1948 U.S. Open victory. The 1948 Open was held
at Riviera Country Club, site of this week's Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some time this week, the announcement will be made,'' Mutch
said, noting that the planned Hogan display will fill a
1,000-square-foot room at the USGA museum, also known as Golf
House. ``The contract hasn't been signed, sealed or delivered ...
but we plan to issue a press release from the Senior Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee Kelly, lawyer for the Hogan family, stressed that the deal
is not final and declined further comment. But several Colonial
members said Tuesday they are prepared for the majority of Hogan's
collectibles, which have been on display for four decades at the
club's Ben Hogan Trophy Room, to move to Golf House by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all disappointed, but there's no hard feelings on
anybody's part,'' said Marty Leonard, daughter of Colonial founder
Marvin Leonard and the person Valerie Hogan first informed of her
desire to move the collection in accordance with the wishes of her
late husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their business and their decision,'' Leonard said.
``Selfishly, I'd love to have them stay here for a lot of reasons.
For Colonial. For Fort Worth. But we need to respect their private
wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial members said Valerie Hogan has expressed a desire to
move the memorabilia to a venue that is more accessible to the
masses and offers heightened security measures. The USGA museum is
home to the world's largest collection of golf-related memorabilia
and receives 25,000 visitors per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been told before Hogan's death that he wanted ... the
whole world to be able to see these items, rather than just people
in this locality,'' said Clark Martin, Colonial president. ``He was
an international figure. I guess his stuff should be put where the
most people will enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the proposed agreement, Mutch confirmed that some
artifacts would remain at Colonial. But most items, including
Hogan's four U.S. Open medals, will head to Golf House.
</P>
<P>
   Security measures at Golf House, said Martin, would be superior
to those at the club. During the time the Hogan artifacts have been
on display at Colonial, there have been two burglaries _ one in
1980, when all items were recovered, and the other in 1992, when
Hogan's 1953 Hickock Belt was taken and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan received the jewel-encrusted, 18-carat gold buckle and
alligator belt for being selected the outstanding professional
athlete of the year. At the time of its disappearance, it carried
an insured value of $35,000. Apparently, the second burglary
weighed heavily in deliberations about housing the Hogan
collection, appraised at $650,000 by one expert in 1990, at Golf
House.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Golf Digest, Valerie Hogan said of the
potential move: ``I know it's quite a blow to Colonial. But it was
Ben's wish and my wish that we wanted those things where they'll be
safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where the majority of Hogan's trophies are housed,
Leonard said the club would maintain a display honoring the
five-time Colonial champ in the Ben Hogan Trophy Room. A committee
already has been formed to discuss renovation of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come up with another memorial for him,'' Leonard
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
