<HEADLINE>
MASSI EMERGES AS WINNER OF 122-MILE STAGE IN PYRENEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing) (rl) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUCHON, France _ The Tour de France entered the Pyrenees
Mountains Tuesday, and a sense of order returned to the overall
standing: Jan Ullrich, Bobby Julich, Bo Hamburger, Laurent Jalabert
and Luc Leblanc.
</P>
<P>
   Gone were Laurent Desbiens, Andrea Tafi and Jacky Durand, who
ruled the roost during the last few days and now are no higher than
Tafi's 54th place. Proving that anything is possible with enough
courage and savvy, however, an unlikely winner emerged after the
122-mile stage across the fabled Circle of Death peaks.
</P>
<P>
   That was Rodolfo Massi, an Italian who rides for Casino and not
one of the major climbers. He benefited from a long breakaway with
Cedric Vasseur, a Frenchman with GAN, and Alberto Elli, another
Italian with Casino, to give the French team its third victory in
10 stages of this 85th Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Massi did no work during most of the breakaway from the first
climb _ the daunting Aubisque peak, rated in the highest category
of difficulty _ through the second climb, the similarly rated
Tourmalet. Team strategy called for him to ride in the slipstream
of Elli and Vasseur, saving his strength for the last two climbs,
the Aspin and the Peyresourde, both rated first category, or a
notch lower than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth climb, Massi took off, leaving his weary teammate
and the unwitting Vasseur behind. Massi had enough power left to
hold off a late charge by Marco Pantani, an Italian with Mercatone
Uno, the winner of the recent Giro d'Italia and _ on the 364 other
days of the year _ a far superior climber to Massi.
</P>
<P>
   But Pantani reverted to his habit of unleashing his charge too
late and once again finished a Tour stage in second place. The
winner was timed in 5 hours 49 minutes 40 seconds, or 36 seconds
faster than Pantani across the finish line after an 8.1-mile
descent from the Peyresourde into Luchon.
</P>
<P>
   Third in the stage, which started in Pau, was Michael Boogerd, a
Dutchman with Rabobank, 59 seconds behind. Clocking the same time
were nine other riders, including Ullrich, a German with Telekom
and the defending champion; Julich, of Glenwood Springs, Colo.,
with Cofidis, and Leblanc, a Frenchman with Polti.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich regained the overall leader's yellow jersey, which he
yielded to Desbiens on Sunday. The German is 1:18 ahead of Julich.
Hamburger, a Dane with Casino, is third, 2:17 behind the leader,
with Jalabert, a Frenchman with ONCE, 2:38 behind and Leblanc 3:03
behind. The 151 remaining riders get another chance to climb
Wednesday before a day off on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An ecstatic Julich attempted to be blase afterward. ``Last year
I had goose bumps when I finished with the leaders in Morzine,'' he
said. ``This time I knew my place was with the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen riders quit the race in the Pyrenees, some out of
exhaustion, some because of crashes on foggy and slippery roads.
The major casualty was Francesco Casagrande, the Italian leader of
Cofidis, whom Julich was obligated to work for. With Casagrande
gone, the American becomes the team leader for whom everybody else
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody'' includes another American with Cofidis, Kevin
Livingston of Austin, Texas, a strong climber who finished 14th
Tuesday, 1:58 behind, and ranks 18th overall, 5:38 behind. He will
very likely excel Wednesday in the final climb to the Plateau de
Beille, which will make its debut in the Tour but which Livingston
knows from his second-place finish last year in the Tour de
l'Avenir.
</P>
<P>
   The weather turned overnight, dropping from a reading of 104
degrees to half that atop the climbs. A heavy fog and swirling
mist, especially on the first climb, contributed to the
difficulties, making descents from the four peaks treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor was the absence of the Festina team, which
was expelled in a drug scandal late Friday. The team's nine riders
are usually dominant in the mountains and would surely have
attacked Ullrich and the other favorites early in the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass., who rides with United States
Postal and who lost more than 18 minutes Monday when he suffered
heatstroke and finished in a daze, was able to brave the conditions
and complete Tuesday's stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he has had stomach troubles for the last month and
that he was not able to keep down any food or drink on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from such a high to such a low in two days,'' he said,
referring to his second place in the individual time trial on
Saturday to his 160th place Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he was game to see how he would do in the Pyrenees
when he spoke in Pau before the start of Tuesday's stage. ``I put
my body through a lot yesterday,'' he said. ``How it reacts today I
don't know. You can only push your body so hard and then it doesn't
want to go any harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton finished the mountain stage in 126th place, among a big
group of riders bringing up the rear, 31:34 behind Massi. In his
way, he rode just as courageous a race as the winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
