fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is a cultural encounter that foreshadows the
future of the United States _ but white America is so far taking
precious little notice.
</P>
<P>
   In its gleaming new convention center that sits right across
from the restored Amish market, this quintessentially WASP city of
William Penn is hosting upwards of 15,000 representatives of the
National Council of La Raza, the country's biggest organization of
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic delegates are conspicuous in a city center that
normally bustles with white and black. In the long corridors of the
convention center, there is a subdued air of Latin festivity and
the quiet buzz of Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   From the mainstream U.S. media, however, you would hardly know
that the Hispanics were around _ a point that rankles perpetually
with their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics have been quietly advancing and earning a place in
this country in a way that is not always understood in many of the
cities of the nation. And Philadelphia, we are afraid, may well be
one of them,'' said a bilingual editorial in Al Dia, one of the
region's clutch of Spanish-language newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   An article in Hispanic magazine put it more emotively: ``We are
_ whether we like it or not _ in the midst of the Hispanization of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are the America's fastest-growing ethnic minority.
Currently numbering around 30 million (11 percent), they are
expected to overtake the number of blacks within seven years.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2050, but probably before, Hispanics will comprise
more than 25 percent of the U.S. population and their growth will
be the main reason why, by that date, white Americans will find
themselves just another minority in the country they have regarded
for more than two centuries as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The vast implications of this demographic shift _ especially for
white Americans _ have hardly begun to be addressed, although they
lay at the heart of President Clinton's year-old initiative on race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Where the population at large fears to tread, however, business
and _ more tentatively _ politics, are starting to venture.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition hall in the Philadelphia convention center is
crowded with exhibitors, more than 500 in all, from department
store chains to car manufacturers, from community action groups to
health and housing watchdogs, all courting the burgeoning Hispanic
market.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker at lunch Monday was the first lady, Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother is standing for political office in Florida, one of
seven states where the Hispanic minority has electoral clout, so
`name recognition' is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker is the mayor of New York City, Rudolph Giuliani,
in what is billed his ``first major address to a national Latino
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Giuliani does not need their votes _ he was reelected by a
landslide last year. The Republicans, on the other hand, do, as
they look to this autumn's midterm congressional elections and the
presidential race in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Their standing with Hispanic voters has been severely harmed by
California's anti-immigration measures which led, in the words of a
Republican consultant's report, to the ``utter collapse of the
Hispanic vote'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both parties must consider one salient fact of
political life. As early as the next presidential election, the
Hispanic constituency will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   The big states of Texas and California, with 86 electoral
college votes between them, are already 25 percent Hispanic.
Hispanics are significant minorities also in Florida, Arizona, New
Mexico, Illinois, New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   This explains why there is now a rush by both parties to have
some sort of Hispanic representation on their presidential ticket
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In recent elections, the question has been when or whether it
would be politically decisive to have a black or a woman on the
ticket. Now, there is speculation that Bill Richardson, a former
senator from New Mexico who is about to go from the ambassadorship
of the U.N. to the post of Energy Secretary, is being considered as
a possible running mate for Al Gore for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's mother is Mexican, he is bilingual and popular with
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, son of the former president, present Governor of
Texas and a favored Republican candidate, has been assiduously
wooing Hispanic voters, helped by a Mexican sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Those who object that Hispanics cannot be treated as a
homogeneous ethnic minority or even as a solid voting block have a
point.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanics of California and Texas are predominantly recent
immigrants from Mexico and Central America and their families;
their opposition to tougher restrictions on immigration and
benefits has pushed them into the arms of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where the bias is towards Cuban exiles, with strong
anti-Castro sentiments, the vote has been Republican. In New
Mexico, where Hispanics constitute almost 40 percent of the
population, political sympathies are less clearly differentiated.
</P>
<P>
   At the La Raza convention this week, Hispanics are going out of
their way to present themselves as responsible and successful
Americans, a minority that has the highest male employment rate and
some of the best health indicators of any in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on the monolingual mainstream, however, of a sizeable
minority that speaks a different language has yet to be gauged. In
California and Texas, it has already caused tension, with
California withdrawing funds for bilingual education, and Texas
employers dismissing workers who persist in speaking Spanish
between themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic mix in those states today is that of America in 50
years' time. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 950-word article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
