<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 04:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6549 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUITION-TRAUMA-BUSTER     07-22 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUITION-TRAUMA-BUSTERS-RESEND-&AMP;SIDEBAR-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMART' MOVES: INVEST TODAY, SAVE ON TUITION TOMORROW  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING for those needing from July 7)   (This helpful 700-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance story _
WITH USER-FRIENDLY SIDEBAR AT END OF STORY _ is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By ELIF S. ARMBRUSTER  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fretting about how much the cost of college will have soared by
the time your kids are ready for four years in ivory-tower bliss?
</P>
<P>
   One increasingly appealing strategy is a prepaid-tuition plan,
which lets parents lock in tuition money now _ regardless of what
the costs are by the time Junior matriculates.
</P>
<P>
   The Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997 made many attractive adjustments
to these plans, so this is a good time to look them over.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, prepaid-tuition plans and tuition-savings plans are
state-run programs that allow families to pay a fixed sum of money
(in either monthly installments or a lump sum) for as many as 17 or
so years before a child is ready to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   With a prepaid plan, the money is guaranteed to cover tuition
later, regardless of the cost when a student is ready to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   With a savings plan, money is socked away now for college, but
if tuition has increased beyond what the plan anticipates, the
parents or student are responsible for the difference.
</P>
<P>
   With both plans, the money grows tax-deferred and, upon
withdrawal, is taxed at the student's income rate, not the
parents'. Since most students will fall into the 15 percent
bracket, there can be considerable tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   The key advantage to a prepaid-tuition plan is that parents lock
in a specific tuition price for a state school at the time they
begin investing, regardless of how much tuition increases for
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the amount parents pay is based on the age of their
child and the projected year of college entrance. Parents also
select how many years of college they would like to save for and
for which type of school, but there is no need to specify a school
at the time investing begins.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of a newborn in Mississippi, for example, can pay a lump
sum of $9,141 now or make 216 payments of $80 a month to cover four
years at a state university that begin in the year 2015 (based on
the average tuition and fees at public colleges, with a factor for
inflation).
</P>
<P>
   The benefit of the lump-sum payment is that you start earning
interest on the entire amount right away.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 1998, 14 states had prepaid-tuition plans, and five
had savings plans. According to the College Savings Plans Network,
in Lexington, Ky., another 20 states intend to launch programs this
year.
</P>
<P>
   To find out more about a specific plan, call CSPN
(606-244-8175), or visit its Web site at www.csg.org/cspn.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the 1997 tax bill, states are now allowed to accept
money to prepay room and board in addition to tuition. The law also
loosened the rules for which type of school and for which state the
money can be used.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the plans were once good only for publicly
supported schools in the state in which the family lived, many
states now allow families to use the money at any accredited two-
or four-year school _ public or private _ in the country.
</P>
<P>
   If Junior ends up at Harvard or Bennington, you'll simply have
to pay the difference in cost. Grandparents are also allowed to set
up a plan in the state where their grandchild lives.
</P>
<P>
   The savings plan will prove too conservative for some investors
_ the plans shoot for just a 5 percent to 6 percent gain, though
the tax advantages shouldn't be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid-tuition plans offer more of a hedge against runaway
inflation. ``States monitor tuitions and make sure earnings keep up
with tuition inflation,'' says Kathy Tyson, research manager at
CSPN. ``With savings plans, states try to earn as much money as
they can on them, but there's no guarantee they'll keep up with
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   If your child decides to pursue his or her acting dream and
forgo a college education together, there may be a considerable
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as Wisconsin, charge a 1 percent fee to
withdraw money from the plan. Others, such as Florida, will return
your money but without the interest it accrued _ a considerable
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Just one more reason to insist that the little ones finish their
education. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Elif S. Armbruster is a staff writer at WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SIDEBAR FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOES YOUR STATE OFFER PREPAID-TUITION OR TUITION-SAVINGS
PLANS? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Alabama: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Alaska: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Arizona: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Arkansas: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -California: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Colorado: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Connecticut: Savings plan in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Delaware: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Florida: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Illinois: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Indiana: Savings plan in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Iowa: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Kentucky: Savings plan in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Louisiana: Savings plan in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Maine: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Maryland: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Massachusetts: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Michigan: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Minnesota: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Mississippi: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Montana: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Nevada: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -New Hampshire: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -New Jersey: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -New Mexico: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -New York: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -North Carolina: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Ohio: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Pennsylvania: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Rhode Island: Savings plan starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -South Carolina: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Tennessee: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Texas: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Utah: Savings plan in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Virginia: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Washington: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -West Virginia: Prepaid tuition starts this year &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Wisconsin: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -Wyoming: Prepaid tuition in operation &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this user-friendly 700-word ``WORTH'' magazine
article _ PLUS HELPFUL 275-WORD SIDEBAR _ it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
