<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`SOLD'-CURB-APPEAL-RESEND-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME NEAT HOME: A SLOB'S GUIDE TO SELLING YOUR HOUSE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from July 7 for those needing)   (This helpful 525-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By RESHMA MEMON YAQUB  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a great time to be selling a house. Buyers are manic over
low interest rates. The new tax law lets sellers pocket up to
$500,000 in tax-free gains.
</P>
<P>
   But you're hardly the only seller on the block, so your chalet
could probably use, say, a grand's worth of attention. You'll
recoup the investment many times over when your house sells faster,
at the price it's really worth.
</P>
<P>
   Have a trusted friend walk through the property and point out
everything that's wrong, says Diane Shrewsberry, a real-estate
agent with Coldwell Banker.
</P>
<P>
   It'll hurt, but it's important, because you've stopped noticing
the tear in the screen, the lock that sticks, and the, uh, aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Take a walk yourself through a few builders' models, then steal
ideas, says Michael Holigan, host of the television series ``Your
New House.'' If white interiors are the rage now and you've got
busy wallpaper, start painting.
</P>
<P>
   Many buyers drive up to a house then refuse to go in because
something minor about the exterior turns them off, says
Shrewsberry.
</P>
<P>
   A new mailbox is an inexpensive way to make a good first
impression. So is a new welcome mat or even a new front door (or a
coat of paint on the old one.)
</P>
<P>
   Some more tips:
</P>
<P>
   Unclog the driveway. If your cars don't fit in the garage, park
in the street, says Ralph Roberts of Ralph R. Roberts Real Estate
in Detroit, Mich. Keep the garage door closed and trash cans out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Landscape. Plant whatever should be blossoming that time of
year, says Daryl Jesperson, president of RE/MAX International in
Denver, Colo. De-landscape, too: Overgrown trees make a house look
small; overgrown bushes block light.
</P>
<P>
   For indoor improvements, concentrate on the kitchen and master
bath, ``where people picture they'll spend most of their time,''
says Holigan. Essential: Wallpaper bathrooms. Re-caulk around tubs
(yellow caulk shows sales). Hang new shower-curtain liners.
</P>
<P>
   Think bright. Install higher-watt bulbs in low-light areas, like
closets. Make sure every single bulb in the house works. ``It's
quite a blooper when the lights don't come on,'' says Holigan.
</P>
<P>
   Simplify. Clear kitchen counters. De-junk closets, drawers and
medicine cabinets. If the space doesn't look big enough for your
stuff, it won't look big enough for theirs, says Jesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Don't rely on a realtor to provide info on schools in your area,
says Holigan. Leave information packets from local schools on your
kitchen counter, with your name, address, and phone number on top.
</P>
<P>
   Create a packet about your house, too, says Roberts. Have a
mortgage broker write out the cost of buying your home with various
percentages down. A buyer who might have considered the place too
expensive could realize that it is within range.
</P>
<P>
   By including the amounts of your monthly tax and utility bills,
you'll make buyers suspicious of homeowners who don't.
</P>
<P>
   A final caution: Once you've restored the house to its original
glory, be prepared to start wondering why you're moving out in the
first place. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Reshma Memon Yaqub is a staff writer at
WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this user-friendly 525-word ``WORTH'' magazine
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
New York Times sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
