<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 394 -- July 22, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. TALKING 'BOUT THEIR GENERATION In this exclusive interview,
rock child Sean Lennon and his girlfriend Yuka Honda (of the group
Cio Matto,) talk about his parents (John Lennon and Yoko Ono) and
their legacy, their own music, their latest release, ``Into The
Sun,'' and their Asian heritage. By Jim Cho. From A Magazine :
Inside Asian America. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
NATASHA RICHARDSON : ESCAPING THE STARDOM TRAP Fresh from her Best
Actress Tony Award for ``Cabaret,'' Natasha Richardson will star as
the mother in Disney's remake of ``The Parent Trap.'' The actress
is hotter than ever, despite having resolved not to fret about
career considerations. In this interview she talks about her roles,
her marriage to Liam Neeson and the challenges of growing up as the
daughter of the controversial Vanessa Redgrage. By Jeanne Wolf.
1,400 words + photo. (N/A England.)
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
CHRISTINA APPLEGATE IS LOOKING FOR A 'MAFIA' HIT As boy-crazy Kelly
Bundy on the TV series ``Married ... With Children,'' Christina
Applegate, 26, won many fans - as well as an image as a trashy,
empty-headed beauty. She has been busy trying to change that image.
In this interview she talks about her two newest projects : In
``Mafia,'' a spoof of gangster movies, she plays a Mafia girlfriend
who becomes president of the United States. In the autumn she will
return to television playing a single mother in the sitcom
``Jesse.'' By Jeanne Wolf. 1,400 words + photo. (N/A England.)
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
THE DANCING ANDROID A legless virtual android called Adonis has
been taught to ``dance'' the macarena as a first step in a project
designed to help robots learn by imitation. By Mark Ward. From New
Scientist magazine. 1,000 words. (N/A Australia, New Zealand,
Brazil.)
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
LAVINIA CURRIER : THE DEBUTANTE Even with wealth and connections,
it was no easy task for Lavinia Currier to produce her first
full-length film, ``Passion in the Desert,'' (based on a short
story by Balzac about a Napoleonic army officer lost in the Sahara
and his encounter with a leopard.) ``It was an odyssey,'' she says
about the five-year-long gestation of the film. In addition to the
difficult desert environment in Jordan where the movie was filmed,
the real challenge was presented by the film's central character -
a leopard. (Of all big cats, the leopard is the least predictable
and most deadly.) Interview by James Reginato. From W magazine.
1,700 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
SWEDISH DISH Swedish actress Lena Olin may have worked with Ingmar
Bergman while still a teenager, but in American films she tends to
play every nationality but her own. She was a Czech artist in''The
Unbearable Lightness of Being,'' an Eastern European in ``Enemies :
A Love Story,'' and a Russian assassin in ``Romeo Is Bleeding.''
This month she is at the centre of the romantic comedy ``Polish
Wedding,'' playing the proud but poor, vibrant matriarch of a
Polish family in Detroit. Olin, who doesn't make a movie unless
she's inspired, says this role was too good to turn down. By Joshua
Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
SAMUEL L. JACKSON : NEGOTIATIONS ARE HEATING UP In ``The
Negotiator,'' Samuel L. Jackson enjoys arguably the biggest role of
his career. It is the latest step forward for a man who began as a
promising young black actor but now, at 49, ranks with America's
finest actors of any colour. Jackson talks about the new movie, his
penchant for adopting a different ``look'' for each role, how he's
stayed off drugs and alcohol after nearly losing his life to
addiction a decade ago and why he'd like to produce and/or star in
a 'thinking man's slasher movie.' By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words +
photo
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
ADAM BEACH : 'SIGNALS OF RESPECT' There may be very few major
actors of Native American descent, but Adam Beach, 25, is
determined to change that. His film ``Smoke Signals'' has become an
unexpected art-house hit. It was written, produced and directed by
Native Americans and may be his ticket to the top. Beach talks
about the movie, his difficult youth after the deaths of his
parents in tragic accidents, his struggle to be authentically
Native American, without defining himself exclusively as Native
American, and why he thinks the film speaks to whites as well. By
Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
