<HEADER>
A6786 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANIBEL-SHELLS23-COX     07-22 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANIBEL-SHELLS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A beach-lover's guide to shells
 &HT;    By Gayle Pallesen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANIBEL, Fla. _ Still rosy with sleep, the sun emerges from warm
gulf waters and begins a lethargic ascent. Hunched over, eyes glued
downward, waves licking my ankles, I am ready. It's not yet 6:30
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   I temporarily shove aside the words of author Anne Morrow
Lindbergh: ``The sea does not reward those who are too anxious, too
greedy, or too impatient.'' I want to be first. I want to pick up
what treasures the sea has sprinkled along the shoreline during the
night. I am a shell hunter and, for me, the hunt has begun.
</P>
<P>
   What better place than an island with more than 20 miles of
beaches and 300 species of shells? Sanibel Island is rated by some
as the third-best shelling place in the world, outranked only by
Australia's Great Barrier Reef and the Philippine islands.
</P>
<P>
   My toes grasp something sharp. I reach into calf-deep water and
pick up a fighting conch. Too many barnacles. Dull finish. I toss
it back. ``Patience, patience, patience, is what the sea teaches,''
Lindbergh's words echo. Before long, I step on another sharp shell.
This one's a keeper: a shiny chocolate brown fighting conch.
Dropping it into my mesh drawstring bag, I begin walking the
shell-laced shoreline in search of lightning whelks and lace murex.
</P>
<P>
   It's not yet 7 a.m. and I still virtually have the beach to
myself. I stoop to pick up a moon shell when, from behind, I hear
the sound of footsteps crunching shells. A young Wisconsin couple,
plastic grocery sack in hand, rapidly pass by. They, too, want to
be first to pick through the night sea's offerings. About 30 feet
in front of me, they slow down and resume the ``Sanibel stoop,'' a
term describing hunched-over shellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience and faith. One should lie, empty, open, choiceless as
a beach _ waiting for a gift from the sea.'' Bunk. Maybe that
worked for Lindbergh, but not here on Sanibel, where there must be
more shellers per square inch than any place on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of white ibis dine at surf's edge. I walk a little faster
while scouring a blanket of miniature and broken shells.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged beanpole from North Carolina with knee-dirty tight
jeans, a ball cap and bifocals easily out-paces me. I stop him to
admire the specimens in his net. Where else but Sanibel would I
stop a stranger in tight jeans and ask to examine his banded tulip?
</P>
<P>
   By 7:45 a.m., I compare bags with an older couple from Colorado.
Theirs isn't nearly as full. I tell them they need to be out at
sunrise to find more keepers. ``Now that's a good trick,'' says the
appreciative fellow with the gray mustache.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is here on this Gulf of Mexico island that lies
off the coast of southwest Florida. Everything evolves around
shells, from pre-breakfast conversations to the city seal featuring
a fighting conch. Shells rule.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the island's streets are named after shells. Off the
main thoroughfare of Periwinkle, you'll find Tulip, Paper Fig,
Golden Olive and Pen Shell Lane. Condominiums and motels carry on
the theme with names such as Junonia of Sanibel and King's Crown.
The plastic grocery bags at Bailey's General Store have a shell
identification chart. Guides and shops are plentiful. I didn't spot
a Shell gas station, but there must be one.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons the shelling is so good on Sanibel.
</P>
<P>
   Aligned in an east-west direction, the island's boomerang shape
snags many of the shells that generally move northward. Because
there are no offshore reefs, the sandy bottom allows shells to roll
ashore intact. The warm water is conducive to colorful shells.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to scour the beaches is the winter months, because
northeasters tend to blow in lots of shells. Storms always produce
good shelling. Locals say El Nino-related storms this past winter
produced some of the best shelling in years.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let their, ``You should have been here . . . '' line
get to you. I found a good array of shells during five days in
June. I went out at sunrise and again at low tide.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I didn't find a prized junonia, but then only one in 1,000
shellers finds one of the 4-inch brown-spotted beauties. I read
somewhere you make the local paper if you find one. It took one
local guide 17 years to find a junonia. I bought one. They run
between $10-$30.
</P>
<P>
   One day, I spent $45 to hire a shelling guide for four hours.
Julie Matthews, a delightful third-generation boat captain, took me
to North Captiva, an island accessible only by boat. Dolphins
bobbed in bay waters on our way there. Otters scattered across the
beach as our boat approached.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the windswept look of uprooted horizontal trees
weathered by salt air and sun. I loved walking the beach and the
early morning isolation. The only thing missing were shells. The
night before, the sea decided to deliver its treasures elsewhere.
That's the way it is. The next day, or the day after that, the same
beach might have been loaded.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned the sea is a fickle sort. Some nights, she turns
the shoreline into a display case for her finest jewels. Other
nights, she just puts out the trash: A dive boot. A tennis ball. A
plastic bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hanley, owner of Neptune's Treasures and an island expert on
shells, says it's like finding 50 cents in a parking lot: being in
the right spot at the right time. Hanley should know. He is the
owner of what he says is the world's largest horse conch, 24 1/2
inches, on display in his shop.
</P>
<P>
   Without any coaching, Hanley pulls out a photo album. There he
is, age 10, shelling on Sanibel in 1944. Beside him is a woman in a
flowing dress collecting shells in a basket. ``In the '40s, you
could shell all day and not see anyone,'' Hanley reminisces.
``Today, you see a shell and you bump heads with someone else going
to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't fewer shells. There are more people going for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   Take State Road 80 west to Interstate 75 just east of Fort
Myers. Go south on I-75 to Daniels Parkway exit, and west to
Summerlin Road. Turn left and stay on Summerlin (which becomes
McGregor Boulevard) until you reach the causeway for Sanibel.
</P>
<P>
   There is a $3 bridge toll.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-22-98 0935E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
