<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6787 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELLS-SIDE23-COX     07-22 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELLS-SIDE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to be a successful Sanibel sheller
 &HT;    By Gayle Pallesen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Be aware of a Sanibel law banning the collection of any live
shells on the island. The rest of Lee County allows two live shells
per species per person per day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sample several gulf-side beaches. Good spots include: Turner's
Beach at Blind Pass, which separates Sanibel and Captiva. It's a
popular stretch and scallops are usually in abundance. Bowman's
Beach is known for sand dollars and skinny dippers. Lighthouse
Point is where you sometimes find starfish. All have public access,
restrooms and parking (75 cents an hour).
</P>
<P>
   _ Smother yourself with waterproof sun block, SPF 15 or higher,
particularly your back side. If no-see- ums are out, also use
insect repellent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear sunglasses and a hat. In addition to shielding the sun,
the hat keeps hair from falling in your face while bent over.
Sunglasses remove glare both on the water and on wet glittering
stretches of shells, making it easier to spot shells worth picking
up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carry a mesh, draw-string bag and a short-handled scoop net.
Both can be purchased at dive, fishing or shell shops. Plastic bags
are not very good for shell collecting because they retain water
and sand, which adds weight and contributes to breakage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Study the tide charts. Low tide is considered by most the best
time to shell since the surf has receded and left behind a new
batch of exposed shells. No matter the tide, sunrise is always a
good time to check out what washed ashore during the night before
dozens of others follow in your footsteps. After a storm,
particularly a winter northeaster, is an ideal time to search for
shells.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use your toes as well as your eyes. Walking in calf-deep or
shallower water is a good way to feel larger shells. Unbroken
fighting conchs and lightning whelks can be found this way. There
is a risk, however, with bare feet in the water: sharp shells can
cut feet and sting rays like the warm, shallow gulf waters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for ledges in the water near shore, places that dip down
where shells have lodged in their trek to wash ashore. A scoop net
comes in handy here since often it's hard to see individual shells.
This a good way to collect miniatures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't get discouraged if one day you don't find many keepers.
The same stretch the next day may produce a windfall.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO CLEAN SHELLS
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash in fresh water to remove sand and algae.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spread out to dry, but don't put shells directly in the sun
for any length of time because the sun fades the colors. Once dry,
shake out the excess sand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shells with furry coats of algae or stains will need to soak
overnight in a mild solution of bleach and water (a cup of bleach
to a gallon of water). If you are in a hurry, use a stronger
solution for a shorter time. Sand dollars also bleach white in the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a stiff-bristled brush to remove stubborn algae coating. A
firm toothbrush works well on smaller shells. For removing
barnacles, use a metal dental pick, which can be purchased at shell
shops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Once shells are clean, you can restore them to their original
luster with either a clear spray available at shell shops or a
mixture of baby oil or mineral oil and lighter fluid. One book
recommends seven parts lighter fluid to one part oil. Another
source suggests a half and half blend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
