A6789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-LOPEZ23-COX     07-22 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-LOPEZ23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To Zoila Lopez, faith in Cuba less important than faith in God
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Zoila Lopez put her faith in the Cuban revolution for
38 years. She cut cane during sugar harvests. She donated blood for
Cuba's internationalist soldiers. She dutifully taught her son that
God didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Her allegiance was rewarded by membership in the PCC, the Cuban
Communist Party, an honor reserved for the revolutionary vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Then the former teacher and bookkeeper found God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I belong to the really eternal party,'' said Lopez, 54, a
dark-eyed woman with tinted red hair and a lean face wrinkled from
years of sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found the party of the father, Christ and the lamb of
God,'' she said in Spanish, spelling out the communist party's PCC
acronym with Christian terms.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez told her story as she sat in the pews of a Methodist
Church in the Havana suburb of Playa, a former middle-class
neighborhood now part of the proletarian urban landscape. Two years
ago, Lopez walked into the church at the invitation of a friend.
When she heeded a call from the pulpit asking non-believers to walk
to the altar rail, her life changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all my life I was taught materialism, ideology and
Darwin's theory of creation,'' she said. ``Now my eyes are open to
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times a week, Lopez rides her bicycle or takes a bus to
the church from her home 30 minutes away in Jaimanitas. She says
her son, 30, calls her a ``robot'' and ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   After her conversion, Lopez carried her Bible to her job at the
Ministry of the Interior and preached to whomever passed by,
including colonels in the state security apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party has accepted Christians as party members
since 1991, but on-the-job preaching crossed the line. Lopez was
sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said she resigned from the party last month because she
did not want to be part of an organization opposed to the preaching
of the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   She uses a Biblical story to draw parallels to next year's 40th
anniversary of the Cuban revolution led by Fidel Castro. She points
out that the children of Israel were lost in the wilderness for 40
years before they were led to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's just an idea,'' she said, with a wink. ``But
40 years is a perfect number in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNS23-COX     07-22 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A life full of joy
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ The first time he finished his leg of the
boy's 200-yard freestyle relay, she cried. But, of course, Terri
Harmon cries at ``the first everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time some kid unknowingly hurt his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The first time a doctor told her he was not quite right.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 10 years ago, my goodness, she can hardly believe
it. And today, when a young mother, maybe even a woman who's
pregnant with a Down syndrome baby, calls to inquire about this or
that, she cannot wait to tell them the absolute, positive truth:
</P>
<P>
   Frank is fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   And she cried once, and only once, about Frank's wacky
chromosomal count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else has been tears of joy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank has had just pretty much a regular life,'' says Harmon.
``We started that right from the beginning. All these things,
they're not easy. But they just seem like the next thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not easy? You can say that again. Like on the day Boca Raton
YMCA swim team coach Andra Pobat read the names for the 200-yard
freestyle relay _ Jonathan, Khary, A.J., Frank, Andra called out _
and Terri Harmon stood there entertaining a very worthwhile
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Is Coach Andra nuts?
</P>
<P>
   Frank on a relay team? All the other sports they had done had
been individual things, so Frank could compete at his own pace.
Bowling. Gymnastics. She thought swimming would, again, be an
individual thing. But Coach Andra was standing there, telling her
and all the other kids that Frank was going to compete as a team
member. He was going to swim the relay.
</P>
<P>
   And Frank might be fabulous, but he's not exactly fast.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Harmon stood there, mind whirling as it always does,
expecting the kids to roll their eyes. She waited for them to hem
and haw about how slow Frank was and how they'd never, ever win an
event if he was on their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never said a peep,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And here's why:
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make any difference,'' says teammate Khary Llewellyn
``I knew he'd be all right.'' _ _
</P>
<P>
   It's a Saturday, competition day, and it's at least a million
degrees in the shade, but Frank is calm and cool as he sits,
poolside, in his strappy blue-and-white lawn chair. He's so
relaxed, you'd think he was on a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   There are 120 wet children roaming around the Boca Raton YMCA
swimming pool, whining and wondering when is it their turn to swim,
when can they have a snack, but Frank is scarfing down his Corn
Pops and chugging from the 1-quart bottle of Zephyrhills water as
if to say, Guys, this is the life.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's Frank's turn to take the starting block, he
strolls over to where he should be and dives into the water when
the starting whistle goes off, and he swims and he kicks. And about
half way through the race you think, oh, geez, he's going to stop,
he's going to flip from freestyle to backstroke, he's going to
stand up and wave to the crowd, he's going to drown himself hanging
on the lane line.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank does none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   What he does do, however, is come in dead last, but that makes
it easier for everyone to give Frank the full attention he
deserves. The crowd cheers and yells, and the sounds echo in the
Boca YMCA's fancy indoor-outdoor swimming pool arena, and Frank is
smiling as he kicks and breathes and kicks and breathes. He
finishes 14 seconds behind everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Then he climbs out of the water, sits down in the lawn chair and
has himself a few more chugs of that Zephyrhills and another box of
cereal, this time Honey Nut Cheerios, as his little brother
Matthew, 7, orbits around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our boys work hard,'' says their father, Scott. ``That's all
we can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   The following would be Frank Harmon's favorite day.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast at McDonalds, pancakes, probably, then maybe a little
television, but only if Arthur was playing on PBS. Then he and Dad
would vamoose into the yard, where they'd fiddle around with the
lawn mower and then fiddle around with the car. Frank has his own
toolbox. And then afterward, cheeseburgers for dinner and an Arthur
story at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you be the one to tell his mother that Frank's life is not
filled with joy.
</P>
<P>
   And the other day, after the photographer had shown up at the
swim meet and after the reporter had tried to make a quick friend
out of Frank, Terri Harmon and her first-born son were driving to
Publix. Harmon was curious. Just how much of this newspaper-story
thing did Frank understand?
</P>
<P>
   Who was that photographer taking pictures of? she asked Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Me, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that reporter, his mother asked, who was she interviewing?
</P>
<P>
   Me, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, Frank, why do you think a reporter and a photographer would
want to come and do a story on you?
</P>
<P>
   Because I'm the best swimmer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because he's The Fabulous Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Harmon is president of the Gold Coast Down Syndrome
Organization Inc. For information about the group, or its 5K walk
this fall, call (561) 451-2163.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
