<SLUG> BC-FIRE-SAFETY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighting measures on hand at Port of Palm Beach
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In January, the Port of Palm Beach went
through a situation similar to the July 20th emergency aboard the
Ecstasy cruise ship. Fortunately, it was only a practice run.
</P>
<P>
   But in the event one of the port's three cruise ships catches
fire after leaving port, the U.S. Coast Guard has two boats with
fire pumps at its Lake Worth Inlet Station, Petty Officer Andrew
Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   The pumps take water from the sea through the boat's fire system
and shoot water on the vessel in distress, Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's enough to fight a particular fire depends on the
size of the ship, the extent and kind of fire, and where it is on
the ship, he said. Ships also must adhere to international and
Coast Guard rules about fire safety, according to Bill Nurthen,
chief executive officer of Contessa International Cruise Line Inc.
These rules, Nurthen said, include:
</P>
<P>
   Fire retardant materials must be used in a ship's construction.
</P>
<P>
   Fire fighting equipment, including hoses, extinguishers, fire
doors, sprinkler systems and signs pointing to the equipment must
be in place.
</P>
<P>
   Crews must be trained to isolate and combat a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continually drilling on board with lifeboat drills and
fire drills,'' said John Thomas, president of Palm Beach Casino
Lines, which operates the Palm Beach Princess. Coast Guard
inspections are conducted annually and quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire at sea is one of the things every mariner is very
concerned about,'' Nurthen said. The regulations ``are stringent
for a purpose _ and we're glad they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Contessa and Palm Beach Princess both sail under the Panamanian
flag, but they still must adhere to the same safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're calling on our port, carrying our citizens and not
meeting our standards, we can enforce it,'' said Coast Guard Cmdr.
Michael Lapinski in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a fire while the ship's still in port, the
Riviera Beach fire department would handle fire and rescue, Deputy
Port Director Martin Mets said. The port is equipped with fire
hydrants, sea water hydrants and fire extinguishers.
</P>
<P>
   And, Mets added, ``The first line of defense is the ship's
crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
