<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   National health database scary
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Before his arrest and conviction for the murder of
168 of his fellow citizens in Oklahoma City, Timothy McVeigh used
to hang with a group of delusional friends who convinced themselves
that the American government was the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh and his fellow anti-government conspirators believed
that the government was building a national database so it could
track every citizen.
</P>
<P>
   America's deadliest terrorist even believed that a tiny chip
encoded with his personal data had been implanted in one of his
buttocks before he was discharged from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded paranoid and goofy, but not long ago Pentagon
officials talked about replacing dog tags with tiny chips encoded
personal data under the skin of service personnel. The data chip
could speed up the identification troops killed in action and help
doctors treat wounded soldiers and sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Something like a portable bar-code reader could retrieve a
soldier's name, rank, serial number, medical history, religious
affiliation, next of kin and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Now we learn that the Clinton administration has given its
blessing to two-year-old congressional proposal to have the
government create a central database that will gather, track and
store cradle-to-grave medical histories on every American.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act
included the ``unique health identifier'' proposal. The Department
of Health and Human Services was instructed to create a coding
system for employers, insurance companies, health-care providers
and ultimately individuals. The goal is to cut administrative costs
by simplifying billing and paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of public hearings on this proposal concluded recently
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of sounding like an anti-government conspiracy nut,
I don't like the idea of the government gathering up my complete
medical history and then patting me on the head and telling me I
don't have anything to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   A national databank with the health and billing history of every
American should simplify record keeping and assist health-care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans should be wary of government promises that it will
keep all personal medical information private.
</P>
<P>
   The government couldn't even keep the secrets of the atomic bomb
out of enemy hands. And every few weeks some 14-year-old who
successfully hacks his way into an impenetrable computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration first proposed giving every American
a health I.D. number back in 1993. Now Health and Human Services
officials are considering the use of Social Security numbers for
the national health I.D. numbers. They also propose giving police
and medical researchers access to private medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   Access to Social Security numbers already is out of control.
Employers, insurance companies and even local bowling leagues have
a list of Social Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies already track the purchasing and financial
histories of Americans. Some companies tie that information with
government data available on individual citizens. A person's
personal medical history added to that mix would destroy the
concept of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike anti-government conspirators, I trust government
officials who say they only want to help. From experience, however,
I also trust that the government will somehow screw it up. I don't
want my medical history to appear on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more secure to encode medical histories on tiny
chips implanted under the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than choose between a Franz Kafka nightmare and the
``X-Files,'' it would be better to just improve the current system.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
