<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUGBOAT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tugboats 'main line of defense' in ship fires
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tugboats that fought a scorching fire on July 20 aboard a
Carnival cruise ship off Miami Beach are part of a critical safety
net at Florida's major ports.
</P>
<P>
   Tugs normally spend their days pushing and pulling massive ships
through narrow port channels, nudging them ever so gently into
tight berthing slips. But when fire strikes, these same nondescript
tugboats are expected to arm their water cannons with sea water and
blast the flames into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the main line of defense in the event of a fire like
that,'' said Jack O'Connell, a vice president with Fort
Lauderdale-based Hvide Marine Inc., which operates tugboats at
several major ports, including Port Everglades, Port Canaveral and
the Port of Tampa. ``If something happens at sea, the tugboats are
really all you've got.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 tugboat operators in Florida. They are paid by the
ship owners who use their services, based on an hourly or job rate.
</P>
<P>
   All tug operators are licensed by the U.S. Coast Guard, but not
all boats have firefighting capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The two tugboats at the Port of Palm Beach, for instance, do not
have high-powered water cannons. But the Coast Guard has two boats
there with firefighting capabilities. And in an emergency,
officials can bring in tugs from Fort Lauderdale, said Deputy Port
Director Martin Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful tugboats, like those operated by Hvide, can
use their cannons to kill a fire with 17,000 gallons of water a
minute. The water is sucked from the sea and pressurized.
</P>
<P>
   The cannons also can be filled with foam to contain a fuel spill
or smother a gasoline fire.
</P>
<P>
   At the Port of Miami, the tugboats that fought Monday's fire are
operated by Coastal Tug &AMP; Barge. Company officials were not
available for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their firefighting capabilities are critical to upholding the
safety standards at Florida ports,'' said Nancy Leikauf, a vice
president with the Florida Ports Council in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
