<P>
   SHIP FIRE
</P>
<P>
   TUGBOAT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The tugboats that fought a
scorching fire on July 20 aboard a Carnival cruise ship off Miami
Beach are part of a critical safety net at Florida's major ports.
Tugs normally spend their days pushing and pulling massive ships
through narrow port channels, nudging them ever so gently into
tight berthing slips. But when fire strikes, these same nondescript
tugboats are expected to arm their water cannons with sea water and
blast the flames into oblivion. (Utley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-INDUSTRY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ All that smoke made
the ``fun ship'' Ecstasy look anything but fun _ yet it caused
barely a ripple in Carnival's business. Ecstasy will miss just two
cruises _ Friday's three-night cruise to Nassau and Monday's
four-night cruise to Mexico _ while it undergoes repair, Carnival
officials say. Passengers on those two cruises will be given a full
refund and 50 percent off another cruise. The ship is expected back
in service July 31. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-SAFETY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In January, the Port of
Palm Beach went through a situation similar to the July 20th
emergency aboard the Ecstasy cruise ship. Fortunately, it was only
a practice run. But in the event one of the port's three cruise
ships catches fire after leaving port, the U.S. Coast Guard has two
boats with fire pumps at its Lake Worth Inlet Station, Petty
Officer Andrew Reyes said. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-FACTS _ WEST PALM BEACH _ What you need to know about the
cruise ship industry in light of Monday's fire aboard Carnival
Cruise Lines' Ecstasy. What's the biggest ship? How safe are they?
What's the hottest destination? (Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-LOPEZ _ HAVANA _ Zoila Lopez put her faith in the Cuban
revolution for 38 years. She cut cane during sugar harvests. She
donated blood for Cuba's internationalist soldiers. She dutifully
taught her son that God didn't exist. Her allegiance was rewarded
by membership in the PCC, the Cuban Communist Party, an honor
reserved for the revolutionary vanguard. Then the former teacher
and bookkeeper found God. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SANIBEL-SHELLS _ SANIBEL, Fla. _ I want to be first. I want to
pick up what treasures the sea has sprinkled along the shoreline
during the night. I am a shell hunter and, for me, the hunt has
begun. What better place than an island with more than 20 miles of
beaches and 300 species of shells? Sanibel Island is rated by some
as the third-best shelling place in the world, outranked only by
Australia's Great Barrier Reef and the Philippine islands.
(Pallesen, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
