<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERDINNERS-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Need a bite? Feed the facts into Web site 
By Elizabeth Lee  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day, ordering dinner over the Internet may be easier than
phoning the pizza joint down the street.
</P>
<P>
   That day is not here yet. Even Tim Glass, president of the
Internet dining service Cybermeals, will admit that.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Seattle-based Cybermeals allows Atlanta computer users
to place takeout or delivery orders for 200metro Atlanta
restaurants. Its roster includes Mellow Mushroom, Mick's and
Takeout Taxi. In the next week, it will add Buckhead Gourmet
Delivery, which serves 65 restaurants from Alpharetta to
Virginia-Highland. Coming soon: Papa John's Pizza and A&AMP;P delis.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, it has signed up 20,000 restaurants and struck
marketing alliances with some big names on the Net, including
America Online, Yahoo! and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Diners register their addresses at the site
and indicate whether they want delivery or takeout. Mapping
software determines which restaurants are nearby and provides a
list of choices, with menus. Orders can be placed immediately or
saved for repeat use.
</P>
<P>
   Once an order is placed, the site sends it to the restaurant by
fax, computer-voiced phone call or computer-to-computer link. The
customer receives an e-mail confirming the order.
</P>
<P>
   To be listed on the site, restaurants pay a fee or a cut of the
sales, generally 5 percent to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ordering sounds time-consuming, and it can be, depending on
Internet traffic and use of the site itself. When The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution tried the site two months ago, the ordering
process took 25 minutes. More recently, a lunch order for three
took 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants that have signed up with the service say they want
access to a new market. So far, though, reviews are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely still a work in progress, but it seems to be
getting better and better and better,'' says Karen Jacobson of the
Peasant Restaurant Group, owner of the Mick's chain.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty's Barbecue, near Emory University(Ga.), reports only a few
Cybermeals orders so far. ``It's something that's going to take
awhile to catch on,'' says owner Linda Thompson. ``It's not costing
us very much, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckhead Gourmet, which delivers from such restaurants as
Romano's Macaroni Grill, Tanner's and Tom Tom, is counting on
corporate catering to bring in online business. Owner Harris
Tessler isn't sure about other users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to order online is possibly the wave of the
future,'' Tessler says. ``You almost want to talk to a human being
when you place an order, you want to know how it'll be prepared.
... That's the downside of it. The upside of it is, you don't have
to talk to humans.''
</P>
<P>
   You also don't have to take your hands off the keyboard if
you're at work or log off the computer to use the phone if you're
at home. In fact, that's how Glass, who was casting about for an
Internet business, came up with the idea for Cybermeals.
</P>
<P>
   He was watching a Sandra Bullock movie, ``The Net.'' When
Bullock's character ordered a pizza through her computer,
inspiration struck. A business was born.
</P>
<P>
   While Cybermeals works to add restaurants _ 100,000 is the
national target _ and improve its software, it waits for the
convergence of TV and the Internet. When that happens, ordering
online will be as easy as hitting the clicker, Glass believes _ or
thumbing through the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that we're early,'' he says. ``It's starting to
become more useful for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cybermeals: http://www.cybermeals.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
