<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES WEB SITE ENDS FEE FOR FOREIGN USERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to expand the popularity of its World Wide Web site
outside the United States, The New York Times said Tuesday that it
had eliminated the fee for access from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Since its creation in January 1996, the site, www.nytimes.com,
has been offered free in the United States and has attracted more
than 4 million registered users.
</P>
<P>
   The Times had, however, charged foreign subscribers $35 a month.
Fewer than 10,000 users outside the United States have elected to
pay it.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Nisenholtz, president of The New York Times Electronic
Media Co., said the decision to end the fee resulted from
``understanding the pricing dynamics on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an audience outside the United States that wanted
the product badly, but it was not large enough to create an
advertising marketplace we considered scalable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts said they expected that increased
advertising revenue from abroad should make up the revenue lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, The Times will do much better driving
the advertising than they ever will on the subscription side,''
said Lauren Fine, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The policy is effective immediately. Foreign users will be
charged the same fees as domestic ones for access to the crossword
puzzle and retrieval of past articles from the archives. They range
from $2.50 an article to $9.95 for five articles a month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 2202EDT &QL;
</P>
