<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-RELEVANT-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Measuring Net use is big topic at I-World 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Even as the Web matures, with more users logging on
every day, there is still a fundamental questionthat goes
unanswered: Who is out there surfing the Net and how can it be
proved that anyone at all is surfing the Net?
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an answer makes advertisers wary. Unlike
television's Nielsen ratings and the magazine industry's Audit
Bureau of Circulation, the Web has no single measurement service
every Web site and advertiser can agree on.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring success is one of the burning questions at Internet
World, the industry's largest and most influential trade show that
opened here Tuesday. Relevant Knowledge, an Atlanta-based company,
came to this show hoping it can provide an answer and help create a
standard. It's in the business of measuring the popularity of Web
sites in much the same way Nielsen does for TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will never be peace in the measurement business,'' said
Jeff Levy, co-founder of Relevant Knowledge, who came to I-World to
discuss Web measurement, along with competitors Media Metrix and
NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Packo, president of Media Metrix, raised the issue of
how measurement companies will adapt once high-speed Internet
access becomes available to a significant number of homes. Most
measurements are currently done with software installed in PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole phenomenon of set-top boxes has the potential to
turn measurement on its head,'' Levy says. He said a company like
his or Media Metrix could install the measuring devices as part of
the Web TV, cable modem or other high-speed broadband service.
</P>
<P>
   ''When that happens, you'll have a set-top box that is capable
of telling you when people turn the volume down and you'll have
that capability in 10 million homes. Broadband is a new world for
TV measurement.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Web measurers can see the future of their industry,
they are still grappling with the present.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now the measurement field is new and young,'' Packo
said. ''It's not a surprise that a lot of people are working on it.
There is room for multiple measures, but eventually one standard
will emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Atlanta-based Internet companies at the show include
Internet service provider MindSpring and cable company Media One.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
