A6848 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      07-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Apples Makes a Comeback in Classrooms and Wall Street  
 By Tom Abate   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanne Hayes has been tracking computer sales in the public
school market for 15 years. But when she finished crunching the
latest numbers the other day, even she didn't believe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in five years we saw an upswing in orders
for the Mac,'' she said. ``We went nuts. I ran the numbers again
just to make sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, who is president of Quality Education Data, a market
research firm in Denver, said after surveying 5,000 public schools,
she found that 38 percent of all new computers ordered for the
coming school year are Macs.
</P>
<P>
   That's up from 32 percent of new orders last year.
</P>
<P>
   And though schools will still buy two Windows PCs for every Mac,
Hayes said Apple's rebound will be her headline when QED releases
its report later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attribute a lot of it to (Steve) Jobs' leadership,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no denying the Steve factor yesterday, as Apple
reported earnings that were nearly double Wall Street's
expectations. Analyst Craig Cline of Seybold Media, who follows the
desktop publishing market, said Apple is doing a little better in
that key market as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cline said publishing types, all Mac-o-philes to the bone, are
jazzed about the new G3 Macs. Yet they still find themselves
holding their noses and buying Windows systems.
</P>
<P>
   Cline cautioned against euphoria, because Apple still has a long
way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to drink the Kool-Aid and say everything's
totally turned around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Mac fans have every reason to cheer today, investors might
be wary of jumping into Apple, whose shares have risen so
spectacularly since Jobs took over last summer, from the low teens
to $34.44 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   George Shirk, editor of The Insider's Newsletter in Florida,
notes that Apple execs and board members haven't been buying the
company's stock, with the exception of Edgar Woolard, who recently
bought 3,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one reason insiders buy their company's stock and
that's because they anticipate higher share prices,'' Shirk said.
``If we saw more insiders buying, we'd say these guys are
bullish.''
</P>
<P>
   So hats off to Apple for great earnings and solid gains in the &QL; 
K-12 market share. But be careful with the stock, for now.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; The laugh test: &LR;  Legal documents rarely make good reading, but
I got a chuckle out of the response Intel filed this week to the
Federal Trade Commission's antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it was no surprise that Intel said it has no
microprocessor monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   But who would have expected this: ``Intel denies that a new
entrant (to the microprocessor industry) would have to establish
both product reputation and technical compatibility with a computer
operating system and the application software desired by a
significant number of computer users.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Intel have us believe users are ready to throw out their
current hardware and software should a niftier chip comes along?
</P>
<P>
   Mac fans could only wish that were true! But the FTC will try to
prove that Intel benefits from the so-called ``network effect.''
That is, the more people who use its chips, the more likely it
becomes that Intel microprocessors will keep new chips from
entering the market.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy said his company ``would explain
the nature'' of the company's statement as the legal process
continues.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Junk revival? &LR;  Junk bonds got a bad name in the 1980s because
they financed so many leveraged-buyouts.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Chamberlain, an investment banker with Morgan Stanley,
said junk bonds have come into favor over the last few years as a
way to finance high-tech firms that need cash but aren't ready for
initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example is provided by competitive local access
providers, or CLECs. These are companies like Covad or NorthPoint
that compete with Pacific Bell in selling high-speed Internet
access and other telecommunications services to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain said privately-held CLECs have collectively raised
$6 billion to $8 billion in junk financing to pay for the wires and
switches to create their networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This significant inflow of bond financing has come at a time
when equity investors have seen substantial risks in putting money
into businesses that compete against Pac Bell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So bond buyers, who can get 10 percent returns on investments
secured against million-dollar machinery, have stepped in to
finance the CLECs.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain expects the CLECs to go public one day. Meanwhile,
if junk bonds kick start this industry, it could start a pattern
for other capital-intensive tech industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Real Gold Rush?  &LR; Everyone wants to jump on the Internet
bandwagon, including lawmakers in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Already more than 50 pending bills in the House and Senate seek
to regulate _ or de-regulate _ everything from pornography and
e-mail, to taxes and private information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This outpouring of legislative interest prompted venture
capitalist Floyd Kvamme to tell my colleague Mark Simon that
although some of the bills were well-intentioned, they reminded him
of one of life's three great lies, ``I'm from the government and
I'm here to help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-15-98 2329EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
