<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY CYBERSURFERS CLICKING ONTO INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By BOB DART  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ E-mail is a great way to keep up with the
grandkids, but that's just one benefit senior cybersurfers are
discovering as they venture on line in growing numbers, experts
told a Senate committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are currently faced with two world-wide revolutions _ the
convergence of aging or longevity and the explosion in technology _
both of which are driving the transformation of society,''
explained Craig Spiezle, Microsoft's director of market
development. ``People over the age of 60 represent the
fastest-growing segment of computer and Internet users.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, retirement communities will find that fast
cable modem connections to the Internet are as important as nearby
golf courses in attracting elderly residents, predicted Mary
Furlong, chairman of ThirdAge Media, an online business providing
information to older Americans and the companies trying to reach
them.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasts of an expanding elderly population that is rapidly
becoming cyber-saavy came at a Senate Special Committee on Aging
symposium on ``Older Americans and the World Wide Web: The New Wave
of Internet Users.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a variety of reasons, many of us view the Internet and
other forms of technology as tools of the young,'' said Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the committee chairman. ``Although young
people are often the first to use new forms of technology, it often
benefits older people just as much or even more.''
</P>
<P>
   While the elderly are going on line at a faster rate than other
age groups, they still make up only a small portion of the wired
community. Only about 5 percent of senior households own and
actively use a home computer, compared to about 45 percent of
households over all, said Spiezle.
</P>
<P>
   But those demographics will change quickly in an aging global
population. ``Every week, worldwide, 1 million people turn 60. In
the United States alone, 10,000 people turn 50 every day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these trends, Microsoft is looking to the elderly to
provide not only customers for its software but also for future
employees in an era where there is already a shortage of high-tech
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view mature Americans as a key solution to this skills
gap'' and have begun programs ``to tap the wealth of experience
seniors bring to the workplace and to help them develop and
cultivate their technological skills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Older people are not the technophobes or cyber-klutzes that they
are often portrayed to be, said Herbert Ernst, a retired government
computer scientist who trains his contemporaries at a SeniorNet
learning center in suburban Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jewish Council for the Aging center, he said, ``most of
us e-mail our family and friends almost daily; many are members of
on-line groups ...and a colleague of mine asks, 'How did we ever
get along without it?.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the elderly quickly find the Internet to be
indispensible, said Micki Gordon, director of the Center for
Productive Aging. She said they use e-mail to communicate with
family and friends, chat rooms to exchange information with others
who have similar interests, games such as Solitaire to keep their
minds engaged, Web sites to find information on Social Security,
health care, investments and genealogy, and media links for keeping
up with news and gossip.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Logging onto the Internet ``prevents isolation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many elderly Americans are going to their community libraries
for computer training and for an on-line connection, said Jeanne
Hurley Simon, chairperson of the National Commission on Libraries
and Information Science. About 73 percent of the nation's 15,718
libraries provide public access to the Internet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some communities have created ``cybermobiles'' _ similar to the
familiar bookmobiles utfitted with computer workstations with
Internet links. When the cybermobiles roll out to introduce
homebound senior citizens to the Internet, she said, ``it provides
a whole new meaning to the term ``Information Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the elderly do get hooked into the Internet, they log on
more often and surf longer than other users _ perhaps because they
have more time, said Furlong.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezle said Microsoft is working with the American Association
of Retired Persons (AARP), the National Council on Aging and other
organizations to introduce older Americans to the Internet and give
them the needed technological training. About 35 million households
of people over the age of 60 don't have a home computer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than two-thirds of the group without PCs says they simply
don't see the need,'' Spiezle said. ``But this attitude almost
always changes with the recognition that such technology presents
the opportunity to be employed in a good-paying job, extend one's
independence and allow individuals to remain productive and
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
