<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WAS LIFE LIKE BEFORE THE INTERNET?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, but the use of graphical browsers to surf
the World Wide Web is just over 5 years old. Mosaic, the first
software to let users see images on the Web, was originally
released in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   For those who rely on a connected computer for work and play, it
seems like a lot longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   Can you recall what you did to warm a plate of leftovers before
the microwave? I suspect in just a few more years serious Webheads
may have a hard time remembering what it was like to order flowers
by phone or browse a bookstore in the 3-D world.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, so perhaps I exaggerate. But you get the point _ few
communications media have changed the world as quickly as the Web
... at least for those who use it regularly. And the numbers of
those who do continue to grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Web changes the lives of those who embrace it,
the Web itself is changing.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, just having a Web site was enough to draw
attention. If it rated as a cool site _ whatever that means _ then
so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the number of sites could be measured in the
thousands. It was not unlike the dawn of television, when early
adopters gathered around sets to stare at test patterns. A little
eye candy went a long way.
</P>
<P>
   But with millions of Web pages online, getting and holding
visitors' attention now requires that a site offer something of
value. The Web has gone from being a curiosity to being a seriously
useful tool.
</P>
<P>
   If you use the Web on a daily basis, chances are there are a
handful of sites you return to regularly for a variety of services.
In some cases, they may have supplanted other ways you used to get
the same information.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I no longer call an airline when I want to find out
when a particular flight is arriving. Instead, I visit TheTrip.com
and use its flight tracker at www.thetrip.- &QL; 
com/flightstatus/.
</P>
<P>
   Choose an airline and a flight number, and not only will the
site tell you when the plane is expected, but it will even tell you
how many miles it is from the destination airport.
</P>
<P>
   When I want directions to a particular location, I no longer
look it up on a paper map. Instead, I visit MapQuest at
www.mapquest.com. This is one of several sites that let you enter
starting and destination addresses to get door-to-door directions,
complete with a map.
</P>
<P>
   You do have to be careful with these because the directions
aren't always perfect. If I'm in doubt, I'll double-check MapQuest
against Maps On Us at www.mapsonus.com, a similar service.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm shopping for computer components, I'll try ZDNet's
NetBuyer at www.netbuyer.com, which lets you compare prices at
dozens of different online vendors. Tell the site you want to find
prices on, say, 9-gigabyte and bigger hard drives with an Ultra ATA
interface. You'll get plenty of choices, sorted by manufacturer,
complete with prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, be aware that some of the bigger computer vendors
aren't listed, including CompUSA (www.compusa.com) and Cyberian
Outpost (www.outpost.com).
</P>
<P>
   When I want to check out the weather _ not that there have been
many changes around here from the hot-and-dry forecast lately _ I
don't wait to hear it on radio or TV. Instead, I drop by
Intellicast at www.intellicast.com.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are other weather sites _ including the Weather
Channel's at www.weather.com _ Intellicast is easily the
friendliest and the fastest. Weather sites tend to bog down when
the atmosphere acts up, but Intellicast stays fairly speedy even
when there is lots of weather news.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the single most useful Web site in Houston is the
Real-Time Traffic Map at traffic.tamu.edu/traffic.html. It shows a
map of the city's freeway system, color-coded to indicate freeway
speeds. Click on any colored segment to get the average speed of
traffic on that road. If you're not in Houston, you can get similar
maps for nearly 30 U.S. cities at TrafficNet at
www.accutraffic.com.
</P>
<P>
   Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silvermanchron.com, or call Houston InfoSource at
713-220-2000 and enter access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
