<HEADLINE>
A MODERN MIXER FOR THE HIGHLY WIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MICHAEL SAUNDERS   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Nobel Prizes were awarded for lack of social skills,
telephone circuits would sizzle from all the long-distance
congratulations passed between Stockholm and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Hand in glove with Boston's role as one of the country's
technology centers is its reputation as safe harbor for all sorts
of brilliant characters who can expound for hours on fluid dynamics
but get that deer-in-the-headlights look when asked something
complex, such as whether he or she is currently dating someone.
More than just fodder for endless ``Dilbert'' comics, this social
isolation is something that Bob Ayers is trying to eliminate _ at
least for a few hours at a time. Ayers created a successful lecture
series, The Next 20 Years, that has evolved into a modern mixer for
the country's most highly wired.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the middle of the idea is that everyone in the new media
industry is working ridiculous hours and they don't get to meet
each other often except over e-mail,'' Ayers said, reached by
telephone in his San Francisco office. ``Things happen when you
throw people in a darkened room with cocktails and live jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold these events in clubs because we want to shake up the
inherent stodginess. It's better to bring a lot of the most
established people into a place that's more edgy, than the
opposite,'' Ayers said. ``We want to put people up there on stage
who have interesting thoughts and want to share them, we want to
show people new technology. But we also want them to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Next 20 Years is an amplified spinoff of a San Francisco new
media-industry salon called Last Saturdays that Ayers started in
1993. The ideal panel, Ayres explains, is a mix of visionaries and
business minds, dreamers butting heads with pragmatists, all of
whom can breathe life into dry theory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC;  What we've been playing with: Live Act from Magix
Entertainment, an engaging product that wraps a comprehensive music
editing tool in a slick interface designed to appeal to teenagers
and young adults. Think of Live Act ($50) as a musical Lego kit
that enables users to build songs out of discrete blocks of sound.
That's true with all editing tools, but Live Act (unlike its
stablemates in the Magix product line) goes beyond basic sample
sequencing and playback by allowing users to play music in real
time.
</P>
<P>
   Most forms of electronica are represented in the sample pool _
ambient, acid jazz, drum and bass, hardcore techno, etc. _ so the
music created is usually very propulsive and beat heavy. By
altering pitch and tempo, and editing out certain notes, even the
most twinkly Hi-NRG track can be given a speaker-thudding dub
treatment. One quibble here: the sample quality is excellent but
purposely kept a little thin, possibly because add-on sample discs
are available for $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to jump right in and start playing, but reading
the clearly written manual will enhance the process and steepen the
learning curve. Experienced users of other editing packages (the
excellent Cakewalk is among the leaders) will immediately notice
that there's no graphical representation of the arranged samples.
This was only a minor annoyance that faded after about an hour of
tinkering, and besides, Live Act is definitely not meant for
professional use.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Live Act are sound editing tools used in its
predecessors, Music Maker 3.0 and Music Studio 3.0. Music Maker is
a basic sample arranger, while Music Studio includes sequencing
software that greatly expands the sonic palette. Live Act combines
these, adds real-time composing functions, and includes .avi video
clips that were packaged in deluxe versions of Music Maker and
Music Studio.
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't get excited about the rudimentary video editing
features in any of these products. They were only marginally
interesting, and tended to be RAM hogs on a P-166 with 16 megs RAM.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  In a year of excellent real-time strategy games,
MechCommander has muscled its way to the top. This new game from
Fasa Interactive and Microprose elevates and enhances the RTS
component of the venerable MechWarrior series by incorporating
first-rate graphics with some of the best artificial intelligence
we've seen in a while.
</P>
<P>
   In several missions, enemy mechs lure you away from the
objective you're supposed to be defending, while a flanking force
creeps in from the opposide side. Similar tactics were used in all
the MechWarrior games; none, however, had this level of emphasis on
resource management and strategic combat.
</P>
<P>
   The screen interface is both clear and detailed, with realistic
video clips of other combatants that boost the adrenaline rush. So
far, it has evicted Total Annhilation from the disc drive and we're
waiting to see if it can hold the fort against Dominion: Storm Over
Gift 3, the highly anticipated RTS game from Ion Storm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC;  For little ones, there's the Mulan Animated Storybook, just
released by Disney on the heels of the animated film, and Pajama
Sam 2, the little blue caped crusader whose latest adventures seeks
to prove that ``Thunder and Lightning Aren't So Frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-16-98 1254EDT &QL;
</P>
