<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE ANNOUNCES NEW WEB BROWSING SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT BEER   
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Netscape wants to be America Online.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message the troubled Mountain View, Calif., company
pushed Thursday along with its new Web browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a major release,'' proclaims Netscape's Bob
Lisbonne, senior vice president of client products. ``It's a sea
change for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communicator 4.5, available free on the Net starting
Thursday (www.home.netscape.com), contains features that will only
work with Netscape's Netcenter portal site.
</P>
<P>
   A portal is a Web site that acts as a jumping off point to the
rest of the World Wide Web. Think of portals as the Internet's
version of TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   Portal sites _ led by Yahoo _ have been the hottest Internet
stocks on Wall Street this summer. Netscape wants to cash in on
that popularity by imitating AOL, the long-standing portal king.
</P>
<P>
   ``But AOL has their content to work with,'' Lisbonne says. ``We
have the entire Internet.'' The new Netscape browser sports a host
of mail, address book and browsing features that automatically link
the user directly to corresponding features on Netcenter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the browser will automatically call up a link to a
specific Web site _ like www.disney.com _ when a user types in
Mickey Mouse. The feature works off a 1.5 million word dictionary
that creates those Netcenter links.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape has a skin-of-their-teeth Web browser market lead over
Microsoft, at 52.2 percent vs. 45.6 percent (third-party browser
makers hold the remaining 2.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Allen Weiner, of Dataquest in San Jose, sees the new
browser as less of a sea change than a ``shell change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's half a revision,'' he says. ``It's really meant as a way
for Netscape to solidify its position. It's meant to slow down
Microsoft a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-16-98 1220EDT &QL;
</P>
