<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WORKERS BACKED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A U.S. district judge in Seattle ruled on Wednesday in favor of
employees of Microsoft Corp. who had been denied health and
retirement benefits and discount stock purchases because they were
classified as employees of ``temporary'' agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Carolyn Dimmick rejected Microsoft's argument in the
class-action lawsuit that any benefits should be apportioned
differently to workers who signed temporary personnel contracts in
1990, 1991 or 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs said thousands of Microsoft employees
had been denied benefits, but neither side would say how many could
now be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen K. Festor, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said he did not
expect a ruling on damages for ``at least several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cullinan, a spokesman for Microsoft, said the plaintiffs
were trying to expand a ``very narrow group'' of workers referred
to in earlier court decisions upholding the plaintiffs' rights to
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-16-98 2127EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
