u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXBILL-     07-22 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXBILL-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS CHALLENGES STATE INTERNET FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taxes on Internet users' access to cyberspace may become a
contentious political issue this fall in eight states.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger for controversy at the state level is congressional
legislation called the Internet Tax Freedom Act, which the House
passed unanimously last month. The Senate, after a hearing last
week by its Finance Committee, is expected to vote on the measure
soon. The legislation would effectively ban taxes on Internet
access, but it includes a grandfather clause that would allow eight
states with existing taxes to continue to impose them.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch. The legislatures of the eight states would
have to vote to re-enact their taxes, and governors would have to
sign the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Some state and local government officials say that this
requirement is a back-door route to killing the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a grandfather clause; that's a dead man's clause,''
said Eugene Gavin, the commissioner of the Department of Revenue
Services in Connecticut, one of the eight states.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Shafroth, policy director for the National League of
Cities, said: ``All eight states have Republican governors, and for
seven it's election time this fall. And there is such incredible
terror these days when anyone accuses you of wanting to raise taxes
that at most two of these states will have the courage to re-enact
their existing tax law.'' In addition to Connecticut, the other
states are Iowa, Ohio, North Dakota, New Mexico, South Dakota,
Tennessee and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Shafroth and other critics of the bill say that its content is
being heavily influenced by the lobbying campaign dominated by
America Online, the nation's largest Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lobbying is 90 percent AOL,'' Shafroth said.
</P>
<P>
   Shafroth and Gavin said that because America Online had refused
to collect and turn over sales taxes on its subscriber fees, it was
eager to find some way to escape liabilities owed to the eight
states and to four others that will not try to re-enact access-fee
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Fishbein, an America Online lawyer working on the bill,
said that ``the grandfather clause is a compromise for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We favored no grandfather clause,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   America Online does not collect state and local taxes on
subscriber fees because it believes it is not obligated to, she
said, but it does collect such taxes in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   The company's terms of service for subscribers explicitly stated
until recently that America Online would not pay any sales or use
taxes that might be due. Within the last month, however, the
company posted a change to those terms, which now advise
subscribers that ``you are responsible for all charges incurred,
including applicable taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fishbein would not comment on the potential tax liability
America Online would face if it were forced to pay these taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The size of America Online's potential liability, including
interest and penalties, could easily reverse the positive cash
flow, which came to less than $6 million, that the company reported
in its most recent annual financial statement. Connecticut alone
says it is owed $3 million through September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If America Online cannot find a way to block these tax bills, it
would be faced with either having to go back and bill customers,
who may not react warmly to having a separate charge added months
or years after they used the service, or paying the bill itself.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Fishbein declined to comment on the effect that the
re-enactment provision of the federal legislation would have in
achieving America Online's goal of ending the Internet taxes in the
eight states. ``I'm a tax lawyer, not a political consultant,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fishbein also said she was aware that there was a widely
held impression among opponents of the bill that America Online was
virtually alone in pressing to eliminate the access-fee taxes. That
impression exists, she said, because America Online is based in
Dulles, Va., a suburb of Washington, and is therefore highly
visible on Capitol Hill. She said that virtually every Internet
access provider was active in seeking a ban on the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin, the Connecticut tax official, said that America Online
was the only company that had fought his state's sales tax on
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state recently surveyed thousands of individuals and
businesses asking for ``areas of our tax system that are
troublesome for you, and not one person or business _ not one _
brought up taxing Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is solely an AOL issue,'' he continued. ``Every other
major online provider, like Prodigy and Erols, is charging the 6
percent tax to the consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut will collect $7 million this year, he said, and has
cut the tax to 4 percent from 6 percent, with annual reductions
until it is phased out on June 30, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL says our tax is unfair, but if anything, other businesses
should say we are being unfair to them because they pay the full 6
percent and AOL and other Internet access providers only have to
pay 4 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online has filed a lawsuit in state court to block
collection of the $3 million the state sought through September
1996.
</P>
<P>
   All eight states that would have to re-enact their Internet
taxes have legislative races this fall, and all but North Dakota
have gubernatorial elections.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Scheppach, executive director of the National Governors
Association, said that governors gave in to the provision
reluctantly in negotiations over the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good practice for the federal government to tell the
states they have to re-enact a law if they want to keep it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Tax Freedom Act is seen by cyberspace industries as
critical to the growth of electronic commerce. These companies say
that having to comply with the sales tax rules of 30,000 local
governments would overwhelm them and lead to multiple taxes on some
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you are an AOL subscriber in Connecticut and you took your
laptop on a trip and accessed the Internet from your hotel room,''
Ms. Fishbein said in a hypothetical example. ``That access would be
subject to the Texas sales tax on information services.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the tax issues raised by Internet access and commerce
were never contemplated when most sales tax laws were adopted in
the Great Depression or even in Connecticut's law, which was
adopted in 1975 primarily as a way to tax the purchase of data put
online by companies and law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., a co-sponsor of the Internet Tax
Freedom Act, said at the Senate hearing last week that the Internet
``should be a global, tariff-free zone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said talk that taxes could smother
an infant electronic commerce industry was absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet companies are not struggling to come up with
capital,'' he said, adding that the proposed act would bias tax
policy in favor of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-19-98 1733EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
