<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: CONCEPT DU JOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Synergy _ that notorious buzzword of the '80s routinely invoked
to sanctify hundreds of ultimately failed mergers and acquisitions
_ is back in heavy rotation.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it is being called into play by the media industry.
With the cable televisionary Geraldine Laybourne departing Walt
Disney Co. to start her own television and Internet studio, and
with the magazine mogul Tina Brown leaving the resolutely
mono-media New Yorker to do a print-film-television start-up for
Miramax Films, ``synergy'' has become the media world's
high-concept du jour.
</P>
<P>
   Boiled down, what the term describes is parking old content in a
new garage: If you liked the movie, then you'll love the TV show,
the book, the magazine piece, the video game, the soundtrack, the
action figures, the desk accessories and _ au courant! _ the Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 years ago, when interactive digital media were first
appearing, old-line media executives had another name for this.
They called it ``repurposing.''
</P>
<P>
   But was it ever a bust. The overwhelming number of failures
(among the most notable a CD-ROM of Life magazine covers) gave the
concept a black eye and made it hard for a budding interactive
entertainment industry to find any buyers for its own inventive
gestalt.
</P>
<P>
   That gestalt _ call it the New Synergy _ is all that the digital
world has come to represent: interactive and decentralized and
networked right down to its DNA. New Synergists believe that what
traditional companies try to pass off as ``synergy'' will continue
to fail until they embrace digital, interactive media and its
emerging role in pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Martinez, the chairman of a San Francisco-based interactive
production company, Postlinear Entertainment, is a New Synergy
pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   In what he dubs the ``postlinear world,'' an entertainment
property starts simply as a very loose story structure, ``populated
only with characters and ambient conflicts.'' From those loose
elements, Martinez said, you can create films, games, comic books,
whatever you like.
</P>
<P>
   But because media companies now want to control all the options
for any project _ or ``chew all the flavor out of the gum,'' in
Martinez's words _ the only way for independent producers like
Postlinear to succeed is by the flukiest, most unpredictable of
phenomena, a crossover hit.
</P>
<P>
   These are rare indeed; the most successful is Carmen Sandiego,
the dashing international thief whose career as a star of
television and books was begun in a Broderbund Software video game.
More recent is Lara Croft, the vastly endowed cyber-Barbie star of
a popular video game, Tomb Raider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lara's Book,'' by Kip Ward and Douglas Coupland, author of
``Generation X,'' was published this month. Paramount Pictures will
release a Tomb Raider movie in 1999, and the ``Lara Croft Come
Alive'' CD is already on shelves in France. Croft worship has
spawned more than 2,000 Web sites in many languages, including The
Croft Times (http://www.cubeit.com/ctimes/).
</P>
<P>
   Amid today's Internet boom, with industries left and right
making the global network the core of their businesses, many New
Synergists are amazed that traditional media companies continue to
treat the Net as some ancillary distribution medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you not care about the Internet?'' Martinez said.
``The Internet is becoming a superset of all other media. At some
point, interactive media producers are going to have to create
flat-out digital labels as the first medium and move them into
things like film and TV _ not the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``other way around'' problem has plagued other notable New
Synergists, as well. Allee Willis and Prudence Fenton, two of the
most innovative artists in the interactive world, have just come
off a bad trip of more than five years trying to sell their
cutting-edge Willisville interactive media project to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Highly acknowledged artists in many genres _ including
songwriting, animation, film and television production _ they
developed an entertainment environment that defined New Synergy.
Willisville _ a ``cul-de-sac on the information superhighway''
populated with bizarre and charming characters _ was to have its
richest presence on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Willisville was built for fluid, continuing connections to and
from television, shopping, e-mail, creativity tools and more. But
in the days when they were shopping the project, the reaction was
always the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was really excited to see it,'' Ms. Willis said.
``We'd go through elaborate conversations before we took these
meetings and say, `We are in complete opposition to the way
entertainment is being developed for the Web. We don't think the
idea is to have a TV show and go online and buy a T-shirt and be
able to chat with the actors.' And everyone would say, `Of course,
we believe in a totally radical approach; we're the place for
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she added, ``their eyes would cross as soon as we'd start
talking about it, and they'd start talking about doing these stupid
`Web-isodes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lammers, chief executive of the children's entertainment
company Headbone Interactive, was luckier than Ms. Willis. She will
take Headbone's popular ``Elroy'' video game character to the TV
screen this fall. But it took years to sell television executives
on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustrating part of dealing with traditional media
companies is they've got a huge business and infrastructure to
support, so they limit the creative risk they're willing to take,''
Ms. Lammers said. ``You can cross over from TV to the Web, but the
most original material, the brain surgery stuff, is going on in the
new media because that's the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-19-98 1718EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
