<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-FUNERALS-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNING CAN HELP REDUCE SURVIVORS' COSTS AND ANGUISH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Joanne Reich visited her parents recently, they
showed her their grave site, gave her their lawyer's business card
and discussed their funeral plans, even though they don't
anticipate a service any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister thought it was gross and creepy. I thought it was
healthy,'' says Reich, support-services manager at Omega House, a
hospice for AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Face it.
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't like to think about death, much less discuss
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think talking about it maybe brings it on quicker,''
says Darryl J. Roberts, author of ``Profits of Death'' (Five Star
Publications, $17.95), a consumer book on how to cut funeral costs.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts finds that when he talks about his area of expertise at
dinner parties, people express some uneasiness and then become
fascinated with the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``But doing something about it is a whole different story,'' he
says. ``We really have a responsibility to face up to it and do the
necessary research to prepare for it, and that's what we don't
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and other experts agree that a little planning can make
a world of difference when the time comes _ not only in reducing
the cost of the funeral but also in sparing survivors anguish and
indecision about doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of death, families are so emotional and
vulnerable,'' says Molly Harrison, senior clinical social worker at
The Hospice at the Texas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more of that whole decision-making process that's either
done ahead of time or by someone else carrying out the wishes (of
the deceased) just tends to make it less stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospice offers a booklet, ``Let the Choice Be Mine,'' to
help patients plan their funerals or memorial services. It includes
space for instructions on everything from hair and makeup
preferences to the type of service desired.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts says the family should sit down ahead of time and
discuss the person's wishes and research the best money-saving
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody goes out and just buys a refrigerator, right? They wait
for a sale, look it up on the Internet or read Consumer's Digest,''
he says. ``But most funerals are bought when a loved one dies.
That's the worst time.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to do when someone dies is to hire a death-care
consultant, he advises. For a few hundred dollars, the consultant
researches the best prices on funeral merchandise and services.
Roberts says a consultant can shave several thousand dollars off
the cost of a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Lambert, owner of a Houston-based consultant service called
Funeral Shoppers, says most families are baffled by the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funeral homes are like car dealerships. There are some
wonderful ones, but a lot of them will rip you off in a
heartbeat,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, who charges 10 percent of whatever a family saves by
using his services, coaches clients to resist high-pressure sales
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   He advises them to request a price list before visiting a
funeral home, to ask to see every casket on the price list, to
never buy anything on the first visit, and to compare prices with
competing funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't or don't want to hire a consultant, Roberts
suggests taking someone along to the funeral home who is less
emotionally involved.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert is wary of prepaid funeral plans. ``Everybody ought to
preplan their funerals, but you don't need to prepurchase, because
once a funeral home has your money, they have you,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to prepay a funeral, Roberts advises buying
an insurance policy from your local agent rather than a funeral
home, which may try to push a less economical dollar-for-dollar
policy.
</P>
<P>
   If you purchase a prepaid policy, make sure the price is
guaranteed and the policy can be transferred to another funeral
home in case you move out of the city or state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
