<SLUG> BC-CPT-MACNEWS21-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Mac News: Periodic refinements help operating system 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to the software that controls its
computers, Apple Computer abandoned revolution for evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when, every couple of years, the company
released a major new version of the software that controls its
computers. Now modest upgrades come like clockwork every six months
_ a major achievement in and of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, none of these semiannual upgrades has been
anything special. But taken as a group over the past two years,
they represent significant change. For example, Apple Computer has
slowly but surely changed what users see on the screen. It has also
sped up routine tasks such as copying files.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Apple Computer plans to release another six-month
upgrade. It will be called OS 8.5. Once again, the upgrade contains
nothing earth-shattering. Yet there are plenty of small but useful
improvements. Here's a description of some of the more important
changes scheduled for OS 8.5.
</P>
<P>
   At long last, Apple Computer has gotten around to updating its
Find command. With OS 8.5, this command will become a three-tabbed
window. One tab will let you search your computer by file name,
another by content within a file and the third will launch a search
across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Another helpful new feature is called Keychain. It is a database
that will let you store all your Net IDs and passwords in one place
on your computer. All you'll have to remember is one password,
which unlocks the Keychain database.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but surely Apple Computer has been changing the look of
its OS. Now the company will let you do it. OS 8.5 will let users
customize virtually any or all of its appearance, including
windows, menu bars, icons and scroll bars.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of scroll bars, these too are getting overhauled in
OS 8.5. The biggest improvement is something called ``live
scrolling,'' which automatically updates a window's contents in
real time as you scroll.
</P>
<P>
   OS 8.5 will also let you, as an option, add double scrolling
arrows to both sides of the scroll bar. That will give any window
up and down arrows at both the top and the bottom, reducing use of
the mouse to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements include consolidating some control panels,
which let you set how some features work. For example, one Internet
control panel will act as a front end for setting all online
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about OS 8.5, check out a recent article on
the MacWorld home page. You'll find it at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .macworld.zdnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 1132EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
