<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-FUNERALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEOPLE HAVE BECOME MORE OPEN' AS CUSTOMIZED FUNERALS PAY TRIBUTE
TO DECEASED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trims, optional ending) 
 
By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When their adult son died in a car accident, the
prominent Houston-area family had definite ideas on how they wished
to bury him.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives requested that his two honey-colored Labrador
retrievers stand guard at each end of the casket during the
service. Afterward, they wanted a lavish reception with Beluga
caviar and premium liquor before the trip to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   When they made it clear they would go elsewhere if the funeral
home couldn't meet their demands, Bob Jones, president of Geo. H.
Lewis &AMP; Sons, didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your caterer or ours?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral service went off without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the most well-behaved dogs,'' Jones recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Such a customized funeral is no longer that unusual. Whether for
the rich and famous or the unknown, services are increasingly
paying tribute to the deceased in ways that would have been frowned
upon a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Scripture, prayer and sermons remain an integral part of
many services, today's funerals also regularly include photographs,
heartfelt eulogies from the person's friends and favorite secular
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral homes report that the theme song from the movie
``Titanic,'' Celine Dion's ``My Heart Will Go On,'' is a favorite
at services throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Other top requests include Whitney Houston's ``I Will Always
Love You,'' Bette Midler's ``The Wind Beneath My Wings,'' Dion's
``Because You Loved Me'' and Led Zeppelin's ``Stairway to Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Balloons and floral arrangements shaped like a golf club, guitar
or other hobby are not uncommon. In some cases, the departed's
paintings, furniture and beloved pets have been brought in for the
service.
</P>
<P>
   There's also likely to be an open bar along with the open
casket. An industry newsletter, Funeral Monitor, recently noted
that in Texas, the operative principle at a growing number of
funeral homes is ``having your wake and eating there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have become more open,'' says etiquette expert Annie
Cater, who reports that much of the cocktail-party chatter she's
heard lately is from people planning their funerals. ``Now it's
become a celebration of their time on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cater, who turns 70 next year and has no immediate intention of
passing on, has already mapped out her funeral plans. When the time
comes, she wants to be cremated and have her ashes divided into
little blue boxes from Tiffany jewelers for her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I am going to every social event in Houston,'' she says.
``My friends are taking me with them wherever they go. I am going
to have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Funerals also are increasingly adding high-tech touches. Some
families are having services videotaped and inserting e-mail
addresses in obituary listings to facilitate the sending of
condolences.
</P>
<P>
   During some services, events of the deceased's life have been
shown on videotape, says the Rev. Michael Patrick Williams, senior
pastor of the Joy Tabernacle Church in northeast Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more touchy-feely about everything,'' he says.
``You see that on the talk shows. People are willing to get up and
tell very personal things about themselves. There's a real sense
that it's OK to be soft.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the service for Princess Diana last year included
soft touches never before seen at a royal funeral. Elton John sang
a new version of the pop song ``Candle in the Wind,'' dedicated to
the princess. The Bible reading, a passage from 1 Corinthians,
contained references to faith and hope more commonly heard at
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Helen Havens, rector of St. Stephens Episcopal Church
in Houston, says she heard some grumblings that the service wasn't
``straight prayer book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought it was splendid,'' Havens says. ``The family was
fiercely trying to make it Diana's and not stiff and stodgy. I
think it reached the people, and it reached me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four-legged creatures played a part in recent memorial services
for Linda McCartney, who was an animal-rights activist before she
succumbed to breast cancer in April.
</P>
<P>
   In London, two of her Shetland ponies were led to the front of
St. Martin-in-the-Fields church. In New York, Pamela Fowler Grace
of Cat Spring rode her brown-and-white-dappled Appaloosa down the
carpeted aisle of Riverside Church while Paul McCartney talked
about his late wife.
</P>
<P>
   At both services, the former Beatle remarked that the inclusion
of animals would have have been his wife's favorite part of the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only the rich and famous who have tailored such
individualized services.
</P>
<P>
   When electrician Elting ``Jerry'' Deyo died four months ago
after suffering a debilitating stroke, his relatives decided to add
some personal touches to the funeral after talking with officials
at Brentwood Funeral Home in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They included photographs of him from various times in his life
and added a floral arrangement in the shape of a guitar, since he
had played in a band for many years. The funeral procession passed
by several nightclubs where he had performed, and his son played
guitar at the grave site.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral home also videotaped the service for the family,
adding photographs and music to the ``tribute video.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a keepsake,'' says his widow, Janis, who has shown
the video to some who were unable to attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   She adds that her husband, who didn't want the family to make a
fuss over a funeral, would have liked what took place. ``It
couldn't have been better,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Such personalized services were a rarity when Molly Harrison
went to work at The Hospice at the Texas Medical Center 11 years
ago; funerals were usually formal and traditional, she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many memorial services she attends include pictures,
posters and testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She recalls a recent service for a young girl in which her
kindergarten classmates sang, everyone released pink balloons, and
her mother spoke movingly about the ways the child had touched
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ripped your heart out, but it was very cathartic,'' says
Harrison, senior clinical social worker at the hospice. ``So much
of what a funeral service should be is to begin the grief process.
It's a ritual that we need to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harrison credits the hospice movement with helping to break down
some of the taboos surrounding death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are getting a little more time at the end
of their lives to put things in order,'' she says. ``What it's done
is make talking about death a more acceptable thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The national debate about assisted suicide and a person's right
to die has led some people to talk about their personal wishes on
such issues, she believes.
</P>
<P>
   With many families dispersed geographically and lacking family
homes to retire to after funerals, some look to the funeral home
for more than services and burials.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Jones of Geo. H. Lewis &AMP; Sons began receiving
inquiries from families about catering funeral-related events. In
response, the funeral home added a room called ``The Pavilion'' at
its Galleria-area location in southwest Houston, where mourners can
gather for cocktails and canapes.
</P>
<P>
   The room has a full kitchen with china, crystal stemware and
uniformed staff. Valet parking is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you used to do at home, you can do here,'' says Jones,
who has handled the funerals of such notables as Howard Hughes and
Howard Marshall, the husband of Anna Nicole Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Etiquette expert Cater finds nothing wrong with such activities,
as long as they're done in good taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal choice. To have the opportunity for friends
and relatives to get together and do their mourning in their own
way is a very gracious thing to do. It gives you some closure for
the person you've lost,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Williams agrees that personalizing a funeral can go a
long way in helping the grieving process. He recalls a somber
funeral for a man who had committed suicide that was brightened
when some of his friends got up and spoke about the pranks he'd
pulled in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought a needed balance and added a very human dimension
to the service,'' he says. ``The Bible says laughter is good
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
