 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Tech Tools: Which graphic format depends on your needs 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week, we answered some questions posed by reader
Bob Wildau. We'll continue this week with some more from him
concerning the various graphic compression formats, which he finds
bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confused by all the various systems for handling
photographs on the computer and various peripherals, i.e. BMP vs
JPEG, JPG vs. GIF, etc. I have software from HP Photo and LviewPro,
plus whatever comes with Win 95, but I can't make any sense out of
them. Is there any one such system one could rely on for everything
and throw the others away?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the graphics compression formats one encounters are
proprietary, and native to a particular graphics program. For
instance, BMP (it stands for bitmap) is the standard format used
for Windows and Windows Paint. Then you have TIF and EPS and PCX
and so on and so on.
</P>
<P>
   GIF (Graphic Interchange Files) is the standard devised for
graphics storage by CompuServe. JPEG stands for Joint Photographic
Experts Group and is shortened in file names to JPG. GIF and JPG
are the standard formats used for graphics on the Internet and the
World Wide Web, apparently the direction in which Wildau is
heading.
</P>
<P>
   The chief difference in all these formats is the quality of the
image and the space it takes up in storage. Typically, the
proprietary formats such as BMP and TIF will be many times larger
than the same image stored as GIF or JPG. JPG is a ``lossy''
format, which basically means some data is lost in compression and
the resulting image will not be as sharp as the original, but most
people cannot see any difference.
</P>
<P>
   Scanner software will allow the user to save a file in any of
several different formats, depending on what the end use will be.
If this software is attached to a quality draw program, as it
usually is, the draw program will probably convert a file from one
format to another. Thus if someone sends you a photo in TIF format,
you can translate it into JPG.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closely related,'' Wildau writes, ``I will soon have to
specify for folks who want to add a head shot to their listings on
an organizational Web site what size of picture to have scanned
into what type of graphics file, but I don't understand the
relationship between the size and quality of the original picture,
the amount of digital detail on the scan (thus the size and
cumbersomeness of the file), and the quality of the resulting image
on the Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   I should think that it would be worth Wildau's time to invest in
a scanner for his home office and have these people send him the
photograph to be scanned; otherwise there's bound to be confusion
if he tries to specify resolution.
</P>
<P>
   In the scanning software with which I am familiar, the size of
the picture depends upon the resolution specified. The image can be
scaled down as required in a graphics program, but the size, and
thus the space requirements, of the original will remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   However, if someone sends Wildau a photo that is far too large,
he needs only to scale it to the size he wants, save that version
and get rid of the larger original version.
</P>
<P>
   To judge quality, some experimentation will be necessary.
Computer graphics experts can take a lousy photograph and make it
look good using a program like PhotoShop, but that's a career.
Obviously, the ordinary user doesn't want to spent the effort
necessary to become an expert in doctoring pictures. This is
another good reason to do all the scanning yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 1131EDT &QL;
</P>
