<HEADLINE>
98
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
TechnoBuddy: Possible problem with custom installation in WindowsBy Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Windows 98 isn't an important program, it's just a
minor upgrade. That's what everyone says. If you've followed the
introduction of Microsoft's newest Windows in the magazines, on TV
or in the newspaper, you've heard it for yourself. I've written
those same words.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if Windows 98 is such a minor deal, then why can't we all
stop writing about it? Here I am writing about it again today
--scared to death you'll slam down the newspaper and think: Why
can't that TechnoBuddy guy write about genealogy programs, or
faster modems or how to use your PC to grow the perfect tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, when a program is introduced that will be
--sooner or later -- used by almost everyone who has a PC, then it
is a big deal. Windows, after all, is the platform used to run all
your PC programs. Just a little shiver from that platform and your
whole computing world shakes.
</P>
<P>
   I started out believing -- and writing -- that Windows 98 is a
worthwhile improvement over Windows 95. I said, and still believe,
that it seems more stable and less likely to freeze; works faster;
and has features that are real improvements over Windows 95. I've
been using it for months now, if you count time spent with test
versions, and have had few problems. I wouldn't want to go back to
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But I keep hearing credible and frequent reports -- from
friends, from the Internet and other publications -- that disturb
me. Almost all of them are about user problems that occur when
installing Windows 98. I don't much like being in the rumor
business, but when things get to the point where Microsoft feels
compelled to acknowledge and deny the rumors -- a July 10 press
release said: ``Contrary to recent reports, the majority of PCs can
be upgraded to Windows 98 without any trouble'' -- it's time to
tell you what I've heard and let you decide.
</P>
<P>
   The reports are consistent in saying trouble with Windows 98 is
most likely to come during the installation. And luckily there's a
specific pattern that will let me give you some advice that -- if
there really is an installation glitch with Windows 98 -- will give
you a good chance of avoiding problems yourself. The pattern
suggests most of the installation woes come when people take the
option for a custom installation.
</P>
<P>
   When you install Windows, you'll be given two choices. You can
accept the default installation option and let Windows itself
decide what portion of the program to install and where to put it,
or you can make the decisions for yourself. I'm suggesting, for
starters, you choose the default installation option. The good
thing about doing this is you can always go back and use the
Add/Remove Software icon in the Control Panel to add and remove
portions of Windows after the installation.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing I suggest is you go to the Microsoft Web site at
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .microsoft.com/hwtest/hcl/default.htm and check out the Windows
98 ``hardware compatibility list.'' You'll find a listing of PCs
and other hardware with known incompatibilities with Windows 98.
That list is too long to reproduce here. But you'll want to check
it out before installing Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Then, make sure your PC meets the minimum system requirements to
run Windows 98. You'll also find that information on the Web site
but -- and this is a boiled-down version -- you must have at least
a 80486DX/66 processor and a Pentium is much better; 16 megabytes
of RAM; and about 195 megabytes of free hard disk space. Keep in
mind that is the minimum. If your machine fits somewhere on the
borderline, it might be smart to pass on Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as long as I am in the rumor business today, I hear
Microsoft is coming out with what is called a patch. That's a small
program, which would be distributed free from the Microsoft Web
site, that would patch, or fix, some of the installation problems.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, here's my advice. If you haven't yet installed
Windows 98 and don't feel a pressing need to do so, wait a couple
of weeks or a month to let some of the dust clear. If you do need
to install it now, use the default installation and make sure your
PC exceeds the minimum system requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted's Technobuddy column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
