 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Portable CD player comes with 'wardrobe' 
By Michael E. Kanell  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not enough to have the technology and
cutting-edge sound. Apparently you've got to have the right color,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Consumer Electronics is banking on that combination to
sell its new personal compact disc players, hoping younger
consumers -- the company says it's pitching to Generation X -- will
care as much about looks as features.
</P>
<P>
   Personal CD players have the youngest buyers in audio, says
Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   The RCA RP-2240 from Thomson comes with interchangeable,
translucent lids in green and purple -- as well as the standard
gray. ``The consumer ... has the option of changing the look of the
product as often as they would like with the swap-top lids,'' said
Sharon Seward, audio marketing manager at Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   The RP-2240 comes with a feature called ``Smart ESP,'' which
might seem a little bit like magic. The feature lets the user
remove the CD from the player -- while continuing to listen to the
music. Put the CD back within about 40 seconds and the music never
misses a beat, says Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, although that trick works and might mystify your
friends, the real purpose of the technology is to protect the
listener from audio shocks should the CD player get a good bump
while in motion. That ``buffer memory'' lets the player keep
playing by pulling from 40 seconds worth of data it keeps in
storage. If the CD gets bumped momentarily off-track, the music
continues.
</P>
<P>
   The RP-2240 comes with stereo headphones and has a suggested
retail price of $89.
</P>
<P>
   Information about Thomson's RCA equipment is available from the
company by phone at 1-800-336-1900 or via the company's site on the
Web (http://www.nipper.com).
</P>
<P>
   Smart keyboard
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody wants to lug a laptop everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Many professionals, salespeople and stenographers -- not to
mention journalists -- want to take notes wherever they go, but
resign themselves to their pens and paper when they consider the
high-tech options.
</P>
<P>
   A laptop can be clumsy, heavy, fickle and expensive. The smaller
alternatives, like the trendy Palm Pilot, are viewed with
skepticism by those of us with illegible scrawls and, besides, they
are designed more for a list of errands than say, transcribing the
brilliant words of the marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   There is, as it happens, a compromise position between laptop
and pen.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligent Peripheral Devices makes a ``smart'' keyboard that
will let you type extensive notes, store them and then upload them
to your computer later. The full-size, two-pound keyboard comes
with a four-line display, and the company says it can run for 300
hours on three AA batteries -- far better than any laptop.
Computerworld magazine calls it ``rugged,'' which would be another
obvious advantage over most laptops. Still one more is the price:
about $230.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the company Web site
(http://www.alphasmart.com).
</P>
<P>
   Bug portrait
</P>
<P>
   So, Mr. and Ms. Hotshot, write-code-in-your-sleep, know-it-all
computer expert, just what does that Millennium Bug look like?
</P>
<P>
   You know about the problem. Many computers, especially in the
early days of information technology, were programmed to use two
digits for the year. With the approach of Jan. 1, 2000, businesses
and large organizations around the world are presented with the
challenge of making sure that computers are cleansed of the
proclivity to see that morning as the first day of 1900.
</P>
<P>
   But forget the jargon and digits. Draw a picture.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you draw well enough, you just might win $2,000.
That's how much Pick Systems will pay the winner of its slightly
tongue-in-cheek contest to find the best drawing or drawings of the
Millennium Bug. Although the contest is meant as something of a
joke, Pick Systems is in the business of finding solutions to the
Millennium problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than take the approach of Chicken Little, who ran
around crying `The sky is falling, the sky is falling,' Pick has
decided that a little humor can go a long way; therefore we intend
to poke some fun at the issue while offering strategies to solve
it,'' reads the contest form.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing of the bug will be judged on its ``creativity,
graphic design layout, marketability, humor and appropriateness to
the problem,'' says Pick.
</P>
<P>
   Entry information is available on the company Web site
(http://www.picksys.com
</P>
<P>
   /y2kbugcontest) or by mail: Y2K Contest, McQuerter Group, San
Diego, CA 92121.
</P>
<P>
   Spam scams
</P>
<P>
   A lot of us are all to familiar with spam.
</P>
<P>
   More formally known as unsolicited commercial e-mail, spam is
what many of us find in our Internet mail boxes each morning. An
awful lot of it is really an invitation to fraud, or at the very
least a chance to throw away money, according to the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC last week released a list of the 12 most common scams
found in spam.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer
Protection, said the agency came up with the ``Dirty Dozen'' after
sifting through more than 250,000 junk e-mail messages that had
been forwarded by consumers to the special mailbox set up to
collect spam. (That mailbox is uce(at)ftc.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet service providers are better than others at
protecting members from spam. The largest online service, America
Online, is the most visible example of a provider that has had
trouble doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most common spam scams, according to the FTC:
</P>
<P>
   -- The business opportunity scam, in which a ton of income is
promised for a small investment of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   -- The bulk e-mail scam, in which you are promised profits -- in
exchange for your purchase of e-mail addresses. Bulk e-mail
violates terms of service for most Internet providers and, besides,
most of the lists are unreliable, Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   -- The easy credit scam, in which credit and loans are promised
on easy terms.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the FTC site on the Web
(http://www.ftc.gov), write the agency (Consumer Response Center,
Room 130, Sixth Street and Pennsylvania Avenue N.W., Washington,
D.C. 20580) or call the FTC (202-382-4357).
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 1131EDT &QL;
</P>
