<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SYQUEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Syquest Looks for Advice  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, when a company enlists the advice of an investment
bank, it's tantamount to proclaiming, ``We're for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the case with Syquest, Chairman Ed Marinaro said
yesterday after the troubled disk-drive maker announced that it has
asked CIBC Oppenheimer to help chart its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is clearly to remain independent and to be able
to expand our business base considerably,'' Marinaro said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, CIBC Oppenheimer, will advise Fremont-based Syquest on
strategic partnerships, joint ventures and even possible
acquisitions that Syquest may consider.
</P>
<P>
   Syquest makes drives that let personal computer users store
large amounts of data on removable cartridges. Its chief rival is
Iomega, maker of the Zip drive.
</P>
<P>
   Like other disk drive companies, Syquest has been murdered by a
prolonged slump in the industry _ the result of a glut of drives
and a weaker-than-expected PC market.
</P>
<P>
   But Syquest's troubles go deeper than that. The company has
suffered three years of steady losses, and its stock has been
sliding.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Syquest would appear to be a fine takeover target. But
Marinaro doesn't see it that way. He believes that Syquest has
turned the corner in a two-year turnaround and is poised for a
financial rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Behind much of Marinaro's optimism is SparQ, a $199 drive whose
cartridges can store 1 gigabyte of data. (That's 700 times what you
can get on a floppy.)
</P>
<P>
   Because the SparQ made its debut last November, Marinaro said it
has outsold Iomega's Jaz drive, its only competitor. The Jaz, which
also holds 1 gigabyte per cartridge, sells for $100 more than the
SparQ.
</P>
<P>
   Syquest's revenues of $47 million in its March quarter were the
highest in more than a year, though it still suffered a net loss of
$31.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The constant trail of red ink _ more than $200 million since
1995 _ has helped sink Syquest's stock. In August of 1995, the
shares peaked at $18.88. Yesterday, they were unchanged at $1.41.
</P>
<P>
   If Syquest isn't exactly a stellar performer, it's in a lot
better shape than when Marinaro took over in February of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week on the job, I had to raise $1 million to meet
the payroll. That's how bad things were,'' he said. ``Syquest was
on the verge of being a bankrupt company.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro, a 36-year computer industry veteran who had been CEO
of Network Computing Devices, embarked on a program to cut
operating expenses, which had strangled profit margins for early
Syquest products.
</P>
<P>
   He financed the company's survival through private stock
offerings that raised several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed did a great job of rounding up financing to keep the
company in good shape while they rebuilt the product line to get
out of the hole,'' said Dick Porter, president of research firm
DiskTrends.
</P>
<P>
   The private stock placements had a serious side effect, however.
The stock in those deals consisted of preferred shares, most of
which have since been converted to common stock _ thereby badly
diluting the common shares. The number of outstanding shares has
soared from 12.5 million two years ago to 127 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marinaro said Oppenheimer ``will be instrumental in
restructuring our capital accounts and raising incremental funds as
the need arises.'' The goal, he said, is to put Syquest in position
for a secondary public offering next year.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Syquest is cash-positive, with about $10 million on hand
and with long-term debt of less than $2 million. It has about 300
employees in the Bay area, and another 2,000 at its manufacturing
plant in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   However, its future success is far from assured. For one thing,
said Dataquest analyst Fara Yale, ``Iomega isn't going to roll over
and let Syquest to continue to take market share away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is new competition from Castlewood Systems, a startup
company also based in Fremont which was founded by Syed Iftikar _
who also founded Syquest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 2204EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
