 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Getting Home Address OffA Web Site  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  How do I get my home address removed from someone's Web
site? Over the past month I have had over 50 young men show up at
my front door at all hours of the day and night (i.e., midnight and
4 a.m.). They are apparently all Web-surfing and are given my
address as the place to meet for a massage. Am I doomed to this
mode of home wrecking, or is there something I can do to end this
growing nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Now THAT'S a computing problem you don't see every day!
What you should do is contact the owner of the Web site _ or better
yet, have your lawyer do it _ and get your name taken off the site.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to do is get the address of the site from one of
your unwelcome visitors. Then you can find out who runs the site by
using Whois, a service of Network Solutions. That's the company
that registers most of the world's Internet domain names (such as
Apple.com, the domain name for Apple Computer's site). You'll find
Whois at http://rs.internic.net/cgi-bin/whois.
</P>
<P>
   Whois lets you search for any domain name ending in .com, .net,
.org or .edu. You should be able to find the name of the person or
company who registered the site, as well as the name, address and
phone number of the site administrator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  How can one become a Web programmer? What programming
languages do you have to know, and how can you go about finding a
job?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Jennifer Cannella, a technical recruiter in the Santa Clara
office of the Elan agency, says the prospective Web programmer
should be fluent in HTML, Java, Javascript and Perl. In addition, a
foundation in C++ is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Good ways to search for a job include contacting agencies like
Elan, going to job fairs and perusing the Internet, where many
companies post job openings on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   One good site is the Westech Virtual Job Fair, at www.vjf.com.
You can submit an electronic resume and search for positions that
are posted by major technology companies. There's also a list of
real-world job fairs, including a Westech Career Expo set for
tomorrow and Thursday at the Santa Clara Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  When I retrieve my e-mail there is a full page of headings
showing where the message came from and how it came to me. It goes
on and on and on. Is there a way I can choose to show only the
person sending the e-mail and the subject? I'm using Netscape 4 as
my Internet browser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Boy, I wish every question were this easy. Go to the View
menu in the Netscape e-mail window and choose Headers. There you'll
find three choices: All, Normal and Brief. All, which is the option
you apparently are using now, gives you all the routing information
for a message. The reason there's so much of it is that e-mail can
go through many computer systems on the Internet enroute to you.
</P>
<P>
   The Normal option shows the subject of the message, the date it
was received, the address of the person who sent it and the address
of the person or mail list to whom it was sent. The Brief shows the
sender, the subject and the recipient. And that sounds like your
best bet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  We would like to copy our address book contacts from
Outlook 98 to a floppy disk. We were told it cannot be done. Can
you advise us?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  It can be done, and pretty easily at that. Here's how. With
your Address Book open, choose Select All from the Edit menu. This
will highlight all your addresses in blue. Go back to the Edit menu
and choose Copy. Then open up a word processor like Microsoft Word
and use the Paste command in the Edit menu to copy all your
addresses into the new document. Finally, save the document to a
floppy disk. I'd recommend saving it in Text Only format, which
will let you open it on any Windows PC, regardless of which word
processor it has. Also, you can use the new file to make a neat
printout of all your addresses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   America Online members, this one's for you. You don't need a
computer with AOL installed on it to check your AOL mail. You can
do it with any Internet connection by going to www.aol.com/netmail.
This new feature, called AOL NetMail, is currently in a testing
phase, but it seems to be pretty solid. It lets you sign on and
displays your AOL mailbox (you can't get any other AOL features,
however). You can send and receive messages just as you would if
you logged into your AOL account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 2204EDT &QL;
</P>
