<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEDDINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Surfing the Web for Wedding Gifts  
 By Julia Angwin   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considering the number of things you can do online these days _
everything from gambling to broadcasting a live birth _ it's
surprisingly difficult to shop for wedding presents in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   That's because most places with popular wedding registries _
such as Bloomingdale's, Crate &AMP; Barrel and Williams-Sonoma _ have
not put them online. The only major retailers that offer online
bridal registries are Macy's, JCPenney and discounter Service
Merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most retailers run on very thin margins,'' said David
Alschuler, director of electronic commerce research at the Aberdeen
Group in Cambridge, Mass. ``It's a challenge for them to make big
investments in new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the companies that make popular bridal gifts are loathe to
sell online for fear of alienating the stores that carry their
wares.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Black &AMP; Decker's Web site has a bridal area that
suggests wedding presents, but doesn't let Web surfers purchase the
DustBusters and rice cookers.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Fear of undercutting Black &AMP; Decker sales to
department and specialty stores, according to Christina Blosser,
who oversees the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still more important to not jeopardize the already
established relationships (with retailers) than to move
aggressively in the online environment,'' said Blosser.
</P>
<P>
   However, a few Web entrepreneurs have stepped in to fill the
gap, offering consumers a one-stop shop for a diverse selection of
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, most sites have a limited selection of
traditional bridal items. Rather, cyber-registries are more likely
to carry nontraditional items such as soaps, candles, camping gear
and even tickets to events.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Palo Alto newlyweds Virginia Wei and Michael Han
registered last month on Ucopia (www.ucopia.com) for golf lessons,
symphony tickets, a video rental card and museum passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very busy; we spend very little time at home,'' said
Wei, who is an attorney at Wilson, Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati in
Palo Alto. ``Our family and friends were delighted that they could
purchase something for us that comported with our lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ucopia, which is based in San Francisco, offers everything from
gift certificates for skydiving and cooking lessons to expensive
knickknacks from hip South of Market boutiques. It also carriessome
items from more traditional retailers such as Strouds and Smith &AMP;
Hawken.
</P>
<P>
   Ucopia charges retailers a commission, but also charges the
shopper from $1.50 to $5 per transaction. The 3-month-old site
eventually plans to charge couples $45 to register online.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most people, the fee is no big deal in exchange for the
convenience,'' said Dave Gulezian, the 30-year-old Stanford MBA who
co-founded the site with fellow alumnus Brian Anderluh.
</P>
<P>
   Ucopia's main competitor is the The Wedding Network (www.wed
dingnetwork.com), which also offers alternative gifts but doesn't
charge couples or buyers for the transaction, instead taking a
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Wedding Network offers wine clubs from Virtual Vineyards and
cigar shipments from Corona Cigar Co., as well as sporting gear
from GrandWest Outfitters and The Flyfisher.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding Network Executive Vice President Larry Smith said he's
hoping to add some more traditional goods to the slim lineup of
china and linens, but it's a slow process because many retailers
are worried about losing their customers to an online competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of wedding sites but there aren't a lot of
registries because it's not easy,'' Smith said. ``It's very
difficult to work with retailers to develop it.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, some Web sites such as TheGift.com have tried
to bypass retailers altogether by buying directly from
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the manufacturers are willing to participate. For
example, KitchenAid _ which makes the popular bridal gift item, a
stand mixer _ refuses to work with online registries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is that we're so powerful in the bridal
industry that we bring more to the table than they do,'' said
KitchenAid spokesman Brian Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   And other manufacturers refuse to let Jeff Swearingen, the
founder of TheGift.com, order small quantities of items.
</P>
<P>
   So he has actually purchased a warehouse-full of china, crystal,
silverware, blenders and grills _ in anticipation of future bridal
registry customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tells me I'm nuts,'' he said. ``But I'd rather sit
on some inventory for a few months than make a customer wait a few
months'' for an item they've purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Swearingen is also opening a store in nearby Dallas so that he
can lure Internet-leery manufacturers to sell to him.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that his business is a long shot, but he believes that
in a few years online bridal registries will become the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say that we're building a luxury liner in ankle-deep
water,'' he said. ``Next year we'll be knee-deep.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-20-98 2203EDT &QL;
</P>
