<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-COPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE POLICE, DRAGNET BECOMES THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN TEDESCO   
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As Dragnet meets the Internet, police work in
cities across the country is taking a high-tech step beyond ``just
the facts, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, the St. Paul Police Department posts names and
pictures of people charged with prostitution, along with the men
accused of picking them up.
</P>
<P>
   In the college town of Pullman, Wash., the police posted
people's pictures on the Internet after a student riot near
Washington State University.
</P>
<P>
   From on-line wanted posters to Internet maps of neighborhood
crime spots, police forces are tapping new ways to reach the public
using the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, police departments have been very closed with
their information,'' said Clara Zainie, who maintains the San
Antonio Police Department's Web page. ``One of the tenets of
community policing is to try to share with the public as much
information as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 400 Internet Web sites for municipal police
departments in the United States, and 26 sites for state police
agencies. Although the sites in some communities offer little more
than a list of phone numbers and, maybe, a picture of a squad car,
other sites are more arresting.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio police Web page provides neighborhood crime
maps, a database of impounded vehicles, a real-time listing of
traffic accidents in the city, crime trends and more. The
information can help a commuter avoid traffic snarls or show
resident Web surfers how many burglaries have hit their
neighborhoods in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The crime maps have received up to 100 hits a day, Zainie said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood groups find the maps useful to spot trouble areas _
or to dispel the perception that an area is crime ridden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people think there's a lot more crime in their
neighborhood than there actually is,'' Zainie said. ``When one
person gets burglarized in two weeks, it's unfortunate,'' she said.
``But, not belittling that, it's hardly a crime wave. People
understand that when they actually see it on a map.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Paul Web site's gallery of people charged with
prostitution has drawn hundreds of comments from 20 countries, most
in favor of the page, said Sylvia Burgos, the police spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people call us and ask if they're going to be on it.
We've had lawyers call and question the legality of it. It's all
legal,'' Burgos said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the launching of the prostitution page in October, the
site recorded about 8,000 hits. Since October, it has received more
than 100,000 hits, Burgos said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, it was too early to say if the page has helped
curb prostitution in the city. The St. Paul Police Department
recently added to its Web site pictures, names and information
about sex offenders living in the community.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio police have no plans in place to post similar
information on the Web. They do plan to add more crime data, crime
analysis and an area where users can print forms, such as
applications for burglar alarms, to save a trip to the police
station.
</P>
<P>
   The police in Montgomery County, Md., a suburb of Washington,
maintain a Web site with crime databases and crime-prevention
information.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville police Internet site includes crime-prevention
questionnaires with titles such as ``Are you going to be raped,
robbed, stabbed, shot or beaten?''
</P>
<P>
   Based on responses, the site computes a score. The higher the
score, the higher the risk of being a likely victim of a crime.
Those determined to be high risk are told: ``You are in a dangerous
category and better change your habits lest you be tomorrow's
headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   The police aren't the only ones distributing law enforcement
information on the Internet. Some organizations use the Web to
police the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Complaint Center in Tallahassee, Fla., makes
available video recordings of apparent police misconduct from
different cities. The American Civil Liberties Union has a site
focused on police reform. Visitors can print a pocket card with
guidelines on how to handle encounters with the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Speed Trap Registry reports rumored speed traps from across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-21-98 1314EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
