<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY     07-22 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTLY, THE U.S. HAS A LEAD _ BUT CAN IT BE PROTECTED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   High wages are the birthright of Americans. But in a world
economy, says Professor Michael Porter of Harvard Business School,
high wages have to be earned. Increasingly, he argues, they have to
be earned through innovation _ by offering new things that can be
sold at top prices.
</P>
<P>
   America can never beat China and Indonesia in hand-stitching
sneakers. We have to focus on the high-profit items _ new drugs,
the latest software and the design and marketing of sneakers. To
maximize those things, argued Porter in a recent speech to chief
executives, we need to know why some countries succeed in creating
many new things, and others don't.
</P>
<P>
   As a measure of innovation, Porter chose patents filed in more
than one country. The countries with the highest rates of
international patenting _ Japan, Switzerland, the United States and
Germany _ have high exports and high wages.
</P>
<P>
   In work for the corporate-funded Council on Competitiveness in
Washington, D.C., Porter tracked down the factors in international
patenting. He found that high-patent societies tend to be open and
competitive. They protect intellectual property rights. They have
money to spend, and they spend a lot on higher education and the
employment of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Who employs those scientists is a question that matters.
Scientists employed in the private and not-for-profit sectors
produce more patents than those employed by government. ``I'm sorry
about that for some of you here,'' Porter said at a recent
conference, ``but that's what the model showed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another finding is that the number of scientific articles _ a
measure of basic science _ ``is not actually significant'' in
explaining the rates of patenting.
</P>
<P>
   This is a shock. Americans expect basic research to pay off in
dollars and cents. Yet British biochemist Terence Kealey argued in
his 1996 book, ``The Economic Laws of Scientific Research,'' that
Britain leads Europe in scientific papers per capita. If basic
science is what counts, Britain should also lead Europe in patents.
Actually, it is far behind, at less than one-fifth the rate of the
Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Porter's findings is that of all the measures of
capital markets _ how well societies set aside money for new
ventures _ ``none of them are significant'' in explaining why some
societies have more patents.
</P>
<P>
   This is another odd result. How could venture money not be
important in generating patents? Perhaps, Porter suggests, other
countries have different ways of funding new ventures and we're not
measuring them.
</P>
<P>
   What we can measure, and what clearly does count, are spending
in research and development, jobs in research and development, and
spending on high school and college education. And on these
measures, Porter sees reason to worry. The American economy has
been so successful in the 1990s that we have begun to slack off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fundamentals have stagnated, except in the life
sciences,'' Porter says. ``The only place where we see graduate
degrees rising rapidly is in the life sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, new competitors are gaining ground _ and not
the low-wage countries. In international patents, says Porter,
``India, China and Malaysia are not in the game.'' But Taiwan is,
as are South Korea, Singapore and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Taiwan and South Korea each accounted for more
information-technology patents than Britain, says John Yochelson,
president of the Council on Competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. advantage may be draining away. For decades, our
universities have have trained scientists and engineers from around
the world, many of whom have stayed here to work for us. Foreign
students have been a ``great strategic asset to the United
States,'' Yochelson said. But as their home countries develop, more
students from such places as Taiwan and South Korea are returning
home to work.
</P>
<P>
   A final change is that federal funding for science is in a
steady decline. Whether this is bad depends on what the private
sector does in place of it. Federal funding has not been an
unalloyed benefit; much has been for defense, and despite the
military origins of the Internet, defense research has not been an
economic investment. The Swiss and Japanese have done almost none
of it and live fat and happy lives. They kept their research
civilian and private, as ours was before 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we'll follow their way is an open question. But we are
moving away from the pattern of the past 60 years, when science was
driven by the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a new strategy,'' Porter said in his speech to the
chief executives. ``We need to figure out what that is _ and we
need to get it implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
