<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      07-22 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAYS FEELS GOP   HEAT OVER FINANCING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A late-night whiff of cigar smoke wafted into the
House chamber as Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut
endured the wrath of his Republican leaders for defying their
back-room strategy to block a new campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Angry voices echoed in the nearly empty chamber as Shays fought
one Republican amendment after another aimed at scuttling an
overhaul plan he is sponsoring with Representative Martin T.
Meehan, a Lowell Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In a midsummer drama that is lurching toward a final scene,
Shays has emerged as a pariah among many Republicans who see his
push for new campaign-finance laws as an unwarranted attack on
House Speaker Newt Gingrich's authority and their incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, yielding to pressure from Shays and his allies in
April, abandoned their opposition to a full debate on how money
mixes with politics in federal elections. They pledged to complete
debate on the issue before the summer recess begins Aug. 7, and the
debate has been scheduled in bits and pieces over seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the development rankles many GOP members, who blame Shays
for turning the spotlight on campaign funding while they scurry to
raise millions of dollars for their reelection races.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate continued long after dark Monday, some Republican
lawmakers directed sneers and jeers at Shays. And the possibility
lingered that Gingrich will punish the former Peace Corps volunteer
for his renegade challenge, even as it gains momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy wants to play the game by his rules or take his ball
and go home,'' said Representative Scott McInnis, a Colorado
Republican, moments after clashing with Shays on the House floor
over a campaign-finance amendment. ``That tends to irritate a lot
of his colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays, 52, a moderate who has represented a wealthy district in
southwestern Connecticut for 11 years, has called the current
campaign-finance system a recipe for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill, which already has been subject to 21
Republican amendments, with 34 to go, would ban the unlimited,
largely unregulated contributions known as ``soft money'' that
increasingly have influenced federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the measure's many other provisions is a
requirement that groups running so-called ``issue advocacy''
campaigns aimed at influencing elections disclose how much the
campaigns cost and who contributed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the high-stakes struggle, Shays repeatedly has broken party
decorum in challenging the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   When Gingrich raised procedural obstacles to his overhaul plan,
Shays called them ``dumb'' and ``deceitful.'' He openly questioned
Representative Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, on
the House floor in April about the leadership's integrity on the
campaign-finance issue.
</P>
<P>
   And his criticism prompted Representative Tom DeLay of Texas,
the majority whip, to issue an apology last week for appearing to
suggest that people with foreign-sounding names were prone to
breaking campaign-finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Shays's staff did not comply with several requests in recent
days to arrange an interview with him about his standing with House
Republicans. Sources said Shays wants to avoid unnecessary
controversy as his long quest for a vote on the Shays-Meehan bill
appears to be nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   However, Shays also faces the possibility of sanctions by
Republican leaders for future acts that are seen as undermining the
GOP majority.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said Shays' recent defiance of party leaders
prompted them to circulate a petition calling on Gingrich to punish
GOP members who break ranks with the majority on major procedural
issues. Gingrich was among the first lawmakers to sign the
petition.
</P>
<P>
   For Shays, the punishment could mean losing his chairmanship of
a subcomittee on human resources and his ranking as the
third-most-senior Republican on the powerful House Budget
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the potential cost of his standing up to the GOP leaders,
Shays's allies described his effort on the campaign-finance front
in heroic terms.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers in both parties said Shays had distinguished
himself as admirably as Representative Greg Ganske, an Iowa
Republican, who defied GOP leaders last week by appearing with
President Clinton at a Capitol Hill event promoting broader rights
for patients in managed-care health programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Chris is taking a lot of heat,'' said Representative
Patrick J. Kennedy, a Rhode Island Democrat who favors rewriting
the campaign-finance laws. ``But members of both parties respect
his integrity on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Shays who spent months enlisting enough Republican allies
to form a majority coalition with the Democratic minority and force
GOP leaders to permit a full debate on the Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been very much a discomfort for a lot of people in our
party,'' said Representative Zach Wamp, a Tennesee Republican who
joined Shays and a dozen other GOP members in signing a petition in
April that spurred the leadership to act.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shays, Wamp has been the target of a blistering backlash,
including radio ad campaigns in their districts funded by the
National Right to Life Committee, a vigorous opponent of
Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wamp said he and Shays have faced some of the most stinging
criticism from their Republican colleagues. ``There's no question
we have felt their wrath,'' he said. ``The cutting comments, the
constant looks, we get them all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign-finance debate, Shays has chastised
Republican colleagues who have vowed to vote against his bill yet
continue to offer amendments to the measure that he denounces as
``poison pills.''
</P>
<P>
   He ridiculed as ``foolish'' a proposal by Representative Anne M.
Northup, a Kentucky Republican, to ban political parties and
candidates from paying cash to workers who help get voters to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, support for the Shays-Meehan bill appears to continue to
grow. In a key victory Monday, Shays-Meehan supporters defeated an
amendment, 248-150, that they said was aimed at breaking apart
their majority coalition. The measure would have required labor
unions to disclose their spending on all political activities, not
just elections.
</P>
<P>
   As the vote ended, Representative Sherwood Boehlert, a New York
Republican who favors Shays-Meehan, said he knew what Shays was
experiencing because he has encountered similar wrath from GOP
colleagues as a leading proponent of strict environmental
regulations. But he said he expects that Shays will survive the
storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
