<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-PEOPLE-BOS &LR;      07-22 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PEOPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISCAL WOES TEAR AT PSYCHE OF JAPANESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.  R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Well before the sun rises every weekday, a few hundred
day laborers crowd outside a social-welfare center in a
hardscrabble district of northeast Tokyo. Some try to crawl under a
metal shutter so that they can be first at the job placement
window, and when the gate rattles open at 6:30, there is a ragged,
desperate scramble to the front of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Only four jobs were given out on a recent morning, about average
these days as construction projects falter and contractors go bust
during Japan's worst recession in 23 years. Hundreds who didn't get
work face another day without pay, so many remain till 9 to get
vouchers for a flophouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here an hour early and pushed my way to the front and
got a job. I was one of the lucky ones. I feel sorry for people
around me _ a lot of these people can't eat,'' said Minoru Sato,
48, a driver. ``I can only get jobs 10 or 15 days a month now.
Something strange is happening this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town in a glittering office tower, dozens of men laid off
from white-collar jobs are learning to fold linens, bus tables, and
make beds, hoping a hotel and restaurant training course gives them
a new start. In a high-rent district nearby, once-overflowing
boutiques attract fewer passersby, while the government employment
office draws a steady stream of visitors in business suits,
visitors with downcast eyes and dwindling savings.
</P>
<P>
   A nation that long has prided itself on nearly full employment,
Japan is suffering its worst rates of joblessness and bankruptcy
since World War II. In contrast to other Asian nations, rocked by
huge debt and devalued currency, Japan's economy is not in a
meltdown; it has been stagnant for most of the decade. It's hard to
see many obvious signs of decline in this bustling, expensive city.
But at companies where tough layoff decisions are being made and at
job centers where fewer opportunities are available, the human
impact of the recession is painfully evident.
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis is still more psychological than real for
many Japanese. But that could change if a new prime minister, to be
chosen Friday, fails to restructure an economy that is regulated,
protected, and bogged down with bad loans and inefficient
companies. Any overhaul, however, will mean more job losses and
business failures in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and discontent over the economy fed a revolt of urban
voters last week that forced Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to
resign and spurred the three Liberal Democratic Party politicians
vying for his job to promise tax cuts and government spending to
reverse the recession.
</P>
<P>
   But many Japanese are likely to hoard a tax break rather than
spend it, because they worry where their next yen is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, everyone was so certain that our future would be
bright. Now we're not so sure,'' said Tsuyoshi Sudo, 25, a systems
engineer. Although he doesn't know anyone who was laid off, he is
still worried. ``Even if things aren't so bad now, we feel Japan
doesn't have the means to make things better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yurika Kurakata, 22, a recent college graduate, says the
recession is hitting low-income people hardest, while those who are
better off can live off their savings for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not be traveling as much, we might cut out some
luxuries, but our lives are not that different than before,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't make the slump easier to accept. ``Japanese
have pride in their economy and country, because we were previously
leading the world, and we don't want to admit we're in a
recession,'' Kurakata said. ``The government is trying hard to
avoid a panic like what triggered the Great Depression ... but I'm
scared. If a crisis did happen, it would be so hard to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, even with a growth rate near zero for several years, the
standard of living has remained fairly constant,, said Teizo Taya,
managing director of the Daiwa Institute of Research. There is
nothing to compare to the hunger or panic that has savaged
countries such as Indonesia, but there are subtle signs of despair
and downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo's notoriously pricey bars and shops still see traffic, but
many proprietors admit sales are down as customers linger over
fewer drinks or buy one article of status clothing instead of
three. Taxi drivers are suffering as people stay home more. And
although prices have fallen, people aren't buying. This creates a
vicious cycle, since lower consumption leads to company losses and
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sei Kojima, a salesman for a new line of Toyota luxury cars
called Progres, said his showroom is meeting its goals, but admits
a few customers canceled orders when their bonuses were eliminated.
``For me, things are still OK, but ... anybody could get fired at
any time these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulate of laid-off bankers with hefty car loans and
mortgages whose wives are now working as escorts. Gambling on horse
races, bicycle and boat contests, and lottery tickets is up. Newly
homeless men in business suits have been found sleeping on park
benches. Students interviewed say their parents have sent them to
less-expensive universities.
</P>
<P>
   Those hit hardest, of course, are the record 4.1 percent _ or
2.9 million people _ unemployed, and the victims of the 10,173
bankruptcies in the first half of this year, a nearly 30 percent
jump from the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   A corresponding jobless rate in the United States would be
considered good news. But in a country that pays companies to keep
excess workers on the payroll, and where a job so defines one's
identity, it is cause for national shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can't be talking about pride at a time like this, but
I don't want to lower my standards,'' said a weary-looking Katsuji
Suetake, 50, who was laid off last month from his management job at
a women's apparel company, and was searching job boards a few days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   He soon may be too desperate to be choosy. ``I'm having
difficulty in all aspects of my life,'' Suetake said. ``I can't go
on any longer without a job. I'm borrowing from relatives and I
need to pay it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Osamu Mori, 43, former head of accounting for an electronics
manufacturer, also feels adrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the same job my whole life. I don't even know how to
look for a job,'' he said. ``I've been looking since March, but
there are too many applicants for each job.... I was laid off with
quite a few people, so I'm worried about them as well. And I'm
worried about supporting my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the government's Hello Work jobs center say they
get 10 to 20 applicants for every posting now, as opposed to five
in the past. In May, there were 2.5 million people seeking work in
state-run employment offices nationwide _ up 14 percent from last
year _ but only 1.25 million jobs were available.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the street, I don't notice or feel like there's a
recesssion,'' said Fujio Aoyanagi, employment counseling director
at the Hello Work branch in Shibuya District. ``But in this office,
I meet people all day who've been laid off.... The hardest hit are
white-collar,'' age 45 and up. ``The saddest are people over 55,
who are 30 percent of applicants but eligible for only 5 percent of
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the United States, employers can openly restrict
postings by age here. Unemployment insurance pays three months at
60 percent salary for people who have worked at least six months,
and is limited to 300 days for those who have worked a lifetime,
according to Aoyanagi.
</P>
<P>
   At one training center in the Iidabashi business district,
scores of men in their 50s are trying to reclaim their lives. Their
companies forced them to retire without pensions, and these people
have given up on getting a job in their field.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiake Kume, 58, used to run a department for a machine
manufacturer. Many small firms, such as the company where he used
to work, have taken the brunt of the downturn and been forced to
downsize, accounting for 70 percent of layoffs. Today, Kume wears a
white shirt with a bow tie and name tag, and is training to be a
waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Kume is sure he will master the skills, and he expects new jobs
will be created by the government's promised deregulation of the
service and finance sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my fear,'' he confided, ``is that young people will take
those jobs. Whether they are available to us is another question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
