<P>
   Surgeons make big incisions because of the need to get their
hands in the body. But with tiny robotic hands, their incisions
would be smaller _ and less traumatic _ reports Kathy A. Svitil, an
associate editor at Discover magazine
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-DOCTOR-ROBOT-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEART SMARTS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY DAJER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wu had entered the emergency room at New York Downtown
Hospital gasping for air. The elderly woman had been shopping with
her daughter when suddenly her legs lost power and her lungs grew
tight. Wu's electrotrocardiogram _ the tracing of electrical
activity in the heart _ looked erratic. Instead of a smooth tracing
bringing forth 80 beautifully spaced spikes a minute, it was
spitting out a rapid-fire and asynchronous 140 spikes, or
heartbeats, a minute. Her ailment: atrial fibrillation. Tony Dajer,
former associate director of the emergency room at New York
Downtown Hospital, reports on the wonder substance that saved Wu's
life _ and that can be found right in your own medicine cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-HEART-SMARTS-NYTSF)
