<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-NEWS-GARAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR DONATION PROGRAM HELPS PEOPLE IN NEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BURLINGTON, Vt. _ &UR;  &LR; A car is your life's blood if you're one of
the rural poor, living in the country with no buses, no trains, no
trolleys.
</P>
<P>
   An automobile means that everything is made easier: Buying
groceries. Going to the doctor. Doing the laundry. It means you
don't have to ask friends and family for rides.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it means a job.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Pecor, &UR;  &LR; a 29-year-old single mother of two young girls,
had a new job that was going to get her off of welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But then she and her boyfriend split up. And suddenly Pecor was
without a ride to work. She couldn't afford to buy a car, not even
a used one. So she had to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, I felt like my legs had been cut
off,'' said Pecor, who lives in a trailer in Milton, north of
Burlington, with a girlfriend and one of her daughters. Her other
daughter lives with Pecor's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone told Pecor about the Good News Garage, a
first-of-its-kind program that fixes and sells donated cars to
people in need. The garage was started by a handful of Evangelical
Lutheran churches in the Burlington area two years ago, with
initial funding from Lutheran Social Services of New England.
</P>
<P>
   In May, she drove away from the Good News Garage here in a 1982
silver Chevrolet Citation. She paid $263.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``When I got the car it was like I sprouted wings,'' said
Pecor, who got her job back and went off welfare last month. ``I
was free of having to depend on other people to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pecor and others with little disposable income, no car
equals tough times, particularly in rural states with little public
transit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``In the whole spectrum of welfare reform, transportation
stands out as one of the top issues that states are going to have
to deal with,'' said William Waldman, executive director of the
American Public Human Services Association, a Washington-based
advocacy group for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, service jobs are sprouting in remote places that can
only be reached by car. In Williston, a town outside Burlington
with no public transportation, Wal-Mart, Home Depot, and Circuit
City have opened stores recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have decent jobs, but if you don't have a car you're out
of luck,'' said the Rev. Frederick K. Neu, pastor of Ascension
Lutheran Church in South Burlington, one of the congregations that
helped start the Good News Garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who have cars take them for granted,'' added Neu,
sitting inside the red brick building that houses the garage by the
shores of Lake Champlain. ``But if you don't have one, life is very
different. It affects what kind of job you have, where you live,
where you go to buy groceries, everything. It's the difference
between being able to provide for your family and being out on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, nearly 300 cars have been donated to the Good News
program. Many, beyond repair, were sent to the junk yard. The
garage prefers cars that are less than 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We don't want anyone's yard ornament,'' &UR;  &LR; said Hal Colston, a
member of Good Shepherd Lutheran Church in Jericho, who was hired
to direct the garage.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 donated cars are sitting outside the garage and at
several church parking lots waiting to be repaired. The Good News
Garage, which has a budget of $220,000, does not make any profit on
the cars. It only charges for the cost of repairs, and it is
difficult for the garage to raise money for additional mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the garage has sold 140 cars for an average of $550. But
there are still 350 people on the waiting list. There is an income
limit for applicants pegged to the federal poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   The program's success has drawn attention from 50 communities
nationwide interested in starting something similar. Edith Lohr,
president of Lutheran Social Services of New England, said the
agency hopes to start programs in Sturbridge, Mass., and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Erica Quinby, 20, a single mother who lives in Middlebury, was
all smiles the other day as she screwed a license plate on the 1989
Honda Civic she was buying for $530.
</P>
<P>
   Quinby, who receives money through Aid to Needy Families with
Children, starts a job in September doing outreach to single
parents and young families. She needs a car, but her last one, a
1980 Saab, died last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then she has borrowed her mother's car or ridden the buses
in Middlebury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``But it's not easy carrying a stroller and carrying groceries
on the bus,'' said Quinby, who applied six months ago to the Good
News Garage. ``And there's no way I could do this job without a
car. The car will bring me financial indpendence and is another
piece to get me going in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Cathie Jones had already experienced the rush of independence
that comes up with a job and car. She had been on welfare for about
15 years before she went back to school for a degree in medical
record-keeping. She got a job last year at two area Brooks
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   But her car stopped running in December. And Jones had to count
on her elderly uncle to drive her back and forth to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt bad because he was doing this for me,'' said
Jones, who lives in Winooski, near Burlington. ``But I had no money
for another car.''
</P>
<P>
   It took two months, but Jones was finally able to buy a 1987
Honda Accord from the Good News Garage in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like a little girl when I got my car,'' she said. ``It
really changed my attitude. It's a matter of pride to be able to do
things for yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
