<HEADLINE>
AFTER SUCCESSFUL STINT, POLICY QUITS AS 49ERS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Carmen Policy, a driving force behind the
success of the San Francisco 49ers in almost eight years as team
president, has resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The move, not totally unexpected, caps Policy's bitter split
with former 49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo and reportedly moves former
head coach Bill Walsh, a DeBartolo friend and ally, to top spot as
Policy's likely successor.
</P>
<P>
   Policy was reportedly in Ohio to discuss a possible executive
job with the expansion Cleveland Browns, due to join the NFL for
the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   49ers Vice President Dwight Clark announced the resignation
Tuesday night after meeting with head coach Steve Mariucci and
other team officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly stunned, and I'm sorry that it came to this,''
Clark said. ``But as far as this team is concerned, we have a great
team assembled and we're going to go play football. That's what we
do now. Play football and keep them focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Team officials would not speculate about a successor.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation culminates a months-long feud between Policy and
DeBartolo. The longtime friends split over questions of DeBartolo's
involvement in legalized gambling and its impact on the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo relinquished control of the team in December after
learning he could be indicted in a gambling corruption probe in
Louisiana. DeBartolo's sister, Denise DeBartolo York, took over,
but her brother has since moved to regain full ownership of the
club.
</P>
<P>
   Policy has said he hasn't spoken a word to Eddie DeBartolo since
heated meeting Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Policy's departure ends a 15-year association with the 49ers,
during which time the team became the first to win five Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Policy joined the 49ers front office in 1983 as vice president
and legal counsel. Before that he had served for many years as
DeBartolo's personal attorney.
</P>
<P>
   He took over as president in January 1991, and was given the
task of rebuilding a team that had won back-to-back Super Bowls two
years before. In 1993, he faced the arduous task of negotiating the
league's first-ever salary cap with a team loaded with well-paid
players.
</P>
<P>
   Policy was a pioneer in manipulating the cap _ stretching out
player compensation over several years to keep the team under the
league limit. Decried as trickery by executives at other franchises
at the time, the approach has since been widely copied.
</P>
<P>
   After the team won Super Bowl XXIX in 1994, Policy was named NFL
Executive of the Year by the Sporting News and Pro Football Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Observers credited Policy's success to his creative accounting,
keen recruiting sense, strong work ethic as well as his close
relationship with DeBartolo. Both natives of Youngstown, Ohio, the
two had been friends for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   To many, the two men were inseparable. They looked so much alike
that publications sometimes confused them in photo captions.
</P>
<P>
   They campaigned hard together last year to pass a $100 million
bond to help pay for a new stadium in San Francisco. The future of
the proposed $525 million stadium and commercial center has since
become murky because of questions about the ownership of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between the two men began shortly after DeBartolo
received a letter in November from the U.S. attorney in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said DeBartolo could be indicted by a federal grand
jury in Baton Rouge in connection with a $400,000 payment to former
Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards to secure a riverboat gambling
license. DeBartolo has not been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBartolo relinquished control of the team, Policy retained
his position and gained a minority stake in the team. DeBartolo and
his sister were soon squabbling and the future of the stadium
project.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Policy acknowledged that if DeBartolo regained control
of the team, he would likely be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if I don't fit into Eddie's scheme of things,
where he is, where he wants to go,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   The news comes just as the 49ers training camp starts at its new
location in Stockton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
