<HEADLINE>
IN CANADA, WILD HORSES MEET A FRAGILE ECOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ For mariners during the great era of
sail and early decades of steam, Sable Island was the treacherous
``graveyard of the Atlantic,'' site of hundreds of shipwrecks that
claimed thousands of lives over the course of four centuries.
</P>
<P>
   For penny-pinching Colonial New Englanders, however, the island
represented free pasture. In the 1700s, Bostonians of various
stripes _ from an exiled Huguenot preacher to a merchant and horse
thief _ started setting horses out to forage on the forbidding
27-mile-long wedge of sand and sea grass perched on the far eastern
edge of the continental shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred and fifty years later, the hardy descendants of
those horses still range free on the storm-battered sliver.
</P>
<P>
   But as offshore natural gas projects rise all around Sable, and
as stewardship of the island passes from the Canadian government to
a nonprofit trust comprising representatives from public and
private sectors, the future of the legendary herd, which numbers
about 300 horses, has become the focus of a quiet but furious
debate.
</P>
<P>
   A recent joint study by the Canadian and Nova Scotia governments
suggested that the horses might be eating themselves out of a home,
devouring the sea grass that holds the island together at a pace
that might cause serious ecological harm _ and even destroy Sable
Island altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sable is basically just sand glued together by vegetation,''
said Anthony Lock, a federal biologist and primary author of the
Sable Island Conservation Strategy, the name of the study. ``Lose
too much grass and you could lose the island.''
</P>
<P>
   The study cautiously suggested that if further research shows
hungry horses are hastening the erosion of the fragile strand, then
``consideration should be given to the management of the horse
population.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lexicon of wildlife officialdom, ``management'' means
human intervention to control animal populations for the greater
environmental good _ in theory, it could mean killing off small
numbers of horses to reduce consumption of the coarse grass. It has
also been hinted by officials that the population might be reduced
through use of high-tech birth control methods.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of some specialists, the creatures constitute the
last truly wild horse herd in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only modern herd unmanaged by humans,'' said Ian
A. McLaren, a wildlife biologist at Nova Scotia's Dalhousie
University and author of a book on Sable Island. ``These are
beautiful animals, roaming unfettered as the sea wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the release of the study, headlines across Canada
proclaimed the herd might be culled _ an alarmist spin, to be sure,
but one with enough historical precedent to rouse public fears. In
1960, the government declared the Sable Island horses to be
``surplus'' and announced plans to ship them off to mainland
rendering plants for transformation into dog food and glue.
</P>
<P>
   That scheme was finally scrapped as tearful letters from
hundreds of schoolchildren poured into newspapers and government
offices. ``You should let the ponies have peace,'' wrote elementary
school pupil Michelle Miller of Weston, Ontario, in a widely
publicized letter to then-Prime Minister John Diefenbaker. ``P.S.
My dog and many others do not like horse meat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the new study, letters are again flowing to
editorial pages _ mostly in Nova Scotia _ from animal-loving
citizens suspicious that the government may be up to old tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a highly emotional issue,'' said McLaren. ``Many believe
that after hundreds of years, these horses truly belong to the
island. But some scientists have the gut feeling that you shouldn't
allow feral animals in a wild place, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to hardcore ecologists, the unnatural presence of horses
on the island represents a potentially dangerous intrusion on the
natural order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ecologically moral thing to do is be very watchful of
these large herbivores running loose on a small, fragile island,''
said Lock, who is marine issues biologist with the Atlantic branch
of Environment Canada, the federal environmental protection agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one is officially saying that the horses should be
culled or removed, there is no such plan in place,'' stressed Lock.
``The conservation strategy simply states that we have to research
very carefully whether the horses are damaging the integrity of
Sable.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1737 that Rev. Andrew Le Mercier, a Huguenot _ or
French Protestant _ pastor living in Boston, set the first horses
out to graze among the grand dunes of the island.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades later, another Bostonian, Thomas Hancock,
plundered 60 horses from farmsteads of Acadian settlers expelled
from Nova Scotia by British overlords. The merchant and shipowner
plunked the ill-gotten herd down on Sable, and apparently forgot
about it.
</P>
<P>
   The wild herd of today is descended from these colonial horses.
Actually, there is not one island herd but scores of small herds
consisting of several mares and young horses kept in line by senior
stallions, according to the Nova Scotia Museum of Natural History.
The horses grow shaggy coats, subsist on sea grass and spring
water, and huddle between sand dunes when 110-mile-per-hour winter
winds lash the island.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brutal climate, so tough that even ship's rats have
failed to survive. There has been a human presence on Sable Island
since 1801, when Nova Scotia opened a lifesaving outpost on the
island to assist shipwreck victims. Today only three full-time
weather station employees, conducting atmospheric tests, and the
occasional wildlife researcher share the island with the horses,
gray seals, and seabirds.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a mile wide, the low-lying, boomerang-shaped island lies
100 miles east of Nova Scotia, smack in the middle of
trans-Atlantic shipping lanes and _ until the advent of radar and
other modern navigational electronics _ nearly invisible to even
the wariest of skippers until it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1583, there have been more than 250 recorded shipwrecks on
its shores _ the actual toll probably exceeds 500 vessels _ with a
loss of about 10,000 lives. The last wreck occurred in 1947; the
life-saving station closed in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Sable is Canada's most remote island, and is shrouded by dense
fog for an average 127 days a year. No other place in North America
is more pummeled by ferocious storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world, a primordial world,'' Norman Bell, 85,
who maintained the island's power station with his wife in the
1960s, recalled earlier this year. ``Nothing can stand there for
long. The wind and sand blows everything away that isn't native,
except those tough old ponies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
