<SLUG> BC-TALL-SHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR SHIP REPLICA MAY BE MORE SHOW THAN SAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Mass. _ Next month, a full-rigged $5.8-million replica of
the tall ship that once made this city rich, is scheduled to arrive
here. ``Friendship'' comes loaded with sailing options that would
have left captains of yesteryear sea-green with envy but baffled
because this ship has no plans to leave the dock.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service, which owns the 170-foot long vessel,
says the Friendship's primary mission is to be a stationary
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Then why, critics ask, was the vessel equipped with twin
300-horsepower diesel engines, air conditioning, operational
rigging for 38 sails, power steering, and a Coast Guard certificate
to transport 149 passengers over the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is an extraordinary waste of money,'' said Rafe
Parker, president of Sea Education Association and founder and
former chairman of the National Maritime Alliance, which serves a
wide range of sea-related institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of ethics. This ship was designed at
considerable expense to sail. Not using it to its full capacity is
a waste of a wonderful concept on which sea education is based,''
Parker added.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Kesselman, superintendent of the Salem Maritime National
Historic Site, counters that while the National Park Service is not
in the business of building a navy, it was prudent to construct a
ship that had the option of sailing sometime in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an evolutionary process. For now, Friendship will be a
dockside, interpretive exhibit. She will not sail, at least for a
couple of years,'' Kesselman said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Friendship appears destined to become deluxe
dockside decor at Derby Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   To be moored at the Salem Maritime National Historic Site,
Friendship is a replica East Indiaman merchant ship receiving final
touches at the Scarano Boat Building yard on the Hudson River in
Albany. Constructed with Douglas fir wood, Friendship is due
mid-August in Salem, where rigging and mast assembly will continue
for at least another year under the auspices of Scarano.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is about a year behind schedule, due in part to the
time it takes to relearn the forgotten art of building big wooden
boats. It also arrives with a price tag paid almost entirely by
taxpayers,who probably will also be picking up the ship's $300,000
annual maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   Friendship will join an elite, small family of similarly full
rigged American ships including the Constitution from Charlestown,
Mass. and the Rose from Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   With all the sails set, including the stunsails _ small
banner-like sails set outside the entire rig _ Friendship can fly
38 sails, promising a splendid sight and a daunting challenge for
the crew. The question becomes: how do you find a captain and crew
capable of sailing the shipwhen it seldom, if ever, leaves the
dock?
</P>
<P>
   David Wood, former commander of the Coast Guard tallship Eagle,
questions the wisdom of building a sailing ship without a sailing
plan already in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Park Service has sailed into a fundamental conflict. You
can't sail and also be a port ornament. There's an old saying:
`Ships and men rot in port,''' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Harris, a strong supporter of the project and the
executive director of the Salem Partnership, a non-profit booster
for economic development in the region, believes such criticisms
are unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the boat actually here and ready to be tested, we
don't know'' how difficult it will be to sail, Harris said. ``I can
say that, in time, we will learn not only how the ship best fits
into the National Park program, but how we will use it and sail it
to promote Salem.''
</P>
<P>
   One scenario she envisions is taking the ship to special events
such as Tall Ships 2000 in Boston, privately raising the $100,000
needed for such a trip from the ship's dockside admission fee,
T-shirt sales, or private on-board parties held during off-peak
tourist hours. One complicating factor is that the ship, with more
than a 13-foot draft, will only be able to sail through Salem
Harbor at certain tides because of shoals, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials estimate some 800,000 visitors come annually
to the Salem Maritime National Historic Site, which offers few
outdoor exhibits harkening back to the ship trading days of the
late 1700s. It was that dearth of nautical artifacts that gave
birth to the original plea for a ship like the Friendship, first
voiced more than a decade ago by the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1994, after much prodding by US Senators John
Kerry and Edward Kennedy, and former US Representative Peter
Torkildsen, the US Congress committed $4.3 million to the project.
The Salem Partnership raised another $1.05 &UR;  &LR; million from state,
county and city sources, and $300,000 from private pockets. Harris
said the remaining $150,000 will be raised when potential donors
have a chance to actually see the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Dewell Smith, executive director of the American Sail
Training Association that takes many sailing cadets to sea each
year, praises Salem for building a ship that meets sea-going
specifications despite the current lack of game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken the long view. You can't go from 0 to 60 in this
business overnight. It's far more prudent to feel out your
community, then set a plan,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
