u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BILINGUAL-BOS &LR;      07-22 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BILINGUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CALIFORNIA SCHOOLS, A DIFFICULT PROPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even now, with the deadline to end bilingual
education for California schoolchildren looming, the adults in
charge of dismantling the programs continue to fight over language.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of bilingual education insist that 60 days is enough
time to rewrite education history. Besides, they add, the law is
the law. But the people who back bilingual education call the
timetable impossible, and argue that the voter referendum known as
Proposition 227 is irresponsible anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The result is confusion in most school districts and open
defiance in others, with two of the largest saying they may refuse
to comply and the largest _ Los Angeles _ agreeing to go halfway at
best. While Proposition 227 allows parents to sue teachers who
refuse to teach in English, state educators concede they may have
no way of knowing which classrooms are emphasizing English and
which are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth, schools are going to have extraordinary
flexibility,'' said Sonia Hernandez, deputy superintendent for
curriculum and instruction at the state Department of Education.
``If some teacher refuses to comply and closes their classroom
door, it's going to be almost impossible to know. ... The truth of
the matter is we can't be the Prop 227 police.''
</P>
<P>
   As opponents of bilingual education interpret the law, students
must be reading and writing in English by Aug. 3, or 60 days after
Californians voted overwhelming to put a stop to learning in other
languages. Sherri Annis of English for the English, the group that
pushed the initiative, said its intention is clear: Students must
be immersed in English. She noted that some school districts are
enthusiastic about the change.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of bilingual education say they cannot meet the
deadline, and add that the law's wording is open to interpretation.
As a result, no one expects the issue to be settled by the start of
the upcoming school year despite a federal judge's refusal to block
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making what we believe is a reasonable attempt to
comply, but there's no way we can do it in time,'' said Joe Tafoya,
deputy superintendent of the predominantly Hispanic Santa Ana
Unified School District, where 37,000 of 53,000 students are in
limited-English programs. ``We don't have the books, we don't have
the materials, we don't have a plan from our board yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Santa Ana, where classes are held year-round, many of the
1,011 school districts statewide are only now coming to grips with
Proposition 227. In addition to retraining teachers, preparing new
coursework, and scrambling for schoolbooks, some are also teaching
parents how to use a loophole in the law and insist on bilingual
education for their children.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, educators in Oakland and San Francisco say
they are bound by a federal consent decree to offer bilingual
classes no matter what voters want. The Los Angeles Unified School
District plans to go only partway: Teach most students in English
but help them in their native languages if necessary. Others, such
as Long Beach, plan a gradual phase-in of English immersion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're caught between the feds and the state, so the school
superintendent has not rushed out to do anything'' to prepare, said
Sue Piper, spokeswoman for the Oakland Unified School District,
where about a third of the 53,000 students are in limited-English
programs. ``We do know kids all learn in different ways whether
they're bilingual or not, and we do take exception to a program
which requires only one approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 227, pushed by a Silicon Valley multimillionaire and
opposed 2-1 by Hispanic voters, forbids teaching students in any
language except English _ unless their parents, teachers,
principal, and local school superintendent agree bilingual
education is best for them. Many districts are planning to help
parents apply for those waivers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, eight districts have asked the state Board of Education
to grant them blanket waivers, Hernandez said. But the board
decided it had no authority to override voters, a decision being
appealed in court. While the board has developed a set of
regulations regarding the new law, it remains unclear how
compliance will be monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the state really equipped to run around from classroom to
classroom asking, `Did you speak Spanish before recess or after?'''
asked Jim Schultz, executive director of the San Francisco-based
Democracy Center, which trains community groups to get involved in
politics. ``How do you check how these kids are being taught?''
</P>
<P>
   Before Proposition 227, about 1.4 million public school students
were enrolled in limited-English programs, with a third of them in
formal bilingual classes. Now all will be required to spend the
first 30 days of the school year immersed in English, even if
parents want taught them in Spanish, Mandarin, or any of the myriad
languages represented in California schools.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the only alternative is to ignore the law. That, they
say, will allow time to negotiate a compromise that allows some
form of bilingual teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to students is that there is a time and a place to
resist the law,'' Schultz said. ``This was a law imposed on Latinos
by white voters. ... I realize that's harsh rhetoric, and that's
not to say there isn't plenty of room for reform in bilingual
education, but playing with a child's education isn't the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
