A7187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-HNS &LR;      07-22 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WASTE TRAIN' PUTS AMERICA IN HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP M. KLASKY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCSICO _ Being escorted this week through San Francisco
Bay are the first of many scheduled shipments of poison fire from
the infernos of foreign nuclear reactor cores _ a batch of spent
nuclear rods from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   An armada of Coast Guard vessels was ready to encircle the three
waste casks from the Korean peninsula in their voyage to the
Concord Naval Weapons Station.
</P>
<P>
   Plans called for the deadly cargo to be transferred onto rail
cars on a ``Waste Train'' that would roll through Martinez and then
Sacramento on its way to ``temporary'' storage in Idaho. Beyond
that, who knows where the rods will rest for the next 200
millennia?
</P>
<P>
   This is just the first of many shipments of the deadly
byproducts of nuclear energy generation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, as part of this country's ``Atoms for Peace''
program, nuclear technology was sold overseas with the proviso that
we would take back the waste. In exchange for the nuclear
technology and the highly enriched uranium we provided, more than
40 nations in the program agreed not to develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some of the participating nations have developed _
or are close to developing _ nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 20 metric tons of nuclear waste from South Korea,
Indonesia, Taiwan, Thailand, the Philippines, France, Denmark,
Germany, Japan and Britain will be returning to the United States.
Additional shipments will enter the East Coast through Charleston,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has yet to devise its own permanent plan to
isolate nuclear waste from the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for deep geologic storage at Yucca Mountain in
Nevada has been beset with cost overruns into the billions of
dollars. The proposed repository is vulnerable to seismic activity.
And there are other serious concerns that the project may not be
able to achieve its goal of a safe and enduring grave for
high-level wastes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurance by the Energy Department, many dangers are
associated with transporting the waste besides the threat of
sabotage. The casks are to travel by train through the Feather
River Canyon, the most accident-prone rail segment in California.
In a 16-year period, 28 derailments and 72 accidents were reported
along the North Fork of the Feather River.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 report, the Union Pacific was cited by federal rail
overseers as experiencing a fundamental breakdown in its safety and
operating procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Energy Department lied to the public when it
reported that the casks were given full and rigorous tests for
safety. The agency depended instead on computer simulations and
scaled-down models, rather than full-size prototypes in actual
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the casks are the most deadly and long-lasting poisons
humankind has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   These shipments should be a wake-up call for all Americans that
the proliferation of nuclear energy is a game that is just not
worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department should stop these shipments and take steps
to determine, on a country-by-country basis, if these wastes can be
stored in highly engineered, monitored, retrievable storage
facilities in the country of origin.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of promoting the nuclear power industry abroad, the U.S.
government should be exporting sustainable energy technologies,
such as wind and solar power, and systematic methods of energy
conservation. The world is becoming too small to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Philip M. Klasky is director of the Bay Area Nuclear Waste
Coalition.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
