<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWER POWER IN THE DECADE OF DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A few weeks back, a guy called me to inquire if I
needed an assistant. Sorry, I told him; I work alone.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, he said. Then he told me how he happened to be looking
for a job. He was 53, had earned a six-figure income for years in
the medical lab business and been downsized out.
</P>
<P>
   He was in OK shape financially, he said, but he wanted to work,
and he simply couldn't get a decent job. Nobody wants to hire a guy
in his 50s, not in an era of rising health insurance costs. He'd
dyed the gray out of his hair and cut a few years off his resume,
but he was getting nowhere in his job search.
</P>
<P>
   My caller was in no way a rarity. The age distributions in the
work force and the general population simply don't jive. Guys in
their 50s, especially their late 50s, are disappearing from the
work force at a fairly startling rate. So, without naming my
caller, I wrote about his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Well, all sorts of response came pouring in. One guy in
California wrote that he was downsized out of an $85,000-a-year
vice presidency and hasn't been able to find a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he said in his letter, ``I've joined the `Working Poor'
at Universal Studios, as they were referred to by the L.A. Business
Journal last week. They pay minimum wage ... Their human resources
person recently related in a chat that their Florida park is run
almost exclusively by downsized executives and college students who
can't find a job either.''
</P>
<P>
   Another California guy wrote, ``I'm a Cold War boomer, grew up
during the nuclear standoff ... I know DOS, Win 3.1, load software,
install PCs and develop business plans and own about 50 copyrights.
Who can use me? Who will hire me?''
</P>
<P>
   But, by far, the most interesting response to that column came
from closer to home, from the comfortable Albany suburb of Clifton
Park. Don Juron wrote this to me:
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked for 40 years in the tough food industry. I started at
the bottom of the ladder and worked my way to the top _ to being
vice president of companies. Then downsizing hit my industry, and I
went from the top, right back down the other side of the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two choices _ be angry and quit or continue to work. I
put my pride aside and continued to work ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I do? Well, I am a delivery driver, and I deliver
flowers ... I get the biggest smile from people when I give them
their flowers for their birthday or for a newborn child. And when I
see that smile and the sparkle in their eyes, I say to myself,
`this is what life is really about _ making people happy and, in
turn, making myself happy ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I happy? Yes _ happier than I have been in 40 years. Am I
bitter? No way. Life goes on, and you forget the past and you say
that each day is going to be a new and better day, and you hold in
your hand every precious strand of happiness ...''
</P>
<P>
   This society would be vastly better off if more people
appreciated the work ethic. But too many people who do appreciate
it define themselves almost solely by their work. And when
capitalism exhibits its randomly cruel side, they let it steal
their very sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Don Juron's letter intrigued me so. Capitalism
smacked him squarely in the teeth, as it has done to so many others
in this hollow, heartless decade.
</P>
<P>
   But he realizes that it also gave him time to smell the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
