<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-22 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOX'S HEIRS SOW HATRED IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Americans seem genuinely baffled by the intractable hatreds
of Northern Ireland, where the incineration of three little boys
can be hailed by some Protestant extremists as a worthy protest in
the name of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even Americans of some strain of Irish descent shrug off the
Orange Order's obdurate refusal to stop rubbing the noses of their
Catholic neighbors in 300 years of now-threatened Protestant
ascendancy. Wearing those bowler hats and those orange sashes?
Marching and drumming their way through grimy sidestreets past
tumbledown apartment blocks of seething Catholics? This celebrates
God?
</P>
<P>
   It now seems the turmoil in Portadown is dissipating, largely
because of the despicable arson attack that killed the Quinn
brothers, described ruefully by nationalist leader Seamus Mallon as
``the victims of somebody else's principles.'' Globe reporter Kevin
Cullen recounted Sunday how, when the Rev. William Bingham, an
Orange Order chaplain, learned that the boys had perished, he
called for an end to the massing of Protestant protesters at the
Drumcree site that had become the flashpoint for the Protestant
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Enough is enough, said the heartsick clergyman. To go forward
with a 15-minute march ``would be a very hollow victory because it
would be in the shadow of three coffins of little boys who wouldn't
even know what the Orange Order was about.'' For voicing such noble
sentiments, the minister was roughed up the next day by thugs and
denounced publicly as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Being a man of God can be dangerous work in a country where
religion is used as a political weapon to defend centuries of
discrimination. The ruffians who attacked Rev. Bingham have a
clergyman more to their liking in the Rev. Ian Paisley, a proven
bigot with decades of hate-spewing on his resume. But seeds of
sectarian strife were sown long before Paisley, and go back to the
Catholic-Protestant split that took many thousands of lives before
the Quinn boys.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Stuart was the Queen of Scotland, whose Catholicism drew
the enmity of her native country's leading Protestant divine when
she returned from France in the year 1561. ``From the moment of her
landing, John Knox made no secret of his merciless antagonism. He
was the great demagogic leader in religious affairs, the organizer,
and master of the Scottish Kirk, the most popular preacher in
Edinburgh. The struggle with him was one of life or death.'' writes
Stefan Zweig in his 1935 history, ``The Queen of Scots.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox was ``domineering and authoritarian ... the zealot'' who
preached ``a kind of superlative Protestantism,'' whose ``Calvinism
was so dictatorial a faith that from the outset it rendered any
kind of mutual understanding impracticable.'' If you think this has
little to do with the people of New England, think again: It was
pilgrims fleeing this atmosphere who landed at Plymouth and laid
out the streets along Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   Knox's intolerance is chilling, even three centuries removed:
``The austere severity, the hatred of everything that made life
pleasant, the iconoclastic antagonism to the arts, the dislike of
merriment and laughter ... the stubborn treatment of jollity and
beauty as sin ... which banned good spirits and urbane manners and
customs, music, poetry, and dancing, and which cast a still
gloomier mantle over a land already condemned by nature to gloom
and sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months as a galley slave, being brutalized by the
French, taught Knox ``to hate everything that was bright, cheerful,
and Hellenic.'' Alas, Knox had ``his genius for violence ...
perhaps the most finished example of the religious fanatic. He was
of harder metal than Luther, who was not free from occasional
gleams of jovial humor.'' Honest and God-fearing, sure; but ``the
blinkers he wore made him one of those cruel and narrow-minded
persons for whom only their own truth is true, only their own
virtue virtuous, only their own Christianity Christian. To differ
from him was criminal; to refuse compliance with every letter of
his demands was to show oneself to be Satan's spawn. ``A born
killjoy, he railed against the `Devil's brood' of the
happy-go-lucky. This coldhearted fanatic knew no other
gratification than the triumph of his dogmas.'' And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Knox's spiritual heirs live on, not just in the muddy gutters of
Drumcree, but in the hearts of the Khmer Rouge and the religious
goon-squads that hector women and stone their enemies and declaim
against modernity in the Islamic world. We know their kind.
``Always,'' wrote Zweig, as Hitler's storm gathered over Europe,
``those who regard themselves as God's doughtiest warriors are the
unkindest men in the world. Believing themselves the vehicles of
heavenly messages, they have their ears closed to whatever is
humane.'' They are the kill-or-be-killed crowd. And they win
whenever the give-peace-a-chance crowd allows itself to be
intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
