<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-HELP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUMMER COLONY WHERE THE WORKERS PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FERRISBURG, Vt. _ You get a lot for your $290 to $405 per night
at the Basin Harbor Club, including a cottage on Lake Champlain,
gourmet cuisine, and wake-up mimosas on the lodge deck. But you
don't get to bunk in a Trenchtown dorm, eat in The Zoo, or party at
The Coop till the Labatt runs dry.
</P>
<P>
   No, guests at this elegant and subdued seasonal resort, which
covers 350 acres where the Algonquin and Iroquois once roamed,
generally aren't privy to life on the other side. Of the nearly 300
folks employed by Basin Harbor, which was opened in 1886 and is
still operated by the founding Beach family, about one-third live
on the property. They make up a unique summer colony tucked deep
among the maple trees. At work, they make $6 to $14 an hour,
whipping up eggs and mixing up drinks. And after the sun goes down,
many of them are also pretty good at rustling up a little social
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in our own little world here,'' declares Alexandra
Carlson, an 18-year-old waitress.
</P>
<P>
   And if they're a diverse group _ nearly one-fourth come from
outside the United States _ they're also a young one. More than
half of the employees are between the ages of 18 and 25. Although
more students worked at Basin Harbor in the days before colleges
reopened in August, about 40 current staffers are in school.
(However, some of them are a tad uncertain about when or where
they'll return to college.) Small wonder that 23-year-old Chana
Chernev, who works in the reservations department, describes being
here for the summer as ``part sleep-away camp, part college, and
part `Dirty Dancing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, ``Dirty Dancing.'' That would be the popular 1987 movie
about the summer of '63 at a Catskills resort, where much of the
live-in help was not only Hollywood-handsome but could also dance
like ... well, like people dance in movies. Living and working at
Basin Harbor is a tad less romantic than that, what with staff
events such as Bingo Night and the Pictionary Tournament. But what
``Dirty Dancing'' got right is what Carlson proclaims: These folks
spend much of their time in their own universe, one that's
decidedly different from that populated by Basin Harbor's paying
customers.
</P>
<P>
   True, the help is allowed to use most of the resort's diverse
facilities, from its crescent-shaped waterfront to its 18-hole golf
course. Staffers are even occasionally invited to fish or play golf
with guests. But no one would confuse, say, the tuna casserole
ladled out in The Zoo, the funky staff eatery, with the sauteed
filet of mahi mahi that's served in the rainbow-shaped main dining
room overlooking the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would staff housing _ workers pay $40 a week for room and
board _ ever be mistaken for Basin Harbor's 77 charming guest
cottages. The principal men's dormitories, located in a back-street
area of the resort referred to as Trenchtown, along with the main
women's dorm, known as Esquire, are warrens of small share-a-bath
rooms in which such necessities of life as mountain bikes, stereos,
mini-fridges, and TVs must be shoehorned. The ultimate status
symbols, incidentally: VCRs and video-game systems.
</P>
<P>
   (Esquire is named for the magazine. Prior to World War II, the
two-story clapboard building housed young single men who paid $25
per week to stay at Basin Harbor and make themselves available to
the daughters of guests. The one-story dorms of Trenchtown,
meanwhile, are called B, A, and C, which some of their residents
insist stands for blood alcohol content.)
</P>
<P>
   They come to work on the shores of Lake Champlain for an
assortment of reasons. Twenty-two-year-old Tucker Lagasse, who's on
the rec-reation staff, is here to spend his free time windsurfing,
sailing, swimming, and golfing. Bartender Sean Tymecki, 21, is
hoping to pocket $5,000 toward another year at Vermont's Lyndon
State College. Allison Becher, an 18-year-old busgirl from nearby
Vergennes, explains that she ``needed to get away from my house and
my family.'' Ruel McBean, a 27-year-old waiter who is one of 13
Jamaicans on the staff, spends his summers here and works winters
at a hotel in Montego Bay. Meanwhile, there's a sizable group of
young nomads aboard, people such as Dave Usdan, a 22-year-old
bellhop who, come October, will point his 1990 Ford Bronco toward
an as-yet-to-be-determined job in Utah ski country. ``I can fit my
whole life in that car,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's even someone here like Baby, the 18-year-old
main character in ``Dirty Dancing'' who finds the staff at the
cinematic resort to be considerably cooler than its paying
customers. That's what happened to Lindsay Russotto, now 19, who
came to Basin Harbor with her family as a guest for two years
before signing on as a hostess this summer. Some of the male
workers noticed her during those seasons of 1996 and 1997, and
before long she was being invited to staff parties. ``So I went,''
says the University of Connecticut sophomore. ``Otherwise, it was
go to bed at 10 p.m. And there was no TV. It was totally boring for
someone my age. So I'd come to Trenchtown or Esquire and hang
out.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent warm evening, Russotto changed from her
green-and-white-striped hostess blouse and black skirt into a
fashionable if borrowed black dress. Then she walked a couple of
hundred yards from her cluttered room in Esquire to the main dining
room. She ate there with members of her family who were once again
guests at the hotel, ordering sauteed Green Mountain trout and
grilled shrimp. But she knew which side of the line she was really
on. ``I felt kinda dumb,'' she confesses. ``I mean, the people who
were waiting on me were my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Arsenault, a 25-year-old reservations clerk, describes
living and working at Basin Harbor as ``like a college campus,
except that you go to work instead of to class.'' (Appropriately,
this year's group is planning a yearbook and a prom.) Others talk a
lot about being part of a ``family,'' although having more than 90
brothers and sisters isn't for everyone, which is one reason nearly
one in four Basin Harbor summer employees leaves before his or her
contract is up. Kera Kandel, an 18-year-old assistant tennis
instructor who lives in Monkton, 20 minutes away, &UR;  &LR; would rather go
home to her biological family at night. ``I'm here to work,'' says
Kandel, who will enroll as a freshman at Northern Arizona
University in the fall. ``I'm really not interested in the rest of
it. Besides, I can't stay up that late.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, some of them do indeed like to party. Although veterans
point out that the late-night decibel level in the dorms is lower
this year than last, and that there hasn't been even a single
midnight bonfire at The Pit, out beyond the airstrip, don't tell
that to pastry chef Andy VanBourgondien. At age 38, VanBourgondien
would rather spend his nights sleeping, thanks. ``There are things
you do when you're 18 that you grow out of,'' he says. ``The music
drives me crazy. I've got Security on my telephone speed-dial.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun begins sometime after 10 p.m., after the last dessert
plate has been cleared. Since night life in Vergennes (pop. 2,735),
located seven miles away, pretty much stops and starts with Swany's
Tavern and its pool table, Basin Harbor has its own staff social
circuit. There are the dorms, of course. There's also The Red Mill,
a bar and restaurant that's open to both staff and guests. After it
closes down at 1 a.m. _ by which time most guests have long since
departed _ serious partyers move on to The Coop, a small staff rec
room consisting mainly of a TV, a foosball game, and a mismatched
assortment of old furniture. The adventurous might take a boat over
to the lean-to at Adirondack Cove, across the lake, where they'll
spend the night and maybe even jump 70 feet into the water from
nearby Barn Rock as a morning pick-me-up. ``Some of us aren't old
enough to be drinking, but it's OK because at least we don't have
to drive anywhere,'' Carlson contends.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the altenative. Montreal, the nearest big city, is
about two and half hours away. The small college town of Middlebury
is 20 miles south, while Burlington, a bit larger and a bit more
collegiate, is 30 miles north. Foreign employees, who usually don't
have cars, tend to be the most startled by the same isolation for
which Basin Harbor's guests are pleased to pay handsomely. ``I
didn't realize it would be this far from a town,'' laments Julie
Gilmour, a 19-year-old bellhop from Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the inevitable summer pairings. As one
staffer puts it: ``It's a long season, people get lonely, they
forget they have a boyfriend or girlfriend at home ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally these relationships even last beyond October. Molly
Shipp, now a 23-year-old captain on the banquet staff, met Brian
Goodyear, now Basin Harbor's systems manager, on her first night as
a resort employee two summers ago. They'll be married in September
on the Lodge lawn, host a buffet dinner in the main dining room,
dance among their guests in a Basin Harbor building called Town
Hall, and finish with a cookout on the waterfront. Whereupon
they'll live here year-round and Shipp will relinquish her
membership in Basin Harbor's summer colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am,'' she says, smiling, ``sentenced to life here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
