<HEADLINE>
BLODGETT PUZZLED BY BENCH ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Stephen King owns season tickets and busloads of
fans from her home state have made the trek to see her play, little
else from Cindy Blodgett's rookie season in the WNBA can elicit
comparisons to her brilliant collegiate career.
</P>
<P>
   A little over four months ago, Blodgett was wrapping up four
years at the University of Maine by playing in her fourth straight
NCAA Tournament as the Black Bears' all-everything point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after a promising start to her professional career,
Blodgett has become almost an afterthought as the last guard on the
Cleveland Rockers' bench.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps even worse, a bewildered Blodgett has no idea why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tough not getting a great deal of playing time right
now,'' said Blodgett. ``I basically approach practice as my game
each day. I feel if I improve each day in practice, then playing
time will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Limited minutes weren't exactly what the 5-foot-9-inch guard was
envisioning when, as the sixth choice overall in the WNBA draft,
she signed with Cleveland last spring after winning two NCAA
Division 1 scoring titles, earning All-American honors, and
becoming arguably the most popular athlete in the state of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Blodgett's impact actually has lessened as the season has
progressed. In the Rockers' first five games, she was the top
reserve guard, averaging 16 minutes and 8.8 points per game and
leading the league for a brief time in 3-point shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But she picked a bad time to go into a shooting slump; right
after she went a combined 1 for 16 from the field in consecutive
games, Boston native Michelle Edwards, a starter last season,
returned from a torn plantar fascia in her right foot (ironically,
the same injury that sidelined Blodgett for part of her senior
season at Maine). Blodgett's minutes began to dwindle, and now
they've become almost nonexistent. Her situation reached its nadir
last Tuesday, when she was a DNP for the first time in a game
against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Theories about Blodgett's situation have ranged from trouble
adjusting to the pros to a need to work on her defensive game to
the difficulty any 22-year-old would encounter in trying to find
her niche on a team filled with veterans. Coach Linda Hill-McDonald
has said that Blodgett has to improve her defense. Blodgett doesn't
agree and told the Portland (Maine) Press-Herald that simply
doesn't know why she keeps sitting, but the No. 6 overall pick in
last spring's draft is trying not to her lack of playing time get
her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal goals are just to continue to work hard and help
the team any way possible,'' said Blodgett.
</P>
<P>
   If she gets the chance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
On their guard
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's also been a mixed bag for another rookie guard with New
England roots. Rita Williams was the opening night starter at the
point for the expansion Washington Mystics, but since has settled
into a reserve role.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who ran the show at Connecticut for the last two
season, was a second-round pick. She's second on the team with 2.1
assists per game and is averaging almost 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition to the pros has been no problem for a
lower-profile rookie guard. Korie Hlede has been perhaps the WNBA's
most impressive first-year player, starting since Game One for the
Detroit Shock, another expansion team, leading all rookies with a
14.5 points per game average.
</P>
<P>
   Hlede, the nation's second-leading scorer last season, had been
continually touted by her coach at Duquesne, Dan Durkin, as the
nation's best guard collegiate guard. But despite being twice named
Atlantic 10 Player of the Year, Hlede came to the WNBA combine as
an unknown quantity due to limited scouting. Her workouts were so
impressive that Shock coach/general manager Nancy Lieberman-Cline
was delighted that Hlede stayed around long enough so that she
could make Hlede the draft's No. 4 pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
