<HEADLINE>
AT THE POOL, SHE'S COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; DOVER, N.H. _ So maybe it's not technically her own pool in
her backyard. But it is called the Jenny Thompson Pool, and the
local woman who just happens to be a five-time Olympic
gold-medalist is treated with celebrity status here, so it might as
well be hers.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who grew up in Georgetown, Mass., moved to Dover at
the age of 12 when she decided swimming was for her. That's where
the Seacoast Swim Team was, and where coach Mike Parratto was, so
that's where Thompson decided she wanted to be. She had been
commuting to train and compete, but said, ``it was a lot of
driving, so we just moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's her mother Margrid, who does the long commuting from
Dover to her job as a medical technologist at the Lahey Clinic in
Burlington, Mass., every weekday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 25, was home earlier this month for a typically brief
visit _ this one was squeezed between swim meets in Europe and the
Goodwill Games in New York, where her events begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   But being an off-Olympic year _ between Atlanta '96 and Sydney
2000 _ Thompson said she's taking it a little easier than usual
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer, I'm sort of relaxing mentally,'' she said.
``After the Goodwill Games, we have the nationals which are
qualifying for some stuff next year, but there's no real
international hard-core swim meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thompson can afford to take a breather and savor the jewelry
that's stashed somewhere in her mom's home is Dover (``I could
probably find them if I had to. I take them out once in a while,''
she said.) The collection includes five Olympic gold medals, one
Olympic silver, plus five World Championship golds, and 17 golds
and three silvers from four Pan Pacific Games.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more, in terms of notations in the record books:
she's the world record holder in the 100-meter butterfly (short
course) and 50-meter butterfly (short course), and holds the
fastest split in the 100-meter butterfly. She also hold the
American record for the 100-yard freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Parratto, the Seacoast coach, is proud of all his
swimmers, he said it was obvious Thompson was special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we noticed most is that she is very competitive
and had really great speed,'' he said. And she'd rarely miss a 5:30
a.m. workout, even if it meant Parrotta would come pick her up if
she needed a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the Jenny Thompson Pool is here in Dover,
the swimmer has been only an occasional visitor since she headed to
California seven years ago to attend Stanford. She's settled in
Palo Alto, Calif., and is taking pre-med classes at Mills College
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   She also trains with the varsity team at Stanford, where her
former coach, Richard Quick, also was the women's Olympic coach.
</P>
<P>
   Quick said he could barely contain himself when he heard that
Thompson was considering coming to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a World Champion before she even came to Stanford, so
I was thrilled to death,'' he said. ``I went to visit her twice at
home. Normally I don't do that, but I would have gone three
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He had told people in the admissions and recruiting departments,
in fact, ``that if we could get that one great sprinter, the team
would be pretty hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right.
</P>
<P>
   Once Thompson enrolled, the swim won four NCAA titles, four
Pac-10 championships, and never lost a dual meet over the next four
years. Of course, Quick acknowledged, the team had other Olympians,
like Summer Sanders and Lea Loveless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great team surrounding her, but she was a big, big
part of that, and she was the cornerstone on all the teams,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson might be in her ``taking-it-easy, in between-Olympics''
mode, but she follows a daily routine that includes two to five
hours in the pool, plus a workout in yoga or pilates _ a cross
between yoga and strength training. And she's always fine-tuning
her strokes, whether it's altering the head-position on her
freestyle, or working on the way she strokes the butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who said she was ``swimming underwater when I was six
months old,'' started swimming with the Danvers Dolphins when she
was 8 years old. Actually, she tried out for the team when she was
7 but she didn't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I took lessons because I really wanted to make the team,''
she said. ``That was one of first times I was knocked down and came
back fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   And there would be more knockdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, she tried out for the Olympic team, but missed by one
spot. In the 1992 Olympics, she missed the gold even though she had
the world record in the butterfly. In the 1994 World Championships
she got ``obliterated'' by the Chinese who were later accused of
using steroids.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, with a knockdown that still hangs over her head,
she didn't make the '96 Olympic team for any individual events,
even though she came home with three gold medals for relay events.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe that disappointment spurs her on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have retired after '96 had I won an invididual,'' she
said. ``But maybe it was blessing in disguise. I still love sport,
and I have several endorsements.'' (Among them are Speedo and The
Zone nutrition products).
</P>
<P>
   And she's not concerned that she'll be 27 when the next Olympics
rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that ``in the past, swimming has been known as
a teenager sport, but thinks that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we haven't seen many 30-year-olds yet, but I've read
that you don't reach your peak in muscle capacity as a woman until
you're 30.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the pool that now bares her name, Thompson said it was
something the town did after the '96 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little strange, but it's a great honor,'' she said.
``The day I got home from the Olympics they picked me up in a
limousine, and there was a parade and we ended up here for the
pool-naming ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   And Amy Parratto, Mike's wife who was Thompson's swim coach at
Dover High, said it was fitting tribute for the woman who made her
mark swimming in the formerly named Guppey Pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was home July Fourth, the kids were really psyched to
see her and watch her swim,'' Parotta said. ``There aren't too many
Jennys around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
