<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE OLD, A NEW MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an election year and health care reform is back with a
vengeance on the public agenda. In the few weeks of business
remaining on Capitol Hill and Beacon Hill this summer, Democrats
and Republicans alike are vowing to whip our health maintenance
organizations into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Congress promises a comprehensive Patients' Bill of Rights to
protect consumers from profit-driven benefit restrictions. The
Massachusetts Legislature promises to hold insurers accountable for
medical decisions made by accountants.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that was the undoing of Hillary Clinton only five
years ago could be the making of congressional candidates this fall
thanks to the dramatic expansion of HMOs in the American workplace.
Since 1993, the percentage of insured workers covered by managed
care plans has jumped from 53 to 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In their belated zeal to address the past sins of managed health
care, elected officials are ignoring the future market for HMOs.
With the workplace all but conquered, managed care companies are
selling their cost cutting schemes to the frailest population in
the nation: the elderly in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, one of country's largest health insurers has been
regulating the care of Medicare-eligible long-term patients in
nursing homes in 10 states, including Massachusetts. EverCare, a
subsidiary of United HealthCare Corp., is operating in 20 Greater
Boston nursing homes as part of a federal demonstration project
under the auspices of the Health Care Finance Administration.
</P>
<P>
   EverCare estimates that the demonstration could save Medicare $5
million a year in the 10 states and that the plan, if applied to
all nursing home residents in the nation, could cut Medicare costs
by $800 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   However, managed care in nursing homes is not immune from the
problems plaguing HMOs &UR;  &LR; for other populations. And the time to pay
attention to the incursion into nursing homes is now, when the
trend is in its formative stage.
</P>
<P>
   EverCare uses Medicare payments to provide a nurse practitioner,
with physician backup, to manage the plan's nursing home patients.
In theory, by providing individual assessment, specialty care, and
the treatment of acute illnesses on site, EverCare saves money by
avoiding expensive hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   What often happens, in fact, is a reduction in care. A
podiatrist who had visited a Medicare patient once a week might be
authorized to visit once a month if she switches to EverCare. A
speech therapist who had worked with a Medicare patient for an
hour, five days a week, might be restricted to two weeks of
half-hour sessions. The result is dangerous for the most fragile
among us.
</P>
<P>
   EverCare officials say their goal is to enroll 40 percent of
eligible residents at participating nursing homes in order to build
the volume necessary to make a capitated system work. EverCare
President Marcia Smith tells the Tampa Bay Business Journal
(Florida is also a demonstration site) that the company relies on
the nursing homes to market the plan to residents: ``The nursing
home has to be advocating the program, or we can't get through the
front door.'' But, in the same interview, she notes that as much as
90 percent of EverCare's aging patients suffer from some form of
diminished mental capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a population that can make informed choices about health
plans that confuse much younger, healthier consumers?
</P>
<P>
   Some Massachusetts health care providers have their doubts. One
health care worker who has seen the number of EverCare patients
skyrocket at a suburban nursing home sees a disparity in the level
of care she is permitted to provide EverCare patients versus
Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   To even evaluate an EverCare patient, she must secure the
approval of the nurse practitioner, who is often not on site. When
permission is obtained, she says, she has no control over the
duration of therapy, even though she is a specialist in her field.
``I assume it is a cost consideration since no one discusses it
with me,'' says the distraught health care worker, whose complaints
to her superiors about EverCare prompted a note in her personnel
file, citing her trouble ``adjusting to managed care.'' What
worries her most, she says, ``is patients are at risk and no one is
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   So many agencies share oversight of nursing homes in
Massachusetts _ the Department of Public Health, the Department of
Medical Security, the Attorney General's Office, HCFA _ it
sometimes seems no one is in charge. But if we all now agree that
HMOs with a largely healthy client base need more regulation, isn't
monitoring even more critical for HMOs aimed at the elderly?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
