<HEADLINE>
CARING IN VIETNAM INSPIRES A JOURNEY TO PRIESTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was only a kid, about 7 or 8, when thoughts of becoming a
Catholic priest first swirled in his head. But Tinh Van Nguyen set
those thoughts aside. He had bigger things to worry about. His
homeland, South Vietnam, was being ripped apart by war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very bad time for all the people,'' said Nguyen, with
a trace of sadness in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of becoming a priest never went away. Instead, the
yearning to serve the Roman Catholic Church grew stronger the older
Nguyen became. Today, people call him Father Tinh. On May 16 at the
Cathedral of the Holy Cross in Boston's South End, Nguyen, 33, was
ordained a priest in the Archdiocese of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was maybe the happiest day of my life,'' said Nguyen. That
day, he said, is rivaled only by the October day three years ago
when the rest of his family _ father, mother, and seven brothers
and sisters _ moved from Vietnam to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen is part of a vibrant and growing Vietnamese Catholic
community in the Boston area. Mass is offered in Vietnamese in
eight parishes in the archdiocese. While Nguyen's church, Most
Blessed Sacrament in Wakefield, isn't one of them, he says he is
actively involved with Vietnamese in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism is still the primary practice of many Vietnamese, but
Vietnamese Catholics have made their presence felt in many dioceses
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen's passion for the faith was kindled while growing up in
South Vietnam. He was impressed by the Catholic missionaries who
ministered to the war's victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they lived their lives, the way they provided
assistance was a very powerful example of living a holy life,''
said Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Vietnamese who left their homeland, Nguyen tells a
harrowing tale of deprivation and danger. He left Vietnam in July
1980 because his father feared that the government would conscript
him to fight in the war against Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   With about 160 people, Nguyen slipped away from Vietnam on an
overcrowded, 45-foot-long fishing boat. For nearly two weeks they
bobbed along in the ocean enduring storms, pirates who robbed
passengers, and a lack of water.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers finally arrived in Malaysia, where Nguyen lived
for two years in a refugee camp run by the United Nations. There
again he was exposed to Catholic missionaries, nuns, and priests
who cared for him. To Nguyen, they were the epitome of selfless
devotion to others.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States in 1982 to live with an aunt in
California and from the moment he arrived he wanted to enter a
seminary and start the journey toward priesthood. But he put aside
his ambition in order to work and send money back to his family in
Vietnam. He also was saving money to try to bring them to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Good fortune befell Nguyen while he was living briefly in New
Orleans among a Vietnamese Catholic community. There he met the
Rev. James E. Gaudreau, pastor of St. Joseph's in Lynn, who was in
New Orleans studying Vietnamese. Nguyen and Gaudreau became friends
and it was Gaudreau who told Nguyen about St. John's Seminary in
Boston's Brighton section.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Nguyen ended up studying for the priesthood. ``I
truly love being a priest,'' said Nguyen. ``I love God and I want
to share that love with the people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a society where lives are sometimes frenetic, Nguyen believes
faith can be an important anchor. ``People care very much about the
church and want the church to care about them and to help them in
their lives,'' he said. ``The church has much to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Since priests receive a small salary and he still provides
financial help to his family, Nguyen works weekends at Bingo games
at Mount St. Joseph Academy in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nguyen realizes that priests in the United States do
not enjoy the same lofty status they once did, he believes the
priesthood can still be a noble calling. ``To serve others can be a
wonderful life for the right person,'' he said. ``I enjoy every
day. But I'm still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four Greek Orthodox priests fired from Hellenic College and
Holy Cross School of Theology have asked for their jobs back in a
letter mailed last week to the national leader of the Greek
Orthodox church.
</P>
<P>
   The four men were fired from the Brookline, Mass. school at the
request of Archbishop Spyridon, the leader of the nation's 2
million Greek Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter to Spyridon, the priests asked him to follow
recommendations passed at a recent Greek Orthodox convention
calling for a task force to be appointed to study the firings and
for the priests to be reinstated while the panel conducts its work.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Spyridon said the bishop had not received the
letter because he is away from his office on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As priests and professors we have poured out our hearts and
minds, indeed our very beings, in the education of over 1,000
students ... according to the highest ideals of Orthodoxy and
Hellenism,'' said the letter. It was signed by the Reverends
Alkiviadis C. Calivas, George Papademetriou, Emmanuel Clapsis, and
Theodore G. Stylianopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   Sources at the college have told the Globe that the four men
were fired because they refused to coverup an alleged incident of
sexual misconduct by a former seminarian. Archdiocesan officials
say the firings were an effort to resolve personal conflicts at the
school among administrators and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``An act of love at this critical time will be an event of
redemption, forgiveness and reconciliation ...'' the four priests
wrote in their letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
