<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S IMPOSSIBLE TO BE ALONE WHEN YOU'RE A LEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; My friend Mark Lee was in town over the weekend, promoting his
novel of Africa, ``The Lost Tribe.'' With a movie and several plays
to his credit, Mark has been famous off and on, but perhaps never
so famous as when Walter Scott (real name: Lloyd Shearer) mentioned
him in the ``Personality Parade'' gossip column in Parade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, he got the wrong Mark Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, Scott's fact-checking juggernaut confused my
friend with the Australian actor Mark Lee, who fought alongside Mel
Gibson in the celluloid classic ``Gallipoli.'' For a while, the two
Mark Lees shared a talent agency, which sent the actor's fat checks
to my Mark while winging the skinny writer's checks off Down Under.
The other Mark Lee has a huge gay following, and my Mark Lee
occasionally receives unsolicited, all-expenses paid weekend
invitations from Northampton bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   Mark was a few months late for the Lee Family Association
meeting that took place earlier this year in Boston's Chinatown.
Those Lees are practically all of Chinese extraction, purporting to
descend from the ancient philosopher Lao Tzu, the founder of
Taoism. In an interview with the Globe, Family Association grand
national president Steven Lee noted that descendants of Virginia's
Robert E. Lee were not expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is said to be the most common surname in the world. For
starters, there are 87 million of them in China. In the port city
of Tianjin, not far from Peking, 2,300 people bear the name Li
Zhang. When police in Shanghai went searching for murder suspect Li
Ming, they narrowed the hundreds of candidates to a ``short list''
of 26, reports the Los Angeles Times. The pregnant wife of one of
the suspects tried to commit suicide; her innocent husband returned
home from the police station just in time to save her life and that
of their child.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the curse of homonomeia! What is to be done? Stamp bar codes
on infants at birth? Not a bad idea, if we could implant digital
scanners into every newborn's retina. We certainly can't rely on
parental imagination. Moon Unit, Dweezil, a billion Caitlins,
Dawns, Fawns, and every conceivable variation of Sheryl (except
possibly Sher-El, as the name would appear on Krypton) reveal the
paucity of parents' contributions to the naming problem. The
Chinese now occasionally pay ``name masters'' to dream up
alternatives to the ubiquitous Lee, or the frequently encountered
Weidong (``protect Mao'') and Songze (``praise Mao'').
</P>
<P>
   In today's feverish rush of scandal reporting, confusions are
inevitable. Newsweek, which has led the pack in Monica Lewinsky
reporting, printed what was supposed to be a picture of her mother,
Marcia Lewis. But the attractive brunette proved to be another
Marcia Lewis. Likewise, an intrepid New York Post scribe thought he
had a scoop when he quoted Washington lawyer Robert Fisk
poor-mouthing Kenneth Starr's Whitewater investigation. But the
hapless hack had reeled in the wrong Fisk. He thought he was
quoting former Whitewater prosecutor Robert Fiske, who works in New
York. The Post wreaked its revenge the next day (``Lying lawyer
admits he duped reporter''), printing Fisk's picture above the
caption: ``Just a nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   You may have noticed that there were briefly two Timothy
McVeighs in the nation's limelight: the Oklahoma City bomber and
the Navy seaman discharged for revealing _ to America Online _ that
he was gay. There's a Tina Brown in New York who's a voodoo
sculptress, and very politely returns the many A-list invitations
that flow her way.
</P>
<P>
   I went to school with a Dave Krieger, whom I don't remember
being quite as funny as former Apple Computer programmer Dave
Krieger of Cupertino, Calif. At his Web site,
(www.fqa.com/dave/index.html) this man writes: ``Stranded far from
Silicon Valley with an irresistible Dave Krieger craving?
Fortunately, most major metropolitan areas are now equipped with
their own Dave Krieger'' _ and then he lists 76 of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate homonomaeic Web site is indubitably ``The True
Horror Story; Being Stephen King.'' (www.isisw3.com/sking/) There,
about 20 real-life people describe the agony of being asked, almost
every day of their lives, ``Are you the real Stephen King?''
Luckily, one of them came up with a snappy answer: ``No, I'm his
brother.'' The real Stephen King has yet to log on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
