<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MARKET-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIKE PLACE SATISFIES THE LINK BETWEEN GROWER AND EATER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Even several blocks away, tantalizing clues lead to
the Pike Place Market. Riotously colored summer flowers _
saffron-hued lilies, blazing red snapdragons, pastel sweet peas
wrapped in paper cones _ bob by. Summer seems to spread through the
crowded downtown streets along with the blobs of color, and it's
impossible not to follow the trail in reverse, augmented by waves
of shoppers eating Bing cherries out of paper bags and carrying
vegetables. To market, to market.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the market buildings, the sense of excitement increases.
Fish literally fly as vendors toss them to one another. Butchers
trim steaks and arrange sausages. In crescendoing voices, farmers
hawk cherries and cucumbers, innumerable kinds of greens, clumps of
shiitakes, and lion's mane mushrooms. Doughnuts, shaped and baked
in bubbling oil, are eaten in seconds by children. Craftspeople
show off jewelry and tie-dyed T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Spilling out of its confines onto the sidewalk, Pike Place
Market is widely acclaimed as the pride of Seattle. From Sol Amon,
whose family has operated the Pure Food Fish Market for three
generations, to the newest immigrant group, the Hmong farmers who
sell at tables the flowers and greens they grow in small plots
around the city, the market has a vibrant history intertwined with
the city and its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s, urban-renewal plans slated the market for
demolition, to be replaced by hotels and retail stores. It was
rescued by a ``Keep the Market'' drive that culminated, in 1971,
with the citizens of Seattle voting to place the market under
public ownership. This is a market that escaped the wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pike Place is part of being in Seattle,'' says Len Barson, a
resident who has worked on market legal issues in the past. ``It
really gives Seattle an identity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's not-too-distant past, public food markets
anchored every major metropolis, brought the country into the city,
and fed the populace. A few still exist: One is Pike Place, which
opened in 1907, and another is Reading Market in Philadelphia,
established by a railroad to spur its competition with another rail
line. Many more died out long ago. Others, like the Quincy
Market-Faneuil Hall buildings in Boston, established as a public
market, were redeveloped as retail spaces and restaurants, becoming
tourist destinations that lost the connection between rural life
and the city.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the world, public markets are still vital,
from the spectacular Mercat de Sant Josep in the center of
Barcelona, one of the premier markets in Europe, to the slightly
chaotic jumble of buildings and covered sheds that make up the
central market in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico. Spanish matrons choose
fine hams or compare egg prices while talking to the purveyors, and
Mexicans select chili peppers and a live quail or two for dinner
before picking up a stack of warm tortillas made right in front of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The more we travel, the more we've gotten used to rushing to the
markets in Europe, the Near East, the Far East _ actually almost
anywhere in the world _ as part of our adventures. Yet our food
experience at home has become further and further removed from the
connection between grower and eater.
</P>
<P>
   The rising number of open-air farmers' markets in recent years
shows we're yearning for that link. Janet Christensen, director of
education at the Massachusetts Food and Agriculture Department
remembers that 10 years ago there were eight to 10 seasonal
farmers' markets in the state. Now, she says, there are 100,
operating in city neighborhoods, in small towns, and in the
countryside. ``We have requests for more, but we've run out of
farmers'' to provide produce, Christensen says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing back the urban-rural connection is important in the
city,'' says David O'Neil, director of the Public Market
Collaborative of the Project for Public Spaces. Markets make a
delightful oasis in urban life, he says, affording the city dweller
a chance to meet those who produce the food as well as satisfying
all the sensory elements _ the smells and sights and sounds _ that
a modern grocery usually lacks. ``People from the country love it
because it means m-o-n-e-y,'' he adds with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is now peppered with about 5,000 food markets,
from open-air to permanent ones, O'Neil adds, with the biggest
concentration on the West Coast. But he thinks it's important to
view permanent markets as more than a summer fancy. ``It's good
business. A market is as valuable an institution as a stadium or a
convention center,'' O'Neil says, adding that cities should
consider giving the same kind of tax breaks for markets that are
extended to shopping malls and other developments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In August, the newest public market in the East will open in
downtown Portland, Maine. The 37,000-square-foot building, with a
heavy timbered roof and glass walls, was funded by the late
philanthropist Elizabeth Noyce, who had made bequests to arts and
cultural institutions in the city and saw the market project as a
way to enrich the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Spitzer, a national authority on public markets who was
hired to do the feasibility study, has stayed on to run the market.
Noyce was interested in connecting the rural economy of Maine to
Portland, Spitzer says, and thought a permanent market was a
natural way to promote the small food producers as well as growers.
Portland was anchored by a market from 1825 to 1882 _ like many a
coastal city _ but since then only a seasonal open-air market has
existed downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole notion of buying high-quality local products is an
idea that's growing,'' Spitzer says. He envisions attracting about
15,000 to 18,000 people a week to the market in peak seasons. The
market is expected to be self-sustaining, and it's estimated that
it could generate $10 million a year in sales.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
