<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7227 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-22 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAUX STARS; POLS, FLAKES, AND CURMUDGEONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The celebritization of America has reached such an extreme that
gossip columns are now engorged with items about movie ``stars''
who've made maybe one or two films before devoting themselves full
time to being public bores.
</P>
<P>
   By the counterfeit coin of celebrity &UR;  &LR; today, many of the
glitterati are more famous for who they've just broken up with or
which rehab clinic they've checked into than for anything they've
actually accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Was it ever thus? When did our obsession with celebrities begin?
In American Heritage, Richard Brookhiser traces the phenomenon back
to the Revolutionary era, when the public became enamored of the
Three Georges: George Washington, King George III, and evangelist
George Whitefield. Back then, fame was based on rank or
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But the modern celebrity culture really began to take shape in
the 19th century when the impresarios of fame arrived on the scene.
Shrewd-ies like P.T. Barnum used advances in media technology and
transportation to make household names of performers like Jenny
Lind, the ``Swedish Nightingale,'' along with many who had not a
fraction of her talent.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to Elvis, Marilyn, Diana, and the lesser lights who
make up the constellation of celebrity in an era of 24-hour news
and entertainment. Brookhiser opines that the collapse of
authority, presumably including moral authority, leads us to seek
the spurious ``companionship'' of celebrities: ``If people don't
know what they are doing on earth, they at least want to know the
people they see in the celebrity sky above them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to welfare reform, education, or innumerable other
issues of public policy, state government has been in the driver's
seat ever since the ``New Federalism'' began redirecting money and
power from the federal government to the states in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally the nation's newspapers, realizing that their
watchdog role is more important than ever, have responded by
beefing up coverage of the nation's state houses, right? Guess
again.
</P>
<P>
   In a comprehensive and troubling report, this month's American
Journalism Review details the systematic cutbacks in capital press
corps from Connecticut to Georgia to Texas to Michigan. (Newspaper
coverage of the Massachusetts State House has held steady, AJR
finds.)
</P>
<P>
   Wrongly convinced that readers are bored by stories about
government and determined to clear out space for more lifestyle
features, many editors have taken the ax to their state house
bureaus and given increasingly short shrift to government stories,
according to authors Charles Layton and Mary Walton.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences for the public of this abdication of
journalistic duty are succinctly summarized by a state
representative in North Carolina who says the prevailing view among
lawmakers in the capital is: ``You can vote any way you want to up
here because the folks back home will never know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Wells is a flaky guy in a business _ major league baseball
_ that has always attracted its share of flaky guys.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 17 at Yankee Stadium, the gonzo southpaw with the
outlaw swagger did what only 14 other players in baseball history
have done: He threw a perfect game, as in no hits, no walks, 27 up
and 27 down.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe that makes a case for flakiness. In the August
issue of Details, author Michael P. Geffner makes a case for the
beefy southpaw as a raw, volatile, but essentially likable fellow.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that you've got to like somebody who threatens, as
Wells once did, to punch out George Steinbrenner. It's that Wells's
throwback quality is awfully engaging in this era of blow-dried,
smooth-talking millionaire athletes. The tattooed Wells has the
demeanor _ and the vocabulary _ of a truck driver who's seen a
million miles of bad road.
</P>
<P>
   He has. Raised in poverty by his unwed mother, a ``biker chick''
who ran with the Hell's Angels, Wells is the classic case of a guy
who used sports as a way out. In addition to the joy of playing and
the opportunity to escape his home life, he may have also seen the
financial possibilities of baseball early on: The Hell's Angels
used to cheer on the 8-year-old Wells during his Little League
games and pay him $1 for every strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curmudgeons are among our most precious natural resources. We
should value these crusty truth-tellers more than we do.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most valuable is Paul Fussell, author of ``Thank God
for the Atom Bomb'' and ``The Great War in Modern Memory.'' Reading
Fussell is like being hit in the face again and again with cold
water: shocking at first, then strangely bracing.
</P>
<P>
   In an epigrammatic interview in the August Psychology Today,
Fussell heaves a few more buckets of his ``joyous pessimism'' our
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``One's going to get older, and it's not going to be much fun,''
he says. ``One should get ready for it early and not be surprised
when it happens; it's a way of joining the human race.'' And this,
on violence: ``There's no solution to it. ... People are
meaninglessly wicked sometimes.'' And this: ``Arriving at
self-respect is the ultimate duty of everybody alive. Otherwise,
you're a drag on the universe, apologizing for yourself or doing
less well than you could.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other curmudgeons such as Gore Vidal, who seem to
regard lesser mortals with Olympian contempt, Fussell has
compassion for those who can't bring themselves to see the truth as
clearly as he does. ``One should be sympathetic with people who
need a false world, because the real one is intolerable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Which could, I suppose, explain the dominance of the celebrity
culture, except that that ``false world'' is more intolerable than
the real one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
