<HEADLINE>
BEST, WORST IN MASSACHUSETTS HARD TO FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Investors who have owned the best or worst performers among
Massachusetts stocks in the last 12 months could be asking the same
question.
</P>
<P>
   It usually wasn't underestimated operating prowess or an
unforeseen financial disaster that suprised shareholders. It was
the degree to which the stock market reacted to more muted news,
good or bad, at smaller to medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
   Go no further than Massachusetts to get a good look at the
volatility that can affect stocks that don't quite make it into the
large-capitalization category preferred by big institutional
investors these days.
</P>
<P>
   The usual influences _ thinner trading volumes, concentration of
ownership, and an occasional mania for certain kinds of stocks _
are helping drive many of the dramatic gains and losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``With small companies like Natural Microsystems Corp., the
liquidity is poor to nonexistent so the impact is probably much
overdone,'' said Brian Stack of Massachusetts Financial Services
Inc. in Boston, referring to the fifth biggest loser on our list.
``The most dramatic upside and downside moves have taken place in
small stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the appearance of a strong stock market,
Massachusetts issues as a group were a decidedly mixed bag.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stocks that make up the Bloomberg Massachusetts index,
181 increased in value over the last year while 167 suffered price
declines. The index itself gained in value by 10.61 percent during
the yearlong period.
</P>
<P>
   Mania is the only way to describe the voracious investor
appetite for Internet-related stocks, and CMG Information Services
Inc. of Andover has been one of greatest beneficiaries of the last
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   CMG shares have risen 1,094.8 percent over the last year, from 7
3/16 on July 21, 1997, to a record 85 7/8 Tuesday, making it by far
the hottest stock in the state.
</P>
<P>
   (Our top performing stocks all have a minimum stock market value
of $250 million. The big losers on our list all started with a
market capitalization of at least that amount).
</P>
<P>
   CMG acts like a public venture capital fund for Internet
businesses. One of its most successful investments was in the
now-public Lycos Inc., a Framingham-based Internet search company.
Lycos the second most popular Massachusetts stock over the last
year, advancing 404.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the state's best-performing stocks are well-established
companies with recent records that rank somewhere between good and
very strong. Shares of Staples Inc., the office supply retailer,
and apparel discounter TJX Cos., have both nearly doubled in the
last yea.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp., the data storage company, advanced 121.3 percent and
added more total value for shareholders than any Massachusetts
stock, from the high-flying Internet names to giants like Gillette
Co. EMC's per-share price increase over the last year increased the
company's total stock market value by $13.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But many other local success stocks of the last year are
smaller, with names you may or may not have heard before. Geotel
Communications Inc. and Mapics Inc. are among the state's hottest
stocks, after Internet shares.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of other companies have posted at least as strong
percentage gains, but fell below our minimum stock market value
even after their advances.
</P>
<P>
   The worst performing stocks, a technology-heavy list of
companies, has one consistent theme. All of them have turned in at
least one earnings disappointment, but the dimensions of their
shortfall are all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the worst-performing stocks suffered large price
declines six months or longer ago, and have failed to regain any
momentum since.
</P>
<P>
   ``An earnings disappointment in technology tends to be viewed
more significantly,'' said Richard Jodka, manager of the State
Street Research Capital fund. ``If you are really missing a cycle
or someone is coming up with a better widget, it's harder to catch
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The one theme besides technology among the worst stocks:
sneakers. Converse Inc. of North Reading shed 69.3 percent of its
value in the last year, making it the third-biggest loser. Reebok
International Ltd. of Stoughton, which did not make the top 10
list, has dropped 46.2 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtics public shareholders have been getting a good
bounce since the team's complicated ownership reorganization took
place July 2. Most investors got a combination of new stock, a debt
security, and $1 in cash for each of their old Celtics shares,
which were trading as low as 16 just before the change.
</P>
<P>
   The new stock, debt, and cash had a combined value of $22.60 per
old share as of Tuesday. It has been slipping from a high of over
$25 reached last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
