<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMANY-MAN-BOS &LR;      07-22 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMANY-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX `COMPANY MAN' BRINGS FERVOR TO THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Following a trail of promotions, Xerox Corp.'s senior
executive in New England uprooted a spouse and three daughters from
Minneapolis to accept the top-drawer assignment in Boston. It was
the family's fourth move in six years.
</P>
<P>
   No less is expected of a company man, a now-quaint label for a
vanishing breed of executive who is hired and, after decades of
sacrifice and devotion to work, retired by the same company.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the 1990s and this ``company man'' is Karen Kruck.
</P>
<P>
   At age 38, Kruck is among the youngest Xerox executives to head
an entire regional sales operation. In just 17 months on the job,
Kruck has demonstrated her passion for Xerox's goal of regaining
lost sales in a tough market, a gusto for the community work
expected of senior executives, and a relentless energy for her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Karen Kruck's career path is one of torn loyalties. The tug
and pull of those commitments, unique to her role as a career Xerox
manager, are more complex than her employer may fully appreciate _
or the upbeat Kruck would admit to.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Jeff Kruck, a willing supporter of his wife's
career, calls the pace of so many relocations for Stamford,
Conn.-based Xerox ``a little crazy.'' And during her last
pregnancy, Kruck met a pressing deadline during a long day's work
only to rush to the hospital to deliver her baby. That monumental
effort was followed by a maternity leave in which she juggled work
and newborn care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met Superwoman,'' a bubbly Karen Kruck says during
an interview in her neat downtown corner office. ``It certainly
isn't me.''
</P>
<P>
   But she seems to be trying. Take Fourth of July weekend. Kruck
threw on her blue mirror sunglasses and packed Lauren, 11, Lindsay,
9, and Alex, 3 _ her husband stayed home in Boxford with two golden
retrievers and the cat _ into the Chevrolet Suburban. They drove
1,000 miles, first to New Jersey to meet Kruck's best friend and
then to her parents' getaway house on Lake Ariel, outside Scranton,
Pa., to meet two sisters and their seven children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Kruck family has a name for this breakneck pace: ``Mommy
Time.'' That, Kruck explains, ``means no naps, no down time. It's
go go go.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no different in college. While commuting to Seton Hall
University in South Orange, N.J., from her parents' home in leafy
Chatham Township, she held part-time jobs at a Shop Rite grocery
store and her father's sheet metal fabrication business. &UR;  &LR; Those
jobs helped pay for summer trips to Mexico or Europe. ``She's not
one to sit by,'' says her &UR;  &LR; mother, Mary Helen Emmerich, an
administrator at the private Newark Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck's decision to join Xerox was as lucky as it was smart.
</P>
<P>
   She was recruited by Xerox on campus in early 1982, after
earning a bachelor's in business in 3 1/2 years _ to ``beat the
resume rush,'' as she puts it. Kruck recalls forgoing three other
job offers in her preferred line of work, fashion merchandising, to
take Xerox's higher salary and promise of greater opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Droves of women who joined corporate America in the 1970s or
early 1980s complain of frustration with their slow progess; many
drop out to start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck chose a Fortune 500 company that was an early promoter of
minorities. In 1968, Xerox founder Joseph C. Wilson instructed his
managers to recruit more black employees, ``a great national
resource.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Xerox was recognized for developing and
elevating women, too. Although women still make up only one-fourth
of Xerox's top executives, Anne Mulcahey last year became the first
woman promoted into the inner circle of executives reporting to
chief executive Paul Allaire. (Allaire's seven top executives also
include one black man, A. Barry Rand.)
</P>
<P>
   But Kruck is in a cohort of 76 top executives who are female &UR;  &LR; _
38 more than in 1995, the year Xerox received the US Labor
Department's first ``Glass Ceiling Award'' for its diverse work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has not let Kruck down. She has seized opportunities that
have come from the company's successful transition from a copy
machine maker to a ``document company'' selling multicopy printers
with direct links to desktop computers. Kruck is one of 39 heads of
Xerox's regional offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably been one of the most fortunate people. I haven't
had too many tough times,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck also gives her husband credit for her success. ``I
couldn't ask for anybody to be more supportive,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kruck is a star among baby boomer husbands who have pitched
in so their wives can pursue careers. After the couple married in
June 1983, Karen Kruck's job assignments allowed them to stay put
in northern New Jersey for a decade while her workaholic husband
commuted to a Rolls-Royce dealership in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she shined as a sales representative and then branch
manager in northern New Jersey, helping to boost weak sales in the
area, says Michael MacDonald, senior vice president and chief of
staff for US customer operations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, she was rewarded with a job offer in Rochester,
headquarters of Xerox's US operations. At that point, Jeff Kruck
agreed to sell the dealership to his business partner. ``It got to
the point that she had to move for Xerox to keep her career on the
fast track,'' he says. ``It was a mutual decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur has accommodated his wife's career ever since,
though each makes an equal financial contribution to the household.
After moving to Rochester, he started a consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: Minneapolis. During a year in that city, Jeff Kruck
nursed his consulting business, albeit on ``a smaller scale. Karen
Kruck, as manager of sales operations, flew vast distances in
snowstorms to visit Xerox customers in Minnesota, Wisconsin, and
North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no simple task to do these jobs and raise three
children,'' says her former boss, Nancy Naigle, head of Xerox's
sales operation in the upper Midwest region. ``Now we have two
people doing that job,'' Naigle says.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck also won recognition within Xerox for her ability to
motivate staff. She cheerfully tells of being ``out to here
pregnant'' and working until 3 a.m. to help her Minnesota staff
prepare equipment for a rush delivery the next day to Kinko's.
``You're a better role model by example,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   After Minneapolis, she was sent back to New Jersey where she
excelled in a 14-month stint overseeing sales managers. Says Carlos
Pascual, president of US customer operations, ``When the New
England opening happened, we couldn't think of any better person
than Karen.'' He adds, ``She made a big commitment to the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kruck was named vice president and general manager for New
England in March 1997. Jeff Kruck found a new job, opening a
regional office in Boston for Sun Financial Group, a Tampa company
that leases computers.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck's assignment at Xerox New England: Boost sales and recover
market share lost to Ikon Office Solutions, one of the company's
toughest competitors. In the first six months of 1998, sales under
Kruck have grown 7.2 percent, compared with the same period a year
ago, Xerox says. Kruck is aiming for a 10 percent to 15 percent
increase in 1998 sales over 1997 sales of $270 million in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As Xerox's ambassador to Boston's business community and
customers and potential customers, Kruck has, in addition to
management duties, taken on the community projects expected of
high-level executives.
</P>
<P>
   She is active in Morgan Memorial Goodwill Industries in Boston.
In May she modeled a chocolate-colored designer suit down a Newbury
Street ``runway'' for the charity. She is also being pursued by the
Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce, according to her husband, and
she is a trustee of the Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation, a
lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph displayed near her office is telling: A toddler
nestles on Kruck's shoulder, sleepy and enduring a winter dance the
company sponsored for elderly residents of the city's Jamaica Plain
neighborhood; a second daughter stands between her and another
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Kruck unfailingly puts a cheerful face on the unique stresses
that shadow her as a company woman willing to make big sacrifices
for her employer. For one thing, she deals with the challenge of
ensuring continuity in her daughters' &UR;  &LR; curriculums as they change
schools frequently. They made the honor roll and have made friends
in their new neighborhood and are ``open to new places and new
people,'' Karen Kruck says. ``I think they've actually benefited
from moving.'' Jeff Kruck is more frank: ``The girls told us they
didn't like moving,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Karen and Jeff Kruck agree that the entire family likes Boston
and has settled in well. But Karen Kruck's success as the Xerox's
most senior executive based in New England could mean a promotion
and, perhaps, &UR;  &LR; another move. Will she move, yet again, for Xerox?
</P>
<P>
   Kruck dodges a dilemma that is, for now, hypothetical. ``I spent
a lot of time getting here,'' she says. ``I want to spend the time
enjoying the job. That's why I'm here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-CONE-ART-BOS     07-22 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-CONE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING MASTER STEPHEN CONE REFASHIONS FIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The first signs that change is afoot at Fidelity
Investments come in the sartorial gestures of the mutual fund
giant's new marketing master. Stephen A. Cone's iconoclastic bow
tie (Bolshevik red with white dots) and funky glasses (thick, black
plastic, round rims with tortoise-shell sides) seem more suited to
a hip advertising agency than to the reserved atmosphere of the
world's largest fund company.
</P>
<P>
   In other industries, such details would be less telling. But at
Fidelity, Cone's style reflects a vision that is refashioning how
one of the fund industry's bellwether firms does business.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Fidelity jump-started modern investing
by attracting in-the-know customers with its legendary Magellan
fund, the nation's biggest mutual fund. Then it focused on
corporations, state pension funds, and other institutional clients,
assuming a lower profile before individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under Cone, Fidelity is returning to its roots. But this
time it is going after individual investors in novel ways. Armed
with an array of innovative marketing ideas, Fidelity is preparing
to let fly some of the first shots of what many say is a
long-overdue marketing revolution in the mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a situation where if you open a certain type of
account with us, you get a very preferable rate for a boat,'' Cone
said, describing plans to woo customers by offering other
companies' products and services with Fidelity's own.
</P>
<P>
   Such moves at traditionally restrained Fidelity make the
Boston-based company, which has 13 percent of the $5.1 trillion US
mutual fund industry and 14.1 million customers, a barometer of a
rapidly changing and increasingly competitive investment
marketplace. Much is at stake: How fund companies court customers
will affect the ways in which legions of Americans plan for
retirements and accumulate wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds are not as ubiquitous as Nike sports shoes. But
they have practically become a mass consumer good in recent years,
with 38 percent of American households owning at least one. Yet the
sophisticated marketing techniques deemed crucial to business
survival have not been embraced by the stuffy fund industry, which
has held itself at arm's length from customers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with financial services firms plying more than 8,000 mutual
funds, even leading fund companies are increasingly anxious over
how to stand out in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything mutual fund companies are learning, it's
from the consumer goods companies, which have created brands and
preferences among customers,'' said John Lister, chairman of Lister
Butler Consulting, a brand and marketing firm in New York. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Exciting customers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who joined Fidelity last February as president of customer
marketing and development, knows that. A creative, outspoken
marketing specialist who was previously at Keycorp, a
Cleveland-based bank, and American Express, the financial services
giant, he rebuked the fund industry for ``not getting it'' in the
way that fashion houses with private trunk showings for elite
clients or airlines with frequent-flier miles have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole retail strategy is now customer-focused as opposed
to product-focused,'' Cone said in a recent interview. ``We want to
excite our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Cone, Fidelity is gearing up to pair Peter S. Lynch _
Magellan's former manager and an icon in the investment world _
with celebrities from Hollywood or the sports arena in witty
television commercials to run from mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to entertain people today,'' said the 48-year-old
Cone. He laughed but nodded somberly as a senior Fidelity executive
joked: ``We've had Michael Jordan in the locker room all these
years; why don't we use him?''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity now researches customer attitudes each quarter, instead
of just once a year. Cone has reorganized the company's retail
group, formerly structured around product lines, along customer
segments tracking age, income, lifestyle, and other indicators. The
firm also plans targeted direct mailings, new print advertisements,
and more extensive one-on-one interaction with customers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Offering enticements
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another move, Fidelity has expanded its offer of travel
vouchers to London, Mexico, and Hawaii to new customers who set up
accounts of at least $10,000 at Fidelity's brokerage. After the
program was opened to existing customers in June, family-owned
Fidelity forked over more than 30,000 vouchers in less than one
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite Ed McMahon and the sweepstakes,'' said Jim
Lowell, who publishes the independent Fidelity Investor newsletter.
``But it's close.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the moves signal that Fidelity is no longer
content to rest on previous successes, when the firm's star
stock-pickers and hot funds made it the uncontested leader of the
industry. The company's goal is to sell individual customers not
just Fidelity funds but a whole array of financial products and
services, including those of other firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a primary investment provider for each of our
customers,'' Cone said. ``That's not going to work for everybody.
But we view one-stop shopping as our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   That view reflects a growing trend in the financial services
sector, where banks, insurers, brokerages, investment houses, and
fund firms are combining to create giants that will sell everything
from mutual funds to car insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity already offers debit and credit cards, life insurance,
and check writing, in addition to other companies' funds. With 1
million people contacting Fidelity daily by telephone, the
Internet, or in Fidelity investor centers, the privately held firm
sees a big opportunity to carve out new niches. ``Fidelity has a
lot to sell to customers who may have already bought their mutual
funds,'' said Russell J. Kinnell, equity fund editor at fund
tracking firm Morningstar Inc. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New marketing strategy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cone's marketing strategy stands in stark contrast to the
bewildering array of numbers and obtuse financial-speak still used
by many firms. Only a few have followed Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the
nation's largest discount brokerage, in using a top executive to
tout funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's television campaigns in recent years attracted
criticism for failing to create a strong image. Not just lapsed
creativity distanced customers. When returns at some of its top
funds dried up in recent years, Fidelity began speaking more about
the investment process and less about performance. Critics said
that tactic, combined with a string of defections by top portfolio
managers, did little to cheer investors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as many Fidelity funds are posting dramatically improved
returns, the firm has decided that numbers are not enough to sell
investment products. ``People are more interested in financial
advice,'' Cone said. ``They've heard the performance message until
they no longer want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's race to craft a new image for itself around the theme
of ``know what you own and why you own it,'' as Cone put it, comes
after more than a decade in which the company was able to sit back
and watch the customers roll in.
</P>
<P>
   Such a luxury no longer exists. Competition abounds in the fund
industry, especially from The Vanguard Group, whose popular index
funds are giving Fidelity a run for its money by attracting the
lion's share of new dollars going into mutual funds. Since 1994,
Fidelity's share of the entire fund market has been flat at around
12 percent. While that is still more than anybody else, Vanguard's
share has grown by one-third to nearly 10 percent, fast closing the
gap with Fidelity, according to Financial Research Corp. in
Boston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Targeting individuals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's marketing drive also comes at a time when most growth
in the fund business has been from institutional customers, who
choose fund families for corporate retirement plans on the strength
of their popularity and name-brand appeal among individual
consumers. By contrast, so many individual Americans now own funds
that growth in that area has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   So why go back to the individual customer? Because there is as
much business to be kept as to be won. Geoff Bobroff, a fund
marketing consultant in East Greenwich, R.I., said the fund
business is moving from an asset-accumulation industry to an
asset-retention industry, in which companies must now focus on
retaining existing customers as much as acquiring new ones.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity already oversees one in five 401(k)
employee-sponsored retirement plans, it wants to capture the
hundreds of billions of dollars that aging baby boomers are
expected to transfer from retirement plans to other investment
products. And winning more points with rank-and-file investors will
help attract institutional customers. About two-thirds of
Fidelity's $676 billion in assets are held by institutional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail business is what made Fidelity great in the first
place,'' said Eric M. Kobren, editor of the independent Fidelity
Insight newsletter. ``But now, the retirement business will fuel
the retail business.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as managing money goes, Fidelity plans no changes to its
rigorous stock-picking approach by individual portfolio managers.
Loath to distract fund managers with the mechanics of sales,
Fidelity will not turn its money managers into mini marketing
czars.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is to get us to be more like the dynamic
college professor and less like the one who uses the same notes
every year,'' Cone explained. ``We're on a mission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
