<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-BOS &LR;      07-22 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATHERINE DIMATTEO PIONEERS A PATH TO ORGANIC STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENFIELD, Mass. _ The Pioneer Valley is filled with sleepy
small towns like this, where energetic small businesses have moved
into abandoned brick warehouses and the movie house is Main
Street's sole entertainment. Like neighboring towns, this one has a
thriving counterculture, partly because of its proximity to five
colleges nearby. So it isn't entirely an accident that the Organic
Trade Association established itself here in 1990, leaving its
former home in Belchertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go unnoticed,'' says Katherine DiMatteo, Organic
Trade's director of nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Unnoticed? Hardly. At least not last spring, when conventional
and organic farmers nationwide focused on the organization as
DiMatteo and her supporters took on the US Department of
Agriculture, winning a sweet victory.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings over several years, the Department of Agriculture
and the organic farming community had come up with a set of
guidelines on what could be labeled ``organic.'' To the surprise of
many, the proposed regulations included genetically engineered and
irradiated foods, and produce farmed with sewage sludge. The
organic farmers were furious and _ fueled with the passion that
kept them farming organically in the first place _ they corralled
their forces, held forums in several cities, and deluged the
Department of Agriculture with mail (to the tune of 290,000
comments).
</P>
<P>
   When negative public comment reached historic proportions,
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman backed down. ``It was really
wonderful,'' says DiMatteo.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have known? When Organic Trade was established 15
years ago, no one could have predicted the movement would have that
sort of power. But no one also would have guessed that this
one-generation farming phenomenon, fostered by ardent
back-to-the-earth hippies who had lived on communes, would ever
reach mainstream America.
</P>
<P>
   Organic Trade is now 760 members strong. In the last seven
years, the organic industry has been growing 20 percent a year,
capturing 1 percent of a $400 billion market. Considering that, you
would think that organic's $4 billion take doesn't account for
much. But with numbers rising each year, DiMatteo ventures that
``an optimistic estimate of what we could get is 5 to 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments like that make mainstream food manufacturers nervous _
especially since the organic umbrella has broadened to include
beef, poultry, all sorts of canned goods, dry cereals, frozen
prepared meals, baby food, milk, yogurt and other dairy products,
eggs, and now fibers. Organically grown cotton and its byproducts _
cottonseed meal and cottonseed oil _ are the latest additions to
the organic family.
</P>
<P>
   That neighborhood supermarkets are clamoring for organic foods
is as much a testament to the purity associated with organic
agriculture as it is a statement of mistrust and fear from American
consumers. Organic-seeking shoppers are worried about the planet
and what corporate farmers are doing to their land. Agribusinesses,
unlike organic manufacturers, don't boast about the clean ways they
raise food or their concern about the environment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Overseas markets have opened up, too. In Japan, there's a
``rather strong demand'' for organic soybeans to make tofu, says
August Schumacher, undersecretary of agriculture for farm and
foreign agriculture services, and former agriculture commissioner
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations that were shot down essentially allowed
corporate farming to piggyback on the organic. ``The secretary
probably received more comments on that rule than any other rule in
the history of USDA,'' says Schumacher. ``Katherine played a major
role. She was one of the leaders for reconsideration.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't surprising, since DiMatteo sees her identity as
firmly, inextricably linked to the land.
</P>
<P>
   DiMatteo's organization was up against hard-lobbying
agribusiness supporters. Before Organic Trade, she says, ``I had
some experience with Washington but not a lot.'' DiMatteo had
worked for the nonprofit Peace Development Fund and was executive
director of the Northeast Sustainable Energy Association, based in
Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business was to band together with groups
sympathetic to Organic Trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Campaign for Sustainable Agriculture, Humane Society of the
United States, Public Voice for Food and Healthy Policy, National
Campaign Against the Misuse of Pesticides, and Center for Science
in the Public Interest helped Organic Trade establish its voice
early on. Greenpeace, Sierra Club, Consumers Union, Mothers and
Others for a Livable Planet, and Union of Concerned Scientists have
since joined Organic Trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined clout has been our success,'' says DiMatteo. ``We
don't affect that many people, so you need to have these partners
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things DiMatteo, 49, learned inside the Beltway is
that ``D.C. politics is being around long enough to establish
relationships and remember shifts in attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also been around the organic movement long enough to see
its changes.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, DiMatteo worked in food cooperatives in the
retail and distribution end. She grew up in New Jersey, connected
to the land only through her Italian grandfather. He lived on one
lot and on the adjacent lot raised vegetables and fruit, including
tomatoes, figs, and grapes. She went to Trenton State College and
came out hoping to teach ``in the years when there were more
teachers than jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Richard, is an artist and musician. Their two
children are grown, and their daughter tends the family garden.
</P>
<P>
   Begun mainly by farmers and traders, Organic Trade includes
representatives of commerce _ the manufacturers, processors,
handlers, and transporters who bring organic food to supermarkets
and also ship it abroad. The group also consists of those who offer
pest control and supply the industry with equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the organic farmers who came together to establish
Organic Trade don't necessarily consider the organization its
spokesman, says Judith Gillan of the New England Small Farm
Institute in Belchertown, which represents a group of farmers not
involved in international trade, or even in much business outside
their own regions.
</P>
<P>
   DiMatteo has managed to weather these changes, says Gillan.
``Katherine is unique,'' she says, ``in that she has been able to
make this transition, to take this extra complicated path of
evolution without alienating the various sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some surprising elements to this evolution. Some
manufacturers grew so fast that they were undercapitalized. And
when mainstream corporations offered an infusion of cash, they
didn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of Change in Santa Fe, N.M., is one such company. A
purveyor of organic seeds, it wanted to preserve heirlooms and
offer seeds that had never been sprayed. Now Seeds of Change is
owned by M&AMP;M/Mars, which allows it to operate independently and
offer canned goods and boxes of grain mixes along with the seed
packets.
</P>
<P>
   There are other changes that the pioneers find distressing. Some
successful CEOs of organic companies live in million-dollar houses.
Others _ even some organic farmers _ smoke organic tobacco and
sprinkle organic sugar on their morning cereal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can be grown, it can be grown organically,'' says
DiMatteo. Organic Trade deals with matters of agriculture and
environment. ``Our mission is to support and sustain organic
agriculture, and organic agriculture is there to support and
sustain a healthy environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dictating a lifestyle,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ashley of Dancing Bear Farm in Leyden, near Greenfield, has
been loosely associated with Organic Trade for many years. His wife
used to write the association's newsletter. Several years ago he
became a dues-paying member.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley cultivates six or seven of his 24 acres and brings a
variety of produce into the farmers' markets in Newton and
Brookline. ``I feel lucky to be in those markets, because they're
known to be two of the best in the state.'' He wholesales to some
restaurants, and if he has too much of a particular vegetable, he
offers it to one of the local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups claiming to offer services to small farmers
actually don't, Ashley says. ``The larger an organization gets, the
bigger the issues it takes on.'' He says he doesn't blame them.
Ideally, he would like an organization to provide someone to broker
a large crop and save him time. During a day that might include
harvesting produce, packing the truck, driving it into Boston,
selling at market, and driving home again, he could also unload 600
pounds of organic garlic for the best price with the least shipping
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Organic Trade has sent several members to him requesting a
larger scale of produce than he can grow. Though he can't fill the
order, ``it gives me a chance to see if I should change my
operation to growing one large crop.''
</P>
<P>
   What he likes about Organic Trade is the extent to which the
association promotes organic agriculture. ``It has a positive
effect on me,'' he says. ``They deserve a lot of credit for
increasing general awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My small farm doesn't amount to a decimal point of anything,''
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Katherine DiMatteo and Organic Trade first
headed to Washington to deal with the Department of Agriculture,
they, too, were just a dot on the landscape. And look what they
did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
