<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TRAFFIC _ LONDON _ Think traffic is bad in your city.
It's gotten so bad here that the Transportation Minister is pushing
hard for drivers to quit using their cars so much and switch to
mass transit. Sound familiar? Problem is, the sales of new cars has
been going through the roof, so folks don't want to give them up.
Moreover, the the mass transit system has about as many fans as
Washington D.C. Mayor Marion Barry does in the U.S. Congress.
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Will move by 3 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   US-AFRICA _ WASHINGTON _ Now that it has presidential ``fast
track'' trade authority attached to it, proponents and opponents
alike are struggling with whether to try and save an important
trade bill that was to expand the U.S. relationship with
sub-Saharan Africa. But with just two months left in this Congress,
the long-awaited measure appears to have little, or no chance of
passage this year because Democrats -- including President Clinton
-- have been placed in a poltical bind. (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Will move by 6 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   A-PLUS _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said Wednesday
that the Republican-controlled Congress will not seek to override
President Clinton's veto of a bill to establish tax-free savings
accounts for public and private education. The bill is expected to
figure prominently, however, in the fall election campaigns.
(Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOBILITY _ WASHINGTON _ The South is the only region attracting
Americans who move, a new Census Bureau study shows, and the trend
could have profound social and political effects. For instance, the
data show an influx of highly educated people that could help fuel
the region's economic boom, and a continuing shift from cities to
suburbs, which could lead to a sharp Republicanization of Texas's
congressional delegation. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Armed Services Committee on
Wednesday rejected President Clinton's choice of Daryl Jones as the
first black secretary of the Air Force. The vote followed harsh
criticism of Jones's personal integrity at a confirmation hearing..
(Joyce, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-UNIONS _ WASHINGTON _ At least 146 employees of the
Social Security Administration work fulltime on labor union
activities and another 12,655 do union work at least three-quarters
time, the agency's inspector general reported Wednesday. The cost
of the work is $14.7 million a year in salaries and office space,
the report said. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   NUN _ Today, Sister Marge Eilerman finds out how long she'll be
in federal prison. The Franciscan nun, a native of Fort Loramie, is
being sentenced for tearing down a sign in protest at the School of
the Americas. The Fort Benning, Ga., military academy trains Latin
American soldiers, some of whom have gone on to torture and kill
political enemies in their home countries. Eilerman's family say
they fully support her activism. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News). 16.
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Bomb task force holds a briefing in Andrews, expected
to be more substantive than recent ones, probably on the results of
the examination of the truck Eric Rudolph allegedly stole two weeks
ago. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SWAMP _ A major energy company here just finished doing 3D
seismic operations in Jean Lafitte Swamp, Louisiana's only National
Park. The operations involve many explosions and the running of
airboats through the marshland. The company says it's safe, and
that they ''probably'' won't need to actually drill for oil in the
park. But park officials and even the National Park Service aren't
crazy about the seismic operations. These were the first operations
ever done with the new 3D technology in a national park, but they
won't be the last. The company that did this job already has plans
to blast in a park in Texas and one in Florida. (I will explain how
this is similar and how different from the controversy in
Okefenokee). (Rochell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
