   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-NAZI-GOLD (Washington) _ The Senate begins hearings on
subject the Swiss won't discuss and the Clinton administration
wants to avoid: reopening the 1946 agreement requiring Switzerland
to turn over the Nazi war booty it amassed during World War II. The
Swiss National Bank has refused to discuss returning the Nazi gold
it has had in its vaults for 53 years. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS (Undated) _ The herbal supplement business is
becoming crowded with companies selling stamina and serenity in a
bottle. No longer are pills and powders that supposedly sharpen the
mind and boost the spirit limited to space next to the bee pollen
at the local health food store. These days, herbal supplements
carry trusted brand names and command premium shelf space in the
nation's supermarkets, drug stores and mass retail chains. Until
recently, large drug companies and consumer-products makers shied
away from the herbal business, leaving it mostly to obscure
manufacturers with limited distribution. But with the growing
popularity of the products, the companies now see an angle in
putting their powerful brand names on herbal formulas. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Fed chairman Greenspan in his 2nd day
of testimony before Congress. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the GM strike and
arbitration hearing. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE-Y2K (New York) _ The results of the Big Board's Year 2000
tests. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-TELECOM (Madrid) _ Telefonica and Canal Plus agree to stop
competing in Spain's nascent market for digital satellite
television by merging their services.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments: The long bond
was off 9/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Examining the issue of whether
patients should be able to sue their HMOs. By Peter Passell.
</P>
