<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RESTRICTS CALIFORNIA SPENDING BECAUSE OF BUDGET IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ With lawmakers and Gov. Pete Wilson stuck
in a partisan impasse over spending, a judge has barred California
from making payments to schools, prisons, the welfare system and
thousands of workers until either a budget or an interim spending
plan is approved.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Robert H. O'Brien ordered the
state controller Tuesday to immediately cease all payments from the
treasury _ worth $4 billion in the next few weeks _ until the
Legislature and Wilson approved the spending.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the state Constitution prohibited California from
spending money if no budget was enacted by the start of the fiscal
year, which began July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Without a budget, the judge said, payments can be made only if
the governor recommends and the Legislature adopts emergency
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling stunned the state Capitol, where Wilson and lawmakers
continue to disagree over the $75.8 billion spending plan. Wilson,
a Republican, wants a $3.6 billion tax cut, and Democratic leaders
in the Assembly seek a modest cut and more money for education.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, said
O'Brien's ruling was irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken literally, it means there could be no one to guard
people in state prisons. State parks would close in the middle of
the vacation season. And no one would answer the bell if a forest
fire breaks out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Controller Kathleen Connell, who was sued by the Howard
Jarvis Taxpayers Association to stop the payments, said she would
appeal the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the ruling added ``a sense of urgency to the budget
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my hope it will provide the Legislature with an added
incentive to reach agreement on a responsible budget package,''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the pressure,'' Villaraigosa said. ``We know what's at
stake here. There's not one of us who wants to hurt anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's ruling, O'Brien said that in order to comply with
federal labor laws, 250,000 state workers must be paid minimum wage
for work performed since July 1. But as of Wednesday morning,
O'Brien said, state workers cannot be paid a dime until the 1998-99
budget or emergency legislation is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employees would simply be volunteers,'' O'Brien wrote in
his four-page ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature already has approved interim spending for the
trial court system. And the state's 320,000 retirees are protected,
officials said, despite conflicting interpretations of Tuesday's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pension payments are not made from the state treasury, they
come from a separate fund,'' said CalPERS chief executive officer
James Burton. ``We expect retirement benefits to go out as usual at
the end of the month.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all agree with the judge that we are frustrated
with the budget process,'' Connell said. ``But the problem is, he
is directing his angst against individuals who are innocents and
who are simply bystanders in the budget war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
