<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7289 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ABORTION-NAT     07-22 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ABORTION-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PRO-CHOICE CONGRESSMEN INTRODUCE ALTERNATIVE LATE-TERM
ABORTION BAN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 22 -- A group of lawmakers who support abortion
rights introduced legislation Wednesday that they say goes farther
in banning late-term abortions than a ban passed by Congress and
vetoed by the President last year.
</P>
<P>
   The group, two Democrats and two Republicans, would outlaw all
abortions once the fetus can live outside the womb, or viability,
which most states have determined to be six months into a
pregnancy. The only exception would be if continuing with the
pregnancy endangered the mother's life or could seriously hurt her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that healthy women with healthy fetuses should
not have post-viability abortions,'' said Rep. Ellen Tauscher,
D-Walnut Creek, who cosponsored the bill along with Reps. Steny
Hoyer, D-Md., Jim Greenwood, R-Penn., and Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The bill introduction came as the House prepared to vote
Thursday on an override to the veto on the bill to ban so-called
partial-birth abortions. The House, which approved the ban by a
296-132 vote in October, is expected to have more than the
two-thirds majority necessary to overturn the veto. However, the
Senate, which passed the provision, 64-32, is expected to fall shy
of the necessary 67 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion advocates paint a graphic picture of the procedure
as the most gruesome form of abortion: a fetus is drawn down the
birth canal, feet first, and the doctor pierces the skull, aborting
the fetus before birth.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer, who introduced similar legislation during the last
Congress, said the partial-birth abortion bill only bans a single
procedure, while the replacement bill would ban all procedures
after the fetus is viable, except when ``in the medical judgement
of the attending physician, the abortion is necessary to preserve
the life of the woman or to avert serious adverse health
consequences to the woman,'' according to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my belief that (the partial-birth ban's) terms would not
prohibit the performance of a single abortion,'' Hoyer said. ``They
would simply be performed by a different procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Tauscher: ``The Republican leadership's partial-birth
abortion ban fails to fully address abortions performed
post-viability and overreaches by banning abortions
pre-viability.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say the health exemption would ``give abortionists
unfettered freedom'' to perform late-term abortions, said Rep.
Charles Canady, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The health exemption, Canady said, would include mental health
or psychological traumas, which effectively would provide an easy
loop-hole for any doctor who wanted to perform the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you allow that, obviously any abortion is permissible,''
said Canady. ``(The bill) is an unfortunate sham. It would do
nothing... For them to claim that their legislation would make more
meaningful restriction on abortion than the partial-birth abortion
ban is truly laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said his bill is similar to late-term abortion bans in 41
states, including California. President Clinton, who passed a
similar law as Governor of Arkansas, supports the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bill contains an exception that will adequately protect
the lives and health of the small group of women in tragic
circumstances who need an abortion performed at a late stage of
pregnancy,'' Clinton wrote in a letter to Hoyer last March. ``At
the same time, your bill prohibits any late-term abortions
performed for reasons not related to the health or life of the
mother. This balance is an appropriate one.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director for the National Right to
Life Committee, said the bill also relies on the doctor to
determine whether the fetus is viable -- another provision that
could be used as a loophole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The abortionist is given, under this bill, the untrammeled
authority to perform abortions any time he wants to,'' said
Johnson. ``It's as if Congress were to pass a law banning assault
weapons and giving the gun dealers the sole authority to determine
whether the gun is an assault weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tauscher said the whole debate on the partial-birth abortion
ban has been misguided from the beginning. Instead of arguing over
whether procedures should be banned, Congress should be working to
prevent unwanted pregnancies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move this debate beyond procedure and beyond
rhetoric that is, frankly, false,'' said Tauscher. ``We need to
help the American people move to a place where we can prevent
unwanted pregnancies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
