<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-TRAFFIC-0723-     07-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TRAFFIC-0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLAIR PLAN TO BOOST MASS TRANSIT CAUSES ROAD RAGE AMONG BRITISH
COMMUTERS
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Seeking to cool Britain's growing love affair with the
car, Prime Minister Tony Blair's government wants to entice
commuters onto buses and trains by improving transit service while
making it even more expensive to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which heralded the initiative as a ``new deal''
for commuters, wants to pry Britons from their cars by levying a
tax on workplace parking in congested city centers and charging new
tolls for using the roadways. The income -- estimated to be about
$1.6 billion by 2005 -- would be dedicated to improving bus
service.
</P>
<P>
   To ease morning drive time, the government also wants to
discourage parents from driving their children to school,
suggesting instead that they walk, take a bus or ride their bikes.
Officials hope to double the overall use of bicycles in six years.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Blair's Labour government departs from nearly two
decades of policy under the Conservative governments of Margaret
Thatcher and John Major that shifted bus and rail services to the
free market.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, road traffic has increased more than 25 percent,
with the number of car trips of less than five miles -- a worrisome
indicator for transportation planners -- increasing by about 10
percent. The goal is to persuade one in 10 drivers to forsake their
cars and to get the rest to use more buses, bikes and trains.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction from the masses -- many of them phoning
talk-radio shows Wednesday from their cars locked in dense motorway
traffic -- will sound familiar to American commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a system of buses, subways and commuter trains that
would shame most U.S. cities, the central complaint about shifting
to mass transit is that it doesn't go where people need it. Buses
and trains also conjure images of muggings and worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's crazy,'' said Marie Mills, a car-bound insurance
agent who drives to work alone every day.
</P>
<P>
   Mills is part of the problem the government is striving to
eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   It takes her about 40 minutes to drive from her home near
Gatwick International Airport to her office in suburban Surrey.
``If I took transit, it would take me two hours at least,'' Mills
said, her voiced laced with outrage. ``That's fine for Londoners,
they can just Tube it.'' The Tube is the common name for the London
subway system.
</P>
<P>
   With the price of gasoline already more than $4 a gallon, the
idea of making it more expensive to commute angers Mills. ``I spend
22 pounds (about $36) a week on petrol and another 150 pounds
(about $244) a year to use the car,'' she said. ``I can't afford to
pay more.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that specific parts of the plan will have to be voted on
by the Parliament, Opposition spokeswoman Gillian Shephard attacked
Blair for imposing extra taxes on road users and imposing more
bureaucracy and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Prime Minister and Transport Secretary John Prescott
said the measures were good -- if unpleasant -- medicine because
they would lead to cleaner air, less congestion and better mass
transit.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the government's enthusiasm for its proposals
Prescott employed language rarely associated with transportation
policy: ``After 20 years in the wilderness, this is the day
transport policy bursts into the the light of a new dawn,'' he
proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   This new dawn should bring few new roads, he argued. ``To keep
up with demand, you would have to build a motorway 150 lanes wide
from London to Leeds,'' he said. That's a distance of about 200
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy minister -- who is chauffeured to work in a Jaguar --
stressed that he is not anti-car. ``The car will remain an
important symbol of a prosperous, inclusive, mobile society,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But without action now, traffic on Britain's already crowded
roads would grow by 30 percent in the next 20 years. Carbon dioxide
emissions would increase 10 percent at a time when Britain is
required under a new international accord on global warming to cut
auto emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No change is frankly not an option,'' declared Prescott, who
also listed measures to improve the rail network, which has fallen
into public disfavor since being privatized.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
