<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEST SHOWS DISPARITIES IN LEARNING FOR NON-ENGLISH SPEAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Results of a new achievement test show startling
disparities between results for students who are fluent in English
and those who are not, providing fuel for critics who say the exam
is unfair to children with limited English proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   While the scores of English-fluent children are hardly stellar,
languishing just below the national average, scores of immigrant
children whose English comprehension is limited are stunningly low.
</P>
<P>
   In reading, 40 percent of all second-graders in the state scored
at or above the national average, compared to 15 percent of those
with limited proficiency in English. By the fifth grade, only 8
percent were at or above the national average in reading.
</P>
<P>
   In math, 43 percent of all 11th-graders met or surpassed the
national average, compared to 19 percent of students with limited
English skills.
</P>
<P>
   State schools chief Delaine Eastin, who was outspoken in her
opposition to giving an English-only test to students who have yet
to learn the language, said she was hardly surprised by the low
scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``California students who cannot read the test are clearly at a
disadvantage with those who can,'' Eastin said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4.1 million students tested this spring, nearly 800,000
were limited in their ability to read or speak English.
</P>
<P>
   These scores are but one part of a detailed report card that
offers the first look at student performance since 1994 and
compares most of California's students to their peers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, parents, teachers and the public will be
able to log onto the Internet to see individual school, district
and county scores, as well as statewide averages by grade and
subject. The results are posted on the Department of Education Web
site: www.cde.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the Statewide Testing and Reporting (STAR) program
were to be published June 30. But a municipal judge issued a
temporary restraining order sought by the Oakland and Berkeley
schools that prohibited the state from releasing the scores of
students with limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, San Francisco Superior Court Judge David Garcia
ruled the state could release scores of these students, but that
school districts could not use the scores in evaluating
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The state had previously released average scores of about 3
million English-fluent children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect all our students _ both limited-English-proficient
and all others _ to be academic achievers. This will require
additional blood, sweat and tears by educators, students, parents
and the community,'' Eastin said.
</P>
<P>
   The test was administered in English at the insistence of Gov.
Pete Wilson, who believed it would offer a comparison for future
years. Opponents, however, argued that testing students in a
language they don't understand violates state law, is
discriminatory and unjust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
