   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   TOOL-CATALOG (Undated) _ Like Garrett Wade, Lee Valley,
Woodcraft and other high-end tool catalog businesses, Bridge City
Tool Works is digging for a bright, hard nugget within the
expanding $14 billion industry for woodworking tools, materials and
supplies. The vein of gold: the new, upscale, fine-woodworking
hobbyist, for whom extraordinary hand tools are like French cooking
knives or English gardening implements.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NEWBURGH-LANDMARK (Newburgh, N.Y.) _ There were no suntanned,
silver-haired corporate angels on hand last week when Hillary
Rodham Clinton visited the Dutch Reformed Church here to talk about
historic preservation. Her backdrop was the derelict Greek Revival
temple by Alexander Jackson Davis, completed in 1835, once a
handsome symbol of the city's material progress and now an
evocative, camera-ready testament to urban decay.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-HOUSE (New Canaan, Conn.) _ The Glass House, that marvel
of the International Style, rests serenely on its grassy slope
here, behind a six-foot-wall of boulders, while controversy _ yet
again _ swirls around it. The tiny house was built almost 50 years
ago, designed by its owner, Philip Johnson; lauded by most critics,
denounced by a few neighbors. Over time, the architect gathered up
acreage and built a spate of accessory buildings, an assemblage
Johnson, 92, has deeded to the National Trust for Historic Places.
Now the Glass House has been swept up by a tempest in a parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SEATS (UNdated) _ Every time I board an airplane,
economy-class ticket in hand, I experience what I think of as the
Goldilocks Syndrome. I work my way down the crowded aisle past the
jumbo Papa Bear seats in first class, the more modest Mama Bear
seats in business class and back to the little bitty Baby Bear
seats in coach. Here the parallel with the fairy tale ends; no one
who flies coach would ever declare that these tightly packed seats
are ``just right.'' By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-TOOLS (Undated) _ There's an indescribable quality that
radiates from old tools. You sense it in the hand-worn patina of
rosewood knobs and grips, the chiaroscuro of glinting brass levers
under darkened steel. But they are mute until you touch them. Then
they won't shut up. Pick up an old tool, and you almost hear the
ticking hours of its long working life. Such tools can be time
machines, portals to a yesteryear farther away than the moon. By
Jeff Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-REALTY-WEB (New York) _ Do you want to know exactly how much
apartments are selling for in the building of your dreams? Want to
read about neighborhoods? The ten best views of Central Park? The
ten best water-tank enclosures? (Yeah, those things up on the
roof.) There's a new website where you don't have to buy anything,
and it's owners pledge not to bug you with unwanted calls and
``cookies,'' those secret little files that advertisers place on
your computer to follow you around. It's called www.nyrealty.com.
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMON-APARTMENT (New York) _ As the movers and shakers build
20,000-square-foot megamansions in the Hamptons and combine
apartments on Park Avenue in Manhattan, the art dealer Holly
Solomon is moving on down. Left behind: a nine-room apartment (plus
maids' rooms and two storage rooms) on Sutton Place. Present home:
a six-room apartment on the Upper East Side that seats six for
dinner. That may seem more than adequate for most people, but Ms.
Solomon used to give buffets for 100. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
