</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-UNIONS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY SPENDS MILLIONS ON UNION ACTIVITIES, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Social Security Administration spends millions
of dollars a year to pay employees who spend all or most of their
time on union activities, the agency's inspector general told a
House panel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Inspector General James G. Huse Jr., told the Ways and
Means subcommittee on Social Security that the agency needs to keep
better track of union activity. He said almost half the Social
Security field managers in a survey conducted last year did know
know which employees represented a union.
</P>
<P>
   The report came on the first of three days of hearings by the
subcommittee exploring what chairman Jim Bunning, R-Ky., described
as an abuse of taxpayer money: allowing union activities to be paid
for by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report identified 145 Social Security
employees as working full-time on union activities and another
1,655 employees who worked up to 75 percent of their time on union
activities. They cost $13.4 million in salaries and $1.3 million in
office space and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A 1978 law allows federal employee union representatives to use
official time for activities such as representing members involved
in grievance disputes with supervisors. About 52,000 Social
Security employees are covered by unions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress have targeted the 20-year-old law for
change and Bunning's three days of hearings are designed to
highlight their objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is outrageous and it's wrong for people on the
public payroll to work for someone else,'' Bunning said. ``People
who are paid by the taxpayers should work for the taxpayers.
Instead, what we have here is a bunch of 'no shows,' 'go slows,'
and 'who the hell knows.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But under questioning from Democratic members, Huse said there
was nothing in his report to support Bunning's statement. Huse said
the report merely looked at the Social Security Administration's
procedures for accounting for union time _ which he said could be
improved _ rather than the question of whether employees should
conduct union activities during their official time.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic members argued that having union members in the work
force engaged full time on union activities is a common practice
among large businesses and most city and state governments because
it helps reduce the instances of grievance cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we talking about something that really is not there ...
and this is much ado about not too much?'' said Rep. Barbara
Kennelly, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby L. Harnage Sr., president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, which represents most of the Social Security
workers, issued a written statement accusing Bunning _ a candidate
for the U.S. Senate in Kentucky _ of trying to use the hearings
``as little more than a platform to lift his low public opinion
ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Harnage noted that time spent by union representatives on union
activities is not take out of the Social Security Trust Fund.
Instead, that money comes out of general federal revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The union has been invited to participate on Friday, the third
day of the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
