<HEADLINE>
DEAD MEN HAWKING: CATALOGS ARE TIED TO LATE GREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just weeks after Tommy Hilfiger's portfolio of primary-colored
towels and preppie print sheets crossed the desk, so did a catalog
for the Claude Monet Collection of artificial flowers. As if that
wasn't weird enough, it was followed by a catalog of Louis XV
furniture reproductions, ``Patines Anciennes,'' written in French
with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy, Claude and Louis; who's next? Evita and Marie Antoinette?
Pablo and Cristobal (that would be Picasso and Balenciaga to you).
</P>
<P>
   With homeware collections racking up the big bucks, it should
probably come as no surprise that old, old artists and style-makers
are being resurrected. And perhaps they should be. With no designer
present, decorating themes seem to run to cartoon cows; with Monet,
even in absentia, the finished products are sumptuous arrangements
of synthetic irises or water lilies. Fake flowers may not be to
Monet's taste, but we'll never know. Dead designers don't cop an
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Louis XV might not recognize the chair upholstered in happy
yellow fabric with blue bows, but the silhouette has his Roman
numerals all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's collection is just as easy to recognize. It shrieks East
Coast with a country club accent. The Hilfiger homewares of
bedding, bath and accessories have names: Greenwich, Club Classics
and Varsity. They all look as if they were hand-stitched by the
Seven Sisters for graduation presents.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger's style appeals to the pre-collegiate generation today.
Next month or next year, that may not be the case. All the Louises
_ XIV, XV and XVI _ have staying power; they've been hot for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised to find more and more collections based on
the styles of the deceased. The dead do not become passe as quickly
as the living.
</P>
<P>
   THE SMALL PRINT: The Claude Monet Collection catalog is
available from Masterpiece Gardens, 90 Novner Drive, Cincinnati,
Ohio 45215, or www.monetgiverny.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patines Anciennes'' is available for $5 through South Side
Imports, 3553 N. Dixie Highway, Fort Lauderdale, FL 33334, (954)
567-0337.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hilfiger homewares are available at department stores
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
