<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLINTON-NIXON PARALLEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Unanimous?'' asked a confused and concerned
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unanimous,'' replied Alexander Haig. ``There is no air in it
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None at all,'' queried Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tight as a drum,'' said Haig.
</P>
<P>
   The event that sparked that brief colloquy between the president
and the general who served as his chief of staff on July 24, 1974,
in San Clemente, Calif., was the Supreme Court's unanimous ruling
saying Nixon had to forfeit tapes of private White House
conversations to Watergate Special Prosecutor Leon Jaworski.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day Nixon telephoned Washington to inform White House
Special Counsel Fred Buzhardt that ``there might be a problem with
the June 23d tape,'' which had been recorded in his office six days
after the break-in at the Democratic National Committee
headquarters in the Watergate complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate scandal that had haunted Nixon for two years was
closing in on him swiftly and ominously _ and he knew it. The
coverup had lost its cover.
</P>
<P>
   Once the June 23 tape was made public, it would inform Jaworski,
Federal Judge John Sirica, Congress and the world that the
president had sought to use the CIA to block the FBI's
investigation of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, numerous Republicans in the House and Senate
who had stood by the president realized his guilt and withdrew
their loyalty to the him.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Supreme Court ruling, the House Judiciary
Committee approved its first article of impeachment, accusing Nixon
of obstruction of justice in trying to cover up Watergate. On Aug.
9, 16 days after the court's ruling, Nixon resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater had informed the president that
there were ample Republican and Democratic votes in the Senate to
convict him.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of history is resurrected at this time because another
presidential career may be as endangered as Nixon's was 24 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   We have no concrete evidence that Bill Clinton is guilty of any
crime, and it seems ludicrous to many Americans that so much time
and money would be spent trying to determine whether he lied when
he testified under oath that he did not have sex with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But it is inevitable that a parallel will be drawn between the
Supreme Court's momentous ruling against Nixon and Chief Justice
William Rehnquist's decision July 17 to permit testimony of Secret
Service agents before Kenneth Starr's grand jury investigating the
current president.
</P>
<P>
   After conferring with some of his colleagues, Rehnquist declared
that the Supreme Court would not overrule a federal appeals court's
decree that there is no legal basis for the exclusion in a criminal
case of the testimony of Secret Service agents, despite their
intimate relationship with the president and their need for close
proximity to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of irony in the chief justice's decision. When
the court ruled on the Nixon tapes, Rehnquist, then an associate
justice, disqualified himself because he had served as an assistant
attorney general in the Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   Because of him the court's ruling in 1974 was 8 to 0 rather than
9 to 0.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton has conducted himself with far more restraint
than Nixon, who made several impulsive and misguided moves in an
effort to cover his tracks and those of his political associates.
</P>
<P>
   When Jaworski's predecessor as Watergate special prosecutor,
Archibald Cox, refused to yield on his demand for the tapes, Nixon
ordered Attorney General Elliot Richardson to fire him. Outraged by
Nixon's action, Richardson refused and submitted his own
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General William Ruckelshaus also refused to fire
Cox. He in turn was fired by Nixon. Finally, Solicitor General
Robert Bork, the No. 3 man in the Justice Department, decreed an
end to Cox's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The date was Oct. 20, 1973 and that sequence of events was the
infamous ``Saturday Night Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, nothing quite that explosive has happened in the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   We can debate endlessly the wisdom of the action taken by the
appeals court and Rehnquist. Having covered the White House during
several presidencies and having known and respected numerous Secret
Service agents, I cannot help putting great stock in their
contention that in being forced to testify, they could break faith
with the president and rupture a relationship that is vital to
protection of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we know from the Watergate experience that a president in
trouble will grasp at any life preserver to keep himself afloat. If
a Secret Service agent witnesses a criminal act, he or she has a
responsibility to report it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law covering this matter. But as Utah's Orrin Hatch,
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, has suggested, Congress
should consider next year establishing guidelines for the testimony
of Secret Service agents. Those rules should protect the
confidentiality necessary between the president and his bodyguards
while also making clear that those agents have a responsibility to
divulge pertinent information regarding criminal acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
