<P>
   AIRLINE-SEATS (UNdated) _ Every time I board an airplane,
economy-class ticket in hand, I experience what I think of as the
Goldilocks Syndrome. I work my way down the crowded aisle past the
jumbo Papa Bear seats in first class, the more modest Mama Bear
seats in business class and back to the little bitty Baby Bear
seats in coach. Here the parallel with the fairy tale ends; no one
who flies coach would ever declare that these tightly packed seats
are ``just right.'' By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-TOOLS (Undated) _ There's an indescribable quality that
radiates from old tools. You sense it in the hand-worn patina of
rosewood knobs and grips, the chiaroscuro of glinting brass levers
under darkened steel. But they are mute until you touch them. Then
they won't shut up. Pick up an old tool, and you almost hear the
ticking hours of its long working life. Such tools can be time
machines, portals to a yesteryear farther away than the moon. By
Jeff Taylor.
</P>
