<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ID NUMBER PART OF HEALTH PLAN THAT WE DON'T NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been nearly five years since President Clinton delivered
that much-anticipated speech unveiling his ambitious plan for
overhauling the U.S. health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is long forgotten. The plan is long gone, although
its architects are constantly rummaging through the debris in the
hope of rescuing scraps from the trash heap of history.
</P>
<P>
   One such scrap is the lifetime health-care ID number, a proposal
that became a mandate when Clinton signed the 1996 Health Insurance
Portability and Accountability Act. This law requires that every
American be assigned an ``identifier'' that would facilitate
electronic collection and storage of medical information.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill was passed, everybody was talking about how it
would help folks keep their health insurance when they lose a job
or change employers. Hardly anyone mentioned the obscure provision
about health-care identifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's time to implement such a system, however, it's
suddenly a matter of widespread controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The debate stems from the possibility that a government-mandated
system of health-care record-keeping could set up the citizenry for
a massive invasion of privacy. If medical records are
electronically filed and made easily retrievable with a simple ID
number, just about anyone will be able to access those records.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates insist that the system poses no threat to privacy and
would drastically improve Americans' ability to receive timely and
appropriate medical treatment. Some even argue that an electronic
identifier could reduce violations of patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents argue that a health-care ID number could subject
patients to rampant intrusions into their personal lives by opening
up their medical histories to inspection by everyone from mass
marketers to law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   There were things to like about Clinton's original health-care
plan _ universal access to health insurance, for one _ and there
was plenty to dislike. In the end, the proposal that was cooked up
by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was defeated because it would
have given the government too much control over America's
health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, when President Clinton spoke to the nation Sept. 22,
1993, the ID-number aspect of the proposal was looked upon by most
Americans as a minor detail. I remember mentioning to a friend
after the speech that I was troubled by the ID proposal _ and I
remember the friend looking at me as if I might be afflicted with
some paranoid delusion about the government's interest in my
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   How could any rational person be worried that the FBI would want
to know what medications his doctor had prescribed for some illness
or other?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, my paranoia did not and does not run that deep. There
was just something about the way that Clinton showed off the
prototype for a national ``health-security card,'' something about
the way he boasted that every American would be required to carry
the card from cradle to grave to receive medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The president was obviously proud of the card and the undeniable
access to health care that it would have guaranteed _ not to
mention the universal filing system that it represented _ and yet
there was something sinister about it. There was a ``Big Brother''
aspect to the idea of national health-care registration that was
extremely unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clinton health-care proposal was shouted down, one of
the elements I was absolutely certain that the country would be
better off without was the universal health-security card.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that we're about to get stuck with that part of
the plan without enjoying many of the aspects of the proposal that
would have been beneficial to most Americans. Lucky us.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it's not too late. If you are troubled by the notion
of an electronic filing system that would make the most intimate
details of your medical history available to anyone who can latch
onto your ID number, why not contact your representatives in
Congress and demand repeal of that provision of the 1996 Health
Insurance Portability and Accountability Act?
</P>
<P>
   They passed it. They can unpass it.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
