<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7481 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-VOICEMAIL-PRIVACY     07-22 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VOICEMAIL-PRIVACY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICE-MAIL SECURITY CASE MAKES USERS WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Colo., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (Eds: the (pound) word in text should be replace with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Chiquita Brands International accused a
reporter for The Cincinnati Enquirer of stealing 2,000 messages
from its voice mail in the course of investigating the company for
a series of articles.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not known exactly how the reporter, Michael
Gallagher, got the messages _ whether someone provided them to him
or whether he broke into Chiquita's voice-mail system. Chiquita
officials have accused him of stealing the messages himself.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, the newspaper dismissed Gallagher, who has not
discussed the matter publicly since then. In any case, there seems
to be no doubt that the voice-mail system was tampered with, which
raises a question for anyone who uses voice mail: How secure is it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as any telecommunications manager can tell you, is
that voice-mail systems are only as secure as the people who use
them decide they should be.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to security, voice mail is often treated like a
forgotten relative. Corporations are conscientious about educating
employees about computer and e-mail passwords, but less so when it
comes to voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Many older voice-mail systems, like the one used at Chiquita,
were often installed with default passwords. On many systems,
individual users were told that they could set passwords of their
own choosing. But, perhaps out of laziness or forgetfulness,
employees often failed to change their passwords, leaving their
voice-mail vulnerable to intruders.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, since voice mail has become common in the
United States, most systems have been the target of hackers at one
time or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to everybody,'' said John Guinasso, director of
corporate integrity and risk management at ICG Netcom, an Internet
service provider based in Englewood, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Netcom's voice-mail system was penetrated by a
15-year-old hacker who called himself Nobody. The teen-ager broke
into the system for fun, then listened to some idle chat among
Netcom employees before growing bored. But after the incident,
Guinasso said, the company stepped up its security, requiring
employees to choose passwords of at least six characters each.
</P>
<P>
   Chiquita uses a system manufactured by Octel Communications, now
the Octel Messaging Division of Lucent Technologies in Milpitas,
Calif. Robert Olson, Chiquita's general counsel and one of a
half-dozen or so executives there whose voice-mail messages were
stolen, said in an interview that the company had been confident
about the security of the system, which is about eight years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had every reason to believe it was secure,'' he said.
Lucent officials refused to say which security features had been on
the system when it was shipped to Chiquita.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of voice-mail break-ins occurred in the early 1990s when
hackers used voice-mail systems as a bridge to outside lines and
even used unassigned voice-mail boxes as message centers. That
prompted voice-mail manufacturers and telecommunications managers
to strengthen security.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lord, a security consultant with Nortel, a
telecommunications and data-networking company that manufactures
voice-mail systems, said that in the current release of Nortel's
voice-mail products, users were forced to choose individual
passwords the first time they logged on to the system instead of
allowing a default password setting like (pound). Lucent officials
said that more recent versions of its voice-mail systems did that
as well. With 100 million voice-mail boxes installed worldwide,
Lucent is the leading supplier of voice messaging systems.
</P>
<P>
   Chiquita has filed a defamation suit against Gallagher in
federal district court, citing in its complaint the voice-mail
messages the company says were stolen by Gallagher. A special
prosecutor in Hamilton County, Ohio, has begun an inquiry, and the
Federal Bureau of Investigation is looking into the case.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher and ``co-conspirators,'' according to Chiquita's
complaint, are accused of breaking ``into the voice-mail boxes of
Chiquita employees as frequently as 13 times a day.'' Chiquita's
phone records show that in a 10-day period in early May, the
company's voice mail was tampered with more than 50 times, the
company says.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate espionage is generally on the rise, experts say. Ms.
Lord estimates that the theft of confidential corporate information
has increased more than 300 percent in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Cold War ended, a lot of people got put out of
work,'' she said. ``They were spies, and they got into the business
of corporate espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice mail can be an important source of confidential
information. Ms. Lord said that last November, a former field sales
manager for a company in Andover, Mass., had been charged with
breaking into the company's voice-mail system to gain access to the
company's sales leads and confidential marketing information.
</P>
<P>
   But companies seldom make public a breach of their computer or
telecommunications systems, as disclosures of security weaknesses
could tarnish a corporate image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies don't want their stockholders to know something like
that happened to them,'' Ms. Lord said. Chiquita did not discover
that its voice mail had been tampered with until shortly before the
Enquirer's package of articles ran on May 3. The articles were
filled with references to, and quotes from, confidential voice-mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Voice mail for the home is also at risk. Increasingly, consumers
are tossing out their answering machines in favor of computerized
messaging services provided by phone companies. Those voice-mail
boxes could also be vulnerable to break-ins by people using a list
of common access codes and other code-breaking devices.
</P>
<P>
   The best advice to keep voice mail secure, and to protect
computer connections and e-mail as well, is to change passwords
regularly and to stay away from passwords that are easily guessed,
like 1234 or 5555. Don't keep passwords in an obvious place after
writing them down.
</P>
<P>
   If you hear a busy signal while trying to retrieve voice-mail
messages, it could indicate that someone else is listening to your
voice mail. In that case, call the telecommunications department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
