<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICK-TV-LADN     07-22 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICK-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKELODEON SINGS WACKY NEW 'TOONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What is funny? After spending most of the past two
decades creating animation for MTV, Hanna-Barbera Studios and
Nickelodeon, Fred Seibert thinks he knows.
</P>
<P>
   And over the next few months, he'll try to prove it with a new
series of one-off animated shorts he commissioned from a group of
writer-directors whose work he admires.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there will be 39 separate animated shorts, starring
about 35 different characters, appearing Sunday mornings on
Nickelodeon's ``Oh, Yeah!'' cartoon series that began last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cartoon laboratory for Nickelodeon and for the
animation industry in a lot of ways,'' said Seibert, the show's
executive producer. ``My view of TV and films has always been that
great talent spawns hip shows and hip characters. I start there and
then I say, `What do you got'?''
</P>
<P>
   If the screening copy of the first three shorts is any
indication, what they have is pretty promising.
</P>
<P>
   First up is ``Chalk Zone,'' premised on the idea that everything
ever drawn on a chalkboard goes to another world called the Chalk
Zone after it's erased. A little boy named Henry finds magic chalk
that lets him move between his ``real'' world and the Chalk Zone
while dealing with a real bully and the chalked stick-figure Bully
Nerd.
</P>
<P>
   The next short deals more explicitly with the metaphysical
question of ``What Is Funny?'' Slap T. Pooch riffs on a series of
gags and alternate takes, asking each time, ``Is this funny? I
don't know. I'm asking.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartoon set off a debate between my Personal Entertainment
Testing System units about what gags worked for their 6- and
7-year-old senses of humor, something no other entertainment has
ever done.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the short, at least, is engaging, even if my
P.E.T.S.' answers to some of Pooch's questions were ``That's not
funny,'' or ``That's disgusting,'' or ``That's just stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The final short, ``Jelly's Day,'' follows a slightly spoiled
little girl through her day with her Lurch-like cousin Hargus from
Entrancylvania.
</P>
<P>
   It, like the other two pieces, has a wonderful level of energy
and fun, far more in the spirit of classic ``Looney Tunes''
creations than anything else I've seen in a while.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to create a bunch of one-off shorts, rather than a
series focusing on one character is also a bit risky, ignoring 40
years of practice, Seibert acknowledged. But he's again looking to
the classic Looney Tunes for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really how Looney Tunes work,'' Seibert said. ``The
first year Bugs Bunny showed up, 10 years into that series, they
did four (episodes) of him. Then they went from there.''
</P>
<P>
   And although in the short term it might be cheaper to do all the
development and animation work for a single-character series,
Seibert said over the long term, his approach might turn out more
hit series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't swear to it, but I wouldn't be too far off in
saying there are more new characters in this one show than the
entire industry does in a year,'' Seibert said. ``This year, we are
taking 35, 36 shots up to bat, rather than in a traditional series
where there's one shot up to bat. The long-term prospects are
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Seibert said he chose animators whose work he knew and worked
with them to create characters that made him laugh and that he
could connect with. Now, with the series on the air, you can decide
for yourself: What is funny?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
