<SLUG> BC-RECITAL-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTUNED TO THE AGE OF MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Michelle Cisneros is a shy giggler, Mario Castro
never happier than when he's imitating a boxer, throwing punches at
imaginary opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But when they sit down at the piano, they're all business.
</P>
<P>
   The two 4-year-olds _ the youngest of Max Music Center director
and instructor Lizbeth Ortuste's students ever to play in public _
are first on the bill for the music school's weekend piano recital.
</P>
<P>
   Are they nervous?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' says Mario matter-of-factly, a big grin on his face.
``I like to play _ loud. I want to be a concert pianist.''
</P>
<P>
   A lofty ambition for a lad who's only studied music for four
months. On an adult-size grand piano, he'll play ``Old MacDonald
Had a Farm,'' rendered in rehearsal in Ortuste's living room with
all the force of a jackhammer pounding pavement.
</P>
<P>
   But Mario hits all the right keys. So does Michelle, in her
quiet way. She'll play ``The Skater,'' a dreamy but simple piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to know the personality of each
student,'' said Ortuste, who graduated from Tomas Frias University
in Potosi, Bolivia, with a degree in music arts and teaches about
30 Valley children at her Van Nuys home. Her first love is
classical music, but she says younger children must start playing
music that appeals to them before tackling more esoteric _ and more
difficult _ pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give a child a waltz to play first, and he won't like
it,'' she said. ``He'll be bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Renato Calderon, the school's artistic director, doesn't play
piano himself but is a longtime student of classical music and
likes to explain the nuances of the music to the kids so they can
recognize the sound of a tinkling brook or a thunderstorm or cannon
fire in the pieces they play.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think classical music is boring,'' he said.
``Lots of people call it `church music.' But they don't understand
it. Once you understand it, you love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven students will participate in this year's recital, which
will feature music by Beethoven, Chopin, Liszt, Strauss,
Senneville, Tchaikovsky, Jarre, Streabbog and Kuhlau.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when most kids are swooning over virtual pets, Beanie
Babies and Leonardo De Caprio, Ortuste says learning classical
music can keep youngsters disciplined, respectful and focused both
on their music and their schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``They learn to respect the music and its rules, how it must be
played,'' she said. ``They learn the discipline, that it takes
practice every day to be able to play. People who like classical
music ... live in another world, liking good things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
