<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SEATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE FAIRY TALE: COACH IS NO PUMPKIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time I board an airplane, economy-class ticket in hand, I
experience what I think of as the Goldilocks Syndrome. I work my
way down the crowded aisle past the jumbo Papa Bear seats in first
class, the more modest Mama Bear seats in business class and back
to the little bitty Baby Bear seats in coach. Here the parallel
with the fairy tale ends; no one who flies coach would ever declare
that these tightly packed seats were ``just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines, eager to attract and retain passengers who will pay
top dollar, keep making the seats at the front of the plane plusher
and spacing them farther apart. Two years ago, British Airways
trumped the competition by introducing accommodations for its
first-class passengers that are positively womb-like. Configured by
a yacht designer, each seat is a module, isolated from the other
seats, with a built-in coffee table and visitor's chair. At the
touch of a button, the whole unit converts into a 6-foot-6-inch
bed. British Airways also advertises a business-class seat called
the Cradle Seat, perfect for overgrown Baby Bears.
</P>
<P>
   What I realized on my most recent flight is that the Goldilocks
Syndrome has entered the digital age. On a new United Airlines 767,
even my humble coach seat was equipped with its own video screen.
(United is playing catch up here; Virgin Atlantic has long offered
this amenity.) On a panel in my armrest was a sophisticated array
of buttons controlling audio, video, a topographical map that shows
the progress of the flight from several perspectives, and the usual
call button and light switch.
</P>
<P>
   As I disembarked, however, I noticed that Connoisseur Class (as
United calls its business class) seats had even more buttons on the
armrests and that first-class passengers had at their fingertips an
array of controls exceeded only by what the pilot has in the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Business-class buttons, it turns out, perform the same
entertainment functions as those in coach, with the addition of a
``noise-reduction'' button that allows passengers to listen through
their headsets to a ``noise-canceling'' electronic signal. But
business passengers also get a row of buttons that controls each
seat's Back Cycler, a moving air bladder to massage the lumbar
region.
</P>
<P>
   First-class passengers get all of the above plus two rows of
buttons to control their personal VCRs, a bonus button to adjust
the color tint of their monitors, and a default button that returns
the video channel, color, tint and volume to preset positions.
</P>
<P>
   Also mounted on the first-class armrest is a second control
panel with 10 buttons that can be used to adjust the pitch and yaw
of the motorized seat backs and foot rests, features that operate
manually in business class.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is a control console so complex that, according
to Tom Chapman, United's program manager for on-board product
planning, an international assortment of seat testers discovered
``things on them so subtle that they never knew how they worked
until the flight was over.'' United solved this problem with an
instructional video _ not on how to inflate the life vests or use
the emergency exits, but on how to make all the seat gadgets work.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace Peltola, the director of marketing at Walter Dorwin
Teague of Redmond, Wash, an industrial-design firm that contributed
to the development of the Connoisseur Class seat, said an effort
had been made to group the various buttons logically, by function,
but that the most important design task was to make sure the
control panel was always in easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   Peltola, who has worked with Boeing on aircraft interiors,
noted, ``We've had situations where people get in full recline and
can't get back up again. You don't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   With faxes, phone calls and e-mail messages coming and going,
and nine channels of video, the new United seats can be viewed as
yet another manifestation of media convergence: the electronic
comfy chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``An airplane seat is one of the most information-intensive
places to be,'' said Peter Dixon, a partner at Lippincott &AMP;
Margulies, the corporate-identity firm that worked on the design of
Continental Airlines' Business First seats in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But the wired seats are also a new manifestation of a time-worn
marketing lesson, one learned by blender manufacturers in the
1960s: the more buttons you put on an appliance, the better it
sells.
</P>
<P>
   What seems significant is not the buttons' ergonomic qualities
or functional attributes, or even the technological advances they
represent. Rather, it's the reassurance they offer the Type A
personalities that cluster in the forward cabins.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, first- and business-class passengers are as much at
the mercy of the air-traffic controllers, the pilots, the jet
stream and the fates as are the less button-endowed travelers in
coach, but Papa Bears and Mama Bears are willing to pay a premium
for the illusion that they are as much in charge at 25,000 feet as
they are on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
