<SLUG> BC-CIR-WORLD-FAIRS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RETURN TO THE FUTURE, 1939 STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Mass.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The blue-and-white pins distributed at the 1939 New York World's
Fair read, ``I have seen the future.'' But they were not promoting
the Soviet Experiment; they were extolling streamlined cars and
superhighways, and every visitor to the General Motors Futurama
exhibition got a pin.
</P>
<P>
   The fair may have gone bankrupt in 1940, but its impact on the
American imagination remains. The opening ceremony on April 30,
1939, which featured a speech by President Franklin D. Roosevelt,
ushered in the first day of television broadcasting in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Other new technology at the fair included robotics
(Westinghouse's Elektro and his dog, Sparko), FM radio, fluorescent
lighting and Futurama's present cloverleafs for 1960 (no stop
signs!). At the RCA exhibition, the ``radio living room of
tomorrow'' even had a crude fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   The fair, with all its utopian promise and raw consumerism, has
inspired several recent Web sites, offering history, evocative
photographs, buying opportunities and sound movie clips of speeches
at the fair by Einstein, Roosevelt, La Guardia and others.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ambitious site is one that is part of the
American Studies program at the University of Virginia and was
prepared by John C. Barans, a graduate student
(http://xroads.virginia.edu/1930s/DISPLAY/39wf/frame.htm). It
offers a history of the two-year fair, as well as a hefty dose of
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World of Tomorrow,'' Barans writes, ``was a modern
extension of Enlightenment thinking, the unswerving belief in the
ability and perfectibility of humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   And those visuals! The site includes a film clip of the
dishwashing contest in the Westinghouse building: ``Mrs. Modern''
washes her dishes in a guess what made by Guess Who, while ``Mrs.
Drudge'' does hers by hand and loses the contest in every way,
including the fact that she is not as ``neat and refreshed as when
she started.''
</P>
<P>
   The good old days are jarring when memory does not have a chance
to filter them. The American Tobacco Co. building, designed like a
giant pack of Lucky Strikes, is in the Food Court along with the
Borden Co.'s Rotolactor, a revolving turntable with real cows.
</P>
<P>
   The Middletons, Westinghouse's typical American family, are
white and from Indiana. The site includes a rare photograph of
black visitors; for some reason, they are shown in front of the
Soviet pavilion. There is also a World's Fair commemorative edition
of the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   For all its high modernism and higher rhetoric, the fair also
had its sideshow, nobly disguised as education. Pictures include
Little Miracle Town, a collection of performing midgets, and Billy
Rose's Aquacade, which had Esther Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Frozen Alive Girl and the Dream of Venus building (designed
in part by Salvador Dali), paid equal homage to imagination and
scantily clad women. But photos of the pavilions of Czechoslovakia,
Poland and Lithuania take on a certain poignancy, given the fair's
coinciding with the early days of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Alan B. Howard, director of the American Studies
programs at the University of Virginia, said, ``We're really
interested in why New Yorkers and other people, many of whom never
went to the fair, all remember it.'' Part of the reason, he said,
is what he calls the generational mapping of the 1930s: ``The
period we look to for most of our learning about ourselves is our
grandparents' generation.'' The fair, he said, was ``a place where
America's future was being invented.''
</P>
<P>
   A more personal Web site for the 1939 fair, a cornucopia of
recollections, contemporary articles and current collectors'
guides, is at wysiwyg://135/http://websyte.com/alan/nywf.htm.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go to this fair was to have your life changed forever,''
wrote the site's creator, C. Alan Anderson, 67, a professor of
philosophy and religion at Curry College in Milton, Mass. He was
about 8 when his family visited from Connecticut. He remembers the
fireworks, a gas mask display and his first glimpse of television.
``That was a very big event in my young life and I've been
interested in it ever since,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's site shares recollections by others. ``Half of my
home is decorated in World's Fair,'' one wrote. Another offers
original souvenirs, including a 1939 World's Fair drink coaster for
$38 and a World's Fair Peanut bookmark for $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``More often,'' Anderson said, ``I get letters from young people
who say they wish they could have been there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
