<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR PETER HORTON FINDS HELL IS NOT A MAXIMUM SECURITY PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Peter Horton, best known from his days on
``thirtysomething,'' returns to the series format this fall in
``Brimstone'' on Fox. Horton plays a good cop who had one really
bad moment in his life: He murdered the guy who raped his wife
because the justice system failed him. He then was killed in the
line of duty and went to hell.
</P>
<P>
   End of story, right?
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Seems hell isn't a maximum-security place. At least not for 113
condemned souls who have managed to escape to the land of the
living and are ready to loose evil on the unsuspecting. The devil
recruits Horton's character, Ezekiel Stone, to round them up. He
was a pretty good cop, after all. To send them back to
nether-netherland, Stone must poke out their eyes _ the windows to
the soul _ by any means necessary, which led one squeamish TV
critic to ask if any of the baddies will be female.
</P>
<P>
   Horton replied: ``Hell is co-ed, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The nominees for the 50th Emmy Awards will be announced
Thursday, but this much is already known: The telecast of the Sept.
13 ceremony on NBC will be as lengthy as some of the network's
miniseries, and nobody is hosting this year. Or, more accurately,
everybody is hosting.
</P>
<P>
   At four hours (7 to 11 p.m.), the prime-time Emmy Awards show
probably will set a record for bathroom breaks per celebrity.
Oddly, though, it will parcel out fewer awards than in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will telecast 27 awards,'' executive producer Don Mischer
said this week. ``There were 28 last year, one of which was the
President's Award. The feeling at the television academy was there
was some redundancy in that award, because every time it had been
given the winner also won an Emmy in some other category. So we've
taken the President's Award out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fewer awards, more air time. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Mischer says it won't mean longer acceptance speeches; winners
are still limited to 30 seconds. He said the extra time will permit
a five- or six-minute segment on the academy's craft awards, which
will be handed out two weeks before the glamour ones, plus plenty
of time for 50th anniversary folderol.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it doesn't mean longer categories, such as this one
from 1954: Best Continuing Performance in a Series by a Comedian,
Singer, Host, Dancer, Emcee, Announcer, Narrator, Panelist or Any
Person Who Essentially Plays Himself (or Herself).
</P>
<P>
   As for the no-host approach, Mischer said: ``We want it to feel
like the entire television industry has come together for this
night. ... There is less predictability, more surprise and more
energy when you don't have a host.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Crude is one word that comes to mind after watching the pilot
episode of ``Costello,'' a new working-class comedy on Fox this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   But comedian Sue Costello, co-creator and star of the
autobiographical series, isn't apologetic. In her charmingly
jarring South Boston accent, she said, ``It is rough to the rest of
the world, but ... it's so true to my life. ... It's like when I
came to Hollywood somebody interviewed me and said, `Sue, how do
you like Hollywood?' And without knowing any better I said to them,
`It's just like growing up in the streets, except you can't call
anybody a whore.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Diane English, the principal force behind the 10-season run of
``Murphy Brown'' on CBS, admits that such success opens doors. This
fall, she takes her track record to Fox with the comedy ``Living in
Captivity,'' a social satire about life in the suburbs, focusing on
two white couples and their new African-American neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But English has no illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get one, maybe two shots'' to win an audience, she said
Wednesday. ``If you don't deliver, it doesn't matter who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
