<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STOCK-TRADING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE STOCK TRADING CAN BE HAZARDOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANA POINT, Calif. _ On-line trading can be hazardous to your
wallet. That was the cautionary conclusion of John L. Steffens,
vice chairman of the board of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., who addressed a
gathering of Internet industry executives and entrepreneurs here
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens told people at the annual Spotlight conference that the
ease and convenience of Internet-based trading seduce people into
buying and selling stocks more often than they should. So-called
E-traders, he said, tend to trade three to four times more often
than people who buy and sell shares through traditional brokerage
firms. And they pay a price for that haste and frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens cited a study by economists at the University of
California at Davis, which looked at the trading habits of 60,000
households from 1991 to 1996. According to the study, the most
active traders had a rate of return of 10 percent per year,
compared with a 15 percent return for those who traded least often.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are killing themselves by trading too much _ there's no
question,'' said Terry Odean, an assistant professor of finance at
the university and one of the study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steffens, 25 percent to 30 percent of retail stock
trades are done electronically, and the median age of an online
trader is about 36.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens, 57, is of the old school of stock market investing,
which is guided by a principle of long-term stock holdings. When
held for years, not months or weeks, stocks gain value, he said,
and serious investors recognize that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, are you interested in fun and games or
investing? The two are very different,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens added that online trading had also caused increased
volatility in the stock markets because of the ease with which it
is done. And he agreed with an audience member that online trading
could become the ``Las Vegas of the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   A half dozen or so firms offer no-frills electronic trading. But
while Merrill Lynch uses the Net to give clients instant access to
research and other information, it does not now offer online stock
trading, though it plans to offer online brokerage services to
certain customers next year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Steffens chose the wrong audience for such a
pronouncement. Most of the 200 or so people in the audience were in
their 30s and early 40s, and their livelihood depends on promoting
the benefits of the Internet. Some two-thirds of those in
attendance said they traded stocks on line. Steffens, it turned
out, was the only person in the room over age 55.
</P>
<P>
   When polled before Steffens' presentation, most members of the
audience said they considered the Internet as more of an
opportunity than a threat. Thirty minutes later, however, after a
round of tough questions from the audience and from Michael
Schrage, the conference's executive producer, many people changed
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   When Schrage posed the same question a second time, most people
in the audience decided that the online world was a threat to the
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   David Braunschvig, a managing director at Lazard Freres &AMP; Co.
and who attended the conference, said of the swing in opinion:
``It's not that they were more bearish on Merrill, but they
realized the complexity of the whole landscape. It was the first
time they started thinking of the relative merits of, and
challenges for, an established brand coming into the online
arena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
