<SLUG> BC-HERB-GINGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGER PROVES A SURPRISINGLY VERSATILE SPICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Ginger is an herbaceous tropical (tender) perennial. Its
aromatic, knotty, tuberous rhizome is used in cooking. Probably
native to India and southern China. Foliage reaches 24 to 48 inches
high.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Plant from rhizome in spring. Pot from a
walnut-size piece with an eye (as on a potato). Provide fertile,
moist, well-drained soil in partial shade. To harvest, pull plant
from pot eight to 12 months after planting and remove leaves. Cut
off what you need and replant the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Beverages, fruit, meat, poultry, fish, preserves,
pickles, vegetables. Used in Asian, Caribbean and North African
cuisines.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT CHEESE SALAD WITH GINGER AND MACADAMIA NUTS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a salad course
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces soft goat cheese, chilled
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces roasted macadamia nuts
</P>
<P>
   6 cups lettuce greens, preferably baby leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 clove garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped cilantro sprigs
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Japanese rice vinegar, unseasoned
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Carefully cut the goat cheese into four thin slices. If nuts are
salted, rinse briefly and pat dry. Place nuts in a food processor
and chop coarsely, then transfer to a plate. Coat each cheese slice
with the nuts and refrigerate. If using large lettuce, tear into
bite-size pieces. Refrigerate lettuce. Set aside olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Combine dressing ingredients and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, stir dressing; toss greens with half the salad
dressing. Arrange on four plates.
</P>
<P>
   Place a 12-inch skillet over medium-high heat. When hot, add the
1 tablespoon olive oil. Heat oil, then gently add goat-cheese
slices. Saute on both sides until cheese is just heated through and
nuts are golden brown, about 2 minutes. Gently transfer to center
of greens. Stir remaining dressing and spoon over goat cheese and
greens. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 518 calories, 52 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 28 milligrams cholesterol,
1,007 milligrams sodium, 90 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Quick Cooking With Pacific Flavors'' by Hugh Carpenter and
Teri Sandison (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED YELLOW TOMATO SOUP WITH GINGER
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8 as a first course
</P>
<P>
   12 vine-ripened yellow tomatoes (red tomatoes can be
substituted)
</P>
<P>
   3 yellow bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch cilantro
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in half through circumference, not through stem.
Gently shake out seeds. Cut away stem area, and cut tomatoes into
large cubes. Stem, seed and cube peppers. Peel and thickly slice
onion. Cut off and discard large cilantro stems. Set aside a few
sprigs of cilantro for garnish. Set aside garlic and ginger. Stem
and very finely mince the jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except salt in a large bowl, then place
about one-quarter of the mixture at a time in a food processor.
Puree until completely liquefied, then transfer to a clean bowl.
Taste and adjust flavors, especially salt and vinegar, then
refrigerate. Soup can be completed to this point up to 24 hours
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Taste soup again and adjust for salt, spice and vinegar. Serve
in chilled bowls, garnished with cilantro sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 161 calories, 14 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 12
milligrams sodium, 14 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Quick Cooking With Pacific Flavors''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SWORDFISH IN LEMON-GINGER MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 medium cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon finely ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 swordfish steaks, 1/3 to 1/2 pound each, no more than 1 inch
thick
</P>
<P>
   For marinade: Combine all ingredients except fish in a medium
bowl. Whisk until blended.
</P>
<P>
   In a large, shallow, nonaluminum dish, arrange fish steaks and
pour marinade over. Marinate fish 2 to 4 hours in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare barbecue for medium-heat grilling. Remove fish from
marinade. Grill fish about 3 inches from heat for 5 minutes on each
side.
</P>
<P>
   Heat remaining marinade thoroughly, to a low simmer, in a small
saucepan over medium heat.
</P>
<P>
   Pour some of heated marinade over fish and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 292 calories, 16 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 66 milligrams cholesterol,
252 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Cuisine of California'' by Diane Rossen Worthington
(Chronicle, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
