<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REALTY-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ZAGAT'S FOR REAL ESTATE ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wake up, you apartment junkies!
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to know exactly how much apartments are selling for
in the building of your dreams? Want to read about a neighborhood?
The ten best views of Central Park? The ten best water tank
enclosures? (Yeah, those things up on the roof.)
</P>
<P>
   There's a new web site where you don't have to buy anything, and
it's owners pledge not to bug you with unwanted calls and
``cookies,'' those secret little files that advertisers place on
your computer to follow you around.
</P>
<P>
   It's called www.nyrealty.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can look up a specific co-op or condominium building _ 500
of them, right now _ and find a brief, often witty description of
its pros and cons, and even the last sales there.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood commentaries and the building reviews were
written by Carter B. Horsley, a former real estate reporter at The
New York Times, who was also the architectural critic at the New
York Post until 1991. On the Web, Horsley describes midtown west
(West 32nd to West 59th) in 13 pages, starting:
</P>
<P>
   ``The East Side may be slightly more elegant and neater than the
West Side but when it comes to energy at the heart of the city's
cauldron, west midtown wins easily. This is where New Yorkers and
non-New Yorkers collide. This is where dreams are fashioned and
legends made. This is the turf. This is where Ratso Rizzo in
``Midnight Cowboy'' bangs on a cab and yells, ``Hey, I'm walking
here!''
</P>
<P>
   The web site, which opened last week, is free, but the company,
NY Realty.Com, is obviously hoping that cybernauts will also check
out the part of the web site where they can actually sign up to see
apartments for sale or rent. Just click on Buying, go to Hot Deals,
pick an address, then a specific apartment and scrutinize its pros
and cons. Interested? Make an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Levy, the company's president, said that even if
customers chose to fill out a form, giving their name and e-mail
address, they would be called only to confirm the appointment
they've requested.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, he added, they want to sign up for another service: they
can be automatically e-mailed when other apartments that match
their specifications become available. But again, Levy assured the
faint of heart: no unwanted sales calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Zagat's for real estate,'' he bragged. ``We'll
have ratings, reviews, photos, maps, financial data that's never
before published.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the top ten views of Central Park (960 Fifth Ave. and
the Beresford, 211 Central Park West (81st Street), head the list)
and the top 10 water tank enclosures (Trump Parc, 100 Central Park
South, and the San Remo, 145 Central Park West (74th Street), are
two), Horsley also selected the top 10 non-rectilinear buildings
(including the Corinthian at 645 First Ave. (East 38th Street), a
tower he says is ``the closest New York comes to the great Lake
Point Tower in Chicago.'')
</P>
<P>
   There are more to come: the top 10 buildings for pets. The top
ten entrance marquees. The top 10 rooftop pools. And, lest you
worry that they were going to be forgotten, the top 10 gargoyles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
