<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: STEPS TO REFACING KITCHEN CABINETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: How-to drawing is being sent to NYT graphics and NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kitchen cabinets subjected to a lot of wear and tear will
eventually start to look shabby. Replacing those old cabinets with
new ones can be expensive. Fortunately there is another, less
expensive option: the cabinets can be refaced.
</P>
<P>
   Refacing entails bonding new material, either plastic laminate
or wood veneer, over the old cabinet faces with contact cement.
Refacing with plastic laminate is best left to a professional. Wood
veneer is a little easier to work with because it can be trimmed
with a utility knife and a smooth file.
</P>
<P>
   One type of veneer, called ''peel-and-stick,'' is available with
an adhesive backing. It is easy to use; simply peel off the
protective paper and press the veneer in place. Contact cement is
unnecessary. With this material, an experienced do-it-yourselfer
can give shabby cabinets a new look.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to veneer your cabinets. With the first
method, all surfaces, including the end panels, exposed frame
surfaces, cabinets doors and drawer fronts, are recovered with
veneer. The second method requires veneering only the end panels
and exposed frame surfaces; the cabinets doors and drawer fronts
are replaced with new solid wood pieces. The second method is more
expensive but is less work and it may be the best option if the
existing cabinets doors and drawer fronts are ornate or have
recessed molding.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by carefully measuring all the cabinet surfaces. Look in
the Yellow Pages under ''Kitchen Cabinets.'' Call the dealers
listed to find where you can purchase unfinished doors and drawer
fronts. (Do not buy finished pieces; it will be difficult to stain
them to match the other facings.) Most dealers will offer a variety
of styles, usually in either oak or maple.
</P>
<P>
   Next calculate the surface area of all the cabinet frame
surfaces and add about 20 percent more to that figure. Then
purchase enough veneer to cover that area. The veneer is to be the
same wood as the doors and fronts.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier if you stain and finish all the pieces before you
mount them. Some pieces, like the solid doors and drawer fronts,
look lighter if they do not absorb as much stain as the veneer. In
this case, you can apply a second coat of stain. After the stain
dries, apply a light coat of polyurethane.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all the cabinet doors, drawers and all hardware. If the
drawers have detachable fronts, take them off. Some drawers have
one-piece fronts that are glued to the drawer sides and are not
removable. Here you will have to saw off the edges of each front so
it is flush with the sides of the drawer, then move the drawer
slides forward. In effect, you are creating a false drawer front.
Mount the new front to this face by driving screws from inside the
drawer. Make sure the screws are not too long or they will
penetrate the new piece.
</P>
<P>
   Good surface preparation is the key to bonding the veneer firmly
to the cabinet face. Examine the surfaces closely. Remove any nails
or staples, then fill all holes, cracks and dents with wood filler.
Sand all surfaces with 100 grit paper. The sanding will remove any
bumps and also create a ''tooth'' for the adhesive to grip. After
sanding, remove the dust with a tack cloth or a rag damped with
denatured alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   With a utility knife and metal straight edge, cut the veneer to
fit the cabinet frame. Cutting the veneer along the grain is
relatively easy, but the veneer may crack or splinter when you try
to cut across the grain. To prevent this, make several light passes
across the veneer rather than one heavy cut.
</P>
<P>
   The cut pieces should be slightly oversize; you can trim off the
excess after each piece is bonded in place. Check the fit of each
piece before bonding it in place. If the fit is good, remove the
paper, press the veneer against the cabinet face. Use a wallpaper
seam roller to flatten the veneer and force out air pockets. Trim
off any overlap with the utility knife and a fine file-tooth file.
With a cotton swab, apply stain and finish to these trimmed edges.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, mount the new cabinet doors in place. Be sure that they
line up with each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
