<SLUG> BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE LISTED ON NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photo available on the Wieck Photo Database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The shares of Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc. began
trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock had previously been traded on the Nasdaq
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst-Argyle is growing rapidly, and we believe the NYSE's
auction-based market will enhance the efficiency of trading in our
stock,'' noted Bob Marbut, chairman and co-chief executive officer
of Hearst-Argyle Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also believe that the NYSE will offer our shareholders
increased liquidity and reduced volatility, which is keeping with
our commitment to improve long-term shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc, owns and/or manages 15
network-affiliated TV stations that reach approximately 11 percent
of U.S. TV households and comprise the fourth largest non-network
owned television station group in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the company announced that it would acquire the nine
television stations and five radio stations of Pulitzer Publishing,
resulting in a 24 station TV group reaching 16.5 percent of U.S. TV
households.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, subject to regulatory and shareholder approval,
is scheduled to be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
