<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLOMON-APARTMENT-ART     07-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLOMON-APARTMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALING DOWN THE SPACE, BUT NOT THE FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the movers and shakers build 20,000-square-foot
megamansions in the Hamptons and combine apartments on Park Avenue
in Manhattan, art dealer Holly Solomon is moving on down. Left
behind: a nine-room apartment (plus maids' rooms and two storage
rooms) on Sutton Place. Present home: a six-room apartment on the
Upper East Side that seats six for dinner. That may seem more than
adequate for most people, but Ms. Solomon used to give buffets for
100.
</P>
<P>
   Her life has changed. In 1990, she was divorced from her
husband, Horace Solomon, an art collector. In 1993, she moved the
Holly Solomon Gallery from uptown back to Soho, where she first
started selling art in 1969. Each night, after going to openings or
dinners with friends, she returned alone to her nine-plus rooms,
went straight to her bed, turned on the television and stayed
there.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, faced with the choice of moving or buying the
rent-controlled apartment, where she had lived for more than 30
years and raised her two sons, she reluctantly packed up and bought
a new place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be dumb,'' she said. ``Basically I was living in one
room, and I was holding on to an idea of something that no longer
existed: the husband, the children, the family.''
</P>
<P>
   A new apartment cannot make a life perfect. But it can help. Ms.
Solomon, 64, asked two of her artists _ Kim MacConnel, a leader in
the pattern-and-decoration movement, and his wife, Jean Lowe, an
installation artist _ to help her create a small salon, ``in the
18th-century idea of a meeting place that was informal,'' MacConnel
recalled. It would be ``a fantasy of extreme elegance, with several
places in the apartment where you could sit and converse,'' he
said. ``She didn't really want a living room, or a dining room.''
Entertaining would be intimate, although she insisted on a
television in nearly every room.
</P>
<P>
   In three days, digging through decorative-art history from
Limoges china to south-of-the-border paintings on velvet, MacConnel
and Ms. Lowe transformed a bleak white box into a style best
described as American baroque. (Or as he said, ``ersatz chateau.'')
</P>
<P>
   They dipped the bedroom and guest room in pink and white, the
living room in dusky French blue, the dining room in pink _ acidy
colors that Ms. Lowe plucked from an 18th-century palette and toned
down. ``This is what artists do,'' said Izhar Patkin, a painter
whom Ms. Solomon represents. ``They don't buy into reality. They
try to transform it, as a novelist would.''
</P>
<P>
   On a gloomy day, the palette is a merry background for a
rotating collection of art _ some cheery (Ms. Lowe), some
provocative (Nam June Paik), some sad (William Wegman's ``Museum of
Beer,'' a landscape with silhouettes of Native Americans). Art and
decoration merge. ``They're symbiotic,'' MacConnel said. ``Certain
kinds of decoration go in and out of favor, just as art goes in and
out of favor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Solomon's apartment, however, nothing GOES with anything
else. MacConnel and Ms. Lowe painted fine antiqued gold and silver
edging on the wall panels, like a wispy memory of 18th-century trim
or frames for late 20th-century art. ``Why can't 18th-century
decoration support contemporary modern work?'' MacConnel asked.
</P>
<P>
   In the pale golden foyer hangs Robert Barry's ``Untitled,'' a
1988 pale gray painting with the words ``Another'' and ``Possible''
emerging as if from a mist, a mantra for Ms. Solomon's new life.
</P>
<P>
   When she moved here, she knew she was abandoning a life as the
art world's Perle Mesta. ``I had 300 on a big night,'' she said
ruefully. ``I'd have poetry readings. I'd show films. I had a
formal salon.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a vast collection of 18th-century china, Art Deco
plates, artists' ceramics and thousands of books. She sold all the
china, and gave all of her books except those on art to the New
York Public Library. She donated 55 pairs of shoes to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. ``It was horrible, a real wrench,'' she
said. But, she added, the hardest thing was to give away the books.
</P>
<P>
   For the new apartment, ``she wanted something feminine, a place
for a tete-a-tete,'' Ms. Lowe recalled. The place is designed to
accommodate small dinners with friends, usually no more than two or
four at a time. When alone, she curls up on one of the beds, turns
on the television and nibbles. ``I don't want to eat at my table
alone,'' she said. (She still throws big parties and openings, but
at the gallery or in restaurants.)
</P>
<P>
   Whimsy abounds. Color and pattern play against type everywhere,
happily colliding. In the living room, the riot begins at ground
level: MacConnel's wild carpet collage, made of dozens of hooked
rugs from flea markets. On the walls are a lot of Hollys _
portraits of Ms. Solomon _ including a famous Warhol that dominates
the room and a portrait by Christo, wrapped in plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to the Warhol, a silk-screen from 1966, Ms.
Solomon reflected: ``It's very hard to age gracefully. No matter
how many times you have your face done, you're still going to age.
You are not young anymore, and who you are shows on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   The room is not devoted to vanity but to her catholic taste. She
has collected and shown artists as diverse as Picasso and Joseph
Kosuth. She embraces painting, sculpture, glass, film, ceramics,
textiles and video. Venetian glass glitters throughout. ``In 1975,
when I went to my first Biennale, it was fashionable to hate
Venetian glass,'' she said. No matter. She has Venetian glass
chandeliers and glass clowns and birds.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny color enlivens a once-dark hallway but doesn't betray the
somber subject: Warhol's 1964 silk-screen of a smiling Jackie
Kennedy in her Dallas pillbox hat hangs near the bedroom door. The
artists striped the bedroom walls in pink and white, allowing the
original dark green to peek through with a deliberate casualness.
The rug is another MacConnel collage: hooked rugs and toilet-seat
covers, like big polka dots.
</P>
<P>
   The guest room, with its plush daybed, makes a fine reading
retreat (though its splashy MacConnel quilt, made of his own
painted cotton and swatches of found Mexican paintings on velvet,
is hardly retiring).
</P>
<P>
   Here, Ms. Solomon feels she is staking a claim to a new
apartment and a new life. ``I'm beginning to know the doorman, and
I can take the bus to Zabar's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she would like to remarry. ``It's rather sad when you have
nice things happen, you don't have someone to share them,'' she
said. ``I want to share the nice things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
