<SLUG> BC-VEGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAT YOUR VEGETABLES _ AND ENJOY THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potatoes and broccoli. Broccoli and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like the usual vegetable offering in your house,
there's a new book that can help. James Peterson's ``Vegetables''
(Morrow, $35) is the perfect assistant for the produce phobic.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson is always encyclopedic in his work (his ``Fish &AMP;
Shellfish'' won a cookbook award a few years back), and his newest
is no exception. Not only does he define Belgian endive, he
explains why it is white and how to separate and core it. Then he
prepares it in dishes like an orange, endive and walnut salad and
an endive and bacon gratin.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vegetables aren't available without a major field
trip (cardoons, fava beans and fiddlehead ferns), but the book is
so exhaustively complete that it hardly matters. The recipes, for
the most part, are straight-ahead creations with precise
instructions and few exotic ingredients. All in all, a solid book
for the cook who is bored with the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   PROVENCAL ZUCCHINI GRATIN WITH TOMATOES AND FRESH MARJORAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as side dish
</P>
<P>
   2 medium zucchini (1 pound), ends cut off
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly chopped fresh marjoram, or 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 medium tomatoes (1 1/2 pounds), peeled
</P>
<P>
   20 fresh basil leaves (finely chopped at the last minute;
optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely grated Parmesan cheese or hard goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Slice zucchini on an angle into 1//8-inch-thick ovals with a
vegetable slicer or by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Crush garlic to a smooth paste with the side of a chef's knife;
combine with the marjoram and 2 tablespoons olive oil in small bowl
and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in half from top to bottom and cut each half into 4
wedges. Push out seeds with your thumb and forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rub bottom of medium baking dish or oval gratin dish with rest
of olive oil. If you are using chopped basil, smear it over the
bottom of the dish. Arrange zucchini in single layer, overlapping
halfway up each slice. Arrange tomato wedges, again in a single
layer over the zucchini. Brush or spoon over chopped marjoram-olive
oil mixture and season lightly with salt (remember the cheese is
salty). Top with grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 1 hour or until there's no liquid left from the
tomatoes and rims of zucchini have browned slightly. Grind some
fresh pepper over it and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 126 calories, 10 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 60
milligrams sodium, 70 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   FUNGHI TRIFOLATI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as main course
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme leaves, or 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds regular cultivated or cremini mushrooms, sliced
paper-thin with vegetable slicer
</P>
<P>
   1 small handful dried porcini mushrooms, quickly rinsed and
soaked in 1/4 cup warm water until soft, about 30 minutes, excess
water squeezed out, chopped coarsely, soaking water reserved
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh or 1 pound dried pasta, such as fettuccine,
linguine or pappardelle (1/2- to 1-inch-wide noodles)
</P>
<P>
   Stir shallots, garlic and thyme in olive oil in wide saute pan
over medium-low heat and saute for 10 minutes _ their aroma should
fill the kitchen _ and then toss in sliced mushrooms. Turn heat up
to high and stew mushrooms until they release their liquid and all
the liquid in the pan evaporates, about 15 minutes. Stir in chopped
porcini mushrooms and carefully pour in their soaking liquid,
leaving any grit behind. Cook for a few minutes more to evaporate
the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   While mushrooms are cooking, bring about 4 quarts of water to a
rapid boil in a large pot.
</P>
<P>
   Stir butter, parsley and cream into the mushrooms and simmer
gently for about 3 minutes, or until sauce thickens slightly.
Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toss pasta into boiling water. Check that the pasta is done by
fishing out a piece with a spoon and biting into it. Fresh pasta
takes a minute or two; dried pasta takes 5-10 minutes. Drain pasta,
return to empty pot, pour mushroom sauce over it and toss quickly.
Season to taste with salt and pepper and serve immediately on wide
hot plates or in pasta bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 636 calories, 20 grams fat, 98
grams carbohydrates, 19 grams protein, 36 milligrams cholesterol,
20 milligrams sodium, 28 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
