</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBILITY23-COX     07-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBILITY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS REPORT SHOWS AMERICANS MOVING SOUTH
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chronicling a migration that foreshadows political
and economic change, the Census Bureau reported Wednesday that
well-educated and affluent Americans are swelling the continuing
population flow into the South.
</P>
<P>
   The South was the only region to record a net gain from internal
migration between March 1996 and March 1997 while the Northeast,
Midwest and West all had net losses, the Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   During that year, about 42 million Americans _ 16 percent of the
populace _ moved, but two-thirds of them stayed within the same
county. About 6.4 million moved to a different state, and about 3.2
million people moved between regions.
</P>
<P>
   The South _ composed of 16 states, including Georgia, Florida,
Texas and North Carolina _ showed a net gain of 391,000 people
moving in from other regions.
</P>
<P>
   The impact goes beyond raw numbers, though, to the type of folks
moving into Dixie. The influx, made up 90 percent of whites, is
making the region better-educated and more affluent _ and likely
will continue turning it more Republican.
</P>
<P>
   These ``upwardly mobile'' newcomers ``have generally helped the
Republican Party'' as they mostly settled into the suburbs, said
Merle Black, a political science professor at Emory University in
Atlanta and an expert on Southern politics.
</P>
<P>
   The migration means the region is likely to pick up additional
seats in the House of Representatives after the reapportionment of
2000, said Black. For instance, Georgia is projected to add one or
two seats _ probably in the Atlanta suburbs or fast-growing
northern counties, he said. Both areas increasingly vote
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is likely to show the greatest Republican gains as
districts are redrawn _ mainly because the GOP is currently
under-represented in the apportionment, said Black. At the start of
this decade, Democrats drew the lines to pack as many Republicans
into as few districts as possible, he said, giving the GOP some
extremely safe seats but minimizing their overall power.
</P>
<P>
   With a Republican governor and greater GOP legislative strength,
Black predicted, the Texas congressional districts will be redrawn
to more accurately reflect the party's strength in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The migratory patterns may also boost the Southern economy by
raising the region's educational level. For instance, the region
showed a net gain of about 30,000 people with graduate or
professional degrees during the measured year, and a net gain of
29,000 with bachelor's degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In this high-tech era, a ``brain gain'' or a ``brain drain'' has
a profound economic effect on a region, said Louis Tornatzky,
director of the Southern Technology Council, a division of the
Southern Growth Policies Board in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a period of years, a state can either accrue human
resources or lose them,'' Tornatzky explained. ``Smart people are
the key to our new economy,'' based on information-age industries.
</P>
<P>
   State policies can affect this migration of highly sought minds,
he said, citing the Georgia's Hope Scholarship program begun by
Gov. Zell Miller. By providing tuition for good students in state
colleges, Tornatsky said, Georgia is trying to keep the state's
talented youth from straying. ``If kids stay in the state after
high school to go to college,'' they're more likely to remain as
adult residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Migration patterns have also given the South a financial boost.
The median income for the newcomers was $17,400, while the median
income for the people who left the region was $15,117, the Census
Bureau reported. In contrast, the median income for people moving
into the Northeast was $16,965 _ nearly $2,000 less than the
$18,533 median income for the people moving out of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The South showed a net gain of people of all ages except over
75, where the number of immigrants and out-migrants was the same.
About half the net gain _ 183,000 people _ came in newcomers
between the ages of 30 and 64. Belying the reputation as a
retirement haven, there was a net gain of only 13,000 people aged
65 and older. That compares to a net gain of 110,000 people younger
than 25.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the highest moving rates were found among young
adults, as nearly 32 percent of people aged 20 to 29 years old
relocated during the year. Moving rates declined as age increased,
with moves by only 4.7 percent of the people aged 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a nationwide shift toward the suburbs, with
central cities losing 3 million people to migration and suburbs
gaining 2.8 million. However, 92 percent of the 1.3 million people
who moved to the United States from abroad settled in metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Whites had lower overall moving rates (15.3 percent) than either
African-Americans or Hispanic Americans, both of whom had moving
rates of about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
