<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A LOCK ON JAIL-HOUSE CHILI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our search for a jail-house recipe turned up several interesting
stories.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable _ and probably most reliable _ tale was written
by Frank X. Tolbert in his classic ``A Bowl of Red.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the arrival of the 1890s, chili con carne had become a
standard entree in most jails in the Southwest. Jail-house cooks
learned the same lesson as did the pioneer chili makers, that chili
peppers could work wonders with inferior grades of beef.''
</P>
<P>
   A Mrs. Clarence A. Mass of Dallas sent Tolbert a recipe for
jail-house chili, which he published in his newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I heard from Smoot Schmid, a former Dallas County
sheriff: `That's just my jail chili. In the old days, the jailbirds
rated my chili the best served behind bars.'''
</P>
<P>
   Readers were quick to respond to our request for jail-house
chili recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipe was sent in by Joan Hallford of North Richland
Hills, Texas. She clipped this recipe from the October 1990 issue
of [ix]Chile Pepper[nm] magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe definitely shows that it is at least 50 years old.
For one thing, suet is rarely found at meat counters these days. (I
asked the butcher at my local Winn-Dixie; he had some in the back.
He ground it, packaged it and gave it to me (at no cost), but I
could see he was wondering why someone would want a half-pound of
beef fat.
</P>
<P>
   In testing the recipe, I opted to use the stove instead of the
smoker. I cooked the meat and spices for one hour, added the water
and cooked for another hour. I would also suggest making a paste of
flour and some of the chili drippings and stirring it into the
chili to thicken it.
</P>
<P>
   A word of warning. Because of the suet, there is a
not-so-healthful layer of orange liquid on the top of the chili. If
you refrigerate the chili overnight, that liquid congeals and can
be scraped off.
</P>
<P>
   The sight was a touch off-putting to me, but my husband, the
Texan, took one taste and said, ``This is what chili tasted like
when I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS COUNTY JAIL CHILI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound beef suet, ground
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds coarsely ground beef
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground dried sweet chile pods (ancho, for
example)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Fry suet in a heavy kettle. Add meat, garlic and seasonings.
Cook for four hours, placing pot in a medium-hot portion of your
smoker, stirring occasionally. Add water and continue cooking for
another hour, or until chili has thickened to desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 632 calories, 53 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 35 grams protein, 135 milligrams cholesterol,
1,307 milligrams sodium, 75 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   And more chili: Evelyn Kellum of Irving, Texas, says she clipped
this recipe from The Dallas Morning News in the 1950s. This one is
a little updated _ substituting olive oil for the suet. Again,
we're talking some heavyweight chili.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS JAIL-HOUSE CHILI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds coarsely ground beef
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Heat olive oil. Add meat, garlic and seasonings, cover. Cook
slowly for 4 hours, stirring occasionally. Add water; continue
cooking until slightly thickened, about 1 hour. Serve plain or
mixed with equal portions of cooked dried pink or red beans. A
little flour and water blended together may be added to make the
chili a little thicker.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 498 calories, 39 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 33 grams protein, 115 milligrams cholesterol,
733 milligrams sodium, 71 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   And one more: Billie Wood of Fort Worth, sends yet another
version, which she clipped from a magazine about 20 years ago. The
magazine writes, ``Legend has it that the Texas prison system made
such good chili, freed inmates often wrote for the recipe.'' And,
no, I need no letters from readers regarding the beans. Thank you
for your consideration.
</P>
<P>
   JAIL-HOUSE CHILI
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dry red kidney or pinto beans, picked over, washed and
drained
</P>
<P>
   8 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   2 (28 ounces each) cans tomatoes, undrained
</P>
<P>
   4-ounce can chopped green chiles
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce can tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes: Chopped onion, shredded Cheddar cheese, red pepper
flakes, fresh chopped green chiles, vinegar, corn chips
</P>
<P>
   Wash beans, drain and place in large sauce pot. For quick-soak
methods, combine beans and water; bring to a boil. Boil 2 minutes.
Remove from heat. Cover and let stand 1 hour (or cover with water
and soak overnight).
</P>
<P>
   Then add 1 teaspoon salt and simmer 1 hour in soaking liquid or
until beans are almost tender. Drain and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Dutch oven, heat oil. Add onions and saute until
tender. Add ground beef and cook until browned, breaking up pieces
with a spoon. Spoon off fat. Add remaining ingredients and beans.
Heat to boiling. Reduce heat; simmer, uncovered for 2 hours,
stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   This can be prepared in advance. Cover and refrigerate up to 24
hours. Or, to freeze, spoon into freezer-proof containers; freeze
up to 2 months. If frozen, thaw in refrigerator overnight. Cook
over low heat, stirring occasionally about 30 to 40 minutes until
heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis for one cup: 349 calories, 13 grams fat, 33
grams carbohydrates, 28 grams protein, 57 milligrams cholesterol,
1,007 milligrams sodium, 34 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Yoder of Arlington, Texas, would like a recipe for
almond-poppy seed muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Manett Fann, somewhere in cyberland, is looking for the recipe
for Underwood's BBQ potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   Al Reinarz of Fort Worth, remembers clipping a recipe from the
Star-Telegram for a low-fat ratatouille that includes pine nuts. A
search through our electronic library didn't turn up the recipe.
Does someone have it?
</P>
<P>
   Bertha McAfee of Fort Worth, would like a recipe for
gingersnaps. The one she wants is from a sugar booklet, either from
Domino or Imperial. She thinks it was on Page 42.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Capriotti of Arlington would like the recipe for orange
blossom muffins. The recipe includes orange marmalade, orange
juice, Bisquick or baking mix, vegetable oil and egg. The recipe
was popular at the Peninsula Hotel in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   A reader is trying to track down a recipe for her daughter. It's
a Prince Regent cake, a white cake with raspberries between the
layers and a chocolate icing. She thinks this recipe appeared in
``Bon Appetit'' many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I checked the magazine Web site (www.epicurious.com), which
catalogs 7,600 recipes. Unfortunately, most of them are from the
1990s. Does anyone have an old-fashioned copy of the magazine that
includes the recipe?
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
