<HEADER>
A7635 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ART-CDROM-2TAKES-     07-22 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ART-CDROM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Va., Calif., N.Y.)  
 ART LOVERS COOL TO LURES OF CD-ROMs  
 (af)  
 By LEE ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever happened to art CD-ROMs, those virtual, interactive
museums that were supposed to take the great works of art off
pedestals and gallery walls and place them on our computer screens?
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, after the release of pioneering efforts like
the 1993 Microsoft Art Gallery, drawn from the collection of
London's National Gallery, and the 1995 Passion for Art, featuring
the Barnes Collection, that curators and museum directors worried
that gallery attendance would plummet as art lovers clicked through
images of their favorite Cezannes and Rembrandts at home.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 18 months, the museum-on-a-disk market has
collapsed, plagued by low sales and high costs. The best-selling
art CD-ROM last year, for example, volume one of Zane Interactive
Publishing's educational software, Power CD History Through Art,
sold only about 8,500 copies in retail chains, according to figures
compiled by PC Data, a Reston, Va., research company.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast Passion for Art sold about 12,300 copies in just the
first four months after its 1995 release, and Riven, the sequel to
the popular computer game Myst, introduced last October, sold about
915,400 copies in its first three months, PC Data said.
</P>
<P>
   Muscled aside by such flashy games and also by mundane
personal-productivity software, art CD-ROMs have experienced a
major shake-out among producers. Companies like the Corbis Corp.
(the producer of Passion), Grolier Interactive (Picasso: The Man,
His Works, the Legend), Macmillan Digital (150 Years of America's
Smithsonian) and Voyager (The Beat Experience) have got out of the
business, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art CDs are very difficult to sell,'' said Robb Lazarus,
director of electronic publishing for the Digital Arts and Sciences
company. ``They're a niche product and distributors are just not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus' company, based in Alameda, Calif., abandoned art after
producing disks for, among others, the Frick Collection, the
Brooklyn Museum, the State Russian Museum and the Harvard
University Art Museums.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Steve Davis, co-president of Corbis, which abruptly
pulled the plug on its Ansel Adams disk last year, observed that
``the CD-ROM market has not been very robust, with the exception of
kill-'em-up games.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is hardly surprising that this fall's debut of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art CD-ROM: Masterworks From the Collection
_ delayed for two years _ is eagerly anticipated by those who still
believe in the potential of art on disk. Not only does the new disk
represent an important cultural event but it may also be the last
chance to breathe life into a dying genre.
</P>
<P>
   If any new art CD-ROM could be said to enjoy a reasonable shot
at commercial success, it would be the Met's, given its electronic
presentation of 257 works from all areas of the museum's collection
and its association with one of the most burnished brand names in
the art world.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by the Met's in-house educational staff, this new
general-audience electronic catalog was modeled on the museum's
popular coffee-table compendium, ``Masterpieces of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art,'' according to Kent Lydecker, the disk's executive
producer and the Met's associate director for education.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of committing the Met's masterpieces to disk was about
$500,000, he said. The Met is also preparing an educational guide
to the disk for classrooms and some of the material from the CD-ROM
will appear on the museum's Web site (www.metmuseum.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of these electronic tools as extensions of the
museum's capabilities,'' Lydecker said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the forecast for art CD-ROMs depends on the Met's
prospects, the outlook remains iffy. An advance look at the disk
revealed a staid electronic catalog that has settled for the
technologically tame when it could have been as vibrant and
arresting as the museum's collections.
</P>
<P>
   The approach to art history on the Met disk is serious to a
fault, and makes scant use of the audio and visual
bells-and-whistles that make multimedia enticing. What's more, it
does not fully exploit the unique ability of CDs to store huge
amounts of information that can be sorted and linked in complex
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Even the disk's best feature _ an appealing, insightful tour by
museum director Philippe de Montebello _ is almost bereft of
multimedia embellishment. A more inventive disk might have
highlighted, magnified or outlined areas on the canvas that best
exemplify what de Montebello describes. When the director says,
``We can feel the wind, hear the flags flapping, smell the sea
air'' while viewing Monet's ``Garden at Sainte-Adresse,'' some
producers might have heard their cue for appropriate sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
