<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ART-CDROM-2NDTAKE     07-22 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ART-CDROM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: sound effects.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teresa Russo, an educator at the museum and one of the disk's
producers, said the museum resisted ``making an art work do
something that it doesn't do in a museum, such as orchestrating or
animating it.'' The use of multimedia was also curtailed by cost
and by the technological limits of the museum's staff. ``We're not
Microsoft,'' Ms. Russo said. ``We bring our expertise in the
subject area, not technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of technological expertise has hurt other art CD-ROMs,
according to Elizabeth Broun, director of the National Museum of
American Art in Washington. Disappointing sales, she said, reflect
their disappointing performance on home computers. ``Many were put
together fast and dirty to republish the material from a book in a
new format,'' she said. ``People were trying to do multimedia on
the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   The NMAAs own 1996 CD-ROM exemplifies the opposite approach.
National Museum of America Art, Smithsonian Institution ranks as
probably the most intelligently engaging and technologically savvy
cybergallery installed on anyone's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The disk presents in-depth explorations of more than 760
objects, full texts of six museum catalogs, nearly two hours of
video, audio and slide shows, detailed written entries from a
variety of distinguished scholars, critics and historical sources,
not to mention the considerable charm of Ms. Broun, who conducts an
hour-long multimedia tour of the museum, focusing on 14 of her
personal favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The disk allows easy access to all of the audio and video treats
through a Media Center menu on the Galleries screen. ``If you want
to just lick the ice cream, you don't have to stumble on it
accidentally after you eat your spinach,'' Ms. Broun quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Met's upcoming title, which presents anonymously
written, relatively brief entries for most objects, NMAA's text
draws upon published commentary from a wide variety of experts _
sometimes several different authorities for a single object.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of offering a standard run-through of the history and
subject matter of Edward Hopper's ``Cape Cod Morning,'' critic
Brian O'Doherty, excerpted from Art in America magazine, finds the
work's essence in Hopper's ``power of concentration (that) makes
the absence an event'' and in his ``great power to hold one through
the sheer curiosity felt before such laconic indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``laconic indifference'' also describes NMAA's
commercial reception, which was hampered by inadequate funds for
marketing and distribution. Ms. Broun acknowledged that the NMAA
CD-ROM, whose $600,000 cost nearly tripled initial projections, has
not recouped its costs in the year and a half since it was
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, there are still those who insist that the
art CD-ROM can survive, even flourish. Some 42 of Voyager's titles
were recently acquired by the three-year-old New York-based Learn
Technologies Interactive, whose president, Luyen Chou, still
believes that art disks can succeed through improved cost-control
and a more aggressive sales strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death of the art CD-ROM is greatly exaggerated,'' said
Nina Tovich, senior producer and creative director of NMAA's disk,
who recently left the museum to form Lucid Design, her own
Washington-based multimedia development company.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that producers look to the techniques of game
designers to revive the form. Successful titles must present ``a
point of view, a perspective,'' she said. ``People don't want to be
just dumped into a bunch of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be able to shape the material themselves, or have
it shaped by someone who knows what he's doing,'' she continued.
``They also want a well-designed, beautiful environment. There is
something to be learned from interactive games, which provide
immersive environments that get your undivided attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Met itself recently surrendered to the gaming craze,
although not quite in the way Ms. Tovich suggested. The museum
recently allowed a commercial software publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster
Interactive, to include 17 objects from the Met's famed Egyptian
collection as plot elements in the recently released three-disk
Nile: An Ancient Egyptian Quest. (Players must collect the objects
to rescue the pharaohs.) The museum received a fee for the images
and will also get a percentage of sales.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to the Met, which prepared a teacher's guide for
the game, the Nile game includes a section with brief descriptions
of the 17 objects, for gamers who thirst for art-historical
knowledge. Maybe the future consumers for art on CD-ROMs aren't the
gallery-hoppers but the kids with joysticks.
</P>
</TEXT>
