<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Van Fleet's Roses
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I was growing up in western Maryland, my grandmother had
a rosebush that she called a Van Fleet rose. I thought she was
kidding because my last name is VanFleet. Can you tell me anything
about it?
</P>
<P>
   A. You should always pay attention to grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Your grandmother's rose may have been Dr. W. Van Fleet, named
for Dr. Walter Van Fleet in 1910 by Peter Henderson, whose nursery
introduced it. Van Fleet (1857-1922) was one of the world's most
important hybridizers of climbing roses, breeding classics like
American Pillar and Silver Moon. He worked for the United States
Agriculture Department, in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Van Fleet wanted to name it Daybreak, but Henderson insisted
that the delicate shell-pink rose honor the man who really invented
``dooryard roses,'' vigorous climbing roses that are tough and
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Or your grandmother's rose might have been Sarah Van Fleet, a
medium pink hybrid rugosa rose named for Van Fleet's wife and
introduced after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Both Van Fleet namesakes are still popular, but neither is as
well known as New Dawn, a sport of Dr. W. Van Fleet, introduced in
1930. A sport is a mutation that causes a single branch of a plant
to look or behave differently from the rest. Discovered years after
Van Fleet's death, New Dawn has all the wonderful properties of Dr.
W. Van Fleet, but it also repeat-blooms. New Dawn was granted the
first U.S. plant patent, so even if you don't use a space in your
name, you may want to check the family tree in your old Bible and
bask in a little horticultural glory.
</P>
<P>
   Variable Beets
</P>
<P>
   Q. My organically grown beets far surpass fresh beets at the
supermarket. The problem is that a limited number mature in the
accepted globe shape, with about 10 to 20 percent of the root above
ground. The remainder grow almost totally above ground and are
cylindrically shaped.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can blame it on the grower or on the seed company, but
either way it isn't your fault (or the beet's).
</P>
<P>
   It is probable that your beet is an open-pollinated variety, one
that is pollinated randomly, rather than a hybrid, where the choice
of parents is controlled by the grower. With open pollination, some
genetic diversity always shows up. If the field of globe-shaped
beets is within 3,000 feet of a field of cylindrical ones,
cross-fertilization can occur. As with humans, some offspring will
resemble Mom, others will look like Dad.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is rare, but a packaging mix-up can happen
as seed companies turn millions of seeds from thousands of
vegetable and flower varieties into small packages. When you think
of the number of seeds involved every year, how small they are and
how similar many of them appear, the odds are against perfection.
</P>
<P>
   You may prefer the look of globe-shaped pickled beets in a glass
jar, but I'll bet the cylindrical ones are tasty, too, and easier
to cut into uniform slices.
</P>
<P>
   Slime Mold
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently, my husband and I put a fine layer of mulch on our
flower bed. A few hours later a yellowish mold started to appear.
It almost looks as though it has a meringue consistency. I shoveled
it off, but the next day it started again in another spot in the
bed. What could it be?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's slime mold. It's one of the most perfectly named
uninvited garden visitors, and each yellow or orange mass is a
single cell, slowly flowing across a wet area, engulfing bacteria
and other microbes. If you had let it alone, you could have watched
it glide along, moving as far as two feet in 12 hours. Clearly you
had better things to do that day, and your approach, scooping it up
with a shovel, was the best you could do.
</P>
<P>
   The slime came in with the mulch, and it loves hot, humid
weather. It will disappear when the mulch dries out or when the
mold has eaten all that is available in it. In the meantime, slime
mold does not harm the plants on which it grows, and it poses no
threat to people, except perhaps for causing a faint level of
disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn-Mowing Dangers
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that if the lawn-mower blades are not sharp,
they will tear the grass top and make it vulnerable to disease,
because the open edges are rough and fungus can enter. Is this
true?
</P>
<P>
   A. Mowing a lawn is not exactly like giving a haircut. Cutting
living tissue is stressful under the best conditions, but using a
dull blade adds insult to injury, especially on a rotary mower,
which cuts by brute force, whacking instead of scissoring neatly
like a reel mower.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't just the direct ability of disease organisms
to enter the wound, although that plays a part. Even with a sharp
blade, the loss of leaf surface means reduced photosynthesis and
reduced ability to take up water. These stresses make the plant
weaker and less able to fight off diseases, and slow down root
growth. When the cut is ragged and torn, the increased surface area
open to the air means 10 to 15 percent additional water loss
through evaporation and a longer time to heal. Diseases find it
easier to enter a host with weakened defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to make it even harder on your grass? Mow when the
grass is still wet. Not only are fungal populations higher when it
is damp or humid, but the water on the grass also impedes the
lawn-mower blade, leading to a poorer quality cut. Again, rotary
mowers are bigger offenders than reel mowers under these
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting grass right also means cutting it the right height.
While grass may prefer never to be cut, and we may prefer that
golf-course-greens look, the best compromise for a healthy,
good-looking lawn is to cut it two and a half to three inches high
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
