<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Unleashed: The Wit and Wisdom of Calvin the Dog''
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Chris Glaser
</P>
<P>
   Westminster John Knox Press, $12
</P>
<P>
   If you thought theology was going to the ... no, I won't say it.
It's too easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole truth of life is more than any one dog can chew,''
says Calvin, the Georgia canine author of ``Unleashed.'' What
follows is a collection of musings on everything from church
services (''The best part ... is when they walk around and pet each
other, passing the treat of God'') to parasites (''I have often
wondered why a good God would allow or ordain the existence of
fleas'').
</P>
<P>
   Calvin's thoughts are rather whimsical, as are translator Chris
Glaser's notes on the linguistic oddities of Canine. On the other
hand, orthodoxy and orthodogsy are not always the same thing,
particularly when the source of the ... er ... dogma has a peculiar
predilection for Zen and thinks that ``God is in the tree as much
as in any human creature.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should leave theology to humans. It may be too ruff
for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Surfonic Water Revival: New Surf Music for the Redeemed
Masses''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   KMG Records
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the summer heat wave comes one of the coolest
albums of the year: surf music. In the late 1990s. With Christian
lyrics. Far out.
</P>
<P>
   The album is a tribute to all kinds of surf music, from the
early instrumentals to the later rich orchestrations of the Beach
Boys classic Pet Sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The songs are performed by some of the hottest alternative and
modern rock singers and bands in Christian music, such as Rebecca
St. James, All Star United, Skillet, Smalltown Poets, PlankEye, The
Insyderz and The O.C. Supertones, as well as veterans Phil Keaggy,
Daniel Amos and Paul Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The album is the brainchild of veteran producer Terry Scott
Taylor, who grew up in sunny Southern California listening to surf
music that celebrated perfect waves, fast cars and beautiful,
suntanned girls. But Taylor also heard a subtle celebration of
God's creation.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing subtle about the lyrics here, most of them
penned by Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Wave Perfect,'' written by Taylor and performed by
Smalltown Poets. ``Don't have to look too far/The point of our
devotion/Praise God/Wave perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The music makes this one of the coolest albums of the year. The
lyrics make it more than that.
</P>
<P>
   As they might have said in the '60s, it's righteous, man.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
