<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7690 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LOVE-CALCULATOR-N     07-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LOVE-CALCULATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIALS ON A TREE, WEB STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word PLUS within parentheses has been
used throughout the article instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(af) 
 By KATIE HAFNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watson and Crick have nothing on Smit and Kinkhorst when it
comes to unraveling the mysteries of life.
</P>
<P>
   Smit and Kinkhorst?
</P>
<P>
   Matthijs Sypkens Smit and Thijs Kinkhorst are two men from
Utrecht, Holland, whose Love Calculator on the World Wide Web
(www.lovecalculator.com) brings a bizarre _ some might say
completely perverse _ mathematical rigor to matters of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Simply type in two names, and after a brief calculation, up pops
a percentage, indicating a couple's chances for romantic success.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you doubt the reliability of the Love Calculator, consider
the evidence: Bruce Willis and Demi Moore: 45 percent. Woody Allen
and Mia Farrow: 38 percent. Allen and Soon-Yi Previn? 79 percent.
Romeo and Juliet: 98 percent (Remember: The Love Calculator
measures compatibility. Fate does not compute.) Are Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman really that happy together? According to Dr. Love _
they scored 99 percent _ they are.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not infallible. Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton
scored a predictable 18 percent. But Liz Taylor and Richard Burton:
82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Smit and Kinkhorst, who together are Dr. Love on their Web site,
offer somber words with each calculation, like this: ``Dr. Love
thinks that a relationship between Tristan and Isolde has a
reasonable chance of working out, but on the other hand, it might
not. Your relationship may suffer good and bad times. If things
might not be working out as you would like them to, do not hesitate
to talk about it with the person involved. Spend time together,
talk with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, then, Smit and Kinkhorst rely on years of accumulated
wisdom. Or do they? Now 18 years old, the two computer science
students were both 16 when they first put the Love Calculator on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, wisdom plays no role in Dr. Love's prognoses. It's all
arithmetic. The calculator uses an algorithm familiar to
elementary-school children and math teachers around the world. It
starts by looking for the number of times the letters L, O, V, E
and S occur in the two names; then, through a series of addition
sequences, it produces the percentage. For example: Bill Clinton
and Hillary Rodham. L: 5, O: 2, V: 0, E: 0, S: 0.
</P>
<P>
   Write those numbers down and you get 52000. Then add up the
individual numbers _ 5(plus)2, 2(plus)0, 0(plus)0, 0(plus)0 _ and
you get 7200. Keep doing the same addition of individual numbers
for each sum.
</P>
<P>
   If you add the numerals in 7200 in the same way, you get 920
(7(plus)2, 2(plus)0, 0(plus)0). Do the addition on 920 (9(plus)2,
2(plus)0) and the result is 112. Once again with 112 (1(plus)1,
2(plus)1), and you get down to two numerals, which gives you the
chance of a successful relationship: 23 percent. The system makes
perfect sense, to a third-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Smit said the Web site had received about 2.5 million hits since
it first went up. He and Kinkhorst have received e-mail from around
the world, thanking them for the service they have done for romance
in the late 20th century. Wrote a grateful calculatee from Brazil:
``I have put my name and my first wife's and I have gotten 0
percent; the incredible thing is: we got divorced 15 years ago! On
the other hand I got 97 percent with my second wife, and we have
been together for 12 years!''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote another: ``On the eve of our fourth date (the day before
Valentine's Day), a friend called me to tell me that she had
entered my name and my date's in the love calculator _ we got 97
percent. Strangely enough, we fell madly in love and are now
engaged to be married. Are we your first Love Calculator wedding?''
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled visitors, Smit said, also send e-mail. ``When people
get a low score and react to it, they most often use offensive
language or say it's all a big fake,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
