<HEADLINE>
ANNAN URGES RENEWAL OF PEACE TALKS IN MEXICO'S CHIAPAS STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The United Nations cannot intervene to help
resolve conflicts in Mexico's southern state of Chiapas, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated calls for such intervention by many human
rights organizations here and abroad, the world body has no role to
play, unless specifically asked by the Mexican government, Annan
told reporters after meeting with President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations does not get involved in the internal
affairs of a country without a request from its government, and
there has been no request,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Without referring to the Zapatista insurgent group by name, he
urged the rebel leaders to meet with Zedillo's government to forge
a durable peace in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any situation like this, I would urge the other side to
work with sustained and consistent effort with the government to
find a solution,'' the secretary-general said. ``I would also urge
that we all do what we can to encourage process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas led a brief but bloody rebellion in January 1994,
demanding rights and greater democracy for impoverished Indians in
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   While government and Zapatista negotiators reached a tentative
peace agreement two years ago, the accord was never implemented and
tensions have erupted into periodic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The state police and Mexican soldiers have clashed with
Zapatista civilian supporters in raids on several municipalities
since January. In June, the police and soldiers engaged armed
Zapatista militiamen in an encounter that killed 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   In December, 45 Zapatista sympathizers were massacred at a
church by paramilitary forces with ties to the state government.
</P>
<P>
   And in another blow to peace, Roman Catholic Bishop Samuel Ruiz
last month abandoned efforts to get government negotiators together
with Zapatista rebels, saying that the Zedillo government's peace
efforts were a sham.
</P>
<P>
   Annan urged all parties to pursue peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chiapas is a complex issue; it is important not to lose
heart,'' he said. ``Four years seems like a long time, but we must
find ways to work through the complexities to a peaceful
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan arrived here Tuesday on a three-day visit, the last leg of
a Latin American tour that also included Argentina, Brazil,
Guatemala and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   He said Latin American nations have made ``tremendous strides''
economically and politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continent has made a lot of progress. Today, almost every
government is democratically elected, and most have gone through
economic reforms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can improve with further development so that the poor and
needy also participate in the advances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
