<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PASSION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PASSION' DRIVEN BY LOVE OF A LEOPARD
</HEADLINE>
 IN THE DESERT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a little disconcerting to step from the unrelenting Texas
heat into a movie set in an unrelenting desert. But you'll find
yourself transported by ``Passion in the Desert,'' the latest
Honore de Balzac story to be translated to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Director Lavinia Currier's adaptation of Balzac's novella ``Une
Passion dans la Desert'' has so much unforgettable imagery that her
gift suggests an instinct for filmmaking that's precerebral, like
that of George Miller or Jane Campion. Currier creates a singular
visual context for Balzac's material, which sounds difficult on the
face of it. The huge dollops of romanticism and absurdity on the
page can translate into mere silliness on the screen. But Currier
gives in to the lushness of Balzac and adds an element of
dreaminess to ``Passion.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a story about man's vanity _ as is much of Balzac _ and his
equally vain attempts to impose order on the wilderness. (The story
is also said to have grown from Balzac's insinuation that a famous
Parisian lion tamer's animal training technique came from a unique
relationship with his cat.) In ``Passion,'' Augustin (Ben Daniels),
a proud Napoleonic officer, is determined to prove that Egypt can
be tamed. In his rigidly logical mind, the desert can be handled.
</P>
<P>
   But after a vicious battle with a warrior clan and a sandstorm,
Augustin and Jean-Michel (Michel Piccoli), an artist who is
documenting the regiment's progress, are stranded. One of the most
oddly poignant moments in recent films comes when the formal
Augustin, clad in his heavy wool uniform, marches through the
desert with an umbrella over his head. Jean-Michel, his lips
stained from the paints he drank to keep from dehydrating, shambles
next to Augustin.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, only Augustin is left. After fleeing Bedouins (he
snatches the veil off a Bedouin woman's face in a scene that
Currier gives the force of rape), Augustin hides out in a cave
where he encounters a leopard. ``Passion'' then becomes both dreamy
and naturalistic, as Augustin falls deeply into the world of the
cat he names Simoom. Akela, the cat who plays Simoom, is runty and
stubborn-looking, a little less regal than the leopards who
regularly snack on slower prey on the Discovery Channel. (Not the
``delightful coquette'' Blazac wrote about.) But she is
distinctive, and willingly submits to Augustin's languorous licking
of her coat.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is entrancing because of Akela's appeal and Daniels'
recklessness. We actually do see a relationship develop between man
and leopard, because he is clearly in the same shot with her much
of the time; this isn't ``Bringing Up Baby.'' We see the foppish
superiority beaten out of Daniels. But even though he surrenders
the movie to the leopard _ in any shot, our eyes go immediately to
her _ he is a generous actor. (On the other hand, it's gotta be
hard to upstage a jungle cat.) Yes, the movie does get a little
foolish. But it shows a bravery and a lust for visual clarity
that's impressive. One thing's for sure; there aren't many other
movies around in which an 18th-century military man falls in love
with a leopard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion in the Desert'' is rated PG-13 for brief nudity,
violence and suggestions of unusual sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Movie: ``Passion in the Desert''
</P>
<P>
   Score: 2 1/2 on a scale of 1 to 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Lavinia Currier
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Ben Daniels, Michel Piccoli
</P>
<P>
   Length: 93 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
