<HEADER>
A7734 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEARABLE-COMPUTER     07-22 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEARABLE-COMPUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LABS, WEARABLE COMPUTERS ARE BECOMING A REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wearable computers have long been a staple of science fiction.
But the wearable computers that were the darlings of magazine
covers in the early '90s _ bulky, underpowered strap-ons with
cyborg styling _ have practically been pariahs in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   That may change, many analysts and academics say, with the
emergence of a new class of wearable computers that are faster,
lighter and smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Xybernaut, IBM and Micro Optical are paving the
way for computers that will literally go straight to people's
heads, displaying all their data on head-mounted monitors, some so
tiny that they could double as ordinary eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Xybernaut Mobile Assistant 4, presented last month
at the PC Expo in New York. Weighing less than two pounds, the MA4,
as its engineers like to call it, is designed to be worn on a
person's belt (along with a four-to-six-hour battery pack). The
Mobile Assistant packs a 266-megahertz processor and a 4-gigabyte
hard drive, says its maker, the Xybernaut Corp. in Fairfax, Va. It
also responds to voice commands and links to a 10-ounce, full-color
head-mounted display.
</P>
<P>
   The Mobile Assistant is a fully functional computer that uses
voice commands, requires neither a desktop nor lap and doesn't need
hands (a wrist-mounted minikeyboard is optional) to operate, said
Carol Covin, the director of marketing for Xybernaut. Her son,
David Covin Jr., a Web programmer, wore a Mobile Assistant on a
1,300-mile, five-month trek along the Appalachian Trail last year.
Using the computer, he communicated with the rest of the wired
world through E-mail and kept an on-line journal, giving a glimpse
of what wearable computers can do.
</P>
<P>
   The applications are almost endless for wearable computers, Ms.
Covin said, especially for people who need easy access in the field
to vast amounts of text, schematics and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about a trouble-shooter roaming the factory floor,'' she
said. ``They used to have to go back to a central site. Now they
access information wherever they are, calling up technical manuals
with this technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Stern, a spokesman for the Chicago Transit Authority, said
Xybernaut's wearable computers were being studied for use by the
authority's inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have literally gone into the deep end with
wearables: The Australian Institute of Marine Science sells a Wet
PC, a wearable computer that can be used underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Work at the Micro Optical Corp. in Boston has attracted the
attention of the military (the United States Army Soldier Systems
Command was a major financial contributor to the development of the
special eye-glasses), as well as industry.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers there have developed functional mock-ups of
eyeglasses that can electronically display computer data through
one or both of the eyeglass lenses. The image is actually a virtual
display, said Paul M. Zavracky, president and chief executive of
the company; it appears to be about 20 inches in front of the
wearer and to be about a quarter the size of a standard computer
screen. The glasses can be used with wearable as well as more
conventional computers, Zavracky said. The hardware that turns the
glasses into monitors does so without adding ``significant'' weight
to them, he said. When the glasses are turned off, they revert to
being simple eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Bitten by the bug to wear a computer, Ted Selker, a technologist
and IBM Fellow, recently created a flexible, two-pound version of
an IBM Think Pad 760 notebook computer. The prototype can be worn
on the belt and fits into the small of a person's back, conforming
to body shape.
</P>
<P>
   Selker was able to shrink much of a notebook computer, making it
a wearable one, by removing its battery, floppy drive and disk. He
created a stand-alone battery that can also be worn on a belt. He
replaced the hard drive with a much smaller PCMCIA hard disk. Its
monitor is mounted on the head, and a small keyboard hangs from a
belt.
</P>
<P>
   Wearable computers are not likely to hit the consumer market any
time soon and may take awhile to be adopted in industrial settings.
But industrial uses are expected to take off once more systems
become available and more managers realize the range of what they
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearable computers will remain a curiosity for the next three
years,'' said a research note issued in March by the Gartner Group,
a technology information and consulting company based in Stamford,
Conn. ``By 2006 it will have grown to become a mainstream technique
for maintenance, inspection, warehousing and other mobile
industrial applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rhinelander, an analyst for Forrester Research in Boston,
many people were already wearing computers every day without giving
them much thought. People are wearing on their belts and in their
pockets millions of Palm Pilots and similar devices, cellular
phones, pagers and compact disk players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Packing a Palm Pilot on your hip is no big deal,'' he said.
``But when you start blending the computer into your person, making
it an extension of your attire, people start to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people resist the idea, Rhinelander said, because it feels
like ``an encroachment of technology.'' Plus, he said, many people
still have a fair degree of suspicion and fear about computers.
``If you are wearing a computer, people want to know if it is
recording their information, if it is being used against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Picard, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Media Laboratory, said a great deal of research was
being done on making wearable computers more comfortable, making
them conform to human needs rather than forcing humans to conform
to computers' needs. Merely making these computers smaller is not
necessarily the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep making computers smaller, to the point where you can
almost inhale them,'' she said with a chuckle. ``But that is not
solving some of the hard problems that we have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Much work remains on ``getting the data in and out in a form
that is understandable for people and effortless for people,''
Picard added. For example, she said, ``someone might be happy to
wear a funny hat'' _ a computer monitor _ ``on their heads when
they play with their children, but not when they are meeting with a
potential customer. People might want different kinds of wearable
computers that are more appropriate for various uses.''
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, where annual symposiums on the technology have been held
for years, Picard said work was being done on wearable computers
that would run continuously, performing a broad range of day-to-day
functions. Imagine, she said, a wearable computer that runs a video
camera that is always on and focused on whatever the person wearing
it looks at. Such a device could make never-miss-a-shot home movies
or record a professor's lecture for a student who had the bad luck
to doze off in the lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   And remember Zavracky's eyeglass monitors?
</P>
<P>
   He said he could easily envision his Micro Optical eyeglasses
linked to new mobile computers that would permit business travelers
to work away on crowded airplanes in serene security.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it's going,'' Zavracky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
