<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WRITING-SOFTWARE-     07-22 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WRITING-SOFTWARE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMMAR AID FOR THOSE WHO/WHOM NEED IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (plus) word should be replaced with symbol)  
 (af)  
 Steven R. Knowlton is an associate professor of journalism at
Hofstra University  
 By STEVEN R. KNOWLTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mythical Golden Days, everyone had Miss Thistlebottom for
eighth-grade English. (She was almost always Miss. Only in rare
incarnations could she be spoken to as Miss T., though she was
always spoken about that way.)
</P>
<P>
   She was an imposing woman with hair in a steel-gray bun and a
formidable grasp of the minutiae of English grammar. Through force
of will, and occasionally, according to legend, through force of
ruler across knuckles, she was able to impart understanding of
gerunds and infinitives to students by the cowering roomful.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, as we all know, Miss T. retired some time ago, and
American education just ain't the same without her. The debates
about whether tough-love grammar can ever work again in a
postliterate world alternate between hysterical and mind-numbing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, four million Americans a year turn 18 and are loosed
upon the world, misplacing their modifiers, garbling their syntax
and dangling their participles. What to do? Can't computers help?
</P>
<P>
   Grammar software for kids is available in a great variety of
flavors and prices, but in an effort to make it appealing enough
for grade-school students, designers have filled the great majority
of the programs with cartoon rabbits and too-cute jingles. All of
that is guaranteed to be off-putting to people who see better
grammar as a step toward career success, immigrants who want to be
more fluent in their adopted language and anyone over 10.
</P>
<P>
   The software packages reviewed here are designed to teach
grammar, not correct the grammar you have already written. Major
word-processing programs like Microsoft Word and Corel's
Wordperfect now include grammar checkers, which are almost never
used but chew up acres of hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But be warned: they are no more reliable than spell checkers,
which have probably contributed almost as much as television to the
national inability to spell.
</P>
<P>
   Given how much poor grammar is afoot on the national landscape,
and given how good computers are at managing the sort of drill that
mastering good grammar requires, one would think that grammar
software would be an extremely crowded field. Not so. Bookstore
owners and college teachers shake their heads when asked about
grammar software.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most established programs, Queue's Mastering English
Grammar, is as ugly and uninviting as any grade-school primer, but
Jonathan Kantrowitz, the program's developer and Queue's chief
executive, said it would be a waste of money to try to recast it in
an attractive package. Many have tried, he said, but most have
failed. Besides, he said, English teachers like it frumpy.
</P>
<P>
   But with the growing interest in distance education as a cheaper
alternative to four years of living among the ivy, several new
grammar programs have emerged in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   These products all do a fairly good job with grammar basics.
None, even those that cost hundreds and even thousands of dollars,
can touch a really good grammar book for depth, but their format
may appeal to many. And people seeking grammar help are likely to
appreciate the effort to use the power of computers to make the
subject more palatable. Among its true believers, grammar excites a
level of passion bewildering to the civilian population. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALL WRITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (McGraw-Hill; $27.50; Windows 3.0 and later and NT.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALL WRITE is designed to work in two ways, as a grammar workbook
and as a grammar handbook or reference book.
</P>
<P>
   The student selects a chapter _ verb tenses, say, or pronouns _
then selects an objective or lesson from within that chapter, like
perfect and progressive tenses or pronoun case. The program then
asks questions and grades the answers with traffic lights showing
green for correct and red for incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   For actual instruction, the user goes to the help files, which
explain the concept in two levels of detail called Tell Me and Show
Me.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the practice session, the student is given a test.
If the student scores 70 percent or better on the post-test, a
little green box lights up next to that lesson on the contents
page. If the student scores less than 70, the box turns red.
</P>
<P>
   If the student quits that lesson in the middle, it turns yellow.
The program can also be used on a network for a class; in that
case, the instructor can raise or lower the passing bar.
</P>
<P>
   Given its versatility, this is a top choice for either home or
school use. At the price, it is very good value.
</P>
<P>
   But the program is very much a work in progress. For example, it
promises animation to teach concepts, but fewer than 20 animations
are included, and those are primitive and hardly worth the
trouble. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MULTIMEDIA HIGH SCHOOL GRAMMAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pro One; $14.95; Windows 3.0 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This software covers the basics _ parts of speech, agreement,
tense _ but without the polish and visual slickness of much pricier
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Each lesson begins with a short video clip of 15 to 20 seconds
in which one of the program's developers, Stan Satz, an English
instructor at Craven Community College in New Bern, N.C., lists the
topics to be covered. The lessons come in a set of multiple-choice
questions. When the correct answer is selected, a little box opens
up bearing a cartoon thumbs up, a smiley-face sun or some other
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   The audio ranges from an enthusiastic ``good'' to a bar of the
``Hallelujah'' chorus. Wrong answers get a sound effect like the
sound of breaking glass. Such things age quickly, but the sound can
be turned off.
</P>
<P>
   The program has some typos and other minor glitches, none really
serious, but enough to be jarring.
</P>
<P>
   And the use of video clips and audio is hardly Industrial Light
and Magic quality. At the end of each chapter, the program offers a
video clip. But the clip is of Professor Satz discussing an error
in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   A student encounters three kinds of explanations for each
problem. An ``example'' button opens two or three more examples of
the objective being presented, like subject-verb agreement, say, or
participles. The ``worked'' button explains the correct answer,
often also explaining why each of the other choices is not correct.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Generally, that is very useful. The ``details'' button is a
context-sensitive reference book of sorts. Clicking on it opens the
appropriate point in the reference to explain the grammar rule.
</P>
<P>
   The program does keep score, but since wrong answers are
instantly flagged and the user can try over and over again without
penalty, there is no need ever to record an incorrect answer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTERING ENGLISH GRAMMAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Queue; $225 for a single user, $1,125 for a network license;
Macintosh, with Windows version expected in the fall.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEVELOPING WRITING SKILLS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Queue; $150 for a single user, $750 for a network license;
Macintosh, with Windows version expected in the fall.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For anyone expecting bells and whistles _ or even recent
programming _ these two CDs from Queue will be major
disappointments. Despite fairly recent copyright dates (1995 for
Mastering English Grammar and 1992 for Developing Writing Skills),
the programs date from the early to mid-80s and show their age
badly.
</P>
<P>
   Developing Writing Skills is broadly focused on all aspects of
writing _ doing research, outlining and other elements _ and is
aimed at students in junior high school. Mastering English Grammar
is more narrowly focused and somewhat more advanced.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental problem with this software is that it might as
well be a spiral-bound workbook. At least then it wouldn't need an
expensive machine to run on, you could shove it into a backpack,
and it would be cheap enough that it wouldn't break your heart if
you left it on the train.
</P>
<P>
   The software uses plain black-on-white text _ and remember, this
is for Macintosh, which is known for fancy graphics. Each screen
makes a statement like, ``Pronouns have to agree with their
antecedents,'' say, or, ``Use a semicolon between two phrases of
equal weight,'' and then asks a question with a multiple-choice or
fill-in-the-blank answer.
</P>
<P>
   About the only other thing that this software does that a
workbook would not is keep score of the right and wrong answers. It
also runs a rudimentary clock to track how long a student spent on
the lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kantrowitz, Queue's founder and the chief developer for
both these programs, said in a telephone interview that the bland,
no-frills look was on purpose. The product is designed for
classrooms, not home use, he said, which means that teachers, not
parents, do the buying. And teachers, he said, especially English
teachers, ``want to see stuff that looks like textbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   English teachers ``are probably the most computerphobic of all
curriculum areas,'' he said. Besides, he added, grammar is simply
``not a subject that has mass appeal.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SKILLSBANK 4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Learning Co.; $249 single user, $1,492 unlimited site
license; Windows 3.0 and later and NT, with Macintosh version
expected in the fall.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAREER ENGLISH SERIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tutorsystems; $395 single user, $3,750 unlimited site license;
Windows 3.0 and later and NT, with Macintosh version expected later
this summer.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the high end of grammar software are a number of programs
designed for classroom use. These come with teacher modules, which
allow an instructor to assign lessons to individual students or
groups of students and to track student progress in all kinds of
ways.
</P>
<P>
   However, these programs can also profitably be used as
stand-alone programs. Part of their premium price is wasted, but
these expensive programs also tend to be the best designed.
</P>
<P>
   Skillsbank 4 is chock full of bells and whistles. This is
juggernaut software from a major player in education. Of the
programs discussed here, this one takes most advantage of the world
of computers, circa 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When a student logs on, a few bars of jaunty music play and a
well-modulated voice explains what to do. (You can turn off the
audio.) This is a well thought-out package, taking full advantage
of current-generation multimedia computers. It is clearly not a
game, but it is designed to be enjoyable as well as informative.
</P>
<P>
   A nice feature is a category of lesson called ``thinking,''
which invites a student to analyze, rather than simply repeat,
material previously covered. Not surprisingly, given the strong
audio and visual dimensions of this program, one of these exercises
in inductive reasoning is built around the premise of being one of
two writers for a television show.
</P>
<P>
   At this high end, there are a number of other major players,
whose products should probably be examined before committing
several thousand dollars, even if it is the school board's money.
These include the Computer Curriculum Corp., Jostens Learning Corp.
and A(plus) Learning System.
</P>
<P>
   Tutorsystems, a much smaller company, has a Basic Skills package
of both English and math and a more advanced Career English Series
for adult learners. It is designed for networked classroom use but
can be used alone.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most programs, this one is truly tutorial in that it
tells you things and then asks questions, rather than asking
questions and then explaining the answers. It also goes into more
advanced grammar principles than any of the other programs. A nice
feature is a link on every screen to the American Heritage Talking
Dictionary, which is bundled with the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
