<HEADER>
A7763 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX     07-22 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS TO READ ON SUMMER VACATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Elvis, Hank, and Me''
</P>
<P>
   By Horace Logan with Bill Sloan
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   THE AUTHOR: Shreveport, La., was a small city of about 100,000
in the years after World War II. Certainly not the sort of place
one would expect to be a breeding ground for country and rock music
legends.
</P>
<P>
   But it did have a huge, 50,000-watt clear-channel radio station,
and a pioneering program director named Horace ``Hoss'' Logan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Logan created the ``Louisiana Hayride'' as an
alternative to the sometimes-staid ``Grand Ole Opry,'' and
``Hayride'' became a radio springboard for entertainers who didn't
fit the Nashville mold.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST THINGS FIRST: Before reading a line of copy, turn to Page
263 for the list of artists who appeared on the ``Louisiana
Hayride.'' Elvis Presley is listed alphabetically between Webb
Pierce and Felton Pruett. Gene Autry is two names down from Betty
Amos and the Lump Boys. George Jones, one entry above Oakie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Grand Ole Opry'' of the day didn't allow any drums, wind
instruments, electrified fiddles (dadgum that Bob Wills) or
anything else unorthodox, Logan recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But the freewheeling ``Hayride'' didn't have those restrictions.
So Elvis, Hank Sr. and Johnny Cash got a chance to happen, as did
Jim Reeves, Slim Whitman, Kitty Wells, Hank Thompson, George Jones
and Johnny Horton.
</P>
<P>
   THE DIRT: The book offers some pretty salacious details,
including a bit of speculation on the 20-year-old Elvis' sexual
appetite and Faron Young's abrupt pickup line. Hank Williams' sorry
decline is graphic enough to explain his bladder habits during the
last two months of his life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Shirley Jinkins
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
