<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOOL-CATALOGS-ART-2TA     07-22 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOOL-CATALOGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWORKING UNPLUGGED 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ore., Maine, Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Easy, fun and gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a personal ad. It's copy for a tool catalog.
Specifically, solid brass and rosewood knobs, for home woodworking
projects, on sale in the latest catalog from Bridge City Tool Works
of Portland, Ore. Elsewhere, their scratch awl balances like ``a
conductor's baton.'' The joint maker's hammer is
``flame-hardened,'' with a ``long, willowy neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Garrett Wade, Lee Valley, Woodcraft and other high-end tool
catalog businesses, Bridge City Tool Works is digging for a bright,
hard nugget within the expanding $14 billion industry for
woodworking tools, materials and supplies. The vein of gold: the
new, upscale, fine-woodworking hobbyist, for whom extraordinary
hand tools are like French cooking knives or English gardening
implements.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines like Fine Woodworking and American Woodworker inform
him. (It is still a ``he,'' by about 84 percent.) Schools like the
Anderson Ranch in Aspen, Colo., and the Center for Furniture
Craftsmanship in Rockport, Maine, instruct him. The Internet nails
him at home, with a flood of sites like the Electronic Neanderthal
that let prospective ark-builders buy, sell and bond as if at a
medieval guild.
</P>
<P>
   Iron John has become Wood Chuck, and he (average age 45) is the
affluent advance guard of what could easily be one of the leading
retirement life-style activities for the baby-boom generation,
right up there with cooking and gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not poised to be life style,'' said Peter Korn, the
director of the Center for Furniture Craftsmanship. ``It IS.'' The
center's current enrollment of 250 _ average age, early 40s _
represents a 500 percent increase over 1993. Korn is considering a
cooking school next door.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture-making and cabinetry hand tools are the Grail for
fine-woodworking hobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of Lie-Nielsen hand planes, Japanese miter
squares and Calvo brass-headed mallets. Priced in the hundreds of
dollars, two or three times the price of their cost-conscious
cousins from Sears or Stanley, they are actually more precious _
made of rarer woods and metals, like mahogany and bronze, not
hickory and cast-iron. They get the job done like a bare fist, but
they are as sensitive as you are.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking make-your-own-rifle racks. Think Mission
mantelpieces (Fine Woodworking, August issue) and Mackintosh chairs
(American Woodworking, August issue).
</P>
<P>
   For this, blame Norm Abram, co-host of ``This Old House'' and
host of ``New Yankee Workshop,'' whose renovation and woodworking
television shows reach 14.5 million people a week, for the
explosion of interest in hobbyist woodworking at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to do the show for four years, and we're in our
11th year,'' Abram said. ``Interest in woodworking is absolutely
growing. It's moving into an upscale, white-collar group. People in
their 40s to 60s, who are looking for an adventurous hobby. It's
like therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some would question the expense of the new crusade, for
some baby boomers, it is also pure nostalgia. Paradise _ high
school shop classes of the 1940s and '50s _ regained. Harry Urban,
the publisher of Custom Woodworking Business, said, ``Middle-age
boomers who think back to their grandfather who made a chair, go
out and spend $100,000 on woodworking equipment to get past their
frustration point of sitting in front of a computer all day, by
making something with their hands to show to their family.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of its subscribers, according to Timothy
Schreiner, the editor of Fine Woodworking, showed their household
income was $100,000, ``which is very high, if you think of it as a
blue collar interest,'' Schreiner said. ``We keep running into
orthopedists.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodworking hobbyists in the United States _ up 7 percent from
1995 _ spent more than $315 million on hand tools last year,
compared with $180 million three years ago, according to an
unreleased 1998 survey commissioned by American Woodworker
magazine. While this is still a fraction of the spending for power
tools, which was more than $1.5 billion, it is exquisite hand tools
and fine woodworking that have seized the imagination of the
high-end hobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Woodcraft, a fine-woodworkers' catalog, has enough confidence in
the future to push into national retail stores, with 33 open and 10
to come. ``We see similarities to gardening,'' said Mark Wirthlin,
the marketing director. ``A lot of people are enjoying the hobby at
Lowe's or Home Depot, but they don't make the radar of exclusive
catalogs and don't know the cool stuff that's available.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hobbyists are converts from power tools. ``About three
years ago, the pendulum began swinging back with a vengeance, to
hand tools,'' said Gary Chinn, the president of Garrett Wade, the
first of the ``boutique'' woodworking catalog businesses, and the
most widely recognized. The company, which mails 600,000 catalogs a
year, discontinued sales of power tools in 1996. ``It's a cultural
thing as much as anything else,'' Chinn said. ``People became
unhappy with the fact that there was nothing of them in what they
produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, blame Norm Abram. ``Everybody was watching Norm do his
power-tool paint-by-number woodworking in his clean workshop, but
you never saw any sawdust,'' said Patrick Leach, a fine-woodworker
who markets reproductions of antique hand tools on the Internet, at
www.supertool.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys were left with an empty feeling _ that there's
got to be more to it than an on and off switch,'' said Leach, who
is renovating his Cape-style house and Federal period house, both
in Massachusetts, with hand tools.
</P>
<P>
   David Sloan, the editor and publisher of American Woodworker,
described the split as one between ``product people'' ``If there's
an electric outlet near, that's the path'' _ and ``process
people,'' who ``take pleasure in the scenic byways, and hand tools
explore that. They give you a tactile result _ a feel, a smell, a
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hand tool woodworkers are fond of comparing themselves to fly
fishermen _ another patient elite, who insist there is art in their
craft. Hand tools are landing woodworkers the same sense of finely
calibrated accomplishment _ justifying, they claim, the same
obsession with the expensive esoterics of the equipment, what
Patrick Leach calls the ```gizmosity' factor, as gizmos,'' he said,
``which gives them their sex appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Abram, who has a carpentry background, argued that appeal of
woodworking was in the skill. ``It's the hands of the craftsman and
not the rosewood handle that makes woodworking fine.'' He added:
``Some would look at `New Yankee Workshop' and say it's not fine
woodworking. It is. There is a difference in quality in power
tools, too. There are people who buy expensive hand tools as an
investment, and I think, what a waste. They won't be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Abram, coincidentally, tried fly fishing last year. ``It was
very calming,'' he said. ``But if I don't catch fish, I don't
worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Useful, humble tools are the last things one would expect
high-end airs and attitude about, but experienced hobbyists claim
that they are generally of higher quality than the selections of
commercial tools found at mass-market home improvement centers,
though add-ons like exotic wood or precious-metal detailing raise
the price like a roof beam.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Reed, the president of the San Diego Fine Woodworkers
Association and a part-time woodworking teacher at Palomar College
in San Marcos, Calif., says they also do their job with some
finesse. ``Everybody lusts to have an engraved Bridge City
tri-square,'' she said. ``I have one _ it's accurate. The tools you
pick up at your local mall are not accurate. Squares are often not
square and levels aren't level.''
</P>
<P>
   High-end woodworking companies also succeed in selling their
fine hand tools to covetous beginners because of the bells and
whistles. ``They are proficiency by association for beginners,''
Peter Korn said, skeptically citing the belief, witnessed among his
own students, that the better the tool, the better the work.
</P>
<P>
   Behind many of the newer, high-end hand tools are small
entrepreneurs, dedicated to manufacturing them and marketing them
to fine-furniture and cabinet makers _ while global tool businesses
like the Stanley Works, with woodworking hand tool sales of $754
million in 1997, have slowly swung their cannons toward contractors
and renovators.
</P>
<P>
   With $1.25 million in sales last year, a 30 percent growth over
1996, Lie-Nielsen Tool Works, in Warren, Maine, has a reputation
polished both by woodworkers and collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Lie-Nielsen, 44, its founder, has a narrow, angular nose
that looks planed by a wood plane. The son of a wooden boat
builder, he is an English major, a woodworker and a hand tool
enthusiast. He could be one of his own customers.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-year stint at Garrett Wade in New York,
Lie-Nielsen returned to Maine in 1981 to try his own hand at tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a market, but it was unclear how healthy it was,''
he said. ``Specialized hand tools were looked on as being
overpriced and fancy and too good to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Lie-Nielsen started making planes in an unheated woodshed on the
200-year-old Maine property where he was subsistence-farming. He
taught himself how to make a wood plane by hand, from forging the
iron for the casing, on up. His mother, Margaret, was his
bookkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with 25 workers in a 10,000-square-foot former ice house
on Route 1, he is manufacturing a line of roughly 16 distinct
models of wood planes, based largely on discontinued Stanley
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanley used to have a hundred different planes, many of them
with very specific uses,'' Lie-Nielsen said. ``They're super tools.
They should never have fallen out of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Jones, the president of the hand tool product group at
the Stanley Works, defended the company's position in leaving parts
of its illustrious past behind, to serve new, larger markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've addressed ourselves to the professional who uses tools
everyday, in his work,'' Jones said. ``The specialized hand planes
that were used in carpentry _ these products are no longer used as
mainline tools, by professional carpenters.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine-woodworkers revived them, buying them as second-hand tools.
When collectors discovered their attraction, as esthetic rarities,
they swept the second-hand market clean, making the tools scarce
again. Enter companies like Lie-Nielsen's.
</P>
<P>
   At his factory, Lie-Nielsen spends much of his day putting his
fingers together in the air to show a measurement to an employee, a
reminder that he has made his tools himself, by hand, from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Lie-Nielsen re-engineers designs, rather than reproducing them,
drawing on his familiarity with older planes to make improvements.
His most popular tool is a $95 bronze block plane, of which he has
sold 20,000 in 14 years. By comparison, the Stanley Works produces
approximately 15,000 block planes a week. Made of cast iron, they
retail for $39.99. Is an elegant tool overkill?
</P>
<P>
   Professional fine-woodworkers would argue that a tool's elegance
lies not only in its utility, but also in the woodworker's intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these tools are patently ridiculous because they're
just the wrong thing for the job _ the Faberge egg as tool,'' said
John Reed Fox, a Massachusetts cabinet maker. But he is prepared to
co-exist with the new high-end hobbyist attention, if it revives
interest in his craft.
</P>
<P>
   Fox uses Japanese hand tools that he buys from a gallery in
Berkeley, Calif. For Fox, it is more philosopher's stone than
Grail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craft isn't really part of the culture anymore,'' he said.
``It's similar to a potter at the wheel. Using handmade objects to
make handmade objects. We're protectors of the ceremony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD-TOOLS-ART-NYT &LR;      07-22 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-TOOLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTH THEIR WEIGHT IN A REALLY TALL PILE OF SAWDUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 Jeff Taylor is the author of ``Tools of the Trade: The Art and
Craft of Carpentry'' (Chronicle Books, 1996).  
 (bl)  
 By JEFF TAYLOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when I began collecting old tools for my
personal use as a working carpenter, the first thing I did was
scrape off the factory decals, not knowing that this was criminal
vandalism against the tools' historical value. For my sins, I
degraded a collection probably worth a low six figures today to a
very nice carpentry outfit worth a few hundred dollars. Let's not
even talk about my speckless Bedrock plane, bought for $10 at a
garage sale and later sold for $20. On the Web, a similar one, in
good condition, is now for sale for $1,200. Let's change the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   There's an indescribable quality that radiates from old tools.
You sense it in the hand-worn patina of rosewood knobs and grips,
the chiaroscuro of glinting brass levers under darkened steel. But
they are mute until you touch them. Then they won't shut up. Pick
up an old tool, and you almost hear the ticking hours of its long
working life. Such tools can be time machines, portals to a
yesteryear farther away than the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who collect hand tools are comparatively sane,
really. At the very least, our sanity is hanging by a stronger
thread than most, for our lifeline is belayed off in the hallowed
past, twirled around the rock of craft. William Hermanek of
Smithtown, N.Y., has amassed 1,800 antiques, most of them Stanleys.
</P>
<P>
   But collecting is a science with a language all its own. And if
you don't know which part of a plane is the galoot or how to tweak
the normites of a chisel, you probably have no business investing
heavily. Try teddy bears instead.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, the only criterion for membership in the pantheon
of collectors is a heart that beats faster in the presence of
rosewood and brass, and goes into tachycardia upon hearing certain
code words and phrases: crispy (very clean), bonerific (fine
condition) and Stanley No. 1 plane. It doesn't hurt that the value
of old tools is creeping _ reliably, dependably, inevitably _
upward.
</P>
<P>
   Set the Wayback Machine to 1965. You could find carloads of
woodworking tools in junk stores for a couple of dollars: Blaisdell
marking gauges, worth $600 now; Stanley Everlasting chisels, $100
to $150 each today. You would have paid 50 cents for a small brass
plumb bob that would now bring $150 to $450. Back then, my father
traded a factory box of 12 Stanley six-foot yellow zigzag rules
(easily $75 each today) for an old handsaw, an ugly thing with a
panther's head carved into the handle. It was in mint condition
until he gave it to his young sons. We wore it out building a
treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone?'' asked Patrick Leach, his day apparently ruined.
Leach is a self-described former computer geek who cast off the
shackles of his day job in 1996 to wallow in old tools full time _
and whose Web site -(www.supertool.com) merits a long look.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, a Panther saw in that condition would be worth
name-your-price.'' Leach said. He said $5,000 would not be far off
the mark; one such saw, in merely good condition, sold a year ago
for $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   My vast collection began quite by accident with my first plane.
It disappeared in the chaos of my garage. I bought a replacement at
a junk store for $5. Then my first plane showed up, so I had a
Stanley No. 1 in the original box. It would be worth no more than a
fortune today, if I still had it.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley No. 1 was produced from the end of the Civil War to
the middle of World War II, and even 10 years ago, you could nab
one for under $100. Today, they fetch well upward of $1,000 in fine
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' under the generally accepted grading system
established by Fine Tool Journal, means almost fresh from the box,
nearly unused. The top tool grade is ``new,'' meaning that no one
has ever stared hard at the piece and the original box smells like
robot deodorant. With superlative luck, $2,000 might get you a
Stanley No. 1 like that. But probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be collectors should visit the grandaddy of annual tool
auctions in Harrisburg, Pa., the weekend before Halloween. (At this
event in 1996, a prototype M.B. Tidey double-bevel wood plane went
for a record $27,500.) Clarence Blanchard, the publisher of Fine
Tool Journal, offers a few bidding tips: ``Look for the rarest tool
in the best condition you can afford. Buy the reference books and
study them.'' Amen.
</P>
<P>
   The novice seeking bargains should seek out oddball tools in
perfect condition, or Stanley No. 55 combination planes, which
still go for $300 to $400. The No. 55 is an up-and-coming
collectible prized for its unquestionable beauty and Byzantine
complexity _ never its utility. Decorators have discovered how
perfectly it enhances a bookshelf, the one task it does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality and condition are the most important criteria,'' said
Peter Habicht, whose shop in southern Massachusetts, Falcon-Wood
(www.oldtools.com), caters to the discriminating tool user and
collector. ``Then rarity. Then price.'' I view the old-tool market
as one of the most volatile in the neurotic world of collectibles.
Habicht disagrees. Although prices are rising 5 percent a year
conservatively, he maintains that apart from blips and fads, the
market is fairly stable. He is probably right, but I hate being
contradicted.
</P>
<P>
   So I tell him: In 1975, at some Gomorrah of a garage sale, I had
a chance to buy an ivory carpenter's rule, a two-foot four-fold
inlaid with silver filigree, for $5. And I passed, instead buying a
Jefferson Airplane eight-track tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Habicht whispers. ``What . . . condition?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never used. Factory-fresh, a virgin, with paper instructions
written in German.'' It would have been too unkind to mention the
original box made of spalted tulipwood, or the outsize numbers that
marked it as a supremely rare ``blind man's'' rule. Neither of us
can bring himself to speculate aloud on what it would be worth
today: very, very conservatively, $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   We collectors welcome new blood, but we also counsel caution.
And we beg you not to duplicate the mistakes of 20 years ago, when
it was fashionable to remove the precious black japanning on planes
with a sandblaster and paint them beige. It's acceptable to remove
surface rust with a little steel wool, revealing microscopically
small patent dates and manufacturer information. You can use
penetrating oil to free seized parts, and it's forgivable to reglue
tight cracks in wood, if done expertly. Prohibitions include wire
wheels, naval jelly, chemical strippers and polishing.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom tools can still be unearthed at garage sales and farm
auctions, but don't rush in like a fool, thinking to auction your
finds tomorrow at Sotheby's. Study the guides: the best and most
current is ``Collecting Antique Tools'' by Herbert P. Kean and Emil
S. Pollak (Astragal Press, 1990; $29.95). And you might visit one
of these Web sites: www2.finetoolj.com/ftj/bas and
www.wowpages.com/ftj.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, you will save yourself much heartache if
you send all your German ivory folding rules, Woodrough &AMP; McParlin
Panther saws and Stanley No. 1 planes, preferably in their original
boxes, to me. I will pay the postage and find a home for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
