<HEADLINE>
LOOK MA, NO HANDS  
 A SAFE $5 MILLION  
 ENGLISH MADE EASY  
 ONLINE LEARNING CENTER  
 LINUX GETS 2ND LOOK  
 NO MORE MESSAGE ANXIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN E. BRIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Computer, On'' and ``Computer, Off'' may work on the Starship
Enterprise but the rest of us still have to go through the motions
of turning on our computers. Now, a new product may turn logging
onto your computer and protecting your data a hands-free operation.
</P>
<P>
   Air ID is a system coming on the market from the Illinois-based
company, RF IDeas Inc. The system combines an ID badge/radio
transmitter for the user and a receiver that plugs into a computer
serial port.
</P>
<P>
   When you stand or sit near a properly configured PC while
wearing the Air ID card, you will be automatically logged onto that
computer. Walk away, and the Air ID card, once the transmission is
broken, will trigger a protective screensaver, blocking access to
the computer as well as concealing anything on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ID badge will work when the holder is within 10 to 20 feet
of the protected computer and can allow access to more than one
computer.
</P>
<P>
   For the fashion conscious, those who don't like too many things
dangling from their pocket protectors, the badge can be used as a
normal ID card, with a user's picture, name, department and other
information prominently displayed. For the slightly paranoid, it
can be left blank so that if lost, the person recovering it will
not know what it protected.
</P>
<P>
   Decrypting Encryption
</P>
<P>
   Psst _ want to break some code and make a cool $5 million? All
you have to do is decrypt a document of unknown length, encoded
with a 4096-bit key, and tell us how you did it. By July 31. And -
oh, yeah _ then you have to do it again to win the money.
</P>
<P>
   This was the challenge posted by Jaws Technology, a Canadian
company trying to make a mark for itself in the field of
encryption. Several other encrypted files have been decrypted
recently, including one last week by a two-person team working with
a privacy-rights organization and a specialized computer built for
$250,000. That file used Standard DES, the standard code
recommended for businesses by the U.S. government, and a 56-bit
key, a piece of code that determines how the encryption algorithm
works. The winner of that contest tried 17,902,806,669,197,312
keys, or about 25 percent of all the possible combinations that
could be generated by the original 56-bit code.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaws file was encrypted by a new program using a 4096-bit
key. There are, needless to say, quite a few more combinations with
a 4096-bit encryption key.
</P>
<P>
   Jaws CEO Robert Kubbernus said that there were problems with
existing encryption programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current standards aren't good enough,'' Kubbernus said, ``so
we took it right off the charts to make sure ours was.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Jaws is Canadian, the company hopes to attract
international buyers eager to avoid the current Clinton
administration encryption brouhaha.
</P>
<P>
   About that $5 million? Kubbernus does not expect to have to pay
out. The contest has been running for about two months and ends in
another week. If the first message is decrypted, it has to be
verified with an outside auditor. Then, a second message has to be
decrypted within 60 days. If that's done, the person has to tell
Jaws how it was done. Only then will the money appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone can break this, we want to know how it was done,''
Kubbernus said. ``We also want to offer them a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Set-Top Translator
</P>
<P>
   English-language television programs may have just gained a
stronger foothold among Spanish-speaking viewers, thanks to a new
translation device.
</P>
<P>
   TCC Communications of Canada has developed a set-top box that
instantly converts English closed captioning into Spanish. The box,
aimed at people in the U.S. who only speak Spanish, is far from
perfect but more than good enough, according to John Grayson, the
CEO of TCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is accurate at best about 70 percent of the time,'' said
Grayson. ``But it is better than looking at 80 channels with
nothing on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Popowich and Paul McFetridge, researchers at Simon Fraser
University in Canada, are working to raise that accuracy rate.
</P>
<P>
   Popowich said that unilingual Spanish speakers do not notice the
difference between a translation that is 85 percent accurate and
one that is 100 percent accurate. He said the translation is
enhanced by the TV program, which provides a story line and images
to provide context and help with the understanding. Popowich and
McFetridge now have a lab version working at 80 per cent accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bilingual speakers would be annoyed with the quality of the
translation,'' Popowich said, ``but this gives me the gist of
what's going on while getting something out of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's source material is provided by government
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``FCC and its Canadian equivalent mandated that everything be
close captioned. That is a rich source for text material,'' Grayson
said. ``We take the analog signal, digitize it, feed it into the
translator and out comes the translation. The user has the choice
of displaying it in English or Spanish, and changing the speed and
size of the display,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial version of the translator is being prepared, and
will be marketed to television stations in Central and South
America, which currently imports about 200 hours of English
language TV programs a day, Grayson said. A Portuguese version,
targeted for the Brazilian market, is in the works, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Schooling
</P>
<P>
   Prodigy Internet has established an online learning center,
offering training classes for popular applications from Microsoft,
Adobe and Lotus, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Prodigy said the classes can reduce the time and costs
associated with training by using the Internet as a delivery
mechanism and using animation and real-time audio technology. The
company has developed a synchronized multimedia file format to deal
with the choppiness and poor quality found in most internet
multimedia files. Users will need to download and install a program
to read the files.
</P>
<P>
   Training is available on about 40 programs with more to be
added, a Prodigy spokesman said. The learning center courses are
available only to Prodigy members and range in cost from $9.95 for
one-week access to one tutorial up to about $200 for a year's
access to the entire catalog.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Writing to Order
</P>
<P>
   The Linux operating system, a stepchild in the world of computer
operating systems, is getting a second look. Computer Associates,
Informix and other corporate software suppliers have recently
announced that some of their applications would be rewritten
specifically for the Linux system.
</P>
<P>
   Linux is a Unix-based operating system available for free
through any number of Linux Web sites. Device drivers, utilities
and all the other add-ons necessary to make it work are written by
the people who need them and also made available for free, an
approach to support that has left many a harried information
systems manager leery. (After all, there is no one to complain to
if the system does not work.) But some changes in the marketplace
are bringing more mainstream corporate suppliers into the Linux
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is starting to be some movement toward commercially
supported versions of Linux,'' Don LeClair, a vice president at
Long Island, N.Y.-based Computer Associates said. ``Caldera and Red
Hat'' _ two of the companies attempting to turn Linux into a
commercial product _ ``are putting out supported versions, and
Linux looks like a more viable platform than it did a year or two
ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Associates is preparing a version of its Ingress
relational database specifically for Linux. Relational databases
are popular corporate products that manage data in a simple format
and then analyze that data. Linux has strong roots in the
educational and software development environments, markets where
Ingress has been popular. That popularity and a number of user
requests prompted CA to make a Linux version.
</P>
<P>
   Relational database makers Informix and Oracle also are reported
to be developing Linux versions. The combination of commercial
support and commercial applications should help improve the image
of Linux in the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   On Call
</P>
<P>
   For those people who can't bear to miss their messages, Motorola
has developed the Pocketalk, a cross between a pager and an
answering machine. The Pocketalk, which was introduced last year
and will be available in the New York area next week, works like a
pager except that it will receive and store voice messages. The
product retails for about $80 and then there are the usual
activation and monthly service charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
