<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE (AT) IN E-MAIL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The words (AT) and (equal) throughout item should be replaced
by the symbol)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the name of the (AT) symbol used in e-mail addresses?
</P>
<P>
   A. The (AT) symbol, found on the Shift of the 2 key on QWERTY
keyboards, is usually defined as just the ``at'' sign by
dictionaries, technical manuals and typographic stylebooks. In its
former (and still occasional) life as a commerce symbol, it also
stands for ``each'' in calculating the cost per unit, as in ``5
muffins (AT) $1.50 (equal) $7.50.''
</P>
<P>
   A single (AT) sign is a mandatory part of every Internet e-mail
address. It was used in the first e-mail message ever sent, which
was in 1972. The engineer who was sent the mail, Ray Tomlinson, was
trying to figure out how to make his computer differentiate between
the name of the intended recipient and that person's computer
address. So he needed a punctuation mark or symbol that did not
occur in a name. Looking at his keyboard, he noticed the (AT), and
an Internet standard was born.
</P>
<P>
   But not all computer networks have always used the (AT) sign in
e-mail addresses. Some computers on Bitnet, the international
network founded in 1981, required the user to spell out the word
``at'' in an address.
</P>
<P>
   Other symbols that have appeared in e-mail addresses throughout
computer-network history include the exclamation point and the
percent sign, but these specialized forms of mail-addressing have
generally given way to the present (AT). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Circuits invites questions about computer-based
technology, by postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York
Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail
to QandA(AT)nytimes.com.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
