<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WIN98-BUGS-NYT &LR;      07-22 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WIN98-BUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98? JUST ONE LITTLE THING ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only reason I considered installing Windows 98 was because
my friend Kip Crosby promised that the upgrade would cure the
crashes that plagued my computer. I figured he should know,
considering that he had recently co-written ``The Windows 98
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How I wish we lived in a world where people like you weren't
afraid the computer would blow up every time you did something to
it,'' Crosby lectured me. ``Your problem is that Windows 95 and
Internet Explorer 4.0 are having severe disagreements. But if you
upgrade, the browser will know the operating system is the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   That possibility intrigued me. How often in life does such a
simple solution to a software problem present itself? It sounded so
much easier than sitting on the phone for hours with a tech support
person, trying this, trying that, groping in the dark for a light
switch to illuminate some arcane code flaw. Besides, if Windows 98
didn't solve my crashing problem, I figured it was on Crosby's
head, not mine.
</P>
<P>
   So I was a little surprised when he answered the phone a few
days later with a weary ``Oh, it's you. Are you calling to say that
Windows 98 has done you dirty?'' His tone of resignation made me
wonder just how many cranks, er, home computer users like me he
spoke to in a given day.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I was calling about a problem that surfaced after I
installed Windows 98 (how did he guess?). Whenever I clicked on an
icon on my taskbar to open my e-mail program, Eudora Pro 3.0, a
mysterious message would appear on screen to announce, ``Could not
rename file from c:/windows/temp/descmap.tmp to
c:/eudora/descmap.pce.''
</P>
<P>
   Descmap? The message might as well have been written in Mayan
for all the sense it made to me. Still, it was a minor annoyance
because it did not prevent me from running Eudora. I clicked on OK,
and the message disappeared _ until the next time I clicked on the
taskbar after booting the computer. (Another weird twist: The error
message appeared only the first time I opened Eudora after booting
the computer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm, this sounds like a Eudora problem, not a 98 problem,''
Crosby said. ``The thing about Eudora is that it originally was a
Mac program. It went from there to being Windows shareware, as
well, and from there to Windows shrink-wrap. But Eudora for Windows
has never worked really well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This never happened when I was running Windows 95,'' I said. I
think a transcript of the conversation would show that I did not
sound accusatory. I was only trying to gather the facts in a
neutral way. ``So it must be something Windows 98 did.''
</P>
<P>
   I heard him sigh. ``I run Eudora myself, but it is not the
best-behaved program that ever lived. Just do me a favor. Call
Qualcomm, which owns Eudora, and ask if they've seen this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I followed his advice _ I always do _ but I also put
in a call to Microsoft at the same time. That was not because I
doubted my friend's assessment. But I subscribe to the philosophy
that in a marketplace of free ideas, the truth will assert itself.
I wanted as many points of view as possible.
</P>
<P>
   I first reached Michael Brooks, who does tech support for
Eudora. He explained that ``descmap'' was a file that Eudora uses
to keep track of mailboxes. ``For some reason, Eudora is not able
to read to the temp file, which it wants to do,'' Brooks said.
``Something weird is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   After we tried a few experiments (I use the term ``we'' rather
loosely), ``we'' realized that the error message disappeared if I
opened Eudora from any other shortcut _ ``we'' created a few in
places other than the taskbar to test the theory _ or from the file
itself. I deleted the offensive shortcut, replaced it with a
sterile new one and rebooted, and the bug disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably just that one shortcut that got corrupted,''
Brooks said. ``But how?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' he said. ``I've reinstalled Windows, and all my
shortcuts got messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   But why would Windows 98 mess up shortcuts? I asked Hugh Taylor
of Microsoft, whom I spoke to next.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't,'' Taylor said. ``The upgrade shouldn't cause
corruption, not in and of itself. Some other factor might have
complicated the upgrade, for instance a third-party application,
such as any utility that essentially tries to track or replace the
functionality of the desk to ... ''
</P>
<P>
   I lost the thread of the conversation at that point because the
error message was back on my machine. I had been fiddling with
Eudora while Taylor and I talked, and there it was again.
</P>
<P>
   As a test, I deleted the new shortcut. Then I created another
and rebooted the computer, and the problem vanished again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still don't know for sure what caused it,'' Taylor
said. ``With every major revision of the operating system, some of
the interfaces that applications need to use to draw on Windows
services change. Sometimes the interfaces can become out of date.
That could be the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said ``we'' could check some other things to get to the
root of it. But by now, I had been on the phone for more than two
hours with two different tech support people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you always have to get to the bottom of what caused it?'' I
asked. ``Or is it enough just to make it go away?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're happy, I'm happy,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I'm happy. After nearly a week, the error message hasn't
re-emerged. (Another plus: Since I upgraded to Windows 98, my
computer has not crashed once while running Internet Explorer 4.0.)
Maybe the Eudora bug was in the process of curing itself, like the
fountain in the pond in my garden that cured itself after refusing
for two weeks to spray water. Or like the knocking in the engine of
my Honda Civic that cured itself after the weather warmed up. Maybe
software was becoming as intelligent as Iron Age machinery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
