<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showers and some very strong thunderstorms will erupt across
portions of the central Appalachians and Northeast on Thursday as a
slow-moving cold front intercepts a very humid air mass presiding
over the region. Showers and thunderstorms will begin over interior
sections Thursday morning and then press eastward to the coast
during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, less humid air will spread into the Great Lakes on
breezes from the northwest. The day will begin mainly sunny over
the region, though currents of air moistening on ascent will induce
puffy cumulus clouds to form by afternoon. A couple of these clouds
could develop into spotty showers southeast of Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, clouds will mix with intervals of sunshine over the
Southeast, including Florida. Scattered thunderstorms will ignite
in the sultry air, especially during the afternoon when heating
from the sun makes the atmosphere most unstable. Thunderstorms will
be most concentrated near the Gulf Coast, where a disturbance
spirals inland from the offshore waters.
</P>
<P>
   Air gliding up the sloping terrain will fuel showers and
thunderstorms in sections of the Front Range and central Plains. A
few of these storms will turn severe, accompanied by hail and
isolated tornadoes as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to mostly sunny and hot conditions will cover much of the
West on Thursday. Burgeoning cumulus clouds will yield to spotty
afternoon thunderstorms over interior sections, particularly in the
mountainous terrain. Patchy morning clouds will again shroud the
Pacific coastline.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HOT NIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the low temperature at the Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport was 81 degrees. It marked the 17th time this
month that the minimum at Dallas was 80 degrees or higher, setting
a new July record for the city. Weather records at Dallas date back
to 1899. Though the media has focused on the number of 100-degree
days in Dallas this month, hot nights have been more impressive.
Average highs in Dallas are in the upper 90s so many of the daily
highs have been approximately 3 to 6 degrees above average.
Nighttime minimums, however, have been 6 to 8 degrees above
average. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
