<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-BENGALS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson in lean, mean fighting trim for Bengals camp
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The first thing you notice about Willie Anderson is
that there isn't as much of him to notice.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Bengals man-mountain offensive tackle will report
to training camp at about 345 pounds, only a couple of Whoppers _
whoops, make that a couple of salads and a bowl of rice _ over his
assigned playing weight of 340.
</P>
<P>
   The camp that begins July 23 at Georgetown College will be the
first ``normal'' training period in Anderson's three-year career.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie first-round draft pick out of Auburn, he missed
three weeks of work because of a contract holdout, then knee and
ankle injuries helped delay his first regular season start until
the seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, he reported at 360 pounds and needed almost half a
season to play himself into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to be in that position again,'' Anderson said
Tuesday after a precamp workout at Spinney Field. ``I realize now
how the offseason can just fly by, how you have to manage your time
and when you have to start working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who now lives in Atlanta, hired a personal trainer to
help him overhaul his body and change his eating habits. ``We did
some kind of workout almost every day. I learned that I have to
keep my body active all the time. If I don't do something to keep
my metabolism going, everything I eat just stays there.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has only one personal goal for 1998. ``My thing is to
be recognized as the best right tackle in football. I really don't
care all that much about going to the Pro Bowl. There are a lot of
outside things involved in that and the best linemen don't always
get to go. All I care about is hearing my peers and the coaches
around the league say I'm the best right tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   He already has the vote of Bengals line coach Paul Alexander.
``In my opinion, Willie is the best right tackle in the NFL right
now. He has tremendous natural ability and worked very hard to
improve his first two seasons. I can't think of anybody I'd rather
have at the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is counting on Corey Dillon, last year's rookie running
sensation, to help with his candidancy. ``When Corey starts putting
together those 1,500-yard seasons, it will be good for me because
the majority of his plays are going to be run on Big Willie's
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Packing up: The Bengals will complete their three-day stay at
Spinney today. All players are scheduled to report to Georgetown by
4 p.m. Thursday. The first workout is at 11 a.m. on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis released: Guard Joel Davis has been released. Signed as a
free agent in 1996, the Army grad spent the next two seasons on
military reserve. He became expendable after the signing of
third-round draft pick Mike Goff.
</P>
<P>
   QB shuffle: Ex-Bengals David Klingler and Chad May are trying to
hook on with new teams as third-string quarterbacks. Klingler, a
bust since the Bengals took him in the first round of the '92
draft, is with Green Bay after two seasons in Oakland. May, who
played for Minnesota and Arizona, was with Cincinnati for only four
months. He was released after the team signed Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
