</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-NEWTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newton blames himself for poor season
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Now that Nate Newton has shed some
pounds, he no longer has the weight of the offense on his
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In the everything-looks-different offense the Dallas Cowboys
have installed at training camp, no player has made a greater
transformation than Newton. After losing 80 pounds in six months,
his physique would make Richard Simmons proud.
</P>
<P>
   When Newton was asked why the Cowboys were 6-10 last season, he
pointed a finger at himself. It's rare when a professional athlete
takes responsibility for the team's lack of success, but the
312-pound guard has accepted some heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let everybody down,'' Newton said Tuesday. ``Most of all, I
let myself down. I'm really a selfish person. I don't care about
what the other guys think. I just know that if I do my job, that's
what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, no one on offense played particularly well, with
the possible exception of left tackle Larry Allen. Newton, entering
his 13th season, was injured and out of shape. His disappearing act
in the second half of the season is one reason the team finished
20th in the NFL in offense.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Newton's off-the-field comedy act wasn't so funny.
After the season, team owner Jerry Jones had a private meeting with
Newton to discuss the lineman's future with the club. Some people
in the organization wondered whether Newton was still serious about
football.
</P>
<P>
   Jones challenged Newton to return in '98 with a new attitude and
a new look. There were no ultimatums, but Newton could read the
writing on the wall. At 36, Newton no longer can afford to enter
training camp with the scales tipping near 400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   When Coach Chan Gailey was hired in February, he shared similar
thoughts about Newton's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's followed Nate's career realizes this is the best
shape he's ever been in,'' Gailey said. ``Nate's a smart guy, and
he realized he was at a point in his career where conditioning was
a vital thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the lines, Newton was running scared. For the first time
in his 13- year career, he ran the risk of getting cut. His base
salary of $700,000, after all, buys a lot of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has run off several aging stars in Dallas in recent
months, and Newton did not want to be the next one getting a pink
slip.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, he got serious about conditioning. He spent months
with strength and conditioning coach Joe Juraszek and implemented a
strict training and diet schedule. Instead of fried foods, Newton
has been spotted eating salads and other vegetables at the campus
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   That was only part of the change. Newton shocked many of his
teammates when he arrived at Valley Ranch for 6 a.m. workouts. He
often was the first player to arrive and the last to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said critics were ``justified'' for ripping him and his
offensive teammates last year. Again, he said much of the blame
should be pinned on his inability to stay healthy and compete at a
high level.
</P>
<P>
   Juraszek said Newton weighed 381 pounds when they started
training together in the winter. By May, he dipped below 300 pounds
for the first time in a decade. The Cowboys want Newton at 315 when
the season starts Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate's pride created the energy and enthusiasm for him to get
back to the top,'' Juraszek said.
</P>
<P>
   The early returns look good. In one-on-one drills against
defensive tackle Leon Lett, Newton has won most of them. After
Tuesday morning's practice, Newton took a few extra laps around the
practice field before heading to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With Allen and a slimmed-down Newton on the left side of the
line, the Cowboys hope their ground game improves from their
disappointing 1997 output. The player who suffered most last season
was running back Emmitt Smith, who had few blocks to follow. He
scored a career-low four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   As for Newton, he would rather forget the '97 season. He refuses
to watch video of the team's miserable slide at the end of the
year. He doesn't want to see the fat guy who wears jersey No. 61.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't watch any of that nightmare,'' he said. ``That was
like looking at your mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
