<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-INDUSTRY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruise industry unaffected by Ecstasy fire
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ All that smoke made the ``fun ship''
Ecstasy look anything but fun _ yet it caused barely a ripple in
Carnival's business.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy will miss just two cruises _ Friday's three-night cruise
to Nassau and Monday's four-night cruise to Mexico _ while it
undergoes repair, Carnival officials say. Passengers on those two
cruises will be given a full refund and 50 percent off another
cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is expected back in service July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature to assess exact damages but we would estimate
that the impact on earnings would be approximately 1 cent per
share,'' said Howard Frank, Carnival Corp.'s vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, travel agents reminded clients that cruising is the
safest form of transportation. Of 45 million North American
passengers in the past decade, not one has died in a shipboard
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a flat tire and that can ruin your trip,'' said
Nancy Beiser, owner of Ship Shop Cruises in Palm Beach Gardens.
``We had people on the ship, and we haven't heard back from them.
They're probably still playing in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   She and other travel agents said they thought Carnival's
compensation for passengers was good. ``I thought Carnival did a
wonderful job,'' Beiser said. ``One client called and said, `Do I
get a free cruise? Carnival's giving out free cruises.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ship mishaps are so rare that cruise lines make compensation
decisions on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   When Carnival's Celebration had a fire in 1995, passengers
drifted for two days before being rescued by the Ecstasy. They got
a short free cruise in the Bahamas with an open bar.
</P>
<P>
   When a fire aboard the Universe Explorer killed five crewmen
during a cruise to Alaska in 1996, passengers were compensated just
for the cruise days they missed. That fire also started in the
laundry room, as did a 1997 fire aboard Cunard's Vistafjord.
</P>
<P>
   More passengers cruise on Carnival's 12 ``fun ships'' than any
other cruise line, and most cruise lines expect a record year _
thanks in part to the movie Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising's popularity has nearly doubled in the past decade,
from 2.9 million passengers in 1987 to 5.05 million last year,
according to Cruise Lines International. Another 20 new ships are
scheduled to sail by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On all those ships, passengers must strap on life vests and
report for a mandatory safety drill before they can indulge too
heavily at the buffets and bars.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers aboard the Ecstasy had already run through their
drill when the fire broke out Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As cruising has grown, so, too, has its regulation. Cruise ships
operate under the standards of a United Nations organization, the
International Maritime Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long history of safety,'' aboard big luxury liners
such as the Ecstasy, said Diana Orban, spokeswoman for the Cruise
Lines International Association, a trade group. ``One of the reason
incidents like this get so much attention is because they're so
rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnival will evaluate the safety standards on the Ecstasy and
its seven identical sister ships, said Tim Gallagher, Carnival
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire should demonstrate that everything works, the fire
suppression system worked,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   None of this bothers cruiser William Wooldridge of Port St.
Lucie, who turned on the television Monday before supper and
wondered whether his vacation would go up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife, `Honey, they're burning our boat!' ''
Wooldridge, 67, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wooldridges are still planning to shove off Aug. 3 on a
four-day Ecstasy trip to Key West and Cozumel, Mexico. They have no
fear of embarking on the same trip as the 2,575 vacationers they
watched Monday huddling on the bow of a burning ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old Coast Guard man and I have no problem getting
aboard that ship,'' he said. ``I have all the faith in the world in
Carnival.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writer Clay Lambert and the Associated
Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
