<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the water and in synch
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somehow I always expected Richard Simmons, all perky and kooky
and calesthenic, to be the first to introduce hairy legs to the
elegant sport of synchronized swimming. Clearly, he has no fear of
looking foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Then along comes Bill May, pride of the Santa Clara Aquamaids,
and strange, new competitive juices enter the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Monday July 20, the native of upstate New York won a pair of
silver medals at the Goodwill Games and did so without the
traditional accessories of sequins and hair goop. What's more, he
appeared to be throughly enjoying his interaction with duet partner
Kristine Lum.
</P>
<P>
   By the conclusion of their free program, choreographed to the
steamy strains of Ravel's ``Bolero,'' these crazy mixed-up synchro
kids had a few judges fanning themselves with their scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain passion and intensity that men bring to the
sport and our free routine today was designed specifically to
showcase that male-female relationship,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   Basic chemistry, sort of like Adam and Eve might have been
before they got in over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, however, Eve and Adam is more like it. The 27-member
Palm Beach Coralytes kids synchro program has been girls-only since
its founding in 1985. And at the Sunshine State Games synchro
competition earlier this summer, only three boys showed up from a
talent pool the size of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bill May, but who else will?
</P>
<P>
   I would give water ballet a whirl myself, of course, except for
this peculiar medical condition. Every minute or so, my lungs
require oxygen. Besides that, Dave George pinched into a pair of
Speedos is an image too horrible to ponder for more than a few
seconds without going blind or insane or both... aaargh, too late!
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, some guys who could pull it off if they
wished, and with a minimum of snickering.
</P>
<P>
   One summer a few years back Matt Taylor, a Jupiter attorney, was
talked into joining the Coralytes Masters level synchronized
swimming team by his wife Lori.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really was no reason not to do it,'' said Taylor, a
triathlete who also swims in the Masters program at North Palm
Beach County Club. ``I don't care what people say or think. If it's
fun and it's a good physical activity that I enjoy, I don't see any
problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that Taylor and Ben Walton, the husband of another
Coralyte Masters level swimmer, began to practice their pirouettes
at the Lake Lytal pool and the Santaluces Aquatic Complex. They
learned quickly that maintaining the proper synchronized swimming
game face _ bright and smiling above the water line, red and
bloated beneath it _ is a supreme challenge. And they learned that
one summer mirroring the artistic arm and leg movements of an
eight-person synchro team was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're getting ready to compete,'' said Taylor, ``and the
adrenalin is flowing, you have a hard time holding your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   For women, it's no big deal. They, after all, deliver babies.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Dowling is a Coralyte synchro swimmer and an assistant
coach for the Masters program. She was in the pool working on her
solo routine for two hours Tuesday and she'll be back out there for
two more today. Evelyn is 70 and in synch with the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do it the way the rule book says,'' Dowling said.
``When Bill May gets his legs up, he's right on the mark. But he
and his partner did more of a dancing thing in the water. With the
female swimmers, like the Russian pair that won the gold medal,
everything is more synchronized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is the one breaking through. I think it's great for a man
to be competing in our sport. I say good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way, baby. All that remains is the perfection
of a macho butt-slap that won't look so suspicious on those
underwater cameras. endit
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-21-98 1830E
</P>
