<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7818 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KERSEE23-COX     07-22 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERSEE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joyner changed perception of female athletes
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At many track meets, heptathlons are contested at odd
hours before the main events, when there's just a smattering of
friends, relatives and coaches dotting the stands. Tuesday, July
21, however, Jackie Joyner-Kersee was center stage at the Goodwill
Games as she started two days of competition in the final
heptathlon of a career that has yielded six Olympic medals, three
of them gold.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, who has won every Goodwill Games heptathlon, not
only made U.S. fans care about what had been an obscure mix of
seven events, she was one of the pioneers that changed our
perception of female athletes. With her grace, and with her sweat
and effort, she helped break down stereotypes and give younger
female athletes, such as sprint sensation Marion Jones, a most
worthy role model.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee was named by a grandmother after Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis in 1962, in hopes, she laughed, that she would
become ``the first lady of something.'' It was a tall order on the
mean streets of East St. Louis, where Joyner-Kersee grew up and
where she still returns to help the community.
</P>
<P>
   Her first athletic activity was celebrating the achievements of
male athletes _ a cheerleader. But what she really liked about
cheerleading was the jumping. As a kid she liked soaring off the
family's high front porch. The landings were a little hard, but
there was a sandbox just across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee remembered, ``My sisters and I, we went to a park
and took sand and put it into potato chip bags. We didn't have too
much grass so we wanted to make a soft landing. Bu we did it before
mom came home because we didn't want her to know.''
</P>
<P>
   With her jumping and her pigtails and cut-off jeans, there was
an easy label for Joyner-Kersee _ tomboy, not athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a sophomore we had to practice at 6 o'clock in
the evening, after the boys. At that time it was felt we were girls
trying to play basketball,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``We won state
that year in track and all of sudden things started to change.
People started respecting us as athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon her mom didn't have to worry about her going to
practice so late. The girls had the gym after school; the boys
played when the champs were done.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee was talented enough in basketball to play for UCLA
and even gave one of the new women's pro leauges, the American
Basketball League, a fling. But track was her best sport and her
all-around talent had the perfect outlet, the heptathlon.
Joyner-Kersee got the itch to try it in 1975 after seeing a movie
about the last great female athlete to be so versatile, Texas- bred
Babe Didrikson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Joyner-Kersee had what she now describes as her biggest
thrill. ``Being the first woman to score 7,000 points ... that was
the beginning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 she had what should have been her crowning moment,
winning both the heptathlon and long jump in the Seoul Olympics.
Those Games, however, were marred by the suspicions that more track
athletes than Ben Johnson were using steroids. Brazilian Joaquin
Cruz pointed a finger at Joyner-Kersee and her famous
sister-in-law, Florence Griffith-Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My moment of triumph, my moment of joy, was in 1988 and with
the drug issue it was like my performance was swept under the
rug,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``I hope no other person achieves a
great thing and has to deal with innuendo and accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, who is coached by her husband, Bob, won the gold
in the heptathlon in 1992. In 1996, however, she was injured at the
U.S. Olympic Trials, finishing second. That was her last
competitive heptathlon until this week, but she did compete in the
long jump in Atlanta. On her last jump, she moved from sixth place
to third in spite of her sore right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, who suffers from asthma, sometimes has struggled
in the 800 meters, the heptathlon's final event. But she has said,
``If I was going to die, I was going to die crossing that finish
line. I was never going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of competitiveness helped changed the view of women in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key for Billie Jean (King), Martina (Navratilova),
Chris Evert, Florence ... all we ever wanted was to be respected
for what we were trying to do,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``I think
that's what's happening now. Now people are accepting us and saying
that it's OK. It's OK to have girls go out and play soccer. It's OK
if they want to play baseball, it's OK if they want to play
football, that they're not going to be criticized, that they're not
going to be looked upon as being different or that something's
wrong with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee's farewell to track will come this weekend when
she competes in the long jump at a meet in Edwardsville, Ill.,
honoring her. Although she has commercial endorsements and a sports
marketing firm, she finds time to give back to her old community.
She is currently helping to build a youth center.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been able to use her success to bring up other
people,'' Bobby Kersee said. ``She's taken her talent and put it in
other things that will benefit people after she retires. That's the
blessing about her sucess. We're not losing a great athlete from
track and field, we're losing a great person.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the first lady of track.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
