<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-PROMISES23-COX     07-22 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-PROMISES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology famous for breaking promises
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Technology is famous for breaking its promises.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago ``the next big thing'' was network computers: They
would would cost less than $500 and have no hard drive. Instead,
the network computer would keep all of its information on the
Internet. To retrieve a document or game, you had to be online.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four months later, the idea lies in the technology
graveyard, along with virtual reality glasses and long distance
over the Internet. With computer prices so low (you can buy a great
refurbished computer for about $600) there is no need for the
network computer. This is unfortunate because network computing was
such a good idea. If we kept our data online, maybe we would be
more concerned about the information that was on the Internet. With
network computing, maybe we wouldn't put up with spamming and
kiddie porn sites. With network computing, the Internet would be a
better place.
</P>
<P>
   Nextec www.nextec.net) is a company that still believes in the
idea of network computing and in what the concept can do for the
Web. On June 11, the company _ which is responsible for the 100
million-hit-a-month RotoNews (www.rotonews.com) fantasy sport site
_ posted FreeDrive (www.FreeDrive.com), a site where you can store
any information you might otherwise keep on your computer for free.
Just by signing on, you receive a password-protected 7.5 megabytes
of storage (the equivalent of about five floppy disks) to hold
pictures, files or to back up your hard drive. To date, the site
has accumulated 5,000 users (with no advertising).
</P>
<P>
   ``FreeDrive is your own personal Web hard drive, a virtual drive
that resides on the Internet,'' said Michael Rhodes, president and
CEO of Nextec.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of the FreeDrive goes far beyond being a virtual
hard drive. It is the beginning of network computing, the beginning
of keeping our information online.
</P>
<P>
   FreeDrive makes it possible for multiple people to view your
files, thus encouraging the formation of separate virtual
communities. You can give your password to friends and colleagues,
then they can then log on to your virtual hard drive and view what
you are working on. On the FreeDrive site, this is called
``carpooling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we've only been up for a month, people are still in the
self-education phase and not really using their storage for very
much,'' Rhodes said. ``We have, however, seen the `carpooling'
function use quadruple in the past week (from 5,000 to 20,000
users).''
</P>
<P>
   The interest of the ``carpoolers,'' along with the initial
sign-on of 5,000 users, shows that people are truly interested in
storing their information online and in the original concept of
network computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to build a community of `drivers' that will learn
and grow together,'' Rhodes said. ``A community that will help
change the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this site hasn't been set up for charity. Nextec sees
a definite marketability to its site. ``Multiple Drivers,'' where
other users can alter and add to material on your FreeDrive, costs
an extra $4.95 a month. Extra megabytes of storage also cost money
and the site will have banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its capitalistic leanings, FreeDrive has hit on a great
idea. If we start storing our data, pictures and documents on the
Net, then the Internet becomes more of a home for us. Once it's a
home, we will start treating the Internet as what it was meant to
be: a communication tool for the exchange of ideas and content.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to look at the Internet as more of a tool
than they did before, as an expansion of their own PC,'' Rhodes
said. ``FreeDrive is a practical application that these people will
use and will definitely expand people's belief and confidence in
what the Internet is.'' Send questions, comments, ideas, products,
graft and fan mail to Gregory Kallenberg at
gkallenbergstatesman.com or write him at P.O. Box 670, Austin
78767. WARES
</P>
<P>
   It's summertime, and you have the kids at home. By now you've
probably done it all: Schlitterbahn, Sea World, the Austin Museum
of Art and the Capitol. Now, you're all at home, making peanut
butter, banana and ham sandwiches and looking for something to do.
You don't want to turn on the television because you don't want
your child dressing like Ginger Spice or talking like Judge Judy.
Why not buy your kid a couple of Broderbund games and let them
expand their minds while having fun? ``Kid Pix'' and the new,
improved ``Where in the World is Carmen San diego?'' will fulfill
both of those desires. ``Kid Pix'' is a drawing program which will
keep your 3- to 12-year-old occupied for hours. And ``Carmen San
Diego,'' a mystery entertainment game for 9-year-olds and up, has
been improved to include Internet links and teach your child
foreign languages. Available for the Mac and PC for $39.95.
SITE-SEER N members.aol.com/rrmwebsite/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Every now and then you come across Cox Newspapers
</P>
