<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7832 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE     07-22 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Of the world's major religions, which ones have the
most members?
</P>
<P>
   Q: An obituary for Richard McDonald said he was a co-founder of
McDonald's. I always thought Ray Kroc was the founder. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kroc was a franchise genius credited with making the
McDonald's empire what it is today, but he wasn't the originator of
the fast-food burger-and-fries concept. Richard McDonald, who died
at 89 Tuesday in Manchester, N.H., and his brother, Maurice, were
the ones who pioneered what would become the giant chain. It also
was Richard McDonald, not Kroc, who dreamed up the company's
symbol, the ``golden arches.''
</P>
<P>
   The McDonald brothers first operated a car-hop shop in 1940 in
San Bernardino, Calif. After World War II ended, as freeways opened
and customers became interested in speedy service, the brothers
came up the idea of a limited-menu place serving inexpensive food
fast. In December 1948, they opened their first hamburger stand in
San Bernardino, and by 1954 they had sold 21 franchises and opened
nine outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Kroc, a food service equipment salesman who owned marketing
rights to milkshake mixers, saw the potential for the brothers'
concept and became their franchise agent. In 1955, Kroc founded
Franchise Realty Corp., and opened his first McDonald's store in
Des Plaines, Ill. In 1960, he changed the name to McDonald's Corp.,
and in 1961bought world franchise rights from the McDonald brothers
for $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, Richard McDonald returned to his native New
Hampshire. Brother Maurice died in 1971. Kroc died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that the government is trying to
track down more than 7,000 people who are owed pensions they earned
from private defined pension plans that have been closed. The
people's names are posted on the Internet. What is the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. is undertaking the
project. Those with computer access can search easily by name,
company and/or state by using the Pension Search Directory on the
PBGC's Internet site: http://search.pbgc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did the term ``honky-tonk'' come from? I've got a bet
riding on this.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several theories, so you and your bet-mate will
have to decide which to accept. The book Picturesque Expressions: A
Thematic Dictionary says the origin lies in the ``tinny, honklike
sounds of ragtime heard in cheap nightclubs and brothels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins traces
the first printed use of the word, describing a ``cheap dance hall
featuring gambling or burlesque,'' to a February 1894 Oklahoma
newspaper. It reported on a honk-a-tonk ``well attended by
ball-heads, bachelors and leading citizens.'' The encyclopedia says
no one is sure how the word originated, adding that the British
attribute it to America, relating it to the slang word ``honky.''
It goes on to say an American authority claims it's from the
English word ``bonk,'' meaning ``to idle about.''
</P>
<P>
   The word honky, by the way, is defined in the Morris Dictionary
of Word and Phrase Origins as a corruption of hunkie or hunky, ``a
slurring term originally applied to white laboring-class men of
Hungarian origin.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought the first gold strike or discovery of gold in the
United States was at Dahlonega, Ga. However, the Reed Historical
Site in North Carolina says it's the first site. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: A gold nugget the size of a small smoothing iron was found at
the Reed Mine in Cabarrus County, N.C., in 1799. Gold in limited
quantities was discovered in the area, but the word ``strike,''
implying a sizable quantity, wouldn't apply. Dahlonega lays claim
to the first important discovery of gold in the United States in
1828. The federal government established a mint there that operated
from 1838 to 1861, when it closed because of Georgia's break with
the Union.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are my legal rights if I see a pet or child left
unattended in a hot parked car? Realizing that one has only so much
time to locate the driver, what is the best course of action?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your question implies a conclusion that you should ``do
something'' and mentions your ``rights.'' The real question, said
Daryl Robinson of the Georgia Department of Law, is what are your
responsibilities. Assuming you're a stranger acting as a ``Good
Samaritan,'' you have no legal obligation; but the Good Samaritan
law protects you if you act in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Several considerations are involved, Robinson said. For example,
has the child (or pet) been unattended for one minute or one hour?
If it's a child, do you know if he or she is asleep, or suffering
from heat exhaustion? Are you thinking about breaking a car window
or forcing a door, and if so, do you really have enough facts to
take such action?
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, unless a clear emergency is apparent, the
safer response under most circumstances is to notify the nearest
law enforcement officer, Robinson said. That person will deal with
the situation in an official capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In two recent movies, ``Titanic'' and ``Contact,'' when
people are calling on the radio, they say ``CQ'' before stating
their message. What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: CQ originated as a general call preceding the transmission of
radio signals (it stands for Call to Quarters ), and evolved as a
general call to talk to anyone interested. CQD (Come Quick _
Danger) was an international distress signal used before SOS.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that three German men who worked on
the rocket team that put Americans on the moon all died within
three days of each other, all in the Huntsville, Ala., area. What
happened to these men?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to published accounts, all three members of the
dwindling ranks of Wernher von Braun's World War II German rocket
team _ Max Nowak, Heinrich Paetz and Albert Schuler _ died of
natural causes. Although it may seem unusual, perhaps, that all
died within less than a week, they were of a certain age: Nowak,
89; Paetz, 88; and Schuler, 83. As reported by The Associated
Press, the original von Braun team consisted of 127 scientists.
Only about 30 to 40 are still living, said Ernst Stuhlinger, von
Braun's chief assistant, and Konrad Dannenberg, a propulsion
engineer for von Braun, both in Huntsville. Of that group, about a
dozen remain in Huntsville, home of NASA's Marshall Space Flight
Center and the Army's Redstone Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it safe to be in a boat when lightning is occurring?
</P>
<P>
   A: Experts say you should never offer yourself as a potential
target when lightning threatens. The best advice to help save your
life is to get out of the water and off small boats, and not to use
metal objects such as fishing rods.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that cooking meat kills the E. coli bacteria.
Does cooking also affect in any way the growth hormone that might
be present in meat?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since cooking methods and temperatures vary, it's difficult
to say that cooking has a particular effect on hormones in meat,
said Judy Harrison of the University of Georgia department of foods
and nutrition. But you needn't be too concerned about the hormone
issue, she added. For one thing, hormones occur naturally in
animals. And for another, the Agriculture Department's Food Safety
and Inspection Service conducts an extensive monitoring program to
prevent the marketing of animals containing unacceptable levels of
animal drugs, pesticides and other chemicals. Human bodies, by the
way, produce hormones in quantities much greater than ever would be
eaten in beef or any other food, Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Aren't telemarketing calls limited to certain hours? I got a
solicitation at 8:25 a.m. recently. I thought such calls weren't
permitted before 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A: With some exceptions, the hours are restricted by federal law
to 8 a.m. to 9 p.m., according to the American Telemarketing
Association in North Hollywood, Calif. The two governing rules used
by telemarketers are the Telephone Consumer Protection Act and the
Telemarketing Sales Rule, an ATA representative said. Some states
impose variations, and some states follow business hours, which
vary, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true, as I have heard, that chocolate is poison for
dogs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chocolate could prove fatal to a dog in some cases, said Dr.
Edward Taylor of Alpharetta, past president of the Georgia
Veterinary Medical Association. You might not notice a problem,
other than agitation or nervousness, if healthy dogs eat small
amounts of chocolate. But larger amounts _ several mouthfuls, for
example _ can cause a fast heartbeat or other heart rhythm
abnormalities, similar in effect to caffeine in humans, that could
result in death in a dog, especially if the animal already has
heart problems. The culprit in chocolate is the chemical
theobromine, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
