<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE     07-22 1945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that a salvage operation within the past year came
very close to retrieving a large section of the Titanic. Do you
know if the people involved will try it again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Another expedition is planned in August, and you can watch
part of it on television. The expedition you mention ended Aug. 31,
1996, when nylon lines being used to lift a 21-ton portion of the
Titanic's hull snapped while seas were getting rough and expedition
mmbers were close to exhaustion. The hull section was 70 yards
beneath the surface when it broke loose from flotation balloons and
returned to its resting place of 84 years.
</P>
<P>
   RMS Titanic Inc., known as salvor-in-possession, will try again
soon to lift that same hull section. ``We have worked everything
out for the August attempt, and this time we're anticipating
recovery, if all goes well,'' Michelle Rollman of RMS Titanic told
Q&AMP;A. She described the 25-by-30-foot hull section as ``small
relative to the whole Titanic, but very large relative to the other
items from the ship that have been recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 8 p.m. Aug. 16, Discovery Channel will have a
two-hour broadcast live from the wreck site in the North Atlantic.
It will mix live and taped footage of all facets of the ongoing
research.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article showing how much money lobbyists in
Washington spend listed the National Committee to Preserve Social
Security and Medicare at $7.7 million. Where does that organization
get its funding?
</P>
<P>
   A: The committee, which describes itself as a ``grassroots
senior citizens' advocacy and education association,'' is funded
entirely by its members _ the public _ paying annual membership
fees of $10, said spokeswoman Kris Geddings. It has 5.5 million
members. Some of them make additional donations, Geddings said, but
any such extra donations are entirely voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you provide statistical information on the new Hong Kong
airport: size of site, number and length of runways, passenger
capacity, parking spaces and so on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hong Kong's new Chek Lap Kok Airport, which opened July 6,
covers 3,083 acres. The passenger terminal area covers 554,000
square feet. The airport has one 12,471-foot runway now, with a
second runway expected to be operational by late 1998. Passenger
capacity is 35 million a year now, with a potential growth
estimated at 89 million people. It has 3,100 parking spaces, is
served by 46 airlines, and is connected by train to Hong Kong's
Central Station.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport covers
3,750 acres. The passenger terminal, including all concourses,
covers 5.7 million square feet (130 acres). Hartsfield has four
parallel east-west runways: two measuring 9,000 feet long, one
10,000 and one 11,889. In 1996, Hartsfield handled 63,344,730
passengers. It has 26,000 parking spaces; serves 48 airlines (32
passenger, 16 cargo); and is connected to the MARTA rapid rail
system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do any companies still pay O.J. Simpson for endorsements? I
saw him being interviewed and he was wearing a cap with a Nike
logo.
</P>
<P>
   A: Simpson must have been simply wearing a cap he liked. He was
dropped from all his endorsements, his attorneys have reported
several times, after he was charged with murdering his former wife,
Nicole Simpson, and her friend Ron Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How many nuclear devices has the U.S. government exploded
inside the United States for test purposes since such testing
began?
</P>
<P>
   A. A total of 1,030 verified U.S. tests have been conducted
since the first one July 16, 1945. Most of them (more than 900)
have been at the Nevada Test Site (in Nye County, Nev.), with
others at Nellis Air Force Range in Nevada; Amchitka, an Aleutian
Island off the coast of Alaska; Hattiesburg, Miss.; Alamagordo,
Carlsbad and Farmington, N.M.; Grand Valley and Rifle, Colo.;
Fallon, Nev.; in one at an unspecified site in central Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Of those outside the United States, many tests between June 1946
and November 1962 were in the Marshall Islands (known as the
Pacific Proving Grounds), Christmas Island and Johnston Atoll in
the Pacific Ocean, or over the South Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, 1963, the United States and the former Soviet Union
signed the Limited Test Ban Treaty, which effectively banned
testing of nuclear weapons in the atmosphere, the oceans and space.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 and 1976, the United States and former Soviet Union also
signed the Threshold Test Ban Treaty and the Peaceful Nuclear
Explosions Treaty, respectively, restricting all nuclear test
explosions to yields no greater than 150 kilotons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I graduated years ago from the high school at Subic Bay Naval
Base in the Philippines. Can you give us an update what has become
of it, and Clark Air Force Base, after they were abandoned by the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since the Americans were booted out in 1992, Subic Bay _ now
called Subic Bay Freeport _ has become a surprising success. One of
the reasons: When the U.S. flag was lowered on Subic Nov. 24, 1992,
the Americans left behind $8 billion in infrastructure _ meaning
buildings, power plant and storage tanks. The facilities were
placed under the guard of 8,000 volunteers so there would be no
repeat of what happened at Clark, where looters stripped the base
of everything from light fixtures to toilet bowls. Clark was
abandoned in 1991 after it was buried in volcanic ash by the
eruption of Mount Pinatubo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the administration of the Subic Bay Metropolitan
Authority, the Subic port quickly attracted manufacturing and
investment, and today Japanese and Taiwanese industrial parks
manufacture a variety of products, from computer motherboards to
armored personnel carriers. Subic also became the regional hub for
Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   While Clark lags behind, Filipino officials say companies are
beginning to pour money into development.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV documentary on Roy Rogers' life and career mentioned
briefly that his second wife, Dale Evans, had a son from her first
marriage. There was no further mention of him. Do you have any
details?
</P>
<P>
   A: Evans was married at age 15, long before she met Roy Rogers.
Thomas Frederick Fox Jr. was born to that marriage, which ended in
divorce in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a music minister in Sacramento, Calif., has always shunned
the limelight. But in a Washington Post interview in 1984, Dale
Evans said her first-born son was responsible for her religious
conversion in 1948, when he would have been 19 or 20. ``My son,
grown then, asked me to accept Jesus Christ,'' Evans told the
interviewer. ``I went to church with him one night. He wanted me to
accept Christ right then, but I didn't. Now, bear in mind that Roy
was No. 1 in box office. I was embarrassed. I didn't know how it
would affect Roy. I went home and prayed all by myself. And all of
a sudden, the Lord just unrolled my life. And you know what? Six
weeks later, Roy was right there with us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Texas Gov. George W. Bush explained what appears to be
his inconsistent approach in two capital offense cases, that of
Karla Faye Tucker and Henry Lucas?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tucker's wasn't the only case in which Bush didn't use the
power of his office to halt an execution. Since he became governor
Jan. 17, 1995, 67 men and one woman (Tucker) have been put to
death. In an interview in the Dallas Morning News, Bush explained
his reasoning in commuting the sentence of Lucas: ``The first
question I ask in every case is whether there is any doubt about
the individual's guilt or innocence. This is the first case since I
have been the governor when the answer to that question was yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas had been scheduled to die by injection June 30 for raping
and strangling a woman whose body was found in a highway culvert
north of Austin on Oct. 31, 1979. Lucas confessed to that crime in
the early 1960s, when he was building his reputation as the worst
mass murderer in American history by admitting to as many as 600
slayings. But in 1985, after it was proved that he couldn't have
committed many of the murders, he recanted all his confessions.
</P>
<P>
   A strong supporter of the death penalty, Bush said no execution
should be carried out if there's a chance that the defendant is
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People often use the word ``cop.'' What is the origin, and is
it considered derogatory?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several theories about the origin. One is that it
comes from the initials c.o.p., from constable on patrol, dating to
the late 1800s when English police officers were called constables.
Some people believe it's short for copper, referring to the copper
badges worn by police officers, and others that it's from the
copper buttons once worn by British bobbies. Untrue, according to
Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins, because the term cop,
in the sense of ``one who captures or snatches,'' was recorded as
early as 1704, and bobbies didn't come into existence until 1828,
when Sir Robert Peel secured passage of Britain's first modern
Police Act. Probably any police officer would prefer to be called
just that, and it's well known that J. Edgar Hoover long found
``cop'' to be a source of irritation. But in most usages, it isn't
intended to be derogatory.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The news media reports there's a $1 million reward for Eric
Robert Rudolph, wanted in connection with the abortion clinic
bombing in Birmingham, Ala. I saw an FBI poster and it said the
reward was ``up to'' $1 million. Which is correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: The correct wording is ``up to'' $1 million for information
leading directly to the arrest of Rudolph. Typically in such cases
a lesser reward amount is possible for useful information that
doesn't necessarily lead to a suspect's arrest, according to the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If someone is awarded the $1 million FBI reward for turning
in Eric Robert Rudolph, is that money tax-exempt?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It's taxable to the recipient, the IRS says. The person
receiving the reward money also would receive a 1099 Miscellaneous
document from the IRS showing the amount of the reward and,
possibly, any amount already withheld for tax. This would be in any
type of reward with money paid by the federal government, not just
the reward offered in the Rudolph case, said IRS spokesman Eric
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Of the world's major religions, which ones have the most
members?
</P>
<P>
   A: As you may imagine, absolute numbers aren't possible, but
here's some data that may be useful. According to the 1998 Guinness
Book of World Records, in 1994, Christianity was the world's
largest religion with some 1.9 billion adherents (or 33.7 percent
of the world's population). Of these, 1.06 billion were Roman
Catholics. The largest non-Christian religion, again in 1994, was
Islam, with about 1.03 billion followers.
</P>
<P>
   World Book Encyclopedia's somewhat differing statistics are for
1993, with an estimated 1.6 billion followers of Christianity
broken down this way: Roman Catholic, 1.04 billion; Protestant,
382.3 million; and Orthodox, 173.6 million. Non-Christian: Islam,
1.014 billion; Hinduism, 751.4 million; Buddhism, 334 million;
Chinese folk religion (defined as a system of beliefs that includes
Confucianism and Taoism), 141 million; Judaism, 12.9 million; and
Shintoism, 3.33 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
