<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDOW-DRESSINGS-NYT &LR;      07-22 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOW-DRESSINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SULTRY SUMMER, WINDOWS IN DISHABILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With 90-degree days upon us, even windows seem to be
crying out for a state of semi-undress. Call it the lingerie look
for windows: One curtain panel even comes with satin bra straps.
The new window dressings are what Scarlett O'Hara would have had on
her windows, if she had bought curtains at Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer cotton batiste panels are embroidered like a fine
nightgown, with small maple leaves. Panels come in white or ivory,
56 inches wide with a rod pocket, in lengths of 16 inches ($18), 30
inches ($28), 63 inches ($48) and 84 inches ($58). From the Garnet
Hill catalog: (800) 622-6216.
</P>
<P>
   New Leaf cotton-polyester sheer panels, with assorted leaf and
flower patterns, come in white or off-white, with a rod pocket. The
90-by-118-inch panels cost $160 each at Zona, 97 Greene St (at
Prince Street).
</P>
<P>
   Sheer curtains of hand-woven cotton with tab tops come in
intense colors. The 44-by-84-inch panels, made in India, are
available in purple, lime green, cobalt blue or saffron yellow; $64
a pair at Ad Hoc Softwares, 410 West Broadway (Spring Street).
Sheer white panels with blue or green plaid are 40 inches wide and
are offered in two lengths: 63 inches ($36 a panel) or 84 inches
($40 a panel). From the Garnet Hill catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Raisin-colored curtains, with lace trim and satin bra straps,
look like a woman's slip. Layer the 100 percent cotton gauze
curtains under draperies or hang them alone like a window camisole.
In beige, pink, gray or blue, 24 inches wide by 120 inches long,
$190 a panel; other sizes by custom order. From ABC Carpet and
Home, 888 Broadway (19th Street).
</P>
<P>
   Silk organza panels are hand embroidered in India with seed
pearls, sequins and beads. One panel, 44 inches by 90 inches, with
gold, silver or copper borders, is $395 at Zona.
</P>
<P>
   For a different taste, there is World War II Army surplus
netting. An 8-foot square costs $75 at H, 335 East Ninth St.
</P>
</TEXT>
