<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-NUKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON CALLS U.S. SANCTIONS POLICY `A MESS,' ASSAILS CLINTON ON
CHINA, RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton must abandon his efforts to
expand trade with Russia and China until those countries stop
selling nuclear weapons technology to U.S. enemies, a leading
congressional critic said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who investigated alleged Chinese
contributions to Clinton's re-election campaign, said the
president's zeal for doing business with Russia and China has
resulted in Clinton ``jumping through hoops to avoid imposing
sanctions'' on these countries for selling technology to terrorist
countries, such as Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The senator called U.S. sanctions policy ``a mess,'' noting that
smaller American trading partners, India and Pakistan, were
summarily penalized for testing nuclear weapons while Russia and
China have escaped sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a major problem with Russia and China,'' Thompson
said. ``We've got to change our philosophy and who we're trading
with ... We need to distinguish between those nations that pose a
threat to us and those that don't.``
</P>
<P>
   State Department press officers disagreed with Thompson's
assessment, saying the United States is working closely with Russia
and China to create and implement effective ways to block the
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who is considering a presidential run in 2000,
assailed Clinton for focusing on trade and not pressing China more
on its technology sales during the president's trip to the Asian
nation earlier this summer. The senator urged Vice President Al
Gore to raise the issue with Russian officials when he visits their
country this week and said the president and Congress should
withhold financial aid from Russia until its leaders stop selling
nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good stuff money is not going to be sustainable unless
they modify their behavior,'' Thompson said. ``We cannot give them
a blank check.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting U.S. leaders ``don't have much choice,'' Thompson said
national security would be placed at risk if the president and
Congress fail to address Russia and China's selling of nuclear
technology. ``I don't see how we explain that failure to the next
generation,'' the senator added.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, as chair of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
conducted months of congressional hearings that failed to show
whether Clinton illegally received campaign contributions from the
Chinese government during the president's 1996 re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who does not face re-election this year, said he
will ``take a look'' at running for president in 2000 after the
elections this November. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
