<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONOPOLY-TOKEN-TEX     07-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONOPOLY-TOKEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONOPOLY OFFERS NEW TOKENS FOR OUR AFFECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The little doohickies are embedded in our national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Ask any American, and most will remember the thimble, the iron,
the wheelbarrow, the battleship, the shoe, the top hat, the cannon,
the rocking horse and the popular fought-over car.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Brothers, which makes Monopoly, is adding a new token to
its game, the first change in 40 years. The toymaker is asking
people to decide whether a 1935 biplane, a piggy bank or a sack of
money will join the ranks of playing pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's another marketing gimmick. But if you look closely,
and if you find a psychologist with a sense of humor, you can learn
something about yourself _ and your playmates _ by examining your
favorite token.
</P>
<P>
   Take the roadster. Choose that and you are a free spirit, a
thrill-seeker, an adventurous type, says Dr. Joe Tecce, professor
of psychology at Boston College, and a heck of a good sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we make a choice ... it is a kind of projective test in
that we choose what fills our needs, fits our personality and makes
us feel good about ourselves,'' Tecce says.
</P>
<P>
   Were you the thimble or the iron? If so, that tells Tecce you
are probably female, practical and have a touch of domesticity.
</P>
<P>
   Psychobabble wasn't part of the first game _ and neither were
tokens. Charles Darrow, who brought the game to Parker Brothers,
suggested that players use household items such as buttons and
pennies. The first tokens, four wooden pawns, came the next year,
in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Monopoly added the tokens we remember in 1937. Because the game
arrived during the Great Depression, the tokens represented things
found in any household, said Monopoly historian Jack McMahon. They
were a rocking horse, a purse, a lantern, a thimble, a shoe and an
iron. Two others _ a top hat and a car _ symbolized ``Rich Uncle
Pennybags,'' the imaginary character whose face still decorates the
box today. The cannon and battleship were swiped from the game
Conflict.
</P>
<P>
   They lasted until World War II, when a metal shortage turned
them into abstract wooden figures like you'd find in Sorry!
</P>
<P>
   Seven other tokens surfaced periodically, but McMahon doesn't
know the history of the bathtub, the candlestick, the streetcar,
the trophy, the roadster with a driver, the anti-aircraft gun or
``Lucy'' the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   The big change came in the early 1950s, when Monopoly booted the
lantern, the purse and the rocking horse, and replaced them with
Uncle Pennybags' dog, a horse with rider and a wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   The doohickies haven't changed since.
</P>
<P>
   United States Monopoly champion Roger Craig uses the iron,
contending that it hides him behind hotels and houses. World
champion Christopher Woo prefers the top hat, for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   Psychology professor Tecce says the top hat tells him you are
elegant and glamorous _ or you want to be. The top hat is also
elitist. ``Maybe your wish fulfillment is at work here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The wheelbarrow? That's the blue collar token. It says you are
proud of your hard work. ``Bill Gates would not choose this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who chooses the dog is a kind, gentle, sensitive and
generous soul. The shoe is another matter. It tells Tecce ``you
could not be a more practical, pragmatic person.''
</P>
<P>
   The battleship and cannon tell Tecce you are probably male, and
these icons ``appeal to you because of the empowerment they
represent.'' Pick the horse with rider and you are competitive,
athletic, outdoorsy and outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   The new tokens come with baggage, too.
</P>
<P>
   Vote for the biplane, and it says you are a romantic who throws
conventional wisdom to the wind. Pick the piggy bank, and you are
thrifty and sensitive to aesthetics and animals. The sack of money
means one thing: You are hard-nosed, unsentimental and
business-minded.
</P>
<P>
   You're the guy who always wins.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLANE OR THE PIG?
</P>
<P>
   To vote for the new Monopoly token, call (888) 81-TOKEN, or go
to www.monopoly.com. Voting ends Sept. 30. The biplane is winning
so far.
</P>
<P>
   SIDER FOR JUMP Monopoly trivia
</P>
<P>
   Rich Uncle Pennybags' first name is Milton. He is called
``Chairman of the Board.'' He debuted in 1936 on the Chance and
Community Chest cards. He once won second place in a beauty
contest. His hobbies are collecting pennies, making millions,
building monopolies, avoiding the luxury tax and strolling on
Boardwalk. He lives on Marvin Gardens with his wife, Madge. They
have three nephews, Andy, Randy and Sandy, and a pet dog, Scotty
the terrier.
</P>
<P>
   We are not making this up. His biography is copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   Monopoly is published in 26 languages in 80 countries. A Braille
edition arrived in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The preferred properties of the current U.S. Monopoly champion
are Illinois, Indiana and Kentucky. The current international
champion favors the orange properties _ New York Avenue, Tennessee
Avenue and St. James Place.
</P>
<P>
   The most-landed-on properties are Illinois Avenue, Go and the
B&AMP;O Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   The guy in jail is Jake the Jailbird. Police Officer Edgar
Mallory put him there.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus offered a chocolate Monopoly game in its 1978
Christmas catalog. Price: $800.
</P>
<P>
   The longest game ever played was 1,680 hours _ 70 consecutive
days.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount of money in the bank is $15,140.
</P>
