<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FOX-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOX FINANCES BLOODIED BY GOP PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 22 -- His Republican challengers may not have
been able to upset his re-election bid, but U.S. Rep. Jon Fox,
R-Abington, has emerged as a wounded incumbent badly trailing
Democratic challenger Joseph Hoeffel in the money race.
</P>
<P>
   As of June 30, Hoeffel had three times as much money remaining
in his campaign account as did Fox, who narrowly beat Hoeffel in
1996 by 84 votes. Hoeffel has $393,270 to Fox's $134,500, according
to reports filed with the Federal Election Commission in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not counting the roughly $150,000 Hoeffel raked in at
a fundraiser Monday in Gladwynne, with First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton on hand. Between 400 and 450 people attended the event,
paying either $125 for the right to hang out with Clinton and
Hoeffel in the backyard of a private home or $1,000 for a smaller
gathering inside the home.
</P>
<P>
   It's a much different feeling for Hoeffel to be leading the
money race against Fox, who far outspent the Democratic Montgomery
County commissioner -- $1.66 million to $697,000 -- in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great help to the campaign, compared to two years
ago,'' said Jeff Stein, Hoeffel's campaign manager. ``He's not
going to be able to outspend us two to one from Labor Day on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with this money edge, Hoeffel faces different circumstances
that could make his upset bid more difficult than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the ticket this fall is GOP Gov. Ridge and GOP Sen.
Arlen Specter, both of whom are facing nominal challengers, as
opposed to 1996 when President Clinton pulled in votes for Hoeffel.
And the AFL-CIO, which spent more than $300,000 in anti-Fox ads in
October 1996, is not going to be active this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But with Democrats needing an 11-seat swing to take over the
House, they have been eyeing up Fox ever since that razor-thin
victory. And so did Republicans in Montgomery County, three of whom
challenged Fox in the May primary. He won by a large margin over
his GOP challengers, but they forced Fox to unload his campaign
funds early.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and the first six months of 1998, Fox spent $856,000.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was ``pleased with the fundraising results,'' Fox said
in a statement, ``Coming on the heels of a very expensive primary
election, the Fox for Congress Committee is well on target to raise
the required funds for the upcoming campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, Fox has raised $957,561; Hoeffel has raised just
$538,178.
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   Raised Total raised Total Spent Cash on hand
</P>
<P>
   (4/1-6/30) (1/1/97-6/30/98)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fox $230,930 957,561 $836,054 134,500
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hoeffel $253,078 538,178 $152,629 393,270
</P>
<P>
   Source: Federal Election Commission
</P>
</TEXT>
