<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-HNS &LR;      07-22 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GROUP PICKETS CONGRESS TO URGE DEFEAT OF ANTI-GAY BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Organization for Women picketed
Congress Wednesday to urge the defeat of two anti-gay legislative
proposals that the NOW president criticized as political gimmicks
designed to energize conservative Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   The protest rally came as the House prepared to vote on the
proposals that NOW President Patricia Ireland said would
politically damage Republicans by making them look ``very mean and
hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   One proposal sponsored by Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., would
prohibit the city of San Francisco from using federal housing funds
if the city continues to require its private contractors to provide
the same benefits to unmarried domestic partners as they provide
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal by Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., would nullify an
executive order by President Clinton that barred federal agencies
from discriminating against gays.
</P>
<P>
   To expose what she called ``a back-door attempt to slip''
anti-gay legislation though Congress, Ireland joined about 50
picketers marching in scorching heat outside a House office
building Wednesday, shouting slogans such as ``Hey, hey, ho, ho,
homophobia's got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some picketers carried placards with such slogans as, ``I feel
fine, I don't need to be cured,'' a response to recent newspaper
advertisements sponsored by conservative groups that maintain
religion can change the sexual orientation of gays.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ireland said the Riggs and Hefley proposals
were attempts to mobilize right-wing Christians to vote in the
November elections in a year in which experts predict a lackluster
voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clearly an election-year wedge issue,'' Ireland
said, adding ``To punish cities that are forward-looking like San
Francisco is just outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why NOW was fighting for gay rights, Ireland said the
group is ``working for all women's equality _ it includes lesbian,
bisexual and transgender people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that all oppression is wrong,'' Ireland said. ``As
feminists we do often raise issues that people consider radical.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland added: ``Every woman who steps forward to claim her
rights faces the allegation that she is queer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland said 150 years ago, women who attended the women's
rights convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y., were called ``mannish,
unnatural, and spinsters.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Peter LaBarbera, president of Americans for
Truth, a conservative group that joined with 14 others to pay for
the anti-gay advertisements in major newspapers last week, said NOW
``is out of touch with American women,'' and ``obsessed with
lesbianism.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBarbera said anti-discrimination protections in civil rights
law should not be applied to homosexual behavior ``that, unlike
skin color, can be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Clinton administration urged Congress to include
sexual orientation under the federal hate crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the acting assistant attorney general for civil
rights, told the House Judiciary Committee that President Clinton
strongly supports changing the law so that the FBI can assist state
and local governments in investigating hate crimes based on sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the FBI is empowered to step in to help
investigate certain hate crimes based on race, color, religion or
national origin. But Lee said the law is deficient because it does
not cover violent hate crimes stemming from bias based on the
victim's sexual orientation, gender or disability.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also heard testimony from Mark Bangerter of Boise,
Idaho, who said he was attacked in April and lost the sight in his
left eye after an assailant beat him, mistakenly believing he was
gay.
</P>
<P>
   Bangerter, an artist, said he had hugged a male friend goodbye
after meeting over drinks in a Boise bar, when a stranger called
him a ``faggot,'' punched him in the head, then pursued him outside
and continued to beat him, breaking bones around his eye sockets.
</P>
<P>
   Bangerter said the assailant was never caught, the Boise police
have said they have little time to investigate, and the FBI has
said it can not intervene because sexual orientation is not
included in a list of federal hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone hated gay people enough to try to kill me,'' Bangerter
said. ``The irony is that I am not gay. This happened to me because
I hugged a friend. Now I know what can and does happen to people
who are gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Traditional Values Coalition _ which claims to
represent 36,000 churches _ issued a statement calling the
administration's effort to expand the definition of a hate crime as
``nothing less than a premeditated assault on religious Americans
who oppose homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Sheldon, executive director of the coalition, said
pending legislation to expand the definition was ``like a bad
B-movie in which all of the enlightened folks from the Northeast
are going to set straight all those `Bible-toting zealots' from the
rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Sheldon said Christians ``no more hate
homosexuals than they do alcoholics or chronic gamblers. We believe
the moral choices made by homosexuals are wrong and we encourage
them to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
