<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7891 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORRINE-BROWN-$ADV26-     07-22 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRINE-BROWN-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONTROVERSIAL FLORIDA INCUMBENT COULD FACE A CLOSE RACE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 26.
 &HT;    BY LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Corrine Brown, D-Fla., is no stranger to
controversy, or to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with controversies swirling around her dealings with a West
African businessman convicted of bribery and the Rev. Henry Lyons,
the indicted head of the National Baptist Convention USA, her
future is again being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome could affect which party will control the House of
Representatives next year.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans holding a 12-member margin, both parties are
looking carefully at any race that might be competitive. Rep. John
Linder, R-Ga., chairman of the Republican National Congressional
Committee _ the group that recruits and helps finance GOP House
candidates _ said there is an opportunity to pick up Brown's 3rd
Congressional District, which sprawls across portions of nine
counties from Jacksonville to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you are running against someone who has to refer all
of her questions about her campaign to her attorney,'' that's a
race with potential, Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   Linder's committee will almost certainly give Brown's opponent,
businessman Bill Randall, the $5,000 maximum contribution allowed.
Whether it also will spend the roughly $60,000 allowed in
coordinated expenditures won't be decided until this fall, though
Linder said it is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to look at all the races and fully fund 90 to 100,
and this will probably be one of those, unless our candidate takes
a hike,'' Linder said, adding that he expects Randall to run a
competitive race.
</P>
<P>
   Linder isn't counting on unseating Brown to retain Republican
control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the key to our holding a majority. With or without
this election, we will add to our numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats are worried about holding Brown's seat, they're
not voicing those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corrine Brown is an excellent member of Congress,'' said Rep.
Martin Frost, D-Texas, chairman of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee. ``I think she will be judged on her record. I
have every confidence that she will be re-elected and probably
re-elected by a significant margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost noted that previous opponents have tried to tar Brown with
ethical misdeeds and failed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Corrine will be just fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite a record marred with ethical missteps Brown's
political fortunes have flourished.
</P>
<P>
   At 51, the Jacksonville native is a political veteran who served
10 years in the Legislature and three terms in Congress. During
those years she earned a reputation as a savvy politician who would
fight tenaciously for her constituents and their causes.
</P>
<P>
   She's also done things that have led political opponents to
question her ethics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1990, Brown helped a friend win a $425,000 federal
``business incubator'' grant. The project failed, and the city of
Jacksonville was forced to repay $314,000 out of future federal
block grants. The state attorney's office investigated Brown's role
in the grant, but said there was no reason to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1993, Brown agreed to pay a $5,000 fine _ but did not admit
guilt _ after a state ethics commission found probable cause to
believe she illegally used state employees to work in her private
travel agency.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also in 1993, Brown's campaign treasurer quit after learning
his signature had been forged on several Federal Election
Commission reports by her administrative assistant. Later that
year, Brown submitted amended FEC reports showing she previously
had not reported more than $12,000 in expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In addition to her campaign finance problems that year,
Brown's chief assistant in her congressional district was
discovered to have been convicted in 1972 of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1994, the FEC issued a report that Brown violated several
campaign finance laws during her 1992 race, including using a
corporate plane without showing she had paid for it, making loans
to her campaign without showing the money came from her personal
account, and illegally accepting donations from foreign citizens
and from corporations. A Brown aide blamed the mistakes on her
unfamiliarity with differences in state and federal campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   The current controversies swirling around Brown could make those
of the past pale by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   They break down into three distinct episodes involving a check,
a car, and a trip, all first reported by The St. Petersburg Times.
Brown, who has repeatedly avoided discussing these controversies
with the media _ even filing harassment charges against two Times
reporters that were later dropped _ declined to be interviewed for
this story.
</P>
<P>
   The first controversy involves a $10,000 check Brown received in
1996 from the Rev. Henry Lyons, drawn on a Milwaukee bank account.
Lyons, who lived a lavish lifestyle as head of the predominantly
black Baptist organization, has been charged by a Florida
prosecutor with racketeering and grand theft. Prosecutors have been
trying to tie Lyons to the Wisconsin account, which held more than
$1 million in money allegedly extorted from a Canadian company.
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not list the check on her campaign finance report or
on her personal financial disclosure report.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's attorneys said the check was used to pay for buses to
carry her supporters to a rally held outside the U.S. District
courthouse in Tallahassee where a three-judge panel was deciding
how to redraw her district's boundaries. The U.S. Supreme Court had
earlier ruled that districts similar to Brown's had been improperly
gerrymandered along racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   Because the money was used to help pay for the redistricting
rally, it was not considered a campaign expense and, therefore, did
not have to be included in her campaign reports, her attorneys
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the news stories indicated Brown was not able to demonstrate
that Lyons' check went to pay for the buses. Her campaign reported
spending only $2,000 on the buses.
</P>
<P>
   The second controversy revolves around the car and the convict.
The Times reported that West African businessman Foutanga Dit
Babani Sissoko bought a Lexus LS400 _ valued at about $50,000 _ for
Brown's 32-year-old daughter, Shantrel, a lawyer with the
Environmental Protection Agency, after Brown tried to keep him out
of prison.
</P>
<P>
   House ethics rules prohibit lawmakers from receiving gifts. The
ban also extends to members' families if the gift to the relative
is an attempt to get around the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Sissoko, who now lives in Mali, was sentenced in 1997 to four
months in prison, four months of house arrest and fined $250,000
for ordering his employees to attempt to bribe a U.S. Customs
officer into letting them ship two Vietnam-era helicopters to West
Africa without the necessary licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Brown lobbied members of Congress on Sissoko's behalf and wrote
two letters to Attorney General Janet Reno urging her to use her
power to deport Sissoko before his sentence was completed. Reno
refused. Brown later visited Sissoko in prison and in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The car was paid for by Karim Pouye, whom Sissoko's attorney,
Thomas Spencer of Miami, described as Sissoko's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Shantrel Brown, who lives in Washington with her mother, issued
a written statement this month denying that the car had anything to
do with her mother's efforts to help Sissoko. She said Pouye, whom
she had met in Miami in 1997 and knew was affiliated with Sissoko,
gave her the car after she told him that her grandmother's car had
been stolen in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conversation led to Mr. Pouye's offer of a car, first for
her, later titled to me,'' Shantrel Brown said, without explaining
why she got the car and not her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that the offer was made in friendship, and I accepted
it without reservation,'' she said. ``My mother was not present in
these conversations, and she had no part in my decision to accept
the car. I am an adult who makes my own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The third controversy involves a trip Brown and two aides took
to Russia and other countries of the former Soviet Union in 1996.
The 10-day trip, which cost $27,861, was paid for by Itera
International Energy Corp. of Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, Brown wrote a high-pressure letter to the
ambassador of Turkmenistan complaining that Itera was being cut out
of a plan to ship natural gas between Turkmenistan and the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that any agreement will include my constituent
and that the United States and the state of Florida, where my
district is located, will continue to have close and warm ties with
Turkmenistan,'' Brown wrote.
</P>
<P>
   House ethics rules prohibit members from attempting to ``exert
undue or improper pressure'' on a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   Three Florida lawmakers _ Reps. Mark Foley, a Republican from
West Palm Beach, C.W. ``Bill'' Young, a Republican from Indian
Rocks Beach, and Jim Davis, a Democrat from Tampa _ have called for
a House ethics committee investigation of Brown, but in the
unwritten tradition of the Florida delegation none have filed
formal charges against her.
</P>
<P>
   Linder, the GOP congressional campaign chairman, has been
quietly looking for a member to file charges. Even if they are
filed, however, it is unlikely the investigation would be completed
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   The controversies surrounding Brown have been reported in local
newspapers in her district, but what affect they will have on her
election is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent news stories ... have helped her to consolidate the
black Democratic base,'' said John H. Libby, president of American
Public Dialogue, a public opinion and marketing research firm with
close ties to Republican candidates. ``We've seen this historically
in this country with African-American politicians, particularly
congress people.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and her opponent, Randall, are both black.
</P>
<P>
   Since the federal panel redrew the district's boundaries two
years ago, the percentage of black voters has dropped from 50
percent to about 42 percent. But it is still overwhelmingly
Democratic: 68 percent against 24 percent Republican and 8 percent
independent, according to Libby.
</P>
<P>
   With little support from black voters and with Republicans
distinctly in the minority, Randall's hopes lie with white
Democratic voters, Libby said.
</P>
<P>
   While Brown has more campaign money to spend than Randall _
$87,252 to $13,171 _ the pace of his fund raising in recent months
has been two-and-a-half times greater than hers. During the quarter
that ended June 30, Randall raised $31,216 to Brown's $12,255.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
