<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday,
July 22, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TAILWIND _ WASHINGTON _ A Pentagon review of Operation Tailwind
found no evidence to support allegations by CNN and Time magazine
that the mission's goal was to hunt town American defectors or that
U.S. forces used sarin nerve gas, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Tuesday. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-ROBERSON _ WASHINGTON - Even in death, 4-year-old Carl Wayne
Roberson of Nacogdoches, Texas, cannot escape being at the center
of a legal tug of war. This time, the boy's estate is squaring off
against an Internal Revenue Service demand for $1.36 million in
estate taxes and penalties on a $4.48 million settlement of a law
suit brought over the boy being exposed to toxic chemicals in the
uterus. Carl died Nov. 23, 1993. The boy's estate filed a petition
asking the U.S. Tax Court here to overturn the IRS decision that
the proceeds from the settlement were taxable. The estate argues
the payment should be tax-free. (Moskal, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-CONTEST _ WASHINGTON _ Americans Discuss Social Security
holds the first annual ``Social Security Challenge,'' a contest
where college students attempt to determine the most effective way
to engage all Americans in importance in preserving and protecting
Social Security. The seven semi-finalists include teams from
Florida, Ohio and Texas. The winning team will receive $100,000 to
implement its plan and each member of the winning team will receive
a $10,000 scholarship. (Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERIOR-FUNDING _ WASHINGTON _ The interior appropriations
bill, with $25 million for the Chattahoochee greenway, is supposed
to be on the floor today. That bill also has NEA funding. It is
highly likely that Gingrich's money will remain, despite complaints
from Democrats that Gingrich inserted his project in at the expense
of Everglades and other land purchases. (Sherman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LA-RAZA-EDUCATION _ PHILADELPHIA _ La Raza releases a report
Wednesday on the status of Hispanic education in the United States,
followed by a discussion of Hispanic civil rights, which presumably
will include talk about limits on the use of affirmative action at
universities in Texas and California. (Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LA-RAZA-POLITICS _ PHILADELPHIA _ New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who speaks at lunch Tuesday, is the Hispanics' favorite
Republican, behind Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, which begs the
question: Could a Bush-Giuliani ticket win in 2000 with the help of
a sudden surge of GOP voting by Hispanics? (Harlan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ MURPHY, N.C. _ Daily update on the search for
Birmingham abortion clinic bombing suspect Eric Rudolph. (Scruggs,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PBALL _ Indiana's powerball jackpot is at $125 million, which
means people are flocking across state lines for a chance at
instant millions. (Wynn, Dayton Daily News). 8.
</P>
