A7920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ARTS-GRANTS-325&AMP;AD     07-22 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTS-GRANTS-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE ARTS GROUPS HOPEFUL ON GRANTS DESPITE NEA CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite changes in financing guidelines at the
National Endowment for the Arts that were driven in part by
anti-New York sentiment in Congress, arts leaders around the state
said Wednesday that they were hopeful that local groups would not
suffer dramatic cutbacks in grants like those they have sustained
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives voted decisively Tuesday to approve
funds for the endowment at its current $98 million a year level,
leaving in place changes in the agency rules designed to disperse
money more evenly around the country.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, which was the clear target of a ceiling passed
last year on how much organizations from a single state can
receive, garners a far greater proportion of the funds than any
other state.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the complicated way in which each state's
financing is tabulated, state arts groups are not likely to suffer
any immediate impact from the ceiling and they remain hopeful that
they will be able to weather this year's changes as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even though New York's grants are just over the 15 percent state
ceiling, endowment officials and others said that because of the
way the financing is calculated, the state's level still comes well
under the 15 percent level.
</P>
<P>
   This is because much of the money goes to productions and
artworks that, while originating here, travel to venues outside the
state. Money for such programs is not counted as part of the
state's total.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several local arts leaders gave qualified praise to
the House's passage of the endowment budget while others said they
were concerned about the actions. Republican leaders in the House
have voted to kill the agency in the past, but have never
accomplished their aim because the Senate has supported the agency,
albeit at dramatically reduced levels. These cutbacks have led to
substantial reductions in endowment aid for New York artists and
institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earle Mack, chairman of the New York State Council on the Arts,
said, ``I'm delighted that the NEA is still alive.'' He said the
council was getting $691,000 from the endowment this year, up from
$680,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Bourscheidt, president of the Alliance for the Arts, an
advocacy group in New York City, said the action ``signals an era
of calmer discussion of federal arts funding.'' He said, however,
that he remained ``concerned over the lack of support from the New
York congressional delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   In deciding last year not to kill the arts agency, despite a
strong push by conservatives, Congress imposed a 15 percent limit
on grant funds to any one state, a provision that NEA spokeswoman
Cherie Simon called clearly aimed at New York. Between grants to
arts groups and to the State Council for the Arts, New York this
year is due to receive $12.5 million, nearly double the $6.7 given
to second-place California.
</P>
<P>
   New York's $12.5 million would represent just over the 15
percent ceiling of the $81 million of the endowment budget devoted
to grants, and so the state could would be close to losing further
grants. But $5.4 million of New York's money is designated for
traveling _ or multistate _ art shows, dance performances and
concerts, and so is not computed to count toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York gets about a quarter of the grants for travel,
that is not material to the ceiling limits. Without the multistate
money, Ms. Simon said, New York received $7.1 million, or 12
percent of the total grant budget.
</P>
<P>
   Yet concern abounds among many arts groups dependent on public
support. Mark Rossier, marketing director of the Alliance of
Resident Theaters/New York, representing a core group of 146
theaters, said endowment financing for its members dropped 43
percent, or $1.1 million, between 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Larger institutions are better able to withstand cuts but also
dependent on federal grants. ``They have told us we can submit only
one application a year _ we used to submit 10,'' said William
Luers, president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, which received
$200,000 toward its $120 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   But he said: ``We're the place people enter the country. New
York is a gateway. There's no question that we feed the arts in
every state. They undervalue that.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Gould, director of Artists Space, said the studio art
group had received $20,000 this year but nothing last year. `We
don't count on government money,'' she said. ``It's no longer part
of our framework.''
</P>
<P>
   Dance companies have been particularly dependent on public
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a big cut last year, from $100,000 to $45,000,'' said
Kathy Edwards, managing director of Dance Theater Workshop in
Chelsea, one of the city's four major downtown dance theaters. ``So
it's terrible even if the money is staying the same. I certainly
applaud money going across the country, but New York City is the
dance capital of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Joyce Theater, another major dance venue in Chelsea,
federal support dropped from $200,000 _ 6 percent of its $3.8
million budget _ last fiscal year to $90,000 for the 1998-1999
fiscal year, and administrators wonder whether the 15 percent cap
is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Elise Bernhardt, executive director of the Kitchen, another
Chelsea dance theater, said she had not applied for endowment funds
in several years, although she is applying for a $25,000 archival
preservation grant for the 1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put an unbelievable amount of work into this,''
Ms. Bernhardt said. ``And now it seems as if there will be less
money.''And, she added, ``it's the places that are the laboratories
that will get hit the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
