<HEADLINE>
BOOKS TO READ ON THE BEACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``On the Occasion of My Last Afternoon''
</P>
<P>
   By Kaye Gibbons
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, 273 pages, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   THE HYPE: Oprah Winfrey added two of the author's earlier novels
to her ballyhooed book club list in December. The timing pressured
Gibbons to finish ``Occasion,'' which had been three years in the
making. She threw out 900 pages and started rewriting.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLOT: Steel magnolia Emma Garnet tells her life story,
beginning on the Virginia plantation of her tyrant father, tromping
through the Civil War with her Yankee husband, Dr. Quincy Lowell,
and ending on her final day.
</P>
<P>
   THE REALITY: Although some chapters read like ``Ladies Home
Journal,'' Gibbons' storytelling surfaces in others. The story
takes off midway through the book and, from there, charges to a
satisfying end.
</P>
<P>
   APPROXIMATE READING TIME: What should take a weekend takes
longer. The 19th-century voice makes comprehension difficult in
parts for a 20th-century reader.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Larry Bingham
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
