<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISBY LOOKING AT THE COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ After their frustrating 7-6 loss to the
Pittsburgh Steelers Jan. 3 in the AFC playoff semifinals, emotions
were running high in the Patriots' locker room. Fingers were
pointing all over the place. Players were saying things they would
later regret. It seemed like a house divided.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration didn't end there for Vincent Brisby and Troy
Brown, two backup receivers.
</P>
<P>
   After missing 13 games in 1996 with a hamstring pull, Brisby had
returned with a strong camp in '97. But that hadn't meant much.
Shawn Jefferson, who had been acquired in '96, started opposite
Terry Glenn, and Brisby, who had caught 66 passes for 914 yards in
'95, again found himself on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, meanwhile, had his best year as a pro. Often thrust into
the frequently injured Glenn's slot, Brown caught 41 passes for 607
yards, made some big catches, and finally felt as if he were more
than a third-down receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the season ended, however, both felt they didn't
belong. The Patriots acquired Brian Stablein, which Brown thought
would severely cut into his playing time, and Brisby felt there
were too many bodies around.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby demanded a trade. Brown was also wondering if he should
explore other options.
</P>
<P>
   Well, training camp 1998 is here, and so are Brisby and Brown,
hoping to make the best of situations they still feel are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I feel like I'm going to get more of an opportuity to
display my abilities,'' said Brisby. ``I want to try to help this
team win games. The big thing was I felt I wasn't being treated
fairly because I got injured. I thought I clearly outplayed Shawn
in camp and didn't win the job. I even had a conversation with
Shawn, and even he thought I outplayed him. If I'm going against
someome on the field, I can beat them out, but if it's something
else, I can't do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing was, if it was going to be that way, why not let me
go someplace else and play for somebody else?''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried to move Brisby but demanded a second-round
draft pick. They tried desperately to deal him during the draft,
but all that was offered was a sixth-round pick, and the team felt
Brisby was worth far more than that. And when they hired Ernie
Zampese as offensive coordinator, it seemed to signal the possible
rebirth of Brisby. Zampese's timing passing game works best with
big receivers who also can block to help the running game. The more
the Patriots looked for a big receiver _ at one point considering
Sean Dawkins _ the more they realized they might already have their
man: Brisby, who is 6 feet 2 inches and can catch the ball over the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll talked to Brisby and assured him he would get
a chance to compete again for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guy (agent Mike George) called Pete,'' said Brisby. ``He
said I'd get the opportunity to win a starting job. It made me want
to attend the offseason workouts and be a part of this team. And
just in case it didn't work out and they found someone to take me,
I was gonna be in shape and ready to go somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   This was major progress.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lasting images of Brisby from the 1997 season
occurred when Drew Bledsoe got in his face on the sidelines for
failing to get open when the quarterback was running for his life
at Jacksonville in Week 15. After the play, Bledsoe ran after
Brisby on the sidelines and lambasted him for not breaking off his
route to help the QB. Brisby stepped it up after that incident and
played well the rest of the game, catching four passes for 58 yards
in a 26-20 win.
</P>
<P>
   But that game didn't do much for Brisby's playing time or his
confidence. He caught only two passes the next two games and got
shut out in the playoff opener against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, he told the coaching staff that if he wasn't
going to be more involved, he didn't want to be brought to
Pittsburgh for the next game. This probably didn't go over well
with the staff, but out of necessity, Brisby played and caught
three passes for 37 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want an opportunity, regardless of how it happens,''
said Brisby. ``I'm glad to be here. I love the players and the
organization. I'm happy in a way that I'm not someplace else and
that I'm right here competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Brisby fails to play well in camp, he could be
released. He's scheduled to earn $1.25 million this year and is
under contract through 2000. The Patriots could save a bundle by
releasing him. But for now, they are telling him he's competing.
And they hope his presence will motivate Glenn. Brisby says the
Glenn situation may be a reason the coaching staff is putting so
much stock in his rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   But there are 12 receivers in camp, and he knows there won't be
room for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of guys who can play and we only run two- or
three-receiver sets,'' he said. ``If you go out there and blow
teams out and we end up in Miami (for the Super Bowl), everyone
will be OK, but if we struggle and guys aren't playing ...''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is in a better mood because he has been given the starting
punt returner's job. He used to be Dave Meggett's backup, but those
duties were taken from him last year. Now Meggett is gone, and
Brown is No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling to be the guy for now,'' said Brown. ``It
may take a while to get the rhythm of it back, but we'll see how
the first preseason game goes. It's my job to lose right now. But
we have Brian Stablein and Tony Gaiter and Chris Canty, all of whom
are trying to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his receiver situation, Brown knows nothing has changed
despite his 1997 contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that I have to fight for a spot every year,'' he
said. ``I just have to worry about myself and do whatever it takes
to make sure I keep what I have. I just have to do my job. I know
I'm giving it my best. They have to make a decision to keep whoever
they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
