u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-985&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-22 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-985&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: VIRTUAL HISTORY AS SHORTCUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A not too burdensome way to fill gaps in your knowledge of
history is books that could be called virtual novels. At least many
people are turning to them in the belief that they are getting
history that excites. Are they kidding themselves? Does it matter?
Like virtual reality, these books are attempts to approximate real
life, although on the written page, not on computers.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual literature is an old genre that book publishing
periodically rediscovers and reinvents. It started, its defenders
like to say, at least as early as Homer, and it was a stock in
trade for Shakespeare. Mostly the virtual novel is seen in
fictional biography, of which there have been a number of examples
recently.
</P>
<P>
   These include novels about John Brown, John Wilkes Booth, Thomas
Jefferson, Andrew Jackson and even Henry Rathbone and Clara Harris,
who were with the Lincolns in Ford's Theater on the evening of Good
Friday, 1865.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual novel of a different sort, ``The Last Full Measure''
(Ballantine) by Jeff Shaara, the final novel of a Civil War trilogy
begun by his father, Michael, is a current best seller, the big
summer read of this fact-fiction school. In it, U.S. Grant, Robert
E. Lee and Joshua Chamberlain are among the military virtuosos
cavorting about its pages in great detail.
</P>
<P>
   E.L. Doctorow in ``Ragtime'' (Random House) in 1975 may have
reinvented this way of giving readers the atmosphere of a period
without too many of its facts, by putting in cameo appearances by
such people as Henry Ford, J.P. Morgan, Evelyn Nesbit and Harry
Houdini. Don DeLillo expands on it in ``Underworld'' (Scribner).
</P>
<P>
   As a preservative of history, these gambols in the lives of the
great and famous are doubtful. Yet to some they represent, in the
words of one book-publishing executive, speaking on the condition
of anonymity, ``historical truth in an entertaining fashion, but
people are getting history.'' Well, sort of. She used Shakespeare
as an example. A more recent one is Robert Graves' ``I, Claudius,''
a classic of virtual literature.
</P>
<P>
   But one writer and critic, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said: ``Shakespeare's plays presented higher truths. The
current novels, however well done, don't. The viewers of
Shakespeare's plays knew he was making it all up.'' He added that
``it's harder to tell that today'' and that the historical
characters in current fictional biography ``are closer in time and
more important to us than Henry V.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the danger is that these species of novels can
become defining. The life of Vincent van Gogh was stolen by Irving
Stone, and the painter will forever be remembered as the crazed
genius of ``Lust for Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Is true history so dully written that there is a need for such
fictional nonfiction? Sometimes yes, but often not. Few novelists,
for instance, write with the verve and page-turning excitement of
Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   The writing of virtual novels is not actually intended to be
mythomaniacal. A great deal of historical research goes into them.
Russell Banks, the author of ``Cloudsplitter'' (HarperCollins),
lives near the grave of the abolitionist John Brown, who was ``a
sort of ghostly presence'' to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned what I could about the people near him,'' he said,
``about his daily life, what he ate for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   But here is a novelist speaking, not a historian: ``He became
for me as real as a fictional character. This is much more real for
a writer than the historical Brown. Which leads you to having him
do things he didn't do, like meeting Ralph Waldo Emerson.''
</P>
<P>
   His novel is different from, say, an Oliver Stone movie,
``JFK,'' for instance. Stone claims to show you the real truth. ``I
say, don't read this as history,'' Banks said. ``I'm very explicit
that I'm trying to engage the reader in a novel using historical
fact and fiction, and I feel the same freedom to use historical
information as I do to use biographical material from my own
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Byrd, the author of ``Jefferson'' and ``Jackson'' (Bantam
Books), read the diaries and read all the histories and then, he
said, ``I gave myself free rein, created fictitious characters, but
with the real characters kept close to what is known about them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``James Hemings (Sally Hemings' brother) was in France with
Jefferson, to learn French cooking for Jefferson. I invented a
little bit about him exploring the possibilities of breaking loose
from his slavery. There was lots of talk of revolution in France
then, and I had James mix with the revolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that there is ``a dryness to most present academic
history, and people want to see some sense of flesh and blood and
vividness in these great figures moving across the stage.'' That's
what he tries to provide.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and Byrd write their virtual novels without an agenda
other than telling a good yarn. Gore Vidal, more than a decade
earlier, in his Random House novels ``Lincoln'' and ``Burr,''
wanted to de-deify Lincoln and rehabilitate Burr.
</P>
<P>
   Shaara speaks the lingo of virtual novels, saying that he is
actually trying ``to put a three-dimensional face on history.''
Which is what virtual reality is about, three dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``I stay away from modern biographies and modern
history books and instead use the diaries and memoirs of the
historical characters and their wives and staff officers _ those
who were there and heard the words.'' At certain times in the
trilogy ``there are word-for-word quotes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters' thoughts and dialogue make these into
novels,'' he said. We don't know what Grant or Lee was thinking,
but what's in the novels is entirely what they could have been
thinking. I don't try to create controversy or manufacture or
embellish history. The events are the way they happened. What I've
added is that you see the events through the characters themselves,
and that's by definition a novel.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Literary novelists have more subtle ways of using real people.
As will be explained in this Sunday's ``Bookend'' page in The New
York Times Book Review, they give the factual person a fictional
name and then slaughter the character intellectually, often
settling an old score. Of course, everyone in the know is aware who
they are writing about.
</P>
<P>
   Like every classification of books, the virtual novel has its
highs and lows and middles. Bantam has published three mysteries
under the name Stephanie Barron in which the 19th-century English
novelist Jane Austen takes time out from her writing to solve
murders. These are supposed to be fun, one supposes. In the middle.
</P>
<P>
   As for low, no one has yet approached the standard for the
bottom reached in 1988 by Alfred A. Knopf, arguably the most
literary publishing house of all, which published ``Traveller,'' by
Richard Adams. Traveller was Robert E. Lee's horse. The novel
depicted the Civil War through Traveller's eyes. The horse, as
narrator, even spoke in what was called a Virginian idiom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
