<HEADLINE>
LONG-DELAYED LESSONS ABOUT FATHERS AND A WAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 William McDonald is deputy editor of Arts and Leisure  
 By WILLIAM MCDONALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the late afternoon of an autumn day in 1962, a comrade in
arms and I were flat on our bellies in a foxhole, peering out from
under olive-drab infantry helmets across a field of tall grass
turned brown and brittle with the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rifles at the ready, we were watching for German troop movements
in a stand of maples and oaks some 50 yards off, ignoring as best
we could the headlight beams blasting through the naked trees from
the Chevy Bel Airs and Ford Fairlanes and Rambler Americans passing
by.
</P>
<P>
   These two-tone sedans and boxy station wagons were carrying
middle-aged men home through the 5 o'clock shadows after a long day
at the office, at the factory, at the shop, men who might once have
shouldered real rifles and worn real helmets and faced real Germans
and Japanese in the woods of Bastogne or in the jungle of
Corregidor, men whom my friend and I were pretending to be in what
really wasn't a foxhole but a natural hollow in that ragged little
meadow that the bulldozers then overrunning the landscape like so
many Panzer divisions had yet to rip up and reshape in the name of
postwar suburban conquest.
</P>
<P>
   Men like our fathers and uncles and the neighbor with one arm,
his other having been given up for his country.
</P>
<P>
   We were small boys, of course, and the war we were fighting was
in our heads. We were good boys, too, if not good soldiers: with
night looming and our suppers waiting, we knew when it was time to
retire from the field and troop home, secure in the faith that we'd
live to fight another day. Soon we unsnapped the leather chin
straps and tossed our helmets into a toy box, stood our air rifles
in a corner and slapped the dirt off our dungarees.
</P>
<P>
   As for the war that had so filled our imaginations, we probably
thought we were putting it aside too on that fall evening, just as
years later, when the cold fact of growing up had forced us from
our worlds of make-believe, we thought we'd put it away for good.
</P>
<P>
   But now I think that was never true. Seeing ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' Steven Spielberg's homage to the Americans who fought in
Normandy, has led me to realize that the war we boys were
re-enacting 36 years ago, the war of our fathers, stayed with us
then and has stayed with us since.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons may be as simple _ or as complicated _ as the blood
tie between fathers and sons. And they may be as large and
inescapable as a wide screen in a movie house. Certainly one can
start looking there. In the year that my friend and I were beating
back Hitler with toy rifles, ``The Longest Day,'' Darryl F.
Zanuck's epic retelling of D-Day and decidedly the father of
Spielberg's, was showing at a theater across town.
</P>
<P>
   This was the definitive World War II movie. Sprawling from the
south of England into northern France, it chronicled Operation
Overlord hour by hour, lending some humanity to the German high
command (with subtitles) but most of all glorifying the Allies
(with a glamorous cast, from John Wayne to Richard Burton).
</P>
<P>
   For young patriots playing at soldiering in a time of Cold War
and classroom duck-and-cover drills, there was probably no World
War II movie more stirring; doubtless it inspired a hundred
thousand engagements with the enemy in backyards and on street
corners across the land.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's impact had a lot to do with its timing. With a
former PT boat commander installed in the White House and the
former Supreme Allied Commander retired of late to his Gettysburg
home, ``The Longest Day'' came along as the torch was being passed
from the wise old men who had prosecuted the war to the young men
who had fought it, a group arriving at middle age in 1962 and
preparing, as John F. Kennedy put it, for ``a long twilight
struggle'' with the Red menace.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was thus as much a celebration of the generation
coming into its own as it was a tribute to the one folding its
tents. And looking on were the impressionable boys with popguns in
their hands (and girls with a less militaristic kind of wonder) _
children born well after Berlin had fallen, well after Hiroshima,
even after Korea. With no memories of war, we were young enough to
believe in its romance and myths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Longest Day'' was a kind of capstone to more than a decade
of war movies that we boys had spent many a rainy Sunday afternoon
watching raptly on television. And it hammered home, perhaps for
one last time before the world moved on, the message that Hollywood
war movies had long been delivering: that our troops were superior
and heroic, that our generals were shrewd and bold, and that our
cause was monumental and just.
</P>
<P>
   To the children watching it, a wartime propaganda movie like
``Guadalcanal Diary'' or a postwar paean like ``The Sands of Iwo
Jima'' was not just an entertainment but also a blood-lifting
pageant honoring the men all around us who had saved the world.
</P>
<P>
   And as the movies pictured them, these men were swell: tough,
brave, sometimes cocky in the face of death, smoking Luckies and
given to hard-boiled wisecracks or cornball speeches about home,
country and the girls they'd left behind. Almost invariably they
were an ethnic and social cross-section of white America, advancing
on the enemy as one, spurred on by the swelling strains of a
martial theme song or a whistled tune of glory. If any fell, they
were gallant enough not to bleed too much.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the John Waynes and Robert Mitchums did more to
shape our image of World War II than the real men who came out of
it, the men who wound up driving the Ramblers and Bel Airs.
</P>
<P>
   They, or at least the ones I knew, barely said a word about the
war. Some had brought home souvenirs _ a helmet, a holster, a set
of dog tags _ and maybe these keepsakes had precipitated a
dinner-table story or two in the distant late '40s, when memories
of service, and the scars, were still fresh. But by the early '60s
the war tales had stopped and the mementos had been consigned to
attics, where instead of acquiring luster they gathered dust.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And yet a war story or two did manage to filter down, enough to
grab hold of a young imagination. There was a friend of my father's
whose story came to us second-hand, never through him: how he had
suffered a bayonet wound to the throat, then survived the Bataan
Death March and a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp; how he had endured
an unspeakable torture involving a rat in a tin can and had been
forced to eat grasshoppers for nourishment. He lived into his 80s
with a permanent click in his throat where the bayonet had gone in.
</P>
<P>
   But war stories, for the most part, went untold, even though the
men of my family must have had some to tell. One, who had been
mistakenly drafted into the Army at the age of 38, fought in the
Battle of the Bulge. One was hastily commissioned a lieutenant in
the thick of battle in Europe when his company leader was killed.
Two served in the Navy in the South Pacific. Another wore
corporal's stripes at a home-front base.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that I can't say much more; details were hard to come by.
Indeed, only in the last few weeks have I learned that an uncle,
himself a veteran of the India theater, lost his youngest brother
in the war when the boy's ship went down.
</P>
<P>
   I don't presume to understand these men's silence. The thought
occurs that maybe they recognized all the hokum in the war movies
coming out of Hollywood but didn't want to shatter anybody's
romantic illusions about it and so just kept mum about the truth.
On second thought, though, that wouldn't have been their style. So
I prefer to leave it as something of a mystery, as something buried
in their generational makeup that inclined them not to look back.
</P>
<P>
   But had we been clear-eyed, we postwar children would have
noticed that the close-lipped veterans who oversaw our lives really
didn't resemble those full-of-moxie, hell-for-leather fighting Joes
on the screen. The men we knew, the ones working 9 to 5, mowing
lawns and coaching Little League, had little of Wayne's swagger.
They were just regular guys.
</P>
<P>
   But small boys aren't built to notice such discrepancies, let
alone reconcile them. Small boys, as a rule, aren't realists. We
preferred to see Hollywood's irrepressible GIs as faithful
renditions of the actual men who had fought the war. To us the
actors were stand-ins for the young men our fathers had been, for
the men we were born too late to know _ perhaps even for the men we
still did not know. And if they were portrayed as heroes, all the
better: what young son wouldn't want to think of his father that
way?
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing reality from fantasy is a grown-up's task, and
Spielberg, another son of the World War II generation, has fairly
risen to it. There is, of course, some irony in saying this of a
filmmaker who has imagined 20th-century dinosaurs and a lovable
extraterrestrial. But in ``Saving Private Ryan'' he is, as he was
in ``Schindler's List,'' a realist.
</P>
<P>
   His opening sequence _ an almost documentarylike half-hour of
unrelieved carnage on Omaha Beach _ is as brutal and as damning a
depiction of warfare as one is likely to see. A filmmaker couldn't
do otherwise now, not after the bitter and disillusioning
experience of Vietnam, a war whose own horrors were sent home
nightly for public viewing. Certainly not a filmmaker of the
Vietnam generation, as Spielberg is.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that ``Saving Private Ryan'' is an antiwar
movie by intention. No Hollywood producer would or could spend tens
of millions to question ``the good war.'' Even the darkly comic
madness of ``Catch-22'' did not challenge the rightness of the
Allied cause.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Private Ryan'' were construed as antiwar, that wouldn't
be saying much anyhow. An honest movie about war these days has to
be, at bottom, against it. Rather, ``Private Ryan'' is simply
overdue cinematic recognition that the men who stormed Omaha Beach
_ or any German or Japanese redoubt for that matter _ weren't icons
or symbols or archetypes; that they weren't Hollywood's gung-ho
fakes.
</P>
<P>
   With horrific images of disembodied limbs and quivering
intestines, Spielberg reminds us of the flesh and blood that
soldiers are made of. He shows them retching onto their boots and
crying for their mothers and desperate to survive in a chaos of
flying lead. And he shows them ultimately possessing the stomach to
see a vital but nasty job through even at the cost of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges are basic, maybe obvious, lessons that may not have
sunk in with the children watching Hollywood's postwar visions of
patriotism: that the men who fought found more ugliness in war than
glory, that if they were courageous they were also scared, and that
none had to be larger than life to deserve our salute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
