<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS BEWARE: BUMPS AHEAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Mich.)  (af) 
 Seth Gussow, who designs electrical systems for General Motors,
writes for automobile magazines  
 By SETH GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a teen-ager growing up near San Francisco in the 1960s, Peter
Foster would occasionally steal his parents' car in the middle of
the night and drive down to Playland at the Beach in search of an
after-hours bumper-car fix.
</P>
<P>
   These days, to satisfy that urge, Foster, 43, doesn't have to go
any farther than the Exxon station he owns in Petaluma, Calif. He
keeps some of the three dozen bumper cars he owns at the station so
that he, his employees and his customers, who come from as far as
300 miles away, can whizz around an impromptu track set up on the
station grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bumper cars were designed to operate using electric power
supplied from a metal-mesh ceiling, but Foster's cars have been
converted to 12-volt battery power, which enables them to run on
any hard, flat surface. It also boosts their speed so much that
Foster has had to lay down some ground rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make drivers promise not to do any head-ons,'' he said. ``A
20-miles-an-hour head-on would not be safe. Somebody would
definitely get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster is one of a small number of enthusiasts, mostly male, who
collect bumper cars. They find cars by scanning ads in publications
like Hemmings Motor News and Amusement Business and haggling with
arcade owners who are short of cash during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   A heavily used car can cost as little as $100, while a carefully
restored one from the '50s or '60s can go for $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Some collectors remove the motor and gearbox entirely and use
the body shell to decorate a living room or den. Others, like
Foster, enjoy tinkering with the mechanical innards to return the
cars to something like their original purpose.
</P>
<P>
   What many collectors share are childhood memories of bumper cars
similar to Foster's. Beyond offering a thrill ride, Foster says,
bumper cars were also an outlet for youthful aggression. If you
were struck by a boyhood rival on the street, ``most of the time he
could get back at him pretty good,'' Foster explained, ``whereas in
a bumper car you could get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster favors cars made by Lusse, which along with Dodgem
produced most of the bumpers cars that for 40 years were a staple
at amusement parks across the country. After the 1950s, the market
for bumper cars declined, and both companies began to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgem ceased production in 1980, while Lusse remained in
business until the death of its founder, Ray Lusse Jr., in 1994.
For years, Lusse's most popular model, the Auto Skooter, featured a
metal body, while the bullet-shaped Dodgem was made of fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   Another collector, Gary Dickinson, former president and chief
executive officer of Delco Electronics Corp. in Kokomo, Ind., owns
a pair of restored 1954 Lusses. He fondly recalls summers spent in
upstate New York riding the Dodgems at Roseland Park amusement
park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he and his wife, Libby, were in the market to buy
bumper cars when they found two for sale at Knoebel's Grove
Amusement Park in Elysburg, Pa. The cars, which were subsequently
restored by Lusse, resemble 1953 Chevrolet DeLuxes, right down to
the hood ornaments, which Dickinson says Lusse bought directly from
General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the Dickinsons had planned to convert a little-used
tennis court in back of their house in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., to
a bumper-car track, but zoning ordinances prevented them from doing
so. Eventually the couple settled for a space in their basement,
where guests can drive the cars.
</P>
<P>
   The cars retain their original 110-volt AC motors, but the power
no longer comes through an overhead pole. Instead, the cars get
power through extension cords.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with extension cords, explained Mrs. Dickinson, is
that anything more than a polite tapping of the cars may tangle the
cord, or worse, disconnect the power.
</P>
</TEXT>
