<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES SLIGHTLY LOWER IN PROFIT-TAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities retreated slightly
Wednesday in what dealers characterized as profit-taking on a
run-up in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's rebound against the yen in foreign-exchange trading
helped to underpin the bond market, dealers said, and the second
and final day of testimony by Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
Board chairman, before Congress had little effect.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond fell 10/32, to 106
10/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, rose to 5.68 percent from 5.66 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's remarks to the House Banking Committee, part of his
semiannual report to Congress, went as expected and did not give
market participants any clear signals on the course of short-term
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices moved off their lows when Greenspan said history
suggested a significant stock-market correction was likely. His
other remarks were viewed as reassuring repetitions of his
testimony on Tuesday before the Senate Banking Committee, when he
suggested that interest rates would most likely remain stable.
</P>
<P>
   An absence of economic data, combined with slow summer trading
and anticipation of elections on Thursday for leadership of Japan's
ruling Liberal Democratic Party, kept many investors from
participating in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury plans to auction $15 billion of two-year notes on
Wednesday. In when-issued trading ahead of the auction, the
two-year note was offered at a price to yield 5.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the fixed-income market, Canadian Pacific Railway
is trying to persuade holders of 1,000-year bonds issued by the
defunct Toronto, Grey and Bruce Railway in 1883 to exchange them
for Canadian Pacific stock or the security's face value of 100
pounds, worth $164 (U.S.).
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Pacific now runs the old railroad and would like to
call these bonds 885 years early, eliminating the administrative
headache of keeping track of $1.18 million worth of the 4 percent
bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
