<SLUG> BC-SMITH-AMBASSADOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ASKS SMITH TO STAY IN IRELAND THROUGH TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has asked Jean Kennedy Smith, the
US ambassador to Ireland, to extend her stay through his September
trip to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Smith's younger brother, said the
president asked Smith to delay her departure from Phoenix Park for
another three months, through the end of September. Smith has
agreed to postpone her return and will stay in the job she has held
since the spring of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Smith had packed her bags and was planning to fly
back to her New York home next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reportedly wants to keep Smith in place because of the
delicate status of the Northern Ireland peace process and the
difficulty of naming her successor.
</P>
<P>
   Although a clear majority of citizens in both the Republic of
Ireland and Northern Ireland approved the peace accord reached on
Good Friday, splinter groups continue a campaign of sabotage
through terrorism. Three young boys recently burned to death when
their house was firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Mowlam, the British secretary for Northern Ireland, met
briefly with Kennedy Wednesday after a longer meeting with
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam said that progress was being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank the Senate, Congress, and the White House for not
being fair-weather friends,'' she said while posing for a
photograph with Kennedy and Senator Christopher Dodd, a Connecticut
Democrat. ``It has been tough, and it will continue to be tough.
We've made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy praised Mowlam and British Prime Minister Tony Blair for
the roles they played in negotiating the peace accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
