<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYS-FILMS-ART-NYT &LR;      07-22 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-FILMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILOSOPHY MAJOR MAKES A BUNDLE WITH BOYS' MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Tom Rothman, president of 20th Century Fox film
production, is a very happy studio executive. ``The boys are
back,'' Rothman said, speaking of the studio's two summer hits,
``Doctor Doolittle'' and ``There's Something About Mary,'' which
owe a hefty share of their box office success to teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Joe Roth, chairman of Walt Disney Studios, predicted
that the company's doomsday film ``Armageddon,'' which opened
somewhat disappointingly on the Fourth of July weekend, could
emerge with the biggest box office gross of the summer, $185
million to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and ``Zorro'' also playing powerfully
among young men, it's turning into a summer of boy's films that
crossed over into larger audiences of families (``Dr. Doolittle'')
and girls (``Armageddon''). And Robert Simonds, Hollywood's
foremost producer of boy films, couldn't be more delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing right now is a reaffirmation that the teen
male really does represent a tremendous amount of cash at the box
office,'' he said. Males from 12 to 22 remain the single most
reliable segment of the moviegoing public _one third of the
audience _ even though their influence at the box office has dipped
a bit in favor of young girls and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds, whose newest boy film, ``The Waterboy,'' with Adam
Sandler and Kathy Bates, is to be released by Disney in November,
is an improbable movie producer. He majored in philosophy at Yale,
wears a suit and tie to work every day, keeps his hair short and
speaks like a shrewd, cheerful businessman. Which, in some ways, he
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly great at producing, but it's just nobody
else was doing what I do,'' he said. What Simonds has done, in a
curiously unflamboyant way, is carve a niche and dominate the
lucrative market of teen-age boys' films. He admitted this will
probably never earn him an Academy Award or a seat at the table of
top Hollywood producers like Scott Rudin (``The Truman Show,'' ``In
and Out'') or Brian Grazer (``Liar, Liar,'' ``Apollo 13''). But
he's earning piles of money.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with his training as a philosophy major (his thesis was on
the nature of evil) and a shrewd sense of the bottom line, Simonds,
34, has developed and produced a dozen films in the last eight
years, including hits like ``Problem Child,'' ``Happy Gilmore,''
``Billy Madison'' and ``The Wedding Singer.'' Though critics have
hardly raved, the films have struck a chord with (mostly) young
male audiences. Though lately he is extending his reach to older
males, too, Simonds said most of his movies have a target audience
of boys from 12 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of these movies have is a blatant disregard for
authority, because when you're a teen you don't have the
traditional weapons of power or money or social status,'' he said.
``So what you have is shock _ and shock is a really important
weapon for a teen.'' His movies also have the classic ``snob versus
slob, popping pretentious balloons, which teens love.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex is surprisingly muted in his films. ``I don't know how you
make sex funny,'' he said. ``And in a weird way, the girls in these
films are like straight men. They're on pedestals. They're
unattainable.''
</P>
<P>
   In emerging as one of the most successful producers in town, he
turned the system upside down in a simple way: the director,
generally considered the king of the world on a movie set, is a
commoner in Simonds' films, not quite an afterthought but
definitely a hired hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually in the movies you're servicing a director's vision,''
said Simonds at his office at Universal Studios. ``In the TV
business directors are more interchangeable because it's built all
around Seinfeld or Roseanne or Drew Carey. My movies are along
those lines. An Adam Sandler movie is all Adam Sandler. The
sensibility and point of view is consistent and idiosyncratic as
opposed to a Spielberg or Bob Zemeckis movie, where the actors are
interchangeable.''
</P>
<P>
   `I Control the Process'
</P>
<P>
   Simonds centers his movies around a star; he's made five films
with Sandler. The star controls the script. A production designer
is hired by Simonds and the star together with an editor and most
of the cast. Simonds and the studio agree on a release date. Then
Simonds hires a director, usually a young filmmaker from television
or the video world, only a few weeks before the cameras are to
roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I control the money, I control the process,'' Simonds
said. Such a public credo would send most Hollywood directors into
shock, but the philosophy is actually a throwback to the 1930s and
'40s, when moguls like Louis Mayer and Jack Warner often picked
directors under contract to make a film based on who was available
that week. And legendary producers like David Selznick often
controlled directors too.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Simonds unusual is that he's candid about practicing
a kind of producing that has no cachet but has never really gone
out of style in Hollywood. Over the years, top action producers
like Jerry Bruckheimer and Joel Silver have often hired young or
first-time filmmakers, partly to control them as well as the
process. But those two have never quite admitted it.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Silver, chairman of Universal Pictures, where Simonds
makes most of his movies, spoke admiringly of the producer. ``If he
says a movie will cost X, that's what it'll cost. If he tells me
what the movie is going to be like, that's what it's going to be.
In a business of surprises, that's a very good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Simonds grew up in Phoenix, Ariz., where his father, Robert,
sells water to the city and state. Majoring in philosophy
``literally prepared me to do nothing,'' said Simonds, who fell in
love with the movie business as a child on the Universal Studios
tour. The studio's theme park rides are visible outside his window.
He moved to Los Angeles after graduation and worked as an intern at
the MGM studios in 1985. Soon he yearned to be a producer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYS-FILMS-ART-2NDTAK     07-22 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-FILMS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: a producer. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So I started coming up with ideas and finding writers who were
also starting out, and we tried to set up pitches,'' Simonds
recalled. ``They were designed to be these low-budget comedies that
weren't star-contingent. They were hopefully things that would fly
under the radar so that on my first one or two I wouldn't be
replaced. I felt like one of those mammals in the age of dinosaurs,
scurrying around trying not to be seen.'' Once stars arrive on a
film, they often replace producers with their own associates.
</P>
<P>
   Two young screenwriters, Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski,
who later wrote ``Ed Wood'' and ``The People vs. Larry Flynt,''
sold him on a comic version of ``The Bad Seed,'' about a devilish
child adopted by an unwitting man. John Ritter signed on to play
the father. Universal agreed to back it for less than $10 million.
Simonds found a young director, Dennis Dugan, who later made
``Happy Gilmore.''
</P>
<P>
   A Niche Few Cared About
</P>
<P>
   ```Problem Child' had some really funny moments, but the film
itself didn't really add up,'' Simonds said. ``We all had this
psychotic ambition that made up for whatever flaws the film had.
And it actually made truckloads of money.'' The film grossed $55
million in the United States, $25 million overseas and $20 million
on video.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Problem Child,'' Simonds said he found his calling as a
producer of teen-age boy comedies: ``It was the one area that I
felt I could compete in, a niche that most of the producers here
didn't care about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What was great about something like `Problem Child' was that
the movie was green-lit regardless of the director, regardless of
the star,'' he said. ``So many people around here are in this
limbo, saying, `Oh sure, we'll make this movie if Tom Cruise wants
to do it or Bob Zemeckis wants to direct it.' I don't want to play
that game.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience taught him that producing should be viewed as a
business. ``One-third of the job is getting the package right,
getting the script right; a big third of it is marketing and
another big third is distribution, finding a safe corridor where
the big movies aren't going to stomp you to death, getting the
right weekend to open.'' (Many of Sandler's movies open around the
relatively quiet Presidents' Day weekend).
</P>
<P>
   His background in philosophy also helped, he said. ``Philosophy
teaches hopelessness and hopelessness teaches comedy,'' he said.
``And ultimately all philosophy is, is training in rational
argument. As a producer, that's 90 percent of your job. It's trying
to formulate a cohesive point of view out of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Simonds has had a flop or two, notably ``Airheads,'' a 1994 Adam
Sandler comedy about three metalheads who take a rock radio station
hostage. ``We got cocky and put it in an unsafe corridor, the
middle of the summer,'' he said. ``And in hindsight we were
basically making fun of the people who were supposed to be coming
to see the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has a very successful track record. His films generally
cost $10 million to $15 million. ``We're averaging a 33 percent
return on investment, which is huge for the movie business
considering the standard return on investment for a comedy is like
6 percent,'' he said. By far his best film, and one of the most
successful, was ``The Wedding Singer,'' with Sandler and Drew
Barrymore. It cost $22 million, and grossed $77 million in the
United States. More a love story than a boys' comedy, it is one of
the few films produced by Simonds with a strong appeal to girls.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds lives in Beverly Hills with his fiancee, Angela
Featherstone, who played the woman who jilted Sandler in ``The
Wedding Singer.'' He has half a dozen projects in production, with
comedians like Sandler, Norm McDonald and Chris Tucker, who is
starring with Mariah Carey in ``00 Soul,'' a black James Bond
takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian David Spade was in Simonds' office earlier in the
day, pitching an idea that the producer adored. ``He sat right
there and said, `I have a comedy and I play a gay guy who goes out
one night and gets hit on the head by a disco ball, gets total
amnesia, and his father sees this as an opportunity to reprogram
him as a straight guy.' I laughed and said, `I love it,' and that's
it. We're going to make that movie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
