<SLUG> BC-PICTURTEL-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURETEL REPORTS PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PictureTel Corp. eked out its first quarterly operating profit
in more than a year, despite lower revenues, and said Wednesday it
plans to acquire a Silicon Valley firm whose technology will
broaden PictureTel's menu of video conferencing services.
</P>
<P>
   Starlight Networks Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., specializes in
video streaming technology, which allows video transmission over
data networks.
</P>
<P>
   By blending Starlight's streaming capabilities with its own
video conferencing expertise, Picturetel will be able to offer
customers the ability to not only participate in a live meeting
from remote locations, but also to store and retrieve the recorded
session for use in corporate briefings, long-distance training, and
business television.
</P>
<P>
   There are other applications as well. An important speech by a
company's chief executive, for instance, could be viewed nearly
instantaneously on the desktop computer of thousands of employees
scattered around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market segment that is just beginning to take off,''
said James Stone, an analyst with Preferred Capital Markets, a San
Francisco brokerage firm. ``And I believe it's going to be a very
important market.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies are still negotiating terms of the deal, so it was
unclear how much PictureTel would pay for Starlight, a privately
held company with 55 employees.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel will use to its common stock as currency to finance
the deal, although it will also pay some cash.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the video collaboration industry said buying
Starlight is a smart move by PictureTel, even though the purchase
will hurt short-term earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They happened to land one of the most well-positioned
companies in the video streaming industry,'' said Jason Ader, an
analyst with H.C. Wainwright &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``It's a perfect
complement for PictureTel's strategy,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of new chief executive Bruce Bond, the once
high-flying company is trying to get back on track after stumbling
badly in 1997 amid an industry-wide slump.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Andover, Mass., company turned a corner when it
announced a return to profitability, excluding special charges.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel, which remains the market leader in sales of video
conferencing equipment despite its recent troubles, reported a
second-quarter profit of $1.2 million, or 3 cents a diluted share.
The figure does not include an $11.6 million write-off of
inventory, a discontinued product line, and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Including the charge, the company's net loss for the quarter was
$6.7 million, or 17 cents per diluted share. That compares with a
net loss of $4.9 million, or 13 cents per diluted share, in the
year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly gain, which was PictureTel's first operating
profit since the first quarter of 1997, was achieved despite lower
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel's sales fell 11 percent to $104.6 million compared to
the same period a year ago. The drop in revenue is due to pricing
pressure from competitors, as well as a continued slowdown in the
industry as customers grapple with buying decisions in the face of
new technologies, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our strategies was to get the company in a position
where it could make money at a lower revenue rate,'' said Bond, who
earns praise from analysts for quickly turning the company around
since his arrival in March.
</P>
<P>
   The return to profitability, said Ader, ``bodes extremely well
for the future and is a tribute to Bruce Bond and Dick Goldman,''
the company's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman announced Wednesday he will resign from PictureTel in
September, after just one year on the job. Bond said it was an
amicable separation and praised Goldman's leadership during ``a
difficult financial period.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said he decided to take advantage of an escape clause in
his employment contract to assess his career options.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel also announced that Frazer Hamilton, who worked
previously with Bond at two other companies, would join PictureTel
in the newly created position of vice president of business
processes and quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
