<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS SAYS DULLNESS MAY BE ASSET IN CALIF. GOVERNOR RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Playfully considering the possibility that he may
be dull, California's Democratic gubernatorial candidate Gray Davis
said Wednesday his image as an austere political figure may
actually help him win in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paying your dues counts,'' said Davis, California's lieutenant
governor, at a luncheon here with Washington political reporters.
Voters, he insisted, are tired of candidates who are all ``flash
and dash'' and geared more to be a ``replacement for Jay Leno''
than governor. Instead, people are looking for a candidate with ``a
solid, substantive vision'' of California's future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also confided, tongue-in-cheek, that he has appointed an
18-member ``task force on dullness'' because he was ``so tired of
being called dull.'' He said the group recommended that ``I keep my
charisma on hold because `dull' seemed to be a path to victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis made the comments after some reporters suggested that
Republican candidate Dan Lungren, California's attorney general,
was, in contrast to Davis, a deft ``Reaganesque'' campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor said his GOP opponent ``may have more
charisma.'' However, apparently envisioning headlines that might
result from that statement, Davis quickly backtracked, adding,
``But he may not have more charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton once advised him
that he needed ``an Al Gore shtick.'' He was referring to the vice
president's frequent jokes about his own reputation as a wooden
speaker. Davis described Gore as ``my charisma coach.''
</P>
<P>
   On a serious note, Davis pointed to issues that divide him and
Lungren. One is abortion, Davis said, adding that he is
``pro-choice'' and that Lungren is ``anti-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   On anti-smoking litigation, Davis said that in January 1997 he
became a leading plaintiff in a San Diego lawsuit to recover
health-related damages from tobacco companies. He said Lungren was
late on the issue, becoming the 37th state attorney general to file
suit in June 1997 when the state legislature authorized such a
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in San Francisco, Dave Puglia, Lungren's campaign
director, said in a phone interview that Lungren was unable to file
earlier because the legislature had granted the tobacco industry
immunity from state lawsuits. Lungren succeeded in persuading the
legislature to rescind the immunity, Puglia said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said he first supported limiting military-style
assault weapons in 1985. Four years later, then Republican Gov.
George Deukmejian signed legislation banning 60 types of assault
weapons and allowing the attorney general to add ``copycat''
weapons to the list. Lungren, Davis said, has done little to add
such guns to that list.
</P>
<P>
   Puglia said Lungren sought to add copycat weapons to the list in
1991 but has been blocked by the courts and is now appealing to the
state supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's campaign page on the World Wide Web stresses his
support of legislation that added 10 years to the sentence of a
criminal who uses a gun, 20 years if the gun is fired and
25-years-to-life if a victim is wounded. The page also stresses
Lungren's support of background checks for prospective gun buyers
to weed out convicted criminals and the mentally ill, saying the
state attorney general's office has denied 30,000 gun purchases.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David was in Washington for a fundraiser Tuesday night at the
home of Rep. Jane Harman, D-Calif., one of two major Democratic
opponents that he beat in the June 2 primary. President Clinton and
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt attended the party.
</P>
<P>
   That event plus fund-raisers Davis is holding in New York and
Chicago will net his war chest close to $1 million, according to
his campaign manager, Garry South.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he expects to spend between $20 million and $30
million on the campaign and expects Lungren to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   Davis tweaked the Washington reporters, reminding them how they
had once dismissed him as ``road kill'' and ``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign season opens, he joked, the only thing that
would get him nervous would be ``if the Washington pundits
predicted (my victory).''
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton will join him at a fund-raiser Aug. 11 at the
St. Francis Hotel in San Francisco, an event chaired by the city's
mayor, Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also made it clear that although Gov. Pete Wilson is
leaving office, he still looms large as a campaign target.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat cited Wilson's backing of Proposition 187, which in
1994 barred most social services and education to undocumented
immigrants, and Proposition 209, which in 1996 ended affirmative
action in state hiring, contracting and admissions to public
colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis praised Wilson for reducing class size, building the
economy and fighting crime, he blamed the governor for ``a legacy
of division and distrust'' that he said will make it ``even
harder'' for Lungren to win this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
