<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIELBERG-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      07-22 2780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIELBERG-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIELBERG SHREDS HOLLYWOOD IMAGE OF WWII  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE FRIDAY JULY 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATE - Steven Spielberg won't let his 13-year-old son see his
new movie _ and he doesn't think you should let your kids see it,
either.
</P>
<P>
   That's an unusual warning from a filmmaker who has created some
of history's favorite family films.
</P>
<P>
   But Spielberg's latest creation is a shock to the system:
``Saving Private Ryan,'' is the most realistic war movie ever made
in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   As a master of film fantasy, Spielberg gave us the galaxy's most
endearing alien (``E.T.``), thrilling monsters (``Jaws'' and
``Jurassic Park'') and the wildest adventure that never happened
(''Raiders of the Lost Ark'').
</P>
<P>
   All of Spielberg's successful fantasies share one quality: They
take the audience along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Spielberg uses all the emotional
techniques at his command to take us on the ultimate non-ride: into
the mechanized maw of modern war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' follows a single squad of American GIs
through the D-Day landing at Omaha Beach, one of the biggest
foul-ups of World War II, and onto an impossible mission: rescuing
one soldier from behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   This is war seen not from the grand sweep of the generals'
battle plans but from one narrow strip of the front, as a few
desperate soldiers try to survive the random death striking down
everyone around them.
</P>
<P>
   The battle scenes, particularly the opening 24-minute invasion
of Omaha Beach, contain some of the rawest footage of what it looks
like when human bodies are ripped apart by machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   How far would Spielberg go to depict the carnage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not go as far as what those real boys experienced 55
years ago,'' the director said. ``I couldn't go that far. That was
the line I didn't allow myself to cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only a glance at what they had to endure on that beach
and live with for the rest of their lives. I intended to make the
most realistic war film ever.''
</P>
<P>
   If Spielberg takes only a glance at the horrors of war, it's a
harder look than most filmmakers would have dared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drew a line in the sand of Omaha Beach,'' he said. ``I got
close to the line but never crossed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people will think he did. According to co-star Matt Damon,
the lab technician who developed the footage of the bayonet fight
in the final battle pleaded with Spielberg to cut it from the film.
He did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to glorify war,'' Spielberg said. ``I was set
and determined to debunk the myth of war created by hundreds of
World War II films. So I needed to make it real. But I also needed
people to allow themselves to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Longest Day,'' the 1963 D-Day epic starring John Wayne,
Robert Mitchum and Henry Fonda, is the ultimate Hollywood World War
II movie: It's big, it's fought gloriously, and whenever faced with
reality it goes Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan,'' covering some of the same hard-won
territory, provides the antidote of grim reality to everything
Hollywood has ever shown us about World War II _ from the
propaganda films made during the war to build home-front spirit, to
the scores of adventure movies that simply used the war as a
backdrop for visceral excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's intention was to honor the soldiers who fought in
World War II by depicting their battles accurately, not cleaned up
and glorified in typical Hollywood style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is closer to some of the Vietnam War
films _ ``Full Metal Jacket,'' ''Platoon,'' ''Hamburger Hill'' _
that graphically depict the physical butchery and mental taxation
of modern battle.
</P>
<P>
   But there was always an asterisk attached to those Vietnam
films. They were viewed as political statements, condemning an
unpopular war fought under a cloud of suspicious political
judgments.
</P>
<P>
   World War II, in contrast, was always the good war, with most of
the world united against Hitler's threat to humanity's future.
</P>
<P>
   World War II films always emphasized the heroism of soldiers who
fought the Nazi horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' slaps us back to reality, stating
plainly that for the guys on the front line there is only war, that
getting killed in a good war makes you just as dead as getting
</P>
<P>
   killed in a bad war.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Baptism of fire' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg contends that the film's opening battle, as gruesome
as it is, ``puts the audience inside the physical experience of
Omaha Beach and creates a brotherhood between the audience and
those eight guys who survived that battle when they go on their
next mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that baptism of fire, the audience would be on the
journey, but as spectators rather than as brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, who typically makes movies aimed at the widest
possible audience, doesn't want his fans confused. He warns people:
``If you think this movie is going to be too hard on you, then you
shouldn't see it. This is not a kinder, gentler Steven Spielberg
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would advise that people 14 and under should not be allowed
to see the picture at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get up at the age of some of the boys who died there
on the beach, you should see a picture about those who did what you
could do.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' opens on Omaha Beach because those sands
were turned into a killing field where some 2,000 American GIs died
on one day.
</P>
<P>
   According to Spielberg, ``Seventy percent of those boys who hit
the beach had never seen combat before. Many of them died without
ever reaching the beach or during their first seconds on the
sand.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Spielberg, the generals planning the invasion
deliberately chose green troops to lead the first wave. ``They
thought that seasoned troops might not want to go through D-Day
because they knew how bad it can get,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The troops sent in that first wave were told the beaches and
bluffs would be cleared of German defenders by bombing runs and
Naval bombardment, that they would land unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs and shells sent against German emplacements were
successful at other Normandy landing points. But at Omaha Beach,
they fell long or short. The GIs storming the beach from landing
craft came upon Germans fully prepared to kill them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two minutes, they were no longer green,'' Spielberg said,
``and hopefully neither is the audience. The audience is completely
in line with the young boys who had never seen combat.''
</P>
<P>
   That's due to Spielberg's skill at re-creating the chaos of
battle yet keeping us tightly focused on the humanity of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, like his cast, was acutely aware of his obligation to
the living and the dead of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been for me less than honorable to have just
done one more World War II movie,'' Spielberg said, ``to use their
sacrifice as simply a backdrop for action and adventure. They
didn't have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   When Spielberg chose the ensemble cast to back up star Tom
Hanks, he inadvertently did something unusual: He cast a squad of
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks directed ``That Thing You Do!'' and part of his TV
miniseries about the space program, ``From the Earth to the Moon.''
Co-star Edward Burns, who plays a disgruntled member of Hanks'
squad, wrote and directed three films, including ``No Looking
Back.'' Matt Damon, who plays the paratrooper the squad tries to
rescue, won an Oscar for co-writing ``Good Will Hunting.'' Two
other soldiers in the squad, Adam Goldberg and Vin Diesel, are also
movie directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know some of the others were filmmakers until they
began second-guessing me,'' Spielberg claimed. ``I said to Vin and
Adam, `Who do you think you are, directors?' And they said, `Yeah,
we are.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They all had opinions about things. It was great being around
a bunch of directors, It was like the DGA (Directors Guild of
America) was making the movie with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Damon intends to direct his own scripts someday, the
actor studied Spielberg during the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned enough to know that I can't put into use most of the
stuff he does,'' Damon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven is so brilliant. The level of decision-making and the
speed at which makes those decisions and the confidence at which he
does it _ it's unlike anything I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks was equally impressed with how Spielberg dealt with such a
large-scale production, which included 750 extras from the Irish
army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see instantly that we were working with the most
facile guy in the world,'' Hanks said. ``There is a handful of guys
who do it as well as Spielberg, and most of them are dead.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reality-based shoot &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg not only had to deal with the massive logistics of an
epic war movie, he had to keep talented actors focused on the
nuances of their performances amid the frenzy of a
special-effects-dominated battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He created this atmosphere for us to act in, in which the
truth of the moment was very truthful,'' Hanks said. ``For
Spielberg, nothing matters but the truth of the shot. If it's real,
it will be self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie Burns said, `Can you believe how fast this guy is
shooting?' All of us actors who were directors swore that we'll
never be slow again.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon was awed by the way Spielberg packed the frame with action
during the battle scenes. ``It's so chaotic. It creates this
atmosphere and sense of horror,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks also credits the director with being willing to change the
screenplay dramatically once he agreed to play the leading role of
Captain Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was originally a cigar-chewing, Medal of Honor winner,''
Hanks recalled. ``We've seen that guy a million times, a standard
war hero. It's not interesting as an actor, and it's false to what
actually happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks' Captain ended up as a man pushing himself beyond his
personal limits of stress to hold up his obligation to his men _
not an invincible warrior but a man doing the best he can under
impossible conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie is not a vehicle for me,'' he said. ``It's not
about any one of us. It's about honoring the past.''
</P>
<P>
   When the director chose the rest of the supporting cast, he was
looking for guy-next-door types, non-heroes stuck in a rotten
situation, trying to fight their way out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked different back then,'' Spielberg said. ``They
were closer to the immigrant stock of the '30s and '40s than we are
today. People look prettier now than they did 60 years ago. Then,
they were more rough-hewn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went with people who looked like the soldiers I see on the
World War II documentaries on the History Channel, which I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg was equally obsessive about getting the detail of
soldiering in 1944 right. To do that, he hired a military expert
who had worked on other war films, retired Marine Capt. Dale Dye.
Then Spielberg took it one step further than most filmmakers: He
actually listened to what Dye told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be the most authentic representation of World
War II,'' Spielberg said. ``When I told that to Dye, he said,
`Sweeter words have never been spoken.' I gave him permission to be
technically obsessive.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see that obsessive attention to detail throughout the
movie: in the way different ordnance sounds when fired, in the
small, quick move of a soldier as he taps a clip against his helmet
to realign the bullets before inserting the clip into his rifle, in
the changing skin tones of a man bleeding to death.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg had his technical crew study the impact of the
different ordnance being used on that beach, so that when shells
and bullets hit the sand it would look authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Dye told Spielberg when the big shells landed that ``I don't
want to see any stinking Hollywood fireballs.''
</P>
<P>
   There are none, and no heroes outracing them to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other movie where they're even trying to be this
authentic,'' Hanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalled Damon: ``If a stunt looked too stunty, he cut it out.
Spielberg is smart enough to hire these incredible people like Dye.
Add that to his wizardry with a camera and his ability to tell a
story.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dye was Spielberg's litmus test, the Vietnam veteran
performed similar functions for the actors searching for
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best resource was Dale Dye standing right off camera the
entire time,'' Damon said. ``He watched us like a hawk. If you did
something wrong, he was going to tell you. It's the ultimate for an
actor. We all look for the real people to base our characters on.''
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Camp was critical &QL; 
 &QL; 
Before the filming began, Dye took Hanks and his seven-man squad
for six days of basic training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the lecture, then we marched out to our camp,'' Hanks
said. ``We were wet and cold and tired and miserable, which worked
out well because we play guys who are wet and cold and tired and
miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Their training ``was about how far you can push your body,''
Hanks said. ``Without those six days, it would have been a
different movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon wasn't invited to boot camp, which disappointed him at
first because he wants ``every advantage and angle I can get on
making a character authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Damon realized, ``It was an ingenious ploy on Spielberg's
part because the movie is about these eight guys risking their
lives for this one guy. By excluding me, when I showed up on the
set and asked, `Hey, guys, how was boot camp?' the seeds of
resentment were already planted in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg shot the opening D-Day battle first and spent three
weeks doing it, so that by the end of the battle the actors would
feel the exhaustion and shock that the survivors of the landing
were left with.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first day on that beach, it was mind-boggling,''
Hanks recalled. ``The only way of doing a movie like this is as
authentically as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg divided that three-week battle production into
geographic zones: in the water, on the sand, at the sea wall, up
over the bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a new brand of chaos and hell at every one of those
sections,'' Hanks recalled. ``It was extremely physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks found it hard to struggle from the landing craft through
the surf. To add to the feeling that everything is bearing down on
you, he ``kept weight in my pack so I wasn't moving too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   They filmed that battle in three-minute bursts on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   In between shots, while the camera crews set up for the next
burst, the actors ``lay down on the sand and went to sleep because
the trailers were too far away,'' Hanks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be true to what those guys went through, not just
to the survivors but to the dead,'' the star added. ``We didn't
want to do this play-acting an Army man thing where we all have
rubber weapons. We owed it to the memory of the whole enterprise of
D-Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg also consulted with survivors of the Omaha Beach
landing, some of whom watched the filming on the Irish coast. ``We
had one man who lost his entire company in that landing. He was the
only survivor,'' Spielberg recalled, adding that some of the
veterans couldn't watch the filming because it brought back too
many memories.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing ``Saving Private Ryan'' to ``All Quiet on the Western
Front'' and ``A Walk in the Sun,'' two realistic war movies
directed by Lewis Milestone, Spielberg thinks of his film as a
``documentary to what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to get people to think twice when they pass a
memorial cemetery. ``Look at it. Don't forget it's there. Take your
hat off to the people who allowed us to have the life we're living
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg clearly made this movie to stir our conscience and
make us reflect upon our history. As a movie with a big message,
``Saving Private Ryan'' fits with his other two historic epics:
``Schindler's List,'' about the Nazi horror of exterminating
civilian populations, and ``Amistad,'' about the brutality of the
American slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   But Spielberg claims he is not on a cinematic mission to
dramatize history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a deliberate plan to make these great social
movies,'' he said. ``I did not set out on a crusade to do relevant
movies about history. I have never had a career plan or spent time
charting my own destiny. No one mortal can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then how does he choose which projects to film?
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust my intuition,'' he replied. ``I have been wrong a lot.
But you can't trust your intuition, get screwed by it, and then
never trust it again. You have to keep trusting it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
