</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PANEL REJECTS CLINTON NOMINEE FOR AIR FORCE SECRETARY
 &HT;    By SHANNON JOYCE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One week after hearing testimony challenging
Florida state Sen. Daryl Jones's personal integrity, a Senate panel
Wednesday rejected his nomination to become the first black
secretary of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare refusal to approve a nominee for the civilian chief of
a military branch, the Senate Armed Services Committee voted 9-9 on
a motion to send Jones's nomination to the full Senate, killing his
nine-month bid for the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have lost a fine opportunity to get a good man,''
Committee Chairman Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said after the vote.
``All the propaganda that has come out against him has turned the
public against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond was the only member of the committee to cross party
lines and vote in support of Jones. While Sens. Robert Byrd, D-W.
Va., and Charles Robb, D-Va., said they would not vote to send a
positive recommendation to the Senate, they did vote to forward the
nomination without any recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who testified on behalf of Jones, said
``The committee's failure to approve him is a tragedy, and a
tremendous loss for America.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Jones was a ``highly
qualified, superb nominee'' who had ``more than adequately answered
the concerns that were expressed by various senators.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton had not decided if he would continue to
push for Jones or choose another nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Jones told reporters at the Pentagon that none of the objections
raised against him ``made logical sense to me.'' He said he would
keep his reserve status and return to Florida to campaign for
re-election to his state Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My constituents are very supportive. ... I hope I am welcomed
back with open arms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 43, an Air Force Academy graduate and former fighter
pilot, faced an unusual daylong grilling last week on allegations
about his fighter pilot status, his work as an Amway salesman, and
his involvement in a bond sale to finance an expansion of Miami
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Republican committee members said the claims of dishonesty and
inappropriate behavior from fellow officers cast too much doubt on
Jones's integrity and ability to unify and inspire Air Force
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This candidate, in my judgment, was brought before this
committee with a record of fact so fulled with controversy and
conflict that he will be unable to serve as a leader to inspire the
persons under him, particularly those in uniform,'' said Sen. John
Warner, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and other committee members have questioned whether Jones
voluntarily chose, as he testified, to stop flying F-16 fighter
planes when he was a member of the Air Force Reserve in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he couldn't juggle the demands of elected office and
a new law practice and still put in the required aircraft training.
After his superior officer, Col. Thomas Dyches, warned him to
commit to training or face a review panel, Jones said he chose to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   Dyches told the committee last week that he ordered Jones to
stop flying, saying Jones ``misrepresented the facts'' during his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow officer said he saw Jones pitch Amway products to
enlisted personnel, a practice forbidden under Air Force rules.
Jones denies the claim, and no enlisted personnel have come forward
to say they were pressured.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case we have a 180-degree difference in what has
happened,'' said Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind. ``I can't write that off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission cleared Jones of
wrongdoing in an inquiry of the Florida bond sale. A Miami
securities firm was one of several local firms that handled bond
sales for the city, but officials thought the firm was too small to
handle such a large project. As an unsalaried employee of the firm
paid on commission, Jones persuaded county officials to let it
handle the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee had questioned whether Jones acted
more as a consultant, a role that would have required that he
register with Florida regulators. Members of the committee met with
representatives of the Securities and Exchange Commission last
month, but many continued to question Jones's involvement last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's supporters said his unique qualifications fit perfectly
with the demands of a job that has both military and political
responsibilities. He is the only nominee for the position in recent
history who graduated from the Air Force Academy, served in the
active-duty Air Force, the Air National Guard and the Air Force
Reserve. After earning a law degree from the University of Miami,
Jones served two years in the Florida House of Representatives and
six in the Florida Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, said accusations do not prove
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess in my mind the question comes down to what are the
proven allegations,'' Glenn said. ``I think if we're going to wreck
a man's career, the least we should do is take testimony under oath
and find out who is telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said. ``I'm disappointed that
they didn't let the full Senate decide.''
</P>
<P>
   A vocal supporter of Jones's nomination, Levin accused the
committee of trying to rob Jones of his dignity and his fellow
officers of being ``out to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
