<HEADER>
A7965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBSPILLOW-DANCE-AR     07-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBSPILLOW-DANCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI BALLET SERVES UP SMORGASBORD OF CHOREOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ Hungry theatergoers visiting the Jacob's Pillow
Dance Festival can find a restaurant, a pub and a snack bar on the
grounds. But anyone who arrived on Tuesday night would also have
discovered an artistically delectable treat inside the Ted Shawn
Theater: a choreographic smorgasbord served up by the Miami City
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   It was an evening of tidbits. All the pieces were short, and
most were excerpts from longer works. They proved a fine
assortment.
</P>
<P>
   The full title of this presentation to recorded accompaniment
was ``Edward Villella and Dancers From Miami City Ballet,'' and it
featured 10 of the company's 50 members. Some people in the
audience might have wondered what part Villella, the troupe's
director, would play in the performance. Although he was one of the
greatest stars of the New York City Ballet, he no longer dances.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he served as host of the feast, commenting on the
presentations with great charm. Using culinary imagery, he likened
the program to an hors d'oeuvres buffet and a Spanish tapas meal.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised that most of the ballets would emphasize
relationships. The relationships turned out to be of two kinds:
esthetic affinities among choreographers, styles and historical
periods and emotional relationships between people. Although these
ballets were plotless, they did express feelings and served as
reminders that George Balanchine, Villella's mentor, once remarked
that two people onstage were ``a story in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   From the 19th century came the buoyant pas de deux from ``Flower
Festival at Genzano,'' by Danish choreographer August Bournonville.
This duet for lovers begins with a gentle stroll, then develops
into joyous leaps and bounds. Jennifer Kronenberg and Didier Bramaz
were sweetly flirtatious as the lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kronenberg looked delicate in the small darting steps.
Bramaz kept his arms in repose in the passages that required his
feet to perform intricate beats. The way the dancers appeared both
merry and decorous made it possible to understand what Villella
meant when he called Bournonville a ``moral choreographer.''
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine shared Bournonville's fondness for speed and
lightness. ``Valse Fantaisie'' certainly made that evident.
Balanchine must have loved this waltz by Glinka; he kept on
choreographing it. The Miami company gave his 1953 staging for a
man and three women, rather than the more familiar 1967 version for
a principal couple and an ensemble of four women.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Paige Fulleton, Tricia Albertson, Joan Latham
and Arnold Quintane suggested that this lesser-known production
deserves to be better known today. Groups kept forming and
dissolving with remarkable rapidity, and the dancers remained at
ease in all the quicksilver comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fleetness and delicacy associated with the
Danish style, Balanchine admired the imperial dignity of the
Russian style in which he was trained. One of his most stately
duets, the pas de deux from the ``Diamonds'' section of ``Jewels,''
received a suitably aristocratic interpretation by Deanna Seay and
Eric Quillere. Ms. Seay revealed that she realized that benign
aristocrats show their good breeding through their confidence
rather than their arrogance, and Quillere was an attentive,
princely partner.
</P>
<P>
   What was billed as the ``concert version'' of ``Who Cares?''
turned out to be the sequence of solos and duets that are the
choreographic heart of this ballet to orchestrated Gershwin songs.
Coming after extroverted ensembles and preceeding a splashy finale,
these smaller-scaled episodes convey a sense of intimacy. The cast
invested each solo with its own special personality. Ms. Seay was
frisky. Ms. Kronenberg emphasized the choreography's quirky shifts
of weight and direction. Ms. Fulleton whirled happily. Quillere was
insouciant. And when the women took turns dancing with him, each
duet suggested that these were people who loved to be together.
</P>
<P>
   The program included two works by the company's capable resident
choreographer, Jimmy Gamonet De Los Heros: ``Nous Sommes'' and a
suite from ``Transtangos.'' ``Nous Sommes'' was the more striking.
Filled with complicated lifts and entwinings, this pas de deux
could have been nothing but blatant exhibitionism. But the way
Iliana Lopez and Franklin Gamero focused so intensely upon each
other made each virtuosic phrase the choreographic equivalent of a
passionate sigh by lovers totally immersed in their own private
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transtangos'' combined classical ballet with Argentine tango
dancing. The mixture looked forced at times. But Gamero was
convincing in a brooding solo in which leaps eventually resembled
acts of defiance, and his duets with Ms. Lopez were sultry and
sizzling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
