<P>
   CHINA-MILITARY (Beijing) _ President Jiang Zemin has ordered the
military to relinquish its business empire.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate Armed Services
Committee rejects President Clinton's choice to be the next
secretary of the Air Force, dealing the administration a stinging
setback on a political appointment that typically sails through the
Senate. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS (Izingolweni, South Africa) _ Years behind many
other sub-Saharan countries, South Africa has finally begun to see
its people die from AIDS. In almost every cluster of desperately
poor huts tucked into the rolling hills of KwaZulu Natal province,
the slow wasting death that few will admit to is wreaking its
havoc. The AIDS epidemic here is now one of the fastest growing in
the world. Experts say that South Africa, protected by apartheid's
isolationism and with a health system better than any other on the
continent, had a unique opportunity to prevent the kind of
explosion of AIDS cases that the rest of Africa had seen. By
Suzanne Daley. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCAFFOLD-COLLAPSE (New York) _ Roundup on the aftermath of
the collapse of a scaffold at at Times Square construction site. By
Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONED-MICE (Undated) _ Scientists from Hawaii say they have
cloned dozens of adult mice and even cloned some mouse clones. The
announcement means that advances in cloning are emerging faster
than even the most confident scientists had imagined. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SHEPARD (Undated) _ Alan B. Shepard Jr., the first American
to fly in space, lifting national spirits at a decisive moment of
Cold War anxiety, and later one of only 12 astronauts to walk on
the Moon, died Wednesday at a hospital near Monterey, Calif. He was
74. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-YOUNG (Hollywood) _ Robert Young, TV's all-knowing dad on
``Father Knows Best'' and the compassionate ``Marcus Welby, M.D.,''
is dead at 91. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
