<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLENN REMEMBERS FELLOW ASTRONAUT SHEPARD
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Glenn said Wednesday he was ``shocked''
by the abrupt death of fellow Mercury astronaut Alan Shepard, who
had been battling leukemia but seemed to be doing well when they
two spoke weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him not too long ago, '' Glenn said in a brief
press conference Wednesday. ``And he had hoped to be down at the
flight in October when I'm scheduled to go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 77, returns to orbit Oct. 29 for a space shuttle flight
that will make him the oldest man ever in space. Glenn said Shepard
acknowledged being at ``half throttle'' because of his illness, but
Glenn still was optimistic that he might be able to attend the
Florida launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was enthusiastic about it, wanted to be there if he
could,'' Glenn said. ``I thought he might well make it to the end
of the year, at least, because he seemed to be in pretty good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn spoke warmly and respectfully of his partner in the elite
fraternity of seven men chosen to be America's first astronauts.
Although Glenn was always the straight arrow and Shepard nurtured a
bit of a wild streak, the two worked well together.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was Shepard's backup for the historic 1961 flight that
made him the first American in space. The pressure to succeed in
space was enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are times when you try and break the tension,'' Glenn
remembered. ``I had a picture that I had installed on the
periscope, or installed in the capsule to break the tension a
little bit, which he got a big kick out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't describe the picture,'' Glenn said, smiling broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said Shepard reciprocated with a prank when Glenn flew
America's first orbital mission in 1962. At the time, a popular
character in comedy television named Jose Jimenez talked about
wanting to be an astronaut, and Shepard loved it. He did the
routine himself during training, talking as the Jimenez character
did of feeling sorry for mice that were being used in early rocket
tests.
</P>
<P>
   So when Glenn achieved orbit during his flight, he reached for a
piece of equipment only to see a felt mouse with pink ears and a
long tail float out into the middle of the capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``These little pressure breakers (are what) you remember very,
very well,'' Glenn said. ``And I still have that little mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
