<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAD-ARTISTS-$ADV26-NY     07-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAD-ARTISTS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF THE MIND AND ARTISTS WHO LOSE IT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years there has been a lot of interest, not least from
composers, in the artistic productions of people who would have
once been called mad. The Danish composer Per Norgaard devoted a
period of his composing life in the '80s to the multitudinous
scrawlings of Adolf Wolfli, who spent decades in a Swiss asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfli's writings have also been set as songs by the German
composer Wolfgang Rihm, as have the poems of Robert Walser.
</P>
<P>
   The fascination of such material is plain to see. Wolfli's and
Walser's poetry invites us to extend our sympathies, and probably
to discover that the mentality of the deeply and permanently
disturbed is not so strange to us.
</P>
<P>
   For a composer, that invitation might easily have creative
consequences, especially in an age when many artists have felt a
call to explore extremes of feeling. Whereas Heine was the most
important of the German Romantics to Schumann, the modern taste is
for Holderlin, and especially for the scary drafts and fragments he
produced during his long period of derangement.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Holliger, the Swiss composer and oboist, fashioned a whole
cycle of choral and instrumental pieces based on late Holderlin.
Bruno Maderna created a Holderlin opera back in the '60s, and the
Hungarian composers Gyorgy Kurtag and Gyorgy Ligeti have both
visited the same territory more recently.
</P>
<P>
   The writings of mad poets offer an interesting corrective to the
way madness has often been portrayed in literature. Unlike Ophelia,
for instance, the authentically insane do not seem to give voice to
graceful if disconnected images, to statements that identify the
causes of their insanity or to trenchant insights into other
people. Nor do they sing.
</P>
<P>
   Music itself, in the case of Ophelia and others, is a sure sign
of madness. Rarely is it so in real life.
</P>
<P>
   If we look for musical counterparts to Wolfli, Walser and
Holderlin _for mad people who composed music or for professional
composers who declined into madness and went on writing _ we draw a
blank. Wolfli's output included musical notations, but only shreds.
Composers who lost their sanity _ like Schumann and Wolf, both of
whom were apparently suffering the effects of syphilis _
simultaneously lost the will or the ability to compose.
</P>
<P>
   A haunting photograph in The New Grove Dictionary of Music and
Musicians shows Wolf staring into the camera under the supervision
of his nurse. In that state he composed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Schumann's last works were composed during his lucid intervals,
and they show signs not of incipient madness but of a collapsing
imagination. One listens in vain for anything monstrous or
extraordinary in his Violin Concerto; it is simply weak.
</P>
<P>
   A possible borderline case is Berlioz. But though he did odd
things on occasion _ like fall in love with Ophelia and make the
mistake of marrying the Irish actress he had seen embody the
character on stage, Harriet Smithson _ he functioned competently in
society, and did so in roles that required him to communicate
accurately and appropriately with others: as conductor and, indeed,
music critic. And though his music may be weird and wild at times,
it is not deranged.
</P>
<P>
   If madness in music is hard to distinguish, there might be two
explanations. One would be simply that all music is mad. This was
the view of those Greek authors who identified poetic and musical
creation as kinds of madness, and it is not unpersuasive.
</P>
<P>
   But it leaves out of account the fact that in poetry we can
broadly separate the mad from the sane, the Wolfli from the
Wordsworth, whereas active composers of the mad sort are not at all
easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the comparison here is complicated by the fact that
nearly everybody in modern societies can write, but only a tiny
minority have the training and the ability to compose. Most people
could, if pushed, produce a pair of rhyming lines in a regular
meter. Very few would be able to achieve something like the musical
equivalent: set down two four-bar melodic phrases, the second
answering the first.
</P>
<P>
   We must regret the fact that basic creative skills are not
taught at an early age in music as they are in literature, but they
are not. This fact must at least partly account for why the
expression of madness is much more likely to come in words than in
music.
</P>
<P>
   That this is so, though, even for professional composers,
restores the puzzle of the lack of mad music. We may have to
conclude that musical composition is just impossible for someone
whose brain is not operating efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The many criteria that have to be considered and the complexity
of the notation, even for an elementary melody, are beyond what the
unbalanced mind can achieve. This would be a heartening thought,
that musical compositions, in their very existence, are testaments
to sanity and logic.
</P>
<P>
   If we want to hear music that instead speaks of madness _ of
real madness, not the madness depicted by conventional melancholy
and flights of virtuosity in 19th-century opera; by the
strong-flavored expressionism Rihm brings to bear on the poems of
Wolfli and Walser, or by the cold isolation Stravinsky used for the
inmates of Bedlam in the most disturbing mad scene yet devised,
that of ``The Rake's Progress'' _ then it would be futile to search
a music library.
</P>
<P>
   Craziness abounds in music but not among composers. It comes out
where the disciplines of writing a score cannot bar it. Performers
and improvisers: search their ranks for the mad.
</P>
</TEXT>
