<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMORA DECLINES TO TESTIFY IN FORMER BOYFRIEND'S CAPITAL MURDER
TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to clarify 4th graf to nearly a year; minor editing
throughout) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Nervous and teary-eyed, Diane Zamora took
the witness stand in the capital murder trial of her former high
school sweetheart Wednesday _ but only to say no when asked if she
would testify before the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, already sentenced to life in prison, declined to answer
questions rather than further incriminate herself in the 1995
slaying of romantic rival Adrianne Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Without Zamora available, defense lawyer Dan Cogdell quickly
concluded his case for David Graham. Cogdell presented no
witnesses, ``standing on (Graham's) presumption of innocence,''
thereby setting the stage for final arguments and jury
deliberations Thursday. Graham, a former U.S. Air Force Academy
cadet, faces a possible life sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting only 20 feet from her ex-fiance, Zamora was in the same
room as Graham for the first time in nearly a year. The
now-infamous couple never spoke, but their gazes appeared to lock
on each other for a few seconds as a packed courtroom and media
cameras scrutinized their every move.
</P>
<P>
   Before that momentary eye contact, Zamora smiled at her family
members and mouthed the words ``I love you'' to them. Then, until
the legal proceedings began, she sat awkwardly, her eyes darting
around the room as if trying to avoid Graham's constant stare.
</P>
<P>
   At Graham's request, Zamora, a former U.S. Naval Academy
midshipman, was summoned from a Gatesville prison where she is
serving a life sentence with a 40-year minimum incarceration.
Cogdell has told jurors that Zamora single-handedly killed the
16-year-old Jones, though Graham confessed at the time of his
arrest to shooting her to appease Zamora's jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, Graham has asserted there was no basis for the
jealousy and that he was not involved in the killing. It was out of
love, he said, that he helped Zamora cover up the crime for nine
months before they were arrested. Graham and Zamora were high
school seniors when the crime was committed, and they were away at
college when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Don Leonard of Fort Worth ruled that
Zamora, who is appealing her February conviction, could not be
forced to testify. But for the trial record, he allowed Cogdell to
pose two questions that she then declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Zamora,'' Cogdell said, ``would you admit that you and
you alone killed Adrianne Jones in the early morning hours of Dec.
4, 1995?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the advice of my attorney I'm exerting my Fifth
Amendment privilege,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you admit, Miss Zamora, that David Graham had nothing to
do at all with the cause of the death of Adrianne Jones in the
early morning hours of Dec. 4, 1995,'' Cogdell queried.
</P>
<P>
   The judge did not require Zamora to say another word. Instead,
he ordered her returned to prison, even though Cogdell said he
wanted jurors to lay eyes on Zamora so they could draw their own
conclusions about whether she was physically capable of
overpowering Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he wanted ``to use Miss Zamora in a physical
demonstration to show logistically and physically that it is more
logical that Miss Zamora had to fire the shots ... given the
testimony of the medical examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had presented testimony indicating that the butt of
Graham's handgun was used to strike Jones in the head, moments
before she was shot twice in the face at close range. The slaying
occurred in a secluded part of Tarrant County near Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County prosecutors concluded their five-day
presentation, which included 27 witnesses and about 100 pieces of
evidence, with crucial testimony from Graham's former best friend,
John Green.
</P>
<P>
   Green said that early one December morning in 1995, Graham and
Zamora crawled through his bedroom window and used his bathroom for
a lengthy clean-up. He said Graham told him not to ask any
questions about the unusual visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never here,'' he quoted Graham as saying. Prosecutors
contend the visit came within half an hour of Jones' slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's decision to present no witnesses came as a
surprise to the jammed courtroom, where people had lined up as
early as 4:30 a.m. to get a glimpse of Zamora and Graham. By the
time the court opened at 8 a.m., about 30 spectators were in line
and some were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora's aunt, Maria Consuela Mendoza, later told reporters that
Zamora was overcome with emotion about having to appear at the
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was nervous, she was upset. I don't think she has that
much of a difficulty having to face him. He knows the truth,''
Mendoza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the family and to Diane, it's like Diane is on trial all
over again. ... It's not about David. It's about Diane and what
Diane has said and done in the past,'' the aunt said, adding that
family members journeyed from the Dallas-Fort Worth area to support
Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to give a smile in between holding back the tears
because it's hard,'' she said. ``It's nerve-wracking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who visits Zamora frequently, as recently as Saturday,
said there is no romantic spark between the former lovers anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' she said. ``That's a relationship gone bad. The
only thing that Diane ever did wrong was be in love with the wrong
person. I'm sure she's got mixed emotions. You don't just get over
it overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Zamora's lawyer, John Linebarger, agreed with Mendoza that if
Zamora had testified, it would not have helped Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left to her own devices, Diane would have had a lot to say,
but she is wise enough to follow the advice of her attorney ... and
I don't think her testimony would have been of any benefit
whatsoever to David Graham,'' Linebarger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am authorized by her to say she would have testified to the
same thing she testified to in her trial.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
