<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-AFRICA-0723-COX     07-22 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AFRICA-0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE WEIGHT OF FAST-TRACK, AFRICA TRADE BILL MAY STILL FLOAT
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Critics of the Africa trade bill stepped up their
opposition Wednesday, arguing that the measure's strengths have
been wiped out as it heads to the Senate floor as part of a bigger
trade package.
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders if this act could have any imaginable benefits at
all,'' Randall Robinson, president of TransAfrica said at a news
briefing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a longtime opponent of the bill, has maintained that
the measure designed to strengthen ties with the continent's
long-neglected sub-Saharan region imposes unfair conditions on
African countries while benefiting large foreign corporations.
</P>
<P>
   But the future of the controversial trade bill -- strongly
backed by the Clinton administration, most African national leaders
and big corporations for its effort to open U.S. markets to African
exports -- is even less certain following Tuesday's mark-up in the
Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks who wanted a 'good' Africa bill more or less got
slapped,'' said Lori Wallach, director of Public Citizen's Global
Trade Watch, which lobbied against the original bill. ``The . . .
bill was sacrificed by super-gluing a bag of hot potatoes to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallach -- who, like Robinson, supports the idea of an Africa
trade bill -- labeled Tuesday's maneuvering as a way to ``cause
political embarrassment'' to President Clinton and use the
House-passed version of the bill as a vehicle to push other
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel attached controversial ``fast-track'' trade
legislation to the bill, which has little chance of passing in the
House. Even the Clinton administration, which tried to push
authority to negotiate trade deals without Congressional approval
last year, winced at having fast-track added the the Africa trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., an opponent of fast-track, was
wavering on whether to support the Africa trade bill to begin with.
But she opposed the measure in the Finance Committee on Tuesday,
calling fast-track a ``poison pill'' to the Africa bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as fast-track is a part of it, that settles the
matter,'' said her spokesman, Michael Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance's revival of fast-track, as well as adding a
number of trade measures to the Africa bill -- including expanding
NAFTA benefits to 24 Latin American and Caribbean nations -- has
generated concern not only from opponents but supporters of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of their concern is that the bill now only grants
duty-free access to textiles from Africa only if the garments are
assembled and cut from U.S. fabric.
</P>
<P>
   ``That negates virtually the entire bill,'' said Larry Neal,
spokesman for Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who supports fast-track
legislation. ``We may pass an Africa trade bill where no trade will
actually occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The textile amendment has even worried the author of the House
version of the bill, Philip Crane, R-Ill. who said the change
``strips the most significant benefits for African nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Rep. Crane and a coalition that has promoted
the bill since it narrowly passed the House last March, say the
damage done to the bill can be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not entirely what we want,'' said Elliott Hall, co-chair
of a coalition made up of 60 businesses that endorse the bill.
``But we expect compromises will be made when it comes to the
Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see whether fast-track drags this bill down,'' he said,
conceding that in order to get the Africa trade bill out of
committee, concessions had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
