<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL MCCARTNEY DEFENDS UC MONKEYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   P &UR; aul McCartney &LR;  has written to Chancellor  &UR; Michael Bishop  &LR; of
University of California at San Francisco to protest tests in which
squirrel monkeys will be subjected to blasts of sound. The
experiments are designed to research high-frequency hearing loss
suffered by humans when they attend rock concerts or are near
planes taking off.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of the noise, to be ``administered'' in four-hour
sessions, is greater than that made by jet engines. says the
monkeys will be anesthetized before the experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The matter came to McCartney's attention through People for the
Ethical Treatment of Animals, which had been alerted by San
Francisco Audio store owner  &UR; Radley Hirsch &LR; . Hirsch had refused to
sell UCSF loudspeakers for the experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I most strongly object to these cruel tests,'' McCartney wrote
to Bishop. ``In a technologically sophisticated world and one in
which we are supposed to be sufficiently aware of the nature and
needs of the other species to respect them, there can be no excuse
for inflicting such misery on these intelligent, feeling beings.
That the monkeys may be anesthetized before they awake to find
themselves bafflingly deaf is no consolation.''
</P>
<P>
   UC's &UR; Alice Trinkl  &LR; said that the university has no record of
having received McCartney's letter, which was dated July 6, and
that the experiments are ``in process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CHAMP GETS ANOTHER GO AT TITLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patricia Miller &LR; , 52, champion darter by night and manager of
San Francisco apartment buildings by day, will be on her way to the
Accudart/Winmay North American Open dart championships in Las Vegas
on August 14.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's been going to the nationals since 1981 and twice has
finished in the top four. She's hoping that a stepped-up training
schedule will make her a winner this year, but shoulder problems
she's been suffering will require surgery after the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the result in Las Vegas, she says the San Francisco
rankings are easy: ``I am the top lady. I can hold my own with most
of the men.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ After reading about computer translation of the Bible,  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Joss  &LR; and  &UR; Rudy M. &LR;  recalled the tale of a phrase translated from
English to Russian and back again. ``The spirit is willing but the
flesh is weak'' became ``The liquor is good but the meat is
rotten.''
</P>
<P>
   _ House Majority Leader  &UR; Richard Armey &LR; , R-Texas, who has been
actively opposing U.S. support of the International Monetary Fund,
told a reporter this week that he hasn't traveled outside the
United States in 12 years. ``I've been to Europe once,'' he said.
``I don't have to go again. ... Foreign travel just is not
something that intrigues me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Erika &LR;  forwards notice of a July 30 benefit for the
re-election of San Francisco Supervisor &UR; Tom Ammiano &LR; , featuring
``carefully choreographed spontaneous performances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OVER THE BOUNDING MAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Nation has invited supporters to sign up for a
$1,800-to-$4,600 fund-raising Caribbean cruise in December, during
which they'll have the chance to hobnob with the writers of that
left-wing periodical.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones' online MoJo Wire contacted some of the writers to
point out that the Holland America Line, which runs the cruise,
``has one of the worst labor records of any cruise company.''
 &UR; Alexander Cockburn  &LR; said, ``You don't have to go far to find
contradictions on the left,'' and  &UR; Christopher Hitchens &LR;  called
such criticism ``sneers that belong on the small-minded right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The corpse exuded the irresistible aroma of a piquant, ancho
chili glaze enticingly enhanced with a hint of fresh cilantro as it
lay before him, coyly garnished by a garland of variegated
radicchio and caramelized onions, and impishly drizzled with
glistening rivulets of vintage balsamic vinegar and roasted garlic
oil; yes, as he surveyed the body of the slain food critic slumped
on the floor of the dozy but nearly empty bistro, a quick inventory
of his senses told corpulent Inspector Moreau that this was, in all
likelihood, an inside job.''
</P>
<P>
   _ First-place winner in the 17th annual Bulwer-Lytton Fiction
Contest for bad writing, by lawyer Bob Perry of Massachusetts. The
contest is organized by the English department at San Jose State
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
