<HEADER>
A8006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-YOUNG-2TAKES-NYT     07-22 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YOUNG-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT YOUNG, 91, ACTOR KNOWN FOR WHOLESOME TV IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Wash.)   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Robert Young, an actor who created solid, wholesome,
common-sense characters on television in ``Father Knows Best'' and
``Marcus Welby, M.D.'' while privately battling some personal
demons, died Tuesday night at his home in Westlake Village, a Los
Angeles suburb. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   After a prolific career as a dependable film actor during
Hollywood's golden age in the 1930s and '40s, he went on to even
greater success in the two long-running television shows that were
among the most popular of their respective decades.
</P>
<P>
   Young's television roles were built on integrity, clarity and
kindness. Although ``Father Knows Best,'' which Young originated on
NBC radio in 1949, was a classically wholesome and idealized
portrait of family life in the Midwest, circa the 1950s and early
'60s, Young insisted that the character he played, Jim Anderson,
should be more realistic than other sitcom dads, who were often
dimwitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be the father, but not a boob,'' he told a
producer friend during the process of developing the radio show. He
and the show's creators sought to portray ``what we thought would
be representative of a middle-class American family, if there was
such a thing,'' Young once recalled. ``There probably isn't, but
that was what we were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour show had its television debut in 1954. The
program, in which Jim Anderson, his wife, Margaret, played by Jane
Wyatt _ Young was the only member of the radio cast who made the
transition to television _ had three children, was not particularly
successful, and CBS canceled it in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   But so many viewers demanded that it be reinstated, and urged
that it move from 10 p.m. to an earlier time slot so that the whole
family could watch, that NBC picked it up the following season and
showed it at 8:30, initially on Wednesdays. The show prospered on
NBC and then back at CBS. In its 1959-60 season, its last with
original episodes, ``Father Knows Best'' had its most successful
year, ranking sixth among all television shows. Successful reruns
followed on CBS and ABC until 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Young ``never had any problems about being a prima donna,''
Billy Gray, who played the son, Bud, on the show said Wednesday.
``He was very generous as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Father Knows Best'' ceased production, Young said he had
tired of the role and wanted to move on. Like ``Seinfeld,'' it was
one of the rare cases in the history of television when production
of a series ceased at the peak of its popularity. Young himself
always defended the program but seemed fully aware of its
white-bread style and shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Adding subplots about illness or drugs or serious problems, he
once said, ``would have been like taking a beautiful painting and
obliterating it with black paint _ and that really would have
turned the audience off.'' He added, ``We never intended the series
to be more than a weekly half-hour of fun and entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief semi-retirement, which Young said he loathed _
``When anyone says `retire,' I say `retire to what?''' he once said
_ he was cast in 1969 as Marcus Welby, a Santa Monica general
practitioner who involved himself in the lives of his patients.
</P>
<P>
   Former NBC chairman Grant Tinker, who in 1969 was a television
executive at Universal Studios (which produced ``Marcus Welby,
M.D.''), recalled in an interview that Ralph Bellamy was set to
play the role. ``Robert Young suddenly appeared and was sitting in
my office,'' Tinker said. ``Someone had gotten him the pilot
script. His opening words to me were, `I want to be Marcus
Welby.''' Young got the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very sympathetic quality to Young as an actor,''
Tinker said. ``You can easily confuse him with a kindly doctor. He
was also a guy who had a backbone. He was very determined.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour show, with James Brolin as his youthful medical
sidekick, had its premiere on Sept. 23, 1969, and was an instant
success. It became the biggest hit in the history of the ABC
network up to that time. Part of its initial success was that the
competition was weak because CBS and NBC opposed it with news
documentary programs. But viewers clearly adored the show and
remained faithful to it against stronger competition in later
years. The show's last telecast was in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show itself, unlike ``Father Knows Best,'' dealt
with serious problems like autism, blindness, LSD side effects,
drug addiction and leukemia, Marcus Welby himself was something of
a fantasy doctor who took a deeply personal approach to all of his
patients. He treated not only physical ailments but the fears and
family issues of each person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's understanding and dedicated,'' Young once said of Marcus
Welby. ``These are words that for some reason have fallen into
disuse. I knew from the start that I had to come back and play this
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, who won two Emmys for ``Father Knows Best,'' won a third
for ``Welby.'' He was also held in esteem by medical groups.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the characters he played and his public image, Young was
a complex and, in many ways, troubled figure.
</P>
<P>
   He was married to the same woman for more than 60 years. Young
was 17, and in high school, when he met Elizabeth Louise Henderson,
who was 14. They married in 1933. She died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Young is survived by their four daughters, Betty Lou Gleason,
Carol Proffitt, Barbara Beebe and Kathy Young. He also had six
grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But his life was sometimes difficult. He had a history of
alcoholism and depression and attended Alcoholics Anonymous
meetings while he was making ``Father Knows Best.'' In 1991, at 83,
he tried to commit suicide by running a hose from his car's exhaust
pipe to the interior of the vehicle. The attempt failed because the
battery was dead and the car wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   Young later admitted that he had been drinking when he asked his
wife to enter into a suicide pact with him and then tried to take
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the son of an Irish immigrant building manufacturer, was
born in Chicago on Feb. 22, 1907, the fourth of five children. The
family moved to Seattle and then Los Angeles when he was a boy.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Young wanted to be an actor. He took part in
high school dramatics and, after graduation, studied and acted at
night at the Pasadena Community Playhouse. He worked part-time as,
among other jobs, a drugstore clerk and loan collector.
</P>
<P>
   His theater work and good looks stirred Hollywood's interest in
1931, and a screen test brought his first role in ``The Black
Camel,'' a Charlie Chan mystery. Signed by MGM, Young soon appeared
in an extraordinary number of films in the early 1930s _ in the
course of four years he appeared in 24 pictures, playing serious
roles in many of them.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared in such films as ``The Sin of Madelon Claudet''
(with Helen Hayes), ``Hell Divers,'' ``Strange Interlude,''
``Tugboat Annie,'' ``The House of Rothschild'' and ``Today We
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
