<HEADER>
A8009 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMER-PHYSICS-SFCHRON     07-22 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMER-PHYSICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMER IS COMBINATION OF PHYSICS, STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ninth inning at 3Com Park. Close game, bases
loaded, Mark McGwire stepping in against Giants closer Robb Nen and
his 100 mph heat.
</P>
<P>
   It's a frightening scenario for the Giants, but probably just
what most fans are hoping to see when San Francisco takes on the
Cardinals and their fearsome slugger tonight and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   If McGwire can get a chance to take some cuts, and a few
technical details of energy transfer, aerodynamics and meteorology
fall into place, there's a good chance he could even loft a home
run into the faraway upper deck seats at 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   No one has done it before, but there's a first time for
everything. Unlikely though it may be, scientists and a Chronicle
review of stadium dimensions suggest it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire can do it,'' said Robert Adair, a Yale University
physics professor who held the title ``Physicist of the National
League'' from 1987 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it might unfold, based on estimates provided by Adair
and Drexel University physicist Donald Larson:
</P>
<P>
   If Nen's pitch starts at 100 mph, it will slow to about 90 mph
within the 0.8 seconds or so it takes to reach the batter's box.
For every 5 mph off that speed, the resulting hit will travel about
3.5 feet less distance, all else equal.
</P>
<P>
   To get it into the strike zone, the 6-foot-5 Nen has to pitch
the ball at a downward angle of about minus 10 degrees. To get the
ball out of the playing field, McGwire has to swing upward, at an
angle of about 20-25 degrees, so the ball starts at an angle of at
least 35 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 33-ounce Louisville Slugger will be traveling 70 to 75
mph if measured at the ``sweet spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a swing delivers about 10,000 pounds of force at the point
of contact, which lasts all of about 1/ 2000th of a second. Even if
he connects perfectly, most of the energy is dissipated in heat and
vibration. Both ball and bat heat up a bit, and the formerly round
baseball is momentarily crushed about one-quarter inch lopsided.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the ball slightly below dead center helps generate a
backspin of about 2,000 rpm _ about the same speed as a standard
asynchronous motor _ as the ball takes off. The backspin generates
aerodynamic lift and perhaps about a 5 degree steeper flight path
as the ball moves higher.
</P>
<P>
   The initial speed of the ball off the bat is between 125 and 130
mph if it's a towering home run. It reaches a maximum altitude of
about 165 feet above the field. It stays in flight 6.2 seconds
before it reaches the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch just clears the upper deck at the left field foul line
in fair territory. Precise measurements taken by The Chronicle last
week show this to be a distance of 433 feet, 7 inches. The vertical
height is 56 feet, 6 inches at the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Such a home run would travel about 470 feet if allowed to return
to field level without hitting anything, assuming a steep fall of
about 60 to 70 degrees. That would be a prodigious shot, but within
McGwire's recent range _ he hit one at San Diego on Monday night
estimated at 458 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, no line drive would make it into the upper deck
at 3Com's left field. Calculations show it would have to leave the
bat at a screaming 132 mph, starting at a low 26 degree angle,
reach only 92 feet maximum height and take just 4.2 seconds to
reach the stands. Projected out to ground level, the distance would
be about 502 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The McGwire-style huge fly ball is more likely to do the trick _
but only if the park's notorious wind doesn't intervene. Every 10
mph of wind blowing in takes about 30 feet off the ball's flight.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologist Jan Null at Golden Gate Weather Services expects
``a typical summertime pattern'' for the Cards-Giants games.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures Wednesday night should be in the low 60s with
westerly winds gusting to about 20 mph, dying after dark. Expect
mostly sunny skies Thursday, temperatures in the low 70s, cooling
rapidly during the game as the seabreeze kicks in, wind gusting
again in the 20 mph zone.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures 10 degrees warmer allow the same home run to travel
about four feet farther, because the air molecules spread out and
generate less resistance on a warm day. Falling barometric pressure
also helps _ figure four feet more distance for each one inch drop
in the mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Such factors don't matter much when the ball is under a full
head of steam leaving home plate. But wind and weather wield a
mighty influence on the ball's endflight, often clipping the final
trajectory into nearly a dead drop.
</P>
<P>
   If the ball hits a blowing hot dog wrapper at 3Com, all bets are
off. But even if it doesn't collide with any airborne flotsam, the
flight path is not easily predicted, said Adair, the physicist.
</P>
<P>
   The flight path of a home run ``is not an ellipse or a hyperbola
or parabola or part of a circle,'' Adair said. ``It's a little more
complicated. But oh, it's a pretty thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
