<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPPERDECK-MCGWIRE-SFC     07-22 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPPERDECK-MCGWIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY MCGWIRE COULD HIT WHERE NO ONE EVER HAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: This is a sidebar to HOMERUNS)   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Those elusive upper deck seats beyond left field
at 3Com Park _ where no home run has ever landed before _ are well
within striking range of St. Louis slugger Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Even straightaway dead center may be closer than you think.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle enlisted a crackerjack team of baseball experts to
measure the potential for McGwire to reach the outer limits at
3Com. The experts included physicists, a baseball wonk, a licensed
land surveyor and a 14-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he can do it,'' said soon-to-be ninth-grader Aarde
Cosseboom, son of surveyor Peri Cosseboom and an ardent McGwire
fan. ``All he has to do is just nick fair territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of home runs have reached the upper deck in right field,
where the cheap seats are closer to the field and a hitter-friendly
wind sometimes blows. But the upper deck seats in left field have
been there since 1972, surviving such long-ball greats as Willie
McCovey and Dave Kingman with nary a dent.
</P>
<P>
   Peri Cosseboom, who helped map out the Candlestick skyboxes in
the mid-'80s, began the field work by setting up a Swiss-made
infrared distance gauge on top of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The $25,000 device, which gives readings on both horizontal and
vertical distances, is accurate to within about one quarter of an
inch within a range of about 3,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretical home-run trajectories and distances were calculated
by Drexel University physicist Donald Larson (not the same Don
Larsen who pitched the perfect game in the 1956 World Series) and
Yale University's Robert Adair. Exploratorium physicist Paul
Doherty confirmed key results, aided by David Barker on the field.
</P>
<P>
   While his dad squinted through the viewfinder at home plate,
young Aarde and his mother, Carol, equipped with a two-way radio
and accompanied by a Chronicle reporter, traipsed around the outer
regions of 3Com lugging a six-foot metal staff topped with a
special reflective glass.
</P>
<P>
   Following the major-league rule book, all distances were
measured from the apex at the back of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   We first checked the distances down the line from home plate to
first and third. Ninety feet, on the button.
</P>
<P>
   Then we checked the signs on the outfield fence, quickly
discovering that the 400-foot marker in dead center is really just
397 feet 7 inches from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' said a Giants spokesman, offering no clue as to when
the sign might be repainted.
</P>
<P>
   The 365-foot signs in the power alleys turned out to be about
364 feet from home plate. Close enough, we figured. Distances at
the foul lines also proved to be accurate within a few inches.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the all-important left-field nosebleed sections.
</P>
<P>
   Results showed that even McGwire would have to strain to make
the upper deck anywhere near left-center.
</P>
<P>
   It's a prodigious 518 feet 11 inches to the right edge of the
scoreboard at bleacher level. A home run there would have to exceed
McGwire's record Busch Stadium blast of 545 feet earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the left field foul line, however, it's a mere 433
feet 7 inches. The railing at the front of the upper deck stands is
56 feet, 6 inches above the field.
</P>
<P>
   A ball hit that far, that high, would have to reach a height of
about 135 feet over left field. It would travel about 470 to 480
feet if the ball were able to complete its trajectory and land at
field level.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire would have to swing a little under the ball, generating
some backspin that would add a nice aerodynamic lift. That way, the
ball could leave his bat at about 35 degrees off horizontal, then
steepen to about 40-42 degrees as it neared the apex over left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 40,000 fans all holding their breath might help, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
