<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAY-NEGOTIATOR-FILM-     07-22 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAY-NEGOTIATOR-FILM-$ADV26-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SOUTH-CENTRAL TO THE CENTER OF HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The director F. Gary Gray was eating lunch in a
modest West Hollywood restaurant recently when a messenger arrived
with a document that needed urgent attention. As Gray scribbled his
name on the papers, three young men at the next table leaned over
to congratulate him, saying they had just attended an early showing
of his new movie, ``The Negotiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, 28, smiled sheepishly, a bit embarrassed by all the
attention but obviously enjoying it. ``Stay grounded _ that's what
I keep saying to myself _ stay grounded, because there are more
things in this industry that are artificial than real,'' said the
director, who grew up in tough South-Central Los Angeles and came
to feature films through his directing of music videos for rap
artists.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Gray is soon going to have problems staying
grounded. After impressing critics two years ago with ``Set It
Off,'' an action drama about four desperate women who stage a bank
heist, he stands to attract even more attention for ``The
Negotiator,'' which opens on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey, the new movie deals
with two Chicago Police Department hostage negotiators who square
off when one of them, played by Jackson, becomes a hostage-taker
himself after he is the target of false accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The film is, in Spacey's words, ``like a locomotive _ it doesn't
stop moving,'' and early test screenings have been so successful
that Warner Bros., which is releasing the movie, is promoting it
blockbuster-style. ``Based on its previews, it'll do a tremendous
amount of business,'' said Robert Daly, co-chairman of Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who is as friendly as he is assured and ambitious, began
his career as a news cameraman, and then turned to directing music
videos for performers like Ice Cube, Mary J. Blige, Whitney Houston
and Coolio. It was this experience that led him into feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Gray quickly agreed to make ``The Negotiator,'' his third
feature, shortly after reading the script by James DeMonaco and
Kevin Fox. ``It was such a smart screenplay, and while I was
reading it, the visuals kept popping in my mind,'' he explained.
But making the movie wasn't quite so simple.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the project belonged to Walt Disney, and Sylvester
Stallone was offered the hostage-taker part. By all accounts,
Stallone insisted on major script revisions _ above all, he wanted
the other hostage negotiator to be a woman. Stallone was also not
especially interested in being directed by Gray, because of the
filmmaker's relative inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Disney eventually dropped the project, and it was picked up by
Warner Bros. Stallone departed, and the two actors whom Gray wanted
in the first place _ Jackson and Spacey _ read the script. By
chance, the two actors, who had appeared briefly together in 1996
in ``A Time to Kill,'' then discussed the script at a party last
year at the home of Ed Limato, a prominent agent at International
Creative Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin and I really enjoyed the scene we had,'' Jackson said,
referring to ``A Time to Kill.'' ``We talked about `The
Negotiator.' He said, `If you do it, I'll do it.' It was as simple
as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that what appealed to him especially about the
script was its lack of convention for an action drama. ``The fact
is, you have two guys who are negotiators, who use words as opposed
to shooting each other,'' he said. ``Each page has dialogue and not
a lot of descriptive action. It was unusual that way. You don't
find that in action films. It had the right combination of tension
and verbal jousting.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey said that preparations for ``The Negotiator'' were
unusual in that he and Jackson worked on the screenplay for several
weeks with the two writers and the director. ``We were paying
attention to all the details that sometimes get stripped in movies
like this,'' he recalled. ``We wanted characters that were more
than cardboard cutouts _ and not just our characters but all of
them.'' Other members of the cast include J.T. Walsh, who died in
February, Ron Rifkin and Regina Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Gray seems alternately confident, bemused and
jittery about his career now. Only 14 years ago, he was a bit of a
wayward kid in South-Central Los Angeles. His parents had divorced.
He lived with his mother, a secretary; his father lived in Chicago
and worked at an Army base. An uncle, Phil Lewis, an actor, was
staging a show called ``The African American,'' about the black
experience, and issued an invitation to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `You need to see this play with your little
brother,' and I'm like, `Tough guys don't see plays,''' recalled
Gray. ``I finally decided to go, and I was blown away. I knew then
and there that there was something there for me. I became a
stagehand, worked behind the scenes, did the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's parents decided that he should leave Los Angeles and live
with his father in Chicago so he could attend Highland Park High
School, a respected public high school. There, Gray immersed
himself in the visual arts, and began to yearn to be a director.
``It's a great school; I wish more public schools were like that,''
said Gray. ``That school really made it possible for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved back to Los Angeles, partly to enter Los Angeles City
College, which he attended for a year, but mostly to pursue the
notion of being a director. ``What I was taught at high school was
not so much to dream but to set realistic goals that you can
clearly define,'' he said. ``Dreams are very lofty, but there are
solid steps you have to take in order to achieve each goal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His first job was on a camera crew that filmed Stevie Wonder
receiving an award. That was followed by freelance jobs at cable
networks like E, CNN and Black Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   At 23, having saved some money, he tried to make a short film
about gang violence. It was never completed, because of financial
problems, but it led to lots of work directing music videos, and
lots of recognition: His video ``Fantastic Voyage,'' with Coolio,
earned Gray the 1995 Billboard Music Video Award for Best Rap
Video. That same year he was a four-time winner at the MTV Music
Video Awards.
</P>
<P>
   His music videos clearly helped him develop the style that he
brings to feature films. ``I took a storytelling approach to almost
all my music videos,'' he said. ``I shot a beginning, middle and
end. I used cranes and steady cams, and a lot of my earlier videos
had dialogue in them. It was great for me. I was given the
resources to do little films.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the rapper Ice Cube offered Gray money so that the
director could rewrite and complete a short dramatic film he had
been working on. ``But then he said, `Instead of me giving you
money to finish a short film, why don't we do a feature film.' And
I said, `Yes, this is what I've been dreaming of.'''
</P>
<P>
   His feature debut, ``Friday,'' a comedy about surviving life in
South-Central, starred Ice Cube and Chris Tucker. Although it was
dismissed by critics as a slight frivolity, it was one of the more
profitable films of 1995, grossing $30 million after having been
made for $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Set It Off,'' which starred Jada Pinkett, Queen Latifah and
Vivica A. Fox, seized the attention of studio executives and
producers. The modest film, about some black women who decide to
rob a bank after struggling in vain to carve out meaningful lives,
reached beyond the action-drama genre and emerged as a big hit for
New Line. It led directly to ``The Negotiator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone else directing `Set it Off' could have made an
exploitive film,'' said David Hoberman, who produced ``The
Negotiator'' with Arnon Milchan. ``But Gary created a work in which
all women were complex characters and were far from stereotypical.
The film had momentum. After seeing `Set It Off,' I knew Gary could
do `The Negotiator.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gray is aware of himself as a black filmmaker in the
predominantly white world of Hollywood, he is young enough for
racial barriers not to have been much of a factor in his career, he
believes. ``I didn't face the same challenges that I'm sure Spike
Lee had to face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Friday,'' his debut, Gray was offered several movies
unrelated to race, but he chose ``Set It Off'' because, he
recalled, it had the best script. And although Jackson, one of the
most prominent black movie stars, is a lead actor in ``The
Negotiator,'' racial issues are not a component of the new movie.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, taking on ``The Negotiator'' was obviously a major
leap for the young filmmaker: the budget of ``Set It Off'' was $6
million; ``The Negotiator'' cost $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   The higher stakes didn't make Gray change his on-set style,
though. ``What surprised me was his ability to listen to people _
and then make his own decisions,'' said Hoberman. ``I really don't
know a lot of young directors who have the ability and personal
confidence to ask the actors, the producers, members of the crew,
`What do you think?' He really listened, and then he made his own
decision. There's a very strong sense of maturity about Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that ``Dog Day Afternoon,'' the 1975 Sidney Lumet
film, influenced him as he was making ``The Negotiator.''
``Obviously these are two totally different films,'' he said, ``but
that was a great hostage movie. And that film must have been an
amazing challenge. How do you manage to feel totally sympathetic to
the Al Pacino character, a bank robber who's trying to get money
for a sex-change operation for his gay lover?'' He laughed. ``They
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's background in music videos still shapes his approach to
movie making. While reading the script for ``The Negotiator'' _
over and over again, even during the filming _ and while blocking
out scenes, he listened to music. ``I'll listen to music and read
the script and I feel propelled, I'll start typing really fast,
type out the definition of a scene, where the characters are, the
visual approach,'' he said. ``Music sparks something in me _ I
don't know what.'' The music, he said, ranged from Marvin Gaye to
Bach.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that he'll listen to much Bach for his next film,
which he wants to be ``a really eerie, tense movie,'' he said. To
avoid being pigeonholed, he wants to move from genre to genre.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the genre, he's trying to avoid being the sort of
director who becomes successful and turns into a megalomaniac. ``I
just don't understand this need to abuse people,'' he said. ``If
someone is like that, then it was in them in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who is unmarried, recently moved into a new home in the
San Fernando Valley. But he gave his old home to his mother and his
older sister, who works in the insurance business. ``I want them
close; they're a good source of reality,'' Gray said with a grin.
``They keep me honest. And sane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
