<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMERUN-SCIENTISTS-SF     07-22 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMERUN-SCIENTISTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SCRUTINIZE POSSIBILITY THAT MARK MCGWIRE WILL BREAK 
 RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: This story has two sidebars, slugged UPPERDECK
and  HOMER)   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Did birds evolve from dinosaurs? Is there life
in outer space? Will Mark McGwire break the home-run record?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it might not seem on par with the other major questions
of the age, the possibility that the St. Louis Cardinals slugger
will surpass 61 home runs in a season is inspiring a level of
scientific scrutiny worthy of a NASA moon shot.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists are obsessing over the dynamics of the ball-bat
collision. Statisticians are recalculating probability
distributions after every game. Psychiatrists are poring over
post-game interviews for hints of ``success neurosis.''
</P>
<P>
   They will soon have data from San Francisco to add to the mix,
as the former Oakland Athletic baseball player prepares to take the
field here. Big, friendly crowds are expected _ 30,000 Wednesday
and 40,000 &UR;  &LR; Thursday, double the usual turnout for weekday games at
3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   At his current pace, McGwire would break the record by early
September, easily eclipsing Roger Maris of the New York Yankees,
who hit 61 in 1961, when he surpassed the immortal Babe Ruth, who
hit 60 in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   It's perhaps the most hallowed record in all sports _ serious
business for practitioners of the art of baseball analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I update my spreadsheets every night,'' said Gene Sunnen, an
Oakland businessman, general manager for the 1988 Watertown Pirates
in the short-season Class A New York-Penn League and a former
national president of the Society for American Baseball Research.
``It's one of my great joys in life.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago, theoretical
physicist Porter Johnson has been setting aside his full-time
studies of high-speed subatomic particle collisions to ponder the
aerodynamics of McGwire's awesome taters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get the right spin on the ball,'' Johnson
said, noting that McGwire's ferocious uppercuts _ bat speeds
approaching 75 mph when measured at the bat's sweet spot _ generate
ball speeds of 120 mph or more at launch.
</P>
<P>
   Drexel University physicist Donald Larson built an elaborate
home-run distance-measuring program, which he loaded into his
laptop and brought with him to Philadelphia's Veterans Stadium for
a recent Phillies-Cards game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, said the disappointed professor, ``McGwire didn't
hit any home runs that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle architect-consultant John Pastier is still refining his
estimate of a memorable home run McGwire hit off Mariners
fireballer Randy Johnson last year at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium officials pegged it at 538 feet _ right up there with
some record breakers, although it's hard to say exactly because
home-run distances are notoriously fuzzy and have not been
systematically recorded until recent years. Pastier estimated
McGwire's Kingdome homer at 470 feet. Reliable estimates,
meanwhile, put a McGwire homer at Busch Stadium in May at 545 feet,
one of the longest home runs in history.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle's famed 562-foot dinger that sailed out of
Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., was likely hit only about 510
feet, according to calculations by Robert Adair, a retired Yale
University professor and one of the nation's top experts on the
physics of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear to have measured the distance to where the ball
stopped rolling,'' Adair said. ``It always helps a home-run hitter
when his team happens to employ a publicist without a lot of
scruples.''
</P>
<P>
   Calculating the distances McGwire has been reaching makes up
just one subspecialty in the new science of the long ball.
Statisticians also are having a field day.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, having hit 43 home runs so far, finished last night's
game in San Diego on pace to hit 71 by the end of the season,
according to the charts appearing in nearly every sports section in
America.
</P>
<P>
   That's accurate, as far as it goes. But does that mean McGwire
really is a shoo-in to surpass Maris and Ruth?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, said Scott Page, an economics theorist and ``huge
Tigers fan'' at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Projecting what will happen during the rest of the season based
solely on the home runs McGwire has hit so far is ``linear
extrapolation'' that assumes no change in the frequency of home
runs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like predicting a coin that landed heads-up five
times in a row will land heads up the next five flips, too. Maybe
it will, maybe it won't.
</P>
<P>
   In McGwire's situation, you have to look deeply into such things
as career vs. seasonal percentages, intentional walks,
psychological factors and team standings and schedules in order to
compute the odds.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, McGwire has been hitting one home run in every
7.1 at-bats, nearly a dinger every other game assuming three to
four chances per outing. Easily enough to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   A safer forecast, though, might be based on McGwire's career
rate of one homer per 11.5 at bats. At that pace, he would hit 17
more this year _ and would tie Ruth for second place.
</P>
<P>
   But consider that McGwire clearly has taken his power-hitting to
a new level for the past three seasons. Over this latest long
stretch, he's been consistently hitting a home run every &UR;  &LR; 9.1
chances.
</P>
<P>
   That pace would give McGwire about 24 more home runs, &UR;  &LR; plenty to
beat the record for the season. All things considered, Page figures
there is at least an 85 percent probability that McGwire will do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides an injury, another factor that could sour his chances
would be if opposing managers avoid pitching to McGwire, who
already has 22 intentional walks. The full-season record is 45, set
by the Giants' Willie McCovey in 1969. Maris, batting ahead of
Mickey Mantle, evidently wasn't intentionally walked at all in
1961; the statistic wasn't recorded in Babe Ruth's era.
</P>
<P>
   Big crowds are coming out to witness every McGwire swing, adding
some pressure on managers to give him some chances, particularly if
St. Louis stays out of playoff contention and games late in the
season do not affect the standings of opposing teams.
</P>
<P>
   Even if circumstances prevent McGwire from breaking the record,
Sunnen maintains that his phenomenal home-run percentages already
place him in the front ranks of baseball deities.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth hit a home run every 8.5 at bats during his peak year.
Maris went long every 9.7 at bats in his storybook season. McGwire
is well ahead of them both in terms of consistent power hitting,
and he is clearing fences nearly five times the 1998 average for
major league players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest home-run hitter in baseball history,''
Sunnen said. ``It's his home-run frequency that's off the charts.
He's hitting them faster than the Babe ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   The big unknown is whether McGwire will fade in the stretch,
perhaps allowing the intensifying media pressure to shake his
legendary concentration. He has already taken to limiting questions
about the home-run record, and complained at one point this season
that he felt ``like a caged animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Leary, a University of California at San Francisco
professor and psychiatrist at San Francisco General Hospital, said
he is on the lookout for signs that stress might be starting to get
to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he seems to be holding up well, Leary said, adding that
McGwire's decision to limit interviews on the Maris-record subject
``is a healthy move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His maturity is going to be helpful,'' Leary said. ``He also
appears to be quite a disciplined person in how he approaches
batting. He doesn't swing at bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Leary wonders what might happen as McGwire starts closing in on
60 home runs and the ghost of Babe Ruth starts to appear every time
he steps to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts call it ``success neurosis'' _ the disabling fear that
can strike just on the verge of reaching a lifelong goal. It could
happen to anybody, even big-league athletes.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire says he just wants to win games and help his team. Even
so, the home-run record is something truly special for anyone in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody but McGwire knows ``what it means to him personally, how
it works into his own personal psychology,'' Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it's possible he could have some problems as he
gets closer. It may affect him in ways that are hard for us to
predict _ it could be detrimental, or he could really rise to the
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has seemed a bit testy lately, which Leary finds a
worrisome sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if he's a little brittle about it,'' the psychiatrist
said. ``He might be a bit more tightly wound than might be
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also might have the good sense to just forget about it and
get out there and have some fun.
</P>
<P>
   Batter up.
</P>
</TEXT>
