<SLUG> BC-MONDAVI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDAVI SETTLES ESPY CHARGES  
 BY PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - REVERSE, EMBARGOED FOR MONDAY AMS OF JAN.   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Mondavi Corp. agreed to pay $150,000 yesterday to settle
charges that it illegally wined and dined a former Clinton cabinet
official to the tune of $394.
</P>
<P>
   The Napa Valley winery acknowledged that in October 1993 it gave
six bottles of its reserve wines worth $187 to former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy at the request of Espy friend and former
Sun-Diamond Growers lobbyist Richard Douglas. It also admitted to
paying for an American Wine Appreciation Week dinner valued at $207
for Espy and his girlfriend the following March.
</P>
<P>
   For these transgressions, Mondavi agreed to pay $100,000 in
civil damages to the U.S. Treasury and contribute $20,000 to defray
the cost of Independent Counsel Donald Smaltz's investigation. It
also earmarked $30,000 to increase corporate awareness of laws
prohibiting gratuities to public officials.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Since 1994, Smaltz has been investigating approximately
$35,000 worth of illegal gratuities allegedly offered to Espy. So
far, the independent counsel has won about a dozen convictions and
recovered close to $11 million in civil penalties and criminal
fines.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  During Espy's visit to the Mondavi winery and the dinner in
Washington, D.C., the independent counsel said that Espy and
Mondavi officials discussed government funding to combat the grape
vine-eating pest Phylloxera as well as to promote the marketing of
wine and the health benefits of moderate wine consumption.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  They also talked about trade issues related to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and the North American Free Trade
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Given the company's dealings with Espy and his department,
Mondavi and its employees were banned under federal law from
providing ``anything of value'' personally to Espy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Besides the gratuities, Smaltz said that Espy received a note
from a senior Mondavi official inviting him visit the winery and
use its guest house anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our people made an error of judgment when pressured to
provide wine for Espy's personal use,'' said winery President
Michael Mondavi. ``We have learned from that mistake and we look
forward to improving the way our company and our industry deal with
government agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
