<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS FARGO PROFITS STAMPEDE 48% IN 2ND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - WELLS   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. announced yesterday a 48 percent jump in profits
in the second quarter from year-earlier levels, with most of the
gain coming from reduced expenses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loan volume and deposit balances at the West's second-largest
bank actually declined.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, which recently announced plans to merge with Norwest
Corp. of Minneapolis but keep its name and headquarters in San
Francisco, reported $337 million in net income for the past three
months ($3.91 per share) compared with $228 million ($2.49) in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Paul Hazen said small-business and middle-market
lending, auto leasing and capital markets ``have been especially
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   However the bank's net interest income of $1.15 billion in the
past quarter was up just $24 million over the previous quarter and
matched year-earlier results. In addition, average core deposits
and assets have dropped 5 percent and 7 percent, respectively,
during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, noninterest income in the second quarter was $735
million compared with $726 million in the first quarter and $679
million in the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Loan, credit card, ATM fees and other charges increased 16
percent during the year to $272 million in the past quarter. But
most of the noninterest income increases resulted from the $58
million gain on the sale of the bank's mortgage servicing business.
</P>
<P>
   Noninterest expenses fell $149 million, or 12 percent, to $1.1
billion in the most recent quarter. A year ago, expenses were way
up because of computer glitches and other problems caused by the
bank's rushed integration with First Interstate Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   Wells continued to cut payroll in the past quarter. It had
31,620 employees at the end of June compared with 32,414 three
months earlies and 33,216 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it was a decent quarter,'' said Van Kasper analyst
Joseph Morford. ``There was strong commercial loan growth,
improving asset quality and Wells has stabilized customer service
problems. The only disappointing note was some deposit runoff after
a couple quarters of increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells' earnings beat analysts' estimates by about 11 cents per
share, but the bank's stock dipped $10.38 yesterday to close at
$369.63.
</P>
<P>
   In other banking earnings, Chase Manhattan said income rose 16
percent to $1.1 billion. Citibank reported $1.1 billion in profit,
up 8 percent. And BancOne reported $487 million in profit, 10 times
higher than a year ago, when acquisition-related costs hurt
profits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
