<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/MARK VEVERKA  
 TOP EXECUTIVES AT BORDERS SELLING A HEFTY CHUNK OF THEIR STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Top executives at Borders Group, the brick-and-mortar retailer that
was a Johnny-come-lately to selling books, music and merchandise
over the Internet, have decided to unload a substantial amount of
stock in the company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six top executives _ including the chairman and CEO of the Ann
Arbor, Mich., retailer _ filed to sell more than 1.1 million shares
between April 3 to June 1 at prices as high as $34, according to
CDA/Investnet, a financial research firm in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The insiders opted to part with their shares just as Borders'
story was starting to get rosier. Borders is the nation's
second-largest seller of books, but it was the last among the
big-three booksellers to hawk books over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Borders' top execs from cashing in some
chips at a critical juncture for the company: the long-overdue
launch of its online operations.
</P>
<P>
   Borders still has a ways to go to catch Amazon.com in the online
race. Amazon of Seattle was first, and it has been one of the stock
market's Internet darlings ever since it went public in May 1997.
Its stock has soared more than fourfold since the beginning of this
year, closing yesterday around $132. And it has arguably been the
most successful online retailer to date.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line was Barnes and Noble. In an attempt to catch up,
Barnes and Noble launched its online operation about a year ago.
The New York-based operator of some 485 bookstores is expected to
rack up online sales of about $1 million for the inaugural year of
its Website. That compares with $500 million in projected revenues
for Amazon this year, which would more than double last year's
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' stock also has its Internet mojo working. Its shares are
trading at around $45, up 50 percent from the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Borders, the last one in the pool, launched its
online operations in May and expects revenues generated from
electronic commerce not to exceed $25 million by the end of the
year, according to Marilyn Horn, its director of investor
relations.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Borders' brass filed to sell their shares right
around the time that the company was unveiling its Web site.
Chairman and CEO Robert DiRomualdo sold 288,850 shares, trimming
his stake (stock, options and warrants) to around 2.3 million
shares, Horn says.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Vice Chairman George Mrkonic shed more than
630,000 shares, cutting his position to around 1 million shares,
Horn says. Four other insiders accounted for the remaining 120,000
shares sold.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of funny, isn't it? Wall Street analysts, who rely
heavily on the CEO for information and guidance in their research,
love Borders. In fact, all 12 analysts who follow Borders recommend
the stock to their clients as a ``buy,''according to Bloomberg L.P.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the company chieftains do? They dumped a boatload of
shares.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Borders' Horn says that the executives remain
confident in the future performance of the company's stock. They
merely sold off shares, she says, to pay certain tax and debt
liabilities that they owed on shares that they were awarded. Most
of the executives had opted for stock instead of cash wages,
getting little or no salary for the past three years, Horn
explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot of confidence in the stock. That's why they
took the shares instead of cash'' in the first place, Horn says.
</P>
<P>
   And they also happened to dump their shares the minute their
company began to benefit from the run-up in Internet stocks.  &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at 415-777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He
also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak on Tuesdays and Thursdays.  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1904EDT &QL; 
