<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM'S SCORCHING NEW INVENTION  
 BY DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - FIRE   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new fire-resistant paint designed to prevent flames from
engulfing a house was put to the test Sunday in suburban Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Some walls of a wood-frame house in Washougal, Wash., were
painted with Firefree 88 from San Rafael-based International Fire
Resistance Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Then a fire was set. When flames blew out the windows,
firefighters rushed in to end the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fire destroyed part of a room, the walls coated
with the new product were charred but still structurally sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real impressive,'' said Larry Saari, captain with the
Washougal Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   In other tests, the paint also was applied to mahogany paneling,
cedar shake shingles and flammable ceiling tiles. In all cases, the
surfaces were charred or bubbled up but were not incinerated in
seconds, as were surfaces that were left untreated.
</P>
<P>
   After years of laboratory experiments, and with a patent
application pending, International Fire Resistance Systems now is
producing the new paint and expects to manufacture 1.5 million
gallons this year. The privately held company does not disclose
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm jazzed, actually doing it in the real world and seeing it
all come together,'' said company founder, chief executive and
part-owner John Simontacchi.
</P>
<P>
   The company claims that Firefree 88 can withstand temperatures
of up to 1800 degrees Fahrenheit. The paint sells for the
relatively high price of $50 a gallon and is available only to
contractors who have been licensed by the company.
</P>
<P>
   Simontacchi, a contractor for 27 years, was serving as an expert
witness in construction litigation cases when he saw a need for a
low-cost way to prevent fires from spreading in condominium
complexes &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He started working with a professor at the University of
California at Berkeley, and then with Early American Paints, which
is based in Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't find anything that worked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The few products available were for industrial applications,
according to Harlan Kline, technical services manager for Ameron,
an Orange County maker of industrial coatings. They were typically
expensive products to protect oil rigs, where the appearance of the
paint is not important, Kline said.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of paint-makers tout ``intumescent'' products that resist
fire, according to Lucho Mauricio, business agent for the
International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades in San
Francisco. But those products are designed for metal and don't
stick to the wooden walls when the fire heats up, Simontacchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Through much experimentation, involving part science and part
luck, a chemist at Early American Paints solved the adhesion
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Simontacchi and his team improved the paint's fire resistance by
incorporating ceramic technology similar to that used in the space
shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   But the formula still had two problems: It was hard to apply,
and it didn't look good enough for residential use. So the team
kept tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, they had devised a method to add colors and a way
to apply it with a heavy duty, airless spray pump.
</P>
<P>
   Some home owners use the paint, which is manufactured only in
white, as is. Others tint it, paint over it or cover it with
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   The company has four licensees in the Bay Area, including Phil
Bass, owner of Bay Area Painting in Castro Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Bass already has used Firefree 88 on some homes in Mill Valley,
and he now is putting it on a condo complex in Rohnert Park. He has
contracts lined up in San Jose and Santa Rosa, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really starting to take off,'' he said. ``People want
something that's going to make everything a little safer. Before
long, you're going to see great interest from the insurance
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
