<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-MANCINI-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW MANCINI STRIKES OUT ON HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The temperature is hovering in the 90s as the
California sun starts to sink outside, but inside the Capitol
Records tower on Vine Street, it's dimmer and cooler as a tall,
elegant woman begins a torch song, her voice lingering like lotion
on the words ``Some days, it's too warm to find, a slow, hot
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Her face is unfamiliar, but her name is not. And as Monica
Mancini sings this half-forgotten song with lyrics by Norman Gimbel
and music by her father, Henry, from the ``Peter Gunn'' television
series, the old hands surrounding her in the studio nod at one
another and smile slowly in the conviction that Ms. Mancini's face
won't be so unfamiliar for long.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two decades as a studio and backup singer for
musicians as diverse as her father, Michael Jackson, Dolly Parton
and Vicki Carr, Ms. Mancini is embarking on a solo career, singing
her father's music. She is also recording her first solo album,
tentatively titled ``Fathers and Daughters,'' as the first artist
signed by PBS Records, a joint venture between Warner Brothers
Records and PBS, for release this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, it didn't occur to me to do his stuff before,
because he was here to do it,'' Ms. Mancini said of her father, the
prolific Hollywood composer, arranger and conductor, who died of
pancreatic cancer in 1994 at the age of 70. When she once proposed
that she might sing his songs with him in concert, she recalled
during a break in a recording session the other day, ``He said, `I
work alone, kid.' I also wasn't ready yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in her 40s and newly married to Gregg Field, a veteran
drummer for Frank Sinatra who anchors her band, Ms. Mancini said
she finally felt ready to take on signature songs like ``Moon
River,'' ``Two for the Road'' and ``Days of Wine and Roses.'' ``It
just seemed that all the energies came together,'' she said. So
far, the response has been positive. Reviewing her debut at the
Cinegrill nightclub here earlier this month, The Hollywood Reporter
declared simply, ``She's got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Singers from Natalie Cole to Hank Williams Jr. have parlayed
parental repertories into revived careers of their own, of course,
and Ms. Mancini's venture comes just as the cool, spare sound of
'60s composers like her father and Burt Bacharach is enjoying a
revival as ``lounge music'' for Gen X-ers. But she is taking no
chances, surrounding herself for this record with veteran
colleagues of her father, from the arranger and conductor Patrick
Williams to Terry Woodson, a former bass trombone player for
Mancini and now a conductor; last year he led a monthlong tour of
Japan in which Ms. Mancini first tried her hand at her father's old
songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a certain class to it and a certain style and a certain
feeling,'' Woodson said in trying to explain the enduring appeal of
the Mancini sound. ``They're beautiful melodies, and they have a
timeless thing about them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Ms. Mancini's mother, Ginny, who had her own 30-year career
as a ``session'' singer in Hollywood and a member of Mel Torme's
Mel-Tones, her daughter's breakout is exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been really trying to analyze this explosion that's
happened to Monica in the last few weeks, and it's almost as if
she's had all this inside her and now let her musical passion
explode,'' Mrs. Mancini said in a telephone interview. ``It's quite
extraordinary what's happened. It's almost spooky, because I get
the feeling Henry's somehow still there with a baton in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Mancini, who made her professional debut with the
Henry Mancini chorus at Lake Tahoe, Nev., when she was 14, brought
a blown-up photograph of her father at the podium to her first
recording session this summer as inspiration. Her father, who
played the flute and piano, could not sing at all, ``would not even
try,'' as she puts it. But she said she ``knew from a really young
age what I was going to do, I was following in my mother's
footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mancini started at Colorado Women's College in Denver to be
near the ski slopes, but then got hired for a touring Las
Vegas-style show led by Peter Marshall, better known as the
avuncular host of ``The Hollywood Squares'' game show, and never
looked back. ``It was my first taste of the road, and I loved it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the recording session the other day, accompanied by George
Doering on a lone acoustic guitar, Ms. Mancini sang a plaintive
rendition of ``Dear Heart,'' the movie chestnut that became a huge
hit for Andy Williams, with the familiar Jay Livingston-Ray Evans
lyrics altered just a bit in memory of her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could kiss you hello, at our front door,'' Ms. Mancini
sang with a catch in her throat, ``my dear heart, I'd want you to
know, you'll leave my arms nevermore.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening in the small control room, seemingly on the verge of
tears himself, Field broke the silence, declaring proudly, ``That
kind of chilled the room out, didn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
