<SLUG> BC-STRATUS-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATUS COMPUTER TO LAY OFF 15 PERCENT OF WORLD WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With no end in sight to the Asian economic crisis that is
choking its business, Stratus Computer Inc. says it would lay off
350 people, or 15 percent of its worldwide work force.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the job cuts will occur in Massachusetts, where
the company employs about 1,200 people, said Stratus chief
executive Bruce Sachs. Stratus plans to eliminate an additional 50
jobs through voluntary attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Stratus, based in Marlborough, Mass., makes powerful computers
that are designed for uninterrupted use, such as the systems that
run telephone networks or banks.
</P>
<P>
   Like many technology companies, Stratus has been hurt by the
Asian economic crisis, which has delayed decision-making by many
corporate customers. Historically, Stratus generates as much as 40
percent of its revenues in Japan and the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly can't change the economy over there,'' Sachs said
Wednesday. ``Because we don't see a change in the revenue picture
in the short term, we need to adjust our expenses accordingly,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the layoffs, Stratus said it will take a
restructuring charge of $20 million, or about 83 cents a share, in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs added that Asia remains an important market for Stratus
and the company is well-positioned for growth once the economy
recovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to back off on our investment in the Far
East,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   News of the layoffs accompanied the release of the company's
quarterly financial results after the close of the stock market
Wednesday. The company had already warned investors last month that
it would record a loss for the second quarter, sending its stock
tumbling 24 percent. Wednesday its shares closed at 22 13/16, up
1/16.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Stratus reported a loss of $10 million, or 42
cents per share, compared to a profit of $17.4 million, or 71 cents
a share, a year earlier. This year's second-quarter results
included a charge of $10 million, primarily to reserve for excess
inventory focused at Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the three-month period ended June 28 fell to $134.3
million, from $167.6 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the troubles in Asia, Sachs said business was good in
Europe, but weaker than anticipated in North and South America. The
company said it expects those business conditions to continue and
to hurt overall financial results in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said, ``We remain confident, nonetheless, that our core
value of continuous availability remains essential to the rapidly
growing market for mission-critical telecommunications and
financial services applications, and we will continue to invest in
these areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Stratus is well-positioned for the long term in our
strategic markets. We are confident of our ability to get the
company back on track and to become a more efficient and profitable
organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
