s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-VOICES-2TAKES-$     07-22 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-VOICES-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTINCTIVE VOICES PAST AND PRESENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note subslug for TEXACO-OPERA-QUIZ) 
(af) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A favorite stump-the-panel segment on the Texaco Opera Quiz
during the Saturday afternoon radio broadcasts of the Metropolitan
Opera is the ``singer ID.'' Recordings of, say, five unidentified
tenors singing the same phrase of a particular aria are played in a
row, and the panelists are asked to name them.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how difficult it can be to recognize the voices of
even famous tenors like Carlo Bergonzi or Giuseppe di Stefano. A
voice may be great without being that distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   But there are voices that seem immediately identifiable, one of
them being the heldentenor of the Canadian Ben Heppner, who will
sing his first Tristan in the Seattle Opera's new production of
``Tristan und Isolde'' on Saturday and who, along with other
distinctive singers of today, is represented in a batch of new
compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   No voice past or present, however, is more recognizable than
that of the Swedish tenor Jussi Bjoerling. Opera buffs can battle
over who the century's greatest tenor was, and Bjoerling would be a
definite contender.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, he is at least the century's most distinctive tenor.
No one else sounded quite like him, as I am reminded by ``The Jussi
Bjoerling Edition: Studio Recordings 1930-59,'' new from EMI
Classics (5 66306 2; four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Bjoerling's sound is extraordinarily rich and radiant. Many
tenor voices share those attributes, of course, but the giveaway in
Bjoerling's case is the plaintive quality of his sound. According
to stereotype, Nordic voices are supposed to be cooler than Latin
voices.
</P>
<P>
   And at least in approach, Bjoerling's singing is Nordic: he
never engages in overt emotionalism, never allows the seamless flow
of his line to be broken by expressive indulgences. Yet even when
he is singing something cheerful, a hint of sadness, an aching
warmth, comes through, almost in spite of his manner. It's just
there in the sound.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, ``Questa o quella'' from Verdi's
``Rigoletto,'' which Bjoerling recorded in Stockholm in 1944, when
he was 33. Although he makes the Duke sound appropriately
lecherous, a touch of ache in the sound nearly melts you and makes
you want to find excuses for the character's womanizing: the Duke
is a sexual compulsive, a pathetic man fleeing his own insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bjoerling sings a truly sad aria, like ``E la solita
storia'' from Cilea's ``Arlesiana,'' recorded in 1947, also in
Stockholm, the effect is devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many superb singers today, it is still uncommon for a
voice to come along that could easily be identified on the Opera
Quiz. But there are some, as those new CDs attest.
</P>
<P>
   Heppner is the first true heldentenor to have appeared in some
time. His voice has the requisite thrust, stamina and power for the
hefty dramatic roles of the German repertory. What makes his sound
recognizable, however, is its color. Most heldentenor voices seem
built from the bottom up, with baritonal shadings even in the high
register. Heppner's sound has a tenorial quality from his beefy
bottom range to his ringing top.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors are evident in ``Dedication'' (RCA Victor
09026-63104-2), a program of songs by Beethoven, Schumann, Liszt
and Strauss in which Heppner is joined by Craig Rutenberg, a fine
pianist. A song recital might seem a risky venture for Heppner,
given the intimacy of the art form.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners may need time to adjust to the sheer impact of his
sound in these songs, even when he sings softly, which he does with
grace. But it is worth making the adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   As a new generation of recital singers emerges _ interesting
artists with lighter voices and a literate approach to song, like
the baritone Matthias Goerne and the tenor Ian Bostridge _
Heppner's work harks back to a time when major opera singers
unleashed their voices in lieder.
</P>
<P>
   The great German bass-baritone Hans Hotter and the Canadian
tenor Jon Vickers, for example, used to give larger-than-life
performances of Schubert and Schumann song cycles. Their
interpretations had charisma, and Heppner's have it, too. Yet
although Heppner brings his customary intelligence and subtlety to
these performances, the sheer presence of the voice sometimes
obscures the finer details.
</P>
<P>
   The Strauss and Liszt songs emerge as vibrant, impassioned,
visionary Romantic statements. Most impressive of all is the
performance of Beethoven's ``An die Ferne Geliebte,'' in which the
protagonist, anguished over a separation from his beloved, asks the
brook, the clouds, the birds and the wind to convey his messages.
</P>
<P>
   The work is not exactly a cycle but rather a set of six songs
linked by piano transitions into one continuous composition, with
the first song reprised in altered form as an epilogue. It takes
musicianly know-how like Heppner's to make the songs cohere as a
whole. But credit also goes to Rutenberg's sensitive and alert
playing, especially his cogent handling of those awkward
transitions. Heppner's singing is at once tender and formidable,
and in its colorations, truly distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   The great Lily Pons, with her lightness, agility, bright tone
and delicacy, probably set the standard and defined the style for
all the French coloratura sopranos who have followed. Now Natalie
Dessay has arrived to change all that.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dessay, a petite French soprano, just 32, shares qualities
with Pons and her national tradition. When she wants to, she can
sing with delicacy and a cool French restraint. But anyone who
heard her last fall at the Met, as Zerbinetta in Strauss' ``Ariadne
auf Naxos,'' knows that despite her diminutive stature, she has a
rich-textured voice with considerable carrying power.
</P>
<P>
   And it is uncommon for a coloratura soprano to combine, as she
does, brilliant agility and warm, affecting sound all the way from
her chest voice to the stratosphere, where she can toss off high Fs
and even Gs with seeming ease.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dessay's latest recording, ``Vocalises'' (EMI Classics 5
56565 2), is no doubt calculated for popular appeal. With the
Berlin Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Michael Schonwandt, Ms.
Dessay offers a program of lighter works and novelties, mostly
French, that allow plenty of opportunities for technical display.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several of the selections, like Rachmaninoff's ``Vocalise,'' pay
homage to traditional vocal exercises, or vocalises, in which
everything is sung on the syllable ``ah.'' But Ms. Dessay's
haunting performance will seduce you into thinking that the
Rachmaninoff is great music. Her sound is vibrant and lush, yet she
can sing finespun pianissimos with focused tone and hushed beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes an elaborate and unusual 14-minute concerto
for coloratura soprano and orchestra by the Russian composer
Reinhold Gliere, sung entirely as vocalise. Delibes' ``Filles de
Cadix'' is an enchanting little work in the style of a folk song,
with fancy coloratura flights, including a climactic high F sharp,
which Ms. Dessay sings exquisitely.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to hear Ms. Dessay in more substantial repertory,
her earlier EMI disks include a splendid recording of Mozart
concert arias. There is also an album of French arias, an
intelligent selection that includes a scintillating performance of
that Pons tour de force, the ``Bell Song'' from Delibes' ``Lakme.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to distinctive sound and style, Russian singers
tend to be a class unto themselves. But even among Russians, the
baritone Dmitri Hvorostovsky has a particularly recognizable sound,
which, though hard to describe, is almost as hard to mistake.
</P>
<P>
   There is a gravelly quality to his tone, especially in the low
range, though grainy remnants of that color are present throughout,
even in his mellow midrange and poignant top voice. This is a
characteristic, not a flaw; it makes his singing sound earthy and
exceptionally mature for his age, 36.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hvorostovsky first made his name in Russian repertory,
major bel canto roles, including Riccardo in Bellini's
``Puritani,'' figured prominently in his early career. He has
worked extensively in the Italian tradition, even when his husky
sound might seem less than ideally suitable. He obviously believes
in what the Italian tradition can bestow in terms of legato line,
evenness of tone, and unforced production.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of his commitment came in his recent Philips recording
``Arie Antiche'' (289 456 543-2), a program of 17th- and
18th-century Italian arias and art songs, performed with the
Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields, conducted by Neville Marriner.
</P>
<P>
   Hvorostovsky's singing here will not be to all tastes: he lacks
some agility in passage work, and at full voice he sometimes sings
with a muscular quality more characteristic of the Russian school.
But he is deeply drawn to this music, and the best of his work is
very fine, including some lovely accounts of Gluck arias and a
superb performance of ``Sorge infausta,'' an elegantly brilliant
aria from Handel's ``Orlando.''
</P>
<P>
   Hvorostovsky's latest Philips recording, ``Olga and Dmitri''
(289 454 439-2), is a program of arias and duets with another
Russian singer of strongly identifiable vocal color, the
mezzo-soprano Olga Borodina. Patrick Summers conducts the English
Chamber Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Borodina's dusky-textured, flexible voice is a good match
for Hvorostovsky's earthy lyric baritone. In arias and duets from
Rimsky-Korsakov's ``Czar's Bride,'' they are stylistically
authoritative and vocally lustrous. A duet from Saint-Saens'
``Samson et Dalila'' also receives a dramatically powerful and
handsomely sung performance.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise here is the singers' commanding, fervent,
Italianate performances of selections from Donizetti's neglected
``La Favorita.'' The more dramatic bel canto repertory, like this,
suits them better than Rossini's ``Barbiere di Siviglia,'' which is
also represented here.
</P>
<P>
   Hvorostovsky is a little driven and humorless in Figaro's famous
``Largo al factotum.'' Rossini's barber and handyman is only
pretending to complain that everybody wants something from him;
actually, he loves his job. And Ms. Borodina's execution of
Rosina's effervescent roulades is somewhat mannered; in strings of
16th notes, she tends to overemphasize the first note of every
couplet. Yet overall, this is a rewarding disk from two distinctive
singers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, when it comes to unmistakable voices,
Bjoerling remains the standard-setter. For most of his mature
career, he recorded for RCA Victor, including many operas still
available. The most fascinating recordings from the new EMI
collection are from his early days. In the first and oldest
selection, ``Celeste Aida,'' recorded in 1936, the 25-year-old
tenor already sounds like nobody else, before or since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
