<HEADLINE>
BULLS TO NAME FLOYD COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is one large question hovering above Chicago this morning.
And it is not: Who is Tim Floyd? Rather: What about Michael?
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls are prepared to name former Iowa State coach
Floyd their coach. The team is expected to announce Thursday that
Floyd will succeed Phil Jackson as the head man of the six-time NBA
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd _ the man Michael Jordan said he couldn't play for and the
man Jackson referred to as ``Pink'' _ arrived in Chicago Wednesday,
only hours after resigning from Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't comment any further right now,'' Floyd said
when approached by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably the last thing Bulls fans want to hear. The city
was in a frenzy exactly one week ago when Jordan gave an impromptu
press conference in suburban Chicago after playing a round of golf.
At that time, Jordan reiterated that the only coach he wanted to
play for was Jackson. He also said he didn't want to play on
another team. Based on those words, it appears Jordan's brilliant
career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael needs to take his time and see how all of the pieces
fall into place,'' said David Falk, the powerful agent who
represents Jordan. ``We only have one piece of the picture. It may
be that piece is of sufficient weight to outweigh everything else.
Only time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Jordan was spending his time doing something that he
may do with more frequency if he retires: playing golf. He did not
respond publicly to news of Floyd's resignation. But his words from
July 16 still resonate: ``I don't know Tim. I don't have anything
against Tim Floyd. To (play for him) is like starting all over
again, and that's what I don't want to do. He may want to do that,
but I don't. I don't condemn him. I don't condemn (the Bulls) for
hiring him. But I just don't feel that I want to start with someone
who really doesn't know me and doesn't know the way I play the game
of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   So the drama is set. Floyd, a fishing buddy of Chicago general
manager Jerry Krause, is putting himself in an unenviable position.
He could be known as The Man Who Pushed Jordan Away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the story of the toad that got the princess to
kiss him, so hopefully, it will work out,'' said Bulls center Bill
Wennington, holding out hope that Jordan will return. The
consensus, though, is that the Bulls will be radically different in
1998-99. Jordan's departure would probably preclude the return of
Scottie Pippen. And Dennis Rodman, who called the potential hiring
of Floyd ``a joke,'' is most certainly gone. It may be the same
story for many of the Bulls, whose number includes nine free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a near-expansion situation for Floyd, who
accumulated 243 wins as a head coach at Iowa State, the University
of New Orleans, and Idaho. Friends of the 44-year-old native of
Hattiesburg, Miss., initially predicted he would stay at Iowa State
because he didn't want to be known as the coach who forced out
Jordan. Obviously, that is no longer a concern.
</P>
<P>
   The news out of Chicago has created a buzz around the NBA. Teams
such as the Pacers and Heat now believe they are the ones to
conquer in the Eastern Conference. And in the West, the Jazz and
Lakers have to like their chances of winning a title. The hiring of
Floyd also has to affect the psychology of other coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Celtics coach and president Rick Pitino said he
didn't think many teams could sign Antoine Walker. He was fearful
that the Bulls _ without Jordan, Jackson, Pippen, and Rodman _
could be in position to sign Walker to a long-term contract. Now
the Bulls could be in position to not only take the Celtics' best
player but those of other teams as well. They will be significantly
under the salary cap if they don't re-sign any of their free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The only stable thing about the Bulls now is that they have a
coach. They don't know if all their assistants will return. And
they don't know if all their players will return, No. 23 most
notable among them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
