<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: BATTLE OVER RIGHT TO SUE HEALTH GROUPS ISN'T GOING
AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With congressional Democrats and Republicans jockeying fiercely
for the high political ground on patients' rights, there is a good
chance that efforts to clamp down on abuses in managed medical care
will come to naught this year. But it's a sure bet that at least
one issue of contention, the right to sue health maintenance
organizations for malpractice, will be back on Congress' agenda
very soon.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the quarter-century-old bar to suits against
medical insurers is, on its face, outmoded because managed care
virtually guarantees that insurers as well as doctors have a role
in choosing treatment. For another, the shield is apt to be
breached anyway, as frustrated judges look for ways to hold HMOs
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a novel proposal by Jeffrey O'Connell and James Neale
of the University of Virginia Law School is so timely. Indeed,
while their ``early offer'' approach to giving both sides potent
reasons to settle malpractice suits seems most relevant to the
managed care controversy, it offers equal promise for coping with
traditional doctor-patient litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Employment Retirement and Income Security Act of
1974, or Erisa, shields fiduciaries that administer health care
against negligence suits. The idea was to encourage employers to
offer this vital fringe benefit by protecting them against injury
claims where they had little control over the wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   But with managed care the rule these days, the shield seems
unfair. Why should a patient be able to sue a doctor who denies him
adequate care, but not the insurance company that ordered the
doctor not to provide the care?
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed? A few years ago, when premiums were rising at
double-digit rates and health care inflation threatened to eat the
Federal budget alive, policy makers were quietly relieved to have
this inconsistency on the books. But now that cost-cutting is out
of vogue and jokes about drive-through heart transplants ring
hollow, Democrats have added the right to sue to their ``patients'
bill of rights'' wish list.
</P>
<P>
   The catch, O'Connell said, is that the tort system is an
inefficient way to compensate injury victims. And that goes double
for medical malpractice, where the issues are more technical.
``Juries have enough trouble figuring out who is at fault in auto
accidents, let alone failed surgical procedures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By no coincidence, a host of studies have shown that most
successful malpractice suits are unjustified while the vast
majority of those injured by medical procedures never see a penny _
or are compensated many years after the fact. Even so, 60 to 70
cents of every dollar paid in malpractice insurance premiums is
spent fighting over claims.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Connell's view, simply extending liability to insurers
assures more of the same. But the most familiar alternative to the
negligence system, ``no fault'' coverage, has problems of its own.
</P>
<P>
   With no-fault auto insurance (which O'Connell pioneered in the
1970's), the injured are compensated for medical bills and lost
wages by their own insurance companies. And in the handful of
states that have also erected formidable legal barriers to suing
for intangible ``pain and suffering'' _ notably Michigan _ no-fault
has done a decent job of covering tangible losses while keeping
down insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connell argues that no-fault translates poorly into
malpractice coverage. While injuries resulting from auto accidents
can be more or less pinned down, it is often very difficult to
isolate the injury caused by a medical procedure: A patient with
cancer was treated and got sicker. What portion of the outcome was
caused by the cancer and what portion by the treatment?
</P>
<P>
   ``In Sweden, where they have no-fault malpractice,'' O'Connell
said, ``arbitrators make that decision. But that approach would
likely break down in our more litigious society.''
</P>
<P>
   A better alternative, he argues, is a system in which
malpractice defendants would have a relatively brief period _ say
four months _ in which to offer to cover plaintiffs' economic
losses, plus reasonable attorney fees in return for eliminating
their tort liability. Plaintiffs would be free to refuse the offer,
and probably would in cases of flagrant medical error. If they did,
though, they would be required to prove ``intentional or wanton
misconduct'' rather than simple negligence.
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost inevitable that malpractice liability will be
extended to managed care providers. That, in turn, will almost
surely lead to efforts to contain malpractice costs without denying
compensation to the most deserving.
</P>
<P>
   What worries O'Connell is that the lessons from the long,
tortuous history of no-fault auto insurance will be ignored in
redesigning malpractice. Unless great care is taken in changing the
incentives of both plaintiffs and defendants, he argues, reforms
intended to deliver swift, efficient justice will boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incentives aren't part of the problem,'' O'Connell said.
``They are the problem.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
