<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-HUTCHISON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUTCHISON ASSAILS GORE FOR SUGGESTING HEAT WAVE TIED TO GLOBAL
WARMING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Claiming that the Earth is ``in a cooling period,''
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison on Wednesday criticized Vice President Al
Gore for suggesting that the current Texas heat wave is linked to
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we really don't want to politicize this heat wave by
trying to indicate that there is a cause that is not proven at
all,'' said the Texas Republican in an interview on C-SPAN's
Washington Journal program.
</P>
<P>
   The senator was asked about Gore's remarks in a July 16
Christian Science Monitor article in which the vice president
blasted Congress for ignoring the global warming issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much more proof do we need that global warming is real?''
Gore was quoted as saying as he advised lawmakers to ``go outside
and feel the temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison dismissed Gore's comments, saying ``actually the
science does not in any way indicate that we are in a global
warming because of anything that is in the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Actually we're in a cooling period. It's not a cool
cooling period but for the last 20 years we have been coming into a
cooling period from the high in the (19)40s when it really was from
natural causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, however, acknowledged that the sizzling Texas weather
had taken a serious toll on the state's agriculture industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is serious, and the sad thing is we really don't see
any relief,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Larry Haas said that the vice president was not
trying to politicize the issue. Haas said that, while no single
heat wave can be attributed to global warming, the country has
experienced record temperatures in 1997 and the last six months of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus of mainstream scientists is that humans are
having an effect on the climate. And, in light of all that, the
president and vice president feel strongly that Congress should
stop blocking their initiatives to address global climate change,''
Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Hutchison's office cited different sources
to prove their points about whether the Earth's temperature was
rising or falling.
</P>
<P>
   The White House produced a study by the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration's National Climatic Data Center that
found 1997 to be the warmest year in this century, based on land
and ocean temperature data. One of the authors of the study
concluded the trend of upward temperatures likely was the result of
the increase in greenhouse gases due to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hutchison's office cited an article in the Dec. 4,
1997, Wall Street Journal by two chemists at the Oregon Institute
of Science and Medicine who claimed that global warming was a myth.
They said that during the past 20 years temperatures have tended to
go down, based on satellite data and measurements from weather
balloons. The authors wrote that long-term temperature increases
are likely due to changes in solar activity, not pollution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
