<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONES-MICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSFUL MOUSE CLONING BOOSTS RESEARCHERS' CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Researchers in Hawaii have created the first
identical copies of mice from adult mouse cells, erasing lingering
doubts about science's ability to clone mammals of different
species and providing a cheap but powerful tool for further cloning
research.
</P>
<P>
   Using techniques similar to those that produced the cloned lamb
Dolly but with important changes, the Hawaii researchers have
created three generations of genetically identical mice _ clones of
clones of clones _ totaling 50 individuals, the scientists said
Wednesday. The feat was all the more stunning because researchers
as recently as 10 years ago had found mice so difficult to clone
that they speculated it might be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The mice were created in the laboratory of Ryuzo Yanagimachi, a
renowned 69-year-old reproductive biology researcher at the
University of Hawaii's medical school. But at a press conference
here, he credited the idea and the ``hard work'' that produced the
mice to Teruhiko Wakayama, a young post-doctoral fellow from Japan
who has been working in Yanagimachi's lab.
</P>
<P>
   The first-born mouse clone, named ``Cumulina'' because she
sprang from a donor cell called a cumulus cell, and the 49 others
are all female. That is because the only adult mouse cell that the
researchers were successfully able to clone was the ``cumulus''
cell, which is found only in the ovaries of female mice.
Yanagimachi hinted that the researchers had solved the problem of
making male mouse clones, but would not confirm it because the work
has not yet been published.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement, documented in a report in the current Nature
magazine, is a long-awaited followup to the announcement more than
a year ago of the birth of Dolly, the first mammal cloned from an
adult cell, at the Roslin Institute in Scotland. Since that time,
some scientists had speculated that no one could replicate the
cloning of Dolly, and some had even questioned whether Dolly was an
authentic clone.
</P>
<P>
   But those worries have been laid to rest by the mouse cloning
report and also by two reports in Nature Biotechnology saying that
DNA fingerprinting has conclusively shown that Dolly was born from
a cloned adult mammary cell from a sheep. John Eppig, a mouse
reproduction specialist at the Jackson Laboratory in Bar Harbor,
Maine, said in a telephone interview that the mouse cloning was
welcome validation of the pioneering work of Scotland's Ian Wilmut,
who led the team that produced Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has repeated it _ and repeated it gloriously,'' said
Eppig. The scientists led by Yanagimachi have ``confirmed that the
excitement about what Wilmut did is justified.'' Moreover, he said,
the creation of the mouse clones emphatically showed that the
technique known as ``nuclear transfer'' that produced Dolly can
work in other species.
</P>
<P>
   The success in mice also confirms the stunning finding in the
creation of Dolly that an adult cell, which has gone through a
process of development that commits it to a specific role, such as
a nerve, bone or liver cell, can be ``reprogrammed'' to start life
all over again as an embryo cell. It is the reprogramming of the
adult cell's nucleus, which contains all its genes, that enables
scientists to create a new individual that is identical to the
adult from which the cell was taken.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishment has no direct implication for the contentious
debate over whether cloning humans should be attempted or
permitted. One scientist noted that in the process of making the
mouse clones many fetuses died or were malformed and for that
reason the technique shouldn't be tried in humans.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary accompanying the report in Nature, Davor Solter
of the Max Planck Institute in Germany hailed the cloning feat and
said being able to copy mice, with their short gestation period and
well-understood genetics, ``opens up the possibility of a broad
experimental analysis of mammalian cloning and of the factors that
determine its outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, mice are very cheap compared to the large farm
animals, and having them in genetically identical copies will speed
research in fundamental biology and drug development.
</P>
<P>
   James Robl, an animal reproduction scientist at the University
of Massachusetts in Amherst, said at the press conference that the
ability to clone mice will shift a great deal of basic research on
cloning to the rodents and away from larger animals like sheep and
cows, in which studying many key questions ``takes too long and
costs too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   Robl, who is a consultant to Advanced Cell Technology in
Shrewsbury and president of a recent spinoff, ACT Agriculture, said
that future uses of animal cloning include everything from making
many copies of outstanding meat- and milk-producing cattle to
creating animal and even human tissues for implantation into
patients suffering from Parkinson's disease and other ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Coleman, an official of PPL Therapeutics, a company that is
commercializing the technology used in creating Dolly, said that
among other things cloning could enable scientists to make cows and
sheep immune to diseases like BSE (``mad cow disease'') and
scrapie; to manufacture medically important antibodies in cows; and
to modify pig organs so that they could be implanted into human
patients without causing immune rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The international team headed by Yanagimachi included scientists
from the University of Tokyo; the Babraham Institute in Cambridge,
England; the University of Pavia in Italy, and the Jackson
Laboratory in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   As with Dolly, creation of the mouse clones involved, first,
plucking a cell from an adult that would be transferred into an egg
cell from the same species to make an embryo. Yanagimachi selected
three types of cells in the mouse that are known to be quiescent _
resting, rather than dividing _ and thus would be good candidates
for genetic ``reprogramming.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the cells _ a cell from the male testis and a brain cell
_ failed to produce viable offspring. But using the donor cumulus
cell from a female mouse ovary, the scientists succeeded.
Altogether, just 2 to 3 percent of the embryoes that were created
developed into live offspring.
</P>
<P>
   There are tens of thousands of genes in an adult cell, but only
a minority of them are ``turned on,'' or active, because the
remainder aren't needed for the cell's specific role. Until the
birth of Dolly, it had been biologic dogma that once a cell had
developed to this point, the silent genes in the cell's nucleus
couldn't be turned on again, and thus it would be impossible to
create a new individual from an adult cell. But the research that
yielded Dolly showed that in fact the cell's clock could be
rewound, its switched-off genes reactivated, and its nucleus used
to make an embryo capable of full development.
</P>
<P>
   Where Dolly's creator Wilmut had starved the donor nucleus in a
laboratory dish until it was forced into a non-dividing state,
Yanagimachi and Wakayama chose non-dividing cells to begin with.
And where Wilmut used an electric shock to insert the nucleus into
a recipient egg whose only nucleus had been removed, the Hawaii
researchers used a special micropipette to inject the donor nucleus
into the mouse egg cell to create the new embryo.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagimachi said he and his colleagues then immersed the embryo
in a chemical solution to activate the embryo _ that is, turn on
its genes. It was apparently in that short period of time that the
donor nucleus reprogrammed itself so that its genes were all able
to function and initiate the development of the fetal clones.
</P>
<P>
   After the embryo had divided a number of times, the embryo was
implanted into the uterus of a surrogate mother mouse to continue
development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1916EDT &QL; 
