<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ASKS SMITH TO STAY IN IRELAND THROUGH TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has asked Jean Kennedy Smith, the
US ambassador to Ireland, to extend her stay through his September
trip to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Smith's younger brother, said the
president asked Smith to delay her departure from Phoenix Park for
another three months, through the end of September. Smith has
agreed to postpone her return and will stay in the job she has held
since the spring of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Smith had packed her bags and was planning to fly
back to her New York home next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reportedly wants to keep Smith in place because of the
delicate status of the Northern Ireland peace process and the
difficulty of naming her successor.
</P>
<P>
   Although a clear majority of citizens in both the Republic of
Ireland and Northern Ireland approved the peace accord reached on
Good Friday, splinter groups continue a campaign of sabotage
through terrorism. Three young boys recently burned to death when
their house was firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Mowlam, the British secretary for Northern Ireland, met
briefly with Kennedy Wednesday after a longer meeting with
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam said that progress was being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank the Senate, Congress, and the White House for not
being fair-weather friends,'' she said while posing for a
photograph with Kennedy and Senator Christopher Dodd, a Connecticut
Democrat. ``It has been tough, and it will continue to be tough.
We've made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy praised Mowlam and British Prime Minister Tony Blair for
the roles they played in negotiating the peace accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-NYT     07-22 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN DEBATE ON HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL IS REKINDLED BY POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Just nine weeks before national elections, a political
insurgent moving back to Germany from New York has injected a
question into the campaign that some thought taboo: should Germany
abandon its project to build a huge memorial to the Holocaust on
the ruins of Hitler's Third Reich?
</P>
<P>
   The insurgent, Michael Naumann, a prominent publisher who has
been a vocal player in the German takeover of American publishing
interests in New York, was nominated last weekend as the opposition
Social Democrats' cultural czar. He would assume the post if
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his Christian Democrats are toppled in
the Sept. 27 election.
</P>
<P>
   In the few days since his selection, Naumann has stirred a fiery
debate. ``It is hard to see how you could smash much more china
than this man has done in just a few hours,'' Kohl said during a
campaign swing Wednesday among vacationers in northern German beach
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews and public appearances, Naumann _ who
said that his maternal grandfather was Jewish, but that he is not _
has raised the possibility that a Social Democratic government
would do what Kohl depicts as unthinkable and lay the memorial
project to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real memorials in Germany are the concentration camps,''
Naumann said in a telephone interview Wednesday night. The
projected memorial ``will not lead psychologically to what a simple
visit to Bergen-Belsen evokes in a more shocking manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, the huge monument sought by Kohl would
represent ``a memorial for memory, a suspension of guilt in art.''
And he accused Kohl of displaying a ``crude understanding of
historical memory, which thinks that things can be finished by a
modeled memory, and then you move on in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Naumann's earlier remarks in interviews with German newspaper
reporters and broadcasters drew criticism from some government
politicians but also evoked the deep ambiguities _ among German
Jews and within political parties _ surrounding one of the most
emotive debates confronting Germany more than a half-century after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Schroeder, the Social Democrat challenger to Kohl, said
Tuesday that he felt ``very close'' to Naumann's views. But some
Social Democrats said the issue should not be part of the election.
``This is not suited to an election campaign,'' said Peter Conradi,
a Social Democrat supporter of the monument.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's support for Naumann seemed intended to underscore
Kohl's discomfort at rising disputes associated with the project.
But it also reflected a marked, and possibly generational, shift
away from the inhibitions of Kohl's era.
</P>
<P>
   It elicited outrage from some German Jews, sympathy from others
and disdain from yet more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the great vision of the federal man of culture, and
if Naumann really has no greater concerns, then all I can say is:
poor culture,'' said Ignatz Bubis, head of the main representative
organization of German Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Since the idea of a memorial to honor Holocaust victims was put
forward 10 years ago, it has become ever more divisive, drawing
objections from politicians, authors and intellectuals that no
artistic construction could possibly reflect the enormity of the
Holocaust, and that the presence of such a monument will serve not
to kindle memory but rather to take the place of it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kohl, who has taken a close personal interest in
the project, has insisted that a final choice among four designs
for the monument would be made before the election, for a
ground-breaking ceremony next January _ whoever is chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Like the debate preceding the Vietnam war memorial in
Washington, the discussion has coaxed forth the nation's ghosts, to
such an extent that countless deadlines for the project have
slipped. Twice this year, in March and June, deadlines for an
announcement from Kohl have passed without word from him.
</P>
<P>
   An initial design competition for the memorial was canceled in
1996 and Kohl ordered a new contest. That produced four finalists,
including one design by two Americans, Richard Serra and Peter
Eisenmann, which is viewed as the front-runner, even though Serra
pulled out of the project in early June.
</P>
<P>
   The American design in its original form envisaged a huge
labyrinth of 4,000 stone pillars of varying heights scattered over
an area of 180,000 square feet on a site between the refurbished
German Parliament in the Reichstag building and the
steel-and-concrete commercial center under construction at the
Potsdamer Platz.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolically, the monument would straddle the erstwhile
no-man's-land around the Berlin Wall and would lie directly above
or close to some of the landmarks of the Third Reich, including
Hitler's bunker.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Eisenmann-Serra project has been scaled down,
according to German press reports, to a monument of some 2,000
pillars. But that has not halted disputes that cross political
lines, divide German Jews and seem to defy any quick solution.
</P>
<P>
   No stranger to controversy, Naumann, 56, has headed Metropolitan
Books/Henry Holt Inc., in New York, which is a unit of the German
publishing giant Holtzbrinck. Earlier this year, another big German
publisher, Bertelsmann, acquired Random House, prompting concerns
among some American authors about the German inroads.
</P>
<P>
   Known in Germany as a publisher and journalist, Naumann
announced plans to leave Holtzbrinck on election day, whether or
not the Social Democrats win.
</P>
<P>
   But, given the furor surrounding his political debut, had he had
second thoughts about his remarks?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not changed my views,'' Naumann said. ``I do not have a
single friend in Germany of Jewish denomination who is in favor of
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
