<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL KILLS $100 MILLION IN FUNDS FOR MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key Senate committee Wednesday killed a measure
that would have given Massachusetts $100 million in highway money
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was two months to the day after Trent Lott, the Senate
majority leader, and Tom Daschle, the minority leader, shook hands
on an agreement to earmark the funds for Massachusetts and the same
amount for Alabama, with the money coming from the pending
water-resources bill. The agreement cleared the way for approving
the $200.5 billion highway spending bill on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was struck after Senators John F. Kerry and Richard
Shelby, an Alabama Republican, each threatened to block passage of
the final version of the highway spending bill unless the Senate
leaders pledged to find more money for their states.
</P>
<P>
   Highway money for Massachusetts was cut back in the final 24
hours of haggling over the transportation bill _ the biggest pork
barrel measure in history _ because of funding promises made to
other states. Kerry worked out the agreement to get additional
highway dollars from another bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee rejected
that move Wednesday by deleting the provision that would authorize
the $20 million a year in extra money for Massachusetts and Alabama
on a 12-6 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senator John H. Chafee of Rhode Island, chairman of
the committee, voted in favor of the funding. Senator Bob Smith, a
New Hampshire Republican, voted against the money for his
neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Graham, a Florida Democrat and former governor who
had been active in the battle to equalize highway funding among the
states, proposed killing the provision, saying it would put the
entire water-resources bill at risk of a parliamentary challenge on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry called Wednesday's committee vote a temporary setback and
said Senate leaders were surprised by the action. He predicted that
the funding authorization would be added to the bill later in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership is thoroughly committed to doing it and will do
it, and will probably do it in conference,'' said Kerry. ``Their
commitment is absolutely firm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
