<SLUG> BC-TEN-FATHER-SON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONTZES OUST HOEVELERS AS FATHER-SON CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Chris Tontz decided to take some chances in the
third set.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he and his father, Dr. Bill Tontz, were able to
conclude Charlie and Charles Hoeveler's five-year reign as US
Father and Son national tennis champions at Longwood Cricket Club
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked second nationally, right behind the Hoevelers, the Tontz
team from San Diego defeated the Hoevelers, of Roth, Calif., for
the first time in four attempts, earning a 4-6, 6-3, 6-4 victory in
a match that lasted more than two hours on the grass courts. They
had also gone three sets last year in the final. But this time the
Tontz duo concluded the Hoevelers' record-tying run, equaling the
five titles in a row captured by J.D.E. Jones and son Arnold from
1928-32.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth game of the third set was decisive. Chris's backhand
pass off the return during the service break made the difference. A
third-year professional (ranked No. 640 in singles, 220 in doubles)
after having been California-Irvine's No. 1 player for three
seasons, Chris grabbed the opening point by using that tactic. Then
the senior Hoeveler, Charlie, double-faulted before Chris belted
another backhand winner off the return. One point later, the
Hoevelers slammed a serve-and-volley half-volley into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Charlie was moving a lot at the net to help his dad out,
so I had to go down the line to see if he kept moving, so I had a
free shot down the line,'' Chris said. ``I thought I was going down
the line too often, but even if Charlie was there, if I hit the
ball hard enough, it's still a tough shot.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th game, on Chris's serve, the Tontzes converted on
their third match point. Chris double-faulted on the first, then
shouted, ``I'm so tight right now.'' On the second, Charlie
Hoeveler ripped a backhand long. And on the third, Hoeveler floated
a backhand lob long.
</P>
<P>
   This was the biggest match of Chris Tontz's career. ``I know
this means a lot to my dad _ he trains the whole year for this, and
I want to do well for him,'' said Chris. ``I was tight when I was
serving for the match, but when I shouted out those words, that was
my way of loosening up, to just let it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played well, and that's what delighted Charlie
Hoeveler. ``Chris Tontz was a dominant player,'' said Charlie, who
runs summer sports camps for Nike. ``He was magnificent. He hardly
missed a first serve. His returns were terrific and he poached at
the net. Backhands, forehands, on both sides, Chris played
extremely well. He just didn't miss. He hurt us. His dad was solid
and we didn't break him. I thought they beat us at full strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Hoevelers had advanced by beating Kelly and
Clayton Hall of Anchorage, Ky., by withdrawal in the semifinals.
The second-seeded Tontzes ousted third-seeded Paul and Kevin Van
der Sommen of Oneonta, N.Y., 6-3, 7-6, in the other semi, then
claimed the big prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
