<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILIPINO-VETS-HNS &LR;      07-22 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILIPINO-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIPINOS WHO FOUGHT IN WORLD WAR II SEEK FULL VETERAN STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Filipinos who fought alongside U.S. soldiers in
World War II urged Congress Wednesday to provide full veterans
benefits to surviving members of the Philippine army, telling a
House panel they deserve the recognition for defending American
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ganio, a prisoner of war and veteran of the battles of
Bataan and Corregidor, told the House Committee on Veterans Affairs
that the veterans only seek what they earned and deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Ganio, 78, said he wanted ``justice after waiting for the past
52 years. Pride is pride, good is good, and justice is justice. We
ask for justice now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganio, a citizen of the Philippines who spoke on behalf of the
American Coalition for Filipino Veterans, said he spent two months
of hard labor in Corregidor where Japanese soldiers beat him with
baseball bats.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had an unbreakable faith in America during his time
in the Philippine Commonwealth Army.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Esclamado, chairman of the National Federation of Filipino
American Associations, an organization that represents some 3,000
Filipino American Associations, said that although the veterans
were not U.S. citizens, they fought for America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best test of allegiance for the Constitution of the United
States is how much one risks in defense of that oath,'' he told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippines was a U.S. commonwealth when the Japanese seized
the island nation after weeks of brutal fighting in December 1941
and early 1942. The islands were retaken more than two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Ganio told the House panel that all Filipino soldiers took the
formal oath of allegiance to the U.S. flag and Constitution. Ganio
and about 20 other veterans who attended the hearing wore their
uniform jackets and hats decorated with medals and insignia.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Tagumpay Nanadiego, a Veterans' Affairs official at the
Philippine Embassy, said there were more than 100,000 Filipinos who
fought to defend the American territory.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer than 75,000 survivors today, about 22,000 of
whom live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Veterans Affairs estimates that granting full
benefits to veterans of the Philippines could cost $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Members of some elite Philippine military units were granted
full veterans benefits, but a 1946 law rescinded most benefits for
all other Filipino veterans who fought in World War II with the
U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 1946 law did extend some disability benefits to the
Filipino veterans who were wounded in combat.
</P>
<P>
   What Ganio and the other veterans who attended Wednesday's
hearing seek are full disability compensation, burial allowances
and pensions for their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Snook of the Congressional Research Service said there
were several factors behind Congress' 1946 decision to rescind some
benefits, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The cost of the providing full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some members of Congress rated service in the Philippine army
below that of service in the U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some lawmakers believed that benefits would create a
privileged class in a newly independent nation with a developing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Filner, D-Calif., has introduced legislation to provide
full benefits for all Filipinos who fought in World War II,
including those who are not U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill says we will restore dignity and honor to these
proud veterans,'' Filner said. ``We will remedy historical
injustice. We will make good on the promise of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure has nearly 200 co-sponsors, but the Department of
Veterans Affairs opposes the bill and says current law provides for
the well-being of these veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Esclamado, who was shot at by a Japanese officer at the age of
14, said there was no justification for denying benefits to
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the war, the U.S. promised to pay the war damage claims
of Filipinos ... but the U.S. reneged even in this promise,'' he
said. ``These Filipinos are losing faith in America's sense of
fairness and justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
