<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SAILING-STANDARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING THE WATERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(runs with sailing story) 
By JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The American Sailing Association administers the
following keelboat certifications:
</P>
<P>
   Basic Keelboat Sailing: Sailors must sail a keelboat of about 20
feet in moderate wind and sea conditions in familiar waters without
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Coastal Cruising: Sailors must cruise safely in local and
regional waters as both skipper and crew on an auxiliary-powered
sailboat of about 20 to 30 feet in moderate winds and sea
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   From there, sailors can test for a series of additional
certifications, including (in ascending order): Bareboat
Chartering, also known as Intermediate Coastal Cruising; Coastal
Navigation; Advanced Coastal Cruising; Celestial Navigation; and
Offshore Passagemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced sailors may challenge any of the ASA standards by
demonstrating both sailing knowledge and on-water skills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-PAULY-LADN     07-22 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-PAULY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBACORE MISSION YIELDS FRUSTRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ Armies of longfins. Can't-miss angling. Albacore
galore.
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard the stories and read the counts out of the San Diego
landings _ 1,000-fish days the norm. I caught the fever when the
largely elusive tuna began showing up in Ventura County fish counts
by mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Plans were made, but as soon as I could get on a boat the bite
petered out and died. Trips I had reserved spots on were canceled
three times in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I could have motored down to San Diego, where 10 albacore
per rod were not uncommon. But my name was slated to grace the
manifest of a four-day boat leaving port there in mid-August, and,
by now, the albacore challenge had become something more regional
for me. I wanted to catch a longfin out of my own backyard of
Ventura, or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Albacore, you see, are the slot machines of Pacific game fishes;
no species is more of a gamble to catch. A pelagic, or open-ocean
denizen, the long-finned tuna swim constantly to find food sources
and agreeable water temperatures, so much so it's impossible to
tell where they'll strike next.
</P>
<P>
   Usually they are found from 50 to 100 miles offshore, or farther
_ a long haul, to say the least. Once schools are located, anglers
need to dedicate up to 30 hours on a party boat with little notice
ahead of time if they want to score.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, albies seldom show in Southern California. The last
significant Southland run before 1997's El Nino-driven bounty _ the
earliest run in a half-century and one of the richest seasons _ was
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   By the sounds of it, this year's run is starting up where last
year's left off, and San Diego anglers are virtually guaranteed
albacore. That just reaffirmed my mission: Catch an albacore at
home.
</P>
<P>
   So desperate had I become, I even agreed to ride on a spotter
plane to track the wily tuna out of Oxnard. But even that fell
through. Besides, what tackle do you use from a plane?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a fax came across my deck _ an exploratory albacore
trip out of Santa Barbara _ and I bit. Bummer is, we got halfway to
Japan and still didn't catch a thing. 0-for-the-boat. A total skunk
for 13 anglers.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard that the best way to jinx a trip is to let a
sportswriter aboard, but this was out of my hands _ out of
anybody's hands. We went to Las Vegas and came back broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``You roll the dice,'' said Merit McCrea, skipper of the
luckless Seahawk LXV who oversaw anglers troll from sunup to 4 p.m.
before turning back at a spot some 110 miles south of port. ``Like
they say, `Heroes or zeros.' Today we were zeros.''
</P>
<P>
   You could feel the collective energy slipping away well before
the Seahawk _ at this point dubbed by some the Seaskunk _ returned
home in what amounted to an expensive, 29-hour boat ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' said fellow angler Ed Sanfilippo, who frequents
a bass-fishing tournament circuit when he's not tickling the keys
as a senior locksmith for the Los Angeles Department of Water and
Power. ``It shouldn't happen with me.''
</P>
<P>
   That about sums up an experience that is difficult to explain or
accept. Every angler knows there's always a chance; they just hope
against hope it doesn't happen to them. There are few emptier
feelings... at least in the fickle realm of recreation.
</P>
<P>
   It must be difficult for party-boat captains to say with any
sincerity, ``Come fish with us again,'' after such a hapless trip _
even when they have done everything right. When they watched
diligently for meter marks on their fish finders, scoured the sea
for balls of baitfish and squinted for bird life until new wrinkles
bore into their foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   Skippers take it personally when seaweed and kelp are the only
things biting and their customers come home with empty fish sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, people feel like they got totally ripped off,''
said McCrea, who explored every spot he wanted to on the trip but
spied just five breaching bluefin tuna that teased him and
disappeared in ``hello, good-bye'' fashion.
</P>
<P>
   He warded off dockside requests for refunds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried,'' he explained. ``It could have gone the other way _
10 guys hammering the snot out of them _ and we wouldn't have
charged any more.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as it is said ad nauseam, ``That's why they call it fishing
and not catching.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a phrase I detest, but one that couldn't be more
appropriate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
