<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MARKETERS BUSY CHANGING ASSIGNMENTS  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another busy day along Madison Avenue, as several
national marketers, well known and otherwise, made changes on
advertising assignments with billings estimated at more than $120
million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest involved barnesandnoble.com, the online division of
the bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. in New York, which named the New
York office of TBWA Chiat/Day to handle its account. Billings were
estimated at $38 million to $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The account for the online division, along with the creative
duties for the parent Barnes &AMP; Noble, had been handled for less
than a year by Weiss, Whitten, Stagliano in New York. Weiss,
Whitten recently began running a campaign to reintroduce the
division's Web site (www.barnesandnoble.com), which competes
against online booksellers like Amazon.com; not long afterward,
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Weiss, Whitten decided to end their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Boyd, a spokesman for barnesandnoble.com, said the decision
to hire TBWA Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of Omnicom
Group, came after a six-week review that had been narrowed to that
agency and two other finalists: DDB Needham New York, part of the
DDB Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom, and Deutsch Inc. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   While TBWA Chiat/Day has been hired to handle the online
division, Mary Ellen Keating, a spokeswoman for Barnes &AMP; Noble,
said, ``The idea has always been to have one agency to deal with
both parts of our business.'' As a result, she added, ``we will be
getting together with TBWA Chiat/Day to discuss our needs'' beyond
the division's ads.
</P>
<P>
   The barnesandnoble.com decision came on the heels of a victory
by the Venice, Calif., office of TBWA Chiat/Day in landing a large
account, Kinko's Inc., after a review. Billings for that
assignment, announced on Tuesday, were estimated at $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another marketer, the Clairol division of Bristol-Myers Squibb
Co., expanded its relationship with Intuition Group in New York by
naming the agency to introduce a hair color brand to be called
Revitalique. Billings were estimated at $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Intuition Group, a unit of WPP Group PLC, was awarded the
assignment after a two-month review that also included another
Clairol roster agency, Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in New York, part of
True North Communications. Intuition Group already handles
advertising for two other Clairol brands, Nice 'n Easy and Natural
Instincts' Exotic.
</P>
<P>
   Another review that ended Wednesday involved Cargill Inc. in
Minneapolis, the international marketer, processor and distributor
of agricultural, food, financial and industrial products that is
the world's largest privately held conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill selected Martin/Williams Advertising in Minneapolis as
the first agency to handle its corporate advertising account.
Billings were estimated at $10 million to $20 million. The six-week
review also included undisclosed agencies. Martin/Williams, which
is part of Omnicom, will create a campaign intended to develop the
Cargill corporate identity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   3Dfx Interactive Inc. in San Jose, Calif., which markets 3D
graphics for personal computers, named Goodby, Silverstein &AMP;
Partners in San Francisco as the first agency to handle its
advertising. Though billings were not disclosed, the trade
publication Advertising Age estimated them at $20 million to $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   Goodby, Silverstein, which is also part of Omnicom, was awarded
the 3Dfx account without a review. Porter Novelli in San Francisco,
yet another Omnicom shop, will handle public relations along with
Copithorne &AMP; Bellows in San Francisco. And Red Sky Interactive in
San Francisco, which is affiliated with the Communicade interactive
division of Omnicom, will handle interactive assignments.
</P>
<P>
   And Yesawich, Pepperdine &AMP; Brown in Orlando, Fla., has been
awarded four accounts with combined billings estimated at more than
$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   One came from Renaissance Hotels and Resorts in Washington, part
of Marriott International, which named the agency to handle
advertising for individual American and Canadian properties. That
assignment, with billings estimated at more than $5 million, had
been handled by McCann-Erickson New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.,
which continues to handle brand advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Cancer Treatment Centers of America in Zion, Ill., and
Tulsa, Okla., named Yesawich, Pepperdine to handle advertising and
direct marketing, which had been handled in-house. Billings were
estimated at $7 million to $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandy Lane Resort in Barbados, West Indies, named Yesawich,
Pepperdine as the first agency to handle its account in the United
States; those billings were estimated at $2 million. And the St.
Petersburg/Clearwater Area Convention and Visitors Bureau in
Florida renamed the agency to handle its account for an additional
three years; the assignment will be handled by the St. Petersburg
office of Yesawich, Pepperdine. Billings were estimated at $5
million for each year.
</P>
<P>
   For all that activity, more big moves are expected soon,
including a decision on a review by Ernst &AMP; Young in New York for
its account, with billings estimated at $3 million. Advertising Age
reported that D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles in New York, a unit of
MacManus Group, would land the account; a decision may come
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
