<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DIFFERENT JETS _ BETTER BUT WORSE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ For the New York Jets, more so than for most
teams in most sports, living up to expectations has always been
more difficult than creating those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Just when last year's Jets were expected to qualify for the
playoffs in their season finale in Detroit, they lost. In too many
other years, just when the Jets did qualify for the playoffs or
were expected to win a big game, they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having soared to a 9-7 record in Bill Parcells' first
season as coach following the 1-15 disaster of two seasons ago, the
Jets' expectations are suddenly high again: make another run at the
playoffs, if not surely qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But will they? Or can they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the expectations are, I've got mine,'' Parcells was
saying Wednesday as his team gathered for training camp. ``And
they're higher than most people's.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was not about to be specific. He knows better than to
put a number on his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Jets followers are still smiling over what Parcells on Wednesday
described as ``a miracle last year; you won't see that again in 10
years in this league.'' But whatever their expectations are, don't
base them on what last year's Jets accomplished. These Jets are
different with a different (and more difficult) schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Different quarterback (Glenn Foley), different running back
(Curtis Martin), different fullback (Jerald Sowell), three
different starters on the offensive line (center Kevin Mawae, left
guard Todd Burger, right tackle Siupeli Malamala), and three
different starters on defense (left tackle Jason Ferguson, right
end Anthony Pleasant and free safety Raymond Austin).
</P>
<P>
   Of those nine players, only Martin and Mawae are proven pros.
The others, even Foley, are unproven.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not a question of these different Jets living up to the
expectations created by last year's Jets as it is these different
Jets creating some expectations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   With a schedule that includes an opener in San Francisco and a
visit to Kansas City, these Jets might be a better team than last
year's Jets and yet not have as good a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent and potential is like horsepower in a car,'' Parcells
said. ``Somebody's got to come in and step on the gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Be assured that Parcells will step on the gas, but the Jets
could get stuck in their own division, again. For all the fun of
last year's 9-7 record, the Jets were only 2-6 in the American
Conference East, beating only the Patriots and the Colts. Against
nondivision opponents, the Jets were 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Patriots won't be as good without Martin. Maybe the
Dolphins won't be as good as Dan Marino ages. Maybe the Bills won't
be as good without Marv Levy as coach and maybe the Colts won't be
as good with a young Peyton Manning at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not as if the Jets know how good they will be,
especially with the uncertainty at quarterback. When two-a-day
workouts begin Thursday, Foley will take more snaps than Vinny
Testaverde, signed as a backup following Neil O'Donnell's release
in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for Foley,'' Parcells said. ``He's feisty. He's
got a little cowboy in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of the coach's assessment, Foley smiled and said, ``That's
better than spunky,'' another word used to describe him last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Foley added: ``I grew up in a family of four boys. You have to
be feisty.''
</P>
<P>
   In 25 possessions as the Jets' quarterback last season, Foley
generated 10 scores _ six touchdowns, four field goals _ for a 40
percent average. In contrast, O'Donnell generated only a 32 percent
average in 159 possessions with 48 scores: 24 touchdowns, 24 field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``And playing games that mean something in December,'' Foley
said, ``we got a little taste of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley didn't get a taste, though. He was hobbling on a damaged
knee in December after having had shoulder surgery in 1995. But
that's why, on Parcells' orders, he has bulked up to 220 pounds,
with about 12 pounds of muscle. Wednesday he was wearing a size XXL
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits better,'' he said, smiling. ``I wore an XL last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Jets want, of course, for Glenn Foley and everybody
else, is a XXXIII shirt, as in the Super Bowl on Jan. 31, 1999, in
Miami. But that's too much to expect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
