<HEADLINE>
CHINESE GYMNAST PARALYZED IN WARMUP FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The 17-year-old Chinese gymnast left paralyzed
after landing on her head while warming up for a Goodwill Games
vault competition was in guarded condition Wednesday at the Nassau
County Medical Center, able to speak and with some movement in her
arms but unable to move her legs.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Sang Lan _ the 1997 Chinese national champion in
the vault _ would walk again, a doctor treating her said that while
he remains optimistic, ``I'm still going to say (it's) unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Leone, her attending physician, whose specialty is
orthopedic spinal surgery, said Sang was able to flex her elbows,
extend her wrists, and feel her shoulders Wednesdayand was aware of
her situation. ``She understands that she has a very serious
condition,'' he said. ``She is very frustrated about not being able
to move her legs. But I have to tell you, she really hasn't cried
much. She's a very tough young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is an incomplete injury, meaning that certain parts
of the spinal cord work while others do not, some improvement in
her condition can be expected, Leone said, although there is no way
to know how much. ``It's a very unstable injury; it's
unpredictable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements are being made to bring Sang's parents to her
bedside from Ningbo, about 40 miles from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   The five remaining Chinese gymnasts planned to continue
competing last night, despite being shaken. ``They assure me they
will do their best,'' said Tu Mingde, secretary general of the
Chinese Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sang's injury was diagnosed as a fracture dislocation of
vertebrae C-6 on C-7, essentially a shift of one bone into another.
She was in traction Wednesday, being treated with steroids and
undergoing further tests after having her spinal column realigned.
After waiting several days for the swelling to go down, she is
expected to undergo surgery to fuse the vertebrae. Leone said Sang
would also be treated with a nerve-regenerating agent.
</P>
<P>
   Leone said Sang could return to China a week after surgery to
continue her recuperation closer to home, ``where she will probably
be able to make better gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened Tuesday night at the Nassau Veterans
Memorial Coliseum while Sang was warming up with what was described
as a ``very simple'' movement, a handspring off the vaulting horse.
But her body rotated too far, according to a witness, and instead
of landing on her feet, she hit the mat headfirst.
</P>
<P>
   First to reach her was Octavian Belu, the Romanian national
coach who was waiting for one of his gymnasts to warm up after
Sang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard bad sound,'' said Belu, like the crack of a broken
leg.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly warned those rushing to her aid not to touch her and
asked her through an interpreter if she could feel anything. ``She
said, `I don't feel my legs,''' Belu reported, although ``she had
no face like afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The warmup movement Sang was attempting, often referred to as a
vault ``timer,'' is a handspring on the vaulting horse performed by
even a Level 5 gymnast. (It is not until progressing past Level 10
that a gymnast is termed ``elite.'') Although there were no
spotters to catch her should anything go awry, Bart Conner, the
1984 Olympic gold medalist who's here as a broadcaster for TBS,
said Wednesday that spotters wouldn't be considered necessary
during a simple warmup. ``It's a common routine that had a sad and
unlucky result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Team leader Yuxin Zhao said Sang told the Chinese coach, Liu
Quinling, that ``even she did not know how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sang's severe injury is not the first at the elite level of the
sport. In 1980, Elena Moukina, a Soviet gymnast who had won the
world championships two years earlier, broke her neck in practice
and became a paraplegic. In 1988, US gymnast Julissa Gomez was 15
when she broke her neck during a practice vault at the World Sports
Fair in Tokyo. She died several years later of complications.
</P>
<P>
   Still, members of the gymnastics community Wednesday defended
the safety record of their sport. ``I can assure you that the meet,
the matting, and the equipment all were in complete compliance with
the international rules,'' said Kathy Scanlon, president of USA
Gymnastics. While expressing sorrow, she added, ``But as sometimes
happens in sports and in life, accidents do occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Abie Grossfeld, who coaches at Southern Connecticut State
University and has been involved in gymnastics for decades, also
cautioned that gymnastics should not be judged too harshly because
of Tuesday's accident. ``It wasn't a very dangerous thing she was
doing,'' he emphasized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
