<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CHEMICAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOPS LIST FOR POTENTIAL OF A CHEMICAL ACCIDENT DISASTER,
GROUP SAYS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEFANIE ASIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Harris County ranks first in the country for the
potential of a chemical accident disaster, an environmental
watchdog group reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.1 million
people and is the largest county in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Park, an industrial city of 30,000 people about 10 miles
east of downtown Houston, ranked second in the United States for
ZIP codes at risk for such a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The report, published by the U.S. Public Interest Research Group
and the National Environmental Law Center, considered the volume of
dangerous chemicals, the nearby population and the type of
chemicals among other factors, said Andrew Thompson, the PIRG
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report should sound an alarm in Harris County,'' he said.
``Citizens have a right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on their calculations of ``worst-case scenarios,'' Harris
County and Texas ranked No. 1 in the potential for danger of a
killer toxic cloud. Los Angeles was No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Other Texas counties making the top 50 list were Brazoria,
Calhoun, Dallas, Galveston, Jefferson and Nueces.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that 2.6 million people in Texas live within a
range of a toxic cloud that could result from a chemical accident
near their home.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thompson could not cite specific safety troubles at any
plant, he said companies need to redesign facilities to be safer.
</P>
<P>
   These companies need to prevent such an accident from happening,
he said, even though it could be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not a pipe dream,'' he said. ``It's public health
we're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the East Harris County Manufacturer's
Association, representing 100 plants, termed the report as
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Jack Coe said there is some risk of chemical accidents
because of the number of plants, but companies are continually
working on making the plants safer. He said from time to time there
are ``nuisance'' releases of chemicals into the air, but none as
serious as PIRG warns against.
</P>
<P>
   Coe said the plants also are working toward reducing the number
of those releases. When possible, firms also are using alternative
chemicals to replace dangerous ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have demonstrated that we can safely manage risks
associated with our operations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said U.S. PIRG thinks the public should demand more and
that the federal government ought to have higher standards for such
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for companies in Texas to stop downplaying
toxic risks and start giving complete information about potential
accidents,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies representing the most dangerous potential for chemical
release are chemical manufacturing, food products, primary metal
industries, pulp and paper and fabricated metal products, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
