<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMERS-GENES-BOS &LR;      07-22 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-GENES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GENETIC DISCOVERIES ADVANCE ALZHEIMER'S RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: A2M-2 and apoE-4 are cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two discoveries have moved scientists toward solving the riddle
of what causes Alzheimer's disease, which devastates memory and
personality among an estimated four million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston research group said Wednesday they it found a gene
variant that more than triples a person's risk of developing
late-onset Alzheimer's compared to siblings without the gene.
Thirty percent of the US population may carry the newly discovered
gene, called A2M-2.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery suggests the possibility of a drug mimicking the
gene's normal function, scientists said, protecting susceptible
individuals against brain damage or perhaps even reversing it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers at the University of Texas in San Antonio
have revised scientists' understanding of the only other
established gene for late-onset Alzheimer's, called apoE-4. That
gene, carried by four to eight percent of Americans, does not
determine whether an individual is likely to develop the disease,
as scientists thought. But those who have it are likely to get
Alzheimer's symptoms at a somewhat earlier age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The apoE-4 gene affects `when' and doesn't affect `whether,'''
said Dr. Deborah Blacker of the Massachusetts General Hospital, a
member of the group that discovered the new late-onset gene. On the
other hand, A2M-2 affects ``whether'' but not ``when.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports on both findings will appear in the August issue of the
journal Nature Genetics. The findings were released early to
coincide with presentations at an international Alzheimer's meeting
in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Much of scientists' excitement about the new late-onset
Alzheimer's gene stems from the fact that scientists already know a
good deal about its normal function and the protein it makes. Often
when researchers find a disease-linked gene they don't know what it
does, and sometimes they can't even identify a specific gene but
only a ``region of interest'' on the chromosome where the gene
resides _ the equivalent of locating the haystack but not the
needle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very exciting,'' commented Dr. Steven Moldin of the
National Institute of Mental Health, ``because it implicates a
precise part of a specific gene, and the biology of that gene gives
us a lot of guidance and hints of what to look for'' in deciphering
the Alzheimer's process.
</P>
<P>
   Moldin's institute, a federal agency, funds a repository of
tissue and data from families with Alzheimer's disease, which the
MGH group used to screen for the new gene.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven DeKoskey of the University of Pittsburgh, who chairs
the national Alzheimer's Association scientific advisory council,
predicted the gene variant's discovery will illuminate the
``cascade of abnormality'' behind the disease and ``how we can turn
that toward therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   The normal version of A2M, which is short for alpha-2
macroglobulin, is one of the so-called ``housekeeping genes'' that
cells need to keep their internal affairs orderly. It is a key
player in the brain's toxic waste-disposal system _ a role that
dovetails with current ideas about how Alzheimer's disease clogs
the brain with a buildup of abnormal proteins.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the gene variant is missing five
crucial genetic elements called ``base-pairs'' out of the tens of
thousands that make up the entire gene. That makes it less
efficient at its garbage-clearing task, leaving those who carry the
gene at greater risk of the debris accumulation that characterizes
Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of this protein as a big sponge,'' said Rudolph E.
Tanzi of the MGH's genetics and aging unit, who presented the
findings Wednesday in Amsterdam. ``It soaks up excess proteins and
takes them to a receptor called LRP. The receptor takes them to
structures in the cell called lyosomes, which are like garbage
disposers that grind them up so they can be disposed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigating 310 families afflicted with Alzheimer's, the MGH
group found that individuals who had the A2M gene variant developed
the disease 3.6 times more often than siblings who did not. That is
the same magnitude of risk that researchers earlier found among
individuals who carry the apoE-4 variant rather than the normal
form of that gene.
</P>
<P>
   Two other labs have reproduced the MGH group's findings, using
cells from the same families. But researchers said it will be
important for other labs to replicate the new findings among
different families, using the same type of analysis, a new method
called family-based association.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzi, Blacker and others stressed the A2M gene variant, like
apoE-4, will not be useful as a tool for screening individuals for
their risk of developing Alzheimer's, at least not in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have one of these variants or the other, or both, and
escape Alzheimer's,'' Tanzi said. ``If someone told me I was
positive for both, I would not despair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
