<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE BREAK IN MIDEAST NEGOTIATING FREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A flurry of diplomatic and political contacts and
press leaks raised strong expectations Wednesday of a long-awaited
break in the negotiating freeze between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is afoot remains indistinct in the crossfire of
hints and denials, but Jerusalem is abuzz with reports of
high-level contacts among Israelis, Palestinians, Jordanians,
Americans and Egyptians, and a new sense of urgency from Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest indication of movement came from Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, whose meeting on Sunday with a senior
Palestinian negotiator, Mahmoud Abbas, was the first such contact
in months.
</P>
<P>
   Though the meeting produced only an agreement to hold further
meetings, Mordechai urged Washington Wednesday to send a senior
official to help bridge the gaps. Later his spokesman, Avi
Benayahu, said he expected that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, would meet with Mordechai as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined Mordechai's appeal. ``We are getting to
a point where we need to know whether the parties themselves are
committed to trying to resolve their differences and move
forward,'' said Michael McCurry, the White House spokesman. ``We
cannot make the decisions that they have to make for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians also denied that any further meeting with
Mordechai was in the offing, and all senior Palestinian officials,
including Abbas, insisted that no progress had been made. The
official Palestinian position has been that Abbas met Mordechai
only to learn whether the Israelis had accepted proposals made by
the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But Abbas made a quick trip to Jordan Wednesday to meet with
Crown Prince Hassan, and there were reports that the Jordanian
foreign minister, Jawad al-Anani, had met with both Arafat and
Netanyahu over the weekend. Arafat also flew to Cairo to meet with
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   For several months now, the State Department has been trying to
win agreement to a package that would include an Israeli withdrawal
from another 13 percent of the West Bank, and a Palestinian
commitment to concrete measures to combat terrorism, extradite or
jail suspected terrorists sought by Israel and revise the
Palestinian National Covenant to exclude any call for Israel's
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have said they accept the American plan, but
until now the Israelis have resisted a 13 percent withdrawal and
have set stringent conditions for the Palestinians, like the
convening of the full Palestinian National Council to adopt a new
charter.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports in the Israeli press, Netanyahu has
proposed a compromise under which he would cede the 13 percent if a
quarter of it became a ``national park'' in which the Palestinians
could not build. He has also reportedly extended the time frame for
revising the Palestinian charter.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority has refused to respond to these
demands publicly, insisting that having accepted the American
proposals, it is awaiting Israel's response.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mordechai's request Wednesday that the United States intercede
was evidently based on the expectation that the Americans could
persuade the Palestinians to budge. But after waiting so long for a
decision by Israel, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
reportedly disinclined to resume direct mediation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense among Israeli politicians and commentators,
however, that after all these months, Netanyahu cannot delay a
decision further, and now needs to close a deal by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   There are several sources of pressure on the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament is preparing to leave on its summer break at month's
end, and Netanyahu has pledged to put any agreement to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the political pressures are rising. Leaders of
the Third Way party have publicly declared they will quit the
coalition if he does reach an accord. And President Ezer Weizman
created a national stir by calling for early elections, or at least
a government of national unity, to break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the prime minister's office insist privately that
he is genuinely anxious to make a deal but that he needs an
agreement he can present to his right-wing constituents as meeting
his promise of ``peace with security.'' He also has to avoid the
impression that he is accepting an American proposal that he had
resisted for so long and at such political cost, and so his hope is
to reach an agreement directly with Arafat, the officials add.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Arafat is prepared to deal only with the
Americans, and let the Americans deal with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
