<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE STONE WALL OF SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It only took 10 or 15 years for the Police Department
to find out that some of its officers had set up light housekeeping
with a madam and her prostitutes in a brothel not far from Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good job,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The episode may have
been sordid and regrettable, but it convinced him, he said, that
the Police Department does ``a tremendous job'' monitoring itself.
Kudos all around.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder how many other scandals are being uprooted
with similar dispatch by the department's crack Internal Affairs
investigators. If we're lucky we'll find out about them around the
end of the first decade of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to be a rat, but I'll tell you the truth, the
whole thing makes me sick,'' said an officer who spent Wednesday's
hot and humid rush hour helping pedestrians navigate the chaos that
resulted from Tuesday's construction accident in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, who asked that his name not be used, said: ``I know
guys that are up to this and that. But the public thinks we're all
scum, which is not true. I think the good guys are getting a raw
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   They sure are, and it's because the Police Department has proved
again and again that it will not police itself, and has fought like
the Allies on the beaches of Normandy against the creation of a
responsible outside agency to investigate police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The Mollen commission, in its report on police corruption that
was issued in July 1994, said: ``From the beginning of our
investigation we were struck by the difference between what the
commission was uncovering about the state of corruption and
corruption controls within the department, and what the department
was publicly _ and privately _ stating about itself. The department
maintained that police corruption was not a serious problem, and
consisted primarily of sporadic, isolated incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said the authors of the report: ``The commission found
that the corruption problems facing the department are far more
serious than top commanders in the department would admit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department will never voluntarily open its doors and
let the public in on the full extent of corruption, brutality and
other criminal activity in its ranks. Every now and then the door
is forced open a little and we get a whiff of the stench within.
But that's all.
</P>
<P>
   So the bad guys flourish and the entire department is demeaned.
Worse, criminal behavior goes unpunished and victims of police
misconduct are most often left without redress _ and are sometimes
unjustly punished themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and his police commissioner, Howard Safir, are the
latest in the long, long line of top city officials who have been
willing to close their eyes and cover their ears when it comes to
police misconduct. And their aggressive opposition to an outside
monitor is clear evidence that they don't want anyone else homing
in on police activity that is illegal, shameful, often brutal and
at times murderous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of creating an atmosphere where we look the other way,
we should be demanding zero tolerance for police misconduct as we
demand zero tolerance for offenses by the general public,'' said
City Councilman Sheldon Leffler, who is the chairman of the
Council's Public Safety Committee and an advocate of an independent
police monitoring agency.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler said in an interview that he believed ``most of the
mayor's positions are good positions, good government positions.''
But he said the mayor's ``deference'' to the police had put him on
the wrong side of the independent monitor issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people,'' said Leffler, ``and particularly the police,
cannot be counted on to use their best efforts to uncover their own
dirty laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mollen commission, referring to supervisors within the
Police Department, used the term ``willful blindness'' to describe
their eagerness to remain ignorant of conduct that was corrupt and
often brutal. Giuliani and Safir are evidence that ``willful
blindness'' is not limited to irresponsible mid-level supervisors,
but is a characteristic easily found at the very highest levels of
command.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
