u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-JONES-BOS &LR;      07-22 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL REJECTS EX-PILOT FOR AIR FORCE SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former fighter pilot who was hailed by supporters
as ``an American success story'' was rejected Wednesday by a Senate
panel as President Clinton's nominee to become the first black
secretary of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing blow to Clinton, his nomination of Daryl L.
Jones, a Florida state senator, collapsed in the Senate Armed
Services Committee amid allegations that Jones lied about his
military record and engaged in improper business activities.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination died on a 9-9 vote, marking the first time in
recent history the Senate panel has rejected a president's choice
to head a branch of the military.
</P>
<P>
   The snub marked the worst setback for a Pentagon nominee since
the Democratic-controlled Senate rejected President Bush's choice
of former Texas Senator John G. Tower to be defense secretary in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country has lost a fine opportunity,'' said the
committee's Republican chairman, Senator Strom Thurmond of South
Carolina, moments after the vote. ``This was a good man who had all
the qualities to make a fine Air Force secretary, and I regret this
committee did not give the full Senate a chance to vote on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's nine other GOP members bucked Thurmond to oppose
Jones, including Senators Olympia J. Snowe of Maine and Bob Smith
of New Hampshire. All eight Democrats on the committee supported
sending the nomination to the full Senate for a confirmation vote,
including Senators Edward M. Kennedy and Joseph I. Lieberman of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   However, two Democrats on the panel _ Senators Robert C. Byrd of
West Virginia and Charles S. Robb of Virginia _ indicated they
would vote against Jones's confirmation if it were to reach the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was ``clearly disappointed'' by the setback, said his
press secretary, Michael McCurry. ``We deeply regret the fact that
the full Senate will not hear the merits of the nomination,''
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Jones, 43, said none of the questions about his
honesty and integrity ``made logical sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones refrained from criticizing the committee's vote
or its nine-month investigation of him _ an exercise one senator
described as ``an incredible crucible'' _ Jones said: ``I never
really thought that I had enemies until I became nominee for
secretary of the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was valedictorian at his high school in Mississippi
before he graduated from the US Air Force Academy and became an
active-duty fighter pilot, faced the stiffest resistance to his
nomination from former members of the reserve fighter squadron unit
he later joined at Homestead Air Force Base in Florida. He was the
first black pilot in the unit's history.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of volatile hearings, the former squadron members
and others accused Jones of embellishing his flying record,
accepting flight pay he had not worked for, and wearing flight
wings he had not earned. He also was accused of wrongfully
pressuring enlisted troops to buy Amway products that he was
selling.
</P>
<P>
   Jones faced additional questions about lobbying fees he accepted
from a Florida bond firm involved in a county airport expansion.
The Senate committee received a private briefing last month from
the Securities and Exchange Commission, which has reviewed the fee
payment. Lieberman said the SEC indicated Jones was not the subject
of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Jones denied all the allegations. But the committee's
Republicans said testimony by numerous witnesses contradicting
Jones raised too many questions about his character.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force needs to have a leader of unassailable
credibility,'' Snowe said. ``Unfortunately, I came to the
conclusion that the nominee didn't bear sufficient accountability
as well as judgment to be an effective secretary of the Air Force
at this point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Warner, a Virginia Republican and former Navy
secretary, said the allegations against Jones convinced him Jones
would be ``unable to serve as a leader and inspire those who served
under him, particularly those in uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, of New Hampshire, a Vietnam-era Navy veteran, said
conflicts and contradictions in Jones's testimony caused him to
oppose promoting him to a position vital to national security.
</P>
<P>
   But Thurmond and the committee Democrats said none of the
allegations against Jones had been proven. And some Democrats said
many of the allegations were products of envy and racism generated
by former members of Jones's reserve unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who did not want him in that squadron
because he was the first African-American,'' said Senator Carl
Levin of Michigan, the panel's highest-ranking Democrat. ``Some
people decided they would oppose his career advancement, and they
kept a file on him that was unofficial and inappropriate. That led
to maintaining the drumbeat of some of these allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond said the Clinton administration did nothing substandard
in vetting Jones for the position or in advocating for him. He
described Jones simply as a victim of ``all the propaganda that
came out against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones would have succeeded Sheila E. Widnall, the first woman to
serve as Air Force secretary. She resigned last fall to return to
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Clinton must search for
a new nominee, while F. Whitten Peters continues to serve as acting
Air Force secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's supporters on the committee, aware of the Republican
opposition, asked only that his nomination be forwarded to the full
Senate without a recommendation, rather than a favorable or
unfavorable recommendation. But the panel deadlocked, killing that
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also floated the prospect of sending the nomination to the
Senate with an unfavorable recommendation. But he dropped the idea
when Republican members balked.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Kennedy said: ``The committee acted irresponsibly. On
a matter of this importance and on a nominee with the impressive
qualifications of Daryl Jones, the full Senate should have the
chance to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would return to Florida to seek reelection to the
state Senate. Leaving the Pentagon Wednesday afternoon, Jones said,
``My constituents are very supportive. I hope I am welcomed back
with open arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
