<SLUG> BC-GREAT-EXPECTATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shallow `Expectations' a Dickens of a love story _ just
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Don't be misled by the title. This isn't an
adaptation of the Dickens novel so much as a slick 1990s fantasia
on similar themes. Only instead of Miss Havisham and her ancient
wedding cake, we get Nora Dinsmoor (Anne Bancroft, waving a
cigarette holder), laying the ham on thick.
</P>
<P>
   She's the man-hating eccentric who lures blue-collar boy Finn
(the Pip figure) into her crumbling Florida mansion. There, she
pays him to be the dance partner to her snooty ward, Estella. The
boy grows up to be Ethan Hawke, madly but secretly in love with the
girl, who blossoms into Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Finn loses Estella, leaves Florida and pours himself into the
flashy art scene, funded by a mysterious patron. (He assumes it's
Dinsmoor.) And there he once again meets Estella, and the runaway
prisoner (Robert De Niro) whom he first encountered as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is as shallow as the bay water surrounding Dinsmoor's
mansion. Or the backbiting art circles the adult Finn enters. But
director Alfonso Cuaron, who's mad for the color green, shoots with
silky finesse. It's a guilty pleasure. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERMAINEDUPRI-COX     07-22 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERMAINEDUPRI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hit producer Dupri scores in his own right
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who's listened to the radio should be laughing at those
who've doubted that Jermaine Dupri could make a hit record for
himself. He's been doing it for almost the past decade for Xscape
(``Just Kickin' It''), Da Brat (``Funk-dafied'') and Mariah Carey
(``Always Be My Baby''). He's doing it now for Usher (``My Way'')
and Jagged Edge (``Gotta Be''). And the 25-year-old,
million-selling College Park-based producer has finally done it on
his solo debut.
</P>
<P>
   Fashioned like a Quincy Jones project _ all guest artists, no
single with Dupri alone _ ``Life in 1472'' is one of the better rap
albums released this year. With Jay-Z (``Money Ain't a Thing''),
Mase (``You Get Dealt Wit'') and Too Short (``Jazzy (expletive))''
contributing, some might ask, ``How could it not be?'' Well,
nothing is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   And give Dupri some credit. That he can keep up with talent of
such varying deliveries and tones testifies to his ability not only
to produce a good record but rap on one.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat, though: The language is rougher than one might
expect from the guy first known as the producer of kid rap act Kris
Kross (``Jump''). Intermittently, Dupri uses the ``b'' and ``n''
words as terms of endearment and derision. Guess that's how he's
living in 1472.
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Life in 1472
</P>
<P>
   (The Original Soundtrack)''
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Dupri.
</P>
<P>
   So So Def Records.
</P>
<P>
   15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``Life
</P>
<P>
   in 1472'' will make 1998 the year producer Dupri has a hit with
his own name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
