<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIREVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Other videos in stores this week
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``U.S. Marshals'' (PG-13) _ Tommy Lee Jones returns as U.S.
Marshal Sam Gerard in this fine sequel to ``The Fugitive.'' This
time, Gerard is on the trail of an ex-CIA operative implicated in
two murders, played by Wesley Snipes. While this installment lacks
some of the emotional resonance of the original, it offers an
exhilaratingly detailed look at what it takes to be a fed. Through
it all, Jones attacks his role like a pit bull. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Days in September'' (R) _ This Oscar-nominated,
fact-based drama from director Bruno Barreto (``Dona Flor and Her
Two Husbands'') is the emotionally complex tale of the young
Brazilian idealists who kidnapped the U.S. ambassador (Alan Arkin)
in 1969, hoping to draw attention to their country's military
regime. The film is a melancholy tribute to the collision between
idealism and brutal reality. Its centerpiece is the growing
friendship between Arkin (excellent as always) and his student
captor (Pedro Cardoso), who may be the one assigned to shoot the
ambassador if things go wrong. In Portuguese and English, with
subtitles. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   ``Kissing a Fool'' (R) _ Two lips up. David Schwimmer plays a
smarmy sportscaster who enlists his best friend (Jason Lee) in a
scheme to ``test'' his new wife's fidelity. The movie follows a
predictable romantic-comedy path, with a few fresh twists. But fans
of Schwimmer's puppy-cute ``Friends'' character, Ross, will be
astonished at how easily the actor slips into the guise of a
not-so-nice guy. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   ``The Education of Little Tree'' (PG) _ An unassuming, quietly
wise family picture. Set in Tennessee during the Depression, it's
the story of a half-Cherokee, half-Caucasian orphan named Little
Tree (Joseph Ashton) who goes to live with his grandpa (James
Cromwell), a backwoods mountain man, and grandma, his Native
American wife (Tantoo Cardinal). These two teach the boy everything
from moonshining to making a spiritual connection with nature.
Little Tree also learns harsher lessons about prejudice. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel
</P>
<P>
   ``Krippendorf's Tribe''
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) _ Not worth discovering. Richard Dreyfuss plays a
widowed anthropology professor who has spent all his grant money on
the care and feeding of his three children. When it's time to
deliver his lecture on a legendary missing tribe from New Guinea,
he enlists the kids to cake themselves with mud and body paint and
perform for his video camera in the back yard. The setup is primed
for comic skewering of academia and the media, but it's full of
diluted jokes and impossible situations. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
