<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MINIREVIEWS-COX     07-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MINIREVIEWS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Mini Music Reviews
</P>
<P>
   cROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Won't Wait''
</P>
<P>
   Rancid. Epitaph. 22 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons with the Clash are de rigueur in any mention of
Rancid. The California quartet has always displayed its influences
like a tattered badge of punk honor. The derivative part is
beginning to change, however, as Rancid grows into a more
consistent and distinctive unit. The songs here carry more weight
than on previous outings, while the band's spring-loaded tightness
is wound even tighter. Rancid's widening scope gets a little help
with appearances by the Specials' Lynval Golden and Neville Staples
and dance hall reggae biggie Buju Banton. These scrappy neo-punks
have yet to match the early work of their primary influence, but
give 'em enough rope and they just might deliver something that
good next time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``People''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Jones. Ark 21. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   What with all things '80s being once again in vogue, it was only
a matter of time before Howard Jones, the purveyor of such sunny
synth-pop hits as ``New Song'' and ``Things Can Only Get Better,''
resurfaced. New Wave's answer to Deepak Chopra may have tamed his
famed rooster mane, but his cloyingly upbeat outlook remains
intact. ``Every woman, child and man / Has the power in their
hands,'' Jones asserts on ``Let the People Have Their Say,'' which
bops along to the same perky synth groove that propelled many of
his past hits. You'll hum along, and you may temporarily feel
better, but you may hate yourself in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   URBAN
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothin' But the Hotness in '98 ''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Boy Records. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Ever the hype man, rapper, producer and Bad Boy Records
President Sean ``Puffy'' Combs uses this unique effort to do some
smart promoting. The unreleased artists on Combs' Fuzz Bubble
label, Tanya Blount and Jerome, get serious positioning alongside
bigger and better-known labelmates Mase, Total and 112. But the
only new single from the established artists comes from Total, a
harmonic break from the trio's usual grit called ``When Boy Meets
Girl.'' So Blount (``Through the Rain'') gets to introduce her
husky, Toni Braxton-like vocals on ``I Love Him'' with relatively
little competition; passable teenage vocalist Jerome squanders this
chance for early notice. (This album is available only at
FootAction.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sound of Music''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Broadway cast.
</P>
<P>
   RCA Victor. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Something's not quite right in the city of Salzburg. Maria
(Rebecca Luker) is stiff; Captain von Trapp (Michael Siberry) is
wimpy. At least the children have their do-re-mi's down pat. This
new ``Sound of Music,'' bankrolled by Hallmark, is greeting-card
slick but lacking in warmth. It's not terrible, just uninspiring.
Granted, Maria's habit is not an easy one to slip into, but as she
goes, so goes the show _ and the recording. Broadway regular Luker
isn't up to the task. She has neither the buoyancy of Mary Martin
nor the crystalline high notes of Julie Andrews. And it's a shame.
These old hills are still alive with the sound of music, but this
go-round, they're breathing kind of heavy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``N'dea Davenport''
</P>
<P>
   N'dea Davenport. V2. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Well, welcome back N'dea. What has it been, four years since you
left acid jazz faves the Brand New Heavies? It was a move that left
many wondering whether that vocal power surging through ``Dream
Come True'' could sustain its momentum whenever you decided to
resurface, but never mind all that. The full-bodied, bluesy and
horns-based ``Save Your Love for Me'' affirms that you're still
just as gorgeous vocally. As on your BNH standout ``Stay This
Way,'' you can still take us there spiritually. And if we don't
mind a few too many instances of pretty and eclectic filler, we
should run out and get this long-awaited solo debut.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
