</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANCIGRIFFITH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friends help Griffith perfect her blend of country, folk
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- With a voice as big and clear as a blue Texas sky,
Nanci Griffith is one of new country music's most bankable
crossover commodities. Straddling the line between folk and
country, she has spent two decades pushing the limits of new
acoustic music with her semi-autobiographical songs of loners,
losers and lovers.
</P>
<P>
   But she hasn't let her newfound stardom eclipse her roots. For
the second time in five years, Griffith returns to the wellspring
of her songwriting with a collection of covers _ performed with a
who's who of folk and country music _ that tips a hat to her heroes
and influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Voices, Too'' is a sparkling follow-up to 1993's Grammy
Award-winning ``Other Voices, Other Rooms.'' And, like its
predecessor, the sequel combines traditionals and neoclassics, all
anchored by the Austin, Texas, native's strong, effortless vocals
and intricate guitar work. The guest list features 67 musicians,
including Emmylou Harris, Lyle Lovett, Steve Earle, Guy Clark,
Richard Thompson, Lucinda Williams and John Prine, and is backed by
Griffith's Blue Moon Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights include fresh retreads of Richard Thompson's
rollicking ``Wall of Death'' and Sandy Denny's wistful ``Where Does
the Time Go?'' She celebrates the godfathers of American folk, with
rousing covers of Pete Seeger's ``Deportee'' and Woody Guthrie's
``If I Had a Hammer.'' And she delivers velvety duets with Williams
on Bobby Ferguson's gorgeous ``Wings of a Dove'' and Lovett on the
ballad ``Dress of Laces.''
</P>
<P>
   There are places where Griffith goes over the top with
we-are-the-world overkill (37 musicians pile on for ``Wasn't That a
Mighty Storm''). But, overall, this is a strong addition to the
14-album Griffith catalog: a collection of chestnuts and new gems
polished to shiny brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   FOLK-COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Voices, Too
</P>
<P>
   (A Trip Back to Bountiful)''
</P>
<P>
   Nanci Griffith. Elektra/Warner Bros. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Folkapaloosa, with a rhythm-and-country twist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
