<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RANDYSCRUGGS-COX     07-22 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDYSCRUGGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rich `Crown of Jewels' does Scruggs' family tree proud
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As the son of bluegrass legend Earl Scruggs, Randy
Scruggs grew up in a home where members of the Carter Family and
other musicians came and went, and he had carte blanche to roam
Nashville's recording studios and rehearsal halls. So being around
talented musicians should be routine for him. But there's nothing
blase about his fleet acoustic and electric flat-picking and
singing on these 12 collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly psyched by his father, Vince Gill, Emmylou Harris, Iris
Dement, Joan Osborne, Trisha Yearwood, Bruce Hornsby, Travis Tritt
and others, Scruggs reaches a magical level. ``I wanted to
collaborate with the artists who influenced and have helped me,''
he says from his Nashville home, ``and it was a real gift to have
the freedom to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning cut is ``Passin' Thru,'' about life's travails
and its brevity, written with Johnny Cash and performed with
Osborne. ``That's something I wanted to say in song and it's
something Johnny has spoken about in songs,'' Scruggs says. It has
the drive of a Bob Dylan song and vocals reminiscent of Dylan's
work with Joan Baez.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Dement give new life to ``Wildwood Flower,'' while
``I Wanna Be Loved Back,'' with Yearwood, calls to mind the emotion
of love songs recorded by Earl Thomas Conley, who helped Scruggs
write it. Tritt dusts off Poco's ``Amie'' and gives it a gentle,
pleasing ride. The title track, a song about pain being universal,
features Hornsby's distinctive keyboards and vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Other cuts are equally impressive, making this talent-rich
collection remarkably strong from start to finish. No skippable
cuts here.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Crown
</P>
<P>
   of Jewels''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Scruggs. Reprise.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Welcome to a world of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
