<HEADER>
A8112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIELBERG-RINGEL-COX     07-22 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIELBERG-RINGEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spielberg has no monopoly on great WWII flicks
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- They are A-lists to end all A-lists.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks, Matt Damon and Steven Spielberg. Sean Penn, Nick
Nolte, George Clooney and legendary, long-vanished director
Terrence Malick (``Badlands,'' ``Days of Heaven'').
</P>
<P>
   All this and World War II?
</P>
<P>
   You betcha. Coming soon to a theater near you: the Last Great
War. The assault begins Friday with Spielberg's spectacular
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Malick's eagerly anticipated ``The Thin
Red Line'' is due this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone more interested in the war at home _ i.e., on
video, laserdisc or DVD _ here are a few of my favorites. And
apologies upfront to fans of John Wayne. I always preferred the
Duke in westerns or ``The Quiet Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Red One'' (1980): B-movie master Samuel Fuller
rummages through his old-soldier's trunk to bring us the blood,
guts and glory of the grunts' war as Sgt. Lee Marvin leads some raw
recruits (including Mark Hamill) from North Africa to
Czechoslovakia. Marvin, a former Marine and full-time drinker in
real life, took to the movie uniform all too well. When an
assistant director tried to help him with his costume, he slammed
the man against a wall and snarled, ``Never touch a soldier's
leggings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope and Glory'' (1987): John Boorman's magnificent,
irresistible comic memoir about growing up in London during the
Blitz. This is a salute to British pluck filtered through the
impish chaos of childhood's priorities. Boorman wanted to make the
film before his elderly mum died, so he had to pass on a little
something called ``Fatal Attraction.'' As it happened, both movies
were nominated for an Oscar; both lost to ``The Last Emperor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Midnight Clear'' (1992): A heartbreakingly effective,
eloquently devastating comment on the insanity _ and odd
brotherhood _ of war. In the winter of '44, a squad of GIs
(including Ethan Hawke and Gary Sinise) is sent to occupy a
deserted chateau and report on enemy movements. Director Keith
Gordon hits just the right tone: harrowing hyper-realism mixed with
the delicate mystery of a Christmas wish.``The Bridge on the River
Kwai'' (1957): David Lean's masterful Oscar winner about delusion,
heroism and glory-mongering in a Japanese prison camp. Alec
Guinness is the imperious British officer who will build his bridge
come hell, high water or William Holden, who has orders to blow the
thing up. Sessue Hayakawa is Guinness' doppelganger _ the
inflexible but somehow admirable camp commandant. This is one of
Guinness' signature roles, yet he turned it down three times. And
he wasn't even first choice: Lean preferred Noel Coward or Charles
Laughton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attack!'' (1956): Director Robert Aldrich had more
action-packed fun with another favorite, ``The Dirty Dozen.'' But
here, he uses the Battle of the Bulge as the backdrop for a deadly
clash between a craven commander (Eddie Albert) and a heroic
subordinate (Jack Palance). While Aldrich portrays the war as
unquestionably just and its true heroes as unassailable, he also
savages a system rife with politics and self-interest. This is one
of the movies Spielberg showed to Hanks before shooting ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Be or Not to Be'' (1942): Ernst Lubitsch applied his famous
comic ``touch'' to this daring and, in its time, controversial
farce about a band of Polish actors, led by Jack Benny (!), working
to sabotage their Nazi conquerors. A month before the film's
premiere, Benny's beautiful, talented co-star, Carole Lombard, died
in a plane crash while promoting war bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I Won the War'' (1967): ``A Hard Day's Night'' and
``Help!'' director Richard Lester went solo with John Lennon and
made this gruesomely inventive, absurdist black comedy about
British soldiers sent on a mission to build a cricket pitch behind
enemy lines. And look closely at that spindly lieutenant; he's
Michael Crawford, later reborn as Broadway's ``The Phantom of the
Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Years of Our Lives'' (1946): Coming home has never
been depicted better than it was in William Wyler's Oscar-winning
saga of three veterans facing new battles on the home front.
Hollywood pros Fredric March, Myrna Loy, Teresa Wright and Dana
Andrews are joined by real-life veteran and double amputee Harold
Russell, who took home two Academy Awards. But he wasn't the only
one who knew the territory. When he accepted the project, Wyler
said, ``I've come home twice myself from war, and I know just how
these fellows feel. No man can walk into the house after two or
three years and pick up his life as before.''
</P>
<P>
   And lest we forget:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Dictator,'' ``Patton,'' ``The Dirty Dozen,''
``Mister Roberts,'' ``The Great Escape,'' ``Casablanca,'' ``Hail
the Conquering Hero,'' ``The Guns of Navarone,'' ``The Last
Metro,'' ``The Victors,'' ``Home of the Brave,'' ``From Here to
Eternity,'' ``The Night of the Shooting Stars,'' ``Stalag 17,''
``Das Boot,'' ``The Elusive Corporal'' and ``Stairway to Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAILWIND-RESPONSE-COX     07-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILWIND-RESPONSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fired producers: CNN was bullied to retract report
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a blistering critique of CNN, two producers fired
for their roles in the Tailwind nerve gas story stood behind their
original report and blamed the network's top management for
``caving into pressure'' from government officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, April Oliver and Jack Smith said the network's
decision to retract and apologize for their story, which first
aired June 7 on ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' had nothing to do with
reporting flaws in their work outlined in a subsequent
investigation conducted by noted lawyer Floyd Abrams and CNN
counsel David Kohler.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Smith said, CNN's backpedaling on the story was a
``corporate calculation'' by CNN Chairman Tom Johnson and President
Richard Kaplan, whom they described as being more concerned with
having a working relationship with the Pentagon than standing up
for the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest disappointment was CNN's cave,'' Smith said. ``I
can take a firing, but it was difficult to watch CNN executives
collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who appeared Wednesday with Oliver at a Freedom Forum
discussion here, also contended that Johnson was bullied by former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and officials at the Joint
Chiefs of Staff. ``Tom Johnson values his comfort with the
Pentagon,'' Smith said
</P>
<P>
   CNN spokesman Steve Haworth said, ``We did not cave to pressure
from the Pentagon or veterans groups or anyone else. The only
pressure we felt was that which was exerted by an extremely
powerful and clear report by Floyd Abrams that proved to us that
the Tailwind story could not stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Since retracting the story, CNN has made a small financial
settlement with retired Adm. Thomas Moorer, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs at the time of Operation Tailwind, who was a source on CNN's
story. After the June 7 broadcast, Moorer claimed Oliver and Smith
had taken his quotes about Tailwind out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and Smith painted a picture of Johnson, Kaplan and other
top CNN producers being heavily involved in reporting and editing
the Tailwind story.
</P>
<P>
   Months before the broadcast, Oliver and Smith compiled a
150-page briefing book detailing sources who were interviewed, a
document they said was vetted by CNN brass.
</P>
<P>
   Their story, titled ``Valley of Death,'' contended that the U.S.
military used the potentially lethal nerve gas sarin in an attack
on a village base camp in Laos in 1970 during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has adamantly denied that nerve gas was ever used
during the war, and it countered Tuesday that the only biological
weapon deployed was a less toxic form of tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were sending me flowers,'' Oliver said of her CNN
superiors' initial reaction to the Tailwind broadcast. She also
recalled CNN attorney Kohler proclaiming, ``No one is going to get
sued over this one.''
</P>
<P>
   No lawsuits have been filed, but the story has caused lingering
embarrassment for CNN, which has been struggling to increase
ratings amid increasing competition by other all-news cable
networks. CNN founder Ted Turner was dragged into the Tailwind fray
and issued his own mea culpa, calling the story ``a screw-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of Oliver and Smith's criticisms were aimed at the
CNN chain of command, they also picked apart conclusions drawn by
Abrams and Kohler in their 52-page report. Abrams and Kohler said
the Tailwind story ``could not be supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and Smith countered with their own 77-page response in
which they described Abrams' report as ``weak and superficial.''
They said Kohler's involvement was a ``conflict of interest''
because he had vetted their work before it aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in top CNN management read it (the briefing report
prepared by the producers) before the furor erupted and signed off
on it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   While Oliver and Smith were dismissed from their jobs,
correspondent Peter Arnett, who conducted three on-camera
interviews, got a reprimand for his part in the story. Pam Hill,
another senior producer involved in the Tailwind story, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver contends that even though several key subjects
interviewed in the Tailwind report have since retracted or changed
their on-camera remarks, she remains convinced that the story was
factually correct.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said she has since gotten additional accounts
corroborating her story from other military personnel who served in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth said these accounts contain nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
