<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Simpsons' creator has his eye on future
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Matt Groening has seen the future, and it
looks a little bug-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons,'' unveiled his next Fox
prime-time cartoon series Wednesday at the Television Critics
Association meeting. It's ``Futurama,'' which will be a midseason
replacement series (as was ``The Simpsons'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' will tell the story of Fry, who is frozen on New
Year's Eve 1999 and wakes up 1,000 years later, in 2099. His main
companions will be Leela, ``a sexy female alien with one eye,''
Groening said, and Bender, ``our robotic Homer Simpson. He's
lovably corrupt, loves his vices. I think he's the first robot in
science-fiction history who shoplifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Groening said he was inspired by the science-fiction novels he
read in the '50s and '60s by Isaac Asimov, Robert A. Heinlein,
Philip K. Dick and others. And not just the texts, but the art on
the book's dust jackets, which he's been collecting at used-book
stores for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take all these conventions of science fiction and
have fun with them in a Simpsons style,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The characters in ``Futurama'' look somewhat Simpsonian, with
bulging eyes and prominent overbites. ``This is a result of my
limited drawing style,'' he joked. ``I've been drawing this way
since I was a kid, and it's the only way I know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new series will be filled with the pop culture of
the future, just as ``The Simpsons'' is in the present. ``The No. 1
show on TV is called `The Mass Hypnosis Hour,''' he said. ``It's on
Fox, no doubt.'' Celebrities may appear as themselves, ``but only
if they're willing to appear as a disembodied head in a jar.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Entertainment President Peter Roth said he has been begging
Groening for three years to launch another series; it's very
unusual for the creator of such a successful TV series not to move
on and create another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the whole universe. That's why it took three
years,'' Groening said.
</P>
<P>
   Groening also divulged a couple of more tidbits from the
upcoming season of ``The Simpsons.'' In one of the ``Treehouse of
Horrors'' Halloween segments, Bart and Lisa will be sucked into
their TV and find themselves on ``Ally McBeal.'' And Groening said
he is negotiating with Rupert Murdoch to play himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the smallest paycheck he's ever seen,'' Groening
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
