<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSALM13-COX     07-22 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSALM13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Hendricks Experience
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Standing alone on an empty stage, 17-year-old Duane
Martin is learning a little about theater, more about tough love.
His teacher in both realms is Freddie Hendricks, 42. Duane is
playing an inner-city rake, bragging about a sexual conquest: ``I'm
the king, man!'' He proudly pulls from his pocket the condom that
the girl gave him to use, still sealed in its gold foil wrapper.
</P>
<P>
   It's a chilling moment. But not chilling enough for Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't sound like no king to me! Are you reciting poetry? I
can go home and read poetry!'' cries the director of the Freddie
Hendricks Youth Ensemble of Atlanta, who wrote the scene in ``Psalm
13'' _ a musical drama about teen pregnancy, opening tonight _
based on discussions with his 34 performers, ages preteen to early
20s. Hendricks rises from his seat in 7 Stages and stalks toward
the worried-looking Duane. For a time in the early '90s, just after
he founded the troupe, Hendricks was so poor that he was homeless,
crashing for the night on friends' floors. Today he has an
apartment across from Atlanta City Hall, though with his ever-weary
eyes, shapeless socks dragging on the ground and jeans
more-than-fashionably torn up, he could almost pass for his former,
transient self. Yet his scowl is that of the perfectionist, and he
is not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to what you're saying, man: `I milked that girl, like a
cow!''' Hendricks lets out a demonic laugh _ suddenly transformed
from gentle artist into scary punk. ``You used her, just like
you've been used all your life, right? This is the theater! Make me
feel it! Paint me a picture with your biggest brush!''
</P>
<P>
   Duane repeats the scene: The improvement is astonishing. He
comes down from the stage; Hendricks embraces him. The hug is a
purging of the ugliness they have just conjured up and faced down.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks has been working pocket miracles like these for eight
years. He gives young performers professional pride but keeps their
emotions free of show biz gloss: honest, pure, even raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a grass-roots organization that could
produce such strong work,'' says Alliance Theatre artistic director
Kenny Leon, ``while giving its young people such confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble's shows use electrifying dance, drama, music and
rowdy comedy to explore such subjects as child abuse, AIDS and
drugs in the schools. It creates at least one original show a year
for its residency at 7 Stages, while touring throughout the year to
schools, community centers and fellowship halls as far away as St.
Louis. The work has rough edges: That's its nature _ and its
beauty. Yet it can be so compelling that it was featured at the
recent National Black Arts Festival and prompted International
Creative Management, a top Hollywood agency, to send a talent scout
to a ``Psalm 13'' rehearsal. He sat pressed against the wall of a
Reynoldstown gym, wide-eyed at the almost overwhelming energy
produced by 30-odd souls filling the space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hunger that burns in all of us that's
unexplainable,'' says Imani Simmons, 14. ``It's like when you
perform, the world is yours.''
</P>
<P>
   `God Is in Control'
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks calls his work ``a ministry''; indeed, the singers can
have the clear and tender sound of a choir. Matters of faith are
often discussed around the Reynoldstown rehearsal hall: a community
center across the MARTA tracks from Inman Park that sits next to a
steel plant and across from a bungalow where a rooster patrols the
front yard. The kids' clothes bear trendy sportswear logos as well
as religious messages. ``God Is in Control,'' says one T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the self-styled minister has an aspect of the field general.
He demands ``AR-TIC-U-LA-TION!'' whenever the actors' diction
becomes unclear. His performers push their bodies and souls to the
hilt in every dance and dramatic scene, pound out ferocious rhythms
against a violent world, sing of their dreams for a better one,
carry their healing message into neighborhoods that hurt. They are
warriors of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned discipline from my stepfather, an Army officer,''
Hendricks says. ``He only left out the love. I got that from my
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night when I was young, I dreamed there were children at
my window crying, `Save us, save us,''' the artist continues. ``I
went through some bad times, growing up in Columbus, but I always
said I would help to make sure other kids didn't have to go through
that.''
</P>
<P>
   His kids perform without pay for the nonprofit troupe, which
draws its $108,000 annual budget mainly from the fees it gets from
guest appearances before professional, social service and fraternal
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   His kids come from diverse backgrounds. There are children of
Atlanta artists and students at private colleges. They work
shoulder to shoulder with kids who were much more than ``at risk''
when, attracted mostly by word of mouth, they joined the ensemble.
Says Johnell Easter, 22: ``I was stealing credit cards, breaking
into candy machines _ stupid, irrelevant stuff. This company gave
me direction, a focus, goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ngaujah, 21, told of a night in his early teens when a
friend was severely beaten by kids from a rival neighborhood in
College Park, and it was only his mother forcing him to go to
church the next night that kept him out of a retaliatory shootout
and probably saved his life. Music director David Kote nodded with
sad recognition. Unbeknownst to Michael, he had been among the
rival group that swept down Michael's street and was dodging
bullets while his future colleague was listening to hymns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's why David and I are crazy tight today,'' Michael
says. ``That life is behind us now but not that entire world.
That's what keeps us doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to home
</P>
<P>
   ``Psalm 13,'' like most Hendricks shows, was born out of the
Circle: a sit-on-the-floor discussion group in which the entire
company brainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks says ``the number 13,'' including the difficult 13th
year of life, ``kept popping up everywhere.'' On a hunch that he
can't explain, he looked up Psalm 13 in the Bible. The line,
``Lord, how long must I bear pain in my soul?'' connected with his
ideas about the crisis of unwanted pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the black community needs to hear this message,''
Hendricks says, ``but so do all communities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the circle, arguments erupted between girls and boys, and
between those wanting to proclaim pregnancy without marriage wrong
and those wanting more emphasis on the positive life options for
those who decide to raise the child. The many viewpoints were grist
for a show that offers no one simple answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show hits close to home,'' says Jekonni Barber, 15,
``because we all have friends and brothers and sisters who weren't
ready to have babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to home, too, for the director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had stepbrothers, cousins, friends who were teen dads,''
says Hendricks, whose soft-spoken, shy persona is so different from
the general who barks out orders at rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   He takes a breath, then takes the plunge. ``I was a teen dad
myself. The girl lost the baby, but it was still a mistake I made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish,'' Hendricks adds, almost in a whisper, ``I had had
somebody to tell me not to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   THEATER PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Psalm 13''
</P>
<P>
   The Freddie Hendricks Youth Ensemble of Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Opening tonight. 7:30 p.m. Thursdays; 8 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays;
5 p.m. Sundays. Through Aug. 23. $15; $10 students and senior
citizens. 7 Stages, 1105 Euclid Ave. N.E. 404-523-7647. In a
benefit for the Sickle Cell Disease Program of Scottish Rite
Children's Medical Center, Sept. 26 at Clark Atlanta University.
404-880-8000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS-AR     07-22 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: private label.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But not everyone sees the trend as a healthy one for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to understand that this is not about health and
this is not about well-being; this is about money and jumping on a
bandwagon,'' said David Kessler, a former head of the FDA and now
dean of Yale University's medical school. Kessler waged a vigorous
but unsuccessful battle against the law that virtually stripped his
former agency of its authority to regulate herbal and other dietary
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   For healthy people, most of the products pose little or no risk,
and some, containing garlic and ginseng, may even be helpful,
Kessler said. The danger, he said, is that some people with
potentially life-threatening illnesses will use the products in
place of standard medical treatments. That has always been a risk,
but the marketing giants now pushing into the industry can pitch
these formulas to more consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they are positioned in the marketplace can lead people
down roads to ineffective treatments,'' Kessler said, pointing to
products whose names, he argued, could cause consumers to think
they could be used instead of prescription drugs. ``If you promote
a product as Mood Mender, you have a responsibility to that person
who is depressed, and if that product doesn't work, you are doing
harm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People with specific illnesses look at these products a
different way than the healthy person,'' he added, ``and it is
through their eyes that the marketplace must be judged.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, critics say, the supplements can be quite
dangerous indeed. The FDA, for example, is attempting to rein in
the use of the herbal stimulant ephedra, which is sold by various
companies in a formula under different names. The formula, which
manufacturers say is safe, has been linked to more than a dozen
deaths nationwide. Marketers promise that the pills provide an
amphetaminelike rush, aid in weight loss and even increase sexual
sensation, but medical experts say they can cause heart attacks,
strokes and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The big-name herbal pill dispensers now entering the market say
they are sticking to more ``mainstream'' substances and argue that
those formulas are safe and effective when taken by healthy people
in recommended doses. Besides, they say, unlike the little-known
manufacturers that once dominated the industry, they have the
research and development budgets and purchasing clout to insure
product quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend tens of millions of dollars putting together
manufacturing and quality-control processes,'' said Elliot
Friedman, chairman and chief executive of Pharmaprint Inc., which
is producing the supplements that American Home Products is
planning to market under the Centrum name. ``The big companies are
very protective of their brands.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be, but the critics say consumers have a false sense of
security about the regulatory oversight of supplements. They
mistakenly assume, the critics contend, that the supplements are
subject to the same scrutiny as toothpaste, cough drops and other
seemingly benign products under the FDA's watch. The agency
requires those goods to carry general cautionary labeling and
dosage information, and it imposes limits on the claims that can be
made in marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Herbal supplements are regulated by a looser set of standards.
Before the passage in 1994 of the Dietary Supplement Health and
Education Act, manufacturers were prohibited, for instance, from
making claims about the potential benefits of their products. But
the revised guidelines allow companies to advertise the health
effects of herbal supplements _ without having to conclusively
prove their effectiveness _ so long as the wording does not suggest
that the products prevent, treat or cure disease.
</P>
<P>
   That gives companies much greater range in making product claims
than manufacturers of, say, mouthwash. While a company cannot claim
an herbal supplement cures cancer or relieves depression, for
example, it can say that it ``promotes prostate health'' or ``aids
in mental focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also worry that pharmaceutical companies will attempt to
classify some products as herbal supplements instead of as drugs to
skirt the rigorous process required to bring a drug to market.
</P>
<P>
   That complaint is at the heart of a battle between the FDA and
Pharmanex Inc., which manufactures a product called Cholestin,
which it sells as an supplement in Wal-Mart and other big chains.
The FDA wants to ban the substance, maintaining that it is an
unapproved drug because it contains a natural form of a key
chemical in the cholesterol-lowering prescription drug Mevacor,
made by Merck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pharmanex won the first round in the battle _ which
was prompted by Merck's complaints about the product _ when a judge
issued a preliminary injunction lifting the FDA's administrative
ban of Cholestin. The company contends that the product is a
natural alternative for people who are too healthy to take the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as other drug makers begin producing herbal pills,
the FDA is struggling to find a way to exercise its limited
oversight authority.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products declined to provide an executive to
discuss its supplements business beyond issuing a statement through
a public relations representative saying, ``Herbals represent a
large and growing market with increasing consumer acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, analysts estimate that the Centrum line alone has the
potential to generate $80 million in revenues within a year of its
introduction, a figure Friedman calls ``on the low side.'' His
company's share would be 10 percent of pretax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said the industry's growth could be even greater as
more retailers make room for brand-name supplements on their
already crowded shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are looking for a name they trust and, to be honest,
that's why we went with Centrum,'' he said. ``Pharmacists know it,
doctors know it and consumers know it. That is the edge in bringing
these new people into the fold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
