<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-HNS &LR;      07-22 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF PEOPLE SICKENED FROM TAINTED TEXAS OYSTERS HITS 368 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Colo., Fla., Ga., Okla. and Tenn.) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The number of people sickened from eating raw
Galveston Bay oysters is still mounting as experts gather at a
national conference to study the outbreak and seek remedies.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, state health officials had documented 368 cases
of illness from raw oysters tainted with ``Vibrio
parahaemolyticus'' bacteria. The bay was closed to oyster
harvesting June 22 because of the rash of sickness.
</P>
<P>
   The total of confirmed victims outdistanced the nation's
previous record: 208 cases in an outbreak from oysters harvested
along the Pacific Northwest coast last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although most illnesses in the current outbreak were in Texas,
health officials also have confirmed cases in California, Colorado,
Florida, Georgia, Oklahoma and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The illness can be fatal for someone with an immune deficiency.
Although a few people have required hospitalization, officials
said, most who became ill suffered flulike symptoms such as
diarrhea, cramps, nausea, vomiting, fever and headache.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts and people in the shellfish industry are meeting
this week at the Interstate Shellfish Sanitation Conference in San
Diego to review lab test results and determine how to prevent a
recurrence and when to reopen harvesting in Galveston Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oyster wholesaler Joe Nelson of Smith Point, in Chambers County,
said his employees have been out of work for a month with no end in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're having to look for other jobs. It's kind of rough on
all of us,'' he said. ``We're still trying to substitute by
bringing in oysters from Louisiana to fill our orders. We don't
have any idea what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium causing this outbreak is not associated with
pollution and had never been found in Galveston Bay in
concentrations that would cause illness, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Elliott, who heads the state's microbiology lab in
Austin, said there are a dozen strains of ``Vibrio
parahaemolyticus'' and only one has been identified in victims of
the current outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   This strain could be more potent than the others and therefore
harmful in lower concentrations than it normally takes to cause
illness, he said. However, he added, this strain has not been
detected in oyster samples taken from the bay since the outbreak
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't found this particular strain, but the bacteria
species itself is still out there,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bay is a big place. We might not have sampled in the right
spot, or possibly it's died out now.''
</P>
<P>
   While the drought and high temperatures are suspected of
allowing this bug to flourish, Elliott said the exact cause may
never be known.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, there was an outbreak of Rocky Mountain spotted
fever in northeast Texas about 12 years ago and since then there's
been nothing,'' he said. ``There may never be a scientific
explanation for this. It's like looking at a jigsaw puzzle with a
third of the pieces missing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
