<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULITZER-PRIZE-JAZZ-2     07-22 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PRIZE-JAZZ-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE CASE FOR AN OVERLOOKED SWING PIANIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Terry Teachout is the music critic of Commentary and a contributing
writer for Time 
By TERRY TEACHOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trivia question: who was the first jazz musician to win the
Pulitzer Prize for music? Hint: it wasn't Wynton Marsalis. The
honor belongs to Mel Powell, who won in 1990 for a two-piano
concerto called ``Duplicates.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the composer of ``Duplicates'' had long since
stopped playing jazz by the time he collected his prize. But
Powell, who worked with Benny Goodman and Glenn Miller in the
1940s, was for a brief time among the best-known big-band sidemen
in America, and when he died on April 24, jazz connoisseurs mourned
him not as a relatively obscure composer of nontonal classical
music, but as one of the most underrated pianists of the swing era.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Powell's early career seems almost too good to be
true. A protege of the stride pianist Willie (The Lion) Smith, he
began sitting in at Nick's, the Greenwich Village nightclub in New
York City that was the headquarters of the guitarist-raconteur
Eddie Condon, at the age of 14. In 1941, when he was only 17,
Powell joined the Goodman band, and within months was attracting
national attention both as pianist and arranger (he wrote the
charts for the clarinetist's hit records of ``Jersey Bounce'' and
``A String of Pearls'').
</P>
<P>
   He spent the war years playing in Miller's Army Air Force band,
and once he came home from Europe in 1945, it seemed a safe bet
that he would quickly establish himself as a major voice in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Powell used his G.I. Bill benefits to go to Yale, where
he studied classical composition with Paul Hindemith. He resurfaced
in the mid-'50s, making a series of well-received records on his
own and with Goodman. Then, in 1957, he abandoned jazz altogether,
spending the next three decades teaching at Yale and the California
Institute of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   His albums went out of print, and his glory days as a jazz
prodigy were soon forgotten, save by record collectors with long
memories. Not until 1986 did he play in public again, and his
``return'' consisted of a two-week jazz cruise on board the S.S.
Norway; a rare neuromuscular disorder subsequently forced him to
give up playing.
</P>
<P>
   All this would be of purely academic interest were it not for
the fact that Mel Powell was no ordinary jazz pianist. In his
earliest records, he blended the smooth, unruffled clarity of Teddy
Wilson and the darting unpredictability of Earl Hines into a highly
personal style noteworthy for its sparkling touch and extreme
virtuosity _ his technique was easily comparable to that of Art
Tatum _ to which he later added a sophisticated harmonic vocabulary
drawn from his studies with Hindemith.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he was a first-rate jazz composer and arranger who
was responsible for four of Goodman's most individual recordings,
``The Count,'' ``The Earl,'' ``Mission to Moscow'' and
``Clarinade.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof of Powell's remarkable gifts can be heard on a new CD
called ``Benny Goodman Plays Mel Powell'' (Hep). The latest in a
series of compact-disk compilations focusing on Goodman's prewar
arrangers, this album contains a dozen of the charts Powell wrote
between 1941 and 1946 (plus another arrangement attributed to him
incorrectly, the famous cover version of ``Why Don't You Do
Right?'' sung by the young Peggy Lee).
</P>
<P>
   ``Benny and I could fly, we could play as fast as anybody,''
Powell told Ross Firestone, Goodman's biographer, and he wasn't
exaggerating: ``The Earl'' and ``Mission to Moscow'' both contain
clarinet-and-piano chases that leave no doubt of Powell's ability
to keep up with his speed-demon boss.
</P>
<P>
   Except for ``The Return of Mel Powell'' (Chiaroscuro), recorded
live on the Norway in 1986, ``Benny Goodman Plays Mel Powell'' is
the first jazz album to be issued under the pianist's name since
the '50s. But he can also be heard to brilliant effect on another
Goodman CD, ``Slipped Disc'' (Columbia), a collection of 14
performances recorded in 1945 with an all-star sextet that featured
the vibraphonist Red Norvo and the bassist Slam Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Wilson plays on the first six sides, Powell on the
remainder, and the juxtaposition of the two pianists is
illuminating. To say that the younger man holds his own is to
grossly understate the case _ he is in fact far more inventive than
Wilson, whose postwar playing was fluent but all too often bland,
and the crisp, twinkling solos Powell bats out on ``Tiger Rag,''
``I Got Rhythm,'' ``Liza'' and ``China Boy'' are as exhilarating as
a tightrope walk on a breezy day.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Powell's later recordings with Goodman, including a blazingly
fast 1947 sextet performance of ``The World Is Waiting for the
Sunrise,'' were briefly available on a four-CD set from Mosaic that
is, alas, no longer in print.
</P>
<P>
   Also out of print in this country are the solo albums Powell
made for Vanguard after studying with Hindemith; fortunately, two
of them, ``Borderline'' and ``Thigamagig,'' have been reissued on
an English CD available through import outlets. Recorded in 1954,
these trio albums feature the tenor saxophonist Paul Quinichette
and the trumpeter Ruby Braff, who both play beautifully throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Powell is at all times the center of attention, not
merely for the fleet invention of his up-tempo solos but also for
his pensive, arrestingly angular reharmonizations of ballads like
``What's New?'' and ``You're My Thrill,'' in which listeners
familiar with Hindemith's music will immediately recognize the
master's touch.
</P>
<P>
   The originality of ``Borderline'' and ``Thigamagig'' is clearer
in hindsight than it was 44 years ago. At a time when even the most
harmonically advanced jazz pianists were still digesting the
implications of the music of Debussy and Ravel, Powell was moving
in a different direction entirely, and had he continued to explore
post-impressionist harmony in a jazz context, he surely would have
come to be regarded as a stylistic innovator.
</P>
<P>
   But his interest in jazz was rapidly waning _ he later admitted
to the author Gene Lees that the only reason he continued to work
with Goodman in the '50s was the money _ and when Yale hired him to
teach composition in 1957, he quit jazz for good.
</P>
<P>
   Why did so superlatively gifted an artist turn his back on the
music that made him famous? ``I have decided that when I retire I
will think through my decision to leave jazz with the help of Freud
and Jung,'' Powell told Whitney Balliett in a 1987 New Yorker
profile.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate reason, he explained, was that he had grown tired
of playing the same charts night after night with the Goodman band.
But he went on to offer a more complex rationale: ``I had done what
I felt I had to do in jazz. I had decided it did not hold the
deepest interest for me musically. And I had decided that it was a
young man's music, even a black music.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Powell's jazz playing is far more likely to be
remembered than his classical compositions, which have never
appealed to more than a tiny coterie of admirers. The
uncompromising serialism he favored had long since fallen from
fashion _ even academic fashion _ by the time of his death. Yet
more of his recorded performances are now available on CD than ever
before, and his Vanguard albums will doubtless be reissued in the
United States at some point in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   When that finally happens, a new generation of delighted
listeners will discover what their grandparents would gladly have
told them: the winner of the 1990 Pulitzer Prize for music was also
one of the very best pianists ever to play jazz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
