<SLUG> BC-MA-YOUNG-DRIVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE DRIVING LICENSE TO BE TOUGHER TO GET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Inside the T-N-T driver's education school, the walls
are plastered with newspaper clippings depicting grisly car wrecks
involving teen-age drivers.
</P>
<P>
   All around, posters in garish colors announce the dangers of the
road, and the commandments for safe driving: no drinking, no
speeding, no horseplay.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 13 students cooped up in driving class in suburban
Hull this week, the posters just didn't seem to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's telling you to grow up and be responsible, but
they're not letting us do that,'' said Michael Hurwitz, 16, of
Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state is poised to help focus the attention of youth
drivers by tripling the number of training hours required for a
license and by imposing new restrictions such as prohibiting
teen-aged drivers from having other teens in the car.
</P>
<P>
   If the new restrictions become law, as expected, Massachusetts
would be the 22d state to adopt a graduated licensing scheme in
recent years. It would represent the first significant overhaul of
the student driver system in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   For many adults, the change can't come too soon. In
Massachusetts, 46 percent of 16-year-old drivers are in an accident
before their 17th birthday, according to the American Automoblie
Association. Nationally, about two-thirds of 6,319 teenagers killed
in car crashes last year were riding in a car driven by another
teen, according to federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't learn driver's skills overnight,'' said Allan
Williams, senior vice president of the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety. ``Let them get on-the-road driving experience to
build up their skills, but keep them in protected situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Even driving instructors like Tony Kuzmicki, who runs T-N-T
driving school with his wife Tina, agree that classroom instruction
cannot match real driving time in giving teenagers confidence and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the kids you have to do at least 30 hours before even
getting a license,'' Kuzmicki said. ``They're reckless when they
get out there with their friends. They forget everything they've
learned and they try to show off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts bill, which was introduced by Rep. Peter
Larkin, a Democrat of Pittsfield, would extend the number of
supervised driving hours, from six to 18, and prohibit junior
licensees from driving between midnight and 5 a.m. unless
accompanied by a parent or guardian. And for the first six months
after obtaining a junior license, teenagers cannot have any
passenger under 18 in the car with them unless someone over age 21
is in the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   The bill attempts to address some of the problems that make
teenage drivers so dangerous, chief among them, experts say,
distractions from passengers, a willingness to take risks, speed,
alcohol, and simple inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   The result, say sponsors of the bill, are accidents that claim
teenage lives with a frightening frequency. Last Wednesday, a
16-year-old from Randolph crashed his car carrying six friends into
a brick wall in Pawtucket, R.I. Two of them were killed -- a
16-year-old boy from Randolph and a 15-year-old girl from
Attleboro.
</P>
<P>
   A study released in April by the Insurance Institute for Highway
Safety found that in the past 20 years, the death rate among
16-year-old drivers nearly doubled -- from 19 deaths per 100,000
drivers in 1975 to 35 per 100,000 in 1996 -- while the rate
declined for the rest of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young drivers are more likely to exceed the posted speed
limits, they weave in and out of traffic, and they are less likely
to wear safety belts,'' said Arthur Kinsman, a spokesman for the
AAA of Southern New England, a sponsor of the Massachusetts bill.
``They have feelings of invulnerability and don't understand what
they have to lose and how easy it is to be injured.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and House passed different versions of the graduated
license bill earlier this year. Larkin said he expects to have a
compromise bill up for a vote in both houses before the end of the
session next week. The bill is expected to pass easily, and Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci has indicated he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic of putting youths behind the wheel with little
experience has contributed to the mayhem on the highways,'' said
Larkin, who had three high school friends killed in a car crash.
``I can still feel the shock of that moment. No one thinks they're
more indestructible than a 17-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety experts say that earlier attempts to reduce teenage
accidents by cracking down on drunk driving and expanding driver's
educations programs failed in the 1980s. They are just now learning
that what really works is to get teenagers to spend more time
behind the wheel, not in classrooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
