A8130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-SHEPARD-BOS &LR;      07-22 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SHEPARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN B. SHEPARD JR.; FIRST AMERICAN IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Bartlett Shepard Jr., who became America's first man in
space and the only person to hit a golf ball on the moon, died in a
California hospital of leukemia early Wednesday. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has lost a shining star,'' NASA administator Daniel
Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard's steely confidence combined with his unassuming
public demeanor helped propel him to the status of a national hero
after his historic 16-minute flight on May 5, 1961, made him
America's first space traveler. That brief sub-orbital foray helped
salve the nation's wounded pride after having been beaten to the
honor of sending the first human into space by the Soviet Union's
Yuri Gagarin, just 23 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who are old enough to remember the first
spaceflights will always remember what an impression he made on us
and on the world,'' said President Clinton Wednesday. ``So I would
like to express the gratitude of our nation and to say that our
thoughts and prayers are with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard was grounded for six years after that first flight
because of an inner-ear problem that affected his balance. But the
problem was later corrected surgically and he returned to the
astronaut corps in time to fly to the moon on the Apollo 14 mission
in 1971, becoming one of only 12 human beings to walk on the lunar
surface.
</P>
<P>
   That mission helped restore America's faith in the space program
after the dangerous and suspenseful Apollo 13 mission, which
suffered a serious explosion that prevented it from landing on the
moon. All three astronauts survived that mission unscathed after a
series of close calls, as recounted in the movie ``Apollo 13.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard's Apollo 14 mission also came close to being
thwarted by a hardware problem, but was salvaged as a result of
quick thinking by a team of computer engineers at Draper
Laboratories in Cambridge, Mass., who were able to reprogram the
onboard computer to bypass a faulty ``abort'' switch. The mission
culminated in Mr. Shepard's now-famous lunar golfing spree, in
which he lofted a couple of balls into near-oblivion using a
makeshift club he had secretly arranged to take along.
</P>
<P>
   He later explained that he hit the golf balls to demonstrate to
young people the great differences between the lunar environment
and that of Earth: its total airlessness and reduced gravity, only
one-sixth that of Earth's.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of nearly routine space missions, it is difficult
to remember the suspense Mr. Shepard's first flight generated. The
Soviet Union had successfully launched the first satellite four
years earlier and the American people had witnessed television
images of one US rocket after another erupting in flames on the
launch pad. Mr. Shepard, riding on a converted Redstone ballistic
missile, had few of the safety measures _ or the amenities _ of
later spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that mission in a television interview, Mr. Shepard
said that at the time ``all of us certainly believed the
statistics,'' which said there was ``probably 88 percent chance of
mission success and maybe 96 percent chance of survival. And we
were willing to take those odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard's Apollo 14 crewmate Edgar Mitchell said recently
that ``we did what we set out to do and had a good time doing it.''
Mitchell added that ``it was the common attitude: `We get paid to
do this?' It was the greatest adventure of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up on a family farm in Derry, N.H., Mr. Shepard spent
his first five years of schooling in a one-room schoolhouse with
one teacher and 25 students in grades one through six. He later
credited the discipline and study skills he learned during that
time, along with a strong home life in what he called a family of
hard workers, with helping propel him toward a life of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard took an early interest in aviation, working at a
small airport in return for the occasional opportunity to fly as a
passenger on small planes and, eventually, pilot them.
</P>
<P>
   Born Nov. 18, 1923, Mr. Shepard was old enough to remember
Charles Lindbergh's epochal solo flight across the Atlantic Ocean,
and he would later describe Lindbergh as a boyhood hero, whom he
met later in life.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard's family could not afford to send him to college,
but he passed the entrance exams for the US Naval Academy and later
as a Naval officer received his first real flight training. He then
became a military test pilot, which put him in position to be among
the first group chosen for astronaut training by the newly created
National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He became part of the original Mercury Seven group of
astronauts, America's first space fliers, who were widely
celebrated in magazines and personal appearances even before the
first spaceflight took place. They were the subject of Tom Wolfe's
1979 book ``The Right Stuff.'' The others were M. Scott Carpenter,
L. Gordon Cooper, Wally Schirra, Donald K. ``Deke'' Slayton (who
died in 1993), John Glenn Jr. (now a senator from Ohio, who is
preparing to return to space aboard the US space shuttle, this
October), and Virgil ``Gus'' Grissom (who died on the launch pad in
the Apollo 1 fire).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Andrew Chaikin, &UR;  &LR; author of the book ``A Man On the Moon,''
which details the history of the Apollo program, said Wednesday
that while there was intense competition among the Mercury Seven to
be the first one in space, Mr. Shepard ``always believed that he
was the best guy to walk through those doors. He never had a
moment's doubt that he should be the first American in space.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shepard, who died in a hospital in Monterey, Calif., is
survived by his wife, the former Louise Brewer, whom he met at the
Naval Academy. He also leaves two daughters and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow astronaut Buzz Aldrin, who was the second man on the
moon, said Wednesday that ``Alan Shepard was the pioneer's pioneer,
the pilot's pilot, and the man who opened space for all Americans.
I cannot convey to you how much he was admired by those of us who
watched and then followed him through that magic door into space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
