u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MFN-HNS &LR;      07-22 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MFN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTE PAVES WAY FOR RENEWAL OF TRADE TIES WITH CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House paved the way Wednesday for renewing
trade ties with China by striking down a resolution that would have
ended normal commerce because of the Communist nation's human
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 264-166, the House rejected a measure that would
have revoked President Clinton's decision last month to extend
``normal trade relations'' for another year with China. The status,
in previous years, has been called ``most favored nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was hailed by supporters of China trade as a strong
signal of Congress' willingness to continue the 26-year-old policy
of constructive engagement that began with President's Nixon's
visit in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote all but guaranteed that China will continue to
receive trading privileges for at least another year. The Senate
must also act to approve the annual renewal, but the outcome in
that chamber is expected to mirror the House action.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of trade with China joined with opponents in taking
issue with many aspects of the U.S. policy pushed by Clinton. But
they said that denying China many of the same low tariffs enjoyed
by most other U.S. trading partners would likely cause a trade war
and lead to the reversal of many political and social reforms made
by China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also warned that breaking off normal trade ties with
China would exacerbate the economic crisis in Asia and further
damage U.S. exports to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a severe economic depression facing many Asian nations,
the United States cannot afford to adopt a protectionist response
to objectionable behavior by the Chinese government,'' said House
Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Archer pointed out that U.S. workers and firms do $17 billion in
trade with China each year and ``revoking normal trade relations
... could trigger more currency devaluations in the region, further
compounding the steep drop in demand for U.S. exports.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Archer noted in a statement issued through his office that
Texas-based industries would be significant losers. The businesses
make more than $651 million from China each year with exports that
range from ceiling fans to airborne navigational systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While sympathetic to concerns about human rights and possible
transfers of U.S. technology to China, Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas,
said the United States could not discount the fact that China has 1
billion consumers eager to buy American-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is our fourth largest trading partner. ... This is a bad
idea that will only hurt the American worker and the American
economy,'' Bentsen said of the move to undercut U.S.-China trade
ties.
</P>
<P>
   The trade preferences have been renewed annually by every
president since Jimmy Carter in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents argue that the huge U.S. trade imbalance with
China has helped support the oppressive policies of the Beijing
leadership and allowed the Asian nation to continue its military
buildup and improve its missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our trade deficit with China is financing the present
leadership in China,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents were more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   Citing recent allegations that U.S. technology may have been
transferred that has helped improve Chinese missile guidance
systems, Rep. James Traficant Jr., D-Ohio, said it would be
``stupid'' for Congress to continue support of normal trading
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a debate about trade anymore. This is a debate
about national security,'' he said. He implored his colleagues who
support continuing normal trade ties to ``wake up'' before ``there
is a Chinese rocket stuck right up your assets.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of those who railed against the campaign violations,
human rights abuses and possible conversion of U.S. technology to
Chinese military use finally supported continuation of normal trade
relations. They cited concern that American businesses in China
would lose out to European and Asian rivals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it has in the past, the annual China trade debate brought
together an unusual coalition of allies. Liberal Democrats joined
conservative Republicans to oppose renewal of normal trade ties,
and Christian right groups sided with labor unions in their
opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
