<SLUG> BC-ATLANTIC-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASA, pilots resume talks; airline posts 32 percent earnings
increase
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlantic Southeast Airlines and its pilot union have
resumed federally mediated contract talks in an effort to avert a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Wednesday, the commuter affiliate of Delta Air
Lines posted a 32 percent jump in second quarter profits, aided by
the addition of new jets.
</P>
<P>
   A union spokeswoman said ASA management offered a revised
contract proposal when mediators convened the two sides for the
first time since pilots rejected a tentative agreement last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress is being made, and talks are continuing at this
time,'' the spokeswoman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based ASA and the union reached a contract agreement in
January, but rank-and-file pilots in March rejected the proposed
pact by a resounding 413-43 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The union membership has authorized a strike if talks fail and
mediators declare an impasse, but such a scenario is still weeks or
months away.
</P>
<P>
   The off-again, on-again contract talks date to late 1995, and
pilots still fly under the old agreement. Among the issues is pay,
which now ranges from $15,000 to $60,000 _ far under levels at
Delta and other large airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots contend the wages are also subpar among commuter
carriers, especially in light of ASA's financial success. They also
want relief from what they contend are unfair scheduling practices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ASA said its profit was $19.5 million, or 65 cents a
share, in the second quarter, versus $14.8 million, or 49 cents a
share a year earlier. Revenue grew 7.1 percent to $106.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The results topped expectations, pushing ASA stock up $1.81 1/4
to $48.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, ASA posted profit of $32.9 million, or $1.09
a share, on revenue of $200.4 million, against $25.5 million, or 85
cents, on revenue of $189.3 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The company attributes the improved results in part to new
50-seat jets deployed last fall. The jets are spurring traffic
growth, as evidenced by an 11 percent gain in revenue passenger
miles for the first six months of the year, on flat capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
