<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CCE-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flat earnings stomp CCE
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola Enterprises set off a Wall Street stampede
by releasing flat second-quarter earnings and a warning that
profits would be much lower than expected until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based bottler said earnings will be crimped this
year and the next _ though they should surge in 2000 and 2001 _
because of a $5 billion capital spending plan. The company will
expand warehouse and production facilities, add to its delivery
fleet and install 840,000 new vending machines and other beverage
dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the stepped-up investments, per-share earnings will
hit only 25 cents this year, with about 10 percent earnings growth
projected for 1999, the company said. In 2000 and 2001, growth
rates should accelerate to more than 50 percent in each year, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   The average analyst forecast was 35 cents this year and 53 cents
for next year, with a 23.6 percent average increase over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was among the most active Wednesday on the New York
Stock Exchange, with nearly 8 million shares trading _ more than 15
times this year's average daily volume. CCE closed at $35.31 1/4,
down $3.68 3/4, a 9.5 percent drop in value.
</P>
<P>
   CCE's second-quarter earnings came in at the low end of Wall
Street estimates, which ranged from 27 cents to 31 cents and
averaged 29 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's largest bottler reported net income of $111 million,
or 27 cents a share, compared with $111 million, or 28 cents a
share on fewer shares, in the year-earlier period. Revenue rose 27
percent, to $3.68 billion, from $2.91 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, net income fell 23 percent, to $60 million,
or 15 cents per share, on revenue of $6.65 billion. This compares
with $78 million, or 20 cents per share, on revenue of $5.05
billion in the previous six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence in the outlook for the stock has not changed one
bit,'' said Marty Romm, a beverage analyst with Credit Suisse First
Boston. The firm arranged the sale of a 3 million-share block of
CCE stock for $35 per share on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every seller, there's a buyer,'' said Romm, who called
CCE's strategic direction ``very appropriate.'' ``The actions the
board took to increase capital expense can only increase their
growth in volume and cash operating profit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the second-quarter and year-to-date net income
primarily reflects the expected impact of its acquisitions of
British, Canadian and New York bottling operations, and related
accelerated spending on new trucks, vending machines and coolers.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Summerfield K. Johnston Jr. said the $5 billion expense
reflects the company's long-term perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates are low, the economy is strong, our business
has unparalleled momentum, and the Coca-Cola system has never been
stronger,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   CCE's sales rose 8 percent in the quarter, compared with a 2
percent gain in the previous second quarter. In the United States
and Canada, CCE's sales volume was up 9 percent, and it rose 4
percent in European markets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
