<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-EARNING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring enjoys another strong quarter
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- MindSpring Enterprises on Wednesday posted its third
consecutive profitable quarter and once again beat analysts'
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Internet service provider _ the largest ISP in
the Southeast and the largest independent ISP in the country _
reported second-quarter revenue of $25.1 million. The company
reported a profit of $2.02 million, or 24 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period last year, MindSpring reported a loss of
$1.43 million, or 19 cents per share. MindSpring also reported a
subscriber base of 393,000, up from 341,000 last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call had expected MindSpring to earn
18 cents a share. The results were reported after the stock market
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the second quarter, MindSpring President and Chief
Operating Officer Michael S. McQuary said, ``We're obviously very
proud of our results. Everyone asks us what the secret potion is,
but the truth is what's unique and magical about our company is the
hard work and the dedication of our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said the company was not for sale but MindSpring is
always weighing potential opportunities to buy as well as sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wanted to buy MindSpring, it would have to be
somebody good for our investors, our employees and our
subscribers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have to be someone who really values the culture of
what we've built here, someone who shared our zeal for making our
customers happy. It's a short list of people,'' McQuary said.
``There's nobody we're mulling over right now, but that's the
criteria we'd measure it against.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MindSpring were up Wednesday on hopes the company
would beat analysts' estimates. After hitting a high Wednesday of
$141.37 1/2, MindSpring closed at $140.31 1/4, up $13.68 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring, trading at $12.87 1/2 just one year ago, has watched
its stock price double over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Grosz, an analyst at Everen Securities Chicago, said,
``In general it looks like a very strong quarter. Their subscriber
numbers were in line with our estimates but their earnings per
share was six cents above.''
</P>
<P>
   Grosz said MindSpring's second-quarter success reflected the
company's ability to keep costs down and develop its Web hosting
business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
