<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-4000(3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UNLUCKY LIVE IN PUBLIC HOUSING
</HEADLINE>
 Takes)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN and JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the blast-furnace heat of the day
finally recedes about 8 p.m., the community comes alive. Adults sit
on front stoops and chat with neighbors. Laughing, dripping
children run between creaky sprinklers while a grouchy old-timer
yells at them to stay off his lawn. Teen-age couples wander about,
holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   It all mimics a Norman Rockwell painting _ except Rockwell
didn't live in public housing. That's what these folks call home.
They are residents of Cavile Place, a 300-unit apartment complex
run by the Fort Worth Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd includes the stereotypical perceptions: a pregnant
13-year-old, a 30-year-old woman with 12 children and another on
the way, a 16-year-old who will be arrested a few nights later on
armed robbery charges.
</P>
<P>
   It might be easy to overlook the 15-year-old computer brain, the
17-year-old determined to go to law school and the 63-year-old
retired maid who is a member of the Fort Worth Housing Authority
board and once represented the city in a meeting with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our good and our misguided,'' says Barbara Deckard,
67, who has lived in Cavile Place since 1958. ``Mostly, we're just
people like anybody else. Except not many people care to come to
public housing and find that out.''
</P>
<P>
   `THEY DESERVE QUALITY'
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth runs six public housing areas _ Butler, Ripley
Arnold, Cavile, Hunter, Fair Park and Fair Oaks _ as well as other
scattered sites. In all, there are 1,398 public housing units
ranging from one-bedroom apartments to houses.
</P>
<P>
   Cavile, the third-oldest complex, sits squarely in the Stop Six
neighborhood near the intersection of East Rosedale Street and East
Loop 820, ringed by bars and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of Cavile's 850 to 900 residents is there by accident.
Most are African-American, but Anglos and Hispanics make up about
20 percent of the ethnic mix. When tenants sit around on their
front steps in the evening and swap life stories, their tales
always share a common theme: There was no place left to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as families that include a husband or father, if I said
10, I'd probably be counting too many,'' says Bettye Walker, 53,
the Cavile housing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have lived in Cavile for an extended period, such as
Deckard and Housing Authority board member Callie Pollard, describe
the community as a one-time residents' paradise that turned bad and
is now relatively safe again.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, gangs and drug dealers made Cavile their base. The
wide ``alley'' bisecting the apartments became a speedway for
drive-by shootings. Old-timers describe the peculiar popping noise
that clotheslines make when snapped by bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was a total mess, a hellhole,'' Pollard says. ``But
we changed. Most of us decided we weren't going to put up with that
stuff anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs of Fort Worth opened a branch next to the
complex office. The Fort Worth library installed a small Cavile
branch instantly known as COOL (for ``Cavile Outreach Opportunity
Library'').
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Pollard said, ``The police gave us a storefront, and
most of all, they gave us Whitehead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whitehead'' is what Cavile tenants call Cpl. Jim Smith of the
Fort Worth Police Department. He earned the nickname because of his
gray hair. Smith, 53, spends all his on-duty hours at Cavile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get very possessive'' about Cavile, Smith says. ``Most
people here are decent and hard-working. They deserve quality
police protection. If anyone involved in criminal activity moves in
here, we're going to find out, and we're going to move them out.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Smith was shot and severely beaten by the
brother of a resident during an attempted arrest for drug
possession. After he recuperated, Smith came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big step was putting up gates in the alley to stop
drive-bys,'' he says. ``Most of the problems, always, came from
outsiders, anyway. The big concern we still have is drugs, but
that's the same anywhere. I care about the people here.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's lucky for that kid who shot Whitehead that the police
arrested him before the residents got hold of him,'' Pollard says
with a sharklike grin. ``I think it would have gotten pretty ugly.
We look out for our own, and Whitehead is one of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BASICS _ OR A SHOWPLACE
</P>
<P>
   When you move into Cavile, you don't get much besides the basics
_ and new friends.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment buildings are squat, red-brick rectangles that
soak up the heat of the sun. Scrubby grass grows all around.
Inside, rooms are small, with yellowy-white concrete walls and pale
linoleum floors. Each unit has a stove and refrigerator, but no
other furniture or appliances. The air smells of disinfectant and
bug decay. Some residents complain about rats. Two years ago, the
housing authority installed air conditioning, which works
intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   Earl ``Bubba'' Lee, 10, takes it upon himself to meet everybody
moving in, although he sometimes warns as well as greets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people got roaches, I hope you know,'' Bubba shrilly
informs a fledgling tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Lacy, 30, sometimes welcomes new neighbors with a pie or
some other treat. She asks them to let her know if her two sons,
ages 13 and 10, make too much noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like everybody to be happy with each other,'' Lacy says.
``I want to know if Dereck and Montrell bother anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Small courtesies are essential to Cavile residents. They try
hard to be respectful of one another because they believe outsiders
don't respect them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They add `black' and `poor' and come up with `trash,' ''
Pollard says. ``We take pride in our families and our homes like
the people in the rich neighborhoods do.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cavile, residents don't have to take care of their yards or
fix up their apartments as long as they avoid outright defacement.
Some let their dwellings slip into grimy disrepair. But others,
such as Louis T. Booker, 55, nurture their property _ which is why
Booker doesn't want kids spoiling his yardwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing in front of my place when I moved in going
on six years ago, just dirt and no grass,'' he says. ``I took my
cousin's truck and got me some good, rich field dirt. Then I put in
St. Augustine runners and some shrubs. It looks good and green
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacy has turned her tiny two-bedroom apartment into a showplace.
Plants extend branches everywhere, and their leaves partially
conceal fish tanks, bird cages, an iguana tank and a rabbit with a
bright green collar. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
