<HEADER>
A8142 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-4000(2     07-22 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-4000(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UNLUCKY LIVE IN PUBLIC HOUSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH: bright green collar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're here, we ought to enjoy living here,'' she said.
``Who says public housing people got to live in dirt? I did this
bit by bit over the seven years. When I moved in, I just had a
mattress and a black-and-white TV.''
</P>
<P>
   IS WORK ENCOURAGED?
</P>
<P>
   Some would say Lacy and her children have lived in their
apartment too long.
</P>
<P>
   Those who meet the stringent requirements of public housing can
stay indefinitely, if they pay rent on time and don't commit
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average resident stays maybe three years,'' Walker says.
``If they haven't moved on in three years, then they're usually
here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Deckard never considered moving out of Cavile, ``though I could
have if I wanted to. But this is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Minimum Housing Authority rent is $50 a month, which the
unemployed can glean from welfare, child-support checks or other
income. Residents with jobs must pay 30 percent of their monthly
net salaries. Rent includes most utility costs; anyone who uses
more than a fixed ``utility allowance'' of kilowatt hours must pay
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The current FWHA annual budget for public housing is $4,675,860.
Dividing the number of units _ 1,398 _ into that results in an
annual cost of $3,344 per unit, or about $279 a month. In June, the
average rent at Cavile was $113.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who don't pay the full cost are not, apparently,
concerned. (About one-fifth do pay $279 a month or more.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is public housing, and we're part of the public,'' Lacy
says.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Holston, FWHA executive director, says regulations
actually encourage tenants to stay put and jobless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say someone moves into (Cavile), paying $50 a month on minimal
income,'' she says. ``She _ I say `she' because most of our tenants
are single mothers with children _ goes to school, gets a job, and
then her rent goes dramatically up. On the private market, if your
rent gets raised $10 or $25 a month, you get mad. Here, with the 30
percent of salary rule, it can easily increase from $50 to $200 or
more. Residents tend to think, `Why should I work? I get a job and
the Housing Authority takes the money I earn.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Walker believes that public housing tenants should have
obligations beyond paying minimal rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should have to participate in some kind of work
program,'' says Walker, who once lived in public housing. ``Even if
it's nothing more than getting out to clean up some public
property, they need to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA COTS
</P>
<P>
   Louis Booker enjoys lounging on his front steps in the evening.
He listens to the radio, sips beer and yells at kids to keep off
the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living here is all right,'' Booker muses. ``I still do some
work during the day, then come back and sit. I expect I'll live
here till death do me part. It would be better if there weren't so
many womens. Womens, you know, got to yell and argue all the time.
I wish there was a few more men.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker can wish all he wants. Cavile, like public housing in
general, is mostly populated by females. Even when there is a
live-in adult male in the picture, he usually is not listed on the
apartment lease because rents are based on combined occupant
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couples that live here, you can best believe, both of them
aren't on the lease,'' says Tina Dennis, a 31-year-old mother of
five. ``If my husband was on the lease, the rent would be too
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Most unofficial male live-ins do their best to stay out of
sight. Many are collectively identified as ``first-of-the-month
boyfriends,'' timing their arrival to coincide with their lovers'
government checks at the beginning of the month, and leaving a few
days or weeks later when the money runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Brooks, 52, who has lived in Cavile for more than 20
years, says young, lonely single mothers are desperate for
affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think about the times of the month that the men
show up,'' Brooks says. ``It's more important to them to be able to
say, `I have someone who kinda cares,' so they put up with that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men of Cavile show up at night, when the
administrative staff has gone home. They are hesitant to be
interviewed, worrying the housing authority might read their
comments and figure out who they are and where they are living.
</P>
<P>
   How many are there? A member of the Cavile maintenance crew
says, ``There's an extra cot in just about every apartment I go
into.''
</P>
<P>
   INTENT ON BREAKING AWAY
</P>
<P>
   The babies grow up _ often, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   One girl looks looks much younger than her 13 years. Her facial
features are soft, her limbs very thin and her body unremarkable
except for a bulging abdomen. Her child is due in early September.
(This 13-year-old and her mother will not be identified, to protect
the privacy of a minor.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happened,'' the girl says, fidgeting. Bit by bit, the
story emerges. When she was 12, her mother was sent to jail,
accused of striking her with a closed fist. Both mother and
daughter say this never happened.
</P>
<P>
   While her mother served a 90-day sentence, the girl lived with
her grandmother and met a streetwise 14-year-old who dared her to
have sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You scared,' and I did it to prove I wasn't,'' she
says. They had sex twice. She got pregnant; the boy, whose last
name she never knew, moved on to another girl.
</P>
<P>
   Now she weighs 96 pounds; 13 pounds is baby. She was an
eighth-grader at Morningside Middle School; now she's at New Lives,
a Fort Worth school district alternative for pregnant teens. She
hopes to finish school, and wants to be a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter moved to Cavile in May. The mother says she
``can't stand'' her little girl being pregnant. Yet abortion was
never an alternative: ``Our family thinks that's like killing
someone,'' the daughter says.
</P>
<P>
   The child who is about to give birth to a child never got a
birds-and-bees talk from Mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like she was an honor roll student,'' the mother says.
``I didn't know how to tell her about sex. I thought my telling her
would be like telling her to go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 13-year-old says she had sex because of a dare,
notes she wrote at the time tell a different story. Her mother
found them while going through the pockets of her daughter's
clothes before doing a load of laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wrote she was very, very lonely, and she didn't have
nobody to talk to,'' the mother says. ``She wrote she just wanted
to be loved. I read (the notes) and I just cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Williams, 30, got an early start, too. She has 12 children
and one on the way. Williams and her enlarging brood have lived in
Cavile for 11 years. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
