<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S SECRETARY APPEARS BEFORE GRAND JURY FOR FIFTH TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a clear signal that the independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, may be nearing the end of his criminal inquiry of
President Clinton, Betty Currie, Clinton's personal secretary,
testified on Wednesday before the grand jury here for the fifth and
final time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie was the first witness summoned to appear last
January before the federal grand jury, which is investigating
whether Clinton attempted to cover up a relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, the 24-year-old former White House intern. On that day,
Mrs. Currie, described by colleagues as sweet-tempered and fiercely
loyal to Clinton, appeared frightened and overwhelmed when scores
of reporters and photographers confronted her with cameras and
microphones on the courthouse steps.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Mrs. Currie appeared far more composed and
clearly relieved after she concluded a seven-hour session with
prosecutors that her lawyer said would be her last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that Mrs. Currie has completed her grand jury
testimony,'' said her lawyer, Lawrence Wechsler. ``We have not been
formally notified to that effect, but we do not have a date on
which to return. All I will tell you is that Mrs. Currie is happy
to have this behind her and she looks forward to returning to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie was drawn into the inquiry last January when
investigators working for Starr interviewed her at her Washington
home, just days after they received the authority from a
three-judge panel to investigate the matter. Since then, she has
emerged as one of Starr's critical witnesses, considered a friend
to Ms. Lewinsky as well as an observer of the comings and goings at
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying on Wednesday was Linda Tripp, the Pentagon
employee and former confidant of Ms. Lewinsky who surreptitiously
recorded 20 hours of her friend's discussions about her
relationship with Clinton and then turned them over to Starr's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp and Mrs. Currie literally passed each other on
Wednesday in the courthouse hallway, but they did not speak. Mrs.
Tripp arrived at the courthouse at 3:15 p.m., presumably to testify
for a sixth time. But Mrs. Currie did not finish her testimony
until 5:20 p.m., and Mrs. Tripp went home without testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp is expected to return to the courthouse on Thursday,
said her lawyer, Anthony Zaccagnini. He said he expected his client
would testify ``two or three'' more times. In addition, Secret
Service agent Larry Cockell, the head of the president's security
detail, is also expected to testify on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides serving as Clinton's gatekeepr, Mrs. Currie befriended
Ms. Lewinsky and may have knowledge about several pivotal events in
the weeks around the time that Ms. Lewinsky was under subpoena in
the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie signed in Ms. Lewinsky for a majority of her 37
visits to the White House after she stopped working there in April
1996, records show. Mrs. Currie also helped Ms. Lewinsky in her job
search in December and January. And perhaps most important, lawyers
have said that Mrs. Currie may have significant knowledge about a
White House meeting between Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky on Dec. 28,
the last day that records indicate that Ms. Lewinsky had visited
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the grand jury heard from two Secret Service
officers who one lawyer said may have knowledge about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie also knows about the circumstances surrounding the
gifts that Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton exchanged, and the efforts of
Ms. Lewinsky to return them to the White House after they had been
sought by lawyers for Mrs. Jones in a subpoena last December. In
statements given to Starr's office, Ms. Lewinsky has said she
returned the gifts after the president told her that she would not
have to turn over the gifts to the Jones legal team if they were
not in her possession.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known what Mrs. Currie has told prosecutors, who are
trying to determine whether Mrs. Currie accepted the gifts on her
own, at the request of Ms. Lewinsky or under orders from Clinton or
someone else.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, legal experts said that Starr could face
troubles if an appeals court refuses to overturn a decision by U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson to compel his prosecutors to
prove they did not illegally disclose secret grand jury material.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers familiar with the judge's ruling said that she was
extremely upset by Starr's own words, published in an interview
with Brill's Content, a new magazine that covers the news media. In
the interview, Starr said that he and a top deputy had occasionally
spoken with reporters, but on the condition that their names not be
used. But Starr adamantly denied that he or any members of his
office have leaked grand jury material to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Brentwood, Calif. on Wednesday, Ms. Lewinsky went
shopping and made plans for her 25th birthday celebration on
Thursday. She had planned to have a barbeque at her father's home
in Brentwood, but those plans were canceled on Wednesday after a
family spokeswoman, Judy Smith, became concerned that reporters
with zoom cameras would attempt to take photographs of the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ms. Lewinsky plans on having a quiet dinner with her
mother, father, stepparents and her brother, Michael. ``For her
birthday,'' Ms. Smith said, ``she wants her life back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
