<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-4000(3     07-22 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-4000(3rdTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UNLUCKY LIVE IN PUBLIC HOUSING
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH: for 11 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She thinks she might consider permanent birth control after No.
13 is born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I wanted one child, and look how I ended up,''
says Williams, who has no job and whose boyfriend, neighbors say,
recently left.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it keeps happening; ``I really don't know why,'' Williams
adds, vaguely waving at the toddlers crawling about the musty floor
in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Williams says she comes ``from a regular family, two parents at
home.'' But many adult Cavile women, Lacy says, are the offspring
of single mothers, and the cycle can continue for generations.
</P>
<P>
   But there are those, like LaTosha, who are intent on breaking
away. The 17-year-old doesn't live in Cavile, but she spends time
at a relative's place there, and she's learned how she ``doesn't''
want her own life to turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Girls ``my age, they see their parents messed up, and they do
the same thing,'' LaTosha says, shaking her head in bewilderment.
``Having kids don't mean you are grown. You can have a child and
still act like a child yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   So LaTosha, unlike her aunt, uses birth control. She plans to go
to college, then law school, and have children only after she's
about 30 _ and married.
</P>
<P>
   GANGS UNWELCOME
</P>
<P>
   The male children at Cavile sometimes struggle with poor
self-image, preferring nicknames to given names _ Butch Dawg, Li'l
Low. They often lie to classmates and potential girlfriends about
where they live.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father moved out in '89,'' says one 14-year-old boy. ``Left
us alone, period. I get mad at school, 'cause if I say I live in
`the projects' people say, `You poor, and you got no daddy,' and
they're right.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they believe they won't receive respect, some of the
boys settle for eliciting fear. However, gang membership in the
infamous Crips or Bloods gangs tempts fewer than the general public
might believe. ``Whitehead'' Smith says only gang wannabes live in
Cavile apartments, with real gang members and drug dealers
preferring surrounding Stop Six streets or the less-regulated
charms of a crumbling nearby apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Fleming, 17, scoffs at the Cavile boys lured to gangs _ and
people who assume that every housing project kid wears gang colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are weak-minded over here,'' says Bo, who plans to
attend the University of Texas at Austin on a track scholarship.
``And away from here, there are people who ask me why I ain't shot
nobody. Stupid question.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo and several of his friends lounging at the Boys &AMP; Girls Club
swear they're going to be real fathers to any children they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's after marriage, and for now marriage is not even in
my head,'' Bo adds quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, boys at Cavile learn about being responsible fathers
by helping their mothers raise younger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother wants all the kids in the house before dark,'' says
Li'l Bill, 15. ``So I go around and get 'em. I mean, we got 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Li'l Bill is Laura Williams' oldest child. He has lived in
Cavile since he was 2. Because his mother ``is stressing every
day,'' Li'l Bill spends many summer hours doing laundry and
escorting younger brothers and sisters to the Boys &AMP; Girls Club
programs he says ``help 'em live better.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get a job because I'm 15,'' L'il Bill says mournfully.
``I would in a second if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   So he'll settle for a college education and then a career in law
enforcement ``because it's good for people to feel like they're
being protected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I live in the projects,'' Li'l Bill, described as a
computer whiz, says defiantly. ``It's nothin' to be proud of, but
it's nothin' to be ashamed of, either. I won't be here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   UP AND OUT
</P>
<P>
   ``Forever'' was never meant to be part of life in public
housing. For many, it works out that way, but there are those with
plans to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first moved in here 12 years ago, I didn't intend to be
here my entire life or raise my kids here,'' Tina Dennis says.
</P>
<P>
   She has resolved to move out of Cavile and into a rental
property owned by her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a lot of things for myself,'' Dennis says. ``I want a
home, a job and I want my kids to be able to go to college. I think
these are things that I have always wanted. Sometimes it takes some
people longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacy is ``thinking'' about a move because her sons want separate
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In housing, the rule is children of the same sex got to sleep
in the same room,'' she says, sitting on her front step while the
family rabbit hops aimlessly nearby. ``But my oldest wants a dog,
and I'm tired of them fighting about who got into someone else's
space.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing authority tries to help tenants move up and out.
Each housing community offers job placement assistance, links with
Tarrant County Junior College classes and evening
``self-sufficiency'' courses that teach basics like how to make a
budget and stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   But programs for nonseniors are very poorly attended. Sometimes,
no residents sign up for the classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perhaps our greatest frustration,'' Holston says.
</P>
<P>
   To a limited extent, Walker says, the FWHA needs tenants with
jobs to stay in public housing when they could afford to move out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a certain income from rents, and people with jobs, of
course, pay more than the minimum,'' she says. ``For rent purposes,
too, we need to keep as many of the apartments filled as we can. We
have vacancies here right now. With our `One Strike and Out' policy
that says you're evicted for any felony or even being present
during a felony, we lose people that way. It can be hard to keep
the numbers up.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH A SMILE
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when Callie Pollard was part of a city delegation
meeting with President Clinton, she bragged about Fort Worth public
housing. A self-professed ``Christian lady,'' she is moved to
cursing by those who simply won't believe Cavile tenants are good
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people say just (angers) me,'' Pollard snaps. ``It
offends me deeply. All they'd have to do to know better is to come
and look.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, everybody ought to come and visit us. We'll greet you with
a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
