<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AEROMEXICO-LATINTRADE     07-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AEROMEXICO-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 HARD kNOCKS 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By BARBARA BELEJACK 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ Talk about business cycles.
 &HT;    Over the last decade, the Mexican flag carrier now known as
Aerovias de Mexico privatized, declared bankruptcy, refloated only
to have its new owners go bankrupt as well, acquired two other
major carriers, sold a major stake in one of them and watched as a
former CEO fled amid scandal.
 &HT;    Now, after a successful turnaround, executives are planning an
IPO this year to sell the government's stake in Cintra, the group
that controls Aeromexico and two other airlines. But as luck or
fate would have it, a strike launched in June by flight attendants
against Aeromexico forced the government to intervene once again to
keep the planes flying. Nothing, it seems, is easy at Aeromexico.
 &HT;    Pundits call it reprivatization. Aside from the recent takeover
to avoid a strike, the government's share in Cintra has been
growing, though the ownership structure is so complicated that even
top management does not know exactly how much the government owns.
Estimates put the stake at 45 percent, split between the Ministry
of Finance, state development bank Nafinsa and Fobaproa, the bank
bailout fund created after the peso crash.
 &HT;    The most recent transaction was Banco Mexicano's 22 percent
share. Spain's Banco Santander rescued the Mexican bank, but forced
the government to buy back its shares in the airline as part of the
deal.
 &HT;    In the early 1990s the privatization of Aeromexico was
considered one of the highlights of the Salinas administration,
celebrated in Harvard Business School case studies and World Bank
forums as the model business turnaround. But Aeromexico sank under
the weight of Mexico's economic crisis and the extravagant
purchases, such as Mexicana de Aviacion, a leading domestic
carrier, and a controlling interest in Aeroperu. With crises
mounting, high-flying chairman Gerardo de Prevoisin departed the
country in 1994 amid a torrent of accusations.
 &HT;    Soon after de Prevoisin's exile, Ernesto Martens, former
chairman of Grupo Vitro took the helm. Though he had no experience
in aviation, Martens insisted that he had logged a lot of airplane
miles and knew how to turn a company around. Martens slashed costs,
staff and air routes. Most importantly, he rescued the airline
group from failure by restructuring in a move that gave ownership
to a syndicate of banks, primarily Banco Mexicano, Bancomer,
Banamex and Serfin.
 &HT;    By the first quarter of 1996, the airline reported a profit for
the first time in several years and Martens presided over the
creation of Grupo Cintra, the holding company for three airlines:
Aeromexico, Mexicana and Aeroperu.
 &HT;    The restructuring has been successful for both Mexican airlines,
says Luis Frias, a Mexico City based aviation expert who runs his
own cargo business and praises Aeromexico and Mexicana for
management and timeliness. ``The two companies are money-makers.
They're well managed.''
 &HT;    Last year Cintra had revenues of US$2.2 billion, an increase of
6 percent over the previous year and passengers per kilometer
transported increased a tenth over the previous year. Together,
Mexicana and Aeromexico controls over two thirds of the domestic
air market and half of international traffic. The airlines have
added routes to South America and reopened routes to Europe that
were shut down in the midst of the peso crisis. Each has a
code-sharing agreement with U.S. carriers, United and Delta,
respectively. Delta has also taken a stake in Aeroperu.
 &HT;    Executives are ready to take the story to investors, in a bid to
get the airline out of government hands. ``The idea is to do an IPO
by the end of the year,'' says Cintra CFO Guillermo Turincio.
 &HT;    Even with Cintra's strong numbers, the sale of the government's
twice-owned airlines will be hard to get off the ground. The
fragmented shareholder structure _ banks, the finance ministry, the
ad hoc bailout fund and others _ will have to consolidate ownership
into a viable asset attractive to a buyer.
 &HT;    Politics and regulatory issues also stand in the way. The
bailout fund and its assets have come under scrutiny by Congress,
which also has expressed interest in Cintra's potential monopoly
power, an issue that could determine how and to whom the airlines
will be sold.
 &HT;    All these issues promise to make this year's IPO a daunting
challenge. But then, that's the nature of Mexico's troubled
airlines.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
