<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-NOMINEE-HNS &LR;      07-22 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-NOMINEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS QUIZ ENERGY SECRETARY NOMINEE ON LEWINSKY, NUCLEAR WASTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Pena) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.N. Ambassador Bill Richardson, nominated to
become the next energy secretary, fielded questions about Monica
Lewinsky, nuclear waste and even his sleeping arrangements at the
Watergate Hotel during a Senate confirmation hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And while some senators are threatening to hold up his
appointment because of a conflict with the Clinton administration
over nuclear waste disposal, Richardson said he is confident he
eventually will be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a few bumps,'' Richardson said after the
hearing. ``Nothing is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, the ranking Hispanic in the Clinton administration,
is vying to replace Federico Pena, who left the $148,000-a-year
post after less than a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate Committee
on Energy and Natural Resources, praised Richardson for bringing a
``refreshing enthusiasm'' for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski said he supported Richardson's nomination ``with some
reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski then led off the questioning Wednesday by asking
Richardson about his relationship with Lewinsky, the former White
House intern at the center of a grand jury investigation into an
alleged presidential affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson told the senators he agreed to interview Lewinsky for
a low-level, $30,000-a-year public relations job at the behest of
John Podesta, White House deputy chief of staff. Podesta described
her as a friend of Betty Currie, Clinton's personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't even know her name when he asked me to interview
her,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky met with Richardson and some staff members at a 7:30
a.m. appointment at Washington's Watergate Hotel. Richardson stays
at that hotel when visiting Washington and uses a suite there ``for
appointments and meetings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski then asked Richardson where he sleeps at the hotel, a
query that drew the ire of Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky. ``You want to
know where the guy sleeps?'' Ford asked.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, while noting that his chief of staff conducted the
interview, said he found Lewinsky ``impressive.'' He was struck by
her ``gregariousness'' and her ability to express herself.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's office eventually offered Lewinsky a job, which she
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski also asked Richardson to provide the names of the
other people who applied for the job. And while Murkowski promised
to keep those names confidential, Ford predicted the names would be
leaked the following day.
</P>
<P>
   While the testimony about Lewinsky gained the most public
attention, nuclear waste could be Richardson's biggest stumbling
block.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, has threatened to try to block
Richardson's appointment because of the Clinton administration's
response to concerns over disposal of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department, Craig complains, has collected $13
billion from utility companies with promises of having a long-term
storage facility for nuclear waste operational this year. Instead,
construction of the facility is still years away.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Congress want to construct a temporary storage site in
Nevada to handle waste now held at sites around the nation, but the
administration has opposed those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time the issue comes to a head,'' Craig said. ``I'm
sorry, Bill, it has to be you.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said a study on the viability of a long-term storage
facility would be completed by the end of the year. And he
repeatedly reminded lawmakers that if they confirmed him he could
spend his time trying to address their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., criticized Richardson and the United
Nations for their handling of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein. Nickles
complained about the leakage of oil out of Iraq in violation of
U.N. sanctions as well as the effort to allow Baghdad to export
more crude to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   While he may have faced some uncomfortable questions, Richardson
had the benefit of knowing he has the support of some powerful
Republican allies. Both Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., head of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, accompanied him to the
hearing and urged their colleagues to support his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was a lawmaker from New Mexico for 14 years. He left
Congress in 1997 to take over as the U.S. representative to the
United Nations. Known for his negotiating skills, he has twice been
nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 50, intrigued many observers with his decision to
abandon the United Nations for the relative obscurity of the Energy
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He has been mentioned as a possible vice presidential contender
and a probable New Mexico gubernatorial candidate, and many have
noted the energy post could be a helpful springboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a lawmaker from New Mexico, Richardson dealt with issues
affecting that state's national laboratories. He also represented
oil and gas producers in the San Juan Basin around the Four Corners
region.
</P>
<P>
   While in Congress he co-founded the House Renewable Energy
Caucus, which has helped promote the use of wind power as an
alternative energy source.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
