<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-DISMANTLE     07-22 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-DISMANTLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE NET TO BE USED IN REMOVING DAMAGED SCAFFOLD AND TOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NY-SCAFFOLD-COLLAPSE and NY-SCAFFOLD-IMPACT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It will be a curtain call the likes of which Broadway
has never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Seven hundred feet high and one hundred feet wide, more than an
acre and a half of reinforced black nylon netting will be required
to enclose the perilously damaged scaffold and exterior elevator
tower at the Conde Nast Building before workers can begin to
dismantle the twisted skeletal remains.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, this giant net _ imagine it as a
VERY tall shower curtain or what might result if Christo came to
Times Square _ will be hanging from the top of the skyscraper by
the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the curtain is up,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Wednesday, ``much of the area can return to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle for sidewalk superintendents promises to be
anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Construction began Wednesday on a specially designed, A-shaped
``outrigger,'' made of steel I-beams, that is to cantilever over
the side of the 49-story skyscraper. A square steel frame will be
suspended from the outrigger, along the length of which will hang
steel cables.
</P>
<P>
   Those cables will reach the ground, 700 feet below, and serve as
guy lines for the netting, which will be raised _ rather than
lowered _ into position, probably by winches. Then the towering
mesh curtain will be stretched taut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use the safety netting to create a kind of shower
curtain,'' said Buildings Commissioner Gaston Silva.
</P>
<P>
   The netting is not meant to support the scaffolding but to
protect the streets below. ``All along the scaffold are dangerous
objects, including objects that are flammable and explosive,'' the
mayor said, including acetylene tanks, tool boxes and even wood
planks, which could be lethal if they fell.
</P>
<P>
   What made the situation especially precarious at first, Silva
said, was that the upper scaffolding was no longer being supported
by the lower portion. Instead, it was resting on struts that are
intended only to stabilize the scaffolding; not hold it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top 25 stories of scaffolding are literally hanging from
the building,'' Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business, therefore, was to lash the
scaffolding more securely to the skyscraper. Beginning Tuesday
night, construction workers and firefighters threaded lengths of
steel cable around the lacy network of metal pipes and tied them to
sturdy perimeter columns on the side of the building itself, floor
by floor. That work was completed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The next protective step, which began Wednesday, involved the
cantilevering of steel beams every three to five floors. They are
to poke out from the building and into the scaffolding like
20-foot-long needles. Should parts of the scaffold break off, Silva
said, they would fall only a few feet before coming to rest on the
beams.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how long it will take to complete the job
of stabilizing and dismantling the crumpled scaffold and fallen
elevator tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's focus is on securing the damaged scaffold to the
building and putting in place the protective netting,'' said
Richard M. Kielar, senior vice president of Tishman Construction
Co. of New York, the construction manager of the project. ``All
parties involved are working 24 hours a day to accomplish this.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the curtain is in place, Silva said, the disassembling of
the scaffold and elevator tower might take another month.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will be lowered through the wide opening at the top of
the outrigger in large buckets at the end of two lines from the tip
of a tower crane perched atop the skyscraper. It has a
180-foot-long boom (almost the length of a city block) and can lift
26 tons (equivalent to 19 Volkswagen Beetles).
</P>
<P>
   Behind the soaring scrim, a worker in one bucket will use a
torch to cut apart the scaffold and adjoining elevator tower. A
worker in the other bucket will collect the pieces for removal.
</P>
<P>
   These pieces, as well as the debris and planking from the
scaffold, will probably be passed to other workers inside the
building and then lowered through the building itself, Silva said,
rather than along the exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday morning, the red elevator tower provided a
strikingly slender counterpoint to the fat skyscraper it served. It
is not much more than a small truss, two or three feet on each
side, set on end. Two passenger elevators, known as hoists, ran up
and down its length, ferrying workers.
</P>
<P>
   A trip on this hoist may have been a routine commute for the
construction crew, but for a visitor to the job site, it was a
breathtaking journey.
</P>
<P>
   It conjured nothing so much as a ride in the gondola of a
hot-air balloon rising slowly _ and noisily _ from Times Square, or
the agonizing ascent to the top of the Parachute Jump. (Only this
was two-and-a-half times higher than the one at Coney Island.)
</P>
<P>
   The hoist would lurch sharply as the operator stopped to pick up
workers and drop them off. At those moments, it also seemed as if
the whole tower was swaying ever so slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Because the building has several setbacks, it appeared from
inside the hoist as if the tower were pulling farther and farther
away as the cab made its way into the sky, heightening the dizzying
sense of suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top of the house!'' the operator would shout on reaching the
last stop: the 48th floor, 657 feet, 6 inches above the sidewalk.
From there, workers walked along wooden planking supported by the
scaffold to get into the building.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the air seem thinner up there, but the
mid-Manhattan landscape was rendered strangely unfamiliar by the
perspective: looking down on the giant fins of 1515 Broadway, down
on the ornate pyramid of Worldwide Plaza, down on the silvery
mansard roof of 1585 Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
