<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-STRUG-LADN     07-22 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-STRUG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUG REMAINS INSPIRING FIGURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Lifetime procrastinators, disabled individuals,
grown men in airports everywhere and children -- her favorite --
won't allow Kerri Strug's valiant vault two years ago today fade
away.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA sophomore who will transfer to Stanford this fall said
matter-of-factly that she's also a home wrecker, sort of. Females
in poor relationships or bad marriages have informed her that her
gutsy leap in the Atlanta Olympics gave them the faith and
inspiration to start over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd been in a bad situation, saying they had to realize
that they had to do something to make it better,'' said Strug, 20.
``They didn't know what to do, and they'd resolved to do what's
best for them because of what they saw in me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing to think that, in a couple of seconds, my
life changed and I made an impact on so many people in the world.
To me, it was my job to make that vault. No matter what the
circumstances were, I was supposed to do it. Now I realize why it
made such an impact. It was a pretty special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Peterson, Strug's San Francisco-based manager, and Strug
are almost always amazed by stories they hear of Strug's influence.
One overweight girl who shed 40 pounds turned her bedroom into a
Strug shrine, and an elderly woman attributes a life-saving daily
walking routine to Strug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, and we always walk away going, `Wow!' '' Peterson
said of the many functions she attends with Strug. ``I remember
looking up to Mary Lou Retton and the impact she made on me,''
Strug said. ``I never thought I'd be in a similar situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 23, 1996, the unassuming 4-foot-9, 90-pound dynamo known
as Baby in U.S. gymnastics coach Bela Karolyi's tumbling stable put
her mind over matter, and her team over herself, to etch perhaps
the most indelible moment at the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu had bitten the Georgia Dome pad on her two
vaults to excite the gaining Russians at the end of the team
competition, and then Strug flubbed her 1 1/2 twisting Yurchenko.
</P>
<P>
   With only 30 seconds to attempt her second and final vault,
Strug tried standing on the pad but slipped onto her right knee.
Her left hand reached back to rub two torn ligaments in her left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a prayer and a boost of adrenaline projected
Strug full-throttle down the runway, over the apparatus and into
the soul of a nation. She landed square, heard another crack from
her left ankle and still executed a pirouette, her left knee bent
with her left foot six inches off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown at the time, the U.S. women would have still won their
first team Olympic gold medal because of average floor routines by
the last two Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Strug's 9.712 score, though, locked it up. But her aggravated
injury prevented her from competing in the individual all-around,
for which she had prepared for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it first happened, I thought it was the end of the world
because I didn't get to accomplish all the personal goals I had set
for myself,'' Strug said. ``Now, two years later, I realize I
probably accomplished a lot more and made more of an impact than if
I had won an individual medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything turns out for the best. Sometimes, you don't
realize it at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Strug is very active with half a dozen charitable organizations,
including the Special Olympics, Children's Miracle Network and
Muscular Dystrophy, and her docket is filled with
motivational-speech engagements.
</P>
<P>
   She figures she has spent six weekends in Southern California
since she moved here to attend UCLA after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Atlanta, I thought I'd go to college, compete in
gymnastics and study pre-Med,'' Strug said. ``I definitely didn't
think I'd be on an airplane every weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosting ``Saturday Night Live'' in the fall of 1996 was another
windfall, and Strug displayed a keen sense of self-deprecating
humor when one skit featured a parody of her stunning vault.
</P>
<P>
   She has written ``Landing on my feet: Diary of dreams,''
detailing her life from when she left home in Tucson at 13 to train
with Karolyi in Houston up to the Olympics, and ``Heart of gold,''
a children's book.
</P>
<P>
   Her height, high-pitched voice and heart are magnets to kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They relate to me,'' she said. ``I'm relaxed with them and I
have a great time. I think they can feel that and feed off that.
Kids are our future, and I think it's important that they have good
role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of problems out there. There are a lot of bumps
in the road, a lot of down times, but I tell them not to be normal.
Try to be extraordinary. They need someone to give them a push, to
say, `You can do it. You can beat the odds.' That's the best thing
I've gotten out of Atlanta, making an impact on kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Strug is interning at ``Entertainment Tonight'' this summer.
Soon she'll pack up her 3-year-old green BMW 318i in front of the
Kappa Alpha Theta sorority and zip to Stanford, her mother
Melanie's alma mater whose undergraduate population is about a
third of UCLA's claustrophobic 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   A stint helping out the Bruins' gymnastics team turned Strug
into more of a cheerleader than an assistant, an uncomfortable
position for anyone who has competed at the highest international
level.
</P>
<P>
   She might even return to the area for graduate school or to
break into the entertainment industry, public relations, marketing
or television.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for now it's time to find new goals, to move on to the
next chapter,'' Strug said. ``Atlanta seems so long ago, but in
other ways it seems like yesterday. It's odd. To me, I was just
Kerri the gymnast, and tomorrow no one would care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then overnight, everyone knew me. I didn't realize it would
last so long, but it's just kept going. It makes me feel
privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
