<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-RESIGNATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILTON ACADEMY HEADMASTER SAYS HE'LL RESIGN IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edwin P. Fredie, the first black headmaster to lead a private
preparatory school in New England, has announced his intention to
resign as headmaster of Milton Academy, effective June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fredie leaves with a long list of financial, academic, and
administrative achievements, including a capital campaign that in
three years raised $42.9 million for increased faculty salaries and
support, student financial aid, and substantial improvements to the
school's buildings and grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But he also is resigning amid more of what communications
director Cathleen Everett called ``the yeasty conflict'' that has
marked his tenure _ this time concerning his decision not to
reappoint the popular dean of the academy's middle school, Jill
Crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Fredie, 53, of Hingham, Mass., did not respond to a Globe
request for an interview. But Everett said Fredie's resignation was
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had completed all the tasks the trustees set out for him.
He had completed seven years as headmaster, and the average tenure
for that sort of job is less than five years,'' Everett said. ``He
was ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fund-raising, Fredie presided over six years of
balanced budgets, construction of a new athletic and convocation
center and a new observatory, renovation of the main library, and
full computerization of the academy's classrooms, offices, and
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, applications for admission increased by 15
percent, student financial aid rose from $1.7 million in 1991 to
$2.9 million in 1997-98, and persons of color accounted for 25
percent of the student body and 17 percent of the faculty, up from
roughly 22 and 12 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; H. Marshall Schwarz, president of the board of trustees, said
that because of Fredie's efforts, both the academy's ``reputation
for excellence and prospects for the future have never been
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   But some faculty members and parents said they were
neither &UR;  &LR; unhappy nor surprised to learn of Fredie's
resignation. &UR;  &LR; He has been a controversial figure at the prestigious
academy _ one of the largest independent schools in the United
States _ since he took its top job in 1991. He was non-traditional
and, as former principal of Needham (Mass.) High School, from a
public school background.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, some parents and faculty complained that his
style was ``too autocratic,'' said one parent Wednesday who is
closely involved in school affairs.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Boston Latin School, Boston University, and
Harvard Graduate School of Education, Fredie was the academy's
unanimous choice to succeed Jerome Pieh, who had served as
headmaster for 17 years. Members of the 1991 search committee
praised Fredie as ``a gifted problem solver'' who had done wonders
for Needham High School, despite serious budget constraints.
</P>
<P>
   But when his resignation was announced, ``it was a real relief
to most members of the faculty,'' said an upper school teacher who
asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Fredie's latest conflict involved Crafts, who in June completed
a five-year term as dean of the academy's middle school. When a
search committee recommended three candidates for the job, without
prioritizing them, Crafts was one of the three contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Everett, Fredie decided not to reappoint
Crafts or to accept any of the committee's other recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the final interviews for the middle school job,
he also was reviewing final candidates for position of dean of
students at the upper school. He developed the opinion that middle
school management needed a different approach than what had gone on
in the past,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that Fredie decided to eliminate the middle school
dean's job, shifting responsibilities so that many of those tasks
would be taken by two class deans _ Don Dregalla and Lenna Dower _
representing the seventh and eighth grade classes.
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty and parents were upset by Fredie's decision, and
Everett described Crafts as ``extremely upset at not being
reappointed.'' Whether she will remain on the faculty at all ``is a
personnel matter that is still in process,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   Crafts declined to comment Wednesday on her dispute with Fredie,
except to say that she will not resign. Everett insisted that
Fredie's resignation had nothing to do with the Crafts conflict,
and did not reflect discontent from the faculty. ``He initiated the
idea himself in June,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his tenure, Fredie ``intends to take some time off
to determine what his next steps will be,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   A successor to Fredie has not yet been named. But Everett said a
search committee is being appointed, with hopes that the next
headmaster _ the eleventh to head the academy in its 200-year
history _ will be chosen sometime early in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
