<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SAILING-STANDARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING THE WATERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(runs with sailing story) 
By JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The American Sailing Association administers the
following keelboat certifications:
</P>
<P>
   Basic Keelboat Sailing: Sailors must sail a keelboat of about 20
feet in moderate wind and sea conditions in familiar waters without
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Coastal Cruising: Sailors must cruise safely in local and
regional waters as both skipper and crew on an auxiliary-powered
sailboat of about 20 to 30 feet in moderate winds and sea
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   From there, sailors can test for a series of additional
certifications, including (in ascending order): Bareboat
Chartering, also known as Intermediate Coastal Cruising; Coastal
Navigation; Advanced Coastal Cruising; Celestial Navigation; and
Offshore Passagemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced sailors may challenge any of the ASA standards by
demonstrating both sailing knowledge and on-water skills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-INSURER-TAXCUT-BOS     07-22 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURER-TAX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE TAX CUT FACES AIRING IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
 CUT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts Senate plans to debate Thursday its
version of a tax cut bill for insurers that would require
significantly more community investment by the industry than a
similar House proposal, a difference that could stall the measure
this session.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, a tougher version of legislation approved by the
House &UR;  &LR; in May, has cheered advocates for disadvantaged communities
but dismayed cost-conscious &UR;  &LR; insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bill approved Wednesday by the Senate Ways and Means
Committee, insurers headquartered in Massachusetts would be
required to invest $250 million in community investment funds in
exchange for wide-ranging tax relief. The amount, to be invested
over five years, is significantly greater &UR;  &LR; than the $150 million
called for by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said it was possible they would vote on the Senate
bill today, although it appeared unlikely a final bill would be
approved by the full Legislature before the session ends July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also contains measures designed to give
community advocates a greater say in how money is directed to
minority-owned and women-owned businesses, job creation efforts,
and affordable-housing projects in low-income areas. One provision
calls for two community representatives to sit on each of two
committees that will oversee how community investment &UR;  &LR; money is
spent. Another creates a statewide advisory committee to represent
the insurance industry before lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are quarreling over how much in-state insurers should
invest in disadvantaged communities in exchange for tax breaks that
could save the industry up to $69 million a year, according to
lawmakers. Massachusetts insurers, who pay some of the highest
taxes in the industry, have complained for years that tax burdens
make them uncompetitive against out-of-state insurers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Community advocates say profitable insurers can afford to
spend more in lower-income areas just as banks have been required
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and House measures would phase out over five
years the 14 percent tax on net &UR;  &LR; investments currently paid by life
insurers. They would also eliminate two taxes now paid by
Massachusetts property and casualty insurers _ a 0.28 percent
surtax paid on premiums sold, and a 1 percent gross investment tax
on worldwide income.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the House measure, the Senate bill contains a tax credit
that covers all insurers in Massachusetts and is designed to
encourage out-of-state insurance firms to participate in community
investment. The credit would equal 1.5 percent of the amount
insurers commit to community initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the $250 million community reinvestment funds, the Senate
bill requires property and casualty firms to pony up $150 million,
or twice as much as the House bill. Life insurers would provide one
third more, or $100 million. Lawmakers expect insurers to finance
community investment contributions from tax savings. Either bill
would save the industry at least $50 million and up to $69 million
a year when fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry's initial reaction to the Senate's
proposal was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to working out the differences (between the
Senate and House versions) in conference,'' said Stephen L. Brown,
chief executive of Boston-based John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance
Co. He was referring to the process by which lawmakers will agree
on a final, possibly compromise, bill before submitting a document
to Acting Gov. Celluci for signing &UR;  &LR;  into law.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Francis C. O'Brien, regional head of the Alliance of American
Insurers, a trade group representing property and casualty
insurers, said he was disappointed by the Senate bill. ``The
numbers are too big and we don't think it can work,'' he said,
referring to the higher community investment requirements. But
community activists hailed the Senate version. ``It's a big step
forward,'' said Thomas Callahan, head of the Massachusetts
Affordable Housing Alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
