<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      07-22 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SIGN CHRIS TAYLOR, BRANDON SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins signed two more players Wednesday, including
the younger brother of center Tim Taylor. Agreeing to terms on
one-year contracts were center Chris Taylor and defenseman Brandon
Smith. Both were unrestricted free agents and were signed in order
to add depth to the Boston roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with the signing of Peter Ferraro (Tuesday), both Chris and
Brandon have been successful at the minor league level and we
believe they are ready to take the next step into the NHL,'' said
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``I think there will be a
lively competition at training camp among all of our young players,
not just the recent additions but players who were already in the
organization. Part of our success last season came from the
enthusiasm of our younger players and the coach's ability to
develop them, and we would like to see that continue this season
with other young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 26, has spent the last six seasons in the Islanders'
organization after being drafted as their second pick, 27th
overall, in 1990. The 6-foot, 189-pound native of Stratford,
Ontario, was second in scoring for the International Hockey
League's Utah Grizzlies last season with 28 goals and 84 points in
79 games.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Smith is a native of Hazelton, British Columbia,
and played last season in the Detroit organization. The 6-1,
196-pounder had nine goals and 36 points in 64 games with
Adirondack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
