<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITHUANIAN-RUMOR-BOS &LR;      07-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITHUANIAN-RUMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITHUANIANS SINK RUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lithuanian sailors who are docked here for the USS
Constitution Bicentennial Salute survived three weeks of driving
rain and tumultuous seas on a trip from the Baltic Sea to Boston
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could have prepared the 47 men and one woman aboard
the 180-foot-long Gore Agor-Ax Vetra for the stormy public
relations brouhaha into which they sailed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a move that had phones ringing, dock crews buzzing, and
Captain Lieutenant Vytautus Mogenis shaking his head. And it had
two of the best-known product and event boosters in town wishing
Wednesday _ uncharacteristically _ that nobody was calling them.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow word got out that the Lithuanians were in need of
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that information from Conventures Inc., the company
running the bicentennial festival, local PR person Sally Jackson
tried to turn the situation into a special-event splash.
</P>
<P>
   But she and her friend Dusty Rhodes, who heads Conventures, were
left all wet when the proud crew members told a translator that
they never expressed a need for supplies, and they did not want to
be part of a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, those caught in the chain of miscommunication
could not say where it all began. Or, they would not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not talking Lithuania,'' said the unsinkable Rhodes. ``I
have never seen a rumor so out of control in this city. It is
nothing. It is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was hardly an international incident, but it was
something, according to those who were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was wrong right away,'' said Jackson, public
relations chief of Jackson &AMP; Company. ``The sailors kind of started
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jackson who sent out a citywide SOS on behalf of the
Lithuanians, telling media outlets the sailors had arrived in town
``without adequate funding and in need of basic supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told news outlets in town to meet her at the dock in the
morning, where she would personally deliver the much-needed
rations: 10 cases of Samuel Adams beer, dozens of H.P. Hood &AMP; Co.
ice cream Hoodsies, and a boatload of Veryfine juices, all donated
by some of her very best clients. But pushing her clients' wares,
she said Wednesday, had nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   `The reason I wanted to get attention for it had to do with the
boat, not with the products,'' said Jackson, explaining that she
was hoping the publicity would prompt local residents to respond
with supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lithuanian captain told a visitor, a Lithuanian-American
who is serving as a local liaison, that the story was fishy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had called him up and asked him if he wanted some
American beer,'' said Gintaras Cepas, the liaison and translator.
``They were confused as to why the reporters were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They planned the trip. They stocked what they needed. And they
will restock at the dock like everyone else,'' said Cepas. ``I
don't know how that idea came out. They were upset. They are not
running low on food. They are not running low on fuel. They are not
running low on water. And they are certainly not running low on
beer because they brought a good stock of Lithuania beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Crockford, a Massachusetts Port Authority spokesman, said
the agency also picked up the information that the Lithuanians were
in need and made a plea to the local community for help.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Rhodes said the confusion stemmed from a
misunderstanding over the words ``want'' and ``need.'' Jackson said
a Conventures Inc. staffer misunderstood that the captain was in
``need'' of liquids. Instead, she said, he must have indicated he
``wanted'' to try some American products.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conversation with Conventures was that, in his
understanding, there was an offer for some local beer,'' Cepas
said. ``There was no conversation about food or any other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where the spin came in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITHUANIAN-RUMOR-BOS &LR;      07-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITHUANIAN-RUMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITHUANIANS SINK RUMOR 
