<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-ANDRUW-COX     07-22 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-ANDRUW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting Andruw's attention
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA -- The first thing anyone sees upon entering the
Braves' clubhouse beneath Veterans Stadium is the baby blue lineup
card taped to the wall facing the door, which was where Andruw
Jones learned he was back in the lineup Wednesday night. But then
that fits the pattern whenever Atlanta's problem child has been
sent to his room these past two years. Bobby Cox always lets him
out the next night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered (benching him) but I didn't think it was in the
best interest of him or me right now. Or the team,'' Cox said. ``My
job is to get him going, not sit him down. That's a manager's job _
get his butt in gear and playing on the same page as everybody
else, abiding by the same rules.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after, there was still some disbelief among the Braves
that Jones had been drummed off the field the night before, after
allowing Lance Johnson's soft liner to fall at his feet. Jones was
humiliated, which was surely part of Cox's rationale. But then to
those who has witnessed Jones' ascension to the majors, humility
has never been his long suit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It embarrassing,'' Jones said. ''The fans were booing and
stuff but they don't know. They weren't in my shoes. I made a
mental mistake and it cost me right there. But these things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Braves tried to find the 21-year-old some slack.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look at it, the only way to learn in this game is to make
mistakes and learn from them,'' said Greg Maddux. Andruw's a young
player, he made a mistake and I bet he learns from it. We've all
been through it before _ brain cramps, memory lapses, concentration
problems _ we've all been there.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell you,'' said Andres Galarraga, ''if there's somebody
who's played hard on the field all year, it's him. He's made too
many great plays to let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But in some corners there is a real concern about Jones'
development. Cox has continued to fine him, for offenses ranging
from missed signals, tardiness, missing a team picture and finally
reporting late after the All-Star break due to travel difficulties
July 9. At some point, a failure to learn eventually becomes
defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to help him since he got here,'' said catcher
Eddie Perez. ``I don't know if he listens or he doesn't listen.
Whenever I say something to him, he says, ``Okay, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is worried about Jones, Perez replied immediately,
``Yeah, because if he looks bad, then we look bad. And I'm not
talking about the team. I'm talking about the Latin players.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an anticipation with Galarraga's signing that Jones
might benefit from a senior Latin presence in the clubhouse. But if
there has been a bond between the two, it has not done much for
Cox, who was just as critical of Jones Wednesday as he was the
night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never tolerated anything,'' the manager said. ``I can't
stand that. And I won't tolerate it. It's not like he's a real bad
guy or anything like that. He's not. It's just that there are
certain ways you play the game and that's the way it is. If you
don't want to do it, then go home. It's very simple to me. You
don't like the game? Quit! Leave!''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested Jones may have missed some lessons in
baseball tradition from his rapid three-year rise through the
Braves' system, Cox bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``They were on him since the day he
signed down there. And everybody is saying, they were too easy on
him. Hey, they were on him. He didn't miss out on a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has seen the replay from Tuesday but refuses to view the
incident as anything more than a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right there,'' he said. ``I should have caught it. But
I don't know what the fans are thinking. I know when I get out
there, I'm trying to do my best and help my team. I just made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what Jones does between those mistakes that keeps him out
there. The frustrations the organization endures over Jones are
matched by its anticipation of the finished player.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he learns to play the game,'' Perez said, ``he's going to
be the best ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
