<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLS-COACH-COX     07-22 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls' move makes Jordan exit likely
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Tim Floyd is an obscure college basketball coach with
no track record of significant success, but barring a dramatic
change of heart, he will be named today as coach of the NBA team of
the 1990s, the six-time champion Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The hire likely will jettison Michael Jordan into permanent
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, speculation has been rampant in Chicago that
Bulls general manager Jerry Krause wanted coach Phil Jackson out of
the picture so he could hire Floyd, his buddy and fishing partner
of 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   When Floyd resigned as head coach at Iowa State on Wednesday,
that scenario came one step closer to realization. The Bulls are
expected to make it official today.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, after six championships in eight years, refused a
one-year contract extension last month, leaving the door open for
Krause to nab Floyd, who complied a 243-130 college career record
with five NCAA Tournament berths.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, 44, apparently will take over the league's most
successful franchise, the team that sold out everywhere it went,
the team that played some serious basketball along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring brings forth many questions. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave Jordan, the sport's ultimate winner and
attraction? He has at least one more year of
better-than-everyone-else basketball in him, but has repeatedly
vowed to eschew a final run if Jackson is not the coach.
</P>
<P>
   And can Krause, the crumpled executive, bear the burden of being
labeled as the man who ran Jordan out of basketball?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions fuel the fire that has surrounded the Bulls
during the last year. Now it's come down to a perplexing triangle _
three men and a controversy.
</P>
<P>
   'Pink' Floyd: A casual meeting at the NCAA Final Four in 1987
turned out to be the defining moment that now thrusts Tim Floyd
into the NBA lexicon. It was then that Floyd, then head coach at
New Orleans, was introduced by UNO athletics director Ron Maestri
to Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   The two men chatted it up and immediately began a friendship
that turned into weekend fishing expeditions. As Krause grew closer
to Floyd, his relationship with Phil Jackson deteriorated. They
hardly spoke to each other on non-basketball related issues in the
last three years. And when Krause invited Floyd and his family to
his daughter's wedding two years ago and did not send Jackson an
invitation, their discord was cemented.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson finally said ``enough,'' and Krause began the
replacement search almost immediately, interviewing a group of
underwhelming candidates: Charlotte assistant coach Paul Silas,
Phoenix assistant Scott Skiles, Indiana aide Rick Carlisle,
Cleveland retread assistant Ron Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd was flown by private jet to meet with owner Jerry
Reinsdorf 10 days ago and again on Sunday. When he resigned on
Wednesday he told his Iowa State players during a 7 a.m. meeting
that he would be the Bulls' next coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of expected it, but the moment it happens, it's kind
of shocking,'' Iowa State forward Klay Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd almost pulled a Bobby Cremins in 1994, but he's not
expected to change his mind with this decision. After accepting the
Iowa State job, Floyd called a news conference at New Orleans,
where he told reporters he had decided to stay at UNO. His reason:
He said he'd rather go bass fishing in Louisiana than ice fishing
in Iowa. But when Iowa State sweetened the offer, Floyd left.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports last week that Floyd nearly backed away from
the Bulls' job because he did not want to be viewed as the man who
ran Jordan out of the game. He got over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a shock to anyone close to the scene had
Tim Floyd not been hired,'' said David Falk, Jordan's agent. ``This
was a decision that was made a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jordan said he would not play for a college coach. He
called Floyd, ``Pink,'' as in the rock group Pink Floyd. Dennis
Rodman chimed in, calling Floyd's possible hiring ``a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fun's just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The game-winner: Although he said he will not make an official
announcement until the NBA labor strife is resolved, Jordan's
basketball career seems over, at 35. In one way, that would not be
a bad thing, considering that Jordan penned an awesome ending with
the game/championship-winning baskets against Utah in June. Problem
is, he wants to play another season, but not in a rebuilding
situation.
</P>
<P>
   And to Jordan, Floyd's hire equals rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything against Tim Floyd,'' Jordan said. ``He
doesn't know the way I play, and I don't know the way he coaches. I
just don't feel like I want to start with someone who doesn't
really know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan reportedly refused a get-acquainted meeting with Floyd
last week. Now, with Floyd on the brink of the job, Jordan sounds
closer to the door than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted someone to put a foot in my butt and kick me
out,'' Jordan said. ``When I walk away, I want you all to realize I
can still lead the league in scoring. I can still lead the Chicago
Bulls to a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, in his most solemn tone: ``I've always stuck to my
guns,'' Jordan said. ``I always said I would not play without Phil
Jackson. I haven't changed that. I just haven't made an official
announcement. I won't make that until the time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tick. Tick. Tick.
</P>
<P>
   The 'mad gerbil': Despite the Bulls' success, Krause is viewed
as practically sinister in Chicago. It was Krause who hired
Jackson, who drafted Horace Grant and traded for Scottie Pippen and
embarked on a exhausting (and successful) pursuit of Croatian Toni
Kukoc. He signed the troubled, but badly needed, Rodman when Grant
signed with Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Krause also signed role players _ Ron Harper, Steve Kerr and Luc
Longley and everyone else on the Bulls' roster.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but Jordan, that is.
</P>
<P>
   So, for all his maneuvering, the ultimate respect still, in some
ways, eludes him. To wit: A Chicago sports columnist referred to
him during the NBA Finals as a ``mad gerbil.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause knew that hiring Floyd would alienate Jordan _ and
probably Scottie Pippen, too _ but he sought his friend anyway. He
had the power because Reinsdorf has entrusted the organization to
Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will work out. Maybe Jordan will give Floyd a try and
persuade Pippen and Rodman to play, too. And maybe Krause will
remembered as the guy who saved the Bulls, not engineered the
team's demolition.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a good Floyd-Krause fish story.
</P>
<P>
   TIm Floyd File
</P>
<P>
   Age: 44.
</P>
<P>
   Born: Feb. 25, 1954, Hattiesburg, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Career coaching record: 243-130, .651 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching background: Hired in May 1994 as Iowa State's 15th
basketball coach and team went 81-47 in four seasons. First coach
to bring Cyclones to three straight first-round victories in the
NCAA tournament. Runner-up to Purdue's Gene Keady for AP Coach of
the Year in 1997. He went 127-58 in six seasons at New Orleans.
Team reached NCAA Tournament in 1991 and 1993. First head coaching
job was at Idaho, where he worked two seasons with a 35-25 record.
He spent nine seasons as an assistant under Don Haskins at Texas-El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Family: wife Beverly and daughter Shannon, 16. His late father,
Lee Floyd, coached Southern Mississippi for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Education: B.S. in health and physical education at Louisiana
Tech, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
