<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves, Buchanan have differing concepts of fun
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta Falcons head coach Dan Reeves said he and his
staff are ready for the opening of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   It begins today at 3 p.m., when the team holds its first session
at the practice facility in Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been excited about our offseason, but as the first day
(of training camp) gets closer, you get more butterflies in your
stomach,'' Reeves said. ``We've had a lot of work in shorts, but
you can't tell a lot from that. This is when it starts getting
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a matter of perspective, of course. Eighty players will
compete for 53 jobs in the oppressive Georgia heat.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan, who is entering his sixth season in the NFL, is a
virtual lock to make the team. He regards training camp as one dry
_ or rather very hot and sweaty _ run after another.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be here? ``No,'' Buchanan said Wednesday, while setting
up hotel arrangements in Suwanee. ``There's nothing fun about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves plans to keep his daily practice schedule flexible. But
the Falcons are expected to practice twice Friday and Saturday, at
9 a.m. and 3 p.m. The workouts are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
