A8217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGED-CARE23-COX     07-22 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP TO UNVEIL COMPROMISE ON MANAGED CARE
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR and MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an attempt to bolster patients' recourse against
their health-care insurers, House Republicans will unveil a measure
Thursday that would authorize stiff fines on managed care companies
that deny needed care and allow doctors to continue treatment while
the case is disputed in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure from Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., keeps intact
what health-care companies want most: a 1974 law that protects
insurance companies and health maintenance organizations from
punitive damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see the measure as a way to bolster a politically
popular bill that would regulate the way managed care is
administered across the country. Graham and other key Republicans
say it would have the same effect as lawsuit seeking punitive
damage awards because it would allow a judge to impose fines of
$1,000 per day, up to $250,000, for making adverse medical
decisions in a ``bad-faith manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This tears down the legal immunity laws that HMOs have,'' said
Graham, who said Wednesday he was ``99 percent sure'' that House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., would support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., chairman of the Gingrich-appointed
House Republican task force on health care, said he would support
Graham's proposal. ``I think it is a perfecting change,'' said
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a GOP caucus meeting about the health-care bill,
Rep. Charlie Norwood of Georgia said he would also support the
Graham proposal. Norwood's endorsement is important, because it was
his ``patient protection'' bill that brought the issue of
regulating the managed care industry to the front burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a dictator it would be different,'' said Norwood,
who has pushed for removing the liability protection granted health
management companies. ``But this really improves the external
review process for the patient, and that's what I care the most
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's proposal exposed cracks in the GOP caucus in the
contentious debate over how best to overhaul managed care. Just
Tuesday, Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., said that Republican leaders
would not support giving patients the right to sue HMOs for
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sneered at Graham's proposal, saying it was an attempt
to make it look like the GOP is being tough on managed care without
going as far as the Democratic bill, which would remove the
liability protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to treat cancer with a Band-Aid,'' said Rep.
James McDermott, D-Wash. ``Managed care is a patient that needs
radical surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
