A8221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUN-COX     07-22 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going to jail for the cause
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Today, Sister Marge Eilerman learns how much
time she will spend behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old Franciscan nun, a Fort Loramie native, will be
sentenced by a federal judge in Columbus, Ga., this morning.
Eilerman faces up to 16 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Her crime: damaging government property during a protest at the
School of the Americas at Ft. Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The school trains Latin American soldiers, some of whom have
gone on to compile nefarious human rights records. Graduates
include former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega and the leaders
of death squads in El Salvador and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Eilerman's activism has won the respect and support of her
family, many of whom still live in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm behind her all the way,'' said her brother, Sidney
insurance agent Ralph Eilerman. ``There's no doubt in my mind that
it takes a pretty strong person to stand up and do what she's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Eilerman grew up in Fort Loramie, leaving at the age of 20 to
join the Franciscan convent in Tiffin, Ohio. She worked in schools
across the state before spending time in Chiapas, a state in
Mexico's southern region.
</P>
<P>
   She said that during stays there in the 1970s and in 1994, she
saw the devastation government troops wreaked upon the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she attended a religious conference in Georgia and
became aware of the U.S. government's role in training foreign
soldiers. She attended her first protest at Fort Benning that week
and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   She was arrested four times during demonstrations and convicted
twice. Her latest conviction _ the one for which she'll be
sentenced today _ stems from an incident last September.
</P>
<P>
   Eilerman and fellow activists removed letters from the school's
welcome sign and painted new slogans upon it: ``School of
Assassins'' and ``School of Shame.'' They also covered the sign
with red handprints _ a mixture of paint and one demonstrator's
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the protesters _ including a Jesuit priest _ were
convicted of damaging government property in March.
</P>
<P>
   Eilerman had an earlier conviction for trespassing at the
school, which brought a six-month sentence. However, she was able
to postpone prison until this case ended.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Rowland, Eilerman's attorney, said she could get as much as
10 months today. She likely will have to report to a federal
minimum security prison within the next 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of Sister Marge becoming an inmate baffles many in
Eilerman's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that she'll go to federal prison because she did
anywhere from $300 to $4,000 worth of damage, depending on who you
talk to,'' said Ralph Eilerman. ``But these (School of America
graduates) who've killed, none of them have gone to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, Botkins resident Edna Fullenkamp, said Eilerman's
fervor about the school has convinced the rest of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really sincerely think, and so do the rest of us, that this
is what needs to be done, that it needs to be closed down,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eilerman hopes she'll be able to serve her time in Lexington,
Ky., not far from the Appalachian church where she now works with
the poor as a missionary.
</P>
<P>
   She added that if the Georgia school isn't closed by the time
she emerges from prison, she will be prepared to risk another
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certain that the issue is one that I'll stay involved
in,'' she said. ``If it takes (more demonstrations) to continue to
bring it to the attention of the American people, I would say
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
