<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWAMP-COX     07-22 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mineral survey of Louisiana preserve sets off environmental
fight
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARRERO, La. _ This summer, underground explosions and loud
airboats have been disturbing the fragile ecosystem of the swamps
and marshlands in the Jean Lafitte National Historical Park and
Preserve. But what's being done is perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Resources, the largest coastal landowner in
Louisiana, leased the privately owned mineral rights to the ground
beneath the park and, with a relatively new technology called 3D
seismic, surveyed the area to look for oil and gas. Their project
marks the first time the technology, which requires more equipment
and more underground explosions than the older 2D method, has been
used in a national park or preserve in the United States. But it
won't be the last. Burlington and other energy companies want to do
similar operations in Big Thicket National Preserve in Texas and
Big Cypress National Preserve in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   How the project, which lasted two months and wrapped up
recently, affects the pristine landscape of the Jean Lafitte swamp
depends on who-- you ask.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will see airboat trails, but there are very few permanent
impacts,'' said Tom Mouchard, Burlington's senior environmental
engineer on the project. The company spent months researching how
best to do the operations without causing major damage. By next
spring it will be impossible to tell Burlington was even there, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Ehret, vice chairman of the Delta Regional Planning
Commission, the swamp's advisory board, sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just hate it,'' said Ehret, who is the founder of the park.
''I know from my 65 years of experience working in wetlands that
major destruction has been caused by oil companies doing mining.
It's terrible the way they leave a place. They leave damage that
can take 10 years to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially affected were the flotants, a unique, delicate
ecosystem of floating leaves and flowers that exists in only four
areas of the world. The equipment trampled it, Ehret said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is doing damage, there's no doubt about it,'' said David
Muth, Jean Lafitte's chief of resource management, who was
responsible for giving the project his blessing. ''Obviously, we
had some concerns, but we had intensive monitoring and planning as
it went forward. And we were pretty pleased with their cooperation.
But when you are running lots of heavy equipment across a delicate
ecosystem, well, you can't even drive a Volkswagen Bug through a
field without causing damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the legislation establishing the nation's newer parks _ those
created in the past three decades _ Congress reserved the mineral
rights for the original private owners. That means those owners can
survey the ground beneath the parks or lease their rights to
companies wishing to survey. If minerals are found and the owners
want to drill in the park, that's legal too.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Hanna, spokeswoman for Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, said the National Park Service is in an ''awkward
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When the subsurface rights are not conveyed to us, we can't
say no,'' she said. ''We are concerned, but we don't have the power
to prevent it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the 3D technology provides a more complete picture than
older methods, most energy companies undoubtedly will want to
resurvey land, including areas under national parks and preserves.
And the method requires more dynamite than the older 2D way:
Burlington set off 440 explosions in Lafitte park alone.
</P>
<P>
   Ehret doesn't believe Burlington will find oil or gas under the
park, and in fact neither does the energy company. Mouchard said
they are more interested in land adjacent to the park but need
information from the park to get a complete picture of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The technology works like this: Workers drill 100-foot holes in
precise places and put five-pound explosives at the bottom.
Recording devices, also precisely placed, note the sound waves the
explosions make. Computers then use those sound waves to draw a
three-dimensional picture of the region, which can reveal whether
oil and gas are present.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between public and private is not a new one when it
comes to federally protected lands.
</P>
<P>
   There have been attempts, so far unsuccessful, by Congress in
recent years to open the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge in Alaska
to oil drilling. In Georgia, DuPont Co. wants to put a strip mine
within half a mile of the Okefenokee National Wildlife Refuge.
Environmentalists and Babbitt have denounced the plans.
</P>
<P>
   And people perceive the national parks to be under siege. More
than half of Americans believe the parks will be in worse condition
25 years from now than they are today, according to a report from
the National Parks and Preservation Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a perfect world,'' Hanna said, ``there would be no
exploration or development in parks and refuges.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
