u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-GOODWILL-LAN-SANG     07-22 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-GOODWILL-LAN-SANG-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY TO CHINESE GYMNAST CALLED `DEVASTATING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Sang Lan, a 17-year-old champion Chinese
gymnast, remained in guarded condition Wednesday, doctors said,
unable to move her legs after suffering a severe spinal injury
while performing a routine warmup vault at the Goodwill Games on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sang was able to flex her elbows and extend her wrists, but she
experienced no feeling below her upper chest, according to Dr.
Vincent Leone, an orthopedic spinal surgeon who treated the gymnast
at the Nassau County Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her spinal cord was realigned and treatment with
cortico-steroids was begun Tuesday night, Leone said. He said
treatment was expected to begin with an experimental drug in an
attempt to regenerate damaged nerves. In about two days, Sang will
undergo surgery to have her damaged vertebrae fused and to implant
metal stabilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Leone called her injury ``devastating'' and ``violent,'' and
said it was too early to give an accurate prognosis about Sang's
future. While he said that some improvement could be expected in
her upper extremities, he added, ``I really can't comment on her
lower extremities.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he believed that Sang would be able to walk
eventually, Leone said, ``You'd be surprised. I'm still going to
say unlikely, but I'm very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Her catastrophic injury again raised questions about the safety
of gymnastics, and of the vault in particular. The apparatus has
now produced three injuries that have left gymnasts paralyzed in
the past decade. Julissa Gomez, an American, broke her neck while
attempting a backward handspring on the horse in 1988, and died
from complications three years later. Adriana Duffy, who competed
for Puerto Rico, was confined to a wheelchair after a vaulting
accident in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Another catastrophic gymnastics injury was suffered by Elena
Moukina, the 1978 world all-around champion from the former Soviet
Union, who was paralyzed in 1980 after an accident during a
tumbling routine.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses to Sang's injury said that there was no spotter to
catch Sang in case she lost control as she performed a rudimentary
warmup routine called a ``timer'' before Tuesday's competition.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the maneuver is a handspring in which Sang jumps
from a springboard, places her hands on the padded vaulting horse
and does a flip with the intention of landing on her feet. It is a
common warmup for more difficult maneuvers. Injuries while
performing this flip are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Conner, a gold medalist for the United States at the 1984
Summer Games who witnessed the accident as a commentator for TBS
television, said that while a spotter might have helped Sang avoid
serious injury, he did not believe it was necessary because she was
a proficient gymnast. ``There didn't appear to be a cause for
concern,'' Conner said. ``It was in warmups.''
</P>
<P>
   Sang was the 1997 Chinese national champion in the vault and
presumably had performed the warmup numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   Octavian Belu, the longtime Romanian national gymnastics coach,
said that Sang pitched too far forward, seemed indecisive about how
to break her fall and landed hard on her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a bad sound,'' Belu said. ``A crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Gymnastics officials Wednesday rushed to defend their sport,
which has come under increasing criticism because of eating
disorders and frequent injuries. Kathy Scanlan, president of USA
Gymnastics, said that thicker floor matting, padding around the
vault platform, safety-certified coaches and equipment-testing
centers had significantly increased the safety record of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was simply an accident that can occur in any kind of
sport, very, very unfortunately,'' Scanlan said. ``But it is not
the result of unsafe conditions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Conner agreed. ``I don't think this is evidence of abuse in
women's gymnastics,'' he said. ``It's not like someone made her do
this and she got hurt. It's a common routine that had a sad,
unlucky result.''
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed to spinal injuries to such professional football
players as Dennis Byrd, Mike Utley and Darryl Stingley, and to the
Boston University hockey player Travis Roy, and said that other
contact sports were more dangerous than gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In boxing, the objective is to knock someone unconscious,''
said Abie Grossfeld, a two-time Olympian who coaches gymnastics at
Southern Connecticut State University. ``They don't even count that
as an injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Leone said that the Nassau County Medical Center annually
treated about 16 to 30 victims of injuries similar to Sang's, most
of them resulting from recreational diving accidents and automobile
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of stress fractures in the lower back in
gymnastics; it's due to hyperextension,'' said Dr. Lewis Maharam,
president of the Greater New York chapter of the American College
of Sports Medicine. ``What happened in her case is very rare for a
gymnast. She was running at high speed and came down on her head.
This is just an accident. It's similar to a linebacker hitting with
his head down instead of up.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The force gets transferred down the vertebrae until
it breaks out at the place of least strength. Did she have a stress
fracture there previously? If she did, did she know? Did she have
an inherent eating disorder, which you see in gymnasts frequently,
making her bones brittle?''
</P>
<P>
   Sang's parents are being flown to visit their daughter from
their home in Ningbo, China, located south of Shanghai, according
to Mike Plant, president of the Goodwill Games. Her mother works in
a leather factory and her father is a government housing worker.
</P>
<P>
   Sang was described by doctors and other officials as being very
courageous, but also frightened and frustrated at not being able to
move her legs.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at the hospital, Sang told her coach, Liu
Quinling, that she did not know how the injury happened and asked
whether she would be able to compete as a gymnast in the future,
according to Zhao Yuxin, vice president of the Chinese gymnastics
federation. Doctors said Sang did not cry until she was being
placed on a stretcher at Nassau County Coliseum to be transferred
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   China's two other female gymnasts would continue to compete in
the Goodwill Games, said Tu Mingde, secretary-general of the
Chinese Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to aspire to the highest level of sport, you have
to pay something,'' Tu said, meaning that there are risks in all
sports. ``They are going to give their best performances to show
that gymnastics is also a beautiful sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
