<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHEPARD-REACTION-HNS &LR;      07-22 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS RECALL SHEPARD'S DRIVE FOR PERFECTION _ AND HIS PRACTICAL
JOKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When he finally got his chance to stand on the moon
and look back at Earth hanging in the blackness of space more than
a quarter-million miles away, Alan Shepard wept.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, he cried because his mission as commander of Apollo 14
was accomplished; in a few moments he would climb the ladder of the
lunar module Antares for the long journey home. He was also, as he
later said, overcome by emotion at the beauty of his home planet,
and was struck by its fragility and the realization of how easily
it could be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   But the tears Shepard shed that day in 1971 were also tears of
joy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after he made history as the first American in space,
only to have his dreams of flying again shattered by a malady in
his inner ear, Shepard had triumphed. He wasn't only flying again,
he had just spent 33 hours on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   To many who knew Shepard and worked with him, and who remembered
him after his death Tuesday in Monterey, Calif., it was that drive
and determination that was the essence of the man.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also fondly, and sadly, remembered as a mercurial
perfectionist _ warm and aloof, funny and serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Alan was doing something, he was very stern, often aloof
in the way he took care of business,'' said Jay Barbree, a veteran
television journalist who teamed up with Shepard, his fellow
Mercury astronaut Donald ``Deke'' Slayton and another journalist to
write a book called ``Moon Shot'' in the early 1990s. ``That was
his personality; he did not brook any playing around. But when he
played he was the biggest practical joker among them.''
</P>
<P>
   This contradiction was epitomized, Barbree said, when grounded
because an inner ear affliction that affects balance, Shepard ran
the astronaut office at the Johnson Space Center in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``His secretary had a picture of him hanging on the wall outside
of his door,'' Barbree said. ``It was a double-sided picture _ one
side was a smiling Alan Shepherd and on the other side was a
frowning Alan Shepard. When he came in in the morning, if he was in
a bad mood she'd flip over to the frowning side so that the
astronauts knew it was probably best to come back another time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he rarely spoke about it, Shepard's friends said losing
his flight status was a crushing blow to a man who wanted to do
nothing else. But instead of brooding about it, Shepard secretly
sought medical treatment and eventually had surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept those feelings very secret ... and he went off and had
that operation performed, which was a very delicate one and a very
unsuccessful one in many cases, by himself,'' said Chris Kraft, a
former director of the Johnson Space Center in far south Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did that with the sole purpose of being able to fly in
Apollo. I couldn't imagine why a man who had already become
probably one of the most famous aviators in history would want to
then risk his life in going to the moon, but that's what he wanted
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it had something to do with wanting to be on the edge,
like his hero, aviation pioneer Charles Lindbergh, or his friend
and golf buddy, Houston heart surgery pioneer Denton Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked the thought of being the first to do something that
had not been done before and he was very proud of his
opportunities,'' Cooley said. ``Of course he made himself famous by
trying to hit a golf ball off the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf was as much of a passion to Shepard in his later life as
flying was earlier, and he was a regular at charity tournaments
when he lived in the Houston area, said Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's death means that the ranks of the surviving Mercury
astronauts are dwindling. He was preceded in death by Virgil
``Gus'' Grissom, who died in a launch pad fire in the capsule of
Apollo 1, and by Slayton who died in 1993. But some of his
remaining colleagues remembered him Wednesday as a member of an
elite fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the original group who was lucky enough to be in on
the real pioneering of space, certainly for the United States,''
said fellow Mercury flier Gordon Cooper. ``He was certainly a very
capable guy, and a very capable astronaut. And of course, he was
like a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Cooper, the remaining Mercury astronauts are M. Scott
Carpenter, Sen. John Glenn and Walter M. Schirra Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who knew Shepard also mentioned his intelligence,
an attribute Kraft said was high on the list of reasons he was
selected to make the first Mercury flight.
</P>
<P>
   It's an assessment shared by Glenn, D-Ohio, who became the first
astronaut to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it became obvious to all of us in that training period
that Al was an extremely intelligent ... dedicated leader whose
motivation toward accomplishing our mission was a true inspiration
to all of us,'' Glenn said at a press conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his Mercury colleagues, Shepard had a penchant for
tomfoolery, a tendency to pull practical jokes to relieve the
tension of training, Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator remembered his flight in 1962 when, shortly after
reaching orbit he reached down to get some equipment and a little
stuffed mouse floated up into zero gravity _ placed there by
Shepard in a joking reference to the TV character Jose Jimenez who
felt sorry for a mouse being sent into space in the nose cone of a
rocket.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the space program in 1974, Shepard went on to
forge a successful career as a businessman and a philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 he was named founding president of the Mercury Seven
Foundation in Titusville, Fla., an organization that raises money
for science and engineering scholarships, and which is now known as
the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation
</P>
<P>
   Howard Benedict, a former space reporter for The Associated
Press who is executive director of the foundation, said he met
Shepard and the other Mercury astronauts when they arrived at Cape
Canaveral to begin training for their mission. He was struck he
said, by Shepard's intelligence and his obvious leadership
qualities, but also by his charismatic smile.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as he got to know Shepard better, and began to
understand him, Benedict said, he also gained an understanding of
just how disappointed the astronaut was when he was grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why, Benedict said, he will never forget Shepard's
first words when he got to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finally here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
