<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHEPARD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN SHEPARD, FIRST AMERICAN IN SPACE, DIES AT 74 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to correct day of death to Tuesday, add 2NDTAKE of 18
grafs.)  (EDS: An optional 3RDTAKE of OBIT-SHEPARD-1STLD-WRITETHRU, will
move by 10 p.m. ET. This version can stand alone, however.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Shepard, the first American to fly in space, lifting
national spirits at a decisive moment of Cold War anxiety, and
later one of only 12 astronauts to walk on the Moon, died Tuesday
night at a hospital in Monterey, Calif. He was 74 and lived Houston
and Pebble Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The family would not disclose the cause of death, saying only
that it came after a long illness. But another former astronaut,
Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, said that Shepard had been suffering from
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of May 5, 1961, Shepard became an immediate
American hero. A lean, crew-cut former Navy test pilot, then 37, he
began the day lying on his back in a cramped Mercury capsule atop a
seven-story Redstone rocket filled with explosive fuel. After four
tense hours of weather and mechanical delays, he was shot into the
sky on a 15-minute flight that grazed the fringes of space, at an
altitude of 115 miles, and ended in a splashdown in the Atlantic
Ocean 302 miles downrange from Cape Canaveral, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Though not much by today's standards, the brief suborbital
flight had stopped a whole country in its tracks, waiting anxiously
at radios and television sets. When the message of success came
through _ with a phrase that would enter the idiom, ``Everything is
A-OK!'' _ everyone seemed to let out a collective sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union's Yuri Gagarin may have been first man into
space, 23 days before, and have flown a full orbit, but now the
United States finally had reason to cheer. In fact, Shepard's
success is credited with giving President John F. Kennedy the
confidence to commit the nation to the goal of landing men on the
Moon by the end of the decade. He announced the goal to Congress on
May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goldin, NASA's director, said the Shepard flight was ``a
tremendous statement about tenacity, courage and brilliance,''
adding with a tone of lingering awe: ``He crawled on top of that
rocket that had never before flown into space with a person aboard
and he did it. That was an unbelievable act of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Logsdon, a political scientist at George Washington
University and author of ``The Decision to Go to the Moon,'' said,
``One can make the argument that the success of the Shepard flight
enabled the decision to go to the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr., a historian and a member of the
Kennedy White House staff, recalled that the Gagarin flight and
then the Bay of Pigs fiasco in Cuba a few days later had given
``Americans a slight inferiority complex.'' Then the Shepard flight
produced ``a great exhilaration and renewed our confidence in our
capacity as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hailed Shepard as ``one of the great heroes of
modern America.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the first flight, Shepard made a comeback from a
serious inner ear problem called Meuniere's syndrome that had
grounded him. And it was also a comeback flight for the space
program.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, 1971, he took off for the Moon in Apollo 14, the
first lunar mission since the near-disaster of Apollo 13 the year
before. He and Edgar Mitchell spent 33 hours on the Moon, a visit
made memorable by Shepard taking several spirited whacks at golf
balls with a makeshift 6-iron he had brought along. The balls
sailed in the low lunar gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived every golfer's dream,'' Clinton remarked. ``Taking a
6-iron and hitting the ball, in his words, `for miles and miles.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shepard was one of the original seven Mercury astronauts chosen
in 1959 by the fledgling space agency and introduced to the nation
with great fanfare. His death leaves only four survivors: Scott
Carpenter, L. Gordon Cooper, Walter Schirra and Glenn, who at 77 is
training for a kind of farewell flight on the space shuttle in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil ``Gus'' Grissom died in a cockpit fire during a
launching-pad training exercise in 1967. Donald ``Deke'' Slayton
died of cancer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Shepard retired from both NASA and the Navy, where he
had achieved the rank of rear admiral. Already wealthy from real
estate and other investments, he became chairman of Marathon
Construction Corp. in Houston and later founded his own business
company, Seven Fourteen Enterprises. The name recognized his two
missions, Freedom 7 and Apollo 14.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
