</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-HEALTH-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OXFORD HEALTH TO RAISE RATES AND CUT FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans, the troubled company that once seemed to
hold great promise for the future of managed care, is warning
doctors that it must raise premiums and reduce the amount it pays
doctors and hospitals, if it is to make money.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to doctors on Monday, Norman Payson, Oxford's
new chief executive, outlined a series of steps the company plans
to take. Oxford is considering shrinking the size of its hospital
network and will try to more aggressively discourage members from
going out of its network.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford would not comment on its specific plans, and it remains
unclear how dramatic these changes will be. ``Its significance will
depend on the degree,'' said Bob Braddick, a benefits consultant
for William Mercer in New York. ``They have significant business
problems. They have to address these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   While the steps outlined by Payson had been expected, they are
the clearest indication to date of Oxford's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   They also come at a critical time. Many employers will soon be
deciding whether to offer Oxford to their employees next year, and
many employees will have the opportunity to switch plans this fall.
Oxford risks losing members if it raises premiums by too much or
makes its popular Freedom plan significantly less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford, once the darling of Wall Street and consumers alike,
seemed to have perfected the best of both worlds in its health
plan. The plan offered members the choice of going to any doctor at
a reasonable price. Then last October it stunned investors with the
news that it expected sizable losses. The company had
underestimated the cost of delivering care to its 2 million
members.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford has spent the last year trying to untangle the chaos that
resulted in a $291 million loss for 1997. As part of its turnaround
plan earlier this year, the company raised $710 million in capital
from private investors and brought in a new management team.
</P>
<P>
   But Payson's letter also seemed to signal that Oxford has a long
way to go before it returns to profitability. ``Oxford is still
losing significant amounts of money in its health plans,'' Payson
said. ``If we took no action, in time we would be in serious
financial difficulty again. Therefore, we must initiate measures
now to stem losses, with a target of reaching break-even within
twelve months.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which has been bludgeoned by news of the
company's losses, hit a new 52-week low Wednesday. Investors appear
to be anticipating more bad news in the coming weeks, when the
company releases its second-quarter results. It closed at $12.50,
down $1.3125.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining Oxford's strategy, Payson said that the company,
``by necessity, must raise rates.'' He said that the company had
already started to raise premiums for some employers, which are
``for the most part staying with Oxford.''
</P>
<P>
   Benefits consultants say that the rate increases so far have
varied significantly from employer to employer. Henry Moyer, a
benefits consultant at Hirschfield, Stern, Moyer &AMP; Ross, said that
while some clients' premiums haven't changed, Oxford recently
raised rates for one client by 32 percent. That client, which Moyer
would not identify, switched plans.
</P>
<P>
   And while some employers have been told to expect a premium
increase of around 10 percent, many are still waiting for Oxford to
provide exact figures. ``Everyone's waiting,'' said Barry Barnett,
a principal at Kwasha HR Solutions, a unit of
PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``There is a lot of bated breath out
there.'' In discussing the impact on doctors, Payson said Oxford's
goal ``is to change only those fees we need to and, in general, to
only affect fees modestly.'' But doctors, especially if they are
still owed money from claims they say are lost or have been
mishandled, may not react well to any sharp reduction. Consultants
say some doctors may abandon the network.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This could have a serious impact on many providers in this
area,'' said Charles Aswad, the executive vice president for the
New York State Medical Society, noting that doctors are under
pressure by many managed-care companies to accept lower
reimbursements. While he said the letter's ``general intent is
positive,'' he worried about the size of any reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Payson also indicated that Oxford's ``net hospital costs have
gone up dramatically'' in New York state, home to most of Oxford's
members, because of the recent New York Health Care Reform Act
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford ``can no longer afford to absorb these costs nor pass
them on directly or indirectly to employers, doctors or patients,''
he said, and the company would be negotiating with hospitals to
reduce those costs. He said the company would consider reducing the
size of its network or develop a preferred network.
</P>
<P>
   The new legislation, which requires plans to help share the cost
of graduate medical education and uncompensated care, should have
had no impact on Oxford's costs, according to Patricia Wang, an
executive at the Greater New York Hospital Association. ``They
really should have been paying this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford also appears to be considering some changes to its
Freedom plan, which became popular precisely because it seemed to
offer substantial choice at a reasonable price. ``Our primary
initiative for our patients is to encourage them more and more to
stay in network,'' Payson explained. Oxford could raise the size of
the deductible it charges members who go outside, or reduce the
amount of their bills that it reimburses them.
</P>
<P>
   Payson also made it clear that Oxford plans to continue to move
away from certain businesses. ``We learned that Oxford cannot be
all things to all people,'' he said. ``We need assistance in the
challenging governmentally financed segments of our population,
Medicare and Medicaid.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter went out as investors are growing increasingly
nervous about the company's financial results, which are expected
in mid-August. Analysts say that they expect a sizable loss. Anne
Anderson, an analyst at Atlantis Investment Co. in Parsippany,
N.J., who continues to bet that the stock will drop further,
forecast that the company would report a second-quarter loss of at
least $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the company takes the steps outlined by Payson, Oxford
has yet to prove it can offer a plan that is both popular and
profitable. According to Arun Kumar, a bond analyst with Standard &AMP;
Poor's, ``Breaking even in 12 months is not impossible, but very
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
