<HEADLINE>
JETT, FORMER KIDDER TRADER, SAYS HE IS INNOCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Jett, a former star bond trader at Kidder, Peabody &AMP; Co.
who was accused of manufacturing huge phantom trading profits,
angrily proclaimed his innocence Wednesday and strongly suggested
that racism had added to his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   An administrative law judge on Tuesday found him guilty of false
record-keeping in a civil case brought by the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Jett, who is black, said in an interview that securities cases
similar to his had resulted in much lesser penalties. ``When all
things are equal and the only difference is color, I have to
wonder,'' he said. ``The laws that are supposed to treat all men
equally don't seem to be doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   After finding Jett guilty of false record-keeping, Carol Fox
Foelak, the judge, ordered him to repay $8.2 million in bonuses he
received at Kidder, fined him $200,000 and barred him from the
securities business.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge did not find Jett guilty of securities fraud as
the SEC had charged, ruling that he had traded phantom securities
that could not be considered real securities and therefore this
could not constitute a securities fraud. Jett said Wednesday that
he would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jett was dismissed by Kidder in April 1994 after hundreds of
millions of dollars made from his bond trading were found to be
phantom profits from anomalies in the way the firm's computers
recorded trades.
</P>
<P>
   The firm sued Jett, charging that he had exploited those
anomalies to manufacture phantom profits to win himself huge
bonuses. Two of Jett's bosses were sanctioned by the SEC for
failing to supervise him properly; they drew fines and temporary
suspensions from the securities business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wonder if the message that Wall Street is sending out
is if you're a black man who goes down on his hands and knees and
says, please help me Mr. White Man, it will help you,'' Jett said.
``But if you want to be judged on merit, that is a different
matter. I have offended the status quo and I am being railroaded
off the Street,'' the Harvard- and MIT-educated trader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I shouldn't be trying to prove my innocence any more;
the arbitration panel found me innocent,'' he said, referring to an
arbitration panel before the National Association of Securities
Dealers that in 1996 rejected Kidder's case seeking $82.8 million
in fraud claims from him, though it withheld millions of dollars of
his deferred compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Jett, who is now managing money for friends and working on a
book about his experience at Kidder, argued that the judge's
repayment order at least implied that money he earned at Kidder in
excess of the $8.2 million fine was rightfully his. ``Tacit in that
request is an admission that the $3.7 million I made previously was
deservedly earned,'' he said, maintaining that this ranked him
among Wall Street's top bond traders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
