<HEADLINE>
A TOWN SPLIT BETWEEN TWO STATES AND TWO TIME ZONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic map
is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE LINE CITY, Ind. _ The border between Illinois and Indiana
runs right smack through the middle of this community of 200 people
in corn country.
</P>
<P>
   That means someone who phones a neighbor across the street must
pay an out-of-state toll charge. And walking across that street
means changing time zones. It is an hour later on the Indiana side
than in Illinois (although only for five months of the year, since
the Indiana side, like most of the state, does not observe daylight
time).
</P>
<P>
   The Tabor grain company, which sits along the Norfolk Southern
freight railway, straddles the state line. The office and the grain
elevator scales are on the Indiana side, but some of the storage
bins stand on the Illinois side. As a result, Tabor must pay
property taxes in both states.
</P>
<P>
   Actually the people on the Illinois side are residents not of
State Line City but, technically, of Bismarck, Ill., 10 miles
north, the town with the closest Illinois post office. But since
they can walk to the post office in State Line City, most of the
Illinoisans keep Indiana postal boxes.
</P>
<P>
   As Susan Van Pelt, the 36-year-old owner of the Country Pantry,
explained it: ``We look like one town. We consider ourselves one
town. We act like one town. But we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's confusing,'' agreed Amy Wright, 30, who tells people that
she lives in Illinois, in a little Indiana town.
</P>
<P>
   While the out-of-state telephone charge for calling a neighbor
may seem a bit much, some people here say it has a silver lining:
since most townspeople are unwilling to pay the toll charges, said
Gary Gustafson, a 42-year-old driver for a cookie company, ``we
just walk over and sit on the porch and talk, you know, face to
face; it's kind of nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Others simply stand on the porch and holler over to the next
state. That does not work so well, though, for Imogene Lewsader and
her mother, Alice Cox, who is in her 80s and does not hear well, or
walk much, as she did a few years ago. So mother and daughter, who
live together on the Indiana side, ride around in a golf cart when
they are not at home playing host to neighbors like Ms. Wright, the
Illinoisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to walk back and forth, instead of calling, it's made
us good friends,'' Ms. Wright said. ``Imogene loves to show us her
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Children on opposite sides of the dividing line, State Line
Road, go to school in opposite directions. On the Illinois side,
the students are bused to Bismarck. The Indiana students take the
bus to Seeger.
</P>
<P>
   The big town nearby is Danville, Ill., which employs most of
State Line City's workers and is famous for some native sons: Gene
Hackman, Dick and Jerry Van Dyke, and Bobby Short.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the freight train, which roars through town several
times a day, there is not much noise in State Line City. In the
mid-1800s, the town and a sister municipality on the Illinois side,
Illiana, were considered up-and-comers. But Illiana faded away, and
State Line City, while retaining a post office, is missing from
most maps.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln spoke here on Feb. 11, 1861, rallying support
for his efforts to save the Union. His words are preserved on a
plaque on a boulder, sitting behind a baseball backstop at the town
park. ``I am under many obligations to you for your kind
reception,'' he said, ``and to Indiana for the aid which she
rendered our cause, which, I think, a just one.''
</P>
<P>
   While good feelings generally span State Line Road, divisions
did surface during the recent basketball playoffs between the
Chicago Bulls and the Indiana Pacers. After the Bulls had won,
several of the town's street signs were spray-painted with ``Bulls
Rule!'' and such.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably some kids on the Illinois side,'' surmised Bob
McLain, a middle-aged resident of the Indiana side of the street
who had rooted in vain for the Pacers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
