<HEADER>
A8261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-FUNDRAISING     07-22 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-FUNDRAISING-RENO-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN INVESTIGATOR URGES RENO TO NAME INDEPENDENT PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a 10-month inquiry, the departing chief of
the Justice Department's campaign finance unit has concluded in a
confidential report to Attorney General Janet Reno that she has no
alternative but to seek an independent prosecutor to investigate
political fund-raising abuses during President Clinton's
re-election campaign, government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Charles La Bella, delivered the report to Reno
last Thursday as he prepared to return to San Diego this week to
take over as interim U.S. attorney. In effect, after being chosen
by Reno to revive an investigation that she had been criticized for
neglecting, La Bella has marked his departure by challenging her to
replace him with an outside counsel.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella's report does not suggest that prosecutors are ready,
or even close, to bringing a case against any top Democrats or
administration officials, but contends only that their fund-raising
activities warrant outside investigation. And in a legal analysis,
La Bella concluded that Reno had misinterpreted the law creating an
artificially high standard to avoid invoking the independent
counsel statute, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella's conclusions, coming from a seasoned federal
prosecutor with full access to all grand jury evidence in the case,
represents a serious internal fracture within the Justice
Department. And the report seemed certain to provide Republicans
with considerable leverage to intensify their demands that Reno
step aside and let an outside prosecutor take over.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she has refused to budge in her refusal to refer the
case to outside counsel, and Wednesday. there was no indication
that Reno seemed likely to reconsider her position. Last fall, La
Bella had urged her to seek the appointment of an independent
prosecutor to investigate fund-raising telephone calls by Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore. But she rejected that recommendation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reno has said she carefully weighed the facts and the law before
determining that the appointment of an independent prosecutor was
not justified under the independent counsel law. She has defiantly
blocked the appointment even in the face of a recommendation last
fall from FBI Director Louis Freeh, who urged her to seek an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Her unwillingness to seek the appointment has exasperated
Republicans in Congress who have accused the Justice Department of
a politically motivated effort to subvert the independent counsel
law to protect upper level Democratic Party and White House
officials from searching scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The report follows a tempestuous hearing last week, in which she
faced withering questions by senators on the Judiciary Committee.
Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who led Senate campaign finance
hearings last year, confronted Reno by quoting a confidential memo
that Freeh sent to Reno in November 1997. He quoted Freeh has
concluded, ``It is difficult to imagine a more compelling situation
for appointing an independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Wednesday that Reno and Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder had received the report and were
reviewing it. But they would not discuss specifics. La Bella would
not discuss the report.
</P>
<P>
   Labella's report has been guarded closely. He produced only two
copies, the officials said. He gave one copy to Reno and sent
another to the home of Freeh, an ally whose top agent on the case,
James Desarno, approved Labella's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Reno assembled several of her top advisers to discuss
the report, but they apparently reached no conclusions about how or
whether to respond. She has already named a successor to La Bella.
He is David Vicinanzo, a prosecutor from New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The report casts possible new light on La Bella's decision on
leaving his job as the top campaign finance prosecutor, suggesting
that he could be stepping down in the middle of the inquiry because
he believed that the case should not be handled by the Justice
Department but by an outside prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the campaign finance inquiry has produced only several
low-level fund-raisers. But there has been no indication that the
inquiry was likely to move up the chain of command at the
Democratic National Committee or the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, the officials said, La Bella concluded that there
was sufficient information to warrant the appointment based on the
mandatory and discretionary provisions of the independent counsel
statute, meaning that he found enough specific information to
justify an outside investigation of high-level officials. Moreover,
he found that the Justice Department could not objectively
investigate them on its own, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was not clear whether La Bella recommended whether an
independent prosecutor should be named to investigate specific
officials although he assessed the activities of several senior
officials, including Clinton and Gore and others like Harold Ickes,
a former deputy chief of staff, who played an important role in
supervising the campaign from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggests that an independent prosecutor should
examine how the Democrats and Republicans used party funds to pay a
massive blitz of television ads that were thinly veiled election
messages for Clinton and Republican nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-DEATH-COX     07-22 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toddler dies from E.coli
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson, Diane Lore and Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- McCall Akin, a 2-year-old vegetarian girl
hospitalized since June 15 from an infection normally associated
with eating tainted beef, died Wednesday at Scottish Rite
Children's Medical Center after contracting E. coli at a kiddie
pool at White Water park in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the only child of Andy and Marisa Akin of Atlanta, had
been in a coma for several weeks, her body drawing life from a
kidney dialysis machine and a respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say she is the only child in the nation known
to have died from E. coli transmitted through a chlorinated public
pool.
</P>
<P>
   McCall had suffered a stroke and several seizures from the
disease that mostly threatens the very young, the old and those
with compromised immune systems. She was one of the youngest of the
26 children public health officials believe were infected with E.
coli at White Water in June.
</P>
<P>
   McCall Akin died in her mother's arms. ``Her mother was holding
her and rocking her and it was a very peaceful death,'' said Mark
Long, the boyfriend of one of the child's grandmothers. The parents
had kept a six-week vigil at their child's side. She had been in
the intensive care unit at Scottish Rite since being admitted in
the early morning hours of June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her parents literally lived in the hospital for six weeks,''
said Long. ``They've been amazingly strong through this. Of course,
they are very sad but they've shown no bitterness toward God and
they've shown no anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her struggle with the virulent toxin, E. coli
0157:H7, surgeons removed her colon, cleansed her failed kidneys
with dialysis, and supported her vital functions with respiratory
and other machines. Because the little girl tore at the intravenous
tubes, her arms were strapped to her hospital bed. She could not
talk or smile because of breathing and feeding tubes.
</P>
<P>
   The family was visited by numerous Atlanta ministers during
their vigil. And McCall, along with the other children suffering
from E. coli, received balloons, flowers and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, the parents prepared to lose their daughter _ but she
pulled through. Doctors could give no explanation for her sudden
recoveries, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall had been playing in the kiddie wading pool with her
mother just a few days before coming down with severe nausea and
abdominal cramps, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one solace I have is that in her short lifetime, all she
knew was love from other people and she`s essentially gone home to
God, '' he said. ``She was a gentle little girl. She was always
singing. Even if she was eating beans, she would be singing about
eating beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would have been an amazing songwriter had she stayed with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a beautiful baby girl,'' said Mark Givens, a
great-uncle. ``She was fun-loving and playful, just a precious
little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Givens said the family is pained by the irony that McCall, who
ate no meat, would die from a disease most often transmitted
through contaminated beef. ``One thing that's so amazing is that
this is a beef disease, and the one thing you think you'd be able
to shield McCall from would be that,'' Givens said.
</P>
<P>
   White Water officials said they were devastated. ``We're
heartbroken by this news,'' said Sonny Horton, general manager of
the park.
</P>
<P>
   White Water officials have been working closely with state
public health agencies to try to determine exactly how the E. coli
was spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't pinpoint the transmission. We're the link,''
said Horton, ``but we're not the source.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six children _ including Atlanta Braves shortstop Walt
Weiss's 3-year-old son, Brody, and 11-month-old son, Bo _ were
infected in the White Water outbreak in June. Seventeen of the
children were from Georgia and nine were from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials suspect a wading pool was repeatedly
contaminated by sick children, spreading the bacteria to others who
ingested the water. The infections clustered around two time
periods: June 11 and 12, and June 17 and18.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children avoided being hospitalized, but of the
half-dozen who were admitted to local hospitals, many required two
to three weeks of intensive care, including dialysis and other
organ-support machines.
</P>
<P>
   One child remains hospitalized: a 4-year-old girl, listed in
fair condition Wednesday at Scottish Rite.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbeth Addison, the mother of a 3-year-old Louisville, Ky., boy
who was re-admitted to Kosair Children's Hospital in Louisville two
weeks ago after contracting E. coli at White Water, said Wednesday
that her son, Matthew, had been back to the doctor Tuesday for
tests. Results from the tests, which included a urinalysis and
blood work, suggest his prognosis is good. Matthew had two
operations while he was in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli sickens about 20,000 Americans and kills 200 to 500 each
year. It produces a toxin that destroys red blood cells and
platelets, needed for clotting. Illness typically is marked by
cramping and diarrhea that can be bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, people recover without antibiotics or other specific
treatment within five to 10 days. However, young children,
particularly those between the ages of 6 months to 5 years, seem
more vulnerable to the overpowering toxin. Young children can
quickly develop a condition called called hemolytic uremic
syndrome. Often, as in McCall's case, blood transfusions and kidney
dialysis are required. Children with the condition can also suffer
strokes, which can lead to permanent neurological damage or death.
</P>
<P>
   McCall was considered an important part of the investigation
because she was a vegetarian. That fact forced public health
officials to examine whether there could be a source of
contamination other than meat.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, E. coli is spread through food contaminated with
fecal matter, and most commonly, through ground beef. It can also
be spread through produce or unsanitary conditions, but tainted
beef is most often the culprit. By eliminating such a source,
public health workers began to focus on contamination at White
Water.
</P>
<P>
   Such a transmission is rare. This is only the second known case
of a chlorinated pool being the route of transmission. The first
case was also in Georgia, occurring in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at White Water park, which has installed a new
filtration system that monitors chlorine levels, has dropped by 30
to 40 percent since the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia does not have regulations regarding the maintenance of
public pools, but offers 20 pages of guidelines for individual
counties. Twenty-five counties, including Cobb County, do have
regulations about pools, but some experts say enforcement varies
widely across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Buchanan, spokeswoman with the Georgia Division of Public
Health, said the agency is working on developing state regulations
regarding swimming pools _ a plan that was in place before the
outbreak, but revisited with more urgency since the White Water
park contamination. Unlike South Carolina, North Carolina and
Florida, Georgia does not set state standards for public pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gathering information from other states, and talking to
other experts in the field,'' she said. ``We want to do what is
right and we want to be thorough _ developing not only standards,
but a way for them to be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   She said public health officials, however, believe the best way
to avoid such a tragedy is for parents to use common sense: ``Sick
children should not be brought to swimming pools.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said the death will not change the course of the
current investigation, which has not yet identified the specific
source of the E. coli outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thoughts and prayers are with this family during this
terrible tragedy,'' Buchanan said. State Public Health Director
Kathleen Toomey was on vacation and could not be reached for
comment, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Slutsker, an epidemiologist with the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, which has been consulting on the
case, said the agency is ``very concerned about this (outbreak),''
and plans to review the state's investigation and share the
findings with public health departments across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do the best job we can to make sure this doesn't
happen again,'' said Slutsker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
