<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beach volleyball meets Gotham state of mind
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- And here's today's report from the real Manhattan
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Surf: Store your boards, dudes. It looks like a duck pond out
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sand: Plenty of it, but don't even think about spreading out the
umbrellas and blankets. Mayor Giuliani hates vagrants and would
order an immediate sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Tanning Index: A 10. Use plenty of sunscreen, especially since
so many of you locals have that Northern big-city, cod-belly
complexion.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the southern side of Central Park, the bronzed endorsers
of swimsuits and lotions and the eternal summer set up shop
Wednesday. When the Goodwill Games came to New York, they brought
along with them the uprooted sport of beach volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if this city had an actual beach, the old folk would have
built condos on it long ago and Boca Raton would be a largely
uninhabited mosquito hatchery.
</P>
<P>
   So, they had to make one up, trucking in 982,000 pounds of
Canadian sand and spreading it thick over a skating rink. They
piped in some of that rock music, put up a net, invited in some
Californians and their foreign friends _ and just like that, there
was a little bit of paradise in the middle of an unrelenting city.
</P>
<P>
   Some expect even New Yorkers to get with the beach volleyball
plan. ``You'll see people (guys, presumably) taking their tops off
before this thing is over. They'll get into it,'' said U.S.
volleyballer Adam Johnson. Having seen various Teamsters going
shirtless in the current heat wave, this is not a real intriguing
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The men's competition opened this facility Wednesday. All seem
to agree it's a fine location, slopping over with aesthetics. The
court sits in a pleasant hollow, beyond the reach of car horns and
jackhammers. The skyscrapers of the city loom over the trees,
making this the picture postcard of the Games. Those lucky folks
atop the Trump Tower have a great view of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very nice. We are used to having a beach behind us. But
this is another view. Very beautiful,'' said Eduardo Martinez of
Argentina. Martinez and Martin Conde had the honor of throwing out
the first victim on these courts. They disposed of the Swiss duo in
the opening match.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, as in most Goodwill venues, was sparse for the
first-ever Central Park beach bash. A couple hundred, maybe. People
were just too busy riding the Dow Jones to relax on the faux shore.
A shame, really.
</P>
<P>
   The heat _ 105 on the sand _ put the players in mind of Rio in
February. But the breeze was not of the usual tropical,
salt-scented variety. It was more like the lingering memory of a
million horse-drawn carriage rides through the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful opportunity. I've always wanted to play
outdoors in New York City. We couldn't have asked for a better
place to play,'' said American Karch Kiraly, who along with Johnson
beat Canada 15-8 in the second match.
</P>
<P>
   Beach volleyball is a state of mind as much as a sport, one that
New York has 11 more days to grasp. Can't help thinking that this
city won't really get into the game until one of the players
happens to trip over Jimmy Hoffa in this big sandbox. &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
