<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bragging rights belong to Greene
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ In a sport where trash talking has been honed
to an art form, Maurice Greene proved a man uncharacteristically of
his word. Greene has boasted to anyone who'd listen that world
record-holder Donovan Bailey couldn't run with him, and he backed
it up by leaving the Canadian deep in the pack while winning the
Goodwill Games 100 meters in 9.96 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm the fastest man in the world,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest man on Tuesday night, and now three straight over
Bailey _ including last year's World Championships. Yet Bailey, who
now makes his home in east Cobb County, still owns the world record
and the belief that his Tuesday night defeat was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey downplayed his seventh-place finish, saying he'd been
bothered by a heel injury until two weeks ago. A miserable start
out of the blocks cost him dearly. But before that, Bailey dipped
into his bag of tricks, staring down Greene and his training
partner Ato Boldon, who was second.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry with the Americans has intensified since Bailey's
record sprint in Atlanta, followed by his defeat of Michael Johnson
in their match race.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson produced the other bold statement, returning to form to
cruise through 400 meters in a meet-record 43.76 _ the year's best
time and the 12th fastest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it sounds as if the rivalry with Bailey is intensifying as
the athletes prepare for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though I lost a friend,'' Boldon said of Bailey.
``Before all this it was cool ... It's about how you treat your
opponents. We're not going to worry about who stares down and makes
comments in Australia.'' The sprint rivalry closed out a night that
saw several outstanding performances:
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hartwig broke his American record in the pole with a
clearance of 19-8 1/2, while world record-holder Sergei Bubka
failed to clear a height in the pole vault.
</P>
<P>
   World record-holder Jonathan Edwards prevailed in the triple
jump with an effort of 57 feet, 11 inches. In doing so, he avenged
his Atlanta Olympic defeat to Kenny Harrison, who was last in 54-2
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta gold medalist Noureddine Morceli of Algeria took the
lead at the start of the bell lap from Kenya's Daniel Komen to
repeat as the mile champion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
