<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rough Dover track knocks out fillings
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bent, missing some parts, but not broken, Scott Sharp
and Buddy Lazier were the final men standing Sunday in the Indy
Racing League's version of a survival of the fittest at Dover, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Lazier said the rough ``Monster Mile'' at Dover Downs
International Speedway knocked at least two fillings loose in his
mouth. The bumpy race track dismounted the dashboard onto the lap
of Tony Stewart, who needed duct tape to re-attach it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Dover Downs estimated Sunday's crowd at close to
45,000 in the 107,000-seat facility. IRL executive director Leo
Mehl said Saturday that any crowd ``north of 25,000'' would be
acceptable to the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   The track will be a lot smoother when the IRL hits Atlanta Motor
Speedway Aug. 29 for the Atlanta Classic 500. For ticket
information, call AMS at 770-946-4211.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Jeg Coughlin of Columbus, Ohio, faced an awesome, all-Georgia
challenge in the NHRA Mopar Parts Mile-High Nationals at Morrison,
Colo., with the Johnson family. Lawrenceville's Kurt Johnson, the
number two qualifier, was on his side of the ladder and Duluth's
Warren Johnson, the number one qualifier and points leader, was on
the other. Coughlin defeated both of them, beating Kurt in the
semifinals and Warren in the finals. Legends
</P>
<P>
   Reed Sorenson of Peachtree City continued to dominate the Young
Lions division of the Thursday Thunder Legends series at Atlanta
Motor Speedway. Other winners: Chargers, Jason Carruth, Powder
Springs; Bandolero, Alan Happel, Warner Robins; Masters, Terry
Mathis, Cumming; Pro, Doug Stephens, McDonough. For more
information, call AMS at 770-946-4211.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Dragway
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Super Pro driver Stacy Blanton of Auburn once compared
himself to Dick Trickle, winless over his entire career, but that
changed last Saturday when Blanton won the Super Pro Division of
the Sears/Craftsman 1/8-mile series race. Blanton took his 1995
Undercover Dragster down the track for an easy win after his
opponent, Jim McKelvey of Lithonia, fouled. Other winners:
Sportsman, Billy Joe Mason, Covington, '79 Mustang, 7.89 Elapsed
Time, 86.71 mph; Trophy, Cliff Donald, Lawrenceville, '67
Barracuda, 14.77, 92.03; Motorcycle, Tim Sutton, Gainesville, '72
Kawasaki, 6.07, 110.30.
</P>
<P>
   CART
</P>
<P>
   More apologies from Alex Zanardi: ``Very honestly, today I did
almost everything wrong,'' the Italian driver said after winning
Sunday's Molson Indy CART FedEx Series race. ``I spun, I got stuck
in an accident, I had problems with my tires and brakes. I was just
so unlucky.'' Right. Unlucky enough to win his fourth straight race
and tie Al Unser Jr.'s 1990 mark. ``I kind of feel sorry for how
much luck I am having,'' Zanardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz
</P>
<P>
   On Track magazine reports that the Panoz Q9 hybrid has been
entered in a British GT Championship round at Donington Park Aug. 2
and could be in the Aug. 23 round at Silverstone. Closer to home,
Team Panoz will be at Mosport Aug. 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
