u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-CONFIRM-ART-50     07-22 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-CONFIRM-ART-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS HINT AT TRADE-OFF ON ENERGY NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Idaho, N.C., N.M.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two high-ranking Republican senators said Wednesday
that they were considering whether to try to hold up the nomination
of Bill Richardson to be energy secretary unless the Clinton
administration moved toward establishing a temporary repository for
nuclear waste from civilian power reactors.
</P>
<P>
   At a confirmation hearing held by the Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, Richardson, who is currently the chief U.S.
delegate to the United Nations, was also aggressively questioned
about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, sought
details about how Richardson had offered a job at the U.N. mission
to Ms. Lewinsky, the former White House intern at the center of an
investigation into her relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he had interviewed Ms. Lewinsky at his suite at
the Watergate Hotel because John Podesta, the deputy chief of staff
at the White House, asked him to do so as a favor to Betty Currie,
Clinton's personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that the interview was conducted by his chief of
staff, that his executive assistant was also present and that
although the meeting took place at 7:30 a.m., it was not a
breakfast meeting. Murkowski went so far as to ask about where in
the suite the interview took place and where Richardson had slept,
but he seemed satisfied with the answers.
</P>
<P>
   But Murkowski and Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, pressed hard for a
sign that the administration would agree to build an above-ground
``interim'' storage site for spent fuel now piling up at utility
reactors around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s the Energy Department agreed to begin taking
custody of such fuel in January of this year, but because of
various delays in trying to find a suitable site, has acknowledged
that it still might be more than a decade from having an
underground repository ready.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has argued that establishment of an
above-ground repository would drain money and attention away from
the search for a long-term solution, a position that Richardson
restated Wednesday. But several members of the committee pointed
out that the courts have ruled that the department has breached
valid contracts with the utilities, and that those utilities are
now seeking damages.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said that Richardson was ``the man who has been touted
around the world as a negotiator'' and that he should negotiate a
deal to open a temporary repository. But Craig said he did not want
the nomination to come to a vote without an indication that the
administration was allowing Richardson leeway on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said he was considering putting a hold on the nomination,
and Murkowski said he was supporting Craig. Several other members
said it would be unfair to hold the nomination hostage over a
policy issue, but aides to Craig said after the hearing that he was
still considering the move, and hoping that negotiations with the
administration would make that unnecessary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, Bill, that it happens to be you,'' Craig said,
adding, ``I don't know where I'll get with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson won a generally friendly reception from the
committee. Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., spoke on his behalf, and said
that although he would prefer abolishing the department, this was
not likely to happen and Richardson was ``a good choice to keep the
department under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a former representative from New Mexico whose
district included a major nuclear-weapons laboratory, testified on
a wide variety of issues facing the Energy Department, which is
mostly concerned with nuclear weapons and environmental cleanup of
weapons manufacture. He broke little new ground, saying he wanted
more communication with states and more efficient spending on
contractors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
