<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SLAYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOODY BOOTS ADD NEW TWIST TO JASPER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A pair of bloody boots could show that a
cooperative suspect in Jasper's racial killing last month had more
to do with the dragging death than he has admitted to
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   If FBI laboratory results on the boots confirm suspicions,
prosecutors may seek the death penalty for Shawn Berry, District
Attorney Guy James Gray of Jasper County said Wednesday. While
declining to elaborate, Gray said that other forensic evidence also
suggests a more active role by Berry in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   When Berry, 23, of Jasper was indicted separately from Bill
King, 23, of Jasper and Russell Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs,
Gray said prosecutors might seek a lesser sentence for Berry in
exchange for his testimony against the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Berry is the only defendant who has made statements to
investigators, telling them that he picked up James Byrd Jr., 49,
after he saw him walking along a Jasper street. He said King later
took the wheel of his pickup and drove Byrd to a remote area east
of Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Jassper, a town of 8,000 people, is about 150 miles northeast of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said the other two men beat Byrd until he was unconscious
and then chained his ankles to the bumper of the pickup.
Investigators found a trail of blood and body parts almost three
miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence may show Berry did more than just watch, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday officials filed an affidavit that said the
``Federal Bureau of Investigation Laboratory in Washington has
informed investigators that blood had been detected on three pairs
of shoes previously seized from John William King, Shawn Allen
Berry and Lawrence Russell Brewer (from) their apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   The document continued, ``It is believed that evidence as to the
suspects' feet will link the suspects to the shoes and to the
homicide of James Byrd Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said each defendant wears a different size of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier affidavit released by investigators said Berry
claimed he ran away while Byrd was being beaten and did not see him
being chained to the truck. Berry later told investigators that he
saw the beating and chaining, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   But Berry's attorney, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn, said blood on
Berry's boots would not prove that he took part in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen any evidence that would indicate that he took
part,'' Hawthorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said there was a lot of blood at the scene and that
Berry might have stepped in some of it. The other two also might
have tracked blood into the pickup and some of it could have gotten
on Berry's shoes in the truck, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said he is not even sure investigators are testing the
right footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed me a picture of a pair of cowboy boots, but that
wasn't what Berry was wearing that night,'' Hawthorn said. He said
his client was wearing a pair of ankle-high Polo brand boots the
night of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not yet gotten lab results showing whose blood
was on the shoes, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that if he decides to seek the death penalty for
Berry, he may ask a grand jury to re-indict all the suspects and
try them all together.
</P>
<P>
   Trying them together not only would save Jasper County money,
Gray said, but also would prevent evidence from being revealed in
one case before another defendant is tried.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said, in any case, he would seek to have Berry's trial
severed from trials of the other defendants. If Berry is tried with
the other two, it might be grounds for an appeal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
