<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-FORCE-CONFIRM-475     07-22 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-CONFIRM-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL REJECTS NOMINEE FOR SECRETARY OF THE AIR FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Fla., S.C., Ohio, Va., W.Va., Conn., Pa., Mass.,
Mich., Calif.)  (th) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Armed Services Committee on Wednesday
rejected President Clinton's choice for secretary of the Air Force,
dealing the administration a setback on a high-level political
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   When supporters of the nominee, Florida state Sen. Daryl Jones,
failed to muster enough votes to win endorsement, they tried to
have the committee send his nomination to the full Senate without a
recommendation. But even that effort failed on a 9-9 vote, mainly
along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the Pentagon on Wednesday could recall the last time
the Senate refused a president's nomination to head a branch of the
armed services. Not since the Democratic-controlled Senate rejected
President George Bush's choice of former Sen. John Tower to be
Defense secretary in 1989 had senators been so torn over a
presidential pick for a top Pentagon job.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Jones, an Air Force Academy graduate and former
fighter pilot, said they were troubled by discrepancies in his
statements about his flying record in the Air Force Reserve and his
business dealings. Above all, they said, they feared that he could
never surmount the controversy and become an effective leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him constantly correcting the record, modifying his
statements and pleading ignorance to rules, regulations and law,''
said Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones' supporters said he was a model public servant and
military man who was victimized by a web of unproven accusations
and honest mistakes. ``We're about to vote to wreck a man's career
and life over unproven allegations,'' said Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   As Jones left the Pentagon on Wednesday, his quest to become the
first black Air Force secretary dashed, the 43-year-old lawyer said
he was ``obviously disappointed'' by the outcome, and added that
none of the objections raised against him ``made logical sense to
me.'' Jones said he would return to Florida to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In Senate hearings in the past month, former squadron mates,
including his former commander, accused Jones of lying about why he
stopped flying F-16s in an Air Force Reserve unit in Florida. Other
accusations surfaced, including that Jones pressured enlisted
airmen to buy Amway household products he sold and that he
collected $88-a-month flight pay for nearly four years after he had
taken a desk job and was no longer flying.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stoutly denied the accusations, and his supporters said at
least some of the complaints against him, especially those from his
former Reserve unit, the 93rd Fighter Squadron, resulted from
racial animosity. Jones was the first black pilot in the F-16 unit,
and some former squadron mates testified last week that some white
pilots had resented him, suspecting that he had won a spot in the
unit because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has repeatedly said he did not encounter racism in the
squadron.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's vote, in an ornate hearing room, senators
alternately defended and condemned Jones, evoking memories of the
grim day nine years ago when the same panel rejected Tower over
allegations about his private conduct and possible conflict of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was the fear of turning Jones' nomination into ``a
national circus'' like Tower's became, Coats said, that led the
committee to refuse to report Jones' selection to the Senate floor,
even without a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the panel's chairman, was the lone
Republican of the committee's 10, to stick up for Jones. The others
did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe he can be a leader or gain the confidence of
others,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect him to be perfect, but we do expect him to be
honest,'' said Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the eight Democrats on the panel _ Sen. Robert
Byrd of West Virginia and Sen. Charles Robb of Virginia _ voiced
strong support for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daryl Jones is an American success story,'' said Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``His commitment has been to public service,'' said Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had telephoned wavering senators on behalf of Jones and
Wednesday he voiced disappointment. ``He deserved the opportunity
to be considered by the full Senate,'' Clinton said in a statement,
after meeting with Jones at the White House for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the Armed
Services Committee, called on the White House to quickly nominate
someone else to fill the Air Force's top civilian job, which
oversees the service's budgets, training and recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials privately mentioned two California
Democrats as possibilities: Ron Dellums, a retired congressman, and
Jane Harman, a California congresswoman who lost the Democratic
nomination in the California governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' doomed nomination underscored the administration's
persistent problem in vetting candidates for high-level positions.
Several of Clinton's picks, ranging from Zoe Baird for attorney
general to Lani Guinier for a Justice Department position, have
become embroiled in such controversy that they either withdrew
their nominations or were abandoned by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's vote, White House and Pentagon officials
blamed each other for not properly vetting Jones. Some officials
even faulted Jones for not alerting administration officials to
potential accusations, even bogus ones, that could be used against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials were aware of some problems, but did
not think they were disqualifying. But there were some unpleasant
surprises, such as fees that Jones accepted from a Florida bond
firm. The Securities and Exchange Commission investigated and
cleared Jones, but the incident troubled many senators.
</P>
<P>
   Some administration aides acknowledged a sense of false
confidence that Jones' political opponents in Florida, where he has
served in the state Legislature since 1990, would have already dug
up any serious accusations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
