<HEADLINE>
GYMNASTIC INJURIES HARD TO AVOID, COACHES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GYM-GOODWILL-LAN-SANG) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the gymnastics injury that left Sang Lan of China
paralyzed below the upper chest, gymnastics coaches agreed
Wednesday that injuries are inevitable in the sport, even in
practice and at any age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accidents happen in contact sports,'' said Tony Gahman of
North Star in Montville, N.J., president of United States of
America Elite Coaches Association, ``and gymnastics is a contact
sport because of the equipment. You're hitting a vaulting horse or
you're hitting the floor. That's contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Sang is 17. Most female gymnasts are much younger, and Gahman
said they are not injured as frequently as their elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get older,'' he said, ``you're going to find more use
injuries coming out. You do something wrong for eight years and it
will show up. If you throw a baseball the wrong way for eight
years, in time your shoulder will pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ways you can get hurt,'' he added.
``Sometimes when they're warming up, the girls are nervous. But
this age is probably the safest gymnastics has ever been. Equipment
is better, mats are softer, coaching techniques and spotting
techniques are more advanced. But accidents happen. There have been
a lot of new acrobatics in the last five to seven years, but I
haven't seen accidents as a result of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Pendergast is the owner and head coach of Paragon
Gymnastics in Closter, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the lower levels of ability,'' he said, ``there are not
many problems. They are not doing enough high-impact pounding or
landing. On higher levels, we have Achilles' tendinitis, patellar
tendinitis, maybe a rolled ankle. The injuries run the gamut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think injuries are ever inevitable, but when you're at
this level of skill and in this level of competition, you pretty
much know how to bail out and not get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for injuries may be the greater physical stress
caused by the increased difficulty in routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago,'' Pendergast said, ``Cathy Rigby did
wonderful things. Now my 7-to-10-year-olds are doing more than she
did. Their compulsories on the beam are harder than what she was
doing in optionals. My 9-to-14-year-olds are doing more than Olga
Korbut did in floor exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 article in the New England Journal of Medicine discussed
the physical and emotional problems of elite female gymnasts. It
said in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Most elite gymnasts do not pass through childhood and
adolescence without injury....Repetitive stress on the developing
musculoskeletal system, which has a much higher cartilage content
than in adults, may cause an accumulation of minor physical insults
that can result in permanent injury or deformity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
