<HEADLINE>
REFEREES VYING FOR 10 OPENINGS IN THE NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Basketball players are not the only
hopefuls in the FILA Summer Pro League at The Pyramid at Long Beach
State. Forty referees, who have officiated in college and/or the
CBA, are vying for five to 10 openings in the NBA. All of the 40
referees are lucky to be at The Pyramid because each was
hand-picked by the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA keeps 58 referees. Typically, only one or two move on
each year. But this season, Wally Rooney, the NBA's assistant
director of referees, expects more openings because of early
retirements and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   `It's very competitive to be an NBA ref,'' Rooney said. `More
and more people play ball in college, want to stay in basketball
and try officiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney rates officials on judgment, appearance and running
ability. This season, he will try something new by telling the
harsh truth to those who miss too many calls.
</P>
<P>
   `Every year, we kept seeing a lot of the same faces of guys who
didn't have a chance,'' Rooney said. `So now we're going to tell
them to forget dreaming of the NBA, stay with college and move on.
Why continue to dream, dream, dream, when it's not going to
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Those dreamers were hoping to become the next Joe Crawford, Hugh
Evans or Dick Bavetta, who each make more than $200,000 per season.
First-year referees make $80,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   GLOBETROTTERS ON TOP
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem Globetrotters (5-0) look like the only team with a
lock into the league's four-team playoffs. In the six-game regular
season, the Globetrotters are the only undefeated team.
Globetrotter players are saying that winning the summer league is
important because they want to change their image.
</P>
<P>
   `It's important for us because most people think of the
Globetrotters as a show, spinning a ball on our finger and joking
around,'' said Joseph Blair, who played at Arizona and was drafted
in 1996 by the Seattle Supersonics. `We want to show everybody that
we can actually play ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair had 22 points and 17 rebounds in the Globetrotters' 111-84
win over the International Stars. He was asked if the Globetrotters
had an advantage because they have played together this season.
</P>
<P>
   `Actually, we have a red and a blue team, and all the guys here
are split,'' he said. `There's really only one guy here that I've
played with.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAYOFF PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   The four playoff spots still are up for grabs with the regular
season to conclude on Friday. Slam (5-1), which features former
Long Beach State star Juaquin Hawkins and Duke standout Ricky
Price, and Hoop Mecca (5-1), which has the Lakers' Shea Seals and
Charlotte Hornets' Anthony Mason, must wait to see the results
other games.
</P>
<P>
   Four other teams are 4-1. If any of those teams lose, it is out.
If the Globetrotters finish undefeated and more than three teams
are tied with 5-1 records, then victory margin will be the
tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL SHOWCASE
</P>
<P>
   The league announced its rosters for Sunday's fifth annual
Southern California High School All-Star Showcase at 7:30 p.m.,
which follows the league's championship game. The area's top high
players are in the showcase, including Poly's Ricky Anderson who is
headed to Arizona and Manuel Arts' Ricky Duff headed to Long Beach
State.
</P>
<P>
   In previous showcases, UCLA's J.R. Henderson and Jelani McCoy
plus Arizona's Miles Simon have played.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   ALSTON IS BACK
</P>
<P>
   Rafer Alston, a point guard from Fresno St. who was drafted 39th
by the Milwaukee Bucks, surprised coaches and teammates on the
Globetrotters when he did not show up to a game on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He had 11 points and 14 assists on Wednesday and was smiling
after his team's win. About missing Tuesday, he said, `I had to
catch up on some family stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
