<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREED IS TURNING SPORTS INTO A BURLESQUE OF ABSURDITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the weird events unfolding in my midst, I oftentimes feel
as though I'm an alien somehow stumbling around in a strange
faraway planet.
</P>
<P>
   I keep going into movie houses where I keep witnessing films
with silly plots and silly actors trying to convey some silly
politically correct message that makes me feel silly for paying for
such silliness in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   I keep turning on television where I keep seeing various talking
heads giving various viewpoints on various sex scandals,
fund-raising scandals, media scandals, banking scandals, talk show
scandals, so many scandals that I become scandalized by the sure
volume of them all.
</P>
<P>
   I need to get back to the earth I remember. I need to get back
to the place where a person can have a smoke in a tavern without
getting busted for it.
</P>
<P>
   I need to get back to a simpler time when athletics was the
essence of competition, and when greed didn't turn it into a
monetary burlesque of absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   This celestial sphere of ours has turned upside down, and I'm at
the bottom struggling to emerge from the quicksand muck of the
internet, of the suffocating tax strictures, of the new world order
that has left me kicking and screaming for a return to the bad old
world when as a kid I was actually allowed to ride my bicycle
without a helmet, God forbid!
</P>
<P>
   I know I'm out of sync with the times when I'm on a Fox
television sports talk show with two other members of the media the
other day, and I'm assaulted for saying what a fool Butch Goring is
for turning down that $400,000 a year contract that was offered to
him by the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I was drowned out by the two other panelists, Randy
Youngman, an Orange County newspaper sports columnist, and Joe
McDonnell, a Los Angeles radio sports talk show host, for uttering
such a blasphemous view.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have heard, Goring felt he was being lowballed by
at least $100,000 by the Mighty Ducks, who still are paying off on
the $500,000 a year contract they gave to Pierre Page, a coach they
recently fired.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, I'm for a person making as much money as he can and
receiving fair market value income for his services.
</P>
<P>
   But, sorry, I just can't work up any sympathy for Butch Goring,
who probably earns less than $200,000 a year to coach the Utah
Grizzlies of the International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   I know too many people in these corporate downsizing days who
are unemployed and not enjoying the fruits of a robust economy. I
know too many people holding down two jobs and working 80 hours a
week just to make ends meet. I know too many people who can't
fathom making $400,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Youngman and McDonnell were loud in their praise of Goring for
sticking to his principles.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fine line between sticking to your principles and
committing self-flagellation--and Goring seems to have crossed the
line into doing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Oh Butchie Boy really showed the Mighty Ducks he's one tough,
principled guy, didn't he! I'm just trying to figure out what all
that display of bravado got him.
</P>
<P>
   He's still stuck in the hockey outback in Utah, while a guy
named Craig Hartsburg gladly accepted approximately the same
three-year, $1.2 million contract that the Mighty Ducks had offered
Goring.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Hartsburg might not have the same storied principles of
Butch Goring, but he definitely has a lot more sense, if now not a
lot more dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Butch Goring is not alone in having a mangled sense
of perspective because of the staggering amounts of money that are
being waved about these days in American athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The classic case of a guy getting blindly caught up in this
insanity and getting burned by it was the one-time second baseman
for the Los Angeles Dodgers, Jody Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Offered a two-year, $6 million contract by the Dodgers after the
1992 season, Reed and his agent stubbornly declined it.
</P>
<P>
   His decision not only turned out to be disastrous for Reed, but
also for the Dodgers, who, rejected by Reed, went after a Montreal
second baseman named Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, to acquire DeShields, Fred Claire, then the Dodger general
manager, had to give up Pedro Martinez, a most unfortunate decision
that wound up having a terrible impact on both the Dodgers and
Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's total income during the next few seasons wouldn't even
add up to $1 million, and this financial genius now is out of
baseball, wondering, I'm sure, what empty thoughts blew through his
mind that year when he so blithely sniffed his nose at a $6 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the planet now rotates on a different axis.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, reportedly offered up to $86 million from the
Dodgers, got into such a terrible salary beef with the team that he
wound up being traded.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweight champion, Evander Holyfield, scoffs disdainfully
when HBO offers him a minuscule $15 million to settle the
heavyweight title with Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   An untried collegian named J.D. Drew thought it below his
dignity to sign with the Philadelphia Phillies a year ago when they
offered him only $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and on and on, and frankly, I'm nauseated by it
all.
</P>
<P>
   But I guess Butch Goring isn't.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the guy feels he was thrown a crumb by the Mighty
Ducks, and no way was he going to let them exploit him with that
400,000 a year pittance.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   And may Butch Goring have a wonderful time next season as he
tours the exotic enclaves around the glamorous IHL, while Craig
Hartsburg endures sweatshop wages working for the Mighty Ducks in
the drab NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
