<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-SANG-COX     07-22 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-SANG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctor: Sang unlikely to walk again
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ A split second of indecision has changed Sang
Lan's life forever.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old Chinese gymnast remained paralyzed from the
chest down Wednesday after losing control of a warmup vault and
landing on her head the previous night at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Attending physician Dr. Vincent Leone said it was unlikely she
would walk again from the ``violent injury,'' but was optimistic
she could regain function in her arms. He said it's too early to
predict, but added ``she's young and has good healing potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill officials worked with the U.S. and Chinese governments
to arrange visas and flights for her parents, while gymnastics
officials and former athletes, fearing damage to the sport's image,
emphasized its safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a difficult maneuver. It was a mistake,'' said
Peter Kormann, a 1976 Olympian and U.S. Atlanta Olympic men's
coach, who saw the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Sang, the Chinese vault champion, was injured on a common vault
called a handspring front somersault. It is essentially a handstand
into two flips. Observers thought she may have slipped while
pushing off from the pommel horse and decided to do what's called a
``timer'' vault _ just one flip. But Sang over-rotated, balled up
and tucked her head before crashing into the mat.
</P>
<P>
   Sang suffered a fracture-dislocation of the C-6, C-7 vertabrae
in the lower neck. Doctors said she can flex her elbows and extend
her wrists. She also can feel her shoulders to about the upper
chest.
</P>
<P>
   There was no spotter, who could have averted the accident,
because Sang was so proficient and the vault was so basic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very familiar with this rotation and did it a lot of
times and even she did not know how it happened,'' team leader Zhao
Yuxia said through an interpreter at the most well-attended news
conference of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao said that while Sang lay on the mat, she asked her coach if
she would be a gymnast again.
</P>
<P>
   And, the interpreter related, ``She really wished she could
stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   Leone, an orthopedic spine surgeon at Nassau County Medical
Center, has realigned Sang's spine and will stabilize and fuse the
injured area. He said an experimental drug will be used to repair
nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth such incident in gymnastics since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elena Moukina, a world all-around champion from the Soviet
Union, was paralyzed while training for the floor exercise prior to
the '80 Olympics. She appeared in a wheelchair at the 1994 Goodwill
Games in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   _ American gymnast Julissa Gomez hit her head on the horse in
1988 at a Tokyo meet. Two weeks later, her oxygen was accidentally
cut off and she went into an irreversible coma. She died three
years later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adriana Duffy, a Stanford student competing for Puerto Rico,
was paralyzed in 1989 on a vault similar to Sang's at the World
Championships in Germany. She's also in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Plant, president of the Goodwill Games, said the event has
insurance to provide for Sang's immediate needs.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding her future requirements, he said, ``We're a big
organization and we have resources and we're going to do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sang, the only child of parents who were described by Chinese
officials as ``workers,'' is a quiet junior high school student. In
her official biography, her hobby was listed as watching
television, especially comedies. Sang does not speak English, but
Leone said she understood her situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very frustrated about not being able to move,'' he said.
``She has not cried much.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Sang asked about him. ``I told her I was a gymnast
and I had hurt my back and that's why I decided to become a
doctor.'' Leone related. ``She said, `Then I'll become a doctor.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The accident comes on the heels of criticism that gymnastics
contributes to eating disorders and injuries when coaches push
teenage girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's evidence of abuse in gymnastics,'' said
Olympic gold medalist Bart Conner, who is doing Goodwill commentary
for TBS. ``The fact that she got hurt on a common vault where she
was taking no unnecessary risks, I can only chalk it up as just a
sad, unlucky attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner said all gymnasts have been in a precarious situation
like Sang's, but that she may have gotten caught up in the
excitement of the moment. He said, ``You're taught by your coaches
if you're in the middle of a trick, you never bail.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
