<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-TRACK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loroupe still loves N.Y. as she buries 10,000 field
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ ``Nice place.'' It's a phrase Tegla Loroupe
turns to over and over again. No wonder. Twice, the diminutive
Kenyan has run to victory in the New York Marathon _ including the
first time she went the distance in 1994 _ and Wednesday night
defended her Goodwill Games 10,000-meter in stylish fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Impressively, in 90-degree heat, Loroupe ran the second half of
the race three seconds faster than the first, winning in 32
minutes, 15.44 seconds. She finished half a lap ahead of runner-up
Sally Barsosio and twice lapped 5,000-meter world record-holder Bo
Jiang of China.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the track competition was contested in a makeshift
stadium about 30 miles from the bright lights and hip beat of
Manhattan. It's still New York.
</P>
<P>
   When her introduction brought a standing ovation, top U.S.
finisher Shelly Steely turned to her and cracked: ``Tegla, you have
more American fans here than anybody.'' Loroupe laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good relations with the people here,'' Loroupe said
later. ``I can say my running in New York has given me a lot of
opportunities to be known worldwide. Because of my (marathons here)
I was able to break the world record.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Loroupe, 26, broke Ingrid Kristiansen's 13-year-old
record in the marathon, covering the Rotterdam course in a time of
2:20:47 _ particularly stunning in that she was 41 seconds off
world-best pace with only seven miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   But her performance wasn't without controversy, as she was paced
through the streets of Rotterdam by two Kenyan men. That's
generally accepted overseas, but in the United States pacing by men
can be grounds for disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rotterdam is a mixed race (men and women), and I always like
to run with the men,'' said Loroupe, six months before diagnosed
with a lower back stress fracture. ``I was able to go with them, so
I took advantage to run with them ...''
</P>
<P>
   And as Kristiansen acknowledged later, ``She still had to run
the race, even if she had rabbits (pacing her).''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kenyan, her record run set off a celebration in the
streets of Nairobi. Photos of Loroupe, petite even by running
standards at 4-foot-11, 82 pounds, surfaced on the front page of
the nation's newspapers. All the while she worried about the safety
of her parents as tribal wars raged nearby the family farm.
</P>
<P>
   While she trained in Germany before the race, her thoughts were
often of her family back in southern Kenya. Her parents, Losiwa and
Mary, are sheep farmers and tribes were stealing animals from
farmers. After Rotterdam, she helped them buy more land some 30
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so worried, and there was nothing I could do,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just win races and break records.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
