<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME HAS COME FOR JOHNSON TO JUSTIFY THE FUSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Keyshawn Johnson will be the Jets' ``go-to
receiver'' this year, coach Bill Parcells said Wednesday as camp
opened. After Johnson's two good seasons, despite a less-than-ideal
relationship with quarterback Neil O'Donnell, this could be the
kind of breakout season the Jets had in mind for Johnson when they
made him the league's top draft pick in 1996. And Johnson is
getting along with Glenn Foley, who will be throwing the football
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a conversation piece,'' Johnson said of Foley. ``We can
talk to him and let him know how our feelings are and what we think
and what we see. He listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Did that mean he did not communicate well with O'Donnell, whom
the Jets cut last month?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that Neil didn't listen,'' Johnson said. ``I
just didn't talk to him as much as I can talk to Glenn. We just
didn't have conversations. Me and Glenn have conversations off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Donnell, now a Cincinnati Bengal, was not a
chatterbox. And his apparent reluctance to have a dialogue with
Johnson presumably was affected by the fact that Johnson described
him as ``a stiff puppet'' in his book about his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, meanwhile, says that he would be foolish not to make
Johnson part of the action. ``He's a big-play guy,'' said the new
No. 1 quarterback. ``I'm going to get him the ball every chance I
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has 127 catches in two seasons, good for 1,748 yards and
13 touchdowns. Those statistics compare favorably to those of his
idol, Jerry Rice, who snared 135 passes, 18 for touchdowns, in his
first two years with San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has told Johnson in several recent private meetings
that he expects him to improve all aspects of his game, and that he
wants him to be the player the quarterback seeks out. Asked about
Foley's importance to the team, Parcells was quick to mention the
newly arrived running back Curtis Martin as well as Johnson. ``It's
not just about Glenn Foley,'' Parcells said. ``But if we can use
Curtis, if Keyshawn can be a real go-to guy like we know he can ...
''
</P>
<P>
   So, will Johnson be the man?
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to be it,'' said Parcells, who has named Wayne
Chrebet as the full-time starter at the other receiving spot.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is expanding the passing game, and not just with the
wide receivers. Martin, an outstanding runner with the Patriots, is
much more of a receiving threat than was the departed Adrian
Murrell. And Parcells now has fullback Keith Byars, one of the best
players in recent years in catching passes out of the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   The title of go-to guy was one that Johnson gave himself from
the moment the Jets made him a pro. ``I'm the same guy I was in my
rookie year,'' he said. ``It's just that I've got Parcells on my
side now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is also listening. Parcells wanted him somewhat lighter
than last year, so Johnson, 6 feet 3 inches, came in at 210 pounds,
seven pounds fewer than in 1997. Parcells has never complained
about Johnson's willingness to block, but demanded better workout
habits. ``I can be whatever he wants me to be,'' Johnson said of
his coach. ``He knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   BILL PARCELLS has put pressure on the second-year place-kicker
JOHN HALL to improve on his field-goal percentage of just over 68
percent. ``I've talked to my scouts'' about bringing in another
kicker, Parcells said. ``He's a tremendous kickoff guy, but 68.5
accuracy is not a winning performance in the NFL'' ... KYLE BRADY,
the club's top draft pick of 1995, is no longer the automatic
first-string tight end. Parcells is placing him in open competition
with FRED BAXTER ... NEIL O'DONNELL still has not returned the
$3.75 million advance on his 1998 salary. Since the Jets cut him
last month, he has earned more than $12,000 in money-market
interest. Parcells said if the money does not arrive soon that
``we'll take action.'' ... The Jets have placed defensive lineman
TERRY DAY on the non-football injury list. He hurt a knee playing
basketball. The team cut offensive lineman JAY HAGOOD, who played
in two games as a rookie last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
