</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RISKS, U.S. WANTS CAMBODIANS TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite warnings that elections in Cambodia this
weekend will be marred by violence and anything but free and fair,
the Clinton administration says it wants to see the balloting in
that battered Southeast Asian nation carried out on time.
</P>
<P>
   The hope within the administration, which is spending $2.3
million to underwrite private groups that will monitor the
election, is that Cambodians will rise above the intimidation and
violence that have marked the election campaign and vote their
conscience on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For months the State Department has been pressed by human-rights
groups and international election monitors who say that the United
States and other foreign governments should demand a postponement
of the election, given the climate of fear that now exists among
the Cambodian government's political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration rejected the advice. If the
election has even a semblance of fairness, American officials say,
it should result in a coalition government in which Prime Minister
Hun Sen, who took sole power in a coup last year in which dozens of
his political opponents were killed, will be forced to share
authority with Cambodian leaders who enjoy far wider public
support.
</P>
<P>
   That is roughly what happened in 1993, when Cambodia held
national elections that were the culmination of a $2 billion United
Nations peacekeeping operation intended to help Cambodia rebuild
after two decades during which the nation was shattered by civil
war, the genocidal rule of the Khmer Rouge and foreign occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States played a major role during those years as the
patron of one side in the Cambodian conflict during the Vietnam War
of the early 1970s, and as a leading force behind the decade-long
isolation of Cambodia when it was occupied by Vietnam in the 1980s.
The United States was also one of the five governments that
negotiated the 1991 Cambodia peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be a perfect election, not at all,'' said
a senior administration official who is involved in Cambodian
policy. ``But we need to give Cambodian voters the chance. If Hun
Sen tries to steal the election, then we can blow the whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration arrived at a policy _ to support the election
schedule, but to make no predictions about the fairness of the
ballot and to be ready to declare it a sham _ after an extended
debate between the United States and its European allies over the
ability of the Cambodian government to carry out a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, led by the French, the former colonial power in
Cambodia, have been far more optimistic in their public statements
about the prospects for free elections.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the United States, the European Union has donated
millions of dollars directly to the government in Phnom Penh to
help pay for the balloting. The United States is providing money
solely to non-government groups and to a special United Nations
team.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent human-rights groups say that the aid money is in
danger of being wasted, and that there is every reason to believe
that the election will be a sham unless postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The present political environment in Cambodia, in which
opposition parties are not able to operate freely and safely, is in
no way conducive to the holding of free, fair and credible
elections,'' Human Rights Watch Asia said in a report last month.
``There is no chance that a deeply flawed and rushed electoral
process will help Cambodian establish democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Two private groups that are being paid $700,000 by the United
States government to monitor the elections, the National Democratic
Institute and International Republican Institute, said in a
statement last week that preparations for the election were
``fundamentally flawed'' and that ``systematic and widespread
political intimidation and violence have affected the ability of
opposition parties to fairly compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the groups said that opposition politicians were
``actively participating'' in the campaign and that, despite
efforts by the government to intimidate voters, ``the outcome of
the election is not a forgone conclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      07-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S ARMY ORDERED TO GIVE UP VAST COMMERCIAL EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ President Jiang Zemin has ordered China's
military to relinquish its sprawling, multi-billion dollar
commercial empire, saying it is the only way to combat an epidemic
of smuggling, which the army dominates.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, appearing somber in a pea-green Mao suit as he addressed
an extraordinary meeting of top military commanders on Tuesday,
called on the armed forces to regain their ``purity'' in order to
regain public confidence and to safeguard the nation's long-term
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Yet business, and smuggling, are so entrenched in the army that
truly separating it from its commerce could take years.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, coming so unexpectedly, offered scant clues
about whether Jiang has the political will or the support from
military leaders to genuinely carry out such an ambitious
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Most remarkable, perhaps, was his indirect admission of the
degree of lawlessness that exists in the army, which has been
off-limits for criticism. Never before in 49 years of Communist
Party rule has the military been so publicly questioned, suggesting
that Jiang may be serious about deep-seated change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army and armed police forces must earnestly carry out
checks on all kinds of commercial companies set up by subsidiary
units, and without exception from today must not engage in their
operation,'' Jiang said in his speech, reported by China Central
Television on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the broadcast, dozens of military leaders were shown
earnestly taking notes. As chairman of the Communist Party's
Central Military Commission, Jiang is China's commander in chief.
Yet the army wields wide power, and it is unlikely that Jiang would
make such a bold pronouncement without the support of top generals.
</P>
<P>
   All of the army's senior leaders attended the anti-smuggling
conference at which Jiang spoke. Seated beside him were Gen. Zhang
Wannian and Gen. Chi Haotian, who are vice chairmen of the Central
Military Commission. Generals Fu Quanyou, Yu Yongbo, Wang Ke and
Wang Ruilin also appeared in the China Central Television
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the world's military forces, China's is by far the most
entrepreneurial. The vast array of businesses it owns or partly
controls ranges from commercial airlines to pharmaceutical
companies and from vegetable growers to arms dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Army-related businesses earn billions of dollars each year,
though they are so numerous and disparate that virtually no one
inside or outside China can accurately estimate their full scope.
</P>
<P>
   Although China's military often appears to outsiders like a
stern-faced monolith, its role in money-making resembles a
hodgepodge of disparate ventures, essentially built by military
officers taking advantage of their authority in China's political
apparatus to build lucrative operations.
</P>
<P>
   The army's role in smuggling appears to have grown in tandem
with the nation's stunning economic growth over the last 20 years.
Although the true volume of goods smuggled into China cannot be
measured, officials conservatively estimate that it has reached
tens of billions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   More than $10 billion in tax revenue is lost to smuggling each
year, the New China News Agency reported. Chinese Customs,
alternatively seen as corrupt and unable to stand up to military
smugglers, confiscated just $330 million of smuggled goods in the
first five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The main contraband is not drugs or illegal arms, but rather
high-end goods that face such onerous import duties that customers
are willing to pay handsomely for an army transport that escapes
scrutiny at a border.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, echoing comments he made last week at a launching of a
broad anti-smuggling campaign, said that all party and government
offices and law enforcement agencies would also be required to cut
ties with companies they own. That will be a gargantuan task.
</P>
<P>
   When any national campaign begins, there may be several
political elements at work. Yet decision-making in China remains so
opaque that it is difficult to know if the driving force behind the
anti-smuggling campaign is Jiang's desire to flex his muscles over
the military, or to buttress his reputation as a
corruption-fighter.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be financial concerns. Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
has argued that the drastic drop in tax collection must be reversed
at a time when the government is undertaking a huge spending
program to spur economic growth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
