<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY AIKMAN LOOKS FORWARD TO TURNING COWBOYS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WICHITA FALLS _ Troy Aikman's face, tanned and lean, is slowly but
surely becoming a road map of his life.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That line there, that's for his mom's cancer. Just had her
one-year checkup, and she's doing great now, thanks for asking.
</P>
<P>
   This one that's just discernible across his forehead _ you'll
have to look close to see it _ that's for his brand new home, which
almost burned to the ground in March, just a month after he moved
into it. No, he won't be moving back in for another year yet.
</P>
<P>
   That one over there he earned all on his own. Remember the
cancerous mole that was removed from his back this off-season?
</P>
<P>
   And the crow's feet at his eyes, the little lines that crinkle
when he smiles _ he's doing that a lot these days, by the way _
well, blame last year's 6-10 record and You Know Who. No need to
mention any names. Time to let bygones be bygones.
</P>
<P>
   Was it only eight years ago that Aikman came striding into our
lives, a golden haired, rocket-armed savior from UCLA out of
Oklahoma? Three Super Bowls and a lifetime later, he remains the
Cowboys' single biggest hope if they are to rise from the ashes of
last season's 6-10 record, when the entire franchise crashed and
burned.
</P>
<P>
   Two resurrections in one NFL lifetime? The Cowboys are counting
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, that is life,'' Aikman says. ``Everyone
has hurdles and obstacles they have to overcome, and that's part of
living and part of growing up. It's how you deal with it and how
you handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like my life is very blessed. A lot of times when
there have been negatives in my life, something positive has come
from it right around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is one of those people who seems to thrive on the rigors
of camp. The omnipresent heat, the discipline that's required, the
repetition, beat some players down. Not Aikman. He eats this up,
like the soft-serve frozen yogurt he is spooning from a cup as we
talk in the Midwestern University lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of wilting, Aikman blossoms in this environment. His
classic quarterback's body is as taut and as tough as rawhide.
Despite the drain of two-a-days and practicing in the heat, there's
a spring in his step. And in his sky-blue eyes a spark _ that
unquenchable will to win _ still blazes as hot and fiery as the
first day he pulled on a Cowboys uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a realist,'' Aikman says. ``I tend to
believe that I'm generally realistic about life. But when I'm
ultimately backed up into a corner and things look their worst,
that's usually when I'm very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider him, then, very optimistic about this football team.
</P>
<P>
   The window of opportunity for an Aikman-led Cowboys team to win
another Super Bowl began inexorably inching downward from the
moment it won in Pasadena in 1992 and Aikman understands that. But
closed and latched tight? Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The window of opportunity is closing with the guys we're
accustomed to playing with and to seeing,'' Aikman concedes. ``In
fact, some of those guys we used to talk about are no longer here.
Tony Tolbert, Charles Haley, Jay Novaceck, Mark Tuinei, those guys
are gone. So sure, that window is getting smaller for guys who have
been here awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what that means is that we've got to rely on younger
players now. You look at the 49ers and the success that they've
had, and they continue to do it with a different cast of guys.
That's what we have to learn to do. That's what every organization
is striving for.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the starting over that gnaws at Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disappointing thing about our situation is that we
allowed it to get to 6-10,'' he says. ``I don't think that should
have ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who were here for 1-15 \Rin 1989\S know how much
work went into getting us back on track, and then to sit and watch
this organization go where it went these last two years was
completely unnecessary, and that's what hurts most of all.''
</P>
<P>
   That hurt, though, is receding. What remains, Aikman believes,
is opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's harder to put the bad things that happen behind
us, but it's over,'' he says. ``Nobody cares about last year now or
that we went 6-10. Now it's what happens from this point forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope last year was just an aberration. That's why I've said
this year is such a pivotal year, just in determining where we're
at from a talent standpoint. The competitiveness we each have
inside makes us say, `We're better than that,' and I think we are.
I truly believe it. But we're going to find out this year how much
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we as good as we like to think we are, or are we entering
a period where we've got some questions? I tend to think that we're
still an awfully good football team, maybe not the most talented
team in the league, but I think if we play as a team and the way
we're capable of playing, then we can win every game we play. We
won't do that, but we could.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Aikman's belief that owner Jerry Jones, accidentally or
otherwise, uncovered a rare gem when he hired Chan Gailey as the
team's new head coach, but Troy is careful not to gush about him,
knowing there are those who might take his approval the wrong way,
considering his problems with Gailey's predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan is good person, and he has a great football mind,''
Aikman says. ``I don't know how to quantify it or how big or how
small a difference he'll make. He has provided some real leadership
for this football team, provided some direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't take this wrong, but Gailey is actually promoting (gasp!)
some team discipline. Penalties in practice equal laps around the
field, even for veterans such as Daryl Johnston and Nate Newton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, discipline has all of a sudden taken on
this negative context,'' Aikman says, frowning. ``I'm not sure why
that is. I've always believed that discipline in one's life is
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard Chan necessarily address discipline as much as
he's addressed doing things the right way: `Here's what we expect,
and here's what I'm asking you to do.' It's a matter of everyone
being accountable, everyone being able to believe in the guy next
to him. That's what it comes down to.''
</P>
<P>
   It is amusing to Aikman that so many fans _ and media, too _
worry about whether he is happy. He really shouldn't be surprised.
As the Cowboys' quarterback and their most visible player, he is a
weather vane for the fans, who tend to gauge the Cowboys'
temperature _ hot, cold or indifferent _ by what they see on
Aikman's face.
</P>
<P>
   It is no exaggeration to say that when he's smiling, most of
Fort Worth-Dallas smiles along. That there haven't been many smiles
the past few years doesn't mean, however, that Aikman is an unhappy
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the public perception, the fans' view of my level of
happiness, isn't always accurate, not when we're struggling like we
were last year,'' Aikman says. ``But I can't just blow that off. I
can't just overlook the fact that we're not playing as well as
we're capable of playing. That's very frustrating, and I know it
shows sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But off the field, I'm very happy with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, it's written all over his face. (Jim Reeves is a
columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram.Com on the World Wide Web at http:
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
