<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEPARD, FIRST AMERICAN IN SPACE, DIES AT AGE 74 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan B. Shepard Jr., the Mercury astronaut whose pioneering
flight into space ignited America's push to the moon, died Tuesday.
He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, who later became the fifth of only 12 men to walk on
the moon _ hitting a golf ball on the lunar surface to the delight
of Earth-bound duffers _ died at 10:30 p.m., CDT, at Community
Hospital of the Monterey Peninsula in Monterey, Calif. His death
followed a lengthy illness, a spokeswoman for the facility said.
Shepard was diagnosed with leukemia 1 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who are old enough to remember the first space
flights will always remember what an impression he made on us and
the world,'' said President Clinton, who led a long list of public
mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's 1961 flight aboard the cramped Freedom 7 capsule,
launched atop a Redstone rocket, was the first manned U.S. space
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``His flight was a tremendous statement about tenacity, courage
and brilliance,'' said NASA administrator Dan Goldin. ``He crawled
on top of that rocket that had never before flown into space with a
person aboard and he did it. That was an unbelievable act of
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Services for Shepard, who in recent years made his home in
Pebble Beach, Calif., were pending.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Louise; three daughters, Julie,
Laura and Alice; and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's suborbital hop on May 5, 1961, from Cape Canaveral,
Fla., lasted just 16 minutes, soared no higher than 116 miles and
no further than 302 miles into the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But it was enough to convince then-President John Kennedy 20
days later to commit the United States to reaching the moon with
human explorers within the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard became a central figure in the unfolding drama of that
Cold War space race between the United States and the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   It was in April 1959, with much fanfare, that Shepard was
selected as one of seven military test pilots for NASA's Mercury
program, a series of rocket missions intended to demonstrate that
humans not only could survive in space but perform piloting tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union had successfully launched Sputnik, the first
man-made satellite, on Oct. 4, 1957. The demonstration shook the
United States because it demonstrated long range missile capability
to go with the Soviet's new nuclear prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Within the year, President Eisenhower and Congress responded
with the creation of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the Soviets scored first again.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, 1961, a young cosmonaut, Yuri Gagarin, became the
first human in space, making a single orbit of the Earth, 23 days
before Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Shepard might have beaten the Russians into space
had the Redstone rocket not required an electrical modification
before Shepard took the first flight, said Max Faget, the former
NASA engineer who guided the development of the Mercury capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to make another (test) flight which held up (Shepard's)
flight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there was no mistaking the significance of
Shepard's shorter flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was based on that success of his flight that President
Kennedy decided to go to the moon, which was an astounding thing,''
recalled Faget. ``The president said we would go in the decade,
which was really only 8 1/2 years. We had a tough job.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Shepard campaigned for an opportunity to fly on another Mercury
mission, an orbital flight launched aboard the more powerful Atlas
rocket. But NASA grew eager to move ahead with its two-man Gemini
program.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was discovered that Shepard had an inner ear problem,
called Meuniere's syndrome, and he was taken off flight status.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard was appointed chief of NASA's astronaut corps, an
administrative job. Biding his time, he sought corrective surgery
that won him a return to flight status in time for an Apollo moon
assignment. He was selected to command Apollo 14 and was launched
on his second trip into space Jan. 31, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The mission followed the dramatic recovery of Apollo 13, whose
astronauts limped safely back to Earth after an explosion aboard
their outbound spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard and Edgar Mitchell became the third crew to successfully
land on the moon and the fifth and sixth men to explore its surface
as they walked the hilly Fra Mauro region and collected 92 pounds
of rock samples. Before he returned, Shepard, an avid golfer,
fashioned a club and lofted a golf ball across the lunar landscape.
</P>
<P>
   After the mission Shepard resumed duties as chief astronaut, a
post he held until he retired from the space agency Aug. 1, 1974.
He retired from the Navy as well, having attained the rank of rear
admiral. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Shepard was born in East Derry, N. H., on Nov. 18, 1923. He
graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1944 and received flight
training in Corpus Christi, Texas, and Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Following graduation from the Navy's test pilot school, Shepard
helped evaluate a range of jet aircraft, for high altitude,
refueling and aircraft carrier landings.
</P>
<P>
   Among his many honors was the Medal of Honor for spaceflight.
</P>
<P>
   With his retirement from NASA, Shepard pursued a business career
in Houston. He became chairman of the Marathon Construction Corp.
and obtained a Coors beer distributorship in Deer Park, an
industrial city of 30,000 about 10 miles east of downtown Houston,
among other interests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he joined with his fellow Mercury astronauts to found
what is now called the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation of
Titusville, Fla., which raises funds and awards scholarships to
college students pursuing careers in science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard moved his permanent residence from Houston to Pebble
Beach, Calif., about five years ago to devote more time to his
favorite recreation _ golf. Seven Fourteen Enterprises, the company
he founded to consolidate his business interests, remained in
Houston at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Among his Mercury colleagues, Shepard is survived by John Glenn,
a U.S. Senator who is training to participate in an October space
shuttle flight; M. Scott Carpenter; Gordon Cooper and Walter
``Wally'' Schirra.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil ``Gus'' Grisson died Jan. 27, 1967, in the Apollo 1 fire
at Cape Canaveral, Fla. Donald ``Deke'' Slayton died June 13, 1993,
at his Houston-area home of brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozen men who walked on the moon, 10 survive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
