<SLUG> BC-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GROUP PICKETS CONGRESS TO URGE DEFEAT OF ANTI-GAY BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Organization for Women picketed
Congress Wednesday to urge the defeat of two anti-gay legislative
proposals that the NOW president criticized as political gimmicks
designed to energize conservative Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   The protest rally came as the House prepared to vote on the
proposals that NOW President Patricia Ireland said would
politically damage Republicans by making them look ``very mean and
hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   One proposal sponsored by Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., would
prohibit the city of San Francisco from using federal housing funds
if the city continues to require its private contractors to provide
the same benefits to unmarried domestic partners as they provide
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal by Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., would nullify an
executive order by President Clinton that barred federal agencies
from discriminating against gays.
</P>
<P>
   To expose what she called ``a back-door attempt to slip''
anti-gay legislation though Congress, Ireland joined about 50
picketers marching in scorching heat outside a House office
building Wednesday, shouting slogans such as ``Hey, hey, ho, ho,
homophobia's got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some picketers carried placards with such slogans as, ``I feel
fine, I don't need to be cured,'' a response to recent newspaper
advertisements sponsored by conservative groups that maintain
religion can change the sexual orientation of gays.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ireland said the Riggs and Hefley proposals
were attempts to mobilize right-wing Christians to vote in the
November elections in a year in which experts predict a lackluster
voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clearly an election-year wedge issue,'' Ireland
said, adding ``To punish cities that are forward-looking like San
Francisco is just outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why NOW was fighting for gay rights, Ireland said the
group is ``working for all women's equality _ it includes lesbian,
bisexual and transgender people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that all oppression is wrong,'' Ireland said. ``As
feminists we do often raise issues that people consider radical.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland added: ``Every woman who steps forward to claim her
rights faces the allegation that she is queer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland said 150 years ago, women who attended the women's
rights convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y., were called ``mannish,
unnatural, and spinsters.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Peter LaBarbera, president of Americans for
Truth, a conservative group that joined with 14 others to pay for
the anti-gay advertisements in major newspapers last week, said NOW
``is out of touch with American women,'' and ``obsessed with
lesbianism.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBarbera said anti-discrimination protections in civil rights
law should not be applied to homosexual behavior ``that, unlike
skin color, can be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Clinton administration urged Congress to include
sexual orientation under the federal hate crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the acting assistant attorney general for civil
rights, told the House Judiciary Committee that President Clinton
strongly supports changing the law so that the FBI can assist state
and local governments in investigating hate crimes based on sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the FBI is empowered to step in to help
investigate certain hate crimes based on race, color, religion or
national origin. But Lee said the law is deficient because it does
not cover violent hate crimes stemming from bias based on the
victim's sexual orientation, gender or disability.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also heard testimony from Mark Bangerter of Boise,
Idaho, who said he was attacked in April and lost the sight in his
left eye after an assailant beat him, mistakenly believing he was
gay.
</P>
<P>
   Bangerter, an artist, said he had hugged a male friend goodbye
after meeting over drinks in a Boise bar, when a stranger called
him a ``faggot,'' punched him in the head, then pursued him outside
and continued to beat him, breaking bones around his eye sockets.
</P>
<P>
   Bangerter said the assailant was never caught, the Boise police
have said they have little time to investigate, and the FBI has
said it can not intervene because sexual orientation is not
included in a list of federal hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone hated gay people enough to try to kill me,'' Bangerter
said. ``The irony is that I am not gay. This happened to me because
I hugged a friend. Now I know what can and does happen to people
who are gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Traditional Values Coalition _ which claims to
represent 36,000 churches _ issued a statement calling the
administration's effort to expand the definition of a hate crime as
``nothing less than a premeditated assault on religious Americans
who oppose homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Sheldon, executive director of the coalition, said
pending legislation to expand the definition was ``like a bad
B-movie in which all of the enlightened folks from the Northeast
are going to set straight all those `Bible-toting zealots' from the
rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Sheldon said Christians ``no more hate
homosexuals than they do alcoholics or chronic gamblers. We believe
the moral choices made by homosexuals are wrong and we encourage
them to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-SHEPARD-1STLD-WR     07-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHEPARD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: made history. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision by Kennedy, which contrasted with the Soviet
policy of secrecy, the launch was broadcast live on radio and
television. The capsule separated smoothly from the rocket.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes into the mission, Shepard took over manual control
from the autopilot, putting the craft through some prescribed
maneuvers. For five minutes, at maximum altitude and traveling more
than 5,000 mph, the astronaut experienced the weightlessness of
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, what a ride!'' he said later. Yet, he said, the trip was
``pleasant and relaxing,'' with no effect on his movements and
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was almost flawless, and so was the splashdown in the
Atlantic. ``On the way to the carrier I felt relieved and happy,''
the astronaut said later. ``I knew I had done a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he used the expression A-OK is problematic. Years
later, a reporter asked Shepard if he had indeed said A-OK, and
where did the term come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Shorty Powers,'' he said enigmatically, referring to Col.
John ``Shorty'' Powers, who was press officer to the first
astronauts. It was Powers who had passed on the quote to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Everything did seem to come up A-OK. Three days later, Shepard
and his wife, the former Louise Brewer, were entertained by the
Kennedys at the White House, then whisked to New York for a
ticker-tape parade in the old Lindbergh tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, space, military and budget officials were
meeting to draw up recommendations for taking bold new steps to
catch up with and surpass Soviet space achievements. A memorandum,
handed to Kennedy the day of Shepard's White House visit,
concluded, ``Of all the programs planned, perhaps the greatest
unsurpassed prestige will accrue to the nation which first sends a
man to the moon and returns him safely to Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, Kennedy told Congress, ``This nation should commit
itself to achieving the goal, before this decade is out, of landing
a man on the moon and returning him safely to Earth. No single
space project in this period will be more impressive to mankind or
more important for the long-range exploration of space. And none
will be so difficult or expensive to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Logsdon of George Washington University said it was doubtful
that Kennedy would have issued such a challenge, if the Shepard
flight had failed.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner celebrating the 30th anniversary of the flight,
Glenn said: ``Al's flight and my flight _ it was almost like we
turned a corner. There was a feeling we were coming back. There was
a great outpouring of public spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepard called it ``just the first baby step, aiming for bigger
and better things.'' His words would be echoed eight years later by
Neil Armstrong as he stepped on the Moon with the declaration,
``One small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepard almost did not make it to the Moon himself. Before he
could train for a second space flight in the Gemini Project, he
developed inner-ear problems. Thomas Stafford, a retired astronaut,
recalled Wednesday that he and Shepard had been chosen for the
first Gemini mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge blow in his life,'' Stafford said of the medical
problems that grounded Shepard. ``He was anxious to get back into
space, to ride again.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for nearly a decade, Shepard was firmly rooted to NASA
managerial jobs, mainly directing the astronaut corps. Stafford
recalled him as a natural leader, who operated ``with more stick
than carrot and would lay down the law, saying here's how it's
going to be, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   After surgery to correct the ear problem in 1968, Shepard was
cleared to fly again and was assigned to what turned out to be the
third lunar landing. Although his first flight had been only 15
minutes, the Apollo 14 journey to the Moon added 216 hours to his
log book and rounded out an astronaut career that also included a
Congressional Space Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, he still had time for work promoting the
space program and had joined the other surviving Mercury
astronauts, and Betty Grissom, the widow of Gus Grissom, in
founding the Mercury Seven Foundation, based in Titusville, Fla.,
near Cape Canaveral. The foundation raises money for scholarships
for science and engineering students in college. He was its
president and chairman until last October.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife of 53 years, survivors include two daughters,
Laura Snyder and Juliana Coleman Jenkins, and six grandchildren.
Funeral arrangements are pending. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
