<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     07-22 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: ADVENTUROUS U.S. THEATERGOERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word (AT) in story should be replaced by the symbol) 
(ART ADV: Photo showing Cesar Sarachu in ``The Street of
Crocodiles''; Max Wright and Brian Murray in ``Twelfth Night'' will
be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As you watch the gorgeous new production of ``Twelfth
Night'' at the Vivian Beaumont Theater, you may find your emotions
tested in ways never intended by Shakespeare, Nicholas Hytner (the
man who directed it) or Lincoln Center Theater (which staged the
play as its own contribution to the theatrical portion of Lincoln
Center Festival '98).
</P>
<P>
   The Hytner production charms, maddens, surprises and
disappoints. You have to keep adjusting to it as if it were the
signal of a riveting but wandering FM broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelfth Night'' is scheduled to run through Aug. 30, while the
festival ends Sunday afternoon with the final performances of two
other theatrical productions: ``F(AT)ust: Version 3.0,'' presented
by the Barcelona company La Fura dels Baus, at the New York State
Theater, and ``The Street of Crocodiles,'' a production of the
Theatre de Complicite, at the John Jay College Theater. Complicite
is the British company that was represented at the 1996 festival by
its epic staging of ``The Three Lives of Lucie Cabrol.''
</P>
<P>
   Already come and gone: ``Village'' and ``Adam Resurrected,''
presented by the Gesher Theater of Israel, founded in 1991 by a
group of Russian emigres headed by Yevgeny Arye, the artistic
director. At first, they performed only in Russian, but now present
each production alternately in Russian and Hebrew with the same
actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``F(AT)ust'' opened too late for inclusion in this consideration
of the festival's theatrical entries, but it is clear that this
year's installment has provided a stunning, if accidental (and far
from comprehensive) overview of the differences between theater in
this country and abroad. It is not a question of money _ mostly
private here, often subsidized abroad _ or of technical facilities,
but of the nature of the audiences for whom these theaters present
their works.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen the offerings in this year's festival might
well suspect that America is a theatrical disaster area, not
because the festival entries from abroad were so uniformly fine
(they weren't), but because they showed us how narrow and limited
are our expectations of theater. When audiences aren't open and
adventurous, you can hardly expect producers, writers, directors
and actors to be.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences get what they want; another way of saying they get
what they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel they flock to the Gesher, which is offering some
startling alternatives to the more conventional works by other
local troupes. La Fura dels Baus, whose latest production is
described as ``Faust in Cyberspace,'' promises to be alternative
theater with a vengeance. Since its founding in 1983, Theatre de
Complicite has put on more than 25 productions and played in more
than 180 cities in 41 countries on 4 continents.
</P>
<P>
   The company doesn't deal in pap. Yet its productions of the
Ionesco classic ``The Chairs,'' co-produced with the Royal Court
Theater, and ``The Three Lives of Lucie Cabrol'' were popular as
well as critical successes in London. The New York critics adored
``The Chairs,'' but the public was somewhat less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, filmmaker to the world, we are in the merciless
siege of entertainment _ movie, television and even Web. Yet we
have no resident theatrical troupes of national repute. Our
audiences seem to have grown lazy _ undemanding _ on a diet of junk
food.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways ``Twelfth Night'' is a typical Lincoln Center
Theater production. It has been done with care. Hytner has a
reputation as a heavy-hitting director in both commercial and
subsidized theaters. Among his credits: the Lincoln Center Theater
revival of ``Carousel'' (a near-duplicate of the earlier version he
staged in London), Alan Bennett's ``Madness of George III'' (both
on stage and on film) and ``Miss Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelfth Night'' is a delight if you don't demand perfection.
That is, if you can be as charmed by the earnest intentions of
so-called name actors, who are not quite ready for their star
roles, as by the seriously substantial performances in smaller
roles, performed by character actors who are at ease with what they
are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Hytner's staging of the play beguiles the eye and the ear, much
in the manner of the uncontrolled substance apparently being smoked
by the bored, lovesick Duke Orsino and his attendants in the first
scene. The setting is an Illyria that, as designed by Bob Crowley,
has the serene, watery beauty of an idealized Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the time of day, whatever the weather, life in Illyria
is one long, lazy afternoon, scored by exotic music (by Jeanine
Tesori) that plays on even when the musicians have left
centerstage. Affairs of the heart, not disputed borders, are the
concern in this enchanted land.
</P>
<P>
   Orsino is obsessed by his desire for Olivia, a beautiful
countess who will have none of him. Instead, she falls in love with
Cesario, the duke's comely young emissary, who is actually the
shipwrecked Viola disguised as a man and who herself is in love
with Orsino.
</P>
<P>
   He, meanwhile, is beginning to feel increasingly warm feelings
for the beardless Cesario, though convinced he is still pining for
Olivia. You don't have to worry, of course. Sebastian, Viola's twin
brother presumed lost in the same wreck that stranded her, is also
wandering around Illyria. He is the means by which Shakespeare
straightens out the confusions resulting from cross-dressing and
mistaken identities.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on, seeing absolutely nothing except his own heady
future, is Malvolio, Olivia's pompous steward, one of the most
deliriously funny creations in all of Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Malvolio is a great character but not a major one, being the
focal point of the play's subplot involving Sir Toby Belch,
Olivia's uncle; Sir Andrew Aguecheek, Sir Toby's faint-hearted
drinking companion, and Maria, Olivia's bossy maid. Yet because of
the splendid, richly comic performances by Philip Bosco (Malvolio),
Brian Murray (Sir Toby) and Max Wright (Sir Andrew), this ``Twelfth
Night'' is turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate practical joke by which Sir Toby, Sir Andrew and
Maria convince Malvolio that Olivia loves him madly becomes the
activating center of the play. The production's high point: the
so-called ``letter scene'' in which Malvolio takes their bait as
the three conspirators spy on him, scarcely able to contain their
nearly apoplectic pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   In a properly balanced ``Twelfth Night,'' Malvolio's cruel
humiliation merely supplements the succession of darkly romantic
minuets being so persistently danced at cross-purposes by Viola
(Helen Hunt), Olivia (Kyra Sedgwick) and Orsino (Paul Rudd). Here,
the raucous, knockabout comedy is the entire show.
</P>
<P>
   The three younger actors haven't the vocal technique, the stage
presence or the innate personas that would give character to some
of the loveliest, wittiest romantic language in the canon.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who was in Hytner's most recent film, ``The Object of My
Affection,'' is a well-muscled Orsino when stripped to his thong
for swimming in an Illyrian pool. Yet he has a tendency to bark his
lines like someone of smallish stature who is always on the
defensive, trying desperately to convince the bigger guys that he
is as tough as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sedgwick is a beautiful, shimmering actress with an
attractively husky voice and the hint of a real stage talent.
Unfortunately, her scenes with Ms. Hunt seem to run out of interest
and wind long before the language stops flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunt is an immensely appealing actress on the screen (where
she won an Oscar this year for ``As Good as It Gets'') and on
television (two Emmys for her work in the sitcom ``Mad About
You''). She has fine, chiseled features of classical purity. Even
more important, she possesses a forthright, humorous intelligence,
though it doesn't yet register on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One day she might be an ideal Viola, but will she ever get the
necessary experience? Would she even want to? She is working very
hard in ``Twelfth Night'' but, as you watch her, you might think
she was trying to run under water: every movement is painfully
deliberate, carefully executed, without a moment's spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Lincoln Center made two attempts to start a repertory
company. Both failed. Some people blamed the critics for being too
harsh too soon, for not giving the nascent companies time to find
their identities. Possibly. But in the way that audiences get the
theater they deserve, repertory companies are responsible for the
reviews they receive. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I missed seeing the Gesher Theater when it brought ``Rosencrantz
and Guildenstern Are Dead'' to the Brooklyn Academy of Music in
1992, the year after its founding in Israel by Mr. Arye. The New
York Times review called that production ``refreshing'' and
``swift-paced'' and credited Arye with finding ``new relevance'' in
the play itself. Since then, the company has taken in non-Russian
Israeli actors, adopted its bilingual Russian-Hebrew performing
policy and, it is now astonishingly evident, become a troupe of
ensemble performers of singular talents and dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Peter Brook's International Center of Theater Research
in Paris and the Theatre de Complicite, which is based in London.
The Gesher can stand with them on the basis of the two productions
presented here. In a little more than eight years, the company has
developed the team work usually found in much older companies,
while it still takes the kinds of risks favored by the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Village,'' by Joshua Sobol, is a big, somewhat overstuffed
Israeli ``Our Town,'' which follows the fortunes of 20 characters,
including a turkey and a goat that talk, from the years before the
state's foundation in 1948 until the war that followed. Some of the
play's conceits are not of the first freshness, but they were
performed with such disarming humor, intelligence and conviction
that the audience was held for its nearly three-hour running time.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe's star, at least on this tour: a skinny, intense,
subversively powerful young actor named Israel (Sasha) Demidov, who
played the idiot-savant narrator in ``Village'' and the seemingly
civilized, casually vicious concentration commandant in ``Adam
Resurrected.'' He was superb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Village'' is easy to like. ``Adam Resurrected'' puts the
audience on edge. Written by Alexander Chervinsky and based on
Yoram Kaniuk's novel, this is an exuberantly impressionistic play
set in the exhausted, addled brain of Adam Stein. He is a German
Jew, a star-clown in prewar Berlin where he owned his own circus,
who is now fighting his way back to sanity in an Israeli hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The play swings abruptly, sometimes wildly through time,
embracing Adam's prewar fame and life with his wife and small
daughter, his postwar guilt and spiritual lethargy and his
hallucinatory concentration camp experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by the commandant to be his performing ``dog,'' Adam also
performs for the prisoners to distract their attention as they go
into the gas chambers. He saves himself and his daughter, but he
can't save his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The production at Lincoln Center was played in a circus tent in
Damrosch Park. The ``stage'' was the circus ring, bisected by
ominous railroad tracks, above which were a trapeze and a
tightrope, all used in various ingenious ways in the course of the
performance. The production was full of echoes of the work of other
people, everybody from Brecht and Fellini to Kander and Ebb, but it
also had its own vigorous, original life. Under the disciplined
direction of Arye, the performance was sometimes breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam Resurrected'' isn't the conventional theater of
narrative, but a theater of ideas and feelings that are expressed
as eloquently through imagery as in words. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is the Theatre de Complicite's production of ``The
Street of Crocodiles,'' subtitled ``A Dance of the Mind.'' The text
is based on stories by Bruno Schulz, the Polish Jewish writer who,
in 1942, was murdered by a Nazi officer in Drohobycz, the
provincial town where Schulz was born and lived most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Three Lives of Lucie Cabrol,'' the piece is described
as having been ``devised by the company from an adaptation by Simon
McBurney and Mark Wheatley,'' meaning that everyone involved was
invited to collaborate.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ever read any of Schulz's stories, you might suspect
they would be impossible to stage. They are the sometimes
fantastic, minutely detailed autobiographical reports from an
almost pathologically reclusive man.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz seems to have lived inside a tumultuous mind that he
protected as if it were a secret sanctuary. A strangely uncertain
place it was, a land where objects and people change shapes and
identities like dream figures. Nothing is quite what it was a
moment ago.
</P>
<P>
   Supplementing elements from the stories with events from
Schulz's own life (including his death), ``The Street of
Crocodiles'' creates an impressionistic panorama of what it might
be like to inhabit Schulz's Kafka-like world. Visions, personal
memories, nightmares and the contents of books all have the same
reality. It isn't easy following ``The Street of Crocodiles,'' even
after reading the synopsis in the program. This is theater to be
experienced as if it were a piece of music.
</P>
<P>
   It is not my favorite kind of theater. For all of its emphasis
on imagery and stagecraft, it seems a very literary kind of
theater, not only because its roots are often literary, but also
because of the volume of interpretation it inevitably prompts. Yet,
when it is staged _ you might say choreographed _ by a director of
McBurney's skills, and when it is played by a company as thoroughly
drilled as these actors, the effects can be magically liberating.
Bravo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
