<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN WEIGHTS DUTCH TRIAL IN LOCKERBIE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By YOUSSEF M., IBRAHIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain signaled its willingness Wednesday to consider
the Netherlands as the site of a trial for two Libyan suspects in
the bombing of Pan Am flight 103, which killed 270 people a decade
ago in an explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Britain and the United States had been adamant in
their insistence that the two Libyans, Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and
Lamin Khalifah Fhimah, should stand trial either in a Scottish or
American court. Libya has consistently denied any involvement in
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The United States announced on Tuesday that it would consider a
trial in the Netherlands. And Prime Minister Tony Blair told
parliament Wednesday, ``It has been our wish that the trial take
place in Scotland or the U.S., and I reject claims that there
should be any difficulty about a fair trial in Scotland.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``As the result of no progress having being made,
however, we are prepared to look at alternative ways of giving
families the justice they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the British prime minister and the Foreign and
Commonwealth office here Wednesday confirmed that Blair and
President Clinton had indeed discussed the idea ``several times''
in the last few weeks and that negotiations were under way with the
Dutch government on how to bring it about. But British officials
said talks were in a preliminary stage and faced complicated legal
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, a Foreign Office official who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the primary motivation behind the move is that too
much time has gone by without a resolution of the case and that
Britain's priority is to bring the suspects to justice, partly to
satisfy relatives of British passengers on board the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here and in the Netherlands said the legal aspects of
such a trial are still to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch Foreign Ministry official who insisted on anonymity said
if the trial were to take place, it would happen in an ad hoc
court, in a courtroom rented or used for the purpose, and would be
conducted not under Dutch law but under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Libya would agree to that. British
officials said they would insist that the trial be conducted by
Scottish judges under Scottish law and not by an international
panel of judges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
