<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSPAN WARNS INVESTORS ABOUT END TO EXUBERANCE
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, warned investors
during his appearance before the House Banking Committee not to
assume that the good times on Wall Street would last forever. But
he could not predict when the exuberance would end and a correction
start. His comments helped send stock market gauges lower. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 61.28 points, to 9,128.91. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed down 0.99 at 1,164.08. The
Nasdaq composite index dropped 9.39, to 1,969.75. The yield on the
30-year bond rose to 5.68 percent, from 5.66 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   KOHLBERG KRAVIS ACQUIRING INSURER
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts is buying insurance broker Willis
Corroon Group of Britain, for (PS)851 million, or $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT SHARES CONTINUE TO DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of E.I. du Pont de Nemours fell $3.1875, or 4.78 percent,
after the chemical company reported profits were 12 percent lower
in the second quarter. DuPont attributed the profit drop to
acquisitions, the strike at General Motors and lower prices for
oil, fibers and chemicals used in crop protection.
</P>
<P>
   4TH COLUMBIA/HCA OFFICIAL CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors filed an indictment accusing a fourth executive of
Columbia/HCA Healthcare of participating in an illegal scheme to
defraud Federal health programs.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKE-UP AT IBM CONSUMER UNIT
</P>
<P>
   James Firestone, head of IBM's consumer division since August
1995, was replaced in an effort to turn around the lagging unit.
The new division leader is Michael Braun, chief executive of a
software company.
</P>
<P>
   PANEL BACKS DRUG TO BLOCK GENES
</P>
<P>
   An advisory panel to the FDA recommended approval of a drug
developed by Isis Pharmaceuticals to treat a viral infection that
can cause blindness in people with AIDS, the first drug using a new
technology that blocks genes from performing their functions.
</P>
<P>
   NO GLITCHES IN A YEAR 2000 TEST
</P>
<P>
   There were no major glitches as Wall Street began a test
simulating trading on the first day in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT EARNINGS DOUBLE IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said earnings before charges more than
doubled in the latest quarter, exceeding expectations.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG SALES BOLSTER LILLY PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Strong sales of the antidepressant drug Prozac and of a
treatment of schizophrenia helped push Eli Lilly earnings higher.
They beat Wall Street estimates by one penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES REPORT SIZABLE GAINS
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines and US Airways Group reported strong
second-quarter earnings, while Trans World Airlines posted a profit
but failed to meet analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   EX-BOND TRADER SAYS HE IS INNOCENT
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Jett, a former star bond trader at Kidder, Peabody who
was found guilty of false record-keeping in a civil case brought by
the Securities and Exchange Commission, proclaimed his innocence
and suggested that racism had added to his troubles. He said in an
interview that securities cases similar to his had resulted in much
lesser penalties.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER OF SPANISH TV SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   Spain's two digital satellite television services plan to merge,
ending a yearlong battle.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY ON BREAST IMPLANTS
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after Dow Corning agreed to pay $3.2 million to
170,000 women who contend they have been injured from silicone
breast implants, a panel of independent medical experts has begun
its own inquiry into the safety of implants.
</P>
</TEXT>
