<SLUG> BC-MA-LOBBYING-DECISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US COURT BACKS JURY IN LOBBYING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a decision that underscores a federal push to
criminalize cozy ties between legislators and lobbyists on Beacon
Hill, a federal appeals court has upheld the conviction of a former
legislator who accepted free rounds of golf, fancy dinners, and a
trip to the Super Bowl from the chief lobbyist for one of the
state's premier insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the 61-page decision issued Wednesday, the US Court of
Appeals for the First Circuit found that a jury was correct to
convict former House Insurance Committee Chairman Francis H.
Woodward in the fall of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected Woodward's claim that John Hancock lobbyist
F. William Sawyer had picked up the tab, totaling more than $7,000,
because he and Woodward were friends &UR;  &LR; _ not to buy influence with
the leader of the committee directly responsible for insurance
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The court found that Woodward accepted the gratuities as part of
an effort to influence him and deprive taxpayers of his ``honest
services.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodward's official actions, for the most part, conformed with
the way Sawyer and Hancock wanted the recipient of their gratuities
to conduct himself,'' according to the decision by a three-judge
panel. ``The jury could have inferred what the deal was _ that the
gratuities would continue as long as he voted favorably to
Hancock's interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, the court wrote, was wrong to argue ``that the
formation of a friendship between a lobbyist and a legislator
somehow insulates both from prosecution ...''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court decision further validates what has been a
controversial legal strategy by federal prosecutors: transforming
violations of state ethics laws into criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the &UR;  &LR; two judges who sentenced Woodward and Sawyer
publicly questioned the prosecution. One wondered why the US
attorney's office was spending its resources on a case ``of
hospitality where you don't have a quid pro quo,'' while the other
called the prosecution ``a threat to liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is likely to further chill the once-warm relations
between lobbyists and legislators, first highlighted in a 1993
Globe Spotlight Team series. The series sparked an FBI
investigation that led to the resignation of former House speaker
Charles Flaherty after he pleaded guilty to a tax charge, and it
also spawned a ban on gifts from lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, Woodward was convicted of four charges,
including mail and wire fraud, resulting from a November 1990
golfing trip/insurance conference in Florida. But he was acquitted
of 21 other charges stemming from events that occurred after
Woodward was deposed as House chairman in January 1991, when the
jury presumably found Sawyer's largesse was not tied to Woodward's
office.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Woodward was sentenced to six months in a
federal halfway house and fined $5,000. Two months earlier, Sawyer
had escaped jail by pleading guilty to a single charge of paying
$183 for golf games with legislators at a Cape Cod course.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer had been convicted in March 1995 of 28 corruption
charges, but a federal appeals court overturned the convictions the
following May. The court ruled that the trial judge should have
instructed jurors that in order to convict Sawyer they had to find
that he intended to corrupt legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a retrial, Sawyer was allowed to plead guilty to a
single count of mail fraud in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also rejected Woodward's claim that he never
intended to break the law, pointing out that he had deliberately
omitted the meals, golf games, and trips from financial disclosure
forms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
