<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-COLLAPSE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION MISHAP CONTINUES TO PARALYZE TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to add 6 grafs at end)  (See also NY-SCAFFOLD-DISMANTLE) 
(bl) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tuesday's collapse of an elevator tower at a Times
Square construction site continued to disrupt the routine of
midtown Manhattan on Wednesday, as dozens of local shops remained
shuttered, hundreds of police officers directed traffic away from
blocked-off streets and multitudes of tourists and workers
marveled, muttered _ and adapted.
</P>
<P>
   For now, adaptation will continue to be the requisite approach
to life in the epicenter of New York City, city officials say. They
said the shops and streets will remain closed at least for the rest
of the week, while construction workers draw a 700-by-100-foot
curtain around the broken scaffolding that runs up the northern
side of the Conde Nast building, on Broadway and 42nd and 43rd
Streets. The curtain, made of reinforced nylon, will allow workers
to take apart the scaffolding under safe conditions, a process that
could take several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called on the developer, the Durst
Organization, and the general contractor, Tishman Construction
Corp. _ whose controlling families have been financial supporters
of his past political campaigns _ to compensate in some way the
many businesses that were forced to close because of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very, very useful to a few of the businesses that
might be particularly strapped for cash over the next three to four
days if some reasonable sum of money were made available,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident's many legal implications were largely left for
another day, while its social implications were more in evidence.
Police officers, tourists, workers and residents found themselves
grappling with the abrupt change visited upon one of the busiest
corners of the world. The west side of Broadway was open to
pedestrian while the east side was closed; those wanting to walk
north on Avenue of the Americas were sent to Fifth Avenue or Eighth
Avenue; and drivers wanting to go across town unimpeded hadn't a
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Many tourists found the emptiness of a barricaded Times Square
rather exhilarating; ``This is actually cool,'' said Lisa Winton,
of Omaha, Neb., as she waited for tickets to a Broadway matinee.
But the momentary charm of upheaval had waned for many locals; one
inconvenienced man stomped down 42nd Street, screaming epithets
that might have constituted a felony in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   During lunchtime at the epicenter of it all _ Broadway and 44th
Street _ a clearly agitated police lieutenant screamed at gawkers
to move along. ``The answer is no!'' he shouted. ``Goodbye! Keep
moving! It's dangerous to stay here!'' An elderly tourist responded
by steadying her camera and snapping his photograph.
</P>
<P>
   But above all, the zany moments there loomed the sobering sight
of the half-completed Conde Nast building, its crumpled scaffolding
gleaming in the hot sun like the broken pieces to some gargantuan
Erector set.
</P>
<P>
   A ghostly quiet along Avenue of the Americas between 42nd and
43rd Street whispered of the emotional and financial costs yet
tallied. The only vehicles to be seen were squad cars, fire
engines, and a blue-orange-and-white bus labeled ``Interagency
Command Center.'' All nine stores on the west side of the street _
Pronto Pasta, Olympic Photo and Electronic, City Jeans, the Hop Won
Express restaurant _ were dark. Closed as well was the business,
around the corner on 43rd Street, that had paid the greatest price:
the Woodstock Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 8:30 Tuesday morning _ just as the helter-skelter
pace of Times Square began to quicken _ a spine of steel broke away
from some scaffolding alongside the Conde Nast building and pierced
the hotel's roof, sending tons of metal and debris through the
floors below. Twelve residents were injured, and one crushed to
death: Thereza Feliconio, 85, whose style of dress and zest for
life belied the fact that she lived in subsidized residence for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, a hunt for beds for the Woodstock's 274 tenants
began at the Times Square Hotel and ended, for some, at Bellevue
Hospital at 1 a.m. Another 150 people who either live in the area
or rented hotel rooms relied on the American Red Cross to help them
find shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Douglas Durst, explained Wednesday that he had to
research his insurance coverage before offering assistance. Now, he
said, he and the contractor, Dan Tishman, were prepared to extend
some help to the displaced and inconvenienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told by our insurance company that we cannot negotiate
directly with anyone who may have a claim,'' Durst said. ``We were
advised that anything we do outside our insurance can jeopardize
our policy. We obviously don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger question was, Why did such an accident happen? One
day after what Buildings Commissioner Gaston Silva described as
``the most serious and dramatic construction failure of this
decade,'' builders and city and federal inspectors were trying to
determine the cause of the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say the accident is particularly puzzling given
the solid reputations of the Durst and Tishman companies, and they
continued to describe two previous accidents at the construction
site _ the collapse of a crane onto another building in January,
and the death of a worker crushed under an elevator cab last month
_ as unrelated flukes in a generally dangerous business.
</P>
<P>
   Durst said he now believes that there was a serious problem with
the scaffolding that was designed and built by a subcontractor,
Universal Builders Supply of Mount Vernon, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
