<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-IMPLANTS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUTRAL EXPERTS STUDYING BREAST IMPLANT DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 16 years of litigation and scientific
controversy over the safety of silicone breast implants, a panel of
independent experts Wednesday began its own inquiry into the
dispute, which pits researchers who say there is no link between
implants and disease against tens of thousands of women who say the
devices made them sick.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member panel, which includes immunologists,
toxicologists, surgeons and oncologists, has been convened by the
prestigious Institute of Medicine at the request of the National
Institutes of Health. It met publicly for the first time Wednesday,
as part of a three-day session that will include testimony from
government and industry scientists, and the women themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came just two weeks after Dow Corning Corp., an
implant manufacturer, agreed _ without admitting wrongdoing _ to
pay $3.2 billion to 170,000 women who assert they have been
injured. Dow Corning scientists said they welcomed the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will be a fruitful discussion of the science,''
said Dr. Robert Meeks, the company's chief toxicologist. ``It is
going to give not only the scientists but also the women with
implants a chance to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   While more than a dozen major epidemiologic studies have failed
to demonstrate the link between implants and established diseases,
including cancer and autoimmune disorders, many experts say the
safety questions are far from settled.
</P>
<P>
   There is much that scientists do not know, including the role
played by genetics and whether there is an as-yet undefined
disorder that plagues the women. And there are the women
themselves, many of whom have turned up sick in doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my patients report symptoms,'' said Dr. Lu-Jean Feng,
a surgeon at Mt. Sinai Medical Center in Cleveland who has removed
implants from 842 patients in seven years. Dr. Feng, who testified
Wednesday, is studying why implants rupture. Although her work does
not address whether they cause disease, she said of her patients:
``The majority of their implants hurt; 71 percent had pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hearing room at the Georgetown University Medical
Center, Wednesday's meeting seemed like any scientific conference,
with a parade of researchers offering up details of their work. The
research ran the gamut, from Dr. Feng's work to studies that
examined whether tumors in mice that had been injected with
silicone had any relevance to humans (Dow Corning researchers say
they do not).
</P>
<P>
   In the hallway, however, the day was a bonafide media event, as
reporters interviewed the dozens of women who came to ``show
support for our silicone sisters,'' in the words of Lorraine Keegin
of Cocoa Beach, Fla. Many of the women will speak Friday, when the
panel takes public testimony again; Thursday's session will be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Keegin, who like the others wore a purple ribbon on her
lapel, said she developed lupus, an autoimmune disease, and
symptoms similar to those of multiple sclerosis, as a result of
implants she received in 1985. ``What I did to enhance my
appearance has taken my appearance and my life away,'' Mrs. Keegin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Keegin is one of 650,000 to one million American women who
received silicone breast implants during the 1970s and 1980s. The
legal disputes, which she is a party to, started soon afterward,
with patients complaining of silicone leaks that they said had
damaged their health.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Food and Drug Administration, responding to the
public outcry, demanded that silicone implants be removed from the
market; today, they are available only for experimental purposes to
mastectomy patients who want them for reconstructive surgery. Two
companies, McGhan Medical Corp., a subsidiary of Inamed Corp., and
Mentor Corp., both of Santa Barbara, Calif., are hoping to gain FDA
approval to market the implants once again.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a welcome change, said Dr. Garry Brody, a plastic
surgeon at the University of Southern California. Brody has studied
3,000 women with implants and has found that they are 30 percent
less likely than other women to develop breast cancer _ a finding
that leads him to maintain that implants are safer than the breast
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most studied product that I'm aware of,'' said
Brody, whose work was financed, in part, by Dow Corning. ``All of
the evidence suggests that it is safe. When can we reassure the
public?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that question is not likely to come until one year
from now, when the Institute, an arm of the National Academy of
Sciences, releases its report. In the meantime, research into the
safety of breast implants continues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One scientist at the Food and Drug Administration, Dr. Frederick
Miller, reported Wednesday that he found unusual genetic
alterations in 12 women with implants who all developed a rare
variant of the autoimmune disease myositis. The finding suggests
that in some women, exposure to silicone may trigger genes that
predispose them to that disease.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting research on silicone implants in a climate that is
infused with legal charges and countercharges has not been easy,
said Dr. Louise Brinton, chief of the environmental epidemiology
branch of the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brinton is supervising a vast study of more than 13,000
women who have had implants, in some cases as long as 20 or 30
years ago. She said she has been peppered by Freedom of Information
Act requests from implant manufacturers, and has been subjected to
allegations that she is in collusion with lawyers for the
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a total mistruth,'' she said. ``This study is complex
enough as it is; to have to deal with these assaults on a daily
basis is very disturbing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
