<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Banks to Offer Online Brokerage Services  
   
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Wells Fargo and BankAmerica are about to unveil major new online
discount brokerage services in an effort to retain current
customers and lure new ones.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six months of quietly testing WellsTrade with a tiny
fraction of its 470,000 online banking customers, Wells will begin
widely promoting its new online product in early August. For a
$29.95 commission, customers can buy up to 1,000 shares of most
U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
   They will also be able to trade about 1,000 mutual funds as well
as trade stock options, get company news from PR Wire, tap Zacks
equity research and get quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have long offered investment services to their wealthiest
customers, or ``high net worth'' individuals, as they are known in
the trade. But Wells Fargo and other banks are keen on providing a
much broader spectrum of products so more customers will be content
keeping all their assets under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Wells plans to offer a variety of products to all customers
rather than keep them in separate ``silos,'' said Dennis Mooradian,
executive vice president of the Private Client Services division.
</P>
<P>
   That means offering online brokerage accounts to those with a
balance as small as $1,000, providing more comprehensive asset
management accounts to those with $10,000 and offering the services
of affiliated money managers &UR;  &LR; to those who have $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The product lines continue to blur as financial services
companies compete to provide one-stop shopping to their clients,''
said John Payne, an analyst with the Boston research firm Cerulli
Associates. ``Banks and investment firms increasingly are targeting
the same customers.''
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica plans to unveil its own online investment services
in September. With one ID and one password, BofA home banking
customers will be able not only to check balances and pay bills 24
hours a day but transfer funds to IRA and other investment
accounts. They will be able to buy and sell all domestic stocks and
about 1,000 mutual funds plus receive financial news and quotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The online investment market is growing at a phenomenal pace,
and we think many of the 29 million households served by
BankAmerica and NationsBank will be interested,'' said BankAmerica
Interactive Banking Division Vice President Cynthia Kopec.
</P>
<P>
   The investment services subsidiary of BofA has yet to set
commissions. But Kopec said they will be ``in the Schwab ballpark''
of $29.95 per trade.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab Corp., the largest discount broker, does not seem
overly concerned by the onslaught of competition from banks,
including BofA, which owned Schwab from 1983 to 1987. Since the
beginning of the year, Schwab's online accounts have increased by a
third to 1.8 million and online customer assets shot from $80
billion to $128 billion, or 30 percent of Schwab's total.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab does not plan to lower trading commissions, said
spokesman Tom Taggart. But it does plan to provide enhanced online
features. For example, later this year Schwab is expected to offer
its customers investment research reports from other firms such as
Credit Suisse First Boston and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Wells and BofA are hardly alone in invading the online brokerage
arena. Last October, Citigroup announced a service with commissions
as low as $19.95 per trade.
</P>
<P>
   Several other banks have forged alliances with brokerages. Last
year, Fleet Financial bought Quick &AMP; Reilly and offers its
SureTrade online service. Mellon Bank bought Pacific Brokerage
Services and Toronto Dominion bought Jack White.
</P>
<P>
   BancOne of Ohio recently teamed up with Palo Alto discount
brokerage ETrade to offer online stock trading to its customers.
First Chicago NBD offers a similar product from DLJ Direct's
discount brokerage services.
</P>
<P>
   Currently none of the top 10 online brokerages are operated by
banks, according to Cerulli Associates. But Payne sees that
changing soon.
</P>
<P>
   Partnering with banks also should bolster the revenues of online
brokerages and provide them a bit of stability. As a sign of the
industry's volatility, ETrade shares yesterday skidded $3.25 to
$28.75 on news that the second-largest online broker expects to
lose money in the next &UR;  &LR; few quarters as it spends heavily on
marketing. Meanwhile, Ameritrade shot up $8 to $45 on news that its
will be featured on America Online's personal finance site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
