<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   New version of Intel's Celeron will arrive next month  
   
 By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
When the Edsel flopped, Ford Motor Co. dumped the name.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp., however, is sticking with Celeron, even though
reviewers panned the computer chip after it debuted in April.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara-based chip-maker will deliver a new version of
Celeron next month in another stab at the sub-$1,000 personal
computer market. The August arrival will put the new chips out
several months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like an impressive product,'' said Nathan
Brookwood, principal microprocessor analyst with Dataquest, a San
Jose market research firm. ``Will the initial images of Celeron as
a somewhat weak product linger and affect this one? That is a key
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Celeron marked Intel's entry into the market for PCs costing
less than $1,000, but critics said that it was a stripped-down
product that didn't deliver the speed PC users need.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Celeron lacked Level-2 cache, a small but
vital memory feature that lets the PC easily access frequently used
information. Without the cache, the computer lagged.
</P>
<P>
   In the new versions, Intel has added the cache. The new Celerons
will also have faster clock speeds, of 300 megahertz and 330 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   Intel never actually admitted any error with the original
Celeron. Last week, when the company announced its quarterly
earnings, officials claimed that Celeron accounted for 5 percent of
Intel's shipments, and that it was one of the quickest selling
products in the company's 30-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is the world's largest chipmaker, producing the brains for
more than 80 percent of PCs sold today. But rivals AMD and National
Semiconductor dealt a blow to Intel by pioneering chips for
sub-$1,000 PCs, which consumers have been snapping up over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Intel announced a $24 million investment in Evans
&AMP; Sutherland, a Utah-based maker of graphics hardware. The deal
gives Intel an 8 percent nonvoting stake in the company, with
options to go to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The investment is Intel's latest push into the graphics market.
``The goal is to make high-end graphics as widely available to
workstation users as possible,'' said Intel spokesman Robert
Manetta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
