<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 300 Lawyers Tackle UCC, the Ten Commandments of Business   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The law will try to catch up with the software business tomorrow,
when 300 lawyers begin a week-long debate about revising the
Uniform Commercial Code.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The UCC is the Ten Commandments of business. When contract
disputes arise, judges open the UCC to find who shalt or shalt not.
</P>
<P>
   Revising the fine print of this tome sounds boring. But the
proposals governing software licenses, under the heading UCC
2B,have provoked a huge legal brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups want 2B to include warranties. The industry
would rather it not. Database firms want legal protections akin to
copyrights. Movie studios want to be left out. Corporate software
buyers and financial lessors each have axes to grind.
</P>
<P>
   What fascinates me is the realization that for years, the
software industry has, in essence, been making up the rules as it
goes along.
</P>
<P>
   These rules are the licensing agreements inside software boxes,
and rarely do they cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But when disputes do arise _ say, a corporation sues a supplier
_ no one's been able to point to chapter or verse in the UCC to
check if the license conforms to the law.
</P>
<P>
   The keeper of the sacred code is the National Conference of
Commissioners on Uniform State Laws, a group of 300 lawyers
appointed by the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting that opens tomorrow in Cleveland is another step in
the process of drafting a model 2B code, which the state
legislatures will, eventually, write into law.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got the time and the frequent-flyer miles, jet to
Cleveland and join in the hair-splitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is open to all,'' said Napa attorney Carol Kunze.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can do like me, and visit Kunze's Web site  &LR; (www.Sof &LR; 
 &LR; twareIndustry.org/issues/guide &LR; ) _ and pray that all these legal
Johnny-come-latelys don't screw up an industry that works.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Cramer vs. Kramer: &LR;  Jim Cramer is the feisty co-founder of
TheStreet.com, a Web-based financial news service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kramer is the pugnacious CEO of CBS MarketWatch.com, a
rival outfit in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In their battle for eyeballs, the East Coast Cramer struck a
blow today. He announced that a team of editorial commandos have
parachuted into TheStreet's San Francisco office, to join bureau
chief Cory Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The new Street people are: Kevin Kelleher, formerly of Wired
News; Suzanne Galante, an ex-C/Net scribe; Marcy Burstiner, a
veteran San Francisco business reporter; Medora Lee, an import from
Reuters in London; and Jeff Hoffman, a free-lancer.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his command bunker on Wall Street, Cramer took a
friendly jab at his West Coast rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell that other Kramer he's on the wrong coast,'' Cramer said.
``If they're going to cover the street, last time I looked it was
Wall, not Montgomery.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, sure, sure, San Francisco's Kramer replied. CBS
MarketWatch already has offices in New York, Washington, D.C., Los
Angeles and soon it will be in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think being based in New York City actually distorts
reality,'' Kramer said. ``You have to be there, no question, and we
are. But you have to keep a clear head and stay in touch with the
new reality, and it's easier to do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the home-boy added, ``What does that guy know? He can't
even spell his own name.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Word games? &LR;  Netscape says the beta version of its new browser
just tries to simplify Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   But online columnist Dave Winer says Netscape is trying to
hijack domain names like his,  &LR; www.scripting.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The fuss revolves around a feature in Communicator 4.5 that lets
people type in plain words, like United Airlines, instead of URLs
like www.ual.com.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape calls this ``Smart Browsing.'' Product manager Ken
Hickman said Netscape is imitating America Online, where users can
type in a keyword, like money or news, and be taken to a financial
or news page _ without having to plow through a search engine or
remember a URL.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape didn't do this just to be nice. It plans to sell key
words one day. Say a cruise line bought ``Caribbean Contest.'' Web
surfers who typed the words into their Netscape browser would be
taken to the ship's home page.
</P>
<P>
   Winer praised this notion in a May 30 column. But that was
before Netscape shipped the 4.5 beta, and he typed in
``scripting,'' and was taken, not to his Web page, but to a list of
scripting resources compiled by Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Now he insists that Netscape's Smart Browser should take people
directly to his registered domain.
</P>
<P>
   But Netscape's new browser has the legal smarts to tell a
generic word, like scripting, from a trademark like Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Generics can be domain names. But they lack the legal
protections of trademarks. So Netscape thinks it can do anything
with generics _ even sell them as a key word.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned 'cause this could get interesting. Netscape could
decide tomorrow to sell ``news'' as a key word _ miffing online
powerhouse C/Net, which use news.com as its domain name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
