Domenici, before a hearing on Richardson's nomination as Energy
Secretary. During the hearing, Richardson was questioned about
interviewing Monica Lewinsky for a job. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- NY-SCAFFOLD-IMPACT, 7-22 --
Times Square is relatively empty Wednesday. The collapse of an
elevator tower Tuesday at a construction site here continued to
disrupt the routine of midtown Manhattan, as dozens of local shops
remained shuttered, hundreds of police officers directed traffic
away from blocked-off streets and multitudes of tourists and
workers marveled, muttered - and adapted. (J. Emilio Flores/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- JETT-SEC, 7-22 -- An
administrative law judge found Joseph Jett, a former Kidder trader,
guilty Tuesday of false record-keeping in a civil case brought by
the SEC. Jett, who is black, claims that securities cases similar
to his have resulted in much lesser penalties. ``When all things
are equal and the only difference is color, I have to wonder,'' he
says. ``The laws that are supposed to treat all men equally don't
seem to be doing the job.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LIVERPOOL, England -- July 22, 1998 --
LIVERPOOL-BEATLES-2, 7-22 -- The address is 20 Forthlin Road,
Liverpool, and Paul McCartney lived there from 1955 to 1964,
writing songs in the parlor with John Lennon. The modest row house
has been restored to its original state by the National Trust of
Britain and opened as a museum. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LIVERPOOL, England -- July 22, 1998 --
LIVERPOOL-BEATLES-1, 7-22 -- The kitchen has period appliances at
20 Forthlin Road, Liverpool, where Paul McCartney lived from 1955
to 1964, writing songs in the parlor with John Lennon. The modest
row house has been restored to its original state by the National
Trust of Britain and opened as a museum. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ORAHOVAC, Serbia -- July 22, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO, 7-22
-- An unidentified man lay dead in front of a barricade in the
streets of Orahovac on Tuesday. Separatist rebels and Serbian
police have been fighting in the mainly ethnic Albanian town in
Kosovo for five days. (Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- July 22, 1998 -- HERBAL-SUPPLEMENTS, 7-22 --
Once largely the province of obscure manufacturers with limited
distribution, the pills and powders that supposedly sharpen the
mind and lift the spirit are no longer consigned to a spot next to
the bee pollen at the local health-food store. Now they carry
trusted brand names and command premium shelf space in
supermarkets, drug stores and mass retail chains throughout the
country. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BOSTON -- July 22, 1998 -- FIDELITY-CONE-BOS, 7-22 -- In
his Boston office, Stephen Cone, Fidelity Investments' marketing
guru, sits on his zebra rug. Cone, who joined Fidelity last
February as president of customer marketing and development, shot
the zebra on a hunting safari in Africa. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HOLLYWOOD -- July 22, 1998 -- BOY'S-FILMS, 7-22 --
Robert Simonds, Hollywood's foremost producer of boy films. ``What
we're seeing right now is a reaffirmation that the teen male really
does represent a tremendous amount of cash at the box office,'' he
says. Males from 12 to 22 remain the single most reliable segment
of the moviegoing public - one third of the audience - even though
their influence at the box office has dipped a bit in favor of
young girls and adults. (Steve Goldstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HOLLYWOOD -- July 22, 1998 -- MONICA-MANCINI, 7-22 --
Monica Mancini sings her father's songs at a Hollywood studio that
is recording her first solo album. ``The truth is, it didn't occur
to me to do his stuff before, because he was here to do it,'' she
says of Henry Mancini, the prolific Hollywood composer, arranger
and conductor, who died of pancreatic cancer in 1994 at the age of
70. Ms. Mancini is performing his music in a two-week stint at the
Oak Room in New York through Aug. 1. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BECKET, Mass. -- July 22, 1998 -- JACOBSPILLOW-DANCE,
7-22 -- Iliana Lopez and Franklin Gamero in ``Nous Sommes'' at the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket. Filled with complicated
lifts and entwinings, this pas de deux could have been nothing but
blatant exhibitionism. (Alan E. Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) POUND RIDGE, N.Y. -- July 22, 1998 --
GLASS-HOUSE-PARKING, 7-22 -- The visitors' center for the Glass
House in New Canaan, Conn., plans to build its parking lot on this
site four miles away in Pound Ridge. ``They should put it in their
own state,'' says Helen Mayrbaurl, who has lived on the road near
the proposed parking lot since 1962. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WARREN, Maine -- July 22, 1998 -- TOOL-CATALOGS, 7-22 --
Thomas Lie-Nielsen, holding a low angle jack plane, with his
father, Oistein Lie-Nielsen, a former wooden boat builder. Today,
Lie-Nielsen Tool Works is manufacturing a line of roughly 16
distinct models of wood planes, based largely on discontinued
Stanley designs. ``Stanley used to have a hundred different planes,
many of them with very specific uses,'' says the 44-year-old
Lie-Nielsen. ``They should never have fallen out of the market.''
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SMITHTOWN, N.Y. -- July 22, 1998 -- OLD-TOOLS-2, 7-22 --
What were these three antique tools, from the collection of William
Hermanek, used for? From left, a rare bronze-cast Stanley plow
plane, Miller's Patent, made sometime between 1871 and 1897 and
used to ``plow'' dados (made obsolete by routers); a violin maker's
plane, user-made, still employed to shape instruments; a Stanley
196 rabbet plane, 1912 to 1934, for cutting curved rabbets. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SMITHTOWN, N.Y. -- July 22, 1998 -- OLD-TOOLS-1, 7-22 --
William Hermanek, with some of his 1,800 beauties. There's an
indescribable quality that radiates from old tools. You sense it in
the hand-worn patina of rosewood knobs and grips, the chiaroscuro
of glinting brass levers under darkened steel. But they are mute
until you touch them. Then they won't shut up. Pick up an old tool,
and you almost hear the ticking hours of its long working life.
Such tools can be time machines, portals to a yesteryear farther
away than the moon. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- SOLOMON-APARTMENT-2, 7-22 --
A reading retreat, replete with Jean Lowe's papier-mache books, in
art dealer Holly Solomon's new six-room apartment on the Upper East
Side. Her present flat may seem more than adequate for most people,
but Ms. Solomon used to give buffets for 100. ``I'm beginning to
know the doorman, and I can take the bus to Zabar's,'' she says.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- SOLOMON-APARTMENT-1, 7-22 --
Art dealer Holly Solomon Q shown in 1998 and 1966 (Warhol) Q is
moving on down. Left behind: a nine-room apartment (plus maids'
rooms and two storage rooms) on Sutton Place. Present home: a
six-room apartment on the Upper East Side that seats six for
dinner. That may seem more than adequate for most people, but Ms.
Solomon used to give buffets for 100. ``I'm beginning to know the
doorman, and I can take the bus to Zabar's,'' she says. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- July 22, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 7-22 --
Refacing kitchen cabinets entails bonding new material, either
plastic laminate or wood veneer, over the old cabinet faces with
contact cement. Refacing with plastic laminate is best left to a
professional. Wood veneer is a little easier to work with because
it can be trimmed with a utility knife and a smooth file. (Edward
R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- July 22, 1998 --
CIR-VOICEMAIL-PRIVACY, 7-22 -- John Guinasso, director of corporate
integrity and risk management at ICG Netcom, an Internet service
provider, stands in the company's testing area. A year ago,
Netcom's voice-mail system was penetrated by a 15-year-old hacker
who called himself Mr. Nobody. ``It happens to everybody,'' says
Guinasso, who's company has since increased their voice mail
security. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- JULY 22, 1998 -- CIR-IMAC, 7-22 -- Apple's new
iMac (pronounced eye-Mac) combines the computer and the monitor in
one, translucent unit. ``It's a statement that Apple is being bold
and daring, and it is consistent with the Apple tradition,'' says
Dave Tremblay, a senior analyst for Computer Intelligence, a market
research company in San Diego, and a former Apple executive. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- CIR-MULTI-TASKING-2, 7-22 --
Marc Prensky, a vice president at Bankers Trust, multi-tasking at
his desk. ``If people are really good at processing information
from lots of different sources and you don't give it to them, you
stifle them,'' says Prensky who has jumped enthusiastically into
the new you-can-do-everything-at-once culture of a new generation
of employees and says businesses need to embrace it. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 22, 1998 -- CIR-MULTI-TASKING-1, 7-22 --
Adam Gwosdof likes to use pay phones in pairs, retrieving
voice-mail messages on one and returning calls on the other.
Gwosdof, 31, runs a database design business. He often finds
himself being paged by one client while meeting with another and
using the Internet to check on a third. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
