<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      07-22 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH DIGITAL TV SERVICES TO MERGE AFTER COSTLY FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spain's two digital satellite television
services, one backed by Grupo Prisa, the nation's largest private
media company, and the other by the government, have announced
plans to merge, moving to end a yearlong bare-knuckles battle that
spilled into national politics.
</P>
<P>
   The two services _ Canal Satelite, owned by Grupo Prisa's
Sogecable unit, and Via Digital, owned by Telefonica, the former
state telecommunications company _ did not disclose the terms of
their agreement in a brief statement on Tuesday, but pledged to
conclude the deal by Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marks a truce to a bitter battle for Spain's
nascent market for digital television, which offers additional
channels and pay-per-view movies.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500,000 subscribers have signed up with Canal Satelite
since January 1997. Via Digital, the government-backed competitor,
reported nearly 300,000 subscribers since it started last
September.
</P>
<P>
   The two rivals have sharply cut prices to attract subscribers,
and company officials said the services had each lost about $92
million last year but had expected to break even, on their own, by
the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts predicted that Jesus de Polanco, the
Grupo Prisa chairman, whose satellite television service has rights
to Spanish professional soccer matches and movies, would call the
shots in the new single provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised if it wasn't going to be run by the
Soge-cable side,'' said Neil Blackley, an analyst with Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. in London.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right government of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
late in 1996 helped organize a satellite television consortium,
including the newly privatized Telefonica and the state-owned
broadcaster Television Espanola, to compete with Polanco's planned
service.
</P>
<P>
   The battle immediately took on a political dimension. Grupo
Prisa's newspaper, radio and television holdings, including the
biggest paper in Spain, El Pais, had grown considerably in size and
influence under the previous Socialist administration.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, parliament approved a law that essentially
outlawed Canal Satelite's transmission technology. The company
appealed to the European Commission and won the right to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, a Madrid court investigated charges of financial
improprieties at Grupo Prisa's Soge-cable and for a time Polanco
was prohibited from leaving Spain without court permission.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was later shelved for lack of evidence, and
the presiding judge in the case has been suspended from duty while
the Supreme Court investigates Soge-cable's accusations of official
breach of duty during the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Arias Salgado, Spain's minister of development, said
Wednesday that the agreement between the competitors should benefit
the subscribers, but he added, ``The government does not take an
official position on the preliminary accord because it's a free
market and business agreements are made freely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
