<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/22/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK HARBOR -- July 20, 1998 -- NY-CONTAINER-SHIP,
7-20 -- The Regina Maersk, at 1,043 feet long the largest cargo
ship to visit the United States, passes under the Bayonne Bridge
into the narrow Kill van Kull on Wednesday before entering New York
Harbor. The intended message is that ships are getting very, very
big, and that any port that wants to dominate maritime commerce in
the 21st century has to be sure its channels are deep enough and
docks modern enough to accommodate them. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) GAITHERSBURG, Md. -- July 22, 1998 --
MD-SCHAEFER-POLITICS, 7-22 -- William Donald Schaefer, former
governor of Maryland and former mayor of Baltimore, center, with
Mayor Ed Bohrer of Gaithersburg. When Louis Goldstein, the state
comptroller for 40 years, died of a heart attack on July 3,
Schaefer, 76, saw a rubber duck in his future. ``Once you're in
politics, it never gets out of your blood,'' says Schaefer, who is
seeking the vacated position. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) STATE LINE CITY, Ill. -- July 22, 1998 --
ILL-IND-DIVIDE, 7-22 -- Amy Wright, on the Illinois side of State
Line Road, holds Colton as another son, Clayton, sits on his
four-wheeler. Looking on from Indiana are Alice Cox and her
daughter Imogen Lewsader. ``It's confusing,'' says Ms. Wright, 30,
who tells people that she lives in Illinois, in a little Indiana
town. (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
