<SLUG> BC-KING-DREAM-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES SPEECH BY KING IS THE PUBLIC'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a setback for the family of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr., a federal judge ruled Wednesday that his famous
``I have a dream'' speech belongs to the public, and that CBS has
not been guilty of copyright infringement by reproducing it for a
documentary series.
</P>
<P>
   King's speech on Aug. 28, 1963, before some 200,000 people at a
civil rights rally in front of the Lincoln Memorial ``was made
available to members of the public at large without regard to who
they were or what they proposed to do with it,'' Judge William C.
O'Kelley ruled in federal district court in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, O'Kelley held, the civil rights leader in effect gave his
words to history in a way that a playwright, say, does not
surrender his words just because his work is performed before huge
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Beck, the Atlanta lawyer who represents the estate of
King, said Wednesday night, ``We are studying the opinion and
likely will appeal.'' If there is an appeal, it would be heard by
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals , in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, a lawyer for CBS, called the ruling ``a
significant victory for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion makes plain that in circumstances in which a
public figure speaks in the most public way on matters of enormous
significance, that the speech is not the private property of anyone
but the property of all,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, the CBS president who is vacationing in France,
issued a statement that said: ``We took on this case to protect the
public's right to know about major events of historical
significance. This decision means that Dr. King's landmark speech
is truly in the public domain, where it belongs. It is not just CBS
News but the American public that won today.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, CBS signed a contract with the Arts and Entertainment
Network to produce a series titled ``The 20th Century With Mike
Wallace.'' One segment contained film coverage of the speech and
included some 60 percent of the words.
</P>
<P>
   King's speech, in which he envisioned a United States no longer
torn by racial hatred, has been widely recognized as one of the
most important events in recent American history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
