<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-RAPIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IDENTIFIED AS RAPIST ADMITS N.H. ASSAULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding; attn.: Ireland, Netherlands)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an emotional transatlantic telephone interview Wednesday
night, a man who identified himself as convicted Nashua, N.H.
rapist and fugitive Steven Gordon confessed to the Globe that he
raped three women in New Hampshire in the past 2 1/2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it,'' he said. ``I did it ... I need to take
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he was staying at a Christian youth hostel in
Amsterdam and had felt unable to control his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about sex,'' he said. ``I just feel myself doing it,
and then afterwards ...'' His voice trailed off.
</P>
<P>
   Police have named Gordon, a Massachusetts native, as a suspect
in the rape and beating of two Irish women in Hampton Beach, N.H.
last Saturday, and were investigating him in connection with the
July 7 rape of a Nashua realty agent in Mancheste, N.Hr.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Globe had no way of independently verifying that
the man on the phone was Gordon, he did know information that has
not been made public, including the name of the realty agent who
was raped.
</P>
<P>
   For his victims, Gordon had these words: ``I'm really sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon allegedly raped the realty agent at gunpoint while she
was showing him a property. The victim said the rapist told her he
picked her out of a glossy booklet that included her photograph
next to her property listings.
</P>
<P>
   In the phone conversation Wednesday, Gordon confirmed that he
picked the woman out of the booklet, and he felt bad about the rape
because ``she was a really nice lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe talked to Gordon from the Boston-area home of a close
relative, who asked not to be identified. A harried and sleepy
Gordon said he was hiding at the youth hostel, afraid to turn
himself in because ``they will kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lost in Europe,'' he said. He spoke for about 20 minutes
and did not seem to want to end the conversation. He said he
originally planned to flee to Israel, but probably will not now.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the phone conversation, a worker at the youth
hostel said Gordon left about 1 a.m. Amsterdam time, saying he was
going to surrender to local police. He had not done so as this
story was being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 28, was paroled and placed on probation 13 months ago
from New Hampshire State Prison after serving 3 1/2 years for the
1992 rape of a teacher at New Hampshire Technical College, where he
once attended school. He was released after a judge deferred the
balance of his sentence and ordered him to attend a treatment
program for sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   After his release, Gordon said he did have counseling and met
with a probation officer weekly, but was not forthcoming with his
counselor about his own concerns about his mental state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to go to counseling,'' he said. But ``I didn't tell
them everything. I was afraid to tell them. I was afraid they would
tell my probation officer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gordon's relative, the latest allegations have caused
heartbreak and concern. They say he is a young man whose childhood
was filled with the trauma of mental illness and the death of his
father when he was a year old.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, if they are going to catch him, I hope he takes
his life,'' the relative said, tears streaming down her face.
</P>
<P>
   She said Gordon has relied on the antidepressant Lithium and
other medications to stabilize his moods since he was 12 years old.
Gordon also said he was hospitalized in a Massachusetts mental ward
for children.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a doctor suggested that Gordon begin taking another
antidepressant, Zoloft, to help him cope with anxiety, one of his
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The relative showed off a stone cup that Gordon painted with
bright colors as a youth. ``He's very artistic,'' she said, her
hands running along the cup.
</P>
<P>
   When he got depressed as a youth, before he was on medication,
the relative said Gordon would withdraw. When his mood elevated, he
was quick to get angry, she said: ``He gets very easily agitated.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gordon and his relatives agreed that his latest problems
started when he was fired from a factory job about three weeks ago
and could no longer afford his medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he was monitoring news accounts of the rapes and the
police search for him on the Internet, and had read the Globe's
article on the rapes on the newspaper's Website.
</P>
<P>
   He said he used a pellet gun to commit the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to news reports, he said, he did not order the two
Irish women at gunpoint into his rental car. According to his
version of the story, the women voluntarily got into his car after
asking for a ride to a nearby party. They had been drinking and
dozed off, he said; he then drove to a cemetery where he pulled out
the pellet gun and raped them.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to escape from the cemetery, Gordon crashed the car
into a headstone, panicked, and ran away. He later contacted a
friend to drive him to Logan International Airport in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   There, he plunked down $413 for a ticket to Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for a motive, Gordon said only, ``I snapped and I did
all these things that didn't make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed sympathy for the judge who commuted his
sentence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge is going to take heat for this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
