<HEADER>
A8366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-BOARD-ART-NYT &LR;      07-22 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-BOARD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTING SHOTS BY LABOR BOARD CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When William Gould IV left his prestigious perch as
a professor at the Stanford University Law School four years ago to
head the National Labor Relations Board, he was confident that as
one of the United States' foremost authorities on labor law, he
could restore the board's luster.
</P>
<P>
   But Gould recently left Washington, a bitter figure, frustrated
that he had accomplished far less than he had hoped, and widely
accused of having politicized the board and antagonized Congress as
well as his fellow board members.
</P>
<P>
   Gould originally said he hoped he would be remembered for
pushing the board back toward the center after its rightward swing
in the Reagan-Bush years. But he is more likely to be remembered
for warring with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, 62, insists that many congressional Republicans have
improperly pressured and even bullied his theoretically independent
agency. But many Republican lawmakers assert that he invited such
meddling by pushing the board leftward and by doing something rare
for the chairman of a quasijudicial agency: speaking out on pending
legislation and often clashing with Republican positions.
</P>
<P>
   The labor board, which has five members, plays the highly
sensitive role of referee in the nation's labor disputes, blowing
the whistle when managers or unions break the rules in organizing
drives or contract disputes. Republican presidents usually appoint
board members who tilt toward management, while Democratic
presidents typically name members who lean toward labor.
</P>
<P>
   Gould's pro-labor tilt has irked many Republicans, and their
anger has been stoked further by his outspokenness and his refusal
to bend to Congress' demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just an unabashedly enthusiastic supporter of the labor
movement,'' said Rep. Harris Fawell, R-Ill., who heads the House
Subcommittee on Employer-Employee Relations. ``He is just so
enthusiastic about it that he has unfortunately avoided neutrality.
It's just antithetical to his nature. I'd give him an `A' for
enthusiasm and an `F' for judicial discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in his office, Gould suggested that it was
Congress that deserved the ``F'' for discretion, accusing it of
``rank interference'' with the board's independence. He had an aide
pull out a dozen letters in which members of Congress went to bat
for their corporate friends, for instance pressuring the board to
take one company's settlement offer more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a dispute with a neighbor,'' Gould said, ``and
your neighbor has a powerful friend who is a judge and the neighbor
is able to lobby the judge who is deciding the case, I think most
of us think this smacks of societies that we would call autocratic
or authoritarian or third-worldish.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould, who said he was returning to California even though his
term does not end until Aug. 27, seemed eager to fire some final
rounds in his war with Congress. Point by point, he castigated
Congress for meddling in the board's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans repeatedly fought the board's aggressive
policy of seeking to reduce delays by seeking emergency injunctions
against companies for actions like illegally dismissing pro-union
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress barred the board from adopting a proposed rule that
would have sped the unionization of fast-food restaurants. (The
rule said a bargaining unit should generally consist of workers at
a single restaurant rather than a group of restaurants in a chain.)
And Congress cut the board's budget by 2 percent in 1995 and froze
its budget for the last two years, forcing the board to reduce its
staff and thus increasing delays in processing cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House Republicans who are the driving force behind the
board's budget cuts want to render us ineffective,'' Gould said.
``There isn't any doubt that Congress is trying to punish the board
because the board stands behind a statute that gives workers the
opportunity to help shape their own employment relationship,'' a
reference to the National Labor Relations Act of 1935 that set
rules for collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, who frequently mentions the fact that one of his
great-grandfathers was a slave in the old South, ridiculed
Republicans' assertions that he is a tool of the labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in anyone's pocket,'' he said. ``I am my own man, and
I march to my own drummer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould's allies say he was no more pro-labor than past Democratic
chairmen, asserting that he was a victim of the heightened partisan
sniping that has characterized Washington in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans scoff at Gould when he suggests that
he is a neutral umpire. They say he has thrown any pretense of
neutrality overboard by endorsing or opposing legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked a Republican-sponsored bill that would let companies
set up management-chosen committees of employees that would discuss
working conditions. And he opposed the California referendum, voted
down in June, that would have barred unions from spending members'
dues on politics without the members' permission.
</P>
<P>
   Some business advocates welcomed Gould's outspokenness because
it made him a lightning rod and fueled Republican efforts to
hamstring the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speaking out gave people who are concerned about the
board's agenda an easy handle to criticize the board,'' said Randel
Johnson, vice president for labor policy at the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce. ``One might say you can get more done as a bureaucrat by
keeping quiet and pursuing your agenda, rather than bragging about
what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although even some Democratic allies called Gould unwise for
speaking out on pending legislation, he asserted, ``It is my
obligation to speak out.'' He added: ``If I as chairman, with my
experience in this arena as a law professor, lawyer and arbitrator,
am not competent to speak out, who in the world is? What is the
alternative? It's to bow down submissively and allow others to win
the day on these critical issues that affect my agency and the
National Labor Relations Act, about which I care so deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould is frustrated about another part of his legacy: The board
has not issued decisions in many important cases where he is eager
to leave an imprint. He asserted that several board members
evidently wanted to delay issuing decisions until after his term
ended, in hopes that his position would no longer command a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of very big cases pending that we should have
dealt with years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members, who insisted on anonymity, asserted that
they were not dragging their feet, explaining that they were bogged
down with hundreds of cases and that they were focusing on the
decisions they thought most important, not necessarily the ones
Gould deemed important. Former board members as well as several
labor lawyers said Gould's forceful personality had alienated other
board members, often making it hard for him to forge a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have repeatedly attacked Gould for having delayed
long-awaited decisions to spell out the rights of union members not
to have their dues spent on politics. But Gould insisted that other
members, not he, were holding up those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some board members simply will not act on certain cases,'' he
said. ``I'm concerned because of my legacy. Indolence and
indecision are being used to thwart the issuance of leading cases,
which include my policy ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
