<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8367 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX     07-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMORA DECLINES TO TESTIFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
By Robert Tharp
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ A dramatic day of testimony in David
Graham's capital murder trial began early Wednesday, when Graham's
former fiancee refused to testify, and ended with defense attorneys
resting without calling any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Rising from his chair immediately after prosecutors dismissed
their last witness at 2:15 p.m., the former Air Force Academy
cadet's lead attorney stood up, approached the jury box and told
jurors that he rested on Graham's ``presumption of innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the absence of defense witnesses, Houston attorney
Dan Cogdell said he believes that prosecutors did not prove over
six days of testimony that Graham is guilty of killing 16-year-old
Adrianne Jones. Cogdell also said he considered calling Graham to
testify but decided that resting was a ``safer decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I believed they had proven their case beyond a reasonable
doubt, I would have put on a defense. ... The way to keep the jury
focused on the weaknesses of the state's case is to rest right
behind them. That's where the emphasis should be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called 27 witnesses in the trial, which began July
15. They built a case against the 20-year-old Mansfield High School
graduate that they say is supported by witness testimony, physical
evidence and a confession that Graham typed.
</P>
<P>
   After both sides rested, Tarrant County District Judge Don
Leonard told the jury of seven men and five women to return at 1
p.m. Thursday to hear closing arguments. Attorneys for each side
will have one hour to wrap up their arguments. Prosecutors will
speak first, followed by the defense, then a prosecution rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Before closing arguments, both sides will meet with Leonard to
determine the range of charges that jurors can consider. Graham is
charged with capital murder, but the jurors could be allowed to
consider lesser charges of murder or aggravated kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Murder can be considered a capital offense when it is committed
during the commission of another crime. Prosecutors are seeking a
capital murder conviction for Graham because they contend that
Jones was killed while she was being kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell, who argued that Graham was not present at any point
when Jones was lured from her home and was beaten and shot along a
road in Grand Prairie, Texas, said Wednesday that he has not
decided whether to request that jurors be allowed to consider any
charge less than capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Mike Parrish said he will ask
Leonard to instruct jurors to consider only capital murder, which
would carry an automatic punishment of life in prison. Prosecutors
previously decided not to seek the death penalty. For a murder
conviction, jurors could consider punishment ranging from probation
to 99 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's `not guilty' or `capital murder,' '' Parrish
said. ``I don't think there's any in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution witnesses included testimony that Graham told police
where to find the gun used to kill Jones. Graham said it was hidden
in the attic of his father's Mansfield home, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony, a medical investigator told jurors that
Graham's former fiancee, Diane Zamora, was not physically capable
of inflicting wounds found on Jones' neck. Zamora's left hand was
still recovering from surgery at the time, the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   And Graham's 4 1/2-page written confession was read in court,
detailing how he and Zamora plotted and carried out Jones' slaying.
</P>
<P>
   But Cogdell has argued that prosecutors have no physical
evidence linking Graham to the crime scene and that Graham is
guilty only of trying to cover up for Zamora, who he says killed
Jones in a jealous rage because she believed that Graham had had
sex with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said he thinks defense attorneys rested because they
were concerned that prosecutors would present ``more bad news''
from damaging testimony in the rebuttal phase of the trial. Parrish
said the rebuttal stage would have included the introduction of
Zamora's written confession and more testimony from Air Force
investigators who questioned Graham before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he had hoped to question Zamora about discrepancies
between her oral and written statements. Zamora appeared in the
courtroom Wednesday morning outside the jury's presence, but
Leonard ruled that Zamora has a constitutional right protecting her
from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   The last witness of the trial, a high school friend of Graham,
testified that Graham and Zamora visited his Burleson house before
dawn the morning after Jones was killed. John Green said that the
two washed up in a bathroom and that Graham asked for extra
clothing. Before leaving, Graham swore him to secrecy, and the
encounter was never again mentioned, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also read a jailhouse letter from Graham to Green
stating that whether he killed Jones was ``beside the point'' and
that Graham felt he did not deserve punishment because he thought
God would forgive him. He also wrote that thinking about sins was
just as bad as committing them and that prosecutors would be
``harshly judged'' for passing judgment on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an evil occurs on Earth it cannot be justified,'' he
wrote. ``Throwing me, Diane or whoever away for life won't bring
back Adrianne Jones. It'll only destroy two more families.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth lawyer and trial analyst Bill Lane said Cogdell's
decision not to present defense witnesses is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that when you are a lawyer, you don't know what
you are going to do until the state rests,'' he said. ``This is a
case that largely depends on final arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Cogdell's decision not to have Graham testify
may have been the right one. At her capital murder trial, Zamora
took the witness stand, and the jury didn't believe her testimony,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``History has a way of repeating itself,'' he said. ``When Diane
Zamora took the stand in her trial, it erased any doubt in the
jury's mind that she was innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors are unlikely to forget the main points of the prosecution
case, Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the jury goes in to deliberate, they are going to
remember three things. One, that a 16-year-old girl was murdered in
Grand Prairie, Texas. Two, that David Graham confessed. Three, that
the murder weapon was found in his attic.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
