<HEADLINE>
U.S. BREAKS WORLD RECORD IN 4X400 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Michael Johnson still has not broken the world
record in the quarter mile, but he again helped lower the world
record Wednesday in the 4x400-meter relay on the final, gripping
night of track and field at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Joyner-Kersee provided a stirring finish to her storied
career by winning the heptathlon. Joyner-Kersee ran well enough in
the 800 meters, the final event, to hold off the Americans Dedee
Nathan and Kelly Blair-LaBounty in the final scoring.
</P>
<P>
   In the 4x400, Jerome Young, Antonio Pettigrew, Tyree Washington
and Johnson ran a searing 2 minutes 54.20 seconds to break the
previous record of 2:54.29 set by the United States at the 1993
world championships. The four will share a total of $120,000 in
prize and bonus money.
</P>
<P>
   Young led off with a split of 44.4 seconds, then handed the
baton to Pettigrew, who delivered a split of 43.2 seconds. At that
point, the race was decided. The only question was whether the
Americans would break the world record.
</P>
<P>
   They would, as Washington ran a 43.5 leg and Johnson, the
rejuvenated Olympic champion, sprinted around the track in an
anchor leg of 43.1 seconds. Johnson also ran the anchor leg on the
previous record relay with teammates Andrew Valmon, Quincy Watts
and Butch Reynolds in 1993 in Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Poland set a national record by nearly two seconds in finishing
second Wednesday night in 2:58 and Jamaica was third in 2:58.33.
</P>
<P>
   After four years of dropped batons and fumbled expectations, the
U.S. men's 4x100-meter relay team also won a major competition
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After being humbled by Canada at the 1996 Summer Olympics and
failing even to make the final of the 1997 world championships, the
American team of Jon Drummond, Tim Harden, Dennis Mitchell and
Maurice Greene prevailed over Canada and Donovan Bailey, winning
convincingly in 37.90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a half-second off the world record of 37.40 run by the
Americans at the 1992 Summer Olympics and the 1993 world
championships, but Wednesday night it was enough simply to win.
Drummond made up a little ground on the opening leg, then Tim
Harden ran a second leg that was vastly improved over the
baton-juggling leg he ran at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   While Canada's Glenroy Gilbert and Bruny Surin struggled on the
baton exchange in the final curve, Harden passed smoothly to
Mitchell, who slingshot the Americans into the lead. He gave
Maurice Greene, the world champion at 100 meters, a comfortable
lead on the anchor leg.
</P>
<P>
   Greene had won the Goodwill Games 100 meters on Tuesday night
and he was not going to be caught Wednesday night, not even by
Bailey, the world record-holder. Bailey had finished seventh in
Tuesday's 100 meters, getting caught in the blocks and shutting
down after 80 meters. Wednesday night, Bailey pulled within a
stride of Greene but he could not sustain the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This relay means one thing _ a new beginning for the U.S.
men's 4x100-meter relay team,'' said Mitchell, who ran on both
world-record squads.
</P>
<P>
   Canada was second Wednesday night in 38.23 and Cuba third in
39.34. This was the first significant victory by the Americans
since the 1994 Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones, the world's top 100-meter runner, did not compete
in the women's 4x100-meter relay, but Carlette Guidry took the
baton in second place and ran down Pauline Davis of the Bahamas on
the anchor leg to give the United States a victory in 42.06
seconds. She was joined on the victory podium by teammates Cheryl
Taplin, Chryste Gaines and Angie Vaughn. The Bahamas was second in
42.19 seconds and Russia third in 42.62.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 5,000 meters, Bob Kennedy of the United States went
to the front early and hung with the lead pack until the final lap
when Luke Kipkosgei of Kenya and Khalid Boulami of Morocco broke
into a furious sprint down the homestretch. Kipkosgei had one final
surge left and he won in 13:20.27, while Boulami finished second in
13:20.66. Tom Nyariki of Kenya was third in 13:23.34. Kennedy was
fourth in 13:27.51. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
