<HEADLINE>
BULLS ARE EXPECTED TO NAME FLOYD AS THEIR NEXT COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Skedded earlier as BKO-FLOYD-RESIGN.) 
(th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls' front office has dared to dangle an exit sign
in front of Michael Jordan by forcing him to decide whether he
wants to take his cues from a former college coach in the Corn Belt
whose only previous link to the National Basketball Association was
his fishing trips with the Bulls' vice president, Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Krause's fishing buddy, Tim Floyd, who resigned as head coach at
Iowa State on Wednesday, is expected to be named as the Bulls'
successor to Coach Phil Jackson on Thursday, according to officials
with the team and with the league.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd arrived in Chicago on Wednesday and will walk into this
job with the knowledge that he, along with the team's president,
Jerry Reinsdorf, and Krause, could be recognized as the men who
pushed Jordan toward a decision to leave the Bulls after six NBA
championships.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Jordan now. In the past, he made it clear that he
only wanted to play for Jackson, who guided the Bulls to a sixth
NBA championship in June and then quickly left what had become a
hostile environment because of his strained relationship with
Krause. Jordan was at a Chicago country club Wednesday and was not
available for comment. Reinsdorf declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the Bulls' search for a coach, Jordan expressed
his uneasiness with the prospect of Floyd _ whose name began
surfacing two years ago as Jackson's potential replacement _
becoming the Bulls' coach. With a playful jab, Jordan had jokingly
referred to Floyd as Pink, as in the rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play for him is like starting over, and that's what I don't
want to do,'' Jordan said last week. ``I just don't feel that I
want to start over with someone who doesn't really know me and know
the way I play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, Jordan had said he would not make a
decision about his future until the NBA's lockout ended. Jordan's
agent, David Falk, said there were factors that go beyond Floyd
that would determine the future course for his client: does Scottie
Pippen leave as a free agent? Will Dennis Rodman be re-signed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Michael Jordan can determine the balance in his own mind
about the comfort level he has that the pieces are in place to win
a championship,'' Falk said Wednesday in a telephone interview.
``The coach is clearly one factor. I'm not certain it is the only
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doubt that Jordan will call it a career because he is still
viewed as the best player in the game. But Falk is quick to remind
one that Jordan retired once before, in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of athletes don't have the courage to leave because they
define themselves so much in athletic terms,'' Falk said. ``Michael
is different than that. He's a businessman and has a broad range of
interests to keep him busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michael could work with any coach. But the issue is
whether, at this point in his career, he wants to invest the time
it would take to develop a comfort level.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's decision to leave was the first sign that the Bulls'
dynasty was in danger of being dismantled. But there have been
blatant hints that a plan to revamp the Bulls has been in place for
two years. Those who have worked closely with Krause over the years
have a sense that he has been itching to show that he can rebuild
the Bulls and maintain the team's greatness without Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Now Krause may get his chance if Jordan decides he cannot play
for Floyd. Entering with no NBA coaching experience, the
44-year-old Floyd will not be a power threat to Krause. After four
years at Iowa State, Floyd was 81-47 and took the Cyclones to three
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournaments. Last season,
a Floyd team finished under .500 for the first time, going 12-18.
</P>
<P>
   During the lockout, Jordan was prohibited from talking with
Reinsdorf and Krause about the coaching candidates, a list that
included NBA assistants Scott Skiles, Paul Silas, Ron Rothstein and
Rick Carlisle. But it was understood by most that Floyd had the job
if he wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been more of a shock if Tim Floyd had not been
hired,'' Falk said. ``I think Michael has a close relationship with
Jerry Reinsdorf. But clearly, they made a decision a year ago,
during the playoffs, that there was the likelihood that they would
disband. That's when they started making plans for life after
Michael and Phil.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
