<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE APPEAL LEFT AS U.S. JUSTICE REFUSES TO DELAY SEX-SHOP LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's crusade to curb the
adult-entertainment industry took a giant step forward Wednesday
when a U.S. Supreme Court justice granted the city permission to
start enforcing zoning laws that ban sex shops and strip clubs
almost everywhere except industrial zones.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg rejected a last-minute request by
the sex shops for a stay late in the afternoon, without issuing any
written order or opinion. Earlier in the day, a panel of three
judges of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also turned down a
request for a stay.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the two decisions cleared the way for them
to finally begin enforcing the 3-year-old zoning laws, which
prohibit sexually oriented businesses within 500 feet of
residential areas, schools, day care centers, houses of worship or
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this point forward we have a green light to proceed,''
said Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for Giuliani. ``We will start
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the sex shops immediately filed a second request for
a stay, this time with Justice John Paul Stevens, who they said
would decide Thursday whether to honor it. The first request had to
go to Ginsburg because she handles cases from the 2nd Circuit, said
Herald Price Fahringer, a lawyer representing 107
adult-entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But federal law allows the sex shops to appeal to one more
justice before giving up, Fahringer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost hope,'' he said. ``Justice Stevens is probably
the one member of that court who is more sympathetic to First
Amendment concerns than any of the other justices.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials would not reveal when enforcement would actually
begin, saying inspections of sex shops and strip clubs would be
more successful if they were kept secret. But while Giuliani said
Wednesday morning that he would wait a few days before starting
enforcement, Ms. Roche said in the early evening _ after Ginsburg's
ruling _ that there would not necessarily be a delay, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Under the zoning laws, which affect 146 of the city's 164
adult-entertainment businesses, the city has to send inspectors to
sex shops and strip clubs before seeking court orders to close
them. Many of the businesses have been preparing for a crackdown in
recent days, posting instructions for employees to follow if
inspectors show up and, in some cases, posting Fahringer's
telephone number.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The operators of several dance clubs near Times Square said
Wednesday night that they were trying to comply with the law by
requiring dancers who had performed nude to wear bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   At a video store called the Palace, at Eighth Avenue and 47th
Street, a man was glimpsed pulling videocassette boxes from
shelves. A sign in the window said: ``Closed 07-19-98 for
renovation until further notice. This video store not a adult store
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   At a theater called Show Follies Theater, on Seventh Avenue near
48th Street, a hand-lettered sign in the window was equally blunt.
``Classic movies only,'' it read, and added, ``No XXX movies.''
</P>
<P>
   But while some owners of adult-entertainment businesses had
visions of inspectors padlocking their stores and clubs
immediately, Giuliani said Wednesday that they should not expect
anything so dramatic. He said inspectors would be looking not only
for violations of the zoning law, but for violations of other city
statutes, like liquor laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law does not allow the city to just go in and close down
places on day one,'' Giuliani said. ``It requires a certain amount
of evidence and observations to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This is going to take place over a two- to
three-month period, not in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoning restrictions took effect in 1995, and businesses had
a year to comply. They have been fighting it ever since, but the
city has won victory after victory in state and federal courts.
Although lawyers for the sex shops and their customers were still
plotting strategies Wednesday, they sounded more pessimistic than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had always hoped that the Supreme Court would be
sympathetic to our concerns,'' Fahringer said of Ginsburg's
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
