u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-ATM-FEES-330     07-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ATM-FEES-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO PROPOSES CUT IN SOME ATM FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Banking Committee Chairman Alfonse D'Amato
said Wednesday night that he planned to attach a proposal to cut
automated-teller fees to a bill that would overhaul the nation's
bankruptcy code.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prevent banks from double-charging customers who
use money machines at banks that are not their own. Most customers
who use money machines at banks that are not their own are charged
$1.50 on top of the $1 they are already charged for processing of
the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, R-N.Y., receives campaign contributions from the
banking industry, but in this election year, he has taken pains to
cast himself as pro-consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The bill eliminating the ATM fees has put him out of favor with
banks. But by attaching it to the bankruptcy bill, which the banks
and credit-card industries support, D'Amato may reduce opposition
to the bankruptcy bill and still emerge as pro-consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a vote on business interests, let's have a vote on
my consumer proposal,'' D'Amato said with a chuckle in an interview
Wednesday night. Of the banks, he said: ``You will still be
entitled to your profit.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates were skeptical of linking ATM fees and
bankruptcy. Gary Klein, the staff lawyer for the National Consumer
Law Center, said it would not be a reasonable tradeoff for
consumers. ``The two issues are not related,'' he said. ``The
people who benefit from ATMs are not the same people who are having
financial problems and are stuck in the bankruptcy system.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the banks oppose the cutting of the ATM fee _ it would
reduce their annual intake from teller machines to $1 billion from
$3 billion _ D'Amato has not brought that proposal through his own
committee. He said Wednesday night that he would offer it instead
as an amendment to the bankruptcy bill, which has stalled in the
Senate despite a multimillion-dollar lobbying campaign by banks and
credit-card companies to overhaul the nation's bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said late Tuesday that he was
postponing consideration of the bill until Congress returned in
September from its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said the bill was being delayed because of
other pressing legislation, particularly on spending bills, health
care and credit unions, not because of any problems with the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay will shorten considerably the time that the Senate
can discuss the complex bill and reach agreement with the House
version, narrowing the bill's chances of passage before Congress
adjourns for good in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you wait on a bill of this magnitude and
controversy, the more difficult it will be to enact into law,''
Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., one of the bill's co-authors, said in
an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, inspired by the ever-climbing number of personal
bankruptcies, would make it harder for people to file for
protection from their creditors, especially if they appear to have
the ability to repay their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Debate was set to begin on the Senate floor Friday, until Lott
unexpectedly said it would probably not come up until September.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the credit-card industry, which has pumped
millions of dollars into lobbying and advertising campaigns in
favor of the overhaul, said their optimism was undiminished by
Lott's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got strong assurances that the legislation will come
before the Senate very early after Congress returns in September,''
said William Binzel, a spokesman for Mastercard International.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is vehemently opposed by groups representing
consumers, women, senior citizens and others who say it would
unfairly oppress people who are already destitute. They see the
postponement as a signal that the bill is in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over till it's over,'' said Mary Rouleau, chief
lobbyist for the Consumer Federation of America, which opposes the
bill. ``It will not sail through. Thank God, the Senate is starting
to read the fine print on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin, for one, said he had ``very mixed feelings'' about his
own bill and wanted to change it to add restrictions on the
credit-card companies. Many opponents of the bill say the banking
and credit industries make credit too easily available and
effectively lure consumers deeper into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Warren, a professor at Harvard Law School who has
worked against the bill, said the measure presented lawmakers with
a ``lose-lose'' proposition just before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you vote against it, you lose campaign contributions from
the banks,'' Ms. Warren said. ``But if you vote for it, you let
your opponent point out to voters that you just socked it to
consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
