<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL FIGURES SPECULATE ON APPEARANCE BY BRAWLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ There was testimony Wednesday at the Tawana
Brawley defamation trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story was outside the courtroom, where the trial's
participants engaged in a frenzy of speculation about one question:
Will Ms. Brawley appear as a witness on Thursday, after a decade of
refusing to testify?
</P>
<P>
   In the yes camp: Stephen Jackson, the lawyer who said he would
call Ms. Brawley on behalf of his client, C. Vernon Mason, one of
the three Brawley advisers fighting the damages phase of the suit.
``I fully expect for her to be available to testify tomorrow,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the no camp: Steven Pagones, the plaintiff, who has waged a
10-year battle to prove that the allegation that he assaulted Ms.
Brawley was a hoax. ``Why,'' he asked, ``would she travel to New
York to commit perjury?''
</P>
<P>
   In the maybe camp: Michael Hardy, the lawyer for the Rev. Al
Sharpton. ``I don't know if she's coming,'' he said, looking
miserable with uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation about the young woman who has always been the
silent figure at the center of the case began on Tuesday when the
judge, S. Barrett Hickman, reversed an earlier decision and said
Jackson could call Ms. Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   But the conjecturing grew fevered Wednesday, as Alton Maddox
Jr., who has been the closest adviser to the Brawley family for
many years, did everything but declare that Ms. Brawley would be
absent. ``The only thing I can say,'' Maddox said, ``is, if I said
Tawana was coming tomorrow, she would be here. But I'm not saying
that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Maddox's aides worked his way into a knot of reporters
with a wad of bills, asserting that he was willing to take bets
that the young woman would be a no-show. Maddox said, ``Whatever
happens tomorrow has nothing to do with Alton Maddox.''
</P>
<P>
   The guessing about Ms. Brawley was far more than a courthouse
parlor game. Instead, it showed the pressure that has mounted on
the defense since the July 13 verdict by a civil jury in state
Supreme Court here declaring that each of the advisers had defamed
Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox appeared to be undermining Mason's strategy in part
because of the damage it could do to the defense in the inevitable
long aftermath of the case. In the past, the advisers have said Ms.
Brawley could not cooperate with prosecutors who were hostile to
her. That assertion could be difficult to make if she spurned an
invitation from Mason to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Mason has made public comments since the jury verdict that
seemed to distance him from the other advisers. He has noted that
he was only found to have defamed Pagones once, while Maddox was
found liable on two counts and Sharpton on seven counts. His
lawyer, Jackson, has said Ms. Brawley would testify that she was
assaulted and that she described the attack to her advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy suggested at the defense table Wednesday that a new battle
over Ms. Brawley could not be good for any of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddox was the player who was watched most carefully
Wednesday. Ms. Brawley, now 26, has said in the past that she views
Maddox as something of a permanent lawyer for her even though he
was suspended from law practice for refusing to cooperate in an
investigation of his handling of the Brawley case.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox turned 53 this week and a rally in support of him is
planned in New York City on Thursday night. In the past, Ms.
Brawley has attended some similar events.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox has been sharply protective of Ms. Brawley over the
years, and people who know him say it is unlikely that he would
acquiesce in the decision to subject her to new legal entanglements
by calling her as a witness on behalf of Mason.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Maddox said that he had spoken to Ms. Brawley's stepfather,
Ralph King, Wednesday. Neither he nor King had spoken to Ms.
Brawley in several days, he said, and neither knew her plans.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddox stopped short of saying that he doubted Jackson's
statements Wednesday that Jackson had established contact with Ms.
Brawley's family and was working out the logistics of her
appearance here. ``Maybe Jackson has a pipeline,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors have not been included in the to-and-fro over Ms.
Brawley. On Wednesday they heard Mason testify that he bore no ill
will toward Pagones when he said in 1989 that Pagones had
kidnapped, raped and sodomized Ms. Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed likely that the jurors had an inkling of the topic
being debated every time they turned their backs. At one point from
the bench, Hickman told the lawyers to be ready to continue on with
the case on Thursday, ``no matter who comes and who doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
