<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-IMPACT-AR     07-22 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-IMPACT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSSES MOUNT FOR CLOSED BUSINESSES IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NY-SCAFFOLD-COLLAPSE, NY-SCAFFOLD-DISMANTLE)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Business was off 95 percent at Hotaling's News Agency
on Wednesday _ not surprising, considering that the store in
midtown Manhattan, which sells hundreds of foreign and out-of-town
newspapers, was reduced to a cart outside a freight door on 41st
Street near the Avenue of the Americas. The store's real entrance,
on 42nd Street, was closed, along with most of the streets around
Times Square and the businesses that line them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty depressing,'' said store owner Arthur Hotaling.
But, he added, he hoped his losses would be covered by insurance he
carries that is supposed to pay for business disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly who was going to pay _ and how _ were the main questions
among the hundreds of businesses that were closed by city officials
after a construction elevator on the Conde Nast building collapsed
on 43rd Street on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A few of these businesses were large. The Millennium Broadway at
44th Street said it was losing a quarter of a million dollars a day
because almost half of its 627 rooms, the ones facing 43rd Street,
were unusable. Many other businesses, however, were restaurants,
shops and small concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most affected were the street vendors _ with their
coffee carts, hot dog stands, and falafel grills _ who usually dot
the area's street corners.
</P>
<P>
   The office building at 1500 Broadway at 43rd Street contained 65
businesses, with about 1,000 employees, all of whom were barred
from the building Wednesday, said Gretchen Dykstra, president of
the Times Square Business Improvement District. Her group counted
10 restaurants that were closed in the district, as well as two
theaters, a nightclub and the district's own sanitation facility.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani strongly urged that money to help small
businesses be provided immediately by the owner of the Conde Nast
building, the Durst Organization, and its contractor, Tishman
Construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very, very useful to a few of the businesses that
particularly might be strapped for cash over the next three or four
days if some reasonable sum of money were made available,'' the
mayor said at a press conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fund should be used for businesses that did not have
insurance or could not wait for the courts to decide liability for
the collapse, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them may be in a critical position,'' he said. ``If
they can't derive some revenue in the next three to four days, then
a lawsuit two years from now and a big claim two years from now may
not be worth as much as it seems to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than establish a fund for the businesses, however, the
building's owner and contractor said their insurer, Liberty Mutual
Group, had set up an expedited process to handle ``loss of
business'' claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those losses of business are yet to be determined, and at this
point, from a legal point of view, we are not allowed to interfere
with that process,'' said Richard Kielar, a senior vice president
of Tishman.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor and the owner are working with the mayor's office
``to seek feasible methods to deal with the personal emergency
problems that may have occurred to individuals and businesses,''
said Douglas Durst, president of the Durst Organization. They have
set up a fund to help individuals with emergency living expenses,
although the size of that fund and other details were not announced
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's comments clearly placed Durst and Tishman on the
spot, since he seemed to be assuming that they _ or their insurance
company _ were responsible for the losses to other businesses in
the area. But the issue may not be that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Each insurance policy is different, and what is ultimately
covered will depend both on the details of the policy and the
investigation into the cause of the collapse, said Dave Dasgupta, a
spokesman for the Insurance Service Office, which collects
statistics for property-casualty insurance companies. If the
individual businesses have ``business disruption'' insurance, they
will put in claims to their own insurers, who in turn would try to
collect from Liberty Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance companies might argue that the government action
of closing the streets, and not the actual building collapse,
caused the losses to businesses in the area, said Stephen Scammell
of Towers Perrin, an insurance consulting firm. Many insurance
policies do not cover losses caused by government activities, he
added, so business owners counting on their own ``business
disruption'' insurance may be out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really messy,'' Scammell said. ``But it will make a
lot of lawyers happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on previous street shutdowns, lawsuits are likely to be
filed. After the facade of 540 Madison Ave. crumbled last year,
prompting the city to close the street for weeks, several merchants
jointly filed a lawsuit against the building's owner. That case is
scheduled for trial in September, said their lawyer, Kenneth
Ashman, adding that his clients lost millions of dollars because of
the closure.
</P>
<P>
   But for many businesses in Times Square, the current disruptions
caused by the street closures were far less serious _ but annoying.
At the Chase Manhattan branch at 43rd Street and Broadway, for
example, two of the four automated teller machines were closed at
the request of police, because they were too close to windows
facing Times Square, a spokesman for the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Other business owners fear the worst is yet to come. Henry
Kallan, who owns the now-closed Casablanca Hotel on 43rd Street,
said he's losing $10,000 to $15,000 a day. Even after he reopens
the hotel, he said, ``the recovery will take time and we will
realize more losses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
