u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      07-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHAT WITH TORRE DID WONDERS FOR KNOBLAUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirteen days ago, Chuck Knoblauch ducked his head
into manager Joe Torre's office immediately after the Yankees beat
Tampa Bay and asked to meet with him the next afternoon. Torre
replied cheerfully: How about now? And for about half an hour they
chatted _ about expectations, about playing for a new team _ each
man feeling afterward that he had a better sense of the other.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Knoblauch had a better awareness of his value to the
team, despite his diminished batting average and occasional
throwing trouble. Torre and others on the team think he has been
more relaxed in the days since his meeting, and the proof may be in
run production: Including his three-run homer in Wednesday's 13-2
thrashing of Detroit _ his 10th home run of the season _ Knoblauch
has six homers and 15 runs batted in since the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez pitched six innings in the hot and humid
conditions, before 49,029 at Yankee Stadium, to improve to 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (71-25), who broke stride in their record-breaking
pace by losing four of five games through last weekend, apparently
are back on track, winning three straight _ their 10th streak of
three or more victories this season.
</P>
<P>
   Having played 14 consecutive days following the All-Star break,
through a four-city trip and a Monday doubleheader that lasted more
than nine hours, the Yankees funneled out of the clubhouse
Wednesday, ecstatic that they do not have to play Thursday. ``I'm
tired, man,'' shortstop Derek Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, wearing a golf shirt and sweat pants after the game,
almost looked refreshed as he spoke. He had returned from the
All-Star break in an excellent frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two at-bats on July 9, Knoblauch hit the ball hard
and had no hits to show for it. Later in the game, Knoblauch struck
out twice and nearly flubbed an easy throw.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Knoblauch slugged a crucial three-run homer to
help spark a successful comeback, and it was that night _ with his
.258 batting average some 46 points below what his career mark was
at the start of the season _ when he spoke with Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needed to talk to somebody,'' Torre said. ``You know,
it takes a little time when you get to a new ball club, and you
expect a lot out of yourself. I know he was very unhappy with his
production up to that point _ he was a .300 hitter who wasn't
hitting .300. Players like that are sometimes tougher on themselves
than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre could draw on his own experience. Before the 1969 season,
he had been traded from Atlanta to St. Louis for Orlando Cepeda, a
popular and productive player. ``You put a lot of pressure on
yourself,'' Torre said. ``It's stupid to do, but you don't know
that when you're in that body and you're trying to impress
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre did not detail exactly what he told Knoblauch. But Torre,
whose expertise is in easing pressure on players, probably told
Knoblauch something along these lines: You have a good on-base
percentage, you set the tone for the attack with your approach at
the plate, you're a Gold Glove second baseman whose temporary
throwing problems haven't manifested themselves in defeat, and the
team is wildly successful. Go have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has been more aggressive at the plate, hitting the
ball harder and more consistently, and he has played his best
defense of the season since his meeting with Torre. ``From at-bat
to at-bat, better swings, more solid contact, line drives,''
Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the All-Star break, Knoblauch sometimes would botch easy
throws _ hard throws presented no trouble _ but he appears to have
moved beyond the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said that he did not come to the Yankees consciously
looking to establish himself. ``Maybe subconsciously, my body
really wasn't allowing me to relax,'' Knoblauch said. ``Maybe
that's in the back of your mind, day to day, maybe there one day,
not there the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch scored three runs Wednesday and has scored 71 runs in
all, putting him on a pace to score 121 this season, or more than
he has scored in all but one of his first seven seasons in the
majors. He has 47 RBIs, and at his current rate would drive in 74,
a career high. Knoblauch has never hit more than 13 home runs in a
single season, averaging six, but already this year he is one of
seven Yankees with 10 or more home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Getting more from Knoblauch, Torre said, ``is more of a concern
to him than it is to me _ or anyone he plays with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
