<SLUG> BC-NY-ZODIAC-TRIAL-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZODIAC KILLER GETS LIFE TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the day he was arrested and accused of being the
Zodiac killer more than two years ago, Heriberto Seda, a loner
obsessed with guns and religion, declared repeatedly that God had
already forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, at his sentencing in state Supreme Court in Queens
for three murders and one attempted murder, Seda, 30, again invoked
the divinity, saying only God knew the truth. Justice Robert
Hanophy responded by sentencing Seda to the maximum possible, life
in prison, and threw in his own religious allusion.
</P>
<P>
   Urging Seda to seek out the prison chaplain, Hanophy added,
``The first thing you should say to him is: `Bless me, Father, for
I have sinned''' _ a reference to the first words that a Roman
Catholic says to a priest during confession.
</P>
<P>
   Seda must serve at least 83 years and four months before he is
eligible for parole. As court officers led him out of the
courtroom, he turned to look at his mother, Carmen Gladys Alvarado,
who rose from her third-row seat, waved faintly and murmured,
``Bye, Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   After a six-week trial, Seda was convicted last month of being
the Zodiac killer, a murderer who vowed in taunting letters to the
police and news organizations to kill one person for each of the 12
signs of the Zodiac during two crime sprees in the early 1990s. He
eluded the police for six years but was caught after shooting his
half-sister and engaging dozens of police officers in a wild
shootout at his apartment in East New York, Brooklyn, in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   No trial date has been set in the four other shootings he is
accused of committing.
</P>
<P>
   In asking for mercy for Seda, his lawyers described him as a
``troubled young man'' who needs psychological counseling.
Prosecutors called him a cold-blooded killer who stalked only the
most vulnerable people _ the elderly, the mentally ill and people
compromised by drugs or alcohol _ and they argued that he should
never be free again.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Hanophy agreed with the prosecutors. ``You are a
very angry young man,'' he told him. ``And you have forfeited your
life. You will die in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stood before the judge Wednesday, Seda offered a subdued
and rambling statement that referred repeatedly to God. He said the
prosecutors' depiction of him as an unfeeling predator was wrong.
``Nobody really knows me,'' he said. ``I have changed and no matter
what happens, God is always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Cardona, one of two jurors who returned to hear the
judge's sentencing decision, said she found Seda's comments
disturbing. ``He might have felt some remorse at one point, but he
really didn't show it,'' she said. ``This was sad for all the
parties involved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kathleen Heller, the sister of John Diacone, a 46-year-old
mental patient who was killed by the Zodiac killer in 1993, flew in
from Colleyville, Texas, to ask for a life sentence for Seda.
Choking back tears, she told the judge that her brother became an
easy target because the mental health system had failed him.
</P>
<P>
   Diacone had wandered away from Pilgrim State Psychiatric
Hospital on Long Island when he was shot to death outside Highland
Park in Ridgewood, Queens. In an indirect reference to religious
absolution, she said that life in prison for Seda would at least
``ensure that justice in the secular case is served.''
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for leniency, David Bart, one of Seda's lawyers, said
that Seda was a borderline schizophrenic who lived an almost
hermitlike existence and resorted to violence because he suffered
from chronic paranoia. Seda's lawyers have said often that they
considered using an insanity defense but could not find experts who
would declare him legally insane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-98 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
