<DOCNO> NYT19980722.0549 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-STADIUM-COLUMN-NY     07-22 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-STADIUM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: TAKING ON STEINBRENNER`S YANKEE MATH  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call it extortion if you want to; you wouldn't be the
first.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, just as the Yankees were about to embark on an
11-game road trip, George Steinbrenner III set a price for what it
would take to get him to start talking about not talking about
moving the team from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the three million,'' he said to a reporter, referring not
to money but attendance, ``and then we'll talk about the Bronx
after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, did the math. With
the team already projected to draw 2.83 million fans to Yankee
Stadium for the season, it would take less than $2 million for the
city itself to buy enough seats to meet Steinbrenner's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fraction of what the interest on building a new
stadium on the West Side would cost,'' Ferrer pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   But no one in City Hall took to the idea. Instead, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani mocked the borough president, accusing Ferrer of being
``sucker punched.'' The city was not going to get into the business
of buying baseball tickets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And so this columnist stepped into the breach. Since shelling
out for all 170,000 tickets was a bit beyond her, she settled for
five.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on Tuesday evening, when David Cone took the mound against
the Detroit Tigers, she and Ferrer and Ferrer's press secretary and
his so-called body man and her own body man _ well, really just her
husband _ were happily ensconced in what is commonly known as the
nosebleed section, eating hot dogs. Seated in front of them was a
group of commercial soap salesmen from Staten Island well started
on their way to what would become, by about the fifth inning, an
impressive state of inebriation. To the left was a group from
Manhattan celebrating a birthday, complete with pink frosted cake.
</P>
<P>
   On the long escalator ride up to the top of the stadium, Ferrer
was asked about the Yankees' must-have figure of three million. Did
he really think that if the city bought up the outstanding 169,995
seats, Steinbrenner would be placated?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most of this, it's Kabuki theater,'' Ferrer replied.
``It's symbolic. He says, `Three million fans' _ English
translation: `Give me 200 luxury boxes.' You've just got to have
the magic decoder ring with this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But still, Ferrer reaffirmed his commitment to his bulk-purchase
plan. Though City Hall was not willing to play along, he said he
had received many phone calls from corporations eager to buy
tickets and donate them to city schoolchildren. He said he was
still busy working to raise the money independently of the mayor,
even if Steinbrenner's challenge was, as he intimated, just a
bluff: ``He made an offer; I accepted. Let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, which the Yankees obligingly won, 5-1,
Ferrer defended the stadium against its various detractors. He
pointed to a tier where, he claimed, more luxury boxes could be
added. He dismissed concerns over parking and access, saying they
were simple problems to solve. For years, he has been pushing for a
new Metro-North station that, by his accounting, would draw an
additional 3,000 fans to every Yankee game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one house that Ruth built, and this is it,'' he
observed as evening set over the Bronx and the players moved,
antlike, in the artificial glare below. ``Demolishing the stadium
is about as unthinkable as taking down the Empire State Building or
the Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxing poetic about the Bronx landmark, Ferrer even warmed to
his less-than-ideal seat in Box 636. ``You're up in the nosebleeds,
you can still see the field,'' he said. ``It's like you are
suspended in air. The Mets would kill for a stadium like this.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the borough president went unhonored among
the fans screaming for beer and throwing peanuts, even though, with
his button-down shirt and red-and-gold-striped tie, he was far and
away the best-dressed man in the upper tier.
</P>
<P>
   But in the third inning, just after Derek Jeter had stolen
second, one of the soap salesmen made the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better keep these Yankees in the Bronx, brother,'' he
said. A few minutes later, he turned to Ferrer with no less passion
and asked, ``You're the borough president, can you get the beer guy
over here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
