<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH SCHEDULE AND HIGH EXPECTATIONS WILL TEST GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John Elway announced in June that he was returning for
another season with the Denver Broncos, it did not immediately
delight New York Giants coach Jim Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish John had retired,'' a smiling Fassel said of Elway.
``We have to play the Broncos this year. And then I realized that
Brett Favre wouldn't be retiring from the Packers and Steve Young
wouldn't be retiring from the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play them. What's one more Hall of Fame quarterback on the
schedule?''
</P>
<P>
   As the Giants prepare to open training camp at the State
University of New York's Albany campus on Saturday, the prospects
of the 1998 team are invariably bound to an onerous schedule that
includes both of last season's Super Bowl teams, the
division-winning Kansas City Chiefs and a ``Monday Night Football''
match at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the Giants' penance for winning the National Football
Conference East last season. It will be a brave, new and demanding
world for them.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when the Giants were 10-5-1, their opponents
compiled the worst aggregate record (86-103-4) in the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   But Fassel, whose rejuvenation of the Giants won him the 1997
coach of the year award, has begun to use the team's imposing
schedule as a motivational tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told our players that people around the league are still
probably trying to make up their minds about us,'' Fassel said. ``A
year ago, people didn't think we could win at all. Now the bar has
been raised and I'm sure people are watching to see how we respond.
It's another thing we have to prove, and that doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel has spent most of the off season telling his charges that
last year's achievements were a beginning, but no longer good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, they were learning how to listen, learning how to
win,'' Fassel said. ``At training camp this year, I expect
everything _ the efficiency, the understanding of the finer points
and the consistency of effort _ to start off at a much higher
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a no-excuse operation from Day 1.''
</P>
<P>
   So, except for a joke here or there, don't expect Fassel to make
much of the Giants' exacting schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the general manager, Ernie Accorsi, and his
predecessor, George Young, Fassel enters what could be a
breakthrough year with every starter from last year's team
returning.
</P>
<P>
   For other teams, training camp is often a competitive
environment where jobs are won and lost. For the Giants, who have
at most two or three starting jobs unresolved, the emphasis will be
on instruction and improvement.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, no one epitomizes the team mission better than
quarterback Danny Kanell. Kanell was 7-2-1 as a starter in 1997 and
widely praised for his ability to avoid game-breaking mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   But can Kanell raise his game and rev up the offense, something
that is essential if the Giants expect to compete at the next
level?
</P>
<P>
   As Fassel said, ``There's no doubt we have to score more
points.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kanell knows what that means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make better decisions,'' he said. ``That will let me
throw more accurately to the right receiver. I have to see the
whole field better, lead the offense better, interpret the game
plan better. I've spent most of the off season trying to make sure
I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell, 24, has also added a few pounds to his 6-foot-3-inch
frame, thanks to his regular attendance at Giants Stadium during
the winter conditioning and weight program.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell should have far more targets to choose from since wide
receiver Ike Hilliard, last year's No. 1 draft pick, appears on
schedule in his recovery from neck surgery. Hilliard went down in
the team's second game, three games before Kanell took over for
Dave Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell and Hilliard have spent hours working on their timing in
the passing game during practices at Giants Stadium since March.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Hilliard in the starting lineup as camp opens will be
the veteran Chris Calloway, the team leader in receiving for the
last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Amani Toomer has impressed the coaching staff with his work
ethic in the off season and has a chance for an expanded role. The
rookie wide receivers Joe Jurevicius and Brian Alford _ as well as
the undersize duo of David Patten and Omar Douglas _ should provide
depth.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few positions as yet unresolved is at running back.
Tiki Barber is the designated starter, but the Giants signed the
free agent Gary Brown, who rushed for 945 yards with the San Diego
Chargers last year, to compete for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mix is Tyrone Wheatley, who could win the job with
a great camp or end up as the Giants' latest No. 1 pick to falter.
</P>
<P>
   At strongside linebacker, Corey Miller has irked Fassel with
some absences at off-season team gatherings and has all but lost
his job to Marcus Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Al Pupunu will get every chance to turn the tight end
spot into a productive pass-catching position, and the Giants will
get inventive as they try to get the rookie safety Shaun Williams
onto the field in regular and nickel defense packages.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Giants' schedule, the secondary _ a team strength _
will have to get even better as it faces some of the league's best
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a determined team,'' Fassel said of his Giants.
``They'll need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
