<HEADLINE>
WATER POLO: U.S. COMES UP EMPTY IN THE POOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Italy, Russia, Spain)  (lb) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ Wolf Wigo made the most of a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play in an international
tournament near home, but the United States still finished without
a medal Wednesday night at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Wigo scored two goals and dished out three assists in the United
States' 8-7 loss to Italy in the bronze-medal game before 1,200 at
the Nassau County Swimming and Diving Center. Leonardo Sottani
scored the winning goal with 18 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   In the championship match, Russia, the defender, won the gold
medal by beating Spain, 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   Wigo, who grew up on New York City's Upper West Side and
attended the Bronx High School of Science, was one of only two on
the national team who were not natives of California. He tied for
the team-high in goals with five in the tournament in front of his
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the 25-year-old veteran of the seventh-place 1996 Olympic
team was not feeling sentimental afterward. He had one goal
disallowed against Italy when the referee ruled that the entire
ball had not cleared the goal line. And a teammate, Brad
Schumacher, appeared to have tied the game with a goal as time
expired, but an official penalized Schumacher for pushing off,
ending the match.
</P>
<P>
   After Wigo's goal was waved off, coach John Vargas said, ``He
was playing harder and harder and smarter. Anybody else, that might
have hurt them the rest of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians marked Wigo with more care in the fourth quarter,
so Wigo became a playmaker. He had two assists, the second to Kyle
Kopp to tie the game at 7-7 with one minute three seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Wigo has degenerative discs in his back and he said playing four
games in five days was an added strain. But he plans to stay in the
sport until the 2000 Olympics, continuing a routine of waking at
4:15 a.m. in his adopted city of San Francisco to trade stocks and
then training at night.
</P>
<P>
   `'I'm sure I can do it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
