<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 49ers PRESIDENT CARMEN POLICY QUITS IN FEUD FALLOUT  
 (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feuds in the National Football League are as common as
touchdowns. But the bitter battle between San Francisco 49ers owner
Eddie DeBartolo and team president Carmen Policy, friends for about
30 years, ended in Policy's resignation Wednesday, concluding one
of the most successful football duos of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Policy finally made official what has been speculated about for
months, that he was leaving the 49ers because of a strained
relationship with DeBartolo. He will be replaced on an interim
basis by Larry Thrailkill, chief operating officer. The current
team vice presidents Dwight Clark and Bill Duffy will be
responsible for day-to-day operations and report to Thrailkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepping aside is very difficult, it's awkward, but it's not
impossible,'' Policy said during a news conference Wednesday in
Burlingame, Calif. ``I'm looking forward to the opportunities ahead
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of club executives throughout the NFL speculated that
Policy may become part of a potential ownership bid involving
billionaire banker Al Lerner, who is considering purchasing the new
Cleveland Browns expansion team, which begins play in 1999. Those
same people say Policy would be given 6 to 8 percent ownership and
would run the daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   Such agreements are rare in the NFL but not unheard of. The
former New Orleans general manager, the late Jim Finks, owned 3
percent of the Saints, and the former general manager and coach of
the Miami Dolphins, Don Shula, owned about 12 percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The rift between Policy and DeBartolo began in December when the
49ers' owner was told by the U.S. attorney's office in New Orleans
that he could be indicted because of a gambling fraud case. Eight
months have passed without any charges being filed, but the case
remains open. Because of the investigation, Debartolo's sister,
Denise DeBartolo York, who owns 45 percent of the 49ers, has
controlled the team.
</P>
<P>
   Debartolo feels Policy has been trying to gain control of the
49ers in his absence, something Policy strongly denies.
</P>
<P>
   Many NFL team executives believe Policy's resignation means that
DeBartolo no longer fears being indicted and therefore wants
control of the team again. Since DeBartolo no longer trusts Policy,
he wanted Policy gone from the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a deep freeze between the two men since the Super
Bowl, the last time they spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been defrosted during the past whatever number of
months,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   Since being named executive vice-president and legal council in
1989, his teams have had a .771 winning percentage, won seven
division titles, made eight playoff appearances and captured two
Super Bowl titles. He later became the club president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen leaves our organization with my best personal wishes,''
DeBartolo said in a lukewarm statement. ``He has been an integral
part of the 49ers' success since we named him president in 1991.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
