<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODWILL GAMES NOTEBOOK: SOCCER AND DECATHLON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOCCER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Women Meet, Greet, Set to Compete &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women will assume soccer's center stage next summer when the
United States will play host to the third Women's World Cup. Unlike
the American men, who finished 32nd and last in France this summer,
the American women are the favorites to become world champions for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games in the New York area this week include
women's soccer for the first time. The U.S. team took the
opportunity to be in the area this week to to promote next year's
World Cup on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of coach Tony DiCicco and his assistants,
Lauren Gregg and Jay Hoffman, the Americans held their first
practice Wednesday at Giants Stadium, in East Rutherford, N.J.,
which will play host to the opening ceremony and first game next
June 19.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey welcomed the team and told
about 1,000 young female players in the crowd that she expected the
Women's World Cup games at Giants Stadium to attract crowds similar
to the sellouts for the men's tournament in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games will be a good test for the Americans because
the other three teams in the tournament _ China, Norway and Denmark
_ are also world powers. The Norwegians were the winners of the
last World Cup, in 1995 in Sweden, and the only team the Americans
have lost to this year.
</P>
<P>
   China will play Norway at noon and the United States will face
Denmark in the evening on Saturday. The winners will meet for the
gold medal Monday night after the third-place game. All four games
will be played at Mitchel Field in Uniondale, N.Y., which is near
the Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX YANNIS
</P>
<P>
   DECATHLON
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien Missed Chance to Beat Record &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Brien could have been disappointed. While he set a
Goodwill Games record of 8,755 points Monday night in his first
decathlon since winning in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, he ran slowly
in the concluding 1,500 meters and wasted a strong chance to break
his world record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I disappointed?'' he said Wednesday. ``I was disappointed
in my discus throw and shot-put more than the 1,500. My emphasis
all year has been to get my field events sound. I haven't run
enough races and done enough pace work, so my 400 and 1,500 were
lacking. I was fortunate to make it through this meet.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's future decathlon plans are unsure. ``I'm going to do
some pole vaults and hurdles this summer,'' he said, ``but we'll
have to see about my next decathlon. Maybe less is better.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien and Marion Jones, who won the Goodwill 100 and 200
meters for women, attended a news conference in Manhattan on
Wednesday to announce a new fitness program for America's 10
million children in grades four through six.
</P>
<P>
   Another guest was Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice President Al
Gore. The program, called Fit Kids, was created by the United
States Conference of Mayors in conjunction with the U.S. Olympic
Committee and USA Track and Field.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FRANK LITSKY
</P>
</TEXT>
