<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine, `Cat' rip Phillies
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They laid out a full table Wednesday night:
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine got his 14th win, matching his entire 1997 total.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga had another two-homer game, his sixth twin-HR
night in 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping Michael Tucker poked a double and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   It was the year's highest output in a 14-2 win over the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   And Mark Wohlers climbed out of his foxhole to throw a 1-2-3
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   What Chicago Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves emerged from two days of abuse from the Cubs and
body-slammed Philadelphia, opening their nine-game trip with their
biggest offensive night of the year. The first three men in the
order scored six times by the second inning, and after rookie
Carlton Loewer coughed up a three-run homer to Galarraga before he
had retired his fourth batter, it was as good as over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't hit him that hard in the first inning,'' said
manager Bobby Cox. ``A lot of ground balls that just happened to be
in the right spot and then Galarraga hit that home run. That was
big.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves first baseman had gone a week without a homer, with
just three hits in his previous 21 at-bats, before he reached
Loewer with a three-run shot in the second. He the hit a solo shot
off Jerry Spradlin in the fifth to make it 12-2, both homers flying
the wall in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hit by pitches 16 times already and I think I opened
(his stance) a little bit so I could get out of the way,'' said
Galarraga, his season HR total at 32. ``I figured that out so in
batting practice, I tried to spray the ball to right field to
forget about it and that helped out out.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who was 14-7 in 33 starts last year, won his 14th in 21
starts and struck out 10, matching his season high. He retired the
first 11 men he faced, was hurt only by a two-run Rico Brogna homer
and was left to wonder what had gone so wrong year ago is going so
much better now.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm trying not to get caught up in any of that stuff,''
Glavine said. ''My last three times out, I've felt real good about
how I'm throwing the ball and I'm just trying to take advantage of
it. Obviously tonight, the offense made it real easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
