<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guillen hopes to stay on with Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Ozzie Guillen made his 25th start of the season
at shortstop Wednesday night, though he went to some length to
disclaim the appearance incentive in his contract. There is none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have one incentive,'' he said, ``and that's a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen's ring mantra. It was the topic his first day with the
Braves and remains moreso now, as the NL East becomes an
increasingly foregone conclusion. But the 13-year veteran dropped a
hint Wednesday that Braves management has not openly considered.
Guillen likes it here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay here,'' he said. ``I want to end my career
here. I want to play for a couple more years with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have both Guillen and Rafael Belliard under one-year
contracts and though Belliard, on the 60-day disabled list with a
torn left quadricep, has been able to resume most physical
activity, he has become nothing more than a Guillen/Walt Weiss
insurance policy. At 34, Guillen is two years younger than
Belliard, gives little in the field and has a 20-point higher
career batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen will continue to get extensive playing time this trip,
while Bobby Cox guards Weiss' sore left quadricep. Asked if Weiss
can play off the bench, Cox said, ``He's available to win the game,
sure. To get him well would take the whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Walter for the long stretch,'' Guillen said. ``We all
know he's been playing hurt, on a real bad leg. That's what I'm
here for. That's the reason they signed me. And when he's healthy,
he'll be back in.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, when Guillen was hit in the left big toe by
Kerry Wood Tuesday night, it maked the first time since 1990 he had
been struck by a pitch. Over his entire career and over 6,100
at-bats, Guillen has only been hit by pitches seven times. Andres
Galarraga has already been hit 16 times this season alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm an easy out,'' Guillen explained. ``Why are they
going to hit me? That's a waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marking time
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wohlers has essentially stopped talking about Mark Wohlers.
Asked if he had considered returning to the minor leagues to work
on his control, he replied, ``No comment.'' Asked if he had spoken
with general manager John Schuerholz about the club's plans,
Wohlers replied, ``Ask John.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers has understandably been a target of extensive media
coverage and it has not worn well on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about it because I don't want to dwell on
my past,'' Wohlers said. ``I want to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
